<HEADLINE>
AUTO WORKERS IN CANADA AVERT STRIKE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for updating, rewriting throughout)   (sw) 
 By ROBYN MEREDITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ With less than two hours to spare before a threatened
strike, the DaimlerChrysler Corp. reached an agreement with the
Canadian Auto Workers union on a new three-year contract covering
the company's 13,800 workers in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, DaimlerChrysler's factory workers will get
annual raises of 3 percent on top of their cost-of-living
adjustments; a $1,200 (Canadian), or $818 (U.S.), annual holiday
bonus; a $1,000 (Canadian) signing bonus; an $800 (Canadian)
tuition reimbursement for workers' children, and a $2,000
(Canadian) child care benefit.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadian union president Basil E. Hargrove announced the
deal at 10:25 p.m. and called it ``an excellent package.'' The
union had threatened to strike at midnight.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadian union will begin labor talks later this month with
the General Motors Corp. The union had already reached a deal with
the Ford Motor Co. on a new labor contract.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the United Automobile Workers union on Tuesday gave
Ford Motor a Friday deadline to reach an agreement with the union
on a new labor contract or watch its 101,033 factory workers in the
United States walk out on strike.
</P>
<P>
   The union strike threat gives Ford until 3:30 Friday afternoon
to find common ground with the union. The company expressed hope
that a strike could be avoided. ``We're optimistic,'' said Edward
K. Miller, Ford's manager of corporate news. ``This is a normal
part of the collective bargaining process and there is no reason to
believe we can't reach an agreement by Friday.''
</P>
<P>
   The UAW.union did not return calls seeking comment. Talks
between the union and Ford recessed this afternoon, and are
expected to resume Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Labor contracts between the nation's 400,000 unionized auto
workers and Ford, GM and DaimlerChrysler were set to expire Sept.
14, but were extended indefinitely as the union continued
negotiations on new contracts with the companies. DaimlerChrysler
and GM have already reached agreements with the union without
strikes _ or even the threat of strikes.
</P>
<P>
   But the union on Tuesday gave Ford the required 72-hour notice
that it would end the current contract Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler workers already ratified their four-year
contract, and GM workers are scheduled to vote next week on a
similar contract. It is expected to win near-unanimous approval.
Both contracts call for a $1,350 signing bonus and annual raises of
3 percent above inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Ford workers are expected to get the same generous raises, but
workers have been upset by Ford's plans to spin off its Visteon
auto parts subsidiary. The 23,500 union members working at Visteon
have been nervous that their jobs would not be as secure as those
at Ford.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
