<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-UPDATE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S BACK TO THE BASICS FOR LAKERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Fixes fourth item to say Gary Garrett was released after Tuesday
practice) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA BARBARA, Calif. _ An unsuspecting passerby could have
dropped into Robertson Gym and found nothing resembling an NBA
practice Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   That was unmistakably the Los Angeles Lakers running through the
UC Santa Barbara gym for two-plus hours in the morning and again in
the evening. But little else on the first day of training camp was
recognizable.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes basketball looked more like a game of charades.
Sometimes like follow-the-leader. Sometimes like a dance with no
music.
</P>
<P>
   It's not supposed to look like kindergarten, but coach Phil
Jackson's method does begin with a remedial course in fundamentals,
and that meant a lot of drills where the basketball never left the
equipment bag.
</P>
<P>
   And where the drills themselves felt like odd rituals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man,'' Kobe Bryant said with a laugh, ``you got to see some of
this stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   (Reporters, banned from Jackson's practices, will see nothing,
however, so we'll let Bryant describe the scene.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Pivot work, without even having a basketball. Just run, set a
pick, then spin, pivot, go, then stop, change direction, without a
basketball. You practice layups without a basketball,'' Bryant
explained. ``It's weird.''
</P>
<P>
   But also fun, fresh and effective based on the players'
reactions so far. Aside from ex-Chicago Bull John Salley, none of
them have seen anything like this since junior high school, if
ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``We broke it down to the basic forms of basketball footwork,''
Rick Fox said, ``being able to work with your teammate in as simple
a form as even running together. It's been a good first morning.''
</P>
<P>
   In the final drill of the session, the 20 players jogged in a
straight line in something Jackson called ``the Indian style,''
according to pupil Bryant. The smallest Laker, Tyronn Lue, was in
front, with the largest, Shaquille O'Neal, in back. Every time the
whistle blew, the big man at the end of the line would have to
sprint to catch the speedier guard at the front.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was funny seeing the big guys trying to catch up to those
little guys,'' Bryant said.
</P>
<P>
   So they ran together, and shared some laughs in the process. A
unifying exercise? ``Absolutely. Absolutely,'' said Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, all drills involved all 20 players, rather than the
usual approach of breaking up into groups of small guards and big
men.
</P>
<P>
   There were drills to teach advancing the ball upcourt, both
dribbling and passing. There were footwork drills. By today, the
Lakers will be honing passing skills by throwing the ball against a
pair of ``Toss Back'' devices. It seems like basic equipment, but
the Lakers never owned them until they arrived here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody here knows (the fundamentals), but it's a matter of
fine-tuning it to the point where you're doing it and not even
thinking about it,'' Bryant said.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, all of this will serve as building blocks in
learning the complex triangle offense, Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's about seven different ways in which you get to the
triangle that have to be practiced over and over and over,'' he
said. ``Every teammate has to have a way to get to the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   And it's not an easy thing to learn.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happens is more than anything else,'' Jackson said, ``is
guys feel crowded on the court, and they don't feel like they can
put the ball down and do their one-on-one moves, so their
speciality is stuffed or whatever else. They have to learn when and
how.''
</P>
<P>
   It might be several days before the Lakers actually run the
triangle in its totality. In the meantime, there will be a few
bewildered looks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of them are on my face,'' Jackson quipped, ``not
theirs.''
</P>
<P>
   Summer school: Some Lakers will pick up Jackson's system sooner
than others. A.C. Green, who learned the triangle in Dallas, and
Salley have a head start.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of others practiced informally with Jackson's staff
for several days in September. Attending the voluntary sessions
were Fox, Bryant, Derek Fisher, Tyronn Lue and Travis Knight.
</P>
<P>
   Harper retires: The Lakers' trade of veteran Derek Harper to
Detroit might soon cost them a draft pick.
</P>
<P>
   Harper has not reported to the Pistons and plans to retire. Once
he files the paperwork to make it official, the Lakers _ per terms
of the trade _ will have to make up for the loss. One possibility
is sending Detroit a future second-round pick.
</P>
<P>
   Ballooning roster: For the first time in recent history, the
Lakers brought the full complement of players, 20, into camp. The
last three to sign Monday were first-round pick Devean George and
free-agent journeymen Gerald Jordan and Gary Garrett. Garrett was
released after evening practice on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   George received a three-year deal worth at least $2.12 million,
with incentives that could push the total to $2.55 million.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan joins a long list of players with non-guaranteed deals
who are here simply to provide extra practice bodies. NBA teams can
carry only 12 players, plus up to three on the injured list, into
the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's important for us (to have extra players) to
provide for injuries early in training camp,'' Jackson said. ``The
other reason is we have a couple (roster) spots that are available
that we think should be open to motivate players.''
</P>
<P>
   Familiar faces: Among the observers at Tuesday's practice were
ex-head coach Kurt Rambis and longtime assistant Bill Bertka, both
retained as consultants with the team.
</P>
<P>
   Bertka's duties, however, will also include some coaching. He'll
assist Jackson's staff at practices and have a seat behind the
Lakers bench at home games.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
