<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-RANGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES CRUSH RANGERS, 8-0, IN FIRST GAME OF PLAYOFFS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Orlando Hernandez passed his manager in the Yankee
clubhouse on Tuesday afternoon and grinned, and Joe Torre suspected
Hernandez's expression was meant entirely to reassure him. As in,
``Don't worry, I've got everything under control.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees might have had a discombobulated regular season, but
the playoffs started on Tuesday night and it was business as usual
for Hernandez, Bernie Williams and company, who blistered the Texas
Rangers, 8-0, in Game 1 of the three-of-five-game division series
at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The teams will play the second game here on Thursday night, when
Texas will try to end its streak of seven consecutive post-season
losses to the Yankees, dating to 1996, and 22 consecutive innings
without a run, dating to 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez shut out the Rangers on two hits over eight innings _
he is 3-0 with an 0.41 earned run average in the post-season,
including last year _ and Williams made a run-saving sliding catch
before hitting a two-run double, a three-run home run and a
run-scoring single, for six runs batted in, before 57,099 fans.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' lineup is stacked with aggressive, powerful hitters
who have a consistent approach at the plate. Attack. Always attack.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the Yankees limited the Rangers to one run in the
three-game division series and swept Texas by using the Rangers'
own aggressiveness against them, David Wells and Andy Pettitte
throwing changeups when Texas was looking for fastballs.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, Hernandez stifled the Rangers exactly the same
way. Hernandez usually relies on his slider, the sweeping breaking
ball that moves away from right-handed hitters, but he altered his
approach on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Ivan Rodriguez doubled in the first inning and after Hernandez
walked Rusty Greer, the hulking Juan Gonzalez strolled to the
plate, always capable of launching a ball into Monument Park.
</P>
<P>
   But with a two-ball, two-strike count on Gonzalez, Hernandez
buried the baseball deep into his palm, flipped it homeward, and
Gonzalez pitched forward on his front leg and swung awkwardly,
missing.
</P>
<P>
   This went on all night _ a Texas hitter leaning awkwardly, the
timing of his swing shattered, the result being a pop-up or easy
fly ball. Hernandez was throwing his fastball about 90 miles and
hour and his changeup 71 to 73 mph and the Rangers were caught in
between. Of the Rangers' first 21 outs, in the first seven innings,
15 came on balls hit in the air, four were on strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Hernandez tiptoed through some early danger. After
Gonzalez struck out in the first inning, Hernandez walked Rafael
Palmeiro on five pitches _ it appeared he didn't want to tangle
with the Rangers' slugger and pitched around him _ but he whiffed
Todd Zeile on four pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez singled with one out in the third inning, stole
second, and Hernandez walked Greer. Gonzalez extended his arms and
somehow lined a changeup to right-center, the ball headed for the
gap between Williams and the right fielder Paul O'Neill.
</P>
<P>
   Williams was in a full pursuit of the ball within two strides,
eyes locked on the flight of the ball, his mouth widening and then
closing as he took quick and deep breaths. O'Neill had no chance,
Williams had to catch the ball. He dropped to his left thigh,
reached out and speared the ball with his glove about three feet
off the ground, sliding across the grass and leaping to his feet to
throw the ball back to the infield.
</P>
<P>
   The play saved two runs for the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro popped Hernandez's next pitch _ a changeup _ to deep
center field, and Hernandez began walking toward the dugout, head
down, quite sure of himself, never bothering to check and see
whether Yankee Stadium would contain Palmeiro's drive. The ball
settled into Williams' glove just before Hernandez stepped over the
first-base line, El Duque respecting this superstition, as always.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers never really bothered Hernandez after that. He would
get ahead in the count, and then Jorge Posada would give the sign
for the changeup _waggling the four fingers of his right hand _ and
tap his glove against the ground, indicating for Hernandez to keep
the changeup low. Hernandez followed his directives precisely, and
Texas' post-season streak of scoreless innings kept growing.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Sele, the Texas pitcher, had a good curveball, but the
Yankees waited patiently for mistakes, and ultimately, they were
rewarded. Darryl Strawberry was on first base when Sele threw a
fastball over the heart of the plate in the second inning and Ricky
Ledee drove it to left field, the ball slicing as if Ledee had hit
it with an oversized driver.
</P>
<P>
   Greer, Texas' capable left fielder, closed on the ball and
seemed in position to make the catch, but suddenly ducked his head;
he had lost the ball in the glare created by the hundreds of
floodlights that rim the top of Yankee Stadium. Strawberry rounded
third and scored, Ledee had a double and the Yankees had a 1-0
lead.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Jeter, who struck out in his first two at-bats, rolled a
two-out single to left in the fifth inning, and with Jeter at first
and Lee Stevens covering first base, O'Neill skipped a single
through the first-base hole, Jeter running to third.
</P>
<P>
   Sele becomes more vulnerable with each pass through the lineup.
Opponents batted .252 against him on his first 45 pitches this
year, .319 thereafter, and as Williams batted in the sixth, Sele
was approaching 100 pitches. Williams fell behind, no balls and two
strikes. Sele spun a curveball with one ball and two strikes, the
ball bending past the outside corner of the plate, Williams frozen
as Sele lurched toward the Texas dugout, thinking he had an
inning-ending strikeout. Ball 2, according to the home plate umpire
Jim Joyce.
</P>
<P>
   Sele tried to throw another curveball on the outside edge, but
it was ball three. Williams fought off another curveball, with a
foul tip. Having thrown Williams six straight curves, Sele changed
his pattern, whipped a fastball; Williams crushed it to center,
both runners scoring. The fans roared for Williams.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees finished off the Rangers in the sixth. Ledee walked,
and after there were two outs, Jeter walked. O'Neill slapped a
tricky grounder to third, where Todd Zeile bent over and had the
ball ricochet off his body and away, an error that allowed Ledee to
score. Yankees 4, Texas 0. Mike Venafro, a left-hander, then
challenged Williams, batting right-handed, with a fastball,
Williams going with the pitch and smashing the ball to right
field. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez rambled back toward the wall, looking up, in perfect
position to see Williams' home run disappear among jubilant fans to
make it 7-0. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
