<HEADER>
A7874 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-MCI-SPRINT-FCC-1STLD-     10-06 1448
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCI-SPRINT-FCC-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-TRIMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FCC HEAD SAYS APPROVAL OF MCI-SPRINT DEAL CANNOT BE ASSUMED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to insert new 6th graf explaining size of deal, bgng The deal
was... ) (See also MCI-SPRINT-ADVISERS and related stories) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The head of the Federal Communications Commission
on Tuesday sharply questioned how MCI Worldcom's $115 billion
agreement to buy Sprint Corp. could benefit consumers and warned
that the companies would have to meet a high standard to persuade
him to approve the deal.
</P>
<P>
   William Kennard, the commission chairman, has typically been
circumspect in his public pronouncements about large mergers
destined to come before him. But talking to reporters after
delivering a speech here Tuesday morning, he was
uncharacteristically blunt, raising the prospect that the two
companies are in for a tough time with at least one of the two
federal agencies that must approve the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``American consumers are enjoying the lowest long-distance rates
in history and the lowest Internet rates in the world for one
reason: competition,'' Kennard told reporters Tuesday morning after
a speech before the Federal Communications Bar Association.
``Competition has produced a price war in the long-distance market.
The merger appears to be a surrender. How can this be good for
consumers? The parties will bear a heavy burden to show how
consumers would be better off.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennard made his comments moments before the chief executives of
the two companies officially announced the deal at a news
conference in New York.
</P>
<P>
   While any decision by the FCC about the deal would require the
approval of three of the five commissioners, Kennard has managed to
get at least two other votes on every important issue during his
term.
</P>
<P>
   The deal was initially calculated to be worth $108 billion but
jumps to $115 billion once $7 billion in stock options is added.
</P>
<P>
   If the deal is approved by a majority of the five-person
commission headed by Kennard and by the Justice Department's
antitrust division, it would concentrate about three-quarters of
the nation's long-distance market in the hands of two companies
instead of three. While it would continue to leave AT&AMP;T the largest
player in long distance, federal regulators, particularly at the
Justice Department's antitrust division, have historically been
skeptical of deals that reduce the competition from three dominant
players to two.
</P>
<P>
   Some officials at the FCC said that Kennard's comments were a
prelude to negotiations with the companies that would lead either
to major divestitures _ pieces of both the long-distance and
Internet-network businesses _ or to significant conditions imposed
on the company, conditions intended to keep the long-distance
market competitive.
</P>
<P>
   The officials, who spoke on condition they not be identified,
said that some analysts and Wall Street generally had been too glib
in assuming an easy ride through the regulatory review of the
proposed acquisition. They said that Kennard's main concerns were
about how the concentration of the two companies' Internet and
long-distance businesses would hit consumers. The chairman and his
aides have spent months proclaiming that one of the hallmarks of
his tenure has been the sharp decline in long-distance telephone
rates, although some consumer advocates have said that high
surcharges and special fees have actually raised prices for
lower-income consumers who make a small number of long-distance
calls.
</P>
<P>
   In part, those who have discounted the regulatory obstacles to
the MCI-Sprint deal have based their views on Kennard's track
record. He has not tried to block a single large deal reviewed by
his agency. But he also said as long ago as last year that the
remarkable consolidation among long-distance providers had prompted
him to take a tougher stance toward any new deals that might
emerge.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference in New York, the top executives of the two
companies said Tuesday that they were confident that Washington
regulators would ultimately approve the deal, the largest corporate
merger in history.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understood from day one it's our burden of proof to show
that this is pro-competitive,'' said Bernard Ebbers, MCI Worldcom's
chief executive. ``We obviously would not have entered into this
transaction if we didn't feel very confident that we could show
that this was pro-competitive, and we look forward to the
opportunity to doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The filing by MCI Worldcom and Sprint for regulatory approval
comes at a momentous time. This week, the FCC is expected to
approve another huge merger, SBC's $72 billion acquisition of
Ameritech, a deal that will reduce the number of so-called Baby
Bells from five to four.
</P>
<P>
   The agency is also expected on Friday to hand down its
cable-concentration ownership rules, which will determine whether
AT&AMP;T can complete its $58 billion acquisition of MediaOne without
shedding any significant assets. And last week, Bell Atlantic asked
the commission for permission to become the first regional bell
telephone company to enter the $80 billion long-distance market.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Precisely what concessions Kennard wants to exact from MCI
Worldcom and Sprint is not known. There is widespread expectation
that Sprint will ultimately sell its Internet-services network,
just as MCI did after it was acquired by Worldcom last year. And
some officials said Tuesday that the agency could also order that
some chunks of the two companies long-distance businesses be sold
as well.
</P>
<P>
   Based on Kennard's track record with other mergers, some
officials said, he may also try to have MCI Worldcom and Sprint
move more aggressively to enter local markets to force competition
in areas that have largely been resistant to competitors. In recent
months, MCI Worldcom has been heavily marketing local telephone
service in New York. And in approving SBC's purchase of Ameritech,
the commission set a series of possible financial penalties if the
companies fail to offer new competition in 30 cities outside their
existing regions over the next 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, the proposed deal is all but certain to have
other major ancillary consequences for the telecommunications
industry. It has already provided new ammunition to some of the
regional Bell companies who want to enter the long-distance market,
a market made less competitive by the merger.
</P>
<P>
   The FCC has denied all previous applications by the regional
Bells to enter the long-distance market because, the agency has
said, the regional Bells have not opened their territories
sufficiently to local competition. Bell Atlantic's application to
enter the long-distance market is widely expected to be approved by
the FCC by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, representatives of some of the regional Bell companies
said that if the FCC were to approve the MCI-Sprint deal, there
would be enormous pressure on the agency to open the long-distance
market to new rivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a no-brainer,'' said Roy Neel, president of the U.S.
Telephone Association, which represents the regional Bell
companies. ``In light of this deal, it's now time to release the
regional operating companies to go head to head with these
monsters.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As a matter of practice, the FCC reviews mergers involving
telecommunications companies to assure that they are in ``the
public interest.'' Using this vague standard, they can force the
restructuring of the deal. While in recent years the agency has
never blocked a deal, Kennard's predecessor, Reed Hundt, once
killed negotiations of a large telecommunications deal by simply
saying he thought it inconceivable that the agency would approve
it.
</P>
<P>
   Kennard has taken a more low-key approach, although more than a
year ago he signaled that he would be tougher on new mergers in the
long-distance businesses. His comments, interestingly enough, came
in connection with the FCC's approval of Worldcom's acquisition of
MCI last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once this merger is consummated, the industry will again be
poised just a merger away from undue concentration,'' he said on
Sept. 14, 1998. ``I daresay that any subsequent merger _ of this or
similar magnitude _ between long- distance firms in the near future
should be judged quite differently than the merger before us
today.''
</P>
</TEXT>
