<HEADLINE>
HICKS BEGINS QUEST FOR MORE HARDWARE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There are two trophies in Tom Hicks' favorite dream.
One is a Stanley Cup. The other piece of glittering hardware is a
World Series trophy.
</P>
<P>
   With the Stanley Cup already belonging to his Stars, Hicks'
Texas Rangers began their quest to make the second half of his
dream come true Wednesday night, facing the New York Yankees in the
opening game of their best-of-five American League divisional
series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't given up on the dream of doing both in the same
year,'' Hicks said as he stood behind the batting cage while the
Rangers took batting practice before the game Wednesday night. ``It
doesn't get much better than this.''
</P>
<P>
   Hicks' youngest son, William, making his first trip to Yankee
Stadium, stood beside his father, wide-eyed as the elder Hicks
talked about the ballpark before it was renovated in the mid-1970s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came here to watch the Cowboys play a football game when I
was in my 20s,'' Hick said, ``but I'd never seen a baseball game
here until the playoffs last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Hicks has had a golden touch since venturing into sports
ownership three years ago when he purchased the Stars. They've won
two President's Cups for posting the best regular-season record in
the NHL and added the Stanley Cup in June.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers have won two consecutive division titles under his
ownership.
</P>
<P>
   The playoff series opened under overcast skies and with cool
temperatures expected to dip into the mid-40s, which wasn't helping
a long list of Rangers players suffering from flu-like symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've probably had 15 players affected in various ways,'' team
physician Dr. John Conway said, ``but they can all play.''
</P>
<P>
   Yankee fans were chirping at second baseman Mark McLemore for a
quote in yesterday's ``New York Post'' in which McLemore said,
``We're going to win. It's as simple as that.''
</P>
<P>
   The quote came from a ``Star-Telegram'' column from Anaheim over
the weekend, and McLemore was not happy that it was made to appear
that he said it during Monday's workout session at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd never come here and say something like that,'' McLemore
said. ``I don't like to stir these people up any more than they
already are.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
