<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-FINLEY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINLEY READY TO TAKE CHARGE FOR MAVERICKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ He used to be a quiet, unassuming leader. But Michael
Finley has decided to come out of seclusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the guy who is going to go out there and get in people's
faces this year and tell them when they're doing the right things
and when they're doing the wrong things,'' Finley said. ``That's
definitely me.
</P>
<P>
   ``My game is going to speak for itself. But as far as being
vocal, I'll be that guy this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Finley, a 6-foot-7 guard, has been the team's leader, averaging
at least 20 points per game the past two seasons. The last Dallas
Mavericks player to accomplish that was Mark Aguirre in 1987-89.
Becoming more of a team leader, Finley said, is ``a role that I've
kind of earned.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't given to me when I first got here (on Dec. 26, 1996
in the Jason Kidd trade). But through my actions, playing and
attitude, it's just something I think I've earned.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also something the Mavericks need. A.C. Green served as the
team's vocal leader last season, but he was shipped to the Los
Angeles Lakers in a sign-and-trade deal for Sean Rooks.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Don Nelson and other Mavericks players sounded grateful to
hear Finley voice his intentions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been trying to get him to do that every since I got here,
so if he feels that way, that's a real positive,'' Nelson said.
``He's my captain. So it's good to have your captain be your
leader.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad, because I've been trying to get him to do that for
two years,'' forward Cedric Ceballos said. ``He's such a quiet guy,
and he doesn't really want to become vocal.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just wants to work hard and have everybody come along with
him. But sometimes you can't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   And why not?
</P>
<P>
   ``People see that you care, but you've also got to let them know
about what's going on and the great opportunities for them,''
Ceballos said. ``So if you keep blossoming and put yourself in the
position like Michael, everybody's got to follow the guy. He's a
franchise guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Finley, who is fourth on the NBA's active Ironman list with 297
consecutive games played, knows he can't transform the Mavericks
into winners overnight or by himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that has shown throughout the Dallas Mavericks'
organization for years, before I was even here, that one guy can't
take a team all the way,'' Finley said. ``It's just going to take a
complete team effort, and hopefully everybody in this gym is on the
same page in trying to get our team better.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that he has increased his own role, Finley knows he will be
under the microscope. Then again, so will the Mavericks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always had high expectations,'' Finley said. ``My main
goal is to win a championship, no matter what team I'm with. But
realistically, I know that _ not being far-fetched _ it's going to
be hard for this team to get there.
</P>
<P>
   ``My expectations for this team is definitely to improve each
and every game, and each and every practice. I think if we do that,
we can make some noise this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially with Finley as a vocal leader. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
