<HEADER>
A7879 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-ANDERSON-COLUMN-N     10-06 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: ROOT FOR AN E-Z PASS PLAYOFF 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ That other Noo Yawk baseball team reappeared on
Tuesday night in all its usual October splendor.
</P>
<P>
   You know, the one with its name on the Bronx stadium where it
plays but no names on the back of the uniforms the players wear;
the one that was mostly out of sight and out of mind while the Noo
Yawk team in Queens did its Lazarus impersonation.
</P>
<P>
   That other Noo Yawk team was back in the Bronx where it belongs,
back doing what it did both last year and three years ago before
winning the World Series: tormenting the Texas Rangers, 8-0, in the
opener of their American League division series.
</P>
<P>
   If anybody still doubts that center fielder Bernie Williams is
worth his seven-year $87.5 million contract, he was a bargain on
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   In the third inning, his sliding one-hand catch of Juan
Gonzalez's liner saved El Duque Hernandez's 1-0 lead. In the fifth,
his two-run double extended the lead to 3-0. In the sixth, he
stretched it to 6-0 with a three-run homer, his 10th on the
post-season stage. In the eighth, his single made it 8-0.
</P>
<P>
   Noo Yawk baseball has never had it so good. Even though they've
been neighbors for nearly 40 years, that other team in the Bronx
and the Queens team have never before been together in the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   And that other team in the Bronx didn't seem to mind that the
Queens team had upstaged it for the last two weeks, at least David
Cone didn't. He's the Bronx right-hander who pitched a perfect game
this season, but in 1988 he was 20-3 with a 2.22 earnedrun average
for the Queens team the previous time it went to the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm rooting for the Mets _ as a friend of Johnny Franco,''
Cone said, referring to the Bensohnurst left-hander who now lives
on Staten Island. ``Who can't root for him?''
</P>
<P>
   Cone and Franco were teammates in Queens for three seasons
before Cone was shipped to Toronto, where he was briefly a teammate
of Al Leiter, who Monday night pitched the Queens team into the
playoffs with a 5-0 two-hitter in the wild-card playoff in
Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice for Al and Johnny to be the center of attention,
especially Johnny,'' Cone said. ``You can count me as one of the
guys who says Johnny doesn't get the credit he deserves. He's had a
remarkable career and he's taken more abuse than he deserves.''
</P>
<P>
   As a year-round Noo Yawker, Cone is rooting for what every Noo
Yawker, no matter what their borough, is rooting for _ a Subway
Series between that other team in the Bronx and the Lazarus
impersonators in Queens.
</P>
<P>
   But as the millenium approaches, Subway Series is a misnomer.
Subway Series was the nickname for the World Series half a century
ago when that other team in the Bronx played those ``Boys of
Summer'' teams in Brooklyn or that Noo Yawk team in upper Manhattan
where the Polo Grounds apartments stand now.
</P>
<P>
   Now that was Noo Yawk baseball at its best.
</P>
<P>
   That other team in the Bronx frustrated those ``Boys of Summer''
teams five out of six from 1947 to 1956, and whacked that Manhattan
one out of one in 1951 after ``The Little Miracle of Coogan's
Bluff'' _ Bobby Thomson's home run off Ralph Branca that some
Brooklyn people still won't talk about without weeping.
</P>
<P>
   But as the millenium approaches, if that other team in the Bronx
and the Lazarus impersonators were to get to the World Series later
this month, it wouldn't be a Subway Series as much as an E-Z Pass
Playoff across the Triborough Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to dream on, I think a Subway Series would be
great for the people of New York,'' said Joe Torre, the Bronx
dugout philosopher. ``If we were lucky enough to get there and the
Mets were lucky enough to get there, well, there's an advantage and
a disadvantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have people that you'd need tickets for; that's the
disadvantage. The advantage would be you sleep in your same bed
every night. That would be O.K., but it would be weird. Of course,
I grew up that way.''
</P>
<P>
   When Torre was a youngster in Brooklyn, he lived through those
seven Subway Series from 1947 through 1956.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up with the Yankees and the Dodgers, or the Yankees and
the Giants; it was always a Subway Series,'' he said. ``In my
teen-age years, I thought that was the way it was supposed to be.''
</P>
<P>
   And maybe a Subway Series _ oops, an E-Z Pass Playoff _ will
materialize this October. Maybe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-99 0030EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
