<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
EFFECT OF SPRINT-MCI MERGER ON KC AREA REMAINS UNCLEAR 
</HEADLINE>
 BC- KC-SPRINT-2TAKES-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TED SICKINGER, MIKE McGRAW and ERIC PALMER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Telecom gurus call it a marriage made in heaven.
</P>
<P>
   But it will be months, or even years, before it is clear how the
$129 billion merger of Sprint Corp. and MCI WorldCom Inc. will
affect the heavily Sprint-dependent Kansas City economy.
</P>
<P>
   Until a jammed news conference Tuesday at the Sheraton New York
hotel in midtown Manhattan, both companies had been so quiet about
a possible merger, you could hear a pin drop.
</P>
<P>
   And even as two former rivals stood shoulder to shoulder to
unveil the largest merger in business history, they offered few
concrete details about what Kansas City, and the 18,789 employees
that call the area home, could expect in the years to come.
</P>
<P>
   The message Tuesday from MCI WorldCom Chief Executive Bernard J.
Ebbers and Sprint Chief Executive William T. Esrey was all about
expansion.
</P>
<P>
   ``This merger is about growth, growth in services for customers,
financial growth for our investors and, importantly, growth
opportunities for our employees,'' Ebbers said before a crush of
financial journalists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Together, Sprint and WorldCom are poised to provide customers
with the broadest possible array of services ever assembled by one
company,'' Esrey added. ``That's the key to this transaction. It's
what customers around the world want _ the ability to one-stop shop
for wireless and wire line, voice, high-speed data and Internet
services.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't help but be caught up by the excitement in this
room,'' Esrey said. ``The upside potential for our new company is
nearly limitless.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sheraton's lobby was a testament to what the merger is
about, full of business people talking on wireless phones, ringing
the register for the new communications conglomerate.
</P>
<P>
   The atmosphere was considerably more subdued Tuesday morning at
Sprint's building at 9300 Metcalf Ave., where Michael Fuller,
president of Sprint's local-telephone division, held a local news
conference.
</P>
<P>
   Stone-faced Sprint employees crowded around journalists and
stood four deep along the balcony that overlooks the building's
lobby, trying to catch clues as to what's to become of their jobs
and their respective divisions as the companies meld operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``What assurance, if any, do the Sprint employees who run the
long-distance network have that MCI WorldCom won't simply retain
the fiber and the switches and lose the Sprint employees?'' one
employee asked.
</P>
<P>
   Fuller hesitated to offer specifics but repeatedly went back to
the big picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``As Mr. Ebbers said today, he fully expects the broader
WorldCom enterprise to continue to grow in its employee head
count,'' Fuller said. ``We anticipate growing on the order of
multiple billions of dollars every year. On that kind of growth
trajectory, we're going to be looking for good people.'' Sprint
divisions
</P>
<P>
   The combined company, which will be called simply WorldCom, is
expected to post revenues of more than $50 billion and will have
140,000 employees worldwide serving more than 40 million customers,
Ebbers said.
</P>
<P>
   When the deal closes, possibly in the second half of 2000, Esrey
is expected to become the chairman of the combined company, with
his office in the Kansas City area. Ebbers will assume the title of
chief executive, with the more active role in the day-to-day
operation of the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a strong believer that there is one person who, in the
end, has to call the shots: the CEO,'' Esrey said in a meeting with
two reporters after the news conference. ``That is Bernie Ebbers.''
</P>
<P>
   Ronald LeMay, Sprint president, will be chief operations officer
of WorldCom. The roles of other senior managers have not been
determined, but Ebbers said his existing management team was drawn
from the companies he had acquired in the past.
</P>
<P>
   At the local news conference, Fuller said significant parts of
the combined company still would be run out of Kansas City,
specifically the Sprint PCS wireless operations; the company's
local telephone operations; its equipment subsidiary, Sprint North
Supply; and Sprint publishing and advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint PCS employs about 15,200 nationally and 3,384 locally.
Sprint's local-telephone companies operates in parts of 19 states.
It employs 26,000 nationally and 4,759 locally.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts have speculated that MCI WorldCom, which has
traditionally shown little interest in the kind of rural markets
where Sprint's local-phone systems are concentrated, might sell
some of those properties to help pay for the acquisition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-99 0037EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991006.0011 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 00:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7883 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-KC-SPRINT-2NDTAKE-KAN     10-06 1247
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
EFFECT OF SPRINT-MCI MERGER ON KC AREA REMAINS UNCLEAR 
</HEADLINE>
 BC- KC-SPRINT-2NDTAKE-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TED SICKINGER, MIKE McGRAW and ERIC PALMER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fuller said he thought that was unlikely, as local customers
were becoming far more valuable, particularly as telephone
companies begin to sell them bundles of services.
</P>
<P>
   The outlook for Sprint's long-distance division is less certain.
The division employs about 4,000 locally and generated almost 60
percent of Sprint's revenues in 1998. From the back-office
operations of the company's network to marketing of its services,
the two companies clearly overlap and offer opportunities to seek
savings.
</P>
<P>
   Fuller said MCI's long-distance operation had substantially the
same distribution of services in the same markets around the
country, but that wouldn't necessarily mean a large reduction in
the long-distance work force.
</P>
<P>
   He had few details on how the networks would be melded but said,
``Components of the long-distance business would likely stay
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Sprint employs about 4,100 at its corporate headquarters in the
Kansas City area. And although Fuller stressed that MCI WorldCom
was a decentralized operation, the new company will be based in
Clinton, Miss., with extensive operations at MCI WorldCom's new
campus near Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Even though construction of Sprint's new office campus in
Overland Park will proceed, many of the company's legal, finance,
regulatory and administrative positions in Kansas City could be
vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, with the merger we expect to realize a lot of
synergies, and as you might expect, many of those synergies come in
the administrative and support functions of the company,'' Fuller
said. ``Change is probably inevitable in those areas of the
company....The approach we're going to take is to take the best and
brightest of our respective organizations.''
</P>
<P>
   The companies already project annual cash savings of $1.9
billion in 2001, the first full year of operation. They plan to
combine domestic and international long-distance traffic and avoid
local access charges that were formerly paid to regional Bell
companies.
</P>
<P>
   The companies think savings from the merger could rise to $3
billion a year by 2004. They also expect to reduce capital
expenditures by $1.3 billion in 2001 as they combine functions such
as purchasing.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether layoffs might be one method of making the deal
worthwhile, Ebbers said: ``The history of WorldCom is that, from
one year to the next, there has never been a net decrease in
employees.'' He said WorldCom's practice was to take talent from
the companies it acquired and ``produce the most competitive
management team in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We need good employees,'' said Ebbers. ``The challenge is to
get employees, not terminate them.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked later about redundancies between the work of some
Sprint and MCI WorldCom employees, Ebbers said: ``Do we have
redundancies? Yes. I don't know where they are.'' Joint ventures
</P>
<P>
   Sprint and WorldCom are already undertaking several ventures
together before the merger closes.
</P>
<P>
   MCI WorldCom will buy Sprint PCS service and sell it under the
WorldCom brand name. Sprint also will buy local capacity from
WorldCom in several cities where its metropolitan area networks
would allow Sprint to reach customers directly, without passing
calls off to the regional Bell companies. Finally, Sprint will also
send its international traffic over WorldCom's network and reduce
its reliance on Global One.
</P>
<P>
   The MCI WorldCom//Sprint alliance will mean the end of Global
One, Sprint's long-troubled international venture with France
Telecom and Deutsche Telekom.
</P>
<P>
   Esrey said one of the partners probably would buy Global One's
assets, adding he hoped it would happen in the next few months.
France Telecom and Deutsche Telekom already have said they plan to
sell their respective 10 percent stakes in Sprint and use the
substantial gains they will generate to finance international
expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Residential and business consumers won't see much change from
the merger in the short term. Long-distance rates will not fall
much further until the long-distance carriers see further
reductions in local access charges from the regional Bell
companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not much juice left to squeeze from that lemon,''
Ebbers said.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies have worked to develop nationally recognized
brands. And the combined company hopes to use them both.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both brands will be extensively used'' in the future, Ebbers
said. ``Both companies have a tremendous amount of equity in these
names, and we'd be foolhardy not to take advantage of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Sprint plans to go forward this year with the introduction of
its Integrated On Demand Network to residential customers in Kansas
City, Seattle and Denver. ION is a bundled service that will offer
local, long-distance and high-speed Internet through a single
connection to the home. It is Sprint's strategy to penetrate local
markets around the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``They see ION as a technology that we're ahead in and fits in
their strategy,'' Fuller said. ``We see ION continuing full speed
ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Ebbers said that the combined company would attack
local-telephone markets with vigor and that the merger would bring
competition promised by the Telecommunications Act of 1996 much
closer to realization.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer advocates are leery of those claims, having seen
unprecedented consolidation in the telephone industry since the
act's passage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not opposed to the merger, but in the short term, this
is not going to benefit business users,'' said Brian Moir, general
counsel of the International Communications Association, which
represents business telephone users.
</P>
<P>
   ``When large companies review their telephone contracts, they
typically send out a (bid) and get three responses, from WorldCom,
AT&AMP;T and Sprint,'' he said. ``When you take one of those three
away, that doesn't make for a more robust contract negotiation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Consumer Federation of America is outspokenly opposed to the
deal, as it thinks the merger of the two long-distance giants may
halt the decline in long-distance rates that consumers have enjoyed
over the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   Ressie Rigdon of North Kansas City said she had contacted the
office of U.S. Sen. John Ashcroft, a Missouri Republican, to oppose
the deal and planned to organize a letter-writing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is there some loophole in our antitrust laws that allows MCI
to do this?'' she asked. ``This may be right for MCI. This may be
right for Sprint. But it's not right for our country.''
</P>
<P>
   Ebbers insisted that previous statements by Federal
Communications Commission Chairman William Kennard were not
anti-merger and that the government would give the merger a
fair-minded hearing, and still protect the public and customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The burden of proof is on our side to show that this is a
pro-competitive merger,'' Ebbers said. ``Obviously we would not put
our companies at risk if we didn't feel extremely confident we
would be able to be convincing in that argument.''
</P>
<P>
   Esrey said he was on his horse in the middle of Colorado, in the
middle of nowhere, when he and Ebbers agreed on the basic terms of
the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bernie and I talked on an iridium phone, and it worked.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Not that well,'' Ebbers responded. ``I thought he agreed to a
lower number than we ended up at.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
