<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS ADD TWO, GIVE HARPER TRYOUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Despite a 3-0 start, the Dallas Cowboys are
hardly standing pat.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys owner Jerry Jones, who said the team must continue to
get better on the field to reach their ultimate goal, did his part
Tuesday, announcing two roster additions and bringing in former
Cowboys receiver Alvin Harper for a workout.
</P>
<P>
   Running back Robert Chauncey (6-foot, 252 pounds) and offensive
lineman Ben Fricke were signed. To make room, the Cowboys released
running back Sherman Williams and placed offensive lineman Tony
Hutson (torn knee ligaments) on the injured reserve.
</P>
<P>
   Considering that they already know what Williams can do, the
Cowboys said the addition of Chauncey allows them to take a look at
big back who can be a backup at running back, fullback and play
special teams.
</P>
<P>
   The interesting thing about the Chauncey is that he didn't play
college football. He played pro baseball for five years out of high
school before spending time the past two seasons with the Chargers
and Bears.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to bring back Fricke, who was released by the
Cowboys last week when they picked up Tom Myslinski, was an easy
one. He knows the offense and the Cowboys liked what he did when he
was here before.
</P>
<P>
   The startling news Tuesday was the sight of the retired Harper,
a star on the Cowboys Super Bowl title teams in 1992 and 1993,
trying out for scouts and coaches. Harper had failed stints with
the Buccaneers, Redskins and Saints after leaving the Cowboys
following the 1994 season and has not played in a year.
</P>
<P>
   Though he's a little overweight, the Cowboys said Harper seemed
to be in decent shape and had a good workout. However, they said
signing him was not imminent. The Cowboys already have seven
receivers on the roster and said they viewed the Harper as more of
a ``look-see'' to discover what kind of shape he was in in case a
need developed. GOOD NEWS ON MATHIS
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys got good news regarding cornerback Kevin Mathis, who
was diagnosed with only a sprained medial collateral ligament in
his left knee. Mathis suffered the injury in the first quarter of
last Sunday's victory over the Cardinals. He is listed as doubtful
for Sunday's game against the Eagles. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
