<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-SELE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS PUNISHES SELE'S FASTBALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Right-hander Aaron Sele threw his second-best pitch
to New York's Bernie Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Sele defended his decision to those who second-guessed him after
the Texas Rangers' 8-0 loss to the New York Yankees on Tuesday
night in Game 1 of this best-of-five American League Division
Series.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' switch-hitting center fielder lined Sele's 3-2
fastball into center field for a two-run, fifth-inning double that
gave the defending World Series champions a 3-0 lead, and the
Rangers never recovered.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great hitter,'' Sele said, ``and when you make bad
pitches, he makes you pay.''
</P>
<P>
   Sele threw seven consecutive curveballs before attempting to
bust Williams inside with a cut fastball, but the pitch caught too
much of the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had thrown him seven curveballs in a row,'' Sele said. ``If
you throw a good fastball in on him, you'd think you'd be able to
get him. I just left it high out over the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   The two-run inning began inconspicuously as Sele retired Scott
Brosius and Chuck Knoblauch for the first two outs. Derek Jeter,
though, prolonged it with a seeing-eye ground ball that eluded
second baseman Mark McLemore and rolled into center field for a
two-out single.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter advanced to third base on the ensuing single by Paul
O'Neill, and that brought Williams to the plate for the game's
decisive at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   Sele's first two pitches put Williams in an 0-2 hole, and Sele
hopped off the mound anticipating a strikeout after Williams took a
1-2 curveball. Plate umpire Jim Joyce, though, viewed the pitch off
the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``He called it a ball,'' Sele said. ``You've got to make a pitch
after that.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams eventually worked the count full, and Sele responded
with a curveball on the first of his two 3-2 deliveries. Williams
barely fouled that pitch to prolong the at-bat and lined the next
delivery into center field.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers center fielder Tom Goodwin, perhaps the American
League's fastest player, did not have a chance of running the line
drive down. The ball hit the base of the wall, and Jeter and
O'Neill crossed the plate uncontested.
</P>
<P>
   Sele struggled with his command throughout his 117-pitch
appearance. He threw only 55 strikes (47 percent).
</P>
<P>
   ``I never found a groove,'' Sele said. ``I was erratic with my
pitches all night.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
