<HEADER>
A7890 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBA-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-T     10-06 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A STERN LANDLORD SERVES PLAYOFF-EVICTION NOTICE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ This has become the same as a real-estate
transaction. The Rangers rent space in baseball's postseason, but
it's strictly a short-term lease.
</P>
<P>
   And then the landlord comes calling with an eviction notice.
That, of course, would be the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees own this property. Worst yet, the Yankees own the
Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Call U-Haul. It might have only been Game 1 of the American
League Division Series here last night, but there was absolutely
nothing to suggest anything will be different.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers will once again be packing up and leaving October in
a hurry. An impressive, doing-everything-right evening for the
Yankees ended in an 8-0 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, it's mind-boggling,'' admitted manager Johnny Oates,
who meant another run-production failure for his club. In October.
Against the Yankees. But Oates' comment also summed up an entire
collapse on this brisk Bronx evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care if it's Yankee Stadium or Yellowstone Park, we
can score more runs than this,'' Oates added. Well, maybe. But the
proof is missing.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever it's supposed to be that makes these Yankees less than
last season's world championship edition ... well, stop right there
with the jokes. New York was better than ever last night. Better
than they'd been in winning six of seven previous playoff games
against the Rangers dating to 1996.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago in October, the Rangers established every offensive
futility record in the postseason books _ fewest runs in a series
(one), lowest team batting average (.141), fewest hits (13). That
was supposed to be the Yankees at their best, until, that is, last
night.
</P>
<P>
   Futility is one thing. But before this series is over, the
Rangers could well lead the world in frustration. That what's Game
1 was all about. Being completely outclassed is frustration waiting
to happen.
</P>
<P>
   Blame a batting order that couldn't solve Orlando Hernandez _
but what Yankees' starter have the Rangers solved since the 1996
postseason? None is the answer. One run in four games is another
answer.
</P>
<P>
   Last October, however, the Rangers had solid pitching despite
being swept in three games. This time, Aaron Sele struggled for
five innings, and the bullpen collapsed behind him.
</P>
<P>
   And then there were a couple of ugly defensive lapses. Rusty
Greer played hide-and-seek with a line drive to left in the second
inning. He ducked just in time as the ball headed for the wall,
costing a run. That one will look hideous on the ESPN replay shows.
</P>
<P>
   But it didn't end there _ in the sixth inning, third baseman
Todd Zeile booted a two-out ground ball that cost a run, but also
the left the inning open for an eventual three-run homer by Bernie
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   What a hero Mr. Williams was. Six RBI and the defensive play of
the game in the third inning. When he chased down a Juan Gonzalez
fly ball in the third, it snatched away two runs from the Rangers.
And also seemed to break the will of a batting order desperate to
break through against the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   But it's strictly a rental agreement. The landlord is tough. And
this landlord owns the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Something, however, could have been cooking in the top of the
sixth. Down by three runs, there was hope. With a runner at first,
Rafael Palmeiro smoked a line drive that appeared headed for the
right-field corner. It might have meant a run, but at the least,
runners would be at second and third. From out of the Bronx night,
however, first baseman Tino Martinez leaped for the catch, then
tagged first, completing the double play and the double dagger to
any Rangers' comeback hopes.
</P>
<P>
   Pitching, defense and a clutch hitter in Bernie Williams _
that's how the Yankees win playoff games. But it has become a
foreign trifecta for the Rangers when it comes to these October
mismatches against the New Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, the top of the first may have been the turning
point for the Rangers. And that turning point was straight down.
The Rangers had runners at first and second with one out. But
Hernandez toyed with Gonzalez, throwing breaking balls on the
outside corner, Hernandez stuffed Juan with a strikeout. From
there, he worked around Palmeiro, and the walk loaded the bases.
But Zeile followed by striking out.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a key right there,'' said Oates. ``As much emphasis
as we put on getting on the board first, plus knowing the troubles
we've had scoring runs against the Yankees, well ...''
</P>
<P>
   The eviction notice has been served.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
