<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 01:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7891 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBA-RANGERS-YANKEES-T     10-06 0657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-YANKEES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS' OFFENSE LOST IN NEW YORK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Texas Rangers' offensive postseason agony just
won't go away.
</P>
<P>
   This team scored 945 runs in the regular season. But when it
comes to the playoffs and the New York Yankees, the Rangers are
still flailing away helplessly.
</P>
<P>
   Continuing the nightmare they went through last year, the
Rangers opened their latest Division Series against the Yankees by
getting shut out by Orlando Hernandez, 8-0, at Yankee Stadium on
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez, getting the Rangers to overswing at a baffling
assortment of off-speed pitches, allowed two hits in eight innings,
both by catcher Ivan Rodriguez. The Rangers have gone 22 innings
without scoring against the Yankees in the playoffs. They have only
one run in four playoff games going back to last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough loss, but we're not down yet,'' Rodriguez said.
``We still have four games to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Game 2 is Thursday night at Yankee Stadium, and the Rangers must
find a way to score against Andy Pettitte or risk going back to
Texas down two games in the best-of-five series.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating not getting any hits,'' second baseman Mark
McLemore said. ``But we have to keep this in perspective and come
back Thursday. We'll be good again. We're a good-hitting
ballclub.''
</P>
<P>
   Offense is the Rangers' strength, but other areas failed them as
well Tuesday night. Starting pitcher Aaron Sele allowed four runs
in five-plus innings, and the Rangers misplayed two balls
defensively that led directly to five of the Yankees' runs.
</P>
<P>
   Center fielder Bernie Williams did most of the damage for the
Yankees with six runs batted in, including a two-run double off
Sele in the fifth and a three-run homer off Mike Venafro in the
sixth.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, the Yankees simply outclassed the Rangers in every
phase of he game.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a great ballclub,'' designated hitter Rafael Palmeiro
said. ``We're not playing any slouch; they've been the best team in
baseball the past three or four years. For us to win, we have to
play well and capitalize on our opportunities. We didn't do that.
It's disappointing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers were hoping Sele could hold the Yankees early and
give their offense a chance to do some damage. That plan crumbled
in the second inning when left fielder Rusty Greer, with two on and
one out, lost Ricky Ledee's slicing line drive in the lights. The
ball went for a double, allowing Darryl Strawberry to score from
first and give the Yankees a 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't see it,'' Greer said. ``I was just trying to get
another angle on it. I should have gone back, kept the ball in
front of me and kept the runner from scoring.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams' two-run double in the fifth made it 3-0 and any chance
of the Rangers coming back died in the sixth when third baseman
Todd Zeile botched Paul O'Neill's two-out grounder for an error.
That allowed a run to score and Williams followed with his
three-run homer.
</P>
<P>
   But the way Hernandez pitched and the Rangers hit, the
second-inning run probably would have been enough anyway. Hernandez
walked six but got out of a couple precarious situations early.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had luck on my side tonight,'' Hernandez said. ``But I like
pitching with pressure. I never relax when I pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first inning, he struck out Juan Gonzalez with runners at
first and second and, after Palmeiro walked, did the same to Todd
Zeile with the bases loaded. He got out of the third inning after
Rodriguez singled and Greer walked, by getting Gonzalez and
Palmeiro on fly balls.
</P>
<P>
   That was it. The Rangers managed only four walks after the third
inning as reliever Jeff Nelson completed the shutout with a
scoreless ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to find a way to break out of this,'' shortstop
Royce Clayton said. ``Thursday's a big game. We can't afford
another loss.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
