<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 01:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7892 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBA-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX     10-06 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEY, ISN'T THIS THE HORROR SHOW WE'VE SEEN AGAIN AND AGAIN?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ New Yorkers have named a dance _ the ``El Duque'' _
after Yankees starting pitcher Orlando Hernandez, emulating his
high, snapping leg kick.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers deserve one, too. We can call it ``The Choke.''
</P>
<P>
   The primary move is to place both hands around the throat and
gag.
</P>
<P>
   Repeat that simple step, over and over again, and you've got it
down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Groundhog Day'' came around again for the Rangers on Tuesday
night at Yankee Stadium. Like Bill Murray in the popular movie, the
Rangers wake up on the same day every October and everything's just
as it was the year before.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez shut down the offense with a two-hitter, Bernie
Williams hit a three-run homer and drove in six runs and the
Yankees opened defense of their world championship with an easy 8-0
victory in front of a delighted and relaxed sellout crowd.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers arrived Monday talking about a change in attitude.
They were confident, they said, that they could win this
best-of-five series.
</P>
<P>
   Then they went out Tuesday night and again played like the
Yankees' best friend Rover: They rolled over and played dead.
</P>
<P>
   Overreaction? Maybe. But how could you watch Tuesday night's
pathetic performance and not have visions of last year's playoff
collapse?
</P>
<P>
   ``We've talked the talk,'' said a frustrated manager Johnny
Oates. ``It's time to walk the walk. Regardless of who's pitching,
you should bump into a run once in a while by accident.''
</P>
<P>
   The way the Rangers have hit the during the past two Octobers,
that's exactly what it would be.
</P>
<P>
   To lay it all completely on the Rangers' wretched offense, which
could muster just two Pudge Rodriguez hits and none after the third
inning, would be to miss the totality of this team's collapse
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Every time the Yankees needed a play, someone stepped up to make
it. Every time the Rangers needed one, someone was there to blow
it.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers had an opportunity to put a foot on the Yankees'
throat in the first inning when Rodriguez doubled to right-center
and Rusty Greer and Rafael Palmeiro walked to load the bases with
two outs.
</P>
<P>
   They'd talked about how important it was that something good
happen early. Here was their chance. Instead, Hernandez fanned Todd
Zeile.
</P>
<P>
   In the third, with runners at first and second, Williams _ him
again _ made a lunging snare of Juan Gonzalez's sinking liner in
right-center.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers never got another hit or advanced another runner
past first base.
</P>
<P>
   Alibis and excuses? Step right up. We can whine out a few if you
need them.
</P>
<P>
   Ricky Ledee's two-out, run-scoring double to left in the second
past a lunging Rusty Greer, who turned his head away at the last
second? Why, any second-guesser could see that Rusty lost the
sinking line drive in the lights.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never really saw it,'' Greer said. ``I was trying to get an
angle on it where I could pick it up. If I had it to do over again,
I'd go back on it and just try to keep it in front of me.''
</P>
<P>
   Derek Jeter's two-out, seven-hopper that trickled into center in
the fifth, just eluding a slow-reacting Mark McLemore? Hey, Mac was
pulled way over toward first.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' two-run double over Tom Goodwin's head two batters
later? Starting pitcher Sele, who deserved a better fate, and
Rodriguez were absolutely certain they'd struck him out on a 1-2
curveball. Home plate umpire Jim Joyce disagreed. The runs counted.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said it was away, but it was a close pitch,'' Rodriguez
said.
</P>
<P>
   Zeile's misplay of Paul O'Neill's two-out grounder in the sixth?
It was a reasonably tricky, sharply hit one-hopper. Anyone could
have botched it, except maybe a Yankee or most major-league third
basemen.
</P>
<P>
   A run scored on the error and Williams then made rookie
left-hander Mike Venafro feel especially welcome to postseason play
with a three-run homer, quelling any thoughts of a Rangers'
comeback.
</P>
<P>
   Not that anyone paying attention or with mental faculties fully
intact were having any.
</P>
<P>
   Even Oates, who said he slept 14 hours Monday night (why bother
getting up when you know you're just living the same day over and
over again?), resorted to desperate measures, using setup relievers
Tim Crabtree and Venafro in the four-run Yankees sixth instead of
saving them for later in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Like everything else he tried, that didn't work either.
</P>
<P>
   Go back to bed, Johnny, and don't forget to set your alarm. Game
2 comes along Thursday and if memory serves, there'll be a long
rain delay in Game 3 Saturday night back in Texas before the
Rangers meekly fade into the October night.
</P>
<P>
   But, hey, it's not like we can't use the rain. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
