<HEADLINE>
BUSH OUT TO STEAL MCCAIN'S ARIZONA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KRIS MAYES  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (PHOENIX) - Texas Gov. George W. Bush is laying the groundwork
for an all-out assault on Arizona Sen. John McCain's home turf,
opening the way for what could become the state's most expensive
and competitive &QL; 
presidential primary ever.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who just three months ago seemed to be conceding the state
to McCain, plans to return to Arizona on Oct. 18 for his second
visit in three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   His campaign is also searching for a state director and has
narrowed the list of candidates to a handful, including Mike Hull,
the son of Arizona Gov. Jane Hull.
</P>
<P>
   And, in the clearest sign that Bush hopes to strip McCain of his
political inheritance, Bush is prepared to spend more than $2
million on television ads and organizational efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are being very smart to pay more attention to this state
because it's an early primary state and because Governor Bush has a
chance to drive a stake through the McCain campaign,'' said state
Sen. Scott Bundgaard, R-Phoenix, a fund-raiser for Bush in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   McCain aides said they are undaunted by the Bush initiative,
believing McCain's status as an incumbent U.S. senator still gives
McCain home-field advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, we've got the grass roots in place, and now we just
have to water it and watch it grow,'' said Jeff Groscost, speaker
of the Arizona House and a paid consultant to McCain. ``It's a lot
more difficult to come into a place and cover it with AstroTurf,
which is what they've got to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Groscost pointed out that McCain's own fund-raising has
outstripped his expectations. The campaign had once aimed to raise
$16 million but now expects to bring in $20 million for the primary
season.
</P>
<P>
   According to Bundgaard and others, the Bush campaign intends to
expend approximately $2 million on a state that Bush has come to
view as both strategic to his success and winnable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that people in the Bush camp assumed that McCain is so
extremely popular here that he would win easily,'' Bundgaard said.
``I think they have since found that not to be true.''
</P>
<P>
   The most recent presidential poll conducted by Arizona State
University pollster Bruce Merrill found Bush leading McCain 31
percent to 22 percent, followed by Steve Forbes with 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes, who won Arizona's 1996 primary by spending nearly $4
million, could further complicate matters by again swamping the
state with cash.
</P>
<P>
   Bert Coleman, Forbes' Arizona campaign director, declined to say
how much the publisher will shell out in his bid for a repeat. He
did say that Forbes ``will do everything it takes to win Arizona.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We anticipate helping Governor Bush's campaign spend every
dollar they have raised,'' Coleman said.
</P>
<P>
   A three-way slugfest, experts say, could be calamitous for
McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to place tremendous strain on McCain,'' said ASU's
Merrill, who predicts that Bush and McCain will eventually spend $2
million to $3 million each in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's tragic, but that's why money has become so important.''
</P>
<P>
   The moves by Bush come just as McCain has emerged as Bush's most
serious rival, inching upward in polls in New Hampshire and gaining
grass-roots support in South Carolina, both key early primary
states.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has said he can win those states, then march into Arizona
for a victory and a bounce into the March 7 GOP primaries in
California and New York, where he is rapidly moving up in the polls
against Bush.
</P>
<P>
   But by forcing McCain to compete in Arizona, a state that by all
rights should be his for the taking, Bush could quickly sap
McCain's strength and end his hopes for the GOP nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about media and money and exposure, and there is no
question that it is going to put McCain at a disadvantage,''
Merrill said. ``It will, frankly, wear him down to the point where
he just does not have the money to compete with Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   By returning to the state so soon after his initial foray here
last week, Bush will again spotlight the state's importance.
</P>
<P>
   The candidate will travel to Tucson for a fund-raiser, then move
on to Phoenix, where he will deliver a policy speech and attend
another event in Phoenix's East Valley, according to Gordon James,
a Bush organizer in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   James attributed the new focus on Arizona to Gov. Hull's recent
endorsement of Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that strategy came about as a result of Mrs. Hull,''
James said. ``That was part of the deal _ that we would take it
(Arizona) seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   The campaign's search for a state director has narrowed to fewer
than a handful of contenders, including Mike Hull, who ran his
mother's gubernatorial campaign in 1998, according to James and a
spokesman for the governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks as though we are going to have an actual presence in
the state from now until the primary, which has evolved over the
last two weeks,'' James said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's (Bush is) being very aggressive and doing what
needs to be done. He's decided to go full tilt.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
