<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-WILLIAMS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS GETS JOB DONE FOR YANKEES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Even by George Steinbrenner's admission, Bernie
Williams was hours away from becoming the scorn of Yankees fans as
a member of the hated Boston Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   An 11th hour phone call from Williams during the off-season,
Steinbrenner said, allowed the two sides to iron out several
differences and get a seven-year, $87.5 million contract done.
Otherwise, the Yankees were ready to sign Albert Belle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely, he was pretty close. We thought he was going to
Boston. They made a bigger offer than we did,'' Steinbrenner said
Tuesday night after Williams went 3-for-5 with a single, double,
home run and six runs batted in to lead the Yankees to an 8-0
victory and 1-0 lead over the Texas Rangers at Yankee Stadium in
the American League Division Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then he called and said, `Can I do this? Can I do that? I
don't want to leave New York.' We got it done,'' Steinbrenner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year I had so many distractions off the field that I felt
that those three-and-a-half, four hours I spent on the playing
field were the easiest part,'' Williams said. ``Right now I feel
the same way. We're having a lot of fun. So I have no complaints.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who earned every cent of his contract by hitting .342
with 25 home runs and 115 RBI this season, got it done Tuesday
night with his glove as well as his bat. He rescued Yankees starter
Orlando Hernandez from early trouble with a sliding grab to rob
Gonzalez of a possible double.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez laced a fast-sinking liner into right-center field.
Williams sprinted to the gap and made a sliding catch on his right
knee, practically a carbon copy of Ricky Ledee's second-inning
liner that Rusty Greer misplayed in left field allowing the Yankees
to take a 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was getting ready to dive for it, but I heard Bernie
coming,'' Yankees right-fielder Paul O'Neill said. ``I was getting
ready to dive for it. I didn't know he caught it.''
</P>
<P>
   The catch saved one run and possibly two, which would have given
the Rangers a 2-1 lead and possibly a different outlook against
Hernandez, who dodged missiles in the first inning as well.
Hernandez went on to retire the next eight consecutive batters and
coasted to a two-hitter through eight innings behind Williams' bat.
</P>
<P>
   On consecutive at-bats in the fifth, sixth and eighth innings,
Williams recorded a two-run double, a three-run home run _ both
coming batting left-handed _ and a run-scoring single.
</P>
<P>
   ``He picked up the whole offense and carried us,'' Yankees
designated hitter Darryl Strawberry said.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' two-out, two-run double off the base of the
center-field wall in the fifth inning made it 3-0 and signaled the
demise of Rangers starter Aaron Sele.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the big blast in the sixth that must have had the
Rangers thinking ``here we go again.'' An error on third baseman
Todd Zeille set up runners on first and second with two out.
Williams victimized Mike Venafro with his 10th career postseason
home run for a 7-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, I thought I was going to have a terrible night,''
Williams said. ``Something happened when they said the lineups.
Something inside of me woke up, said it's time to play.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
