<HEADLINE>
MAVERICKS ASSISTANT SEES POSITIVE ATMOSPHERE FOR WINNING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The Stars are the defending Stanley Cup champions. The
Dallas Cowboys are 3-0 and the defending NFC East champions. The
Texas Rangers just won the AL West for the third time in the past
four years.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the, uh, Dallas Mavericks.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks have missed the playoffs the past nine seasons _
the longest current streak in the NBA. But those at Mavericks
headquarters say they aren't jealous because they haven't been able
to keep pace with the Stars, Cowboys and Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's positive that the Stars have done that, positive
that the Cowboys are looking good, and positive that the Rangers
are successful,'' Mavericks assistant coach Donnie Nelson said. ``I
think all of that stuff is what makes this attractive, not
unattractive.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson drew a parallel to his younger days in Boston when his
father, Don Nelson, played for the Celtics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back in the days of the Celtics when I was growing up, we
followed the Bruins and then the Red Sox and then the Celtics,''
Donnie Nelson said. ``That's what makes Dallas one of the top
sports markets in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to get up to speed and get with those other folks, and
it's going to be a matter of time before we do it. I see that as a
challenge.'' SMITH TO SiOUX FALLS
</P>
<P>
   Leon Smith might wind up playing this season for the Continental
Basketball Association's Sioux Falls Skyforce, Smith's agent said.
</P>
<P>
   The Skyforce drafted Smith on the ninth round (80th overall) of
the Sept. 21 CBA Draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point they hold his CBA rights,'' said Matt
Muehlebach, Smith's agent. ``So I need to contact them from a
bigger picture view.''
</P>
<P>
   Mavericks coach/general manager Don Nelson said CBA teams often
will make a trade to accommodate a player. So he's holding out hope
that if Smith plays in the CBA, the Skyforce will trade him to a
team closer to Smith's hometown of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks acquired Smith in a draft day trade with the San
Antonio Spurs. On Monday, they finally convinced him it would be
better off if he played this season in the CBA or in the inaugural
International Basketball League. HARPER RETURNING?
</P>
<P>
   Derek Harper hasn't reported to the Detroit Pistons training
camp, fueling speculation that the former Mavericks guard could
finally retire after playing 16 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   If that happens, Mavericks coach/general manager said he would
like Harper to join the Mavericks organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't talked to him, nor were we expecting him to retire
this year when he signed a two-year contract \Rlast year\S,''
Nelson said. ``But we have an interest in hiring him; I just don't
know when. But it probably couldn't be this year, though.'' INJURY
REPORT
</P>
<P>
   John ``Hot Rod'' Williams missed both workout sessions with back
spasms. Shawn Bradley worked out, despite a strained back. BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   _ The Mavericks spent the first half of their morning workout
watching a 20-minute video of the new rules the NBA plans to
incorporate this season.
</P>
<P>
   _ The father-in-law of Mavericks developmental coach Kiki
Vandewedghe died on Sunday.
WHO'S HOT
</P>
<P>
   Cedric Ceballos had a dunk, buried three consecutive jumpers and
converted a steal into a reverse layup in rapid-like fashion. WHO'S
NOT
</P>
<P>
   With one of the scrimmage games on the line, Sean Rooks let Dirk
Nowitzki blow by him for the winning layup, which infuriated
Ceballos. WHOA NELLIE
</P>
<P>
   Asked how Michael Finley fared with water sports when he visited
him this summer in Maui, Hawaii, Nelson said: ``He can't even swim.
The Pacific Ocean is deep. He's got a swimming pool and can't even
swim. He ought to be ashamed of himself.'' nn
</P>
