<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEDESTRIANS-EDUCATION-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. OFFICIALS DECRY HIGH DEATH RATE CROSSING STREET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY TROY ANDERSON  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Citing a report that Los Angeles County has the
highest rate of pedestrian deaths in the state, the Board of
Supervisors voted Tuesday to urge state and local governments to
provide more protection, especially for children walking to and
from school.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shouldn't be a death sentence to walk in Los Angeles,''
said Supervisor Gloria Molina, who sponsored the motion.
</P>
<P>
   The recent study by the Surface Transportation Policy Project
found Los Angeles County to be the most dangerous place for
pedestrians in California. In 1998 alone, 200 were killed and 5,541
were injured in the county -- more than one-third of pedestrians
killed or injured statewide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being hit by a car while walking is the second leading cause
of death for kids ages 5 to 12,'' said Gloria Duran, a board member
of the Los Nietos School District in Whittier.
</P>
<P>
   The supervisors voted unanimously to support more government
funding for pedestrian safety, to create a task force to examine
the issue, to ask the California Highway Patrol for stepped-up
enforcement near elementary schools in unincorporated areas and to
identify and improve the most dangerous intersections in the
county.
</P>
<P>
   The supervisors' motion also urged Gov. Gray Davis to sign the
Safe Routes to School bill sponsored by Assemblywoman Nell Soto,
D-Ontario, which would provide about $20 million annually to local
governments to improve pedestrian safety near schools through
methods including crosswalks, bike lanes, overpasses and pedestrian
paths.
</P>
<P>
   Gloria Ohland, the Southern California safety campaign manager
for the nonprofit organization that conducted the study, said some
of the $20 million could be used in the San Fernando Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money would definitely be available to improve safety around
schools in the Valley,'' Ohland said. ``About 20 percent of the
traffic deaths are pedestrians' (deaths), but Caltrans spends less
than 1 percent of its money on pedestrian safety.''
</P>
<P>
   The supervisors called for creation of a task force of county
and Los Angeles city officials to develop a plan to improve
pedestrian safety.
</P>
<P>
   Their vote came just days after an unidentified driver struck a
family of three Friday night in Panorama City, killing a
grandmother and seriously injuring her daughter and grandson as
they were crossing a street near their house. On Tuesday, police
were still searching for the driver.
</P>
<P>
   John Fisher, assistant general manager of operations for the
city Department of Transportation, said city officials are
interested in working with their counterparts in county government
on improving pedestrian safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had a little more money, there are programs and projects
we'd like to undertake, such as projects redesigning streets and
studies near schools,'' he said. ``We are already doing a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisher cited 23 programs the city has undertaken in recent
years, including education programs for 400,000 students a year and
``smart crosswalks'' whose signals are activated when pedestrians
are about to enter them.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all the things we've done, we've brought down the number
of pedestrian accidents by 30 percent in the last nine years,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Pedestrian injury incidents in the city dropped from 3,937 in
1990 to 2,752 in 1998, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``While there may be a greater instance of accidents in Los
Angeles County, the number of accidents, at least in the city, has
gone down dramatically,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Molina said the CHP and public works agencies in county
government as well as cities need to be more aggressive in
protecting children and other pedestrians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Local residents and school officials frequently request
additional traffic controls, such as crosswalks and traffic
signals,'' Molina said. ``However, the (county's) Department of
Public Works routinely denies these requests.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
