<SLUG> BC-FBN-HILL-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WE MIGHT FIND OUT IF IRVIN CAN BE A SUBORDINATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Yes, it's a bit premature, considering the
season is merely four weeks old, the Dallas Cowboys are undefeated
and that Michael Irvin leads the team with three touchdown
receptions.
</P>
<P>
   But the positioning needs to begin for this season not to be the
last in Dallas for the Playmaker.
</P>
<P>
   No, the Cowboys have not put Irvin back on the trading block. He
is not in coach Chan Gailey's doghouse. And he seems to be having
an enjoyable season.
</P>
<P>
   As a guest on Darren Woodson's radio show Monday night, the
chatty Irvin rarely let the host talk, kind of like days gone by
when Irvin hosted his own show and was the most visible player in
town.
</P>
<P>
   But these aren't the old days.
</P>
<P>
   These days Irvin, the team's all-time leading receiver and the
original ``throw me the damn ball'' guy before the Jets' Keyshawn
Johnson patented the phrase, no longer receives top billing in the
Cowboys' passing game.
</P>
<P>
   Free-agent signee Raghib Ismail is the Cowboys' go-to guy. He
leads the team with 13 catches for 288 yards. Irvin has nine
catches for 159 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Irvin, 33 and in the last year of his contract, has
tripled his touchdown total from a season ago. But the truth is in
the numbers. Ismail has more catches and more balls thrown in his
direction.
</P>
<P>
   It's the old double cross, considering the preseason hype of the
speedy Ismail serving as a complement to Irvin as the No. 2
receiver.
</P>
<P>
   The facts are, and the coaches will tell you, that Gailey's
offense has no primary receiver. They simply throw the ball to the
open man. It succeeds because of its unpredictability in being able
to count on several different weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The technical explanation for Ismail's early success is that
teams are leaving him with one-on-one coverage and still doubling
Irvin on the backside. In the past, not only did that take Irvin
out of the game, but it took the Cowboys' offense out of the game.
</P>
<P>
   The mystery is why defensive coordinators would rather shut down
Irvin, a playmaker as a drive sustainer, and chance a back-breaking
bomb to Ismail?
</P>
<P>
   Ismail's early success is also no coincidence from the Cowboys'
standpoint. Gailey likes, and wants, to get the ball to Ismail as
much as possible. That desire seemingly grows every week.
</P>
<P>
   What's also true about this season is Irvin's streak of eight
seasons as the team's top receiver is about to come to an end.
</P>
<P>
   This is where we get to next season. In all the preseason talk
of Irvin getting a rest and taking a lesser role, never was it
discussed that he take a subordinate role.
</P>
<P>
   But that is the case. How Irvin, who generally plays second
receiver to nobody, processes that and how it impacts his earning
potential on the free-agent market next spring will ultimately
decide his future.
</P>
<P>
   It's no secret that the Ismail-Irvin combo works well on the
field for the Cowboys. But the question is how it works in the
locker room and on the Cowboys' salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   SMITH AND LETT GROW CLOSER
</P>
<P>
   They say adversity can sometimes create odd relationships.
</P>
<P>
   And so it has with Cowboys cornerback Kevin Smith and defensive
tackle Leon Lett.
</P>
<P>
   With Smith being sent home to Dallas during training camp with
back problems and Lett suspended by the NFL until the Green Bay
game Nov. 14 for violating the league's substance-abuse policy, it
was easy for the two players to not feel a part of the team.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who will play Sunday against the Eagles after missing the
first three games, said it was a good thing that they had each
other.
</P>
<P>
   ``We became closer during that time,'' Smith said. ``It was a
blessing for both of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said they worked out together and hung out together. But
they also had someone to talk to about life, football and life
after football.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny, we both felt like we are at the turning point in
our careers,'' Smith said. ``Is there a light at the end of the
tunnel or is this the end? Both of us know we can decide our own
destiny and choose how we want it to be. Big Cat helped me, and I
helped Big Cat.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said Lett will be able to help the team out a great deal
when he returns. Lett is lighter and quicker than ever, Smith said,
and he is working out with a personal trainer and playing
basketball on a regular basis with former Mavericks star Mark
Aguirre. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-99 0137EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
