<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-RANGERS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES CRUSH RANGERS, 8-0, TO TAKE FIRST GAME OF PLAYOFFS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for rewriting throughout)   (sw) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Orlando Hernandez passed his manager in the Yankees
clubhouse on Tuesday afternoon and grinned, and Joe Torre suspected
Hernandez's expression was meant entirely to reassure him. As in,
``Don't worry, I've got everything under control.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez, confounding the Rangers with a pitch he didn't learn
until after he joined the Yankees last summer, held Texas to two
hits over eight innings on Tuesday night and the Yankees won
easily, 8-0, in Game 1 of the three-of-five-game division series.
Bernie Williams drove in six runs with a two-run double, three-run
home run and an run-scoring single, sending 57,099 fans home
believing that the Yankees are serious about winning their 25th
championship in this century.
</P>
<P>
   Game 2 will be at the Stadium on Thursday night, before the
series shifts to Texas for the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Some Rangers have suggested the Yankees aren't as good as they
were last year, but Texas might not be the best gauge. The Rangers
have lost seven consecutive post-season games against the Yankees,
dating to 1996, and haven't scored in their last playoff 22
innings, dating to last year.
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Oates, the Texas manager, was tense afterward, squeezing
his words as he spoke of Hernandez and his own team's failures
against the Yankees. ``Taking nothing against El Duque _ he made
some great pitches _ but we can score runs by accident,'' Oates
said.
</P>
<P>
   But it is no accident that Texas was scoreless on Tuesday night,
that the Rangers have managed only one run in their last 42 playoff
innings against the Yankees. The Texas lineup is stacked with
aggressive, powerful hitters who have a consistent approach at the
plate. Attack. Always attack. The political consultant James
Carville would fit in nicely with the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the Yankees limited the Rangers to a run in the
three-game division series and swept Texas by using the Rangers'
own aggressiveness against them, David Wells and Andy Pettitte
throwing changeups when Texas was looking for fastballs.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night, Hernandez stifled the Rangers exactly the same
way, with a changeup _ a pitch he did not throw until the middle of
last summer. In chatting with teammates, he developed a circle
change, a pitch thrown with the ball tucked deeply into the palm,
pushed by the hand rather than the forefinger and middle finger,
the effect a dramatic decrease in velocity.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez usually relies on his slider, the sweeping breaking
ball that moves away from right-handed hitters, but he altered his
tactic, as he worked carefully through the Texas lineup. Ivan
Rodriguez doubled in the first inning and Hernandez walked Rusty
Greer, and the hulking Juan Gonzalez strolled to the plate, always
capable of launching a ball into Monument Park.
</P>
<P>
   But with a two-ball, two-strike count on Gonzalez, Hernandez
buried the baseball deep into his palm, flipped it homeward, and
Gonzalez pitched forward on his front leg and swung awkwardly,
missing; Oates mentioned this at-bat later, in frustration.
</P>
<P>
   This went on all night _ a Texas hitter leaning awkwardly, the
timing of his swing shattered, the result being a pop-up or easy
fly ball. Hernandez was throwing his fastball about 90 miles and
hour and his changeup 71-to-73 mph and the Rangers were caught in
between. Of the 24 outs Hernandez registered, 15 came on balls hit
in the air, four were on strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez survived through some early danger. ``Luck was on my
side,'' Hernandez said later. After Gonzalez struck out in the
first inning, Hernandez walked Rafael Palmeiro on five pitches, but
whiffed Todd Zeile on four pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Williams was in a full pursuit of the ball within two strides,
eyes locked on the flight of the ball, his mouth widening and then
closing as he took quick and deep breaths. O'Neill had no chance,
Williams had to catch the ball. He dropped to his left thigh,
reached out and speared the ball with his glove about three feet
off the ground, sliding across the grass and leaping to his feet to
throw the ball back to the infield. The play saved two runs for the
Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro popped Hernandez's next pitch _ a changeup _ to deep
center field, and Hernandez began walking toward the dugout, head
down, quite sure of himself, never bothering to check and see
whether Yankee Stadium would contain Palmeiro's drive. The ball
settled into Williams's glove just before Hernandez stepped over
the first base line, El Duque respecting this superstition, as
always.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers never really bothered Hernandez after that. He would
get ahead in the count, and then the catcher Jorge Posada would
give the sign for the changeup _ waggling the four fingers of his
right hand _ and tap his glove against the ground, indicating
Hernandez to keep the changeup low. Hernandez followed his
directives precisely. ``He was just incredible,'' said Posada, who
had wasted no time in angering Hernandez before this game,
challenging the pitcher to concentrate when the two were in the
trainer's room. ``His control, he was amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Sele, the Texas pitcher, had a good curveball, but the
Yankees waited patiently for mistakes, and ultimately, they were
rewarded. Darryl Strawberry was on first base when Sele threw a
fastball over the heart of the plate in the second inning and Ricky
Ledee drove it to left field, the ball slicing as if Ledee had hit
it with an oversized driver.
</P>
<P>
   Rusty Greer, Texas' capable left fielder, closed on the ball and
seemed in position to make the catch, and suddenly ducked his head;
he had lost the ball in the glare created by the hundreds of
floodlights that rim the top of Yankee Stadium. Strawberry rounded
third and scored, Ledee had a double and the Yankees had a 1-0
lead.
</P>
<P>
   Sele becomes more vulnerable with each pass through the lineup.
Opponents batted .252 against him on his first 45 pitches this
year, .319 thereafter, and as Williams came to bat in the sixth
with two runners on, Sele was approaching 100 pitches. Williams
fell behind no balls and two strikes. Sele spun a curveball with
one ball and two strikes, the ball bending past the outside corner
of the plate, Williams frozen as Sele lurched toward the Texas
dugout, thinking he had an inning-ending strikeout. Ball2,
according to the home-plate umpire Jim Joyce.
</P>
<P>
   Sele tried to throw another curveball on the outside edge, but
it was ball three. Williams fought off another curveball, with a
foul tip. Having thrown Williams six straight curves, Sele changed
his pattern, whipped a fastball; Williams crushed it, far and
beyond the outfielders, both runners scoring. The fans roared for
Williams, who put the game out of reach with his home run the next
inning. They roared, for Hernandez.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
