<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 01:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7901 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-BRAVES-HNS     10-06 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-BRAVES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
ATLANTA _ Nostradamus, who developed a pretty good reputation for
predicting the future, probably would be reduced to quack status if
he tried to predetermine the Astros' course.
<TEXT>
<P>
   This team lives to prove everyone wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Prognostications of another sure-fire first-round exit were in
need of re-evaluation Tuesday after the Astros claimed a 6-1
victory over the Atlanta Braves in Game 1 of a best-of-five
National League Division Series at Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing against Astros starter Shane Reynolds, but any pitching
matchup that features Greg Maddux is a pretty safe bet for the
Braves. That myth was dispelled Tuesday when the Astros frustrated
and rattled Maddux en route to their first Game 1 playoff victory
since 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie left fielder Daryle Ward cracked a homer off Maddux on
the first pitch of the sixth inning to snap a 1-1 tie, and Ken
Caminiti's three-run homer in the ninth broke open the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros scored only two runs in seven innings off Maddux, but
that doesn't begin to tell the story of Tuesday's momentum-grabbing
performance. Maddux allowed 10 hits and four walks (two
intentional) but worked out of jams, including two bases-loaded
situations, until Ward gave the Astros the lead for good with his
homer.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, the Astros refused to pronounce themselves in
control of the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not in the driver's seat yet,'' Astros outfielder Carl
Everett said. ``To be in the driver's seat, you have to win three
games. Until we do that, we're just a passenger.''
</P>
<P>
   At least they're on the right road this time.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros wasted well-pitched games in losing Game 1 of the
Division Series each of the past two years. This time, they refused
to be denied, overcoming obstacle after obstacle in a victory that
was more hard-earned than the score might indicate.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros held tight to a one-run lead before sticking a
four-run dagger on the scoreboard against reliever Mike Remlinger
in the ninth. Any hopes the Braves had of coming back faded when
Billy Wagner sprinted from the bullpen to seal the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting this first one was huge,'' said Astros outfielder Bill
Spiers, who was 2-for-4. ``They handed it to us earlier in the
year, and it was important for us to show that we can play with
these guys. We still have to win two more games, but this is the
right way to start.''
</P>
<P>
   Ward, who didn't figure into the Astros' plans in spring
training, has been a major force down the stretch. He hit .348 with
five homers and 20 RBIs over his final 20 starts of the regular
season, and he's showing no signs of letting up.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds, working on three days of rest, was viewed as the
Astros' third-best option to start Game 1 behind 20-game winners
Mike Hampton and Jose Lima. But it's difficult to imagine either of
Reynolds' mound mates getting the Astros off to a better start than
he did Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me to get the ball in the first game gave me a lot of
confidence,'' said Reynolds, who was 2-3 with a 4.08 ERA over his
last seven starts of the regular season. ``I feel like I let the
team down in the second half of the season.''
</P>
<P>
   After Tuesday, it's safe to assume all is forgiven.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds held the Braves to a run on seven hits in six innings
before surrendering the mound to the bullpen, which combined for
three perfect innings to preserve the victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shane pitched a great game, and the bullpen did a heck of a
job,'' Caminiti said. ``Knowing what this team has gone through in
the postseason the last couple of years, it just felt good to get
this win. It was a big one.''
</P>
<P>
   The big one started off with a little play that turned out huge.
Everett led off the second inning with a surprise bunt base hit and
scored on Tony Eusebio's RBI single.
</P>
<P>
   Braves left fielder Gerald Williams tied the score with a single
in the fifth, but Ward's homer in the sixth put the Astros on top
for good. Ward had just three at-bats against Maddux before
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter who is on the mound,'' Ward said. ``He's
concentrating on doing his job, and I'm concentrating on doing
mine. I was just trying to hit the ball. I can't explain it any
better than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Maddux spent most of the afternoon in search of an explanation
regarding plate umpire Mike Winters' strike zone. The sound of
Maddux barking his disgust was often audible throughout the
stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maddux got a little frustrated,'' Caminiti said. ``He's a
competitor. He threw some pitches that he thought were strikes that
were called balls.''
</P>
<P>
   Everett said: ``He got frustrated because we were hitting him.
He's not used to that. He was complaining about balls and strikes,
but the times he complained, they were balls.''
</P>
<P>
   Everett's sacrifice fly in the ninth gave the Astros a run after
the Braves had intentionally walked Jeff Bagwell, and Caminiti's
blast put the game on ice. It was a sweet moment for Caminiti, who
missed 79 games because of an injury this season and didn't get to
show his stuff nearly enough during the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be able to hold my head high for a little while,''
Caminiti said. ``But tomorrow is another day.''
</P>
<P>
   It will be a day with a lot less pressure because of what the
Astros did Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
