<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 01:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7902 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     10-06 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
ATLANTA _ Think about this. A guy wants to give you $700 million to
join your club, and you have to hold a meeting to discuss it?
</P>
<P>
   Two meetings?
</P>
<P>
   Bud Adams put up $25,000 to get Houston into the American
Football League. Today, he's of the opinion Bob McNair should pay
$1 billion to get Houston back into the NFL. Hey, Bud, even
allowing for inflation
</P>
<P>
   It's crazy, that's what it is. But McNair, bless him,
desperately wants to return pro football to Houston, and so there
he was, holed up for a good while in his suite at the Hyatt Regency
on Tuesday while, downstairs, the NFL's expansion committee debated
the merits of McNair's stupendous proposal, which happens to be the
most money ever offered strictly for the ownership of a sports team
in North America. No team anywhere has sold for that much, by the
way.
</P>
<P>
   They debated and debated and debated, ad nauseam. Cripes,
fellas, $700 million. That's more than a pound of flesh.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, there apparently was no decision made per se,
although it remains hard to imagine how that could be construed as
bad news for Houston. The expansion committee members should sleep
like babies on what they've heard. They should be deliriously happy
to wake up today, pinch themselves, then rush downstairs and shout
it from the rooftops to the full membership: Houston is ready to go
and, therefore, the only way to go.
</P>
<P>
   McNair, for his part, said the finish line ``was getting
closer.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, whether 24 of the 31 existing owners will buy into the
program remains to be seen. Hidden agendas lurk everywhere. Adams,
for one, remains a skeptic. He understands the consequences of
formally opposing his hometown, hence he's saying privately he's
against expansion because there aren't enough good quarterbacks to
go around.
</P>
<P>
   Right.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, there was a time McNair said he wouldn't spend a nickel
more than $400 million for the privilege of becoming a member of
one of the world's most exclusive and expensive fraternities. But
he's a determined fellow and, as the chances of his winning the
right to own the NFL's 32nd franchise increased, he decided to
throw caution _ plus a significant percentage of his personal
fortune _ to the wind.
</P>
<P>
   It seems safe to say that, based on what we've seen to date,
nobody in my profession will feel any need to call McNair ``Bottom
Line Bob.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, all he and his partners, up to 24 in number, will be
doing is exchanging cash for equity in what smart people say is a
slam-dunk investment. As big as the NFL has become, it will only
get bigger _ i.e., richer _ as the U.S. economy expands.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, the man likes football. When Dexter Manley, the former
Redskin, asked McNair at the Houston Touchdown Club luncheon last
week how passionate he was about the game, Bob replied: ``On a
scale of one to 10, I'm a 10.''
</P>
<P>
   But he was referring just to the sports spectacle, not the
endless back-room wrangling, the unsavory aspect of trying to make
his dream come true.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regarding the business part,'' he said, ``I'm about a one.''
</P>
<P>
   McNair has spent $7 million and 18 all-consuming months
attempting to close the deal. Another three hours squandered
Tuesday night was no great loss given what has been expended, but
his impatience with the process has begun to show.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to bring this thing to a conclusion,'' he said the
other day. ``We've about talked it to death. We all need to get on
with our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after 7:30 p.m., a couple of hours after the meeting
began, NFL spokesman Greg Aiello wandered through the waiting area
outside the room where the 14 owners on the committee, commissioner
Paul Tagliabue and assorted other NFL poo-bahs huddled.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're making good progress,'' he replied, smiling a
politically correct smile.
</P>
<P>
   Several minutes later, McNair emerged from an open elevator _
causing momentary minicam pandemonium _ and disappeared into the
inner sanctum. At that point, the official wait for a puff of white
smoke began. It wasn't forthcoming, but it should be. Another NFL
spokesman, Joe Browne, indicated a recommendation being made is a
virtual certainty.
</P>
<P>
   At 7 a.m. today, the expansion committee reconvenes. At 8 a.m.,
it takes its decision to the full membership. McNair expects
several more hours of heated conversation before the voting begins,
but he says he's ``cautiously optimistic'' there will be a vote and
also that he will pass muster. In his mind, he has left nary a
``t'' uncrossed nor an ``i'' undotted.
</P>
<P>
   The myriad Los Angeles groups, in turn, barely have begun to
compose a coherent sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Still, you worry. Seven hundred million bucks won't buy what it
used to.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
