<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 01:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7904 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     10-06 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
ATLANTA _ This is why they brought him back. For days like this.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros had been here in each of the past two seasons,
stepping into the early part of October as if it were later in the
month and the threshold of the playoffs was the doorway to a
haunted house.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997 against the Braves and again in 1998 against the Padres,
they seemed to walk so gingerly, so quietly, even timidly.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Caminiti does nothing quietly. Or timidly.
</P>
<P>
   He is all bulging muscles and pent-up energy, practically
bursting through his skin. He is elbows and knees and bowed neck
running straight forward, almost a fullback at third, and you might
knock him down, but you won't keep him down.
</P>
<P>
   This is why they brought him back. For situations like this.
</P>
<P>
   It was the top of the ninth inning, and an afternoon when the
Astros struggled to manufacture runs was turning into an evening
when you wondered if they would let the end of the rope slip
through their hands again.
</P>
<P>
   Then Caminiti turned on a pitch from Atlanta reliever Mike
Remlinger, and it was like a dam broke in the Astros' dugout and a
short time later inside their clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Caminiti's tracer bullet over the wall in deep left-center field
was not the winning hit in the Astros' 6-1 victory Tuesday. But the
three-run homer was the blow that eased all of the tension and just
might turn out to be the jab in the ribs this team needs to stop
worrying about what happened in the past and concentrate on making
things happen in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Shane Reynolds had given the Astros the kind of gutty pitching
effort they needed right out of the box at Turner Field, working
six innings and giving up just one run. And rookie Daryle Ward
already had given Reynolds the slimmest of edges that he needed to
hold on with his first-pitch long ball off Greg Maddux to open the
sixth inning. And Doug Henry already had given manager Larry
Dierker a sparkling 1 innings of setup work before handing the ball
over to the Human Blowtorch, Billy Wagner.
</P>
<P>
   But if there was a difference between the Astros of the past two
years in the postseason, if there was a palpable feeling of change
in the air, it was there because Caminiti provided it.
</P>
<P>
   This is why they brought him back. To reach base four times in
five plate appearances, with a walk and two singles preceding his
homer. To have himself right in the middle of the action all
through the game, from the moment in the third inning when he was
caught off third in an aborted suicide-squeeze attempt with
Reynolds at the plate to a spot in the fifth when Atlanta manager
Bobby Cox intentionally walked Carl Everett to load the bases with
one out and he suffered through a miserable at-bat and bounced into
a rally-killing double play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't happy with the way either of those plays turned
out,'' Caminiti said. ``But once they're over, that's just it.
They're over. You don't think about it or let it eat at you. You
try to do something the next time.''
</P>
<P>
   That is the spirit Jeff Bagwell and Craig Biggio virtually
begged general manager Gerry Hunsicker and team owner Drayton
McLane Jr. to bring back when they campaigned hard for Caminiti in
the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``Craig and I both wanted to play with Cammy again,'' Bagwell
said. ``First off, when he's healthy, he's one of the best players
in baseball. Second, he brings a kind of, well, fire.''
</P>
<P>
   It is the heat of a blast furnace, a roaring inferno that has
nothing to do with fancy speeches or locker-room pep talks, but
everything to do with how he plays the game. You remember the
painful images of him going 2-for-14 for the Padres in last year's
World Series sweep, falling to the ground on almost every missed
swing. But you also remember how he kept getting back up.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the part of Caminiti that we missed for several
years,'' Bagwell said.
</P>
<P>
   That's the part they missed for 79 games this season while he
nursed an aching calf, and the part that has steadily rounded into
form since early September as he hit better than .300 and drove in
key runs down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   One big difference this year is the way Caminiti and Everett and
Ward have been able to give the Astros punch from the left side of
the plate. That had been a hole in their attack.
</P>
<P>
   Then in the ninth, he turned around to the right side and tagged
Remlinger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really didn't think anything when I first hit it,'' Caminiti
said. ``I was too busy trying to run the bases. It was a line
drive, and I didn't know it was going out. Then I got around first
base, looked up and saw it bouncing back onto the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, `That's cool.'''
</P>
<P>
   So it's 1-0 Astros with an attitude.
</P>
<P>
   This is why they brought him back.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
