<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 01:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7905 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      10-06 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
ATLANTA _ You win a playoff series like this.
</P>
<P>
   You get more than you might have expected out of starter Shane
Reynolds. You beat the other team's ace. You get a clutch home run
from the phenom, Daryle Ward, and you get what you paid for from
Ken Caminiti _ a 3-for-4 day with a towering, clinching bomb in the
ninth inning.
</P>
<P>
   You play an all-around loose, confident, smart game like maybe
you hadn't played in the postseason since the days of Mike Scott's
split-finger dancing in the air and Billy Hatcher sending one deep
inside the left-field foul pole in the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   And then you hand the ball over to Kid Heat _ Billy Wagner _ and
sit back and enjoy the confused, tormented looks on the faces of
the final three Atlanta Braves batters.
</P>
<P>
   But more than anything, you get people like relievers Trever
Miller and Doug Henry to redefine their long seasons in a single,
memorable day. You get more than you ever expected from those you
least expected to see come up clutch.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was big, big, big,'' said Henry, speaking as much on a
personal level as for what it means to the team. ``It was important
to me that they showed so much faith in what I could do.''
</P>
<P>
   Rest assured, if the Astros go on to take this series from the
National League's team of the decade, they should remember the
performances of Miller and Henry on Tuesday as the spark to it all.
</P>
<P>
   Miller and Henry were ``setup men'' in more ways than one,
pitching two clutch and perfect innings in what would be a 6-1
Astros win at Turner Field, and perfectly setting up the pitching
staff for the rest of the series.
</P>
<P>
   Until Tuesday, middle relief more than anything else was what
had the Astros coming into this Division Series as underdogs
against the mighty Braves. The Astros knew they probably could
count on 20-game winners Mike Hampton and Jose Lima to go seven or
eight innings. They knew they had a chance in those games if it
ever came down to a close lead in the late innings and it all could
be handed over to the reliable Wagner.
</P>
<P>
   But what they didn't know was how they could handle a game like
Tuesday's, when starter Shane Reynolds went six strong innings and
was protecting a slim 2-1 lead, but then middle relief had to be
counted on until the game went to Wagner.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the rest of this series has been set up for the Astros,
after manager Larry Dierker turned to these often-embattled setup
men and Miller and Henry came through with the postseason
performances of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Miller came into the game with a 5.07 ERA but was pitching well
late in the year and even lowered his ERA nearly a full point in
September. Henry, who missed two months of the season after
undergoing elbow surgery, entered as the pen's great unknown. He
had a 2-3 record and a 4.65 ERA, as much capable of blowing a lead
as setting down the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've pitched like they did today off and on all year,''
Wagner said of Miller and Henry. ``Today, they won the game right
there (in the seventh and eighth innings).''
</P>
<P>
   Said Astros slugger Jeff Bagwell: ``What they did was huge.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Astros win this series, you might even call it a decisive
first blow.
</P>
<P>
   Miller and Henry set down six consecutive batters in the seventh
and eighth innings, including a marvelous eight-pitch assault by
Henry in the eighth against the Braves' heavy-hitting Chipper
Jones, Ryan Klesko and Brian Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   By coming up with those great efforts, Miller and Henry set up
the Astros for something they haven't ever had against the Braves:
an edge in the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   It might also have set up this series how the Astros had hoped
it would go, considering Lima and Hampton are up next in the
rotation and the odds favor them taking their games into the late
innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they (Lima and Hampton) do what they've been doing all
year,'' Miller said, ``we'll be in great shape. I'd say we're in
the driver's seat right now, but it's a long way from over.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the pen appears to be in this thing for the long haul.
</P>
<P>
   Miller's and Henry's setup performances gave Dierker the luxury
of not having to pitch the more consistent middle-relief arms of
Jay Powell and Jose Cabrera. It also allowed Wagner to remain
available for today's 3 p.m. game if necessary because he pitched
just one inning Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Former starter Chris Holt also did not have to be used out of
the pen, and Scott Elarton, who could be used as a long reliever or
perhaps a starter for Game 4, also remains available.
</P>
<P>
   ``This gives us a great feeling going into (the rest of the
series),'' Bagwell said. ``Our backs aren't against the wall.''
</P>
<P>
   More significantly, lots of arms remain fresh.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
