<HEADLINE>
L.A. NFL BID LOOKS BAD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ That NFL expansion momentum that swung to Los Angeles,
away and then back again, may have finally left for good Tuesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL expansion committee met for three hours in a downtown
hotel here, and although they aren't expected to make a formal
recommendation until this morning prior to the full owners'
meeting, Houston seems to have taken control with a huge franchise
offer.
</P>
<P>
   NFL executive vice president of communications Joe Browne said
the expansion committee summoned Houston's Bob McNair to answer
specific questions about his organizational structure and
financing. They had already been wowed by his reported $700million
franchise offer and were getting down to the details.
</P>
<P>
   But Browne said Michael Ovitz spoke to the committee because he
wanted to stress the importance of the 32nd franchise coming to Los
Angeles, a notion that appears overshadowed by McNair's bid.
</P>
<P>
   Still, at least Ovitz was allowed to speak to the owners. Ed
Roski Jr. was left waiting in his hotel room, never even being
asked to speak to the owners, as Roski said he had been told he
would be prior to the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Only a confident McNair made himself available to the media
afterward, which seemed telling in itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good about our chances,'' McNair said. ``I'm cautiously
optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based upon the information I've seen in terms of the various
proposals, certainly prudence and good judgment would indicate the
situations ought to be for Houston.''
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz had promised last week when he and partner Ron Burkle
assumed the sales option on the nearly 100 acres at Hollywood Park
that he would return to Los Angeles with the next NFL franchise.
</P>
<P>
   With a bid that was believed to be at least $150 million less
than Houston's, it may take an unexpected move by the Ovitz team
this morning to head off a recommendation for Houston. Ovitz did
not return phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the owners are not going to rule anything completely
out until they must.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those of you who are experienced in negotiations such as this
know that anything can happen right up to when that 9 a.m. meeting
starts,'' Browne said.
</P>
<P>
   The expansion committee will meet first an hour earlier, and
Browne said a vote is expected to be taken and a recommendation
made for the next franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there will be a recommendation made (today),'' Browne
said. ``What happens after that in terms of the other 17 clubs, I'm
not sure.''
</P>
<P>
   It only takes a majority vote of the 14-member expansion
committee to recommend the next franchise, but 24 of the 31 owners
must give final approval.
</P>
<P>
   If the NFL was keeping Ovitz and Los Angeles in the expansion
game only to push the Houston bid up, it worked.
</P>
<P>
   McNair and Ovitz had been invited to the meetings to address the
committee. Roski tried to crash the party but could not quite get
in the door. He met with Commissioner Paul Tagliabue and committee
co-chairmen Jerry Richardson and Bob Kraft for 1{ hours earlier in
the afternoon and said he was told he would be given an opportunity
to speak to the committee that night.
</P>
<P>
   Roski and partner Eli Broad entered a bid of $500million _
$50million less than Broad's offer in August _ and $25million in
earnest money (the same offer previously made by Ovitz). The
proposal included $100million in bonds to be repaid by tax
increments generated by the renovated stadium and a $150million
loan from the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Roski and Broad had also questioned the wisdom of building a
stadium at Hollywood Park, which reportedly irked Ovitz. Roski was
predicting massive traffic jams in Inglewood if the franchise was
awarded to Hollywood Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it can be done there, personally,'' Roski said.
</P>
<P>
   Roski denied he and Broad were undermining the entire Los
Angeles effort with criticisms of Hollywood Park and confusing
owners by still trying to present dual area offers.
</P>
<P>
   Browne said Tagliabue would meet again this morning with Roski
prior to the expansion committee meeting because, ``Ed wants to see
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Owners were not offering any public comment. All owners,
Tagliabue and Ovitz, slipped out a back door to avoid the media
after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no back doors, only a number of front doors,'' Browne
said.
</P>
<P>
   The expansion committee had all the final numbers from each
would-be ownership group and was no doubt prepared to vote Tuesday.
But Browne said they didn't want the rest of the owners to have to
learn about their decision second-hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's cleaner to do it (today), so you walk right into the room
and not have it fueling around for several hours,'' he said. ``To
go in and be the first ones to tell the other 17 owners, rather
than have the owners read about it in the paper.''
</P>
<P>
   McNair said he can wait one more day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel real good about our chances,'' he said. ``Of course, I
felt good about our chances all along. I think we have a very sound
proposal. There are no holes in it. I think it's becoming apparent
to everyone it is solid and we're ready to go. Houston is ready.''
</P>
<P>
   McNair said he had not seen the Ovitz proposal but was generally
aware of its contents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it compares to what we're doing,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
