<HEADLINE>
INJURIES AND EXITS HAVE REWORKED THE NFL LANDSCAPE
</HEADLINE>
 REPORT-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Four weeks into the 1999 NFL season this much is already
certain: What was in vogue in 1998 has gone out of style like a bad
B-movie in 1999. At the top of the list are running backs,
quarterbacks, and dynasties.
</P>
<P>
   Terrell Davis, Jamal Anderson, Garrison Hearst and Barry Sanders
were the top four rushers in 1998, combining for 6,915 yards and 46
touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   But Sanders retired before the 1999 season. Hearst broke his leg
in the 49ers playoff game last January and complications with blood
circulation might keep him out all of this season. Anderson tore up
his knee against the Cowboys in Week 2 and is out for the year.
Davis tore up his knee against the Jets last weekend and is also
done for the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if this is the saddest day in franchise
history,'' Broncos owner Pat Bowlen said after Davis was injured,
but, ``I can think of three Super Bowls (losses) that were sadder
than this.''
</P>
<P>
   The run of injuries and unusual circumstances to Davis and other
great backs from 1998 has opened the door for new talent to emerge
at the running back position in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The league's leading rusher is Washington's Stephen Davis (400
yards, nine TDs), whose infamous claim to fame before this year was
that teammate Michael Westbrook sucker-punched him a few seasons
back.
</P>
<P>
   Second is Carolina's Tim Biakabutuka (366). He has been
injury-prone for much of his four seasons, but in a rotation with
Fred Lane, Biakabutuka has ripped off three touchdown runs longer
than 60 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore's Errict Rhett, who was run out of Tampa Bay, and who
began this year as a backup to Priest Holmes, is third in rushing
with 350 yards.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets' Curtis Martin is the only familiar face among the top
four rushers, with 305 yards on 79 carries.
</P>
<P>
   The quarterbacks who made things happen in 1998 are also out of
style in 1999. John Elway has retired. Chris Chandler has a bad
hamstring. Vinny Testaverde is out for the season. And Steve Young
is out with a concussion.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the new stars, one could say, are out of this world, or
from at least out of the country. Kurt Warner and Jon Kitna had
meager beginnings in NFL Europe. But both have come on to lead
their clubs to surprising starts. Warner, of St. Louis, leads the
league with a 125.0 passer rating. Kitna, of Seattle, has a passer
rating of 93.8.
</P>
<P>
   Brad Johnson couldn't get his job back in Minnesota last season
after an injury. The Vikings traded him to Washington, and all he
has done is throw for 1,191 yards, a league-high nine touchdowns
and no interceptions. Tennessee's Neil O'Donnell and Oakland's Rich
Gannon are other quarterbacks who were run off from their previous
clubs, but have responded this year with 90-plus passer ratings.
</P>
<P>
   The change in the elite at quarterback and running back has had
a direct effect on the change among the elite teams. Denver and
Atlanta, the Super Bowl teams from a year ago, have struggled
without their stars and are a combined 0-8. Meanwhile, perennial
losers Seattle and St. Louis have capitalized on the play of their
quarterbacks and are a combined 6-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are going to have to stop taking us for granted and
start preparing and getting ready to play a good team,'' Warner
said.
</P>
<P>
   Parity, in fact, has spread all over the league. Of the six
division winners from last season, only the Cowboys and Jaguars
lead their divisions this season. Four of the division winners from
1998 _ Jets, Broncos, Falcons, and Vikings _ are currently in last
place or share last place in their respective divisions.
</P>
<P>
   So through the first quarter of the last NFL season of the 1990s
presses on, the only certainty is uncertainty. At this point,
Redskins-Titans Super Bowl should not surprise anyone.
</P>
<P>
   THE FIRST QUARTER REPORT THE CONTENDERS Team Record Comment Packers
2-1 Best offense, defense combination Cowboys 3-0 Offense is good
enough to win a Super Bowl Bills 3-1 Bruce Smith and company have
one more Super Bowl run left Jaguars 3-1 Defense finally playing
well Vikings 2-2 Offense will start to play better, and watch out
when it does
THE PRETENDERS Team Record Comment Redskins 3-1 Best offense in
league, but defense will cost some games Rams 3-0 Teams they've
defeated are a combined 2-10 Titans 3-1 Not enough clutch players
on the roster Seahawks 3-1 Will make playoffs because of bad
division, but won't get far Dolphins 2-1 Fish are in trouble as
long as Jimmy has to play aging Marino
</P>
<P>
   FIRST-QUARTER GAINS The NFL players whose stock is climbing
after the first four games of the season: RB Stephen Davis,
Redskins: Beaten up by teammate a few years back, beating up the
league now. QB Kurt Warner, Rams: Former NFL Europe player was
working at YMCA before Rams came calling. RB Tim Biakabutuka,
Panthers: Already has 366 yards rushing. Best previous output was
427 in 1998. DE Greg Ellis, Cowboys: Longest scoring play is 98
yards, or, 29 yards longer than Randy Moss's. RB Edgerrin James,
Colts: So, the Colts knew what they were doing when they picked
James over Ricky Williams
FIRST-QUARTER LOSSES Four of the six division winners from 1998 are
in last place through the first four weeks, including: Division
Team Record-Comment NFC Central Minnesota 2-2 Offense, Moss both
slow out of the gate NFC West Atlanta 0-4 Is loss to Ravens the low
point? AFC East Jets 1-3 So far, it's been a big pain for Parcells
AFC West Broncos 0-4 Has any team ever fallen so far so fast?
nn
</P>
