<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EASLEY GETS INTO LONG BEACH CITY COLLEGE HALL OF FAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ The Anaheim Angels do not need to be
reminded of their old mistakes, not with all of the embarrassing
new ones they made during the ugly 1999 season.
</P>
<P>
   But an old one will haunt nonetheless Friday when Long Beach
City College inducts former Angels second baseman Damion Easley
into its Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Around here, Easley is best remembered for helping Lakewood High
to the 1987 String not found, STYL STYL.INL, PC 38B6
</P>
<P>
   12 LNs CIF 4-A baseball title and then taking the Viking
baseball team to the 1989 Southern California regional championship
title game against Cerritos. Easley hit .320 as the team MVP that
season, leading the team in home runs (8) and stolen bases (10) and
being a second-team all-state selection.
</P>
<P>
   In Detroit, Easley is an important part of the Tigers' nucleus
of talented players, which they hope will help the team contend for
postseason play. He's had three stout seasons since arriving,
hitting .264 with 22 homers, 72 RBI and 28 steals in 1997 and
earning a 1998 A.L. All-Star berth with a .271 average, 27 homers
and 100 RBI. He finished 1999 with 20 homers, 65 RBI, and a career
low eight errors.
</P>
<P>
   The Anaheim years? Easley and the Angels are still trying to
figure out exactly what went wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Easley was a 30th round draft-and-follow pick by the Angels in
the 1988 amateur draft. The club closely watched his progress at
LBCC in 1989, and as soon as his season ended, signed him and put
him on a fast track to Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels' gain was Dave Snow's loss. Easley had signed a
letter to play for the 49ers, but decided to turn pro when the
Angels offered a contract.
</P>
<P>
   Easley was ecstatic over the opportunity to play professionally
for a team in his backyard. ``I grew up a diehard baseball fan,''
said Easley. ``When I was at Lakewood, it was my dream to play in
the major leagues. I didn't know how I would get there, but it was
a goal. And I was never afraid of hard work.''
</P>
<P>
   Easley made steady progress each step of the minors, hitting in
the .270 to .290 range with speed (20-plus steals each season) and
better-than-average power for a second baseman. In the second half
of 1992, the Angels recalled him from Edmonton and worked him into
the lineup as a replacement for Luis Sojo.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take long for whatever curse there is on the Angels to
also work on Easley. He was hitting a robust .313 in 1993 when he
was forced out of the lineup with painful shin splints. He went on
the disabled list twice and missed the last two months of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, he was bothered by a sore shoulder that led to a DL
stint, and he finished the strike-shortened season hitting .215.
The shoulder and a injury bothered him in 1995, and he hit .216.
</P>
<P>
   ``I finally reached my dream of being in the major leagues, and
then it was injury after injury,'' Easley said. ``During that time,
I felt a lot of frustration and self-doubt about what I could
achieve. I knew I had talent, but mentally, I was struggling.
</P>
<P>
   ``You start to question everything. Was I doing this right? Did
I belong here?''
</P>
<P>
   In the majors, yes. With the Angels, maybe not. He was hitting a
meager .156 in 1996 when the Angels traded him to Detroit for
pitcher Greg Gohr, whose Angels career would eventually encompass
one game.
</P>
<P>
   Easley's career took off once he landed in Detroit. He hit .343
for the balance of the season and became the Tigers regular second
baseman.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was weird,'' Easley said. ``I've been asked what was
different a thousand times, and really, there wasn't anything. I
liked being with the Angels. I learned a lot about hitting from
(coach) Rod Carew. I guess it was just bad timing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once I got away from the Angels, it did feel like a fresh
start. I didn't know a soul (on the Tigers), not a single player or
coach. Maybe that's what I needed, a chance to get away from home
and grow up mentally.''
</P>
<P>
   There's been physical growth, too. At the invitation of Tigers
first baseman Tony Clark, Easley trained with Clark and a weight
trainer during the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony once had injury problems like I did, and he said a
trainer helped him get stronger and stay healthier,'' Easley said.
``I felt it couldn't hurt. There wasn't anything drastic about it.
It was a matter of being dedicated to get into the weight room.''
</P>
<P>
   The added strength allowed Easley to start pulling the ball
more, a sensible idea since Tigers Stadium was a power hitting
park. Easley posted the best 1997 power numbers of all major league
second baseman, and became only the fourth Tiger with a 20/20
season (20 homers, 20 steals).
</P>
<P>
   He also worked with a therapist on visualization, a
mental-confidence tool that asks the player envision hitting
against someone like Roger Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   ``You mentally put yourself right in the moment and make it as
lifelike as you can you see the pitcher, you feel like you're in
the batter's box, and see yourself hitting the ball hard,'' Easley
said. ``It's a sense of being there.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you visualize getting a hit off Clemens, then you're better
prepared when you do face him. It's helped me refine my skills. I
worked hard to be a success with the Angels, but a lot of my
improvement with the Tigers has been through the mental side.''
</P>
<P>
   Easley is honored and humbled to be inducted into the Vikings
Hall of Fame. ``I try not to gloat or ever get too high on what
I've accomplished,'' he said. ``That's usually when you start
falling on your face.''
</P>
<P>
   He credits his coaches for much of his success. Lakewood coach
Spud O'Neill encouraged him to keep playing, saying he had the
talent if he took the time to refine it. And Ken Gaylord, his
Vikings baseball coach who is now the baseball coach at Cerritos,
demanded all of his players learn and perfect the little things in
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted us to know how to bunt, how to hit and run, when to
hit and run,'' said Easley. ``I didn't realize how much he taught
me about baseball until I got into the pros.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (LBCC) memory that sticks out wasn't even a victory. We
were playing Cerritos for a state-title berth, and we had to win
one of two games. I had a very sore strained quad; any other game,
I wouldn't have played. But I played every inning of both games,
both losses, and we were really routed in that second game.
</P>
<P>
   ``As much as it hurt to lose, I was proud that I left everything
I had on the field.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
