<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAS BENJAMIN CHANGED HIS TUNE?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Charles Scarlett arose at 6 o'clock one morning
last month and was surprised to find his house guest already up and
pacing restlessly, ducking through doorways as a 7-footer must.
</P>
<P>
   Benoit, is that you?
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `I couldn't sleep all night,' '' Scarlett recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Benoit Benjamin had learned the day before that the Los Angeles
Lakers wanted to sign him, and even though only part of the $1
million in the one-year contract would be guaranteed, the center
who'd played 24 NBA games the past three years was elated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so happy to have this opportunity to play with the
Lakers,'' he said that morning at Scarlett's Los Angeles home.
</P>
<P>
   Scarlett is a retired Los Angeles Superior Court judge who
befriended Benjamin through common acquaintances in his Clippers
days, and has become his unofficial adopted father. Benoit calls
Charles Scarlett ``Dad'' and Charmaine Scarlett ``Mom.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's going to work hard (with the Lakers),'' Scarlett
said on the phone this week. ``I don't think he's going to let
anybody down.''
</P>
<P>
   So goes the latest story about Benoit Benjamin and why this time
will be different.
</P>
<P>
   Until you hear from Scarlett, you wonder why the Lakers are
taking even the smallest chance on Benjamin, the chronic screwup
best remembered in Los Angeles for bringing two left shoes to a
Clippers exhibition game in 1986 and for flashing an obscene
gesture at a booing Sports Arena crowd upon his first return to
town with the Seattle SuperSonics following a 1991 trade.
</P>
<P>
   You wonder if 7-foot backup centers are so hard to find that the
Lakers are willing to dredge up a living relic of one of the worst
deals in recent franchise history, the 1993 trade that brought
Benjamin back from Seattle along with guard Doug Christie in
exchange for forward Sam Perkins.
</P>
<P>
   Did the Lakers sign Benjamin on Sept.29 because they envision
him surviving the cutdowns from 19 players in training camp to the
12-man regular-season roster, or because Shaquille O'Neal needs a
big man to bang on in practice?
</P>
<P>
   Anybody who remembers Benjamin's five-plus seasons as the
quintessential Clipper and his 28-game stay with the Lakers has to
be skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say this,'' said A.C. Green, the Showtime forward who
returned in the offseason, the only player in camp who was with the
team when Benjamin was a Laker in 1993. ``Benoit has changed. He's
different than he was the last time he was here ... according to
what Benoit's been telling me all morning long.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope,'' Green said, ``his perception of the game and his
priorities have changed. We'll find out in training camp, for
sure.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in shape mentally and physically,'' Benjamin said. ``This
is a better Benoit now. I just hope and pray they (fans) will give
me a second chance. Everybody deserves a second chance.''
</P>
<P>
   The bald man wearing uniform No. 00 in Santa Barbara this week
is like the spit take, the banana peel and the one about the
bartender and the horse. A bad joke that never gets old.
</P>
<P>
   It's 14 years since Benoit Benjamin, an only child reared
primarily by his mother and grandmother in small-town Louisiana,
left Creighton as the third pick in the NBA draft and reported to
Clippers training camp wide-eyed, innocent and unprepared for pro
basketball's hard knocks.
</P>
<P>
   He played a few great games. More often he'd lose confidence in
the early minutes and sulk through the night. And he couldn't take
the boos. He said this week that the night he flipped off the fans,
``I was scared to be back in L.A.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles became an even scarier place when a Louisiana friend
was slain after witnessing a shooting in a liquor store. Benjamin
avoided the city and the bad memories for five years before
returning to live with the Scarletts while working out with other
NBA players at UCLA this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Has he grown up?
</P>
<P>
   His adopted dad says yes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's dedicated and hungry now, because of the maturity of
years and the fact he's had some financial reversals over the last
few years,'' said Scarlett, who said Benjamin was ``too trusting''
with the people who handled the millions of dollars he earned.
``And I think one of the things he understands is that he's been
given basically the last opportunity to make it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he doesn't do well, it won't be for lack of effort. I have
never seen anybody that's as focused as he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin does look in good shape. He said he's been running for
six months while waiting for an NBA club to call. He said he wants
to win an NBA championship before he goes and thinks this could be
the year.
</P>
<P>
   But if he makes the Lakers, this will mark his ninth NBA stop,
not to mention the part-seasons he spent in Greece and with Yakima
of the Continental Basketball Association. He made the same
promises in all of those places.
</P>
<P>
   So Benoit Benjamin remains a mystery wrapped in an enigma
wrapped in a ``Tonight Show'' monologue. The question is whether
he'll get the ring before the fans get the finger.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
