<SLUG> BC-RAC-HOLLYPARK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW HOLLYWOOD PARK OWNERS TELL PLANS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK C. GIRARDOT  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ The corporate owners of Hollywood Park put a
human face Tuesday on their venture into the California
thoroughbred horse racing business at a meeting with community
leaders, horsemen and the media.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Meeker, chief executive officer of Churchill Downs, the
company which purchased Hollywood Park this past summer, outlined
plans for the track during the lunchtime gathering of 250.
</P>
<P>
   Meeker and other executives promised the company would help
enrich Inglewood and improve racing at the slowly fading track.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many respects, Hollywood Park is the signature of
Inglewood,'' Meeker said. ``We thought that we could be a major
contributor to the community.... We have a deep and abiding
commitment to the communities we serve.''
</P>
<P>
   Churchill Downs' acquisition of Hollywood Park came less than
one year after Canadian auto-parts magnate Frank Stronach purchased
Santa Anita in Arcadia.
</P>
<P>
   While Stronach has begun to pump several hundred million dollars
into an overall renovation of the Arcadia landmark, Churchill
Downs' immediate plans are a bit more understated.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have $15 million to spend over the next couple of years,''
said John Long, chief operating officer for Churchill Downs.
</P>
<P>
   How that money will be spent on capital improvements remains to
be seen, Long said. The track will seek input from owners, horsemen
and patrons before plans are finalized, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood Park will also invest in Inglewood. The track will
donate $30,000 toward the purchase of Little League uniforms for
1,375 children in surrounding communities.
</P>
<P>
   Further, the company pledged $20,000 to the Inglewood School
District for students at all 13 elementary schools to receive music
training that was curtailed or cut by budget cuts in the 1980s,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, officials promised to hold annual food, clothing and
toy drives for the needy in the community at Thanksgiving and
Christmas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
