<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-WILLIAMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS CATCHES FIRE AS TEXAS FOLDS TENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bernie Williams glided across center field, his eyes
staring straight into the black night and his mouth opening and
closing while he sprinted after a deep fly ball. Williams grabbed
Juan Gonzalez's blast in right-center and slid across the grass as
he caught it. All the while, Williams looked in control.
</P>
<P>
   The nifty play occurred in the third inning, and it was just the
beginning of Williams dominating the opener of the American League
division series and helping the Yankees destroy the Texas Rangers,
8-0. When the Rangers saw Williams steal a hit from Gonzalez, they
should have known it was going to be another long and frustrating
night.
</P>
<P>
   With Orlando Hernandez stifling the Rangers and Williams rocking
a three-run homer, a two-run double and a run-scoring single, the
Yankees made Tuesday night feel like the 1998 division series or
even the 1996 division series. They did not let the Rangers breathe
again, mostly because Williams did his baseball imitation of
Michael Jordan as the most exciting player on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bernie is that type of player,'' Darryl Strawberry said.
``He's a complete player. He can do just about anything he wants on
the baseball field. Nobody in here is surprised by what he did.
Bernie has a tendency to step up in the post-season. He's real
quiet, but we know what he can do.''
</P>
<P>
   So do the Yankees, who signed him to an $87.5million contract
last year. So do the Rangers, who have been pounded by Williams in
the post-season before. Williams stroked three homers against the
Rangers in the playoffs three seasons ago, but he went 0 for 11
last season and then went hitless in his first two at-bats last
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, I thought I was going to have a terrible game,''
Williams said. ``I was feeling sleepy and it was kind of cold. All
through batting practice, I was wondering how I was going to get
through it. When they read the lineups and I heard the national
anthem, something happened. I told myself that it was time to
play.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Joe Torre explained that he was so shaken after his
bench coach, Don Zimmer, was drilled by Chuck Knoblauch's foul
liner in the fifth inning that Williams went up to him and asked,
``Are you with us?'' Torre told Williams that he would be fine.
</P>
<P>
   The next time Williams batted, in the bottom of the fifth, he
ripped an 0-2 pitch for a two-run double off Aaron Sele. He
followed that with the three-run blast and then the run-scoring
single. Suddenly, Williams looked to be in complete control.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like that lit a fire under him,'' Torre said. ``He was
a different player. That's what happens with Bernie. You never know
what's going to light a fire under him and you can't get him out.''
</P>
<P>
   As Williams strolled into the interview room with an ice pack
covering his left shoulder, he did not look so menacing. He looked
like the studious Williams that the Yankees see in the clubhouse.
But once the game starts, Williams is as electrifying as any Yankee
and as important as any Yankee.
</P>
<P>
   Williams does not like to dwell on being the highest-paid Yankee
ever, but there are definite responsibilities that accompany his
lucrative paycheck. While the Yankees cruised to a World Series
title last year, Williams admitted that he was distracted by the
possibility of becoming a free agent and by some personal issues
that he never disclosed. This season, Williams has no distractions.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as the pressure on the field, it's the same,'' Williams
said. ``The easiest part is playing the game. Last year, I had so
many distractions that the three and a half or four hours on the
field were the best part.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
