<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-OKLAHOMA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOOPS HAS TAKEN OKLAHOMA OFFENSE TO NEW HEIGHTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORMAN, Okla. _ Steve Spurrier Jr. took more than a passing
moment to decide to join Bob Stoops' new staff at Oklahoma coaching
receivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He offered me the job in mid-December, and I didn't accept
until Jan. 1,'' Spurrier said.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, it was a great opportunity to rid himself of the
behind-the-back whispers of nepotism _ that the only qualification
the young Spurrier had to warrant a position on the staff of a
major power such as Florida was the fact that his father was the
head coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were certainly strong and to a certain degree
validated,'' Spurrier said candidly.
</P>
<P>
   There was, however, something in Stoops' delivery of the job
offer that caused Spurrier hesitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me he had four (receivers) on scholarship, but only
two had played. And they had 20 catches between them,'' remembers
Spurrier, a former Duke receiver who worked with quarterbacks and
receivers at Florida. ``And of those two, one transferred. So I
knew I had to go out and find some people.''
</P>
<P>
   He did. To date, 16 players have at least one catch for the
Sooners, who rank third nationally in passing offense (341.8 yards
per game) heading into Saturday's showdown against Texas at the
Cotton Bowl. And all 16 have recorded career totals in number of
catches. Fifteen _ excluding that lone returning wide receiver,
Jarrail Jackson _ have also recorded career highs in total yardage.
In four games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing how many good receivers we have and completely
surprising when you come into a place where they were
run-oriented,'' said transfer quarterback Josh Heupel.
</P>
<P>
   Spurrier's gang includes Jackson, converted quarterback Brandon
Daniels, four redshirt freshmen _ three of whom were recruited as
defensive backs _ and a few running backs and tight ends thrown in
for the good measure of 1,367 yards on 121 receptions and 16
touchdowns. Eight first-year players have combined for 50 of those
catches, for 590 yards and six touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, quite a change from last year,'' said slotback Daniels,
the Sooners' No. 2 receiver (13 catches, 149 yards) who was the
starting quarterback in last year's game against Texas. ``I think
we have surprised a lot of people that we have guys here who can
catch the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   While many are surprised at the early proficiency of OU's
who-are-those-guys group of receivers, the consensus on the team is
that things can only get better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've made some pretty good strides this year,'' said
redshirt freshman Damien Mackey, one of those converted defensive
backs who has 13 receptions for 119 yards. ``We've got a great
coach in Coach Spurrier, but we've still got a long way to go.
There are a lot of things we still don't understand yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Distribution and a plethora of receivers are keys to the offense
the way coordinator Mike Leach likes it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like to utilize everyone's talent rather than just moving
receivers around formationwise,'' said Leach, who ran the same
offense as coordinator at Kentucky. ``If you throw a bunch of
people at 'em who can do a bunch of different things, that makes it
difficult for the defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how many linebackers and defensive backs (teams)
can put in, but it's hard for them to put in the best corner-route
covering linebacker and then the best option-route covering
linebacker and then the best run linebacker. But it's easy for us
to customize the offense that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've moved quite a few people in and out so far and we're
still finding out what people can do best, but we have a bunch of
young guys who work really hard and have stepped up. Josh has done
a great job of spreading (receptions) around. It's by design, but
there are times when I've had to lean on that more in the past than
I've had to do with Josh.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Cool Hand'' Heupel, a transfer from Snow Junior College, has
been the key.
</P>
<P>
   ``The number of guys we've had make catches has got to worry
defensive backs,'' said freshman wide receiver Antwone Savage, who
played quarterback last year in high school. ``If we've got five
receivers out, any one of them could catch the ball. It keeps DBs
on their toes.''
</P>
<P>
   Though all is relative considering OU's offensive philosophies
under previous regimes, the left-handed Heupel has already set
school records for passing touchdowns in a season (16) and
single-game records for yards (429), touchdowns (5) and total
offense (410).
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, OU's receivers come into the Texas game seeking
atonement for 10 dropped passes in the 34-30 loss to Notre Dame
last week. Stoops said those drops cost the Sooners at least 130
yards _ not factoring potential yards after the catch and the
potential first downs lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would think they're a little embarrassed at the way they
played last week,'' Stoops said. ``I've been pleased overall with
the receivers. But we can still run better routes and we can catch
the ball when we get it near us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our receivers are by-and-large young,'' Heupel said. ``But we
can't have them perform like they're young. We have to have them
perform like upperclassmen. And so far, they've been able to do
that.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-99 0206EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991006.0035 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 02:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7916 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBA-RANGERS-YANKEES-H     10-06 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-YANKEES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DANNY ROBBINS  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Talking to reporters Tuesday before the opening game
of his team's Division Series with the New York Yankees, Texas
Rangers manager Johnny Oates struck an optimistic chord.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball is a game of cycles, he said. And while the Yankees had
indeed dominated the Rangers in the teams' two previous Division
Series meetings, perhaps the Rangers' time had come.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a firm believer in the fact that the worm does turn,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   When and where remains to be seen. As Tuesday turned into
Wednesday in the Bronx, the only worms turning at Yankee Stadium
were under its hallowed turf.
</P>
<P>
   Riding the bat and glove of Bernie Williams and the gyrations of
Orlando ``El Duque'' Hernandez, the Yankees added to the Rangers'
postseason blues, taking Game 1 of the best-of-five series 8-0.
</P>
<P>
   So it was that the Yankees and Rangers reprised, at least for
three-plus hours Tuesday, the one-sided ugliness of last season's
Division Series, when New York swept a Texas team that managed to
score only one run and hit .141. The Rangers have lost seven
consecutive Division Series games to the Yankees, a streak going
back to Texas' first postseason appearance in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the Rangers collected only two hits, both by Ivan
Rodriguez, in the first and third innings.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the Rangers' most deflating moment came in the first
inning, when they failed to score despite putting two runners on
base with one out and their top run-producers, Juan Gonzalez and
Rafael Palmero, coming up.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the offense we throw out there, you're going to score
some runs by accident,'' a frustrated Oates said later. ``We had
some good chances early. When those fizzled, we couldn't get
anything going.''
</P>
<P>
   Yankees manager Joe Torre said his team has been fortunate to
get outstanding starting pitching against the Rangers, beginning
with last year's postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're so good offensively,'' he said. ``But it's like
(Boston's) Pedro Martinez (pitching) in the All-Star Game. He
dominated. With pitching, you can control the game. And we've been
very fortunate against this club in that we've pitched well as
starters. It's been pitching. Back when I played, in the dark ages,
it was the same way. Good pitching stops good hitting.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez, the Yankees' starter, went eight innings, giving up
only the two Rodriguez hits. Jeff Nelson completed the shutout with
a scoreless ninth.
</P>
<P>
   The batting and fielding star for New York was center fielder
Williams. He had three hits and six RBIs, including a two-run
double in the fifth and a three-run homer in the sixth. He also
made a running, one-handed catch of a drive in the gap by Gonzalez
that would have put the Rangers on the board in the third inning.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers starter Aaron Sele lasted just five-plus innings,
allowing six hits and walking five, and the Rangers' once-vaunted
middle relief was equally mediocre.
</P>
<P>
   The night started on an upbeat note for the Rangers when their
second batter, Rodriguez, doubled off the right-field wall. Rusty
Greer worked Hernandez for a walk, putting two on with one out and
Gonzalez and Palmeiro coming up.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez fell behind 0-2, worked the count even and then struck
out swinging. With first base open, Hernandez pitched carefully to
Palmeiro and walked him on five pitches, bringing Todd Zeile to the
plate with the bases loaded and two out. Hernandez quickly got
ahead of the Texas third baseman and struck him out.
</P>
<P>
   The third inning followed a similar script for Texas. With one
out, Rodriguez singled and stole second. Greer walked. This time,
Gonzalez sent a drive into the gap in right-center, but Williams
was able to reach it and make a marvelous one-handed catch.
Palmeiro's fly to deep center ended the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Sele struggled with his control early. He settled in for a
while, retiring seven Yankees in one stretch, but then gave up
three straight hits with two out in the fifth as the Yankees scored
two runs and took a 3-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   After singles by Derek Jeter and Paul O'Neill, Sele got the
count to 0-2 against Williams, the Yankees' cleanup hitter, but
couldn't close out the inning. Williams battled back to 3-2 and
then launched a bases-clearing double over the head of Rangers
center fielder Tom Goodwin.
</P>
<P>
   Sele came out for the sixth, walked Ricky Ledee on five pitches
and was promptly replaced by Tim Crabtree.
</P>
<P>
   After Scott Brosius moved Ledee to second with a sacrifice bunt,
Crabtree struck out Jeter for the second out. At that point, Oates
went to lefthander Mike Venafro to face the heart of the Yankees'
lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Venafro got O'Neill to ground to third, but Zeile couldn't come
up with the ball _ E5, 4-0. Next up was Williams, who turned on a
2-1 pitch and deposited it in the right-field seats _ 7-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bernie is a special talent and a special person,'' Torre said
later. ``He'd play baseball if they only paid him 10 cents. The
night he had was unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees scored their first run in the second on Ledee's
two-out double. Ledee poked a low, hooking line drive to left that
Greer seemed to judge correctly and then lost at the last instant.
As the ball went through to the fence, Darryl Strawberry scored
from first.
</P>
<P>
   The play raised questions about the readiness of Greer, who
suffered a bruised retina when he was hit by a thrown ball during
batting practice Sept. 13. As a result of the injury, which caused
blurred vision, Greer sat out seven games.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
