<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 02:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7917 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-CHASS-COLUMN-1STL     10-06 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CHASS-COLUMN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LESSON OF GAME 1: NO NEED TO BE AFRAID
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for rewriting throughout)   (sw) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Not only did the Mets win their last three games of
the regular season and force a playoff for the playoffs, not only
did they win the playoff and advance to the post-season, not only
did they defeat the upstart Arizona Diamondbacks in the opening
game of their National League Division Series. As if all of those
deeds weren't sufficient to shut up the doubters and the critics
and the vacillators, the Mets on Tuesday night exposed Randy
Johnson as a myth.
</P>
<P>
   Unless the tall, gangly, stringy-haired fellow wearing the
Diamondbacks white uniform with the turquoise letters and numbers
standing on the mound and throwing left-handed was an impostor, the
Mets did things to Johnson that at the least were sacrilegious. For
their dirty deeds, they probably will be banned in Arizona. If
Johnson knows what's good for him, he would endorse the ban.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, hitters in the National and American leagues
have found Johnson a frightening presence. John Kruk was never the
same after his all-star encounter with Johnson. Larry Walker made a
joke of his all-star appearance against Johnson, figuring that was
better than having the left-handed hitters' tormentor pitch to him
seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Many left-handers come down with sudden illnesses on days
Johnson is scheduled to pitch against their teams. Not Rafael
Palmeiro. He readily admits he wants no part of Johnson and asks
for days off when he pitches. Johnson simply is deadly against
left-handed hitters, and left-handers don't like the prospect of
being fooled by Johnson's wicked pitches and winding up dead.
</P>
<P>
   In his career, left-handers have hit a wimpish .186 against
Johnson. This season they hit a laughable .103, getting 9 hits and
striking out 40 times in 83 at-bats. In his career, Johnson has
given up 199 home runs. Left-handers have hit only 10 of that
total. This season he allowed 30 home runs. None was sent over the
fences by a left-handed hitter. No left-handed hitter belted a home
run against Johnson last year either.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the last time one did was a full two years ago when, on
Sept. 23, 1997, Jim Edmonds of Anaheim connected for not just one
home run against Dandy Randy but two home runs. He thus became a
member of one of the most elite clubs in baseball, joining Von
Hayes, Jim Eisenreich, Wally Joyner, Mike Greenwell, Mo Vaughn
(twice), Darren Bragg and Darrin Erstad as left-handed hitters who
have slugged home runs against the left-handed Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   But all of those facts and statistics were compiled before the
Mets stood up to Johnson on Tuesday night and showed the league
bully they weren't going to take his guff any more.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' lineup featured only two left-handed batters, John
Olerud in his customary third spot and Robin Ventura in the No. 6
slot, a notch below his position against right-handed pitchers. In
previous confrontations with Johnson, Olerud had failed to hit
safely in five at-bats and Ventura had 6 hits in 34 at-bats for a
.176 average. They were perfect examples of why left-handers would
rather go to the movies when Johnson pitches.
</P>
<P>
   But they accompanied their teammates to the oversized hangar
known as Bank One Ballpark in downtown Phoenix and battered Johnson
for three hits in their first four collective at-bats. Their hits
will not appear on Johnson's record in the future because details
such as hits and strikeouts in post-season games are not routinely
included in a player's statistics.
</P>
<P>
   But more than 50,000 people, including 49,584 fans, witnessed
the rare sights and, under oath, would attest to the turn of
events.
</P>
<P>
   Olerud batted for the first time in the first inning after
Edgardo Alfonzo hit a towering home run to center field and rapped
a single to center. Ventura batted later in the inning, with two on
and two out, and struck out.
</P>
<P>
   When it was Olerud's turn again in the third inning, he
electrified his teammates and stunned the crowd into shocked
silence, crushing a home run into the right field stands for two
more runs and a 3-0 lead. Ventura led off the fourth inning by
lashing a line drive to right for a double. Shawon Dunston's bunt
single moved him to third, putting him in position to score the
fourth run on a squeeze bunt by Rey Ordonez.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura was not finished. Although he struck out in his time at
bat before the double and again after the double, he went to bat
leading off the ninth and lined a single to right, a hit that
marked the beginning of Johnson's end. The single gave the
left-handed platoon 4 hits in 8 at-bats for .a 500 average, which
looks pretty impressive next to figures like .186 and .103.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, when Johnson left the game in the ninth inning, Ventura
and Olerud had as many hits against him as the Mets' right-hand
batters collected in 23 at-bats. It was a development of the
magnitude of the news story that man bites dog.
</P>
<P>
   When Johnson was still in the game, he displayed a bit of flash
himself with a bat in his hands, lining a double to right field
with one out in the seventh inning and the game tied, 4-4. But his
swing was mightier than his mind. When Tony Womack followed by
lofting a routine fly to left field, Johnson took off for third and
was standing there when Rickey Henderson threw the ball to second
for an inning-ending double play.
</P>
<P>
   Two innings later, when Alfonzo stroked a grand slam against
Johnson's replacement, Bobby Chouinard, Johnson was on his way to
his sixth successive post-season defeat. None of the previous five,
however, included a home run and all of those other hits by
left-handed hitters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
