<DOCNO> NYT19991006.0037 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 02:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7919 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-METS-DBACKS-NYT &LR;      10-06 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-DBACKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALFONZO BASHES GRAND SLAM IN 9TH FOR METS VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ The Mets applauded themselves all the way around the
bases, rejoicing that their good karma did not end.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Johnson had walked slowly off the mound toward the dugout
moments before in the ninth inning, his head down, a bit diminished
by what the Mets had done to him. He had loaded the bases full of
Mets, well after he had thrown 125 pitches and, even though third
baseman Matt Williams had made a spectacular play to throw Robin
Ventura out at the plate, Johnson must have known the Diamondbacks
were the latest foil for baseball's newest charmed set.
</P>
<P>
   Edgardo Alfonzo, who had blasted a home run to score the Mets'
first run in the game, smashed a 3-1 pitch from Johnson's
replacement, Bobby Chouinard, for a two-out grand slam that gave
the Mets a stunning _ is there any other word for what they do now?
_ 8-4 victory over Arizona in Game 1 of their National League
division series.
</P>
<P>
   The shot sent Alfonzo's teammates on a jogging ovation around
the bases and sent Johnson reeling to his sixth straight
post-season loss.
</P>
<P>
   It almost seemed as if baseball wanted to keep the Mets grounded
after their otherwordly surge into the playoffs. Congratulations on
the wild card, and your reward is facing Randy Johnson, a Cy Young
award candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Facing Johnson twice in a five-game series against a team that
the Mets had lost five of seven games to during the regular season,
when they faced Johnson only once?
</P>
<P>
   Mets Manager Bobby Valentine had juggled his lineup in
anticipation of the meeting, leaving just two left-handed hitters
to face Johnson, who terrorizes them with his long-limbed sidearm
release. Lefties had hit just .103 with no home runs against
Johnson, and lefties had 35 strikeouts in 87 at-bats against him.
</P>
<P>
   So Valentine dropped the lefties Darryl Hamilton and Roger
Cedeno from the lineup and modified the regular group that faces
left-handed pitchers. He inserted Benny Agbayani into the fifth
spot _ trying to offer some protection to Mike Piazza as well _ and
dropped the lefty-hitting Robin Ventura to sixth. John Olerud, the
only other lefty hitter, was in his usual three spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think our guys are intimidated by anything,''
Valentine said. ``But he definitely is different from anybody else
in the league right now. And his slider, if he's getting it over
when he's behind in the count, creates a devastating situation
because it's real hard to pull the trigger on it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Johnson's dominance has remained a regular-season
phenomenon. Since beating the Yankees twice in the 1995 playoffs
when he pitched for Seattle, Johnson has been tepid in playoff
games. So, despite the overwhelming numbers, the awesome aura, it
should not have been a complete surprise that the team that went a
miserable two weeks struggling each time at the plate suddenly
began battering the National League leader in earned run average
and strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   Alfonzo, who hit a home run against Cincinnati on Monday,
launched an 0-2 fastball _ the radar gun said it was 98 miles an
hour, but it was up in the zone _ off the left-center-field facade.
Although the Mets did not score again in the first, the ease with
which they hit him _ Olerud and Piazza both singled _ indicated
that Johnson would not be able to mow down this lineup, even though
he struck out two Mets in the first.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets struck again in the third. Rickey Henderson drew
Johnson's first walk and, after Alfonzo struck out, Olerud came to
the plate. His recent slump _part of the Mets' greater frustrations
_ had sent his batting average dipping below .300 (.298) for the
first time in months. Valentine had said before the game that his
left-handers would have to work just to hang in with Johnson. But
on a 2-2 count, Johnson left another ball up and Olerud blasted it
10 rows deep into right field to give the Mets a 3-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   It was somehow weirdly appropriate that the Mets, who had turned
baseball upside down in the last five days, had the more dominant
pitcher on the mound for a few innings.
</P>
<P>
   Masato Yoshii has no post-season record in the United States,
and he joked after the Mets eliminated Cincinnati that he thought
maybe he could get a hit off Johnson. Fat chance, but Yoshii was
not cowed by his larger-than-life opponent either. Yoshii had a 5-0
record with three no-decisions in his last eight starts; during
that time, his era was 1.61.
</P>
<P>
   But the Diamondbacks were able to hit Yoshii, and Tony Womack
smacked a triple to the left-field wall in the third. He scored on
a sacrifice fly by Jay Bell to narrow the Mets' lead to 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   But the Mets are not operating by the same laws as the rest of
baseball these days. Johnson was supposed to dominate left-handers,
but the Mets' lefties killed him. Ventura led off the fourth with a
double down the right-field line, and then Shawon Dunston _ a
regular in the left-hander lineup _ singled to move Ventura to
third. Rey Ordonez then bunted, allowing Ventura to score on the
squeeze to give the Mets a 4-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   But Arizona's thunderous lineup kept the game close for Johnson.
Erubiel Durazo, who became a major leaguer on July 25 and has since
taken hold of the Diamondbacks' first base position, slammed a solo
home run in the fourth to make the score 4-2.
</P>
<P>
   By then Johnson seemed to have had enough of this challenge.
Using his explosive pitches, he began to embarrass the Mets,
sending fastball after fastball whizzing past them. He retired the
side in the fifth and sixth innings, striking out Olerud, Piazza
and Ventura during that span.
</P>
<P>
   When Yoshii gave up a two-run homer to Luis Gonzalez in the
sixth inning, the game was tied at 4-4, and he faced just one more
batter before Dennis Cook came in to relieve him.
</P>
<P>
   After a week of spectacular pitching _ including two complete
games _ Yoshii left the game after 5 1/3 outings having allowed
four runs. It was the most runs he'd allowed, and the fewest
innings he'd pitched since Aug. 8.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
