<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 02:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7921 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-METS-DBACKS-COX     10-06 0643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-METS-DBACKS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Alfonzo puts Mets up 1-0
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Phoenix _ A week ago, no one believed in the Mets except
themselves and even that was hardly unanimous. Tuesday night, that
fragile belief took firm root.
</P>
<P>
   New York's Edgardo Alfonzo delivered a grand slam, his second
homer of the night, off reliever Bobby Chouinard with two outs in
the ninth, powering the Mets to a head-shaking 8-4 victory over
Arizona in the first game of the League Division series.
</P>
<P>
   Left for dead late last week, the Mets delivered Randy Johnson
his record sixth consecutive postseason loss, a huge first step
against the Diamondbacks' ace pitcher. The game was played before
49,584, the largest paid crowd ever at Bank One Ballpark and some
509 above listed capacity.
</P>
<P>
   New York loaded the bases off Johnson on two singles and a walk,
the last a four-pitch pass to Melvin Mora, a .161 hitter, to load
the bases. Johnson, who struck out 11, was lifted fores to load the
bases for Chouinard relieved Johnson and while third baseman Matt
Williams save him once with a diving stop to throw out Ventura at
the plate, Alfonzo's slam came five pitches later.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson did himself no favors when, after hitting a one-out
double in the seventh and moving the go-ahead run into scoring
position, he lost track of the situation and ran on Tony Womack
weak fly-out to left. Rickey Henderson easily doubled Johnson off
second to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Luis Gonzalez, whose .336 average placed him second in the
National League, erased a two-run New York lead in the sixth with a
titanic home run off Mets starter Masato Yoshii. After Jay Bell
opened the inning with a single, Gonzalez drove a 1-0 fastball an
estimated 452 feet over the wall in right center, tying the game
4-4 after New York had led throughout.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Mets pressured Arizona immediately, the
Diamondbacks stayed within reach. A Tony Womack triple and Jay Bell
sacrifice fly in the third dug into New York's three-run lead and
one inning later, rookie Erubiel Durazo's opposite field homer
closed the gap to 4-2.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets tormented Johnson in the early going, which was counter
to the way New York's season had gone. This was the same Mets team
that played just .550 baseball (22-18) against left-handed
pitching, opposed to .610 (75-48) against righties.
</P>
<P>
   Although Johnson had faced the Mets only once in his career, he
had dominated them in a May 30 meeting at Shea Stadium (one run and
five hits over eight innings with 10 strikeouts). And while Johnson
wiped out of the bottom half of New York's order, the top four
spots generated four hits and a walk in the first three innings
alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's obviously the toughest guy to face for any left-hander,''
said Mets third baseman Robin Ventura. ``I think for most of it,
you just go up there and take your best hacks and try to get the
bat on it.''
</P>
<P>
   That early success translated to a 4-2 lead after four, most of
the damage created by Mets left-handers. Ventura opened the fourth
with a double and later scored on Rey Ordonez's safety squeeze
bunt.
</P>
<P>
   In the third, it was left-handed John Olerud's turn. With Rickey
Henderson on base, Olerud powered a 2-2 fastball over the fence in
right-center, first postseason home run Johnson had ever given up
to a left-handed batter (in 54 1/3 career innings) and the first to
any left-hander since Anaheim's Jim Edmonds hit two off him Sept.
23, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   New York second baseman Edgardo Alfonzo, who put the Mets on
their way past Cincinnati with a first-inning homer Monday night,
pulled the trick again. Johnson, who gave up 30 homers this season,
left an 0-2 fastball over the plate and Alfonzo drove over the
center field wall for an instant 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
