<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 02:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7922 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-RHODEN-COLUMN-1ST     10-06 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-RHODEN-COLUMN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: FOR THE METS AND DIAMONDBACKS, MONEY TALKED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for updating) (jt) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX. Ariz. _ In the span of two weeks, the amazing Mets have
criss-crossed the country in pursuit of a dream. They've traveled
South to the red clay of Georgia, East to Pennsylvania, Midwest to
the plains of Ohio. On Tuesday night, amid Arizona's desert and
cactus, the Mets stunned Randy Johnson and the Arizona
Diamondbacks, 8-4, to take a 1-0 lead in the division series, and
they began yet another chapter of an unlikely journey.
</P>
<P>
   The surging Mets _ the National League's team of yesteryear with
their Brooklyn Dodger-New York Giants roots _ play the expansion
Arizona Diamondbacks in a series which, at first glance, seems like
a fairy tale. One franchise, the Mets, is in its 38th season, and
playing its first post-season game in 11 years. The other, Arizona,
is an expansion franchise which rocketed to the playoffs in only
two years.
</P>
<P>
   In days of old such a rapid turnabout would be hailed as a
tribute to the farm system, knowledge of players. The success of
both of these teams is not cultivation, but deep pockets. I offer
this not as anything new, but as something to sober up the
fairytale. The Mets and the Diamondbacks are a couple rich kids
with everything at their disposal whose benefactors decided, in a
fit of exasperation, that they were going to try to buy themselves
a championship.
</P>
<P>
   The conservative Mets, tired of playing in the lengthening
shadow of Yankee Stadium, opened the checkbook and signed Mike
Piazza to a seven-year, $91 million contract last season. This
season they let it all hang out: they brought in the redoubtable
Rickey Henderson; the wise old owl Orel Hershiser, solid Robin
Ventura. When it was over the Mets had spent $71 million.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona lost 97 games last season and finished in last place
under first year-manager Buck Showalter, exiled from New York to
Arizona to manage the expansion team.
</P>
<P>
   This year the Diamondbacks, operating under the theory that if
the opposition can't score it can't win, bought the best three
pitchers it could get. The headliner was Randy Johnson, the
mercenary troubadour who pitched with Houston last season and
Seattle before that. They also signed outfielder Steven Finley from
San Diego. At the end of the spree, Arizona had spent $66 million.
These two ``fairytale teams'' were built for quick turnarounds.
Arizona got what it paid for.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a lament for the ``good ol'days'' when players were
homegrown and money didn't matter. Money has always mattered. Now
it seems to matter in a way that obliterates honor and
responsibility to the game. There is a long list of things money
can buy: In sports it includes hard hitting outfielders, hard
throwing pitchers and slick fielding infielders. The saving grace
is the unpredictable timing of human foibles and frailties. Randy
Johnson went through a stretch this season when he lost five
straight starts despite near flawless pitching. Why? Because while
Arizona opponents couldn't hit Johnson, the Diamondbacks couldn't
hit opposing pitching. You can tempt fate, but you can't buy it.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night, the Diamondbacks got the worst of both worlds.
The Mets _ Edgardo Alfonzo in particular _ lighted up Arizona
pitching, and the Diamondbacks couldn't hit the Mets when it
counted. The Diamondback organization is also discovering that,
even with the fat payroll, you can't buy enthusiasm either, not
from fans, not from players. You can't make people ``feel''
baseball before they are ready.
</P>
<P>
   Money has turned the Diamondbacks into winners overnight, but _
mystery of mysteries _ fans aren't falling over themselves to get
to the lavish new ball park. There was a shortfall in attendance
this season. The team's season-ticket base dropped by 9,000 from
1998. Thus, Arizona has the distinction of being the only team in
 &UR; any &LR;  sport to draw fewer spectators as a first place finisher than
it did the previous year after finishing last.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with the lost revenue, the owner, Jerry Colangelo, had to
secure another $24 million from team investors recently to cover a
cash shortage. The franchise needed more money to cover operational
costs, including the player payroll. Colangelo said the club
expects to lose nearly $15 million this year.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona has deep roots in baseball but they are not the same
roots. The Southwest is where baseball comes in spring to thaw out
after a long winter off. Fans here have grown accustomed to
enjoying baseball played in first and second gear, watching the
gradual thaw of arms and legs, observing young prospects on the way
up, veterans squeezing one more season out of a tired body. They
look forward to sending their adopted teams off to their respective
seasons. This manner of generation and regeneration is a
longstanding, Southwest tradition unto itself.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the high octane, big league spring-to-fall baseball, with
its false sense of urgency, takes some getting used too.
Diamondback fans do not seem to have made up their minds about this
team, though they clearly like the bells and whistles of winning.
Mets fans, many who made the trip West for these first two games,
are drenched in baseball tradition that goes beyond the team's fat
payroll.
</P>
<P>
   So here you have it: Arizona and New York.
</P>
<P>
   Not quite a fairytale, but a lesson all the same. Buying
championships has become the vogue but, as Diamondbacks backers are
about to discover, nobody really likes mercenaries _ no matter how
well they pitch. It's only a matter of time before they'll be
pitching against you.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
