<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Wednesday, Oct. 6.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-GROZNY (Grozny, Chechnya) _ For the second time, panicked
people in Chechnya's capital (ruined in first Russia-Chechnya war)
are packing up and fleeing, fearing Russian attacks. By Carlotta
Gall.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-POLITICS (Jakarta) _ Opponents of government have
great expectations for change at the top, but the first sessions of
new national assembly indicate that opposition leader Megawati
Sukarnoputri's presidential bid may be faltering. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NASSAU-DEFICIT-WOES (New York) _ While other comparable counties
are pondering tax cuts or new spending, this storied suburb is
contemplating something else: a deficit that reached $300 million
this summer and bonds downgraded to a level now hovering just above
junk. How this happened is an unlikely tale, but experts on
municipal finance say it making Nassau County a serious contender
to be labeled the most fiscally irresponsible county in America. By
David M. Halbfinger.
</P>
<P>
   CHICKEN-MISSION (Georgetown, Del.) _ It was an incongruous
sight, the white-haired clergyman, in black shirt and white collar,
standing in an immense poultry house filled with thousands of
clucking birds and the acrid, ammonia stench of chicken manure. The
clergyman, the Rev. Jim Lewis, was in this unlikely place because
the Episcopal Church has assigned him an unlikely mission: to
improve the lives of Delaware's chicken farmers and poultry plant
workers. By Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   PROSTATE-PROTEIN (Undated) _ The PSA protein that people use to
monitor for prostate cancer may actually help fight cancers. This
may explain why prostate cancer grows so slowly. By Gina Kolata.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NASHVILLE-GORE (Nashville) _ Talk of Nashville on eve of Gore's
arrival at new headquarters. By Emily Yellin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MCI-SPRINT-ADVISERS (Undated) _ A look at the advisers to the
MCI-Sprint deal: how they got it done, what they're getting paid.
By Laura M. Holson.
</P>
<P>
   NASDAQ-MARKETPLACE (New York) _ Frank Zarb, chairman of the
National Association of Securities Dealers, unveiled a new
electronic trading system for NASDAQ stocks on Tuesday that he said
would make the trading of these shares more efficient and fairer
for all investors. By Gretchen Morgenson.
</P>
<P>
   PERFUME-MEN (New York) _ For a growing group of young American
men, perfume is not just some musky bottle that their wives put in
their Christmas stockings and expect them to wear on special
evenings out; it is a grooming product used as routinely as
toothpaste, and one that makes a significant statement, just like
choosing whether to wear a leather jacket or a tweed blazer. Men's
fragrance sales are experiencing a dynamic growth. By Leslie
Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo and graphic have been sent to NYT graphics
clients.)
</P>
<P>
   DOGS-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ A canine ``family'' is being enlisted
to help stimulate sales in a product category where the competition
resembles a, well, dogfight. By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
