<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 03:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7956 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-STROKE-DIET-SFCHRON &LR;      10-06 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STROKE-DIET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 EATING VEGGIES CUTS RISK OF STROKE, 14-YEAR STUDY FINDS  &HT;     By CARL T. HALL 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A diet rich in fruits and vegetables can cut your risk of stroke
by nearly a third, scientists are reporting Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest long-term studies ever done on diet and
disease gives a strong endorsement to broccoli, orange juice and
other healthy stuff that mothers have been pushing for generations.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the famed Harvard University study of health care
professionals, researchers surveyed 76,000 female registered nurses
over a 14-year period and 39,000 male doctors and other medical
workers for eight years.
</P>
<P>
   The results are reported Wednesday in the Journal of the
American Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
   The most dramatic finding shows that people who ate at least
five servings of fruits and vegetables a day had 31 percent less
risk of a stroke than those who ate fewer than three helpings a
day.
</P>
<P>
   Each additional serving of a fruit or vegetable delivered about
6 percent less stroke danger, although more than six servings
appeared to provide no extra benefit.
</P>
<P>
   Quantities per serving can be surprisingly modest. Experts
recommend 6-ounce servings of fruit juice, for example, which is
less than a cup, while only a handful of raisins or other dried
fruit is enough to constitute a serving.
</P>
<P>
   But Americans on average eat less than the recommended five
servings a day, and about half of the adult population falls into
the least healthy category, consuming less than three helpings
daily.
</P>
<P>
   No single food item proved to be a magic bullet, but the
researchers did find some fruits and vegetables better stroke
fighters than others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carrots are good for you,'' said lead author Kaumudi
Joshipura, a Harvard dentist and epidemiologist. ``Potatoes don't
really help, and we didn't find much beneficial effect for peas,
beans and legumes.''
</P>
<P>
   The strongest protective effects against stroke were found for
citrus fruits and juice, leafy greens and vegetables in the cabbage
family, including broccoli, cauliflower, collard greens, brussels
sprouts and bok choy.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're bright, they're colorful, and they pack a high
nutritional profile,'' said nutritionist Linda Nebeling at the
National Cancer Institute, which has recommended five or more
servings of fruits and vegetables since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   At a time of widespread confusion about just what constitutes a
healthy lifestyle, experts see the new study as welcome
confirmation that at least some traditional dietary advice holds up
under scientific scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   About the only unexpected result was that eating much more than
the recommended number of servings seems to deliver little or no
added benefit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may just be that six servings a day is the right amount,''
Joshipura said, ``but it's hard to say why.''
</P>
<P>
   The study focused on the risk of suffering what is known as an
ischemic stroke, which accounts for about 80 percent of all strokes
in the United States. They are caused by a blood clot or some other
interruption in the flow of blood to the brain. Inadequate blood
flow causes brain cells to die.
</P>
<P>
   Some strokes have little recognizable effect, while others can
quickly cause death. Stroke kills about 150,000 Americans each year
and is the leading cause of adult disability.
</P>
<P>
   Those surveyed began the study free of cardiovascular disease,
cancer and diabetes. Women were ages 34 to 59 and were tracked from
1980 to 1994, while the men were ages 40 to 75 and were surveyed
starting in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Other studies have highlighted various ingredients in vegetables
and fruits that could influence the cardiovascular system,
including phytochemicals, anti-oxidants, potassium, folates and
fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence on any one ingredient's role is inconclusive, prompting
the study's authors to emphasize the role of fruits and vegetables
in their natural form. The study also found that people who
consumed dietary supplements still benefited from frequent visits
to the produce shelves.
</P>
<P>
   Lifestyle and diet patterns were based on what the study
subjects reported in detailed questionnaires. Medical records were
later checked for stroke diagnoses.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers noted that the study subjects, all health care
professionals, tend to be more health savvy than the general public
and also have fewer socioeconomic differences that could skew
results. This made the finding of a strong ``dose-response''
relationship for diet and cardiovascular health ``particularly
notable,'' the study concluded.
</P>
<P>
   The authors took pains to adjust for other known risk factors
for stroke, including smoking, exercise, weight and fat intake. In
all cases, the central finding held true independent of the other
factors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really the fruits and vegetables that give the protective
effect,'' Joshipura said.
</P>
<P>
   Meat consumption, for example, did not substantially change the
result. But that doesn't mean it's healthful for people to eat
whatever they want as long as they also load up on greens.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Dean Ornish, a Sausalito, Calif., physician and the nation's
most prominent champion of low-fat, vegetable-rich diets, saw no
reason to change his tune after reviewing the study in JAMA
Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-99 0318EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
