<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 REAL WINNER LEFT HOLDING THE BAGS  &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Two runners from Kenya arrive in the city just
in time for the start of last Sunday's Bridge-to-Bridge charity
run. They dash to the Ferry Building just as the starting gun is
fired.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Korir takes off, tossing his backpack to pal David
Makori Omiti.
</P>
<P>
   Three minutes later, David takes off, too, carrying both
backpacks loaded with clothing, tickets and passports.
</P>
<P>
   Down the road, at Pier 35, David discovers why most serious
runners don't carry two loaded backpacks. He chucks the packs to a
bystander and zooms away.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony wins the 12K race in 36 minutes, 34 seconds. In third
place, two seconds back, is David.
</P>
<P>
   A thousand runners drag home and say, ``I just got smoked by
some guy who was carrying his luggage.''
</P>
<P>
   Were Anthony and David reunited with their backpacks? Yes!
Someone brought the packs to the Red Cross tent, and they were
hustled to the runners' hotel just in time for them to make their
return flight to Kenya.
</P>
<P>
   Hope you two guys recommend us to all your friends.
</P>
<P>
   THE CANNERY is searching for a new administrative assistant, and
management is impressed by the resume of one man who is not afraid
to dream the dream:
</P>
<P>
   ``Seeking to expand my horizons, looking for a great job that
will allow for the following: Living in a grand, beautiful older
home in a nice neighborhood, relocating expenses provided by
employer, having enough money to own a nice, newer vehicle, and
nice furniture and nice home furnishings, eat well, send home money
to my retired parents, enjoy a nice social life, possibly adopt and
care for one or two children in the future, and time to pursue my
interests of writing novels and gourmet cooking.''
</P>
<P>
   Done. And this is San Francisco, so we'll throw in a brace of
love slaves who also do light housekeeping.
</P>
<P>
   FESTOON THE Golden Gate Bridge with this banner, says Lotta
Dotz: ``Welcome to San Francisco, Avg. household income 75K,
jackets &AMP; ties required.''
</P>
<P>
   INTERACTIVE MUNI, indeed. A recent item here told of a Muni
driver on a Giants' ballpark express who asked the passengers'
advice on the best route to the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's nothing,'' says caller Jane. ``I ride the No. 16
express every morning, and we frequently get drivers who don't know
the route. We're getting used to calling out directions.''
</P>
<P>
   How about if the first driver out in the morning on any given
line leaves a trail of breadcrumbs along the route?
</P>
<P>
   THOSE MAMMOTH tire fires will be a lot less drab, says Wes
Haley, once we start discarding the new tires that come in bright
colors _ red, yellow, etc.
</P>
<P>
   We won't be polluting the sky, but painting it.
</P>
<P>
   IT'S THAT TIME of year again when we Bay Area residents put
aside our own trivial concerns and devote our time to
psychoanalyzing and advising 49er quarterback Steve Young, the
Concussion Kid.
</P>
<P>
   We divide into two camps:
</P>
<P>
   Camp A asks _ begs _ Steve to quit football before he takes one
more good hit upside the head and becomes a handsome, curly-haired
rutabaga.
</P>
<P>
   Camp 2 tells Camp A to mind its own business and stop using
corny phrases like ``upside the head'' and tells Steve to play
football as long as he can remember which extremities his cleats go
on.
</P>
<P>
   Steve is our Punxsutawney Phil. He looks at his medical chart,
and if he sees that everything is still connected, he goes back
into the huddle, and we have four more months of football.
</P>
<P>
   What worries me are Young's TV commercials.
</P>
<P>
   In one, he's in the car with his fiance, having purchased a
potted plant that he leaves on the roof as he drives off. In
another, he's being picked up by a blind date, evidently having
forgotten that he's engaged to the woman he gardens with, at least
in TV commercials. He tells the blind date he's a lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   In a third commercial, Steve goes on a wilderness camping trip
with some guy he seems to barely know, and he's watching ``I Love
Lucy'' on TV and ordering pizza at the campsite. I realize the rich
are different from you and me, but this is unusual behavior.
</P>
<P>
   In still another, Young furtively picks up hamburgers from a
drive-through, acting as if he believes himself to be a CIA
operative.
</P>
<P>
   What this all says about Steve is that he can't leave football
now. It's his island of sanity.
</P>
</TEXT>
