<HEADER>
A7958 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e BC-TV-ROSWELL-REVIEW-SFC     10-06 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-ROSWELL-REVIEW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELIEVE IT OR NOT, `ROSWELL' COULD BE A HIT 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It doesn't take long for TV to carry a workable idea to absurd
lengths.
</P>
<P>
   Teens feel alienated? Then you depict them as idealistic but
paranoid figures in a world corrupted by their elders.
</P>
<P>
   Taken to extremes, that idea metamorphoses into ``Roswell,'' a
teen drama premiering Wednesday night on the WB.
</P>
<P>
   Now the teens are alienated in the sincerest sense. They're
space aliens, and humans are their enemies.
</P>
<P>
   The premise toys dangerously with guffaws. Sure enough, an
earthling girl who's smitten with an alien boy delivers this
scripted rock Wednesday night: ``It's just so ironic that when
something like this happened to me, it was with an alien.''
</P>
<P>
   Bummer. Falling for an alien must be the nadir of an Earth
girl's day.
</P>
<P>
   The line is a laugher, in any solar system. Of the worst kind,
too, because the rigidly earnest ``Roswell'' is no ``Buffy the
Vampire Slayer.'' Nope _ laugh here and you laugh alone.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Roswell'' somehow works in spite of its party-pooper
seriousness. The show's cast could make it the year's sleeper hit.
</P>
<P>
   Doe-eyed Shiri Appleby, a veteran of not much more than Taco
Bell commercials, is teenager Liz Parker, who works after school at
her parents' diner in the world's flying-saucer capital, Roswell,
N.M..
</P>
<P>
   Appleby has the tandem that can translate into stardom _ a
tablespoon of sexuality stirred into a cup of girl-next-door
innocence. Her character, Liz, is a latter-day Juliet who finds
herself attracted to 16-year-old Max Evans (Jason Behr), an alien
Romeo.
</P>
<P>
   Behr was in six episodes of ``Dawson's Creek'' last season,
meaning that he's supposedly stamped prime rib for the TV teen
market. He has his own high-beam brown eyes and a kind of
smoldering vulnerability that might put someone in mind, however
loosely, of Montgomery Clift (a reference that will make sense only
to alien WB viewers).
</P>
<P>
   The deal is that Max, his sister, Isabel (Katherine Heigl), and
their friend Michael Guerin (Brendan Fehr) are descended from the
aliens who crash-landed in Roswell in 1947. They popped out of pods
years after the crash, which explains why they're teenagers in
1999. They have powers, some of them curative. Liz is drawn into
their secret when Max uses his healing power to save her life.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently the alien adolescents are on the run from the Fox
network, because their main fear is that they'll be caught and
autopsied. Fox has autopsied Roswell aliens before. With the
November sweeps approaching, aliens must feel like turkeys the week
before Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, the kids are afraid they'll be caught and sliced up by
inquisitive earthlings. The immediate threat of apprehension is in
the person of the town sheriff (William Sadler), though a broader
government search enters the picture in next week's episode.
</P>
<P>
   To make matters more interesting, there's mysterious evidence
that at least one other living alien, unknown to the teens, may be
in Roswell. And that alien might not be friendly.
</P>
<P>
   Two other important ``Roswell'' notes:
</P>
<P>
   First, and don't forget this, we learn from Max that ``alien''
could be a derogatory, species-centrist term.
</P>
<P>
   Says Max, ``I prefer the term `not of this earth.'''
</P>
<P>
   Second, although everything else about ``Roswell'' oozes with
credibility, the producers must be taken to task for one blatant,
inexcusable inaccuracy.
</P>
<P>
   Liz tells her best friend, Maria (Majandra Delfino), that her
old boyfriend is ``steady and loyal, and he appreciates me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sounds like you're describing a poodle,'' Maria responds.
</P>
<P>
   No, it doesn't. Steady? Loyal? Appreciative? Now we've got alien
poodles, too?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
