<HEADLINE>
GAME 2 STARTERS KNOW ABOUT REHABILITATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX -  &UR; Todd Stottlemyre, meet  &UR; Kenny Rogers.
</P>
<P>
   The two have more in common than just their roles as starters
tonight in Game 2 of the NL division series. Both suffered rotator
cuff and labrum tears. They took different routes, however, in
their comebacks.
</P>
<P>
   Mets starter Rogers underwent shoulder surgery in 1996.
Stottlemyre built up his shoulder this summer without surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers admires Stottlemyre's determination.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think as long as a pitcher is never scared to go out there,
even if he knows he's not going to have a whole lot of stuff, to go
out there and try, he's going to have a chance to beat you,''
Rogers said. ``I know that's my approach, and I'm sure that's
his.''
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre said he didn't bypass surgery to prove how tough he
is. But he said he owed it to  &UR; Jerry Colangelo, Diamondbacks
managing general partner who gave him a four-year, $32 million
contract, to try to come back and contribute this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably a miracle, and, medically speaking, if you look
at my shoulder, maybe I shouldn't be pitching,'' Stottlemyre said.
``But I am, and I feel good and my arm feels strong and my mind is
sound, and I'm able to go out there every fifth day and compete as
hard as I can compete.'' &QL; 
No media allowed &QL; 
They wear No. 25 on their caps, but the Diamondbacks weren't
letting &UR; David Dellucci in the clubhouse Tuesday. That's because the
injured outfielder is now technically part of the media.
</P>
<P>
   Dellucci is analyzing the Diamondbacks' playoff run for Channel
12. In the playoffs, media are given no clubhouse access before
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys were giving me heat for it,'' Dellucci said before
Tuesday's game. ``They say, `The media aren't allowed in the
clubhouse.' They told me they were going to clean my locker out
(Monday). They ask me for my credentials every time I go in
there.'' &QL; 
Late show &QL; 
At least one die-hard Diamondbacks fan in Florida stayed up late to
watch Tuesday's game: Manager  &UR; Buck Showalter's mother, Lina.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's going to have my sister over and make a big bowl of
popcorn and second-guess me just like everyone else,'' Showalter
said. &QL; 
Short hops &QL; 
Showalter received good-luck telegrams from Hall of Famer
 &UR; Reggie &UR; Jackson and New York Jets Coach  &UR; Bill Parcells. Showalter
also received a letter from Cardinals Coach  &UR; Vince Tobin, wishing
him luck.
</P>
<P>
   Diamondbacks first baseman  &UR; Travis Lee, not on the playoff
roster, went to his parents' home in Washington state.
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher  &UR; Byung-Hyun Kim, also left off the playoff roster, went
to Los Angeles to have dental work done. He'll return to Tucson to
work in the instructional league.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Dwight Patterson, the man responsible for bringing pro baseball
to the Valley by finding a spring training home in Mesa for the
Chicago Cubs in 1952, threw out the ceremonial first pitch.
</P>
<P>
   The national anthem was sung by (drum roll) . . . the fans. &QL; 
Staff writer Don Ketchum contributed to this report. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
