<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VALENTINE: I TOLD YOU SO  
 PLAYOFF PLAN PAYS OFF FOR ROGERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAUL CORO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - New York Manager  &UR; Bobby Valentine said  &UR; Kenny Rogers
had been acquired in late July so he could pitch for the Mets in
October.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind how Rogers' first postseason stint went in New York,
when the Yankees won the 1996 World Series despite his 14.14 ERA in
four postseason games.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind the Yankees gave Oakland $5 million to take him away.
Never mind he had struggled this season through elbow tendinitis in
the spring, back spasms in May and hamstring tightness in July.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind _ because it worked out. Rogers, today's Game 2
starter, is 5-1 with a 4.03 ERA since the trade. It was like the
perfect dating-service match. Ground-ball pitcher meets greatest
infield ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time around (in the playoffs), I'm better prepared in a
lot of different ways to being out there and competing,'' said
Rogers, who last saw Arizona as an Athletic with eight innings of
two-hit shutout ball four months ago. ``Before when I went out
there, I was at a disadvantage. I didn't know from each day what I
would have when I toed the rubber. Now, I kind of know what to
expect when I get out there.'' &QL; 
Late night in NYC
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, the only people from New York not affected by the 11
p.m. (New York time) starts of the games in Arizona are the Mets,
who rested well after arriving in Phoenix at 1:45 a.m. Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Mets fans are livid at home because the Yankees have prime-time
slots both nights. It's not any better for the New York media
contingent of 38.
</P>
<P>
   Most newspapers are holding the final edition until the game
ends, but those go to only a fraction of the city.`` The New York
Po''st will put out a Mets Extra on a 4 a.m. deadline with hopes
200,000 will sell on the streets. &QL; 
Bad odds
</P>
<P>
   According to the books, this series is a no-brainer. Arizona won
seven of nine against New York this season. New York is a .500 club
against left-handers, which Arizona would use in all but Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody on this team thinks we're a .500 team
when we play against a left-hander,'' Mets third baseman  &UR; Robin
Ventura said. ``Those numbers don't mean a lot once we're here.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Orel ( &UR; Hershiser) &UR; kept reminding everybody of the '88 season
that the Dodgers were pretty much dominated by the Mets and they
were able to beat them in the (National League Championship
Series).'' &QL; 
Long time coming
</P>
<P>
   Mets reliever  &UR; John Franco is experiencing postseason ball for
the first time, just like Arizona fans. He just paid more dues.
</P>
<P>
   The boyhood Mets fan from Brooklyn had gone 15 seasons without
playing in the postseason, the longest stretch of any active major
league player. That's even longer than the Mets, who last played
postseason in 1988. &QL; 
Bonilla over Lopez
</P>
<P>
   Valentine chose outfielder  &UR; Bobby Bonilla, who has been limited
to 60 games by injury, over infielder  &UR; Luis Lopez for the final
playoff-roster spot. Despite Bonilla's .160 clip, Valentine wanted
his switch-hitting power and playoff experience. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
