<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-DUCKS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW STARTER AT GOALIE GETS SHUTOUT IN HOME OPENER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Before they dropped the puck at America West Arena for
the Coyotes' home opener, they ran a video of highlights from the
team's first three seasons in the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Spliced into the mix of hits, goals and celebrations were
occasional shots of the Stanley Cup. And the sounds of U2's ``I
Still'' ``Haven't Found What I'm Looking For''.
</P>
<P>
   While it's true the Coyotes still haven't found their hands
hoisting Lord Stanley's Holy Grail _ or even a way to get out of
the first round of the playoffs _ they've found a way to look
pretty good so far in this young season.
</P>
<P>
   Getting another solid team performance and some great individual
efforts, the Coyotes cooked the Mighty Ducks of Anaheim, 4-0,
before an energized crowd of 15,780 for their second straight win
and their best start since moving to Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after opening the season with a 2-1 win in St. Louis, the
Coyotes can tie a franchise record for the club's best start in
history with a victory Friday night in Chicago, where they open a
three-game trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's only two games, but they were both really good games for
us to say the least,'' center Jeremy Roenick said. ``We were solid
all around again today.''
</P>
<P>
   What wasn't there to like?
</P>
<P>
   Roenick looked like his old, free-wheeling self, scoring a
shifty goal and adding two assists for a three-point game,
something he accomplished just twice last season. Shane Doan, who
endured a mind-boggling slump to start last season, picked up where
he left off from the postseason by pumping in two goals.
</P>
<P>
   Do-everything forward Mike Sullivan set up two goals with
perfect feeds and played unreal defense. Four different defensemen
picked up an assist by either joining the rush or quarterbacking
counter-attacks, a key element to new Coach Bob Francis' system.
And, once again, goalie Mikhail Shtalenkov was defiant in stopping
21 shots for his seventh career shutout.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't have any real good chances to score. It was a
pretty boring game for me, actually,'' said Shtalenkov, who for
that very reason, was not recognized as one of the game's customary
three stars.
</P>
<P>
   The closest the Ducks came to scoring was when Matt Cullen went
crashing into the net _ his own _ early in the third period.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phoenix played a great game in all areas, they outplayed us in
all areas,'' Anaheim Coach Craig Hartsburg said. ``Forechecking.
Throwing in. Playing better in the neutral zone. You name it.''
</P>
<P>
   Dallas Drake started the scoring with a rebound goal off a
Roenick shot midway through the first period. Roenick then made it
2-0 with 7:03 remaining in the period when Sullivan set him up with
a great behind-the-back pass in the neutral zone. Roenick then
faked out defenseman Kevin Haller and deked goalie Guy Hebert to
score.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those goals don't come along too often, so you have to savor
them when you get them,'' Roenick said. ``That was one of the
better ones I've had in the last couple of years.''
</P>
<P>
   And what of Sullivan's fancy assist?
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, Gretzky just retired,'' Roenick said. ``Somebody had to
fill the role.''
</P>
<P>
   Doan looked like he had a shade of The Great One in him after
scoring back-to-back goals 4:35 apart in the second period. It was
just the second two-goal game for Doan in his five-year career.
Last season, it took him half the season _ 41 games to be exact _
just to score two goals last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I knew it was a long time,'' Doan said, smiling. ``It
was great just to have an opportunity to get that first one out of
the way.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
