<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-IRISH-PROBLEMS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCANDALS DON'T ROB IRISH OF MYSTIQUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It shares the traits of other NBC programming: sex,
embezzlement, cheating and a rash of high-priced lawyers. Welcome
to the new era of Notre Dame football.
</P>
<P>
   No program in the country can match the tradition and mystique
of the Fighting Irish. But a university that was once the moral
measuring stick for its peers is now accused of indiscretions that
it has effectively escaped for 11 decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing I've realized at Notre Dame is that there are
always going to be some issues to deal with, and some of greater
magnitude than others,'' Irish Coach Bob Davie said. ``I'm not
trying to minimize it, but one of the things you have to take pride
in as a football coach is to only concentrate on the things you can
control.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously we're embarrassed about it, but we can't control the
outcome.''
</P>
<P>
   Davie dismissed the suggestion that off-the-field distractions
have contributed to Notre Dame's 2-3 record. Arizona State gets a
first-hand look at the program Saturday when the Sun Devils make
their first-ever trip to Notre Dame Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Irish are expected to receive word soon on NCAA sanctions
related to academic fraud and gifts players received from a
convicted embezzler and are in danger of being found guilty of
their first major violation in school history.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point,'' Davie said, ``all we want is closure.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest charges come on the heels of an embarrassing
age-discrimination suit won by former assistant football coach Joe
Moore. And in August, the Irish found themselves defending
accusations by Michigan Coach Lloyd Carr that they violated a
gentlemen's agreement by committing to play in the preseason Eddie
Robinson Classic. Carr contends that the schools agreed their Sept.
4 game would be the season opener for both.
</P>
<P>
   Although details of Notre Dame's violations became particularly
numerous this year, their genesis can be traced to the 1993 Cotton
Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   That's where Kim Dunbar, a then-23-year-old bookkeeper and
secretary, met former Irish receiver Derrick Mayes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It kind of started from there,'' Dunbar said in court
documents. ``I started dating him. And once you kind of meet one of
the football players, it sort of gets into them all.''
</P>
<P>
   A sexual relationship with the 19-year-old receiver began, and
Dunbar paid for gifts and many of their outings. She spent $1,836
for first-class airplane tickets to Las Vegas, according to court
documents, as well as a trip to Kalamazoo, Mich., in a stretch
limousine on Valentine's Day.
</P>
<P>
   When the pair's relationship ended in 1995, Dunbar, then 25,
became involved with defensive back Jarvis Edison, who had not yet
begun his sophomore season. They now have a 3-year-old daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Dunbar was traveling to most Notre Dame away games
and staying in luxury hotels. When asked how she could afford such
perks, she had an explanation.
</P>
<P>
   ``What people thought was that I resold Notre Dame football
tickets and got a lot of money that way,'' she said. ``That's what
I made everybody believe. I mean, even my boss believed that.''
</P>
<P>
   But the truth was that Dunbar was embezzling more than $1
million from her employers and spending some of it on players. She
currently is serving a one-year prison sentence and is expected to
be released Oct. 17. Her mother is raising her daughter.
</P>
<P>
   According to the NCAA, the Irish aren't responsible for most of
Dunbar's gifts to Mayes because they took place before she became a
member of the since-disbanded Quarterback Club. Once she joined the
group, which costs just $25, she became a representative of the
university, the NCAA said, and thus the school became responsible
for her actions, which included giving gifts to as many as 12
players.
</P>
<P>
   Just when that episode seemed to be behind the Irish, news of
more infractions came to light.
</P>
<P>
   Notre Dame acknowledged on Sept. 17 that a part-time tutor had
written a paper for a former athlete. In a statement, the Irish
said the athlete is no longer at Notre Dame and that the tutor was
discharged.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA is now trying to determine whether to incorporate the
possibility of academic fraud into its current evaluation and
determination of sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a challenging time for the university,'' Athletic
Director Mike Wadsworth said. ``To speculate beyond that wouldn't
make sense.''
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA's delay in announcing penalties has Notre Dame fearful
about how that may affect recruiting. Athletes can begin signing
letters of intent in February.
</P>
<P>
   To help quell other rumors, Notre Dame extended Davie's contract
in July for another five years. He took over the program in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all the turmoil he inherited, Bob came through it with a
lot of maturity,'' Wadsworth said. ``He has been able to focus on
the job at hand and still have success.''
</P>
<P>
   And, Notre Dame is still Notre Dame. Despite losing three
straight, the Fighting Irish have a mystique unmatched.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still there,'' ASU Coach Bruce Snyder said. ``They have a
storied tradition. I notice that every week their attendance is
80,012.
</P>
<P>
   ``That says a lot.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-99 0339EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
