<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-FORWARDS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW FORWARDS TO HELP END SUNS' `SOFT' IMAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLAGSTAFF, Ariz. - During his three years with the Los Angeles
Lakers, forward Corie Blount said he never heard anybody call the
Suns ``soft'' or knew of players questioning his new team's
toughness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never really heard any of that until I got here,'' Blount
said. ``When you've got forwards as talented as Tom Gugliotta and
Cliff Robinson, it's hard to call those guys soft. But the coaches
seem to be putting a lot of emphasis on it.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been no secret that the Suns weren't going to beat
anybody with muscle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to change that,'' said forward Rodney Rogers, who,
along with Blount, brings a new look to the Suns' frontline.
</P>
<P>
   With the trade that brought Penny Hardaway to Phoenix, the Suns
gave up forwards Danny Manning and Pat Garrity. They've added
Rogers, Blount and rookie Shawn Marion, who can swing from small
forward to big guard.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a combination of forwards that allows Coach Danny
Ainge a lot of different looks instead of a lot of players with
similar games, as he had last season.
</P>
<P>
   In all the hoopla over the arrival of Hardaway, the additions of
Rogers, Blount, Marion and center-forward Oliver Miller have been
largely overlooked.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we've got is a lot of guys who can really get up and down
the floor, and with Jason (Kidd) and Penny, they're going to get
you the ball,'' Robinson said. ``I think we're a little more
athletic and tougher around the basket. Tom is a tremendous
rebounder, Corie and Rodney are really good rebounders, and I try
to do what I can do to get a few. We've got some different looks
because Rodney's a big body, and I think Oliver is really going to
be a key coming in and pounding guys around the basket.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the Suns can still go small and fast with Marion, a sleek,
long-armed 6-foot-7 finisher who might be the only guy fast enough
to outsprint Kidd.
</P>
<P>
   Ainge believes the Suns can play big or small and still put a
group of tough-minded and physical players on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been preaching toughness from the time I got here as a
player,'' Ainge said. ``And I believe as a team we've gone from
being about a four on a toughness scale of 10 to at least a seven
or eight.
</P>
<P>
   ``On every team I've been associated with, there have always
been some guys who were tougher than others. You just hope you get
enough of them to make the whole team tough enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now as a coach, there's only one thing that bothers me. It
isn't going to bother me if somebody questions whether I know the
game or criticizes my substitutions. But the one thing I can't
stand is having somebody say my team doesn't have toughness. I
don't think anybody can say that about this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Blount, a 6-10, 242-pounder, has made a career out of defense
and rebounding. He'll bring the kind of rebounding on the offensive
boards that the Suns haven't seen since Charles Barkley played in
Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't take (crap) from anybody,'' Blount said, smiling.
``I'm excited about this team. We've got a great group of guys here
and a lot of talent.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers, 6-7 and 255, shares that feeling. He struggled through
his last season with the Clippers, and vowed after signing with the
Suns to get in tip-top shape for his new start in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   He hired Marvin Brown, a former Duke football player, to help
him with his conditioning. Brown put Rogers on a sprinter's
program.
</P>
<P>
   ``He recruited me for football when I was in high school,'' said
Rogers, who ended up choosing basketball at Wake Forest over
football at Duke. ``I got to know him, and I called him up and told
him, `I'm with a new team. I want to get myself together.' So we
went to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers said it involved a lot of track work, running interval
sprints from 100 meters up to 400 meters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like a different person than last year,'' he said.
``It's not the same as playing basketball, but that will come here
in camp.''
</P>
<P>
   Ainge said he hasn't determined yet what role Rogers will fill,
but he's sure it will be integral.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a basketball player,'' Ainge said. ``He can pass, shoot,
dribble, defend.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been playing mostly outside and occasionally going down
low. I'd like him to play mostly inside and occasionally pop
outside. With Rodney and Corie added to Cliff and Googs, we've got
a lot of versatility.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to be a lot tougher inside, more physical and a
better rebounding team. We're going to give up a lot less layups
than we have in the past.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
