<HEADLINE>
NEDNEY SIGNED BY RAVENS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, ARIZ. - It didn't take former Cardinals kicker  &UR; Joe
Nedney long to find another NFL job.
</P>
<P>
   Nedney was claimed on waivers by the Baltimore Ravens on
Tuesday, 24 hours after he was released by the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is outstanding,'' Nedney said. ``I'm excited. I'm
ready to go. This is how the league works: Here one day, gone the
next. ``I'm glad to be among the ranks of the employed. It shows me
that I'm worth something.''
</P>
<P>
   Nedney flew to Baltimore on Tuesday night. He was scheduled to
take a physical examination this morning and practice this
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The Ravens have been looking for a kicker since  &UR; Matt Stover
missed a 38-yard field goal Sunday at Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore Coach  &UR; Brian Billick was so upset about the miss, he
was seen on TV cursing Stover.
</P>
<P>
   When Billick called his mother from the team bus after the game,
he was chewed out by her for his language. His wife and 10-year-old
daughter later chastised him.
</P>
<P>
   Stover, who was 6 of 9 on field goals and had only one touchback
in 17 kickoffs, will remain on the team because the Ravens have to
pay him a full year's as a vested veteran. Nedney is expected to
handle the kickoff duties and the long field-goal attempts in the
Ravens game Sunday at Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Nedney will be reunited with former Cardinals quarterback
 &UR; Stoney
 &UR; Case and Ravens deep snapper  &UR; Frank Wainwright and punter  &UR; Kyle
 &UR; Richardson, both of whom he played with on the Miami Dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   He said he wasn't surprised he was cut by the Cardinals, who had
two place-kickers the first four weeks of the season. They decided
to keep  &UR; Chris Jacke, who handled the place-kicking duties in the
first four games.
</P>
<P>
   Jacke replaced Nedney last December after Nedney suffered a torn
anterior cruciate ligament of his left (kicking) knee while making
at tackle at Kansas City on Nov. 27.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been preparing for something since the start of the
season,'' Nedney said. ``Actually, I'm glad it's over. I can move
on. &QL; 
Making an impression
</P>
<P>
   With  &UR; Rob Moore a long shot to play this weekend because of a
hamstring injury, the Cardinals might turn to their smallest player
for help at wide receiver.
</P>
<P>
   Mac Cody, listed at 5 feet 11 but actually about 5-7, will get a
chance in practice this week to compete for the No. 3 receiving job
with  &UR; Andy McCullough.
</P>
<P>
   Cody impressed the coaches with 59 punt-return yards, 15
kickoff-return yards and 11 receiving yards in last week's loss to
Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like him with the ball in his hands,'' Cardinals Coach
 &UR; Vince
 &UR; Tobin said. ``He has ability to make people miss. Sometimes we are
hung up more on size than we should be.
</P>
<P>
   ``He catches the ball extremely well, and it's not like he's a
rookie. He was the leading receiver in the Canadian Football League
one year (at Hamilton in 1996). I coached up in that league six
years and know there are quality receivers there. To lead that
league, he has to have something.'' &QL; 
Learning process
</P>
<P>
   Just because the Cardinals placed first-round draft pick  &UR; L.J.
Shelton on the active roster Monday doesn't mean he will see action
Sunday against the New York Giants.
</P>
<P>
   Shelton, the offensive tackle from Eastern Michigan, has
practiced only four times since ending his eight-week holdout.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see how much he knows in practice,'' Shelton said.
``He'll have to know a lot before there's a chance we'll play
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Short shots
</P>
<P>
   If starting cornerback  &UR; Corey Chavous' sore knee continues to
bother him, he could be replaced Sunday by  &UR; Tom Knight.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals announced Tuesday that all tickets for the Nov. 21
game against Dallas have been sold out. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
