<HEADLINE>
CARDS WON'T FACE GRAHAM  
 INJURY SIDELINES GIANTS' QB; COLLINS TO START 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, ARIZ. - A concussion to starting quarterback Kent Graham
has ended the New York Giants' quarterback controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Jim Fassel announced Tuesday that Kerry Collins, an
off-season free-agent acquisition, will make his first start in
Sunday's game against the Cardinals at Sun Devil Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``After listening to the doctors, the most important thing is to
not put Kent at greater risk,'' Fassel said. ``The doctors told me
because of the concussion Kent suffered on Sunday, he'd be more
susceptible to a concussion on Sunday. If Kent was to sustain
another concussion, we'd be looking at a longer period of
inactivity.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassel has been under public pressure to bench Graham, an
ex-Cardinal, for Collins, who signed a four-year, $16.9 million
contract in February.
</P>
<P>
   Graham was pulled in last Sunday's 16-15 victory against the
Philadelphia Eagles after throwing three interceptions. On two of
the interceptions, he threw late and into coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Fassel said after the game that Graham's concussion might have
affected his decision-making in the game. Graham said the
concussion hadn't bothered him.
</P>
<P>
   The concussion made Fassel's decision easier. In fact, Graham
has been ruled out of the game, and Mike Cherry will be Collins'
backup on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``A battery of tests on Kent on Monday showed some significant
alterations,'' team doctor Russell Warren said. ``At this point, he
is still symptomatic and will be re-evaluated on an ongoing basis.
My recommendation to the Giants is that Kent not play this week.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham started all four games this year for the Giants (2-2). He
has completed 70 of 120 passes (58.3 percent) for 746 yards and
four touchdowns. He has been intercepted four times and sacked six
times.
</P>
<P>
   Collins has completed 9 of 19 passes for 130 yards and been
intercepted once. He has come off the bench in two of the four
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I've been preparing well, even though I haven't gotten
a lot of reps in practice,'' Collins said. ``I feel confident if I
do have to play, I'll be able to execute this offense. I've started
a bunch of games, and I think I realize what it takes to be
prepared.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals faced both players last year. Graham completed
only 8 of 23 passes for 144 yards and was intercepted twice in last
year's 23-19 victory against the Cardinals on Dec. 6 at Sun Devil
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks later, Collins, playing for the New Orleans Saints,
completed 25 of 43 throws for 265 yards and one touchdown in a
19-17 loss to the Cardinals. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
