<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-DOAN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOAN BURIES A PAIR, CONTINUES HIS STREAK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Shane Doan always has been a streak scorer during his
NHL career, which is to say he has scored at least a goal every
other month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, that's right, I'm getting October and November out of
the way early though,'' Doan said, after scoring back-to-back goals
in the second period to lead the Phoenix Coyotes past the Mighty
Ducks of Anaheim 4-0 on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, after scoring 17 points as an NHL rookie, the
Coyotes were saying the onus was on the 21-year-old Doan to provide
the organization with a breakthrough year and be the 57-point man
he was in junior hockey.
</P>
<P>
   He played just 33 games in the NHL and was sent to the minors
for the first time in his career and played in 39 games for
Springfield.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the team again quietly said Doan must have a
breakthrough year. While other areas of his game were solid on the
ice, it took him 17 games to score a point, and 67 before he scored
his first goal. He finished with six goals and 16 assists in 79
games. But he provided hints of scoring ability with four points
and two game-winning goals in the first-round loss to St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Last August, a breakthrough was no longer talked about. It was
expected, and he was presented with a new three-year contract. He
seems to have picked up where he left off in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   He had an assist in the season-opening 2-1 win in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``The contract is a big part of it,'' he said. ``You feel a lot
more comfortable and I appreciated it. After the playoff series I
felt confident coming into the exhibition season. This year I was
trying to prepare myself for the regular season like the other
veterans do and that's to build toward it.''
</P>
<P>
   His first goal, at 3:17 of the second, came after he had time in
front of the net to deke a shot and pull Mighty Ducks goalie Guy
Hebert totally out of position, then calmly flip the puck into the
net.
</P>
<P>
   His second, a slapper from the slot that appeared at first to be
deflected by Dallas Drake just 4:32 later, gave the Coyotes a
comfortable 4-0 lead and signaled the end of the evening for
Hebert, who was pulled by Coach Craig Hartsburg in favor of Dominic
Roussel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just about to go for a line change,'' Doan said. ``We
got a turnover and I was up high and Jeremy hit me with a great
pass and I was lucky enough to get good wood on it and it went
in.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
