<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-METS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALFONZO'S SLAM SINKS D-BACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - During a conversation before his team's first-ever
playoff game against the New York Mets on Tuesday night,
Diamondbacks Manager Buck Showalter was asked what he thought about
Houston's victory over Atlanta in the National League's other
first-round game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me answer the question with a question,'' he said. ``Do
you think Atlanta is dead just because they're down, 0-1?''
</P>
<P>
   The same question now must be asked about the Diamondbacks after
their 8-4 loss at sold-out Bank One Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Are they dead just because they're down, 0-1, in the
best-of-five series?
</P>
<P>
   Because the Mets beat ace left-hander Randy Johnson in
resounding fashion, the evidence would seem to point toward an
affirmative response.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who had 364 strikeouts, 12 complete games and a 2.48
ERA while fashioning a 17-9 record, was roughed up for seven runs
on eight hits while walking three and striking out 11 in 8 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Second baseman Edgardo Alfonzo provided the big fireworks for
the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Alfonzo, who hit a key home run in the Mets' 5-0 victory at
Cincinnati on Monday night that clinched the NL wild card berth,
hit two Tuesday night, including a ninth-inning grand slam.
</P>
<P>
   Alfonzo's decisive shot came with two outs off right-hander
Bobby Chouinard, who entered the game with one out in the ninth
after Johnson loaded the bases. Johnson had run out of gas after
throwing 138 pitches.
</P>
<P>
   It appeared that Chouinard was on the verge of getting out of
trouble after third baseman Matt Williams made a diving stop of a
grounder by Rickey Henderson and forced Robin Ventura at the plate.
But Alfonzo connected on a 3-1 pitch and sent it near the
Diamondbacks bullpen in left field.
</P>
<P>
   Showalter said Johnson told him an inning before being removed
that he was ``getting there (tired).'' But he decided to send the
big man out for the ninth, anyway, and he gave up a base hit to
Ventura, a base hit to Rey Ordonez and a walk to Melvin Mora.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I just got a little tired and walked some people and
got behind and gave up a couple base hits and, you know, gave it
all I had out there in the ninth inning,'' said Johnson, who
scattered five hits through eight innings to beat the Mets, 10-1,
at Shea Stadium on May 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just tip my hat to the Mets. They played well last night (in
the wild card game) and they are probably riding a little bit on
that still. And I didn't make my pitches, and if you don't make
your pitches to major league hitters, you get hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the Diamondbacks' mind-set, Johnson said: ``The team
has never gotten too high on any win or too low on any loss all
year, so I don't imagine that will be the case after (Tuesday's)
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Showalter perhaps could have gone for right-handed closer Matt
Mantei to get his club out of trouble, but he decided on Chouinard,
who had a 5-2 record with one save in 32 games during the regular
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobby, we felt like _ or I felt like _ was best-suited for
that situation,'' Showalter said. ``He's done the job for us most
of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Alfonzo, who hit a solo homer off Johnson with one out in the
first inning, said he was trying to be patient against Chouinard.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't want to walk me,'' Alfonzo said. ``He was just
throwing me fastballs to see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   As he had on a handful of occasions during the season, Johnson
struggled in the early going.
</P>
<P>
   Alfonzo's home run, a two-run homer by first baseman John Olerud
and a fourth-inning sacrifice by Ordonez gave the Mets a 4-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Olerud's was the first homer off Johnson by a left-handed hitter
in postseason play and the first homer by any left-handed hitter
off Johnson since the California Angels' Jim Edmonds hit two off
Johnson when he was with Seattle on Sept. 23, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona cut the lead to 4-2 in the fourth when rookie first
baseman Erubiel Durazo continued his amazing 1999 climb when he hit
a one-out, opposite-field homer to left off right-hander Masato
Yoshii.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks got to Yoshii to tie the score at 4 in the
sixth inning. In a nice piece of hitting, second baseman Jay Bell
reached across for an outside pitch and served the ball to right
field for a leadoff single. Luis Gonzalez, who had career highs of
a .336 average, 26 homers and 111 RBIs, hit a 452-foot homer to
right. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
