<HEADLINE>
A DREAM NIGHT TURNS REAL UGLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The table was set. National TV. A sellout home crowd
on its feet, in a ballpark draped with bunting. Opportunity awaited
under a canopy of desert stars.
</P>
<P>
   He dreamed of this night.
</P>
<P>
   ``His'' night.
</P>
<P>
   He wanted the ball. He deserved it. For the Diamondbacks'
first-ever playoff game, Buck Showalter called upon his best, the
ace of the staff, their $52 million man. Who better than baseball's
strikeout leader packing 98 mph heat?
</P>
<P>
   ``This game is all about winning,'' the pitcher said. ``It is
for me.''
</P>
<P>
   He took the mound Tuesday night, looking confident and as nasty
as he is tall _ 6 feet 10, all arms and legs. His cold, predatory
eyes stared at the plate. The Mets looked back into the
sharp-featured face of a chicken hawk.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't flinch.
</P>
<P>
   Or blink.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks hired him to pitch in big games, and on the eve
of the biggest game in team history, Randy Johnson sounded like a
man who welcomed the pressure and the challenge. A fierce
competitor, he would be ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hyde to Jekyll,'' he said of his game-day personality change.
</P>
<P>
   He meant Jekyll to Hyde.
</P>
<P>
   You pictured him Tuesday afternoon at home, locked in a basement
laboratory. His wife calls the children together. And tells them,
``Daddy's not himself today.''
</P>
<P>
   Someone said having the Big Unit on your team is like keeping a
werewolf in the refrigerator. They make great watchdogs.
</P>
<P>
   But the Mets weren't frightened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think any of our guys are intimidated by anything,''
Mets Manager Bobby Valentine said before the game.
</P>
<P>
   Edgardo Alfonzo wasn't. The second batter Johnson faced _ and
the hero in the Mets' 8-4 victory _ started the scoring, drilling a
solo home run to center field.
</P>
<P>
   John Olerud wasn't intimidated either. When Johnson made another
costly mistake in the third inning, leaving a slider up in the
strike zone, Olerud ripped the ball over the right-field fence for
a 3-0 lead. It was the first home run Johnson had given up to a
left-handed hitter in two years.
</P>
<P>
   After four innings, the Mets had six hits and a 4-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   These road warriors who went to Cincinnati on Monday night and
beat the Reds to make the playoffs were aggressive at the plate. In
the sixth, Benny Agbayani hit a line drive that came at Johnson's
head like a New York subway train. Fortunately, Randy ducked.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was angry. Between pitches, he barked at himself.
Between innings, he walked off the field with those long slow
strides, jaw set, eyes downcast.
</P>
<P>
   His baserunning gaffe _ Johnson forgot how many outs the
Diamondbacks had, after hitting a double _ added to his
frustration.
</P>
<P>
   Only the Big Unit knows how much he wanted this game, how much
winning it meant to him. Last year he went 10-1 with a 1.28 ERA in
his two months as a hired gun in Houston. But he lost both playoff
starts, not because he didn't pitch well. The Astros booming bats
went silent.
</P>
<P>
   When he left Houston, the Astros tried to put a positive spin on
his departure. Johnson was 35 years old, the club noted. He has a
history of back problems. ``Pitchers are like race horses,'' said
Gerry Hunsicker, the Astros general manager. ``The experienced ones
break down just like the inexperienced ones. But the risk is
greater.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson wanted to finish what he started. His teammates had
brought the team back, with Luis Gonzalez tying the score in the
sixth with a two-run home run.
</P>
<P>
   But Johnson didn't make it. The end for him _ and the beginning
of the end for the D-Backs _ came in the ninth when Johnson,
tiring, gave up two singles and a walk to load the bases. Buck
Showalter had seen enough.
</P>
<P>
   The manager handed the ball to Bobby Chouinard.
</P>
<P>
   At 1:50 a.m. New York time, Alfonzo deposited it into the
stands, his grand slam home run clearing the bases that No. 51,
watching from the dugout, had filled. &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at (602) 444-8635 or at
david.casstevens(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
