<HEADLINE>
A TIME FOR DESPERATE MEASURES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - In its most simplistic form, a long and grueling
baseball season is all about adversity.
</P>
<P>
   Winning clubs meet it head-on, find a way to deal with it and
overcome it. Losing clubs founder in adversity's grip for stretches
at a time, usually unable to escape its clutches.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Randy Johnson, easily the club's best hope, and the
Diamondbacks have lost Game 1 of the division series to the New
York Mets, Arizona finds itself staring deep into the throat of Mr.
Adversity.
</P>
<P>
   The view, expectedly, is dark and depressing for the
Diamondbacks, no matter how many times they try to talk themselves
into not believing it. There are few rays of light inside this
gorge right now.
</P>
<P>
   With the tide apparently rising, the Diamondbacks find
themselves waist-deep in serious trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Send out the distress signals, because when the Mets can pop
Johnson for seven runs, what's to stop them from pummeling any of
the Diamondbacks' other starters, all of whom pale in comparison to
Johnson and his overpowering fastballs and sliders?
</P>
<P>
   For the Mets, this could be the kind of victory that catapulted
San Diego to its first-round victory against Houston last year,
when the Padres beat Johnson in Game 1 and came back to get him
again in Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt like if we beat him, we could probably beat him
again,'' San Diego's Tony Gwynn said last weekend. ``He pitched as
well as he could possibly pitch, and we still beat him.''
</P>
<P>
   If this all sounds like a time for desperate measures, it's
because that's exactly what the Diamondbacks are now facing. They
cannot head to the zoo-like atmosphere of Shea Stadium on Friday
night buried in a 2-0 hole. &QL; 
A tough match-up
</P>
<P>
   Todd Stottlemyre, remarkably pitching with a partially torn
rotator cuff and a torn labrum, will take the mound tonight and
hope to reverse the mounting tide against the Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Working against Arizona is New York's starting pitcher Kenny
Rogers. He's exactly the kind of pitcher who can give Diamondbacks
hitters fits. He is a finesse pitcher who is very athletic.
</P>
<P>
   If the Diamondbacks were facing a hard-throwing left-hander,
they would match up much better.
</P>
<P>
   The night actually started looking good for Arizona after Luis
Gonzalez slammed a key two-run home run in the sixth to tie the
score at 4. Given a reprieve, Johnson appeared to get into his
rhythm.
</P>
<P>
   But when Johnson began to tire late in the game, the
Diamondbacks' Achilles' heel was revealed for all to see. Manager
Buck Showalter called on Bobby Chouinard to come into a tense
situation in the top of the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Pitching in his first postseason game ever, Chouinard found
himself facing the bases loaded and only one out. After a
miraculous play by third baseman Matt Williams, Chouinard and the
Diamondbacks appeared to have Lady Luck on their side.
</P>
<P>
   But four pitches later, Edgardo Alfonzo was laughing his way
around the bases, following the three other Mets toward home
plate. &QL; 
Running out of options
</P>
<P>
   When it came to crunch time in the late innings and Showalter
needing a right-handed reliever, he was faced with choosing among
Chouinard, Darren Holmes, Gregg Olson and Andy Benes.
</P>
<P>
   Closer Matt Mantei was no real option because he has tended to
be erratic against the first batter he's faced, making a
bases-loaded walk too risky a proposition.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson had a horrible night all around, culminating with his
forgetting how many outs there were in the seventh inning when he
was on second base with Jay Bell due up.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of remaining near the base on a fly to left, Johnson
jogged to third, believing there were three outs. This on a night
when he did not have his usual dominating stuff on the mound.
</P>
<P>
   Is tonight a must-win situation? It's way beyond that stage.
Desperation must set in. &QL; 
Pedro Gomez can be reached at (602) 444-2364 or at
pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail.
</P>
</TEXT>
