<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-NINTH-INNING-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPECIAL MOMENT RAISES HOPE  
 `VICTORY SIGN' FALSE FOR D-BACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - It was one of those magical plays that the
Diamondbacks, once upon a time, turned into victory.
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman Matt Williams made a diving stop, got up and fired
a strike to home plate to keep the New York Mets from breaking a
tie in the ninth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way our year has gone, when he made that play, I thought
we were going to get out of that inning and come back and score
some runs,'' said left fielder Luis Gonzalez, who had tied the
score at 4 in the sixth with a two-run homer. ``But that's not the
way it happened.''
</P>
<P>
   If right-hander Bobby Chouinard only had it to do over. If he
could have gotten a strike first and not fallen behind the count.
If he had not had to face one of the hottest hitters on the planet.
</P>
<P>
   After falling behind in the count, 3-1, to second baseman
Edgardo Alfonzo, Chouinard said he threw a fastball ``right down
the middle'' and Alfonzo deadened the sellout crowd at Bank One
Ballpark with a grand slam that gave New York an 8-4 win and a 1-0
lead in the best-of-five National League Division Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to walk him,'' Chouinard said. ``I didn't want
to complicate things with (left-handed hitter) John Olerud coming
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Chouinard, who started the year in Triple-A Tucson, had pitched
well down the stretch, but this was all new. A huge crowd. A
playoff game. Trying to bail Randy Johnson out of a bases-loaded
jam with one out in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Chouinard fell behind, 2-0, in the count to Rickey Henderson,
the first batter he faced, before Henderson hit a shot to Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just killed myself by falling behind,'' Chouinard said. ``I
was over-throwing. In a game like that, it's hard to keep your
emotions in check.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Buck Showalter had both Chouinard and closer Matt Mantei
warming up in the bullpen, while Johnson labored in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   With the bases full and no margin for error, Showalter elected
to go with Chouinard over Mantei with a selective Henderson at the
plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobby has been one our best pitchers out of the bullpen,''
Showalter said. ``I thought he was best in that situation. He's
done the job for us most of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Matt (Williams) made a great play. It looked like we had a
shot to get out of it. He was trying to get a ball away and down
and it ran back over the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   Showalter had right-handers Darren Holmes, Gregg Olson and Andy
Benes in the bullpen. Holmes said Chouinard was the right call.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of the reasons why we're where we're at,'' Holmes
said. ``Without him, who knows where we'd be right now. He's done a
great job.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't get down. You can't dwell on it. He's a bullpen guy.
He's mentally tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Chouinard said he won't let the loneliest moment he's felt on
the mound linger.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't,'' he said. ``It's a short series. We have to win
three out of four. I'd like to get back out there (tonight). We're
not out of it yet. I won't let this defeat me.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't matter to Gonzalez that he had a double and a 452-foot
home run that brought the Diamondbacks back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll take 0 for 4 if we can win the game,'' he said. ``But
we'll be ready to play. We'll put this one behind us.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who has played in more postseason games than any other
Diamondback, isn't worried.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wouldn't be here if they didn't do that (come through
with huge hits) once in a while,'' Williams said. ``And we wouldn't
be here if we didn't do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll let it fly (today).'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
