<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-ALFONZO-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS HAVE MAGIC MAN IN ALFONZO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAUL CORO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The New York Mets don't know whether to touch second
baseman Edgardo Alfonzo or leave him be.
</P>
<P>
   They don't want to mess with this magic groove he is riding, but
they sure wouldn't mind if whatever he's got would rub off on
everybody else.
</P>
<P>
   A night after he kick-started the Mets' victory in Cincinnati
with a first-inning, two-run homer to give them postseason life,
Alfonzo's torrid bat carried them past the Diamondbacks on Tuesday
at Bank One Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   He crushed a 98 mph Randy Johnson fastball for another
first-inning homer, a solo shot, and then escalated his hero status
in Queens to an unfathomable plane with a two-out, second-deck
grand slam in the ninth. It gave the Mets an 8-4 victory before
49,584 stunned fans in Game 1 of the National League Division
Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now is when it counts,'' Alfonzo said. ``I've been feeling
really good at home plate.''
</P>
<P>
   Alfonzo already was entrenched in good graces in the borough for
Monday's heroics that also included an RBI double. That helped put
New York in the postseason for the first time in 11 years. On
Tuesday, he was the star attraction again.
</P>
<P>
   A slick glove man who hit .304 with 27 homers, Alfonzo entered
the night hitless in three tries against Johnson in his career. He
watched two strikes before rocketing a 422-foot blast to
left-center field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just trying to be patient with myself,'' Alfonzo said.
``When I get behind in the count, I don't expect to hit a home run.
I think it was just a good pitch for me.''
</P>
<P>
   In the ninth, he watched three straight balls from reliever
Bobby Chouinard to set himself up to anticipate a 3-1 fastball. He
jumped all over the offering, almost too much, as it hooked inside
the foul pole for a 397-foot shot.
</P>
<P>
   Chouinard said Arizona's coaches had warned the staff that
Alfonzo was a great fastball hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was supposed to be outside, but it was right over the
middle,'' Chouinard said. ``As soon as I heard the bat hit the
ball, I just knew it was a matter of fair or foul.''
</P>
<P>
   The pitch was foul. The hit was fair.
</P>
<P>
   ``He always comes through,'' center fielder Shawon Dunston said.
``He's clutch. That was a beautiful thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Alfonzo was not the only Met who got to Johnson. Left-handed
hitters John Olerud and Robin Ventura went 4 for 8, including two
extra-base hits. Johnson had only yielded one extra-base hit this
season and came into the game with lefties batting just .103
against him.
</P>
<P>
   Olerud creamed a two-run homer in the third for his first career
hit off Johnson, who had not yielded a home run to a left-handed
hitter since Angels outfielder Jim Edmonds hit one in September of
1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
