<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-SCENE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FANS JAM DOWNTOWN  
 STREETS PACKED, TRAFFIC HEAVY BUT PARKING A BREEZE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN STANLEY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Imagine a city bigger than Flagstaff, composed
entirely of delirious Diamondbacks devotees, howling hockey fans
and sophisticated theater aficionados.
</P>
<P>
   Now imagine all of them converging on downtown Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   That's what happened Tuesday night as the Diamondbacks hosted
their first-ever playoff game, the Coyotes opened their season at
home and ``A'' ``Chorus Line'' began its run at the Orpheum
Theatre.
</P>
<P>
   Despite earlier fears of an ugly downtown gridlock, traffic
flowed relatively smoothly and parking was plentiful for the nearly
70,000 sports fans and theater patrons who flocked downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Suzette Crider, who had been transporting people in her
horse-drawn carriage since 5 p.m., said she had seen a lot more
foot traffic Tuesday than normal.
</P>
<P>
   Like many, John Konvicka, a salesman, and Janis Langford, an
accountant, both of Scottsdale, came early to avoid traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd rather be drinking margaritas than sitting in traffic,''
Langford said, as they waited to see ``A Chorus Line''.
</P>
<P>
   Tim and Lori Wilson of Prescott, who arrived two hours before
Coyotes faceoff because of concerns about traffic, found parking to
be a breeze.
</P>
<P>
   But traffic was heavy in places, especially as game time
approached. Tempers flared, horns blared and cars were backed up at
Central Avenue and Jefferson Street an hour before the first pitch
at Bank One Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took us 25 minutes to go 25 miles to get here,'' said Steve
Colombo, of Scottsdale, ``and another 25 minutes to go 25 yards
once we got downtown.''
</P>
<P>
   Colombo, 35, had tickets for both the Coyotes game and the
Diamondbacks game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once the (Coyotes) game is half over, or if it gets boring,
I'll head over to the ballpark,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Loren and Peg Andrews of Sun City West said they left home
earlier than they normally do to attend the show at the Orpheum,
but that they really didn't need to.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expected it to be a lot worse than it was,'' Peg said.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix opened 2,700 parking spaces at the new Civic East Garage
north of the ballpark Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Traffic is always the main problem when there are multiple
events downtown,'' Phoenix police spokesman Jeff Halstead said.
``But we'll also be checking vendors, looking after lost kids _ all
kinds of things.''
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix police Sgt. Robert Jones, working out of the Downtown
Special Events Command Center on Jefferson Street, said about 48
police officers were on duty downtown Tuesday, about 15 more than
normal. &QL; 
John Stanley can be reached at (602) 444-4414 or at
john.stanley(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
