<HEADER>
A7973 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s BC-BBN-DBACKS-BICKLEY-AZ     10-06 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS LOSS BAD OMEN FOR D-BACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - One game means nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Unless, of course, you're talking about Tuesday night's game. A
terrible tease of a baseball game that instantly changed the tone
of an entire series.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of an 8-4 loss and an 0-1 postseason deficit come a
few logical conclusions, none of them good for the Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   After swatting around Randy Johnson, the Mets have no reason to
think they can't do it again, if necessary. An emphatic victory to
start the playoffs _ on the road and after an overnight flight _
will only pad the armor of a battle-tested opponent.
</P>
<P>
   And after winning their fifth consecutive game since teetering
on the edge of elimination, the Mets are starting to suspect
``they'' are the team of destiny.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel very confident,'' Mets reliever Dennis Cook said. ``If
we keep playing this brand of baseball, I like our chances.''
</P>
<P>
   You know, there's nothing like New Yorkers overflowing with
confidence.
</P>
<P>
   And that's what we have here.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can create momentum,'' Matt Williams said. ``But we want
to stop that momentum (on Wednesday) in whatever fashion it
takes.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite their mad stagger just to reach the playoffs, the Mets
entered Game 1 with a distinct advantage. In essence, they had been
playing under postseason duress for the past 13 games. Granted, the
Mets lost most of those contests. But in the end, they got the hang
of it. They swept the Pirates to close the season and stay alive.
And they beat the Reds in Game No. 163, winner takes all. &QL; 
Tests of character &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pressure had become a way of life for the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those guys have had an incredible week, conquered a lot of
things,'' Luis Gonzalez said. ``But I think, on (Wednesday), this
team will be right back. We've had tests of character as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Pockets of pressure, maybe. But the Diamondbacks haven't played
a really important game since a weekend series in Atlanta to start
September. Nothing close to the encompassing vacuum of playoff
baseball. And certainly not under the spotlight of a bona fide
historic event in Arizona history.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks almost plowed through it all. Matt Williams
with his glove, Jay Bell with his situational hitting, Luis
Gonzalez and Erubiel Durazo with big-time home runs. But in the
end, one team was simply sharper and one team was simply better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody expected this to be easy,'' Manager Buck
Showalter said. ``And now we have to make it tougher on them.''
</P>
<P>
   A shame, really.
</P>
<P>
   For all the warranted criticism over a lack of passion, the
locals in the stands finally made it feel like a budding baseball
town. People lined up before the game to get an autograph from the
owner, Jerry Colangelo. Babe Ruth's daughter was in attendance. The
carnival atmosphere outside the BOB was real, not contrived. Inside
the building, fans actually hung on every pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Mets unfazed by conditions &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Nevertheless, a few words of advice: When the scoreboard tells
you to get loud because ESPN is about to go live and the nation
will be watching, don't. It makes us look like Hooterville, USA.)
</P>
<P>
   Problem is, the Mets were unfazed by any of the external
conditions. Two mistake pitches from Johnson ended up in the seats,
a pair of unwanted souvenirs. They stole a couple of bases,
squeezed home a run. They hit Johnson and a capacity crowd of
nearly 50,000 with a stun gun. And after the hosts rallied to tie
the game, the Mets did it again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good to know that we can get to him (Johnson),'' Olerud
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets didn't exactly thrive against left-handed pitchers this
season (22-18), and the prospect of facing four lefties in five
games _ Johnson, Omar Daal, Brian Anderson and Johnson again _
seemed to be another intangible in Arizona's favor.
</P>
<P>
   That, too, has changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody on our team necessarily thinks that
we're a .500 team when we play against a left-hander,'' the Mets'
Robin Ventura said. ``Those numbers don't mean a whole lot once
you're here.''
</P>
<P>
   In truth, they don't mean a thing. All that matters is belief
and results.
</P>
<P>
   (Big) Advantage, Mets. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at (602) 444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com via e-mail.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
