<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 03:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7974 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s BC-BBN-GOMEZ-WRITETHRU-A     10-06 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-GOMEZ-WRITETHRU-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TIME FOR DESPERATE MEASURES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - In its most simplistic form, a long and grueling
baseball season is all about adversity.
</P>
<P>
   Winning clubs meet it head-on, find a way to deal with it and
overcome it. Losing clubs flounder in adversity's clutches for
weeks on end, unable to escape its grip.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Randy Johnson, the Diamondbacks' messiah, has been
slain by the New York Mets, the National League West champions find
themselves staring deep into the throat of Mr. Adversity.
</P>
<P>
   With Johnson, the league's most dominating pitcher all season,
looking very beatable in Game 1, Arizona is faced with an uphill
climb that may simply be too daunting a task to overcome.
</P>
<P>
   The tide is coming in at the Diamondbacks, who find themselves
waist-deep in serious trouble. The kind that can easily swallow
even the most confident of clubs.
</P>
<P>
   Send out the distress signals, because when the Mets can pop
Johnson for seven runs, what's to stop them from pummeling any of
the Diamondbacks other starters, all of whom pale in comparison to
Johnson? &QL; 
A chink in Johnson's armor
</P>
<P>
   New York second baseman Edgardo Alfonzo, one of the best-kept
secrets in the game the past few years, spit on Johnson's ninth
pitch of the game, an obvious mistake fastball that stayed out over
the heart of the plate, sending it deep into the seats in
left-center field.
</P>
<P>
   It was only one run, but the message was sent to the rest of his
teammates: Johnson could be had on this night. Three more runs
followed in the next three innings as New York loaded up on
confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Arizona managed to tie the score in the sixth
inning, the Mets never relinquished the lead or stopped having that
look of a winner on this night.
</P>
<P>
   For the Mets, this could be the same type of victory that
catapulted San Diego to its first-round victory against Houston
last year, when the Padres beat Johnson in Game 1 before beating
him again in the decisive fourth game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt like if we beat him, we could probably beat him
again,'' San Diego's Tony Gwynn said last weekend. ``He pitched as
well as he could possibly pitch, and we still beat him.''
</P>
<P>
   If this sounds like a time for desperate measures, it's because
that's exactly what the Diamondbacks are now facing. They cannot
head to the zoo-like atmosphere of Shea Stadium Friday night buried
in a 2-0 hole.
</P>
<P>
   When Johnson, who ran the Diamondbacks out of an inning in the
seventh when he forgot how many outs there were, began to tire in
the ninth, the Mets seized the chance and exposed a flaw in the
Diamondbacks' bullpen.  &QL; 
Running out of options
</P>
<P>
   Closer Matt Mantei, who has had difficulties walking first
batters, was not an option with the bases full of Mets. Manager
Buck Showalter's choices consisted of right-handed setup relievers
Andy Benes, Bobby Chouinard, Darren Holmes and Gregg Olson.
Showalter called on Chouinard, who had never before appeared in a
postseason game.
</P>
<P>
   Chouinard managed to escape danger against Rickey Henderson, but
only because of a miraculous play by third baseman Matt Williams.
Two pitches later, Chouinard was tracking Alfonzo's second home
run, this one a towering blast deep into the left-field corner.
</P>
<P>
   Just like that, it was over.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Diamondbacks pin their hopes on Todd Stottlemyre, who
remarkably is pitching with a partially torn rotator cuff and a
torn labrum. He also has a 2-5 postseason record that includes a
6.59 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks will need everything Stottlemyre can muster
from his frayed right shoulder. Making matters worse for the
Diamondbacks is the opposing pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Rogers, a finesse left-hander, is exactly the kind of
pitcher who gives Arizona's hitters fits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've won games before after losses,'' reliever Greg Swindell
said. ``(Tonight's) a big game. If we go down 0-2, that's
different.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not a big game. This is a win-or-else-it's-really-over
type of game for the Diamondbacks. As it stands, the belief that
this series may already be over is taking hold in many corners.
</P>
<P>
   Desperation time has arrived. That's what happens when your ace
gets beat _ and beat good. &QL; 
Pedro Gomez can be reached at (602) 444-2364 or at
pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
