<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 10:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7997 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i PM-BRITAIN-WRECK-1006-CO     10-06 1272
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 PM-BRITAIN-WRECK-1006-COX &HT;    WITH 27 DEAD, RESCUE CREWS BEGIN TASK OF REMOVING BODIES,
LOOKING FOR ANSWERS
 &HT;    700&AMP;ADD
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Search teams clad in white plastic coveralls probed the
charred and mangled commuter rail car this morning that officials
fear contains many more bodies of people killed Tuesday in one of
Britain's worst-ever rail disasters.
</P>
<P>
   The first-class car was near the lead of a train carrying
commuters into London during morning rush hour suggesting that it
may have been carrying dozens of passengers. The car, which was
covered by a cocoon of tarpaulins Wednesday morning, was crushed in
the collision and engulfed in a diesel fuel-fed fireball.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators tried to stabilize the car overnight and wait for
morning before examining its interior. Inside the damage was so
complete that officials expressed concern that they may be unable
to discern the human remains. ``There is nothing inside but ash and
debris,'' said Tony Thompson, the superintendent of the British
Transport Police, during an afternoon news conference.
</P>
<P>
   The death toll from the disastrous collision increased to 27
Wednesday morning, police said. About 160 people were injured, and
more than 42 remained in area hospitals Wednesday. Fourteen of
those are in critical condition, primarily from burns.
</P>
<P>
   The heavily damaged car _ belonging to Great Western Trains _
had sitting spaces for 48 people and standing room for many more.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the number of people still reported missing, Andy
Trotter, a deputy police commissioner at the scene, said ``the
number of fatalities will rise considerably.'' No more passengers
are expected to be found alive in the wreckage.
</P>
<P>
   Heavy cranes were being assembled to allow rescue crews to lift
the train cars so investigators can look for more bodies
underneath. ``This is going to be a long and laborious task,''
Trotter said.
</P>
<P>
   While the cause of the crash has not been determined,
investigators are expected to focus on driver error or signal
failure, newspapers reported Wednesday. The inquiry is expected to
look first at whether the driver of the outbound train ran a red
light near the station.
</P>
<P>
   Detailed tests also were being performed on signaling equipment.
Investigators have recovered a data recorder _ called a ``black
box'' _ from one train and are still searching for the other. Both
engineers were presumably killed on impact.
</P>
<P>
   Among the flowers left on a rail bridge overlooking the scene of
the disaster was a bouquet bearing a card dedicated to one of the
engineers. It began ``For Dear Brian,'' and was signed, ``God bless
you, Gerald and Maureen.''
</P>
<P>
   Further, it read: ``Today is the saddest day of my life when my
brother was taken away from us . . . My only wish is that he never
suffered.''
</P>
<P>
   The engineer's last name has not yet been released by the rail
company because his body has not been officially identified.
</P>
<P>
   British Prime Minister Tony Blair and his wife, Cherie, toured
St Mary's Hospital in Paddington Wednesday to meet victims of the
rail crash and thank the emergency services for their work. During
the 45-minute private tour Blair praised the ``truly heroic''
doctors and nurses who treated injured passengers, said a spokesman
for No 10. Downing Street.
</P>
<P>
   The trains collided two miles from busy Paddington Station at
8:11 a.m. (local time) Tuesday sending smoke and flames into the
sky over a west London neighborhood. The accident occurred on the
same rail line as 1997 crash that killed seven, and prompted
concerns about the safety of the city's aging rail system. A
passenger rail company, Great Western Trains, was fined $2.47
million for safety violations in that crash. Great Western operated
one of the trains involved in Tuesday's disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Train drivers threatened Wednesday to consider going on strike
unless rail companies respond positively within seven days to
demands for a package of improved safety measures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not tolerate any more unsafe working practices and we
will not tolerate our members, or the public, being put at risk,''
said Mick Rix, a leader or the drivers' union. ``Failure to respond
within seven days will bring the train companies into dispute with
this union.''
</P>
<P>
   The union is demanding the installation nationwide of a
fail-safe automatic train protection system as well as in-cab
radios. The sophisticated, but expensive, automatic train
protection system is fitted on only a few British lines. Its
network-wide installation could cost as much as $1.6 billion and
has been ruled out because of its cost.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows).
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Stotson of the Transport Police told CNN that he
believed the two crowded trains were traveling at a relatively slow
speed when they collided.
</P>
<P>
   The rail cars were flung from the tracks, their metal roofs
sheared off by the impact. Doctors said many of the injured were
severely burned; some suffered scorched lungs after they inhaled
the super-heated air. Hospitals in the surrounding area were
overwhelmed with casualties.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was one big bang and then there was black smoke and
flames,'' said Marianne O'Neill, who was roused from bed at her
house, 200 yards from the accident. ``It was a dreadful thing,''
said O'Neill, who owns a pub nearby. ``It was an eerie thing. All
day long there were so many people around but there was also a
silence about the place.''
</P>
<P>
   Great Western said as many as 500 people might have been on
board its train, minutes away from Paddington. Thames Trains' cars
may have carried 150 passengers.
</P>
<P>
   Paddington, one of London's busiest stations and the terminus
for the city's primary train to Heathrow Airport, is expected to
remain closed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   A crane and special lights were brought in Tuesday to help the
recovery teams. Authorities also were planning to tear down two
small buildings near the wreckage to gain better access.
</P>
<P>
   Amateur video shot minutes after the accident shown on news
broadcasts here showed passengers, some in business suits, emerging
from the windows and doors of a rail car resting in its side. Some
even crawled back into the car to help other passengers as flames
roared nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Some described their feelings as they frantically tried to
escape. ''I was thinking, 'God, please don't let me die,''' Stuart
Allen told The Associated Press. ''You've got flames. You've got
smoke. You've got a big bang. You've just got to think the worst.''
</P>
<P>
   Passenger David Taylor described ``an almighty bang.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked up, and I could see the front of the coach was on
fire,'' Taylor said. ``There were balls of flames coming down both
sides.''
</P>
<P>
   Robin Touquet, an emergency room doctor at St. Mary's Hospital
told Sky News that it was one of the worst episodes of his career.
``The smell of burning flesh has an absolute acidity about it, and
when you see passengers coming in from a World War II-type of film
with white bandages over their face, with just two eyes looking
out, one realizes just how horrific it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Rosenheim, 44, an American traveling on the Great Western
train, felt fortunate just to be alive. While Rosenheim said he
would get on a train again. ''It is very depressing to think in the
light of this terrible tragedy that it can still happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's accident was Britain's worst rail crash since December
1988, when three trains collided outside London's Clapham Junction,
killing 35 people.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
