<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
  
 Wednesday, Oct. 6, 1999     
 Editors      The Hearst News Service will file the following for
Thursday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6320.    (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all sluglines.)   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   POLICE-PROFILING (Oakland, Calif.) _ Some angry local elected
officials said it was ``racist'' for California Gov. Gray Davis to
veto a controversial bill that would have required police officers
to track the race of motorists they stop. Racial profiling has been
a hot national issue this year with several states and the U.S.
Congress considering bills to track it. By MATTHEW YI.
</P>
<P>
   FEINSTEIN-OPPONENT (Sacramento, Calif.) _ Silicon Valley
entrepreneur Ron Unz, who wrote a successful 1998 ballot initiative
banning bilingual education in California, announced he will
challenge Sen. Dianne Feinstein for re-election. By ROBERT SALLDAY.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BOB-EDWARDS (San Francisco) _ Bob Edwards goes to bed at 6 p.m.
so he can be in a Washington, D.C., radio studio by 2 a.m. to host
the early-morning radio news magazine ``Morning Edition'' on
National Public Radio. By BERNADETTE FAY.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SILICON-RACIAL (San Francisco) _ Silicon Valley's record on
racial and cultural diversity is ``a national disgrace,'' according
to civil rights leader Jesse Jackson who announced plans to bring
an updated version of the 1960s civil rights movement to the 1990s
high-tech industry. By MATT BEER.
</P>
<P>
   COMPANY-RESEARCH (Colonie, N.Y.) _ For years Intermagnetics
General Co. was run more like a university than a business. There
was plenty of time for research and science for science's sake. The
system worked. But new CEO Glenn Epstein wants to make the company
more market sensitive. By JO-ANN JOHNSTON.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PARTY-COOKBOOK (Albany, N.Y.) _ Emeril Lagasse's new cookbook,
``Every Day's a Party,'' takes cooks through a year of events,
including the Sugar Bowl, Mardi Gras, the French Market Tomato
Festival, the New Iberia Gumbo Cook-Off and Christmas dinner,
Louisiana style. ``I don't want people to lose the tradition and
the wonderful things that have built over the last couple of
hundred years,'' Lagasse says. By RUTH FANTASIA.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-AGING-NINERS (Santa Clara, Calif.) _ On a team deep in the
throes of ancestor worship, the time is as ripe as a summer peach
for the San Francisco 49ers to look to the future by seeing if the
young players populating the lower economic rungs on the roster can
actually play the game. By JOHN CRUMPACKER.
</P>
<P>
   RATTO-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Sports fans have gone beyond just
abusive, and one wonders if maybe we aren't closing in on the day
when fans finally outlive their usefulness on site. Some smart
people suggest that the common denominator here is alcohol, and
that makes sense as far as it goes. By RAY RATTO.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Saratoga Springs, N.Y.) _ The First Amendment
protects religious freedom just as it protects free artistic
expression. But the controversial art exhibit at the Brooklyn
Museum of Art raises this touchy legal question: What's the duty of
the custodian of public funds when that money ends up subsidizing
what many people can reasonably interpret as an artistic attack on
their faith? By DAN LYNCH.
</P>
</TEXT>
