<HEADER>
A8082 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS07-TAKE     10-06 1958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS07-TAKE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: Edmund Morris, author of the controversial new biography of
Ronald Reagan, previously won a Pulitzer Prize for a biography of
the early life of Theodore Roosevelt. I thought Morris was working
on a sequel to that. Do you know the status?
</P>
<P>
   A: Morris says he hopes the Roosevelt sequel, ``Theodore Rex,''
will be out on Sept. 14, 2001, the centenary of his accession to
the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Some months ago, the American Airlines pilots' union was
fined $10 million for its ``sick-in'' campaign against the airline.
Was it ever paid?
</P>
<P>
   A: The fine, assessed by U.S. District Judge Joe Kendall in
April against the Allied Pilots Association, actually was $45.5
million. The union is appealing, said a spokeswoman for AMR Corp.,
American's parent company. Kendall has said interest will accrue
until the $45.5 million is paid.
</P>
<P>
   Pilots began calling in sick Feb 6 to demand guarantees they
wouldn't lose out on promotions and flights to the lower-paid
pilots of Reno Air, which American bought. The job action led to
6,600 canceled flights, with the fine resulting when the pilots
disobeyed Kendall's return-to-work order.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What were the circumstances of the death of country music
performer BoxCar Willie? Also, how did he get his start?
</P>
<P>
   A: The entertainer died April 12 in Branson, Mo., after a long
battle with leukemia. He had been diagnosed with the disease three
years ago, and after a brief remission it returned last year. Until
his health began to fail, BoxCar Willie _ born Lecil Travis Martin
in Sterrett, Texas, on Sept. 1, 1931_ performed as many as six
shows a week at the BoxCar Willie Theatre in Branson.
</P>
<P>
   BoxCar Willie was an invented hobo character whose creation
propelled Martin to fame. His singing career never got off the
ground while he was performing under the name Marty Martin.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-'60s, Martin wrote a song called ``BoxCar Willie,''
based on a hobo he saw on a train while he was stuck in traffic.
The hobo reminded Martin of a buddy named Willie Wilson, he said,
so the character was born. He adopted the name as his performance
character and dressed like a hobo on stage.
</P>
<P>
   In 1976 he replaced a sick George Jones at a Nashville club. As
BoxCar Willie, Martin was spotted by a Scottish booking agent who
took him on a tour of England. Further tours in England established
his popularity there. In the early '80s he was a regular on
television's ``Hee Haw,'' while cranking out a number of albums as
well as playing a hobo in ``Sweet Dreams,'' a film about Patsy
Cline.
</P>
<P>
   Q: People say that Georgia's Stone Mountain is the largest stone
monolith in the world. How does it compare to the one in Australia?
</P>
<P>
   A: Ayers Rock, in central Australia's Uluru National Park, is
bigger, but Stone Mountain is the largest piece of exposed granite
in the world. Ayers Rock rises more than 1,130 feet above the
surrounding desert plain. The oval sandstone rock measures 2.2
miles long by 1 1/2 miles wide.
</P>
<P>
   World Book Encyclopedia describes Stone Mountain as ``the
largest smooth-sided rock dome in North America,'' measuring about
2 miles long by 1 mile wide. At its highest point, the granite mass
rises more than 700 feet above the surrounding terrain.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The recent loss of the Mars Climate Orbiter because of
confusion between English and metric measurements prompts my
question: What has happened to efforts to initiate the use of the
metric system in the United States?
</P>
<P>
   A: Public acceptance continues to be slow, but the federal
government hasn't backed away from supporting a conversion to
metric.
</P>
<P>
   A bill passed by Congress in 1975 established a policy of
voluntary conversion to the metric system of weights and measures
for U.S. trade and commerce, and an amended bill passed in 1988
made metric the ``preferred'' system. In addition, the bill called
for agencies of the federal government to use metric for purchases,
grants, and other business-related activities. And many U.S.-made
products that compete in the global market are in metric.
</P>
<P>
   At some point _ especially if other countries stop buying
non-metric goods _ that competition may force the United States to
change. After all, according to the U.S. Metric Association, 99
percent of the rest of the world uses metric.
</P>
<P>
   Q: It was reported several weeks ago that the remains of an
ancient person, thought to date to 3,500 years ago, were found in
Canada. Testing was to be done at a lab, but I never saw or heard
anything else about it. Can you update me?
</P>
<P>
   A: The well-preserved remains, whose discovery was announced
Aug. 24, aren't nearly as old as originally was speculated. Initial
reports about the remains, found in a glacier in a remote corner of
northwestern British Columbia, said only that scientists and tribal
leaders had discovered ``an ancient man'' on Aug. 14 in
Tatshenshini-Alsek Park.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists at first had thought the remains could be up to
10,000 years old. But clothes on the mummified adult male, now
called Kwaday Dan Sinchi _ ``Long Ago Person Found'' in the
language of the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations tribe of the
region _ have been determined to be considerably more recent.
Carbon-dating tests conducted on the apparel indicate that the man
met his fate sometime between 1415 and 1445.
</P>
<P>
   The body is being stored at the Royal British Columbia Museum in
Victoria while scientists develop a research plan. The research
will be under joint provincial and aboriginal supervision. After
that, the body will be returned to the Champagne-Aishihik for
burial.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I frequently read and hear about Social Security trust funds.
What are they, how are they funded, and how are they invested?
</P>
<P>
   A: The trust funds are financial accounts in the U.S. Treasury
funded by Social Security and Medicare taxes, premiums and other
income. The only purposes for which these trust funds can be used
are to pay Social Security and Medicare benefits and program
administrative costs, said Patti Patterson of the Social Security
Administration.
</P>
<P>
   By law, the assets of the Social Security program must be
invested in interest-bearing government securities or in securities
whose principal and interest is guaranteed by the government.
</P>
<P>
   The trust funds hold a mix of short-term and long-term
government bonds. The funds can hold both regular Treasury
securities and ``special obligation'' securities issued only to
federal trust funds. In practice, the securities in the Social
Security trust funds are of the ``special obligation'' type,
according to the agency.
</P>
<P>
   These funds earn interest set at the average market yield on
long-term Treasury securities. Interest from investments in 1998
amounted to $49.3 billion, representing an effective annual
interest rate of 7.2 percent, the agency reported.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who was the first person to receive monthly Social Security
benefits?
</P>
<P>
   A: Ida May Fuller of Ludlow, Vt., starting Jan. 31, 1940. Three
years earlier, Ernest Ackerman of Cleveland received the first
benefit payment, a lump-sum, one-time payout of 17 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Members of my household are curious about Robert Novak of
CNN's ``Crossfire.'' Do you know anything about his educational and
professional background? Also, what is his address?
</P>
<P>
   A: Novak, who was born Feb. 26, 1931, in Joliet, Ill., took his
first news jobs as a reporter for the Joliet Herald-News and the
Champaign-Urbana (Ill.) Courier while attending the University of
Illinois between 1948 and 1952. He has a bachelor's of arts degree
from Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   After two years of Army duty (1952-54), Novak joined the staff
of the Associated Press in Omaha, Neb., and after that was assigned
to Indianapolis. In 1957, the AP transferred him to Washington,
where he helped cover Congress. He joined the Washington bureau of
The Wall Street Journal in 1958 and became the newspaper's chief
congressional correspondent in 1961.
</P>
<P>
   In 1963, Novak teamed with Rowland Evans to write ``Inside
Report,'' a syndicated political column, which evolved into a
newsletter, ``The Evans-Novak Political Report.'' Novak has been a
comentator for Corinthian Broadcasting in Washington, as well as a
commentator on CNN. He hosts ``Crossfire'' with Mary Matalin and
Bill Press. Novak also has written four books.
</P>
<P>
   Mail can be sent to him in care of CNN, 820 First St. NE,
Washington, DC 20002.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm curious about the official residence of the vice
president of the United States. What can you tell us about it?
</P>
<P>
   A: The 33-room mansion is on the grounds of the U.S. Naval
Observatory, on Massachusetts Avenue in Washington. Formerly known
as the Admiral's House, the residence served as the home of the
observatory superintendent until 1928, and of the chief of naval
operations until 1974. Adm. Elmo Zumwalt was the last naval
resident. Although the president has had an official Washington
residence since 1800, not until July 1974 did Congress give the
vice president a permanent home.
</P>
<P>
   Designed by Washington architect Leon E. Dessez and completed in
1893, the house is a Queen Anne-style, three-story, brick and wood
frame structure barely visible from the road. The first floor
consists of an entrance hall, dining room, living room, library and
administrative offices. Four bedrooms, plus a master bedroom suite,
are on the second and third floors, along with a family room,
kitchenette and office. The main kitchen, laundry, and quarters for
the staff and Secret Service are in the basement.
</P>
<P>
   The house is on 12 acres, landscaped in the style of an English
park. The Navy still owns and maintains the house and supplies
staff, including six enlistees who serve as stewards.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How many children does Sen. John McCain have? I've seen it
reported as both five and seven.
</P>
<P>
   A: McCain (R-Ariz.) married his first wife, Carol, in 1965, and
adopted her two sons, Douglas and Andrew. They had a daughter,
Sidney Ann. The couple divorced in 1980. Later that same year,
McCain married Cindy Hensley. They have four children, Meghan,
Jack, Jim and Bridget.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you explain the basics of the Higher Education Act of
1965? Who initiated it?
</P>
<P>
   A: The act was sponsored by Rep. Edith Green, a Democrat from
Oregon, It embodied numerous requests of President Lyndon Johnson
and was enacted with broad bipartisan support in Congress. It was
passed Oct. 20, 1965, by a 313-63 House vote and Senate voice vote.
</P>
<P>
   Revolutionary in several aspects, particularly in its student
aid provisions, the act initially was an eight-part, $840 million
bill. With it, Congress approved federal scholarships for
undergraduate students for the first time in U.S. history. Another
new aid program under the act was insurance on loans, with federal
subsidies on interest payments. Also included were new programs of
graduate study for public school teachers, prospective teachers and
other school personnel, including social workers and guidance
specialists.
</P>
<P>
   Other sections of the act authorized funds for community service
programs focusing on urban problems, to be conducted by colleges
and universities; grants to improve college libraries and train
librarians; a program to raise the academic quality of developing
institutions; and equipment grants to improve classroom instruction
in the sciences, humanities, art and education.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
