<SLUG> BC-BBA-CAMERAS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS WILL BE NO GAME OF CANDID CAMERA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ The Red Sox won't need to arm their
counterintelligence forces with infrared glasses and drop them into
Jacobs Field by parachute in the middle of the night. Espionage and
intrigue will not be factors in their Division Series against the
Indians. The notorious I Spy camera in center field will remain
covered in white canvas, as it has been for the past two weeks, per
request of the American League at the behest of the Sox.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Cleveland manager Mike Hargrove has another suggestion
for solving the case once and for all and preventing further
accusations of high treason: ``I'd just as soon get rid of the
s.o.b.''
</P>
<P>
   He was referring to the camera, which he considers a nuisance,
not to the Boston personnel who during their last visit, Sept.
12-15, accused the Indians of employing it to pick up the opposing
catcher's signals, beaming the video to the home dugout, then
having the information on the upcoming pitch relayed to the batter
by that most sophisticated of clandestine weaponry _ a human
whistle. Hargrove probably considers the Boston whistleblowers
nuisances, too, but he's too busy laughing off the entire incident
as pure paranoia.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they thought we were actually doing it,'' he said, ``I
would hope they'd think we're smarter than to pass it on through
whistles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm telling you, we've never stolen anything, and one thing
people will say about me is that I won't lie. Given a choice
between lying and not saying anything, I'll go with `no comment.'
''
</P>
<P>
   That's what Indians general manager John Hart had for his Red
Sox counterpart, Dan Duquette, when he was advised of the
allegations. ``I didn't bother to call Dan,'' said Hart, ``because
the whole thing was so ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   But the two GMs are good friends, and when their families get
together this winter for their annual ski vacation at Attitash or
Duquette's new retreat in Maine, Hart will have a question for his
host: ``How did we do it?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Just consider the logistics,'' said Hart. ``First of all, look
in our dugout. We have a camera that shows the batter's area, same
as they have in the visitors' dugout. No hidden cameras. No hidden
mikes. Otherwise, the picture we get is the same one everyone else
in the park gets (on a center-field video screen) _ the network
feed.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if the Indians had access to the precious view from center,
Hart wondered, what would they do with it?
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, let's say I'm in the dugout runway getting the signal,''
said the GM. ``Then I have to relay it to a guy at the top of the
steps. Then he has to relay it to the guy in the on-deck circle.
Then he has to relay it to the batter. In a matter of
microseconds.''
</P>
<P>
   That's assuming they could find any conspirators to begin with.
Such good scouts are the Indians that according to one club source,
they have refused requests to relay pitch signals from second base
to the batter, which is considered unethical but is still practiced
by some players.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what, the Red Sox will be happy. The Indians are
setting their visitors' minds at rest, even though it's obvious
they believe the Sox are just whistling ``Dixie.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
