<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 11:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8086 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS07-TAKE     10-06 1707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS07-TAKE2-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I understand that a U.S. helicopter went down in Colombia
recently with five American soldiers aboard, but I haven't seen
much about it. Do you have any details?
</P>
<P>
   A: As reported by many news outlets, it was a U.S. Army
DeHavilland RC-7 reconnaissance plane that crashed July 23 while
flying on an anti-drug mission in a rebel-occupied area of southern
Colombia near the Ecuador border. Five U.S. soldiers _ including a
woman pilot _ and two Colombian air force officers were killed when
the aircraft hit a 9,000-foot peak while circling above a major
drug-producing area.
</P>
<P>
   The American soldiers, who were based at Fort Bliss, at El Paso,
Texas, were said to be the first U.S. military personnel killed
while fighting illegal drugs in Colombia. Since 1997, three
American pilots flying drug-interdiction missions for a private
U.S. military contractor also have been killed, according to a
report in Newsweek.
</P>
<P>
   As Newsweek also reported, while American officials sought to
downplay the RC-7 mission as a routine anti-narcotics patrol, the
aircraft was packed with sophisticated intelligence equipment that
would be useful in tracking guerrilla movements. ``This had to do
with surveillance,'' the magazine quoted a source familiar with the
flight's mission as saying. ``We're not supposed to be monitoring
guerrillas, but that's what they were doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: I used to enjoy watching Spencer Christian, the weatherman on
``Good Morning America,'' but he's no longer there. Where is he
now, and how can fans write to him?
</P>
<P>
   A: As previously reported, he parted ways with ABC on Jan. 1
after his contract was not renewed. The jovial, wisecracking
Christian now works at KGO-TV in San Francisco. Write to him in
care of the station, 900 Front St., San Francisco, CA 94111.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What does the K stand for in Y2K?
</P>
<P>
   A: This question comes up often. It represents kilo (thousand),
as in kilometer (1,000 meters) or kilogram (1,000 grams). So in
Y2K, Y is Year and 2K is two thousand (designating, obviously, the
year 2000).
</P>
<P>
   Q: I read that President Jimmy Carter awarded the nation's
highest civilian medal to Roger Baldwin, founder of the American
Civil Liberties Union. The letter further stated that Baldwin was a
member of the Communist Party. Can you verify if any of this is
true?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Carter Presidential Center in Atlanta confirmed that on
Jan. 16, 1981, Carter awarded the Presidential Medal of Freedom to
Baldwin, who founded the ACLU in 1920. Baldwin, who was born in
1884, died on Aug. 26, 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Some early critics indeed did accuse the ACLU of defending only
Communists, but the organization responded by pointing out that for
the same reason it defended them, it also defended Nazis and
members of the Ku Klux Klan. It explained that it defended not
their doctrines, but their right to make them known as guaranteed
by the Bill of Rights. Current Biography (1940), in its section on
Baldwin, quoted this as the ACLU's statement of purpose: ``We stand
on general principle that all matters of public concern should be
freely discussed without interference.''
</P>
<P>
   So far as Baldwin personally being a member of the Communist
Party, there's no evidence, although he was known to be ``extremely
active'' in the American left in the 1920s and '30s, as The New
York Times reported at his death. The Times obituary went on to
say: ``A member of no party, he was nonetheless amenable to helping
the Communists, Socialists and Leftists. By 1940, however, he had
experienced a change of heart about the Communists . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Q: I recently took part in a Catholic wedding. The priest told
me I could not receive Communion during the mass because I am not
Catholic, although I take Communion at my own church. Can you
explain?
</P>
<P>
   A: The book ``Believers and Beliefs,'' subtitled ``A Practical
Guide to Religious Etiquette for Business and Social Occasions,''
by Atlanta Journal-Constitution religion writer Gayle Colquitt
White, explains: ``The Catholic church restricts consumption of the
elements of the eucharist to those who are considered in a state of
grace, having confessed any sins and living within the law of the
church. This means only baptized Catholics and members of Eastern
Orthodox churches who have met certain conditions are supposed to
partake. . . . Non-Catholics should sit quietly in their pews, or
if they wish to be blessed by the priest, move forward with arms
crossed across the chest.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's the difference between an earthquake and an
aftershock? And can an aftershock be stronger than the original
earthquake?
</P>
<P>
   A: The difference is in degree. Let's first define what an
earthquake is: a shaking of the ground caused by the sudden
breaking and shifting of large sections of the Earth's rocky outer
shell. Aftershocks are ``smaller earthquakes following the largest
one in a series, concentrated in a restricted crustal volume,'' as
defined by the U.S. Geological Survey.
</P>
<P>
   So no, by definition an aftershock cannot be stronger than the
original quake. But the damage, coming on top of what the first one
has done, can be quite severe. And frequently more than one
aftershock occurs, further increasing the devastation.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm interested in Bruce Tinsley, creator of the Mallard
Fillmore political cartoons. What can you tell us about him?
</P>
<P>
   A: Born in Louisville, Ky., Tinsley created the Mallard Fillmore
duck in July 1990 as a logo for an entertainment section in The
Daily Progress in Charlottesville, Va. He was an editorial
cartoonist and graphic artist there.
</P>
<P>
   Tinsley said he first drew a big, blue hippo for the logo, but
was warned that overweight people might be offended. He next
submitted a caricature of an artiste with a big nose, like the late
comedian Jimmy Durante had, but that didn't fly, either. He finally
settled on a duck named closely after Millard Fillmore (1800-74),
the Whig who was 13th president of the United States. ``The duck
won by default,'' Tinsley said. ``It didn't offend anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mallard Fillmore comic strip first appeared weekly in The
Washington Times in September 1991, and has been syndicated
nationally ever since.
</P>
<P>
   The strip has been called the conservative answer to Doonesbury,
created by Garry Trudeau. Tinsley says the cartoon's basic
political message is that the media are overloaded with liberals
who impart a liberal slant to news coverage, and that big
government is a threat to individual liberty. That viewpoint, he
admits, reflects his own beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Former Vice President Dan Quayle has ended his bid for the
Republican presidential nomination. An article said he had raised
about $4 million. Does he have to return it to contributors, or
does he keep it?
</P>
<P>
   A: Like all presidential and congressional candidates, he cannot
convert the money for his own personal use, said Pete Sepp of the
National Taxpayers Union. Before 1993, it would have been possible
to do so, but the law was changed in that year to make the practice
illegal.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't mean Quayle or any other candidate must refund
the money to contributors, Sepp added. They can do so if they wish,
or they can donate it to another political party organization, or
conceivably they could donate it to a charity. A number of members
of Congress made such charitable donations after the law was
changed in 1993, Sepp said.
</P>
<P>
   Q: With the Reform Party so much in the news, is it true that
Jesse Ventura was elected governor of Minnesota with less than 50
percent of the vote?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. Ventura, the first Reform Party candidate to be elected
to statewide office, captured 37 percent of more than 2 million
ballots cast. Republican Norm Coleman, the mayor of St. Paul,
received 34 percent of the vote. State Attorney General Hubert H.
Humphrey 3rd, the Democratic-Farmer-Labor Party nominee, garnered
28 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's the status of Ted Turner's $1 billion gift to the
United Nations? How has the money been distributed so far, if any
has?
</P>
<P>
   A: The United Nations Foundation has awarded more than $108
million, according to foundation spokesman David Harwood. Of that,
24 percent ($26.4 million) was designated for children's health, 25
percent ($27 million) for the environment, 35 percent ($37.7
million) for women and population, and 16 percent ($17.8 million)
for ``select U.N. causes.'' An emergency $1 million grant also was
made in April to support relief efforts in the Kosovo region.
</P>
<P>
   The television mogul's $1 billion gift is in the form of
Time-Warner stock, capped at 18 million shares, to be funded in 10
annual installments to the United Nations Foundation and other
charities estabished to support U.N. causes.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The movie ``Double Jeopardy'' is based on the concept that a
person can't be found guilty of the same crime more than once. Is
there really such a term in legal practice?
</P>
<P>
   A: There is such a thing. As defined by Black's Law Dictionary,
double jeopardy is a Fifth Amendment guarantee, enforceable against
states through the 14th Amendment, protecting against a second
prosecution for the same offense after acquittal or conviction, and
against multiple punishments for the same offense.
</P>
<P>
   But the movie's basic premise is different in a significant way.
As the story unfolds, Nick Parsons, the handsome, successful
husband (played by Bruce Greenwood) is missing from a sailboat.
Just as the Coast Guard arrives, his wife, Libby (Ashley Judd)
picks up a bloody knife. She's swiftly convicted of murder. But he
wasn't actually killed; his apparent death was faked so he could
collect insurance money.
</P>
<P>
   The faulty premise is that filmgoers are told that someone
falsely convicted of murder can get away with actually killing the
same person, since the constitutional protection against double
jeopardy prohibits being tried twice for the same crime. Of course,
the real murder in this particular scenario would be a wholly
separate felony, committed at a different time and place, same
victim or not.
</P>
<P>
   But that's Hollywood, and it hasn't kept ``Double Jeopardy''
from becoming a hit.
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
