   FOOD-APPLES _ Hilda Mobley was a woman on a mission. Striding
purposefully into Hidden Valley Fruit Farms on Ohio 48 in Warren
County late on a hot September afternoon, Mobley knew what she
wanted _ Gala apples _ and she would accept no substitutes. Never
mind that Hidden Valley has no less than 52 varieties of apples. As
fierce as Mobley's allegiance is to Galas, other customers are
equally as enthusiastic and loyal to their varieties, be they
Melrose, Fuji, Cortland, Braeburn, Granny Smith or Golden
Delicious. Still, subtle taste shifts do occur, nudged along by the
occasional revolution. (Dayton Daily News). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   APPLES-SIDE _ The late-summer drought hit some orchards hard,
local growers say, reducing the size of the apple crop in two ways:
smaller apples, and fewer apples per tree. But those orchards that
enjoyed a refreshing bath at a few opportune times when scattered
showers danced through the Miami Valley, or which had access to
water through irrigation, enjoyed a banner year. One thing is
certain: apples will be sweeter this year. (Dayton Daily News). 10
</P>
