<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991006.0085 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 11:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8092 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-SHAUGHNESS     10-06 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOPE SPRINGS ETERNAL IN THE FALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's all around you. At the newsstand, the diner, the office
copier. Folks stand around, smell the autumn air, and offer . . .
</P>
<P>
   (itals)I know I said this last time, but I'm really beginning to
think this might be the year.(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   If you've just logged on to www.redsox.com, it's happening
again, ladies and gentlemen. Otherwise rational people suddenly
think the Sox are going to win the World Series for the first time
since 1918.
</P>
<P>
   In this there is energy, innocence, and a disregard for the
past. It's the old ``people forget pain'' syndrome. It is said that
if women could recreate childbirth, they'd never have more babies.
Same for marathon runners and Red Sox fans. If you could remember
how it felt last time, you wouldn't do it again, but you can't
really remember the pain, so you go back and get your hopes up for
the Red Sox. Again.
</P>
<P>
   My neighbor said he had a dream that the Sox would win. Another
friend, sounding like an alcoholic who thinks he can handle just
two glasses of wine with dinner, said he's convinced Pedro Martinez
is going to make all the difference. And Tuesday's office mail
included ``Apocalypse and Baseball,'' a prophetic poem outlining
how the Red Sox will be champs. Any day now I'm expecting Joe
Mooney's ``Leaves On Grass'' and ``A Week on the Concord and
Merrimack Rivers with Joe Castiglione.''
</P>
<P>
   I love these people. Citizens of Red Sox Nation should have
``kick me'' signs on their backs. They are the jilted lovers who
keep going back, no matter how many times they replay the tape of
Bill Buckner, no matter how many times they listen to ``Won't Get
Fooled Again.''
</P>
<P>
   Whenever the Red Sox are playing in October, there is irrational
hope. Like annual losers on Wall Street, Red Sox fans see the
upcoming playoffs and think, (itals)This time it's
different.(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   This is what is best about New England _ the continuousness, the
connection to the past. Nothing ever changes. For some of us,
there's weird comfort in that.
</P>
<P>
   And that is why the Red Sox, more than any trendy sports team of
any decade (Bruins in the 70s, Celtics in the 80s, Patriots now)
are the only sports institution that truly matters around here.
They can be hideous, but they never go out of style and their
storyline is forever.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox are in Cleveland Wednesday night for Game 1 of a
best-of-five with the Tribe. Boston has the best pitcher in
baseball (Pedro), plus American League batting champ Nomar
Garciaparra and a gritty band of overachievers. The Sox have been
astonishingly resilient, and managed to improve over last season
despite the subtraction of Mo Vaughn and injury to closer Tom
Gordon. In Jimy Williams they have a manager who got more out of
less than any man in baseball in 1999. And they have a raft of
tough, veteran ex-National League pitchers who know how to win.
</P>
<P>
   They can beat Cleveland, but only if Pedro wins. But could they
win a second series, against the winner of Yankees-Rangers, and
then a World Series against the survivor of the
Mets-Braves-Diamondbacks-Astros bakeoff?
</P>
<P>
   Highly unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   But it's possible. The 1999 Red Sox are certainly as good as the
1988 Dodgers who beat the A's or the 1990 Reds who swept Oakland.
The best team does not always win a postseason series and a stopper
of Pedro's magnitude can hide many weaknesses.
</P>
<P>
   But know that the 1999 Sox are long shots, just as they were in
'86, '88, '90, '95, and last autumn. If you think this is the year,
try to remember that you probably felt the same for the Morgan
Magic Sox of 1988, or the Kevin Kennedy Sox of 1995.
</P>
<P>
   It's nice that the Red Sox have made so many playoff appearances
in recent years and the Sox like to brag that this is their first
back-to-back postseason parlay since 1915-16, but some perspective
is in order. When the Sox were winning back-to-back championships
eight decades ago, they were finishing first in an eight-team
league. In those days, only two of 16 big league teams went to the
playoffs. Now we've got eight of 30 going to the postseason. The
'96 Sox owned only the fourth-best record in the American League,
which would not have gotten them anywhere in the days when second
wasn't good enough for Ted Williams and Co.
</P>
<P>
   October has been cruel to Boston baseball fans. The Sox lug a
monstrous postseason slump into The Jake. Starting with the Buckner
grounder in '86, your Red Sox have lost a startling 16 of their
last 17 postseason games, a record that is unlikely to be
duplicated.
</P>
<P>
   But if Pedro continues to dominate and Bret Saberhagen is on his
game, and Ramon Martinez reverts to his old form, and they get some
timely hits, and the bullpen does the job, and the Tribe slumps,
and Clemens chokes, and Jupiter aligns with Mars . . .
</P>
<P>
   (itals)This could be the year.(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-99 1124EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991006.0086 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 11:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8093 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-CLEVELAND-COLON-B     10-06 0441
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-CLEVELAND-COLON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLON HAS BEEN A MODEL FOIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Bartolo Colon idolizes his fellow Dominican native,
Pedro Martinez. But the homage is getting ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night in the opener of the best-of-five Division
Series, the Indians righthander will oppose the Red Sox' Cy Young
cinch for the fifth time. In their first four meetings, Colon has
pitched well. Martinez has pitched better _ no surprise, since
virtually every one of the Boston righthander's rivals can offer a
similar lament.
</P>
<P>
   Colon is 0-2 with a 2.57 ERA when he's opposed Martinez, who
answers with a record of 3-0 and a 1.64 ERA in those encounters.
</P>
<P>
   Colon, who went 18-5 this season, realizes that this would be a
great time to alter that trend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very happy that I got this opportunity,'' he said Tuesday
through his interpreter, catcher Sandy Alomar, ``and I will do the
best I can to come out on top.''
</P>
<P>
   To do that, he'll have to stop bowing toward Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the All-Star Game, I had the opportunity to talk to him,''
said Colon, who will be followed to the mound by Charles Nagy in
Game 2 Thursday. ``Whenever we get together for a game or before
the game, whenever we see each other, we have conversations about
pitching. He's a great person. He can help me a lot with my
pitching and with life, and he's a good person to follow.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Colon looks up to me and respects me a lot,'' said the humble
role model. ``Even though he is not on my team, I try to teach him
the right things and tell him how to do it because so far, he's
been good to me. So I would like him to learn the same way, and he
seems to be doing it because he makes it tough for me every time I
face him.''
</P>
<P>
   Indians manager Mike Hargrove hopes Colon can make it a tad
tougher on Martinez this time. While there is no question that
Martinez is the ace of the Red Sox, Colon, 24, is at best a
reasonable facsimile for Cleveland. During the first half of the
season, he was 7-3, but his ERA was an unsightly 5.35. In the
second half, he revved up to 11-2, 2.60.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bartolo has been awfully good for us the second half of the
year,'' said Hargrove. ``He's been very consistent with what he has
thrown and has kept us in the games he started. So right now
Bartolo is as close as we come to a No. 1. I can't sit here today
and tell you he is a No. 1 because I think that has to be
established and Bartolo is in the process of doing that. But it's
still work unfinished.''
</P>
<P>
   Hargrove would settle for a step forward.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-99 1125EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
