<HEADER>
A8095 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-LIVE-FROM-NYSE-BARTIR     10-06 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIVE-FROM-NYSE-BARTIROMO-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARIA BARTIROMO: THE MONEY HONEY  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from W magazine,
contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT
at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!----------------------
 &HT;    ONE COLOR SLIDE is available FREE OF CHARGE to purchasers of
this article. The art can be sent ELECTRONICALLY by e-mail. Please
specify that you want the art when you order the article.
 &HT;    ----------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``l'' lifestyle news and ``f'' business news.)  
 &HT;    
 By SHARON EDELSON 
 c.1999 Fairchild Publications   
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Pity Maria Bartiromo, the comely CNBC business anchor who gets
more attention for her looks than her reporting skills. She's been
dubbed ``The Money Honey'' by the New York Post and hit on by
comedian Richard Lewis as he called into a show she was hosting.
</P>
<P>
   There's even The Maria Bartiromo Market Hairdex, a Web site
devoted to monitoring the correlation between Bartiromo's cowlicks
and stock trends.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't bother me,'' Bartiromo says. ``I know it's all in
good fun. Viewers know I'm about rapid-fire reports from the New
York Stock Exchange floor.''
</P>
<P>
   Bartiromo, 31, is clearly not just another pretty talking head.
She studied economics at New York University and can dilate at
length on the economic factors driving the current buff market. And
when it comes to breaking news, Bartiromo can be as aggressive as
any arbitrager.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell my viewers what all the major trading floors are doing
in their morning meetings,'' she says. ``My trick is to get the
information a lot earlier than most reporters.''
</P>
<P>
   Investment banks such as Merrill Lynch and Donaldson Lufkin &AMP;
Jenrette use their morning meetings to decide what stocks to
recommend to their clients, which in some cases include large
institutional investors, so word of their picks can really get a
stock moving.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get calls from the trading desks saying, `Maria, you're
killing me,''' she says. ``It's a little bit of a balance to
walk.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She thinks so fast,'' says discount brokerage queen Muriel
Siebert. ``That's a real talent. She's become a very powerful force
because she's got her name in front of breaking news items all the
time. This thing has really turned her into a star.''
</P>
<P>
   Bartiromo, who was the first person to broadcast live from the
floor of the New York Stock Exchange, is arguably the daytime face
of CNBC.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so refreshing to see a beautiful girl doing finance,''
says Diane Von Furstenberg. ``When I was on her show, she was so
nice and gracious. I think she has a big career ahead of her.''
</P>
<P>
   Speculation about Bartiromo's next move heated up in mid-June
amid rumors that she was being considered to replace Lou Dobbs, the
popular anchor of CNN's ``Moneyline News Hour.''
</P>
<P>
   Bartiromo ultimately signed a new contract with CNBC, but
sources say the big three broadcast networks are keeping a close
eye on her.
</P>
<P>
   While the contract relieves Bartiromo of anchoring duties on
CNBC's flagship ``Business Center,'' the new deal gives her a solo
anchoring slot on ``Street Signs'' from 2 p.m. to 3 p.m., as well
as a new evening program, which she says will be filmed live at ``a
major financial institution, probably the New York Stock
Exchange.''
</P>
<P>
   Think of the new show as Wall Street Week for the coffee
generation, says Bartiromo's boss, CNBC business news chief Bruno
Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're taking on Louis Rukeyser,'' Bartiromo says of the PBS
host. ``I'm targeting his audience. We're going to interview all
the top strategists and ceo's and try to make it fresher than
what's out there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The ceo's are incredibly exciting. I've been fortunate to hear
firsthand how the semiconductor business is doing from Intel
chairman Andy Grove. My job is sort of an instant entree into the
executive suite.''
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes to investing her own portfolio, Bartiromo
claims she hasn't traded on her access to captains of industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't invest in any company listed on the New York Stock
Exchange,'' she says. ``People say I'm crazy, but I find it to be a
bit of a gray area. I skirt the issue by doing longterm mutual
funds as a way to participate in the bull market and still do the
right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   In June, Bartiromo married Individual Investor Group's Jonathan
Steinberg, the 34-year-old son of financier Saul Steinberg, in
front of 250 guests , including Barbara Walters and Martha Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   ``We met through friends,'' Bartiromo says of her husband. ``We
are both driven and passionate about the financial world. My
mother-in-law, Gayfryd Steinberg,'' she adds, ``warned me not to
talk about my personal life.''
</P>
<P>
   Bartiromo, however, is always happy to talk finance.
</P>
<P>
   ``People should be aware of what their 401k is investing in,''
she says. ``The investor is armed with so much information, it's
crazy not to know.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no reason to believe this stuff is over your head,''
she adds. ``A woman, particularly a woman, needs to know. It's not
brain surgery.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Sharon Edelson is a reporter for Fairchild Publications.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   -0-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-99 1127EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991006.0089 </DOCNO>
