<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-INDIANS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIANS' STATS HARD TO BELIEVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ The numbers on the stat sheet appear to be part of
someone's creative writing project. They are not really the
Cleveland Indians, they are Jacobs Field's Men of Fiction.
</P>
<P>
   They were all here Tuesday, preparing for Wednesday's Division
Series opener against the Red Sox. You saw them. You talked to
them. You shook their hands. You remained skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   Is this team real?
</P>
<P>
   They have a young player named Richie Sexson. He has 31 home
runs and 116 RBIs. He will be on the bench when the Red Sox play
these fictional Indians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, if you're not able to play him every day,'' manager
Mike Hargrove said of Sexson, ``the alternative is pretty doggone
good.'' He used the word alternative in a singular context. He
should have said alternatives. He is using both David Justice and
Harold Baines rather than Sexson right now.
</P>
<P>
   We are talking about a team that is the seventh in history to
score more than 1,000 runs. There are five players who have scored
more than 100 runs and five who have driven in 100-plus. Manny
Ramirez drove in 165 runs and people here still debate if he is the
team MVP. A couple of seasons ago, the storybook Indians traded
Sean Casey to the Reds and Casey became that team's best hitter.
Last offseason, they traded Brian Giles to the Pirates for a
lefthanded reliever named Ricky Rincon. Giles hit 39 home runs,
Rincon was a regular-season bust. There aren't many complaints
about the deal.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers are mesmerizing. The more you look the more you
begin to believe the Indians can't be stopped. But if you are
rooting against them, one thing is on your side _ history.
</P>
<P>
   You can leave Jacobs Field, head south, and, about 230 miles
later, you will find yourself in Cincinnati at the site where
another powerful offense was easily thwarted. The 1990 Reds crushed
the A's of Mark McGwire, Rickey Henderson, and Jose Canseco in the
World Series. At the time, Reds outfielder Eric Davis was told the
nation did not expect the Reds _ who won 91 regular-season games _
to disarm one of the most powerful offenses of all time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nation doesn't concern me,'' Davis said at the time. ``The
nation ain't in this clubhouse.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years earlier, the A's were silenced by the Dodgers and Orel
Hershiser in five games. McGwire and Canseco were a combined 2 for
36. And in '95, the Indians went into the playoffs with the
American League's best offense in 45 years. They went on to bat
.179 in the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was four years ago,'' Indians shortstop Omar Vizquel said
Tuesday. ``That was a long time ago.'' It was before Vizquel was a
.333 hitter; before Ramirez was a cleanup hitter; before Roberto
Alomar stood next to Vizquel on defense; and before guys with 116
RBIs were relegated to the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was on the '90 A's,'' Harold Baines said, ``but this is the
best offense I've ever been a part of.''
</P>
<P>
   But if the playoffs have proven one thing, it is that terrific
defensive teams will almost always turn flamboyant offenses into
whispering ones. After the Indians were beaten by the Braves in the
'95 World Series, Tom Glavine said that he threw his changeup
constantly in the clinching Game 6 because the Indians didn't know
how to adjust.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is a frightening Indians stat from this season.
Forget about the fact that they have never beaten Pedro Martinez.
Against Tom Gordon, John Wasdin, Rod Beck, Derek Lowe, and Rheal
Cormier, the Indians are a combined 4 for 71. They are 1 for 30
against Lowe. They are 1 for 11 against Beck. Cormier has puzzled
them into a 1-for-19 funk.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like we have two or three guys having great years,''
Vizquel countered, explaining why this lineup is nearly
slump-proof. ``We have nine guys having great years.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to discredit the strength of the Indians, but there may be a
good explanation for that. The collective AL earned run average is
4.86 (the NL is 4.56). The team plays in the brutal Central
Division, which it won for the fifth consecutive season. In '95,
the Indians won the division by 30 games. This season, the margin
was 21 1/2. No team in the Central had its starters finish with an
ERA less than 5; the Indians led the division at 5.08.
</P>
<P>
   Hargrove and Jimy Williams were asked, constantly, what the
difference is between these teams now and a year ago. They talked
about maturity, focus, and desire. But the biggest differences are
Roberto Alomar for the Indians and superior pitching for the Sox.
Boston led the league in starters' ERA (4.04) and was second in
relief pitching (3.93; the Yankees were first).
</P>
<P>
   Are the Indians, with all their offensive opulence, real? Or
will they, like other offensive teams, be haunted by history? It is
a fact that no AL team since 1950 had scored 1,000 or more runs. It
is also a fact that that team, the Red Sox, finished third and won
nothing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-99 1128EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
