<DOCNO> NYT19991006.0097 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 11:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8105 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-DUQUETTE-B     10-06 1842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-DUQUETTE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUQUETTE PLAYED CARDS RIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ They all got it wrong. Mo Vaughn, Roger Clemens, Jose
Canseco. The angry voices on talk radio and the sarcastic wiseguys
in the newspapers. Jealous peers and exasperated agents. The gamut
of those who aimed their slings and arrows at the general manager
of the Boston Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   The issue, Dan Duquette said, has never been Dan Duquette.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, the story for the fans of New England is the Red Sox
team,'' he says. ``That's what they're interested in. They're
interested in Dan Duquette to the extent he gives them a good ball
club.''
</P>
<P>
   It is the morning after the Red Sox clinched their second
consecutive trip to the playoffs, and in his Chicago hotel suite,
Duquette is having a worse hair day than usual, the left side of
his head at war with the right.
</P>
<P>
   Not that he cares. Duquette tells Kevin Shea, the team's
publicist, that try as he might, he hasn't been able to wash out
the beer and champagne he had been doused with the night before
from a cadre of players who pretended they were storming past him
for Jimy Williams, only to double back to give him a celebratory
soaking.
</P>
<P>
   Duquette laughs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an interesting phenomenon,'' he says. ``If we have a good
team, I'm well-received in the community. If the team isn't so
good, then I'm not as warmly received.''
</P>
<P>
   He laughs again, this time without mirth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more about the Red Sox'' _ he bites off those words for
emphasis _ ``and the organization. We're just passing through. We
have a great opportunity to be a part of the Red Sox organization,
to be a part of the leadership, but at the end of the day it's more
about the team than it is about Dan Duquette.
</P>
<P>
   ``To the extent I can help these fans fulfill their lifelong
goals and dreams, they're interested in what I do. If I make good
choices, they'll support the team, they'll support me. They may not
like my choices, but if they're effective, they'll support the
team. For the fans of New England, it's more about the team than it
is about the general manager.''
</P>
<P>
   Duquette may never inspire love, though he was happy to report
that in the newsletter of his alma mater, Amherst College, he was
recently listed as the Lord Jeffs' ``Athlete of the Week.'' The Red
Sox had just swept the Yankees in New York, the Amherst teams had
not yet begun their seasons, and his old coaches back in Amherst
thought they'd give Duquette an honor he'd never gotten while he
was an athlete there. It delighted him no end.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Dan Duquette can have a laugh at his own expense.
</P>
<P>
   But when the Sox clinched last Wednesday night in Comiskey Park,
he sat alone in the press box. There was no one to give him an
embrace and, until he made his way down to the clubhouse, only
reporters to shake his hand. Ask him whom he called that night to
share the moment, and he gives you a quizzical look. He didn't call
anyone, he says.
</P>
<P>
   But with the Red Sox advancing to the playoffs for the third
time in five full seasons under his watch, Duquette has become less
a lightning rod of controversy than a beacon of hope for fans who
sense that the team is in the right hands.
</P>
<P>
   In a culture driven by personality, Duquette, who has been
painted with a brush as prickly as his stubborn hair _ aloof, cold,
passionless _ offers an alternative.
</P>
<P>
   ``My style is very results-oriented,'' he says. ``When you have
this much at stake, day in and day out, things aren't always going
to go the way individual people would like them to go. You try to
balance the interests of the organization. At the end of the day, I
represent the interests of the organization. I try to do that in a
committed way, and a fair way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fair to the players and to the fans. The fans deserve a good
return for what they invest in the ball club, economically and
emotionally.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The season is ripe for gloating, of course. No Sox team had been
to the playoffs in consecutive seasons in 83 years, and this after
a winter in which Duquette was barbecued for letting Vaughn leave
as a free agent (even CEO John Harrington said recently he cringed
at the beating Duquette took) and for signing Jose Offerman to what
his critics felt was an exorbitant contract (four years, $26
million).
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn encountered only disaster in Disneyland. He fell down the
dugout steps in his first game for the Angels, and the team never
recovered, ultimately dissolving into an orgy of finger-pointing
and back stabbing that resulted in the resignations of manager
Terry Collins and, one month later, general manager Bill Bavasi.
</P>
<P>
   Offerman, meanwhile, went 4 for 4 in his first game for the Sox,
then endured a midseason slump and brief benching to become the
dependable leadoff man Boston lacked last season, while playing an
acceptable second base.
</P>
<P>
   Has it occurred to people, Duquette was asked, that he just
might know what he's doing?
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no one player bigger than the team,'' he says. ``If
you have a team of players in a winning culture, you should be able
to put a good team on the field year in and year out. We've been
able to show effectively we can put a good team on the field year
in and year out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's face it. What it came down to (with Vaughn) was money.
The organization was willing to pay Mo Vaughn a handsome salary but
we weren't willing to pay the premium he received to play in
California. And the reason we weren't willing to pay that premium
is if you put all that money in a hitter, you don't have a lot of
leeway to staff the rest of your ball club, especially your
pitching staff.''
</P>
<P>
   There was money, then, to risk on Ramon Martinez, who has made a
remarkable recovery from shoulder surgery. Money for Mark Portugal,
the veteran who began the season in the starting rotation before
his unceremonious release in the final days. Money to gamble on Rod
Beck, who was coming off major elbow surgery but helped fill the
void left by the injury to Tom Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a much better position financially to contend,''
Duquette says, ``without giving $80 million to a first baseman.''
</P>
<P>
   Surely, then, there was vindication in the play of Offerman.
</P>
<P>
   ``It validated the deal,'' Duquette says. ``His performance
validated our financial commitment to him. I'll never understand
that one (the criticism).
</P>
<P>
   ``Jimy Williams wasn't well-received when he came to town,
either. I hope our fans aren't using initial receptions as a
measuring stick to what type of contribution these people can make
to our ball club.''
</P>
<P>
   A year ago last winter, Duquette was ripped for inflating the
pitching market by signing Pedro Martinez to a six-year, $75
million deal. Duquette made little effort to contain his sarcasm on
that subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got banged pretty good by the other teams who wanted to sign
him for their teams,'' he says. ``That's where I got criticism _
the Yankees and Cleveland. You don't think they'd like to have him
on their teams now? They wanted to have him on their teams then. Do
you think they'd accept his contract?
</P>
<P>
   ``I really didn't know what the market was, but I knew how good
this pitcher was. I knew how unique his talents and skills are. I
knew that he was driven and dependable. The only thing I didn't
know about him was if he knew how to be a star, and he does.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's matured. He's intelligent. He likes to be on stage when
people are watching. He relates to fans because of his personality.
He relates to fans because of his size.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's possible that someday Duquette might be recognized for
making the best two trades of the '90s. Twice he traded for
Martinez, once with the Expos, then with the Red Sox. But he also
has proven to have a knack for the late-season pickup with a
pennant race at hand. Last season, he brought back Mike Stanley as
a much-needed righthanded bat, and picked up a lefthander, Greg
Swindell, for the bullpen. This season, he landed a closer in Beck,
a lefthanded starter in Kent Mercker, and righthanded power in
Butch Huskey.
</P>
<P>
   His best late-summer deal came with the Red Sox out of
contention, in 1997, when he unloaded closer Heathcliff Slocumb,
the Human Angioplasty, for Derek Lowe and Jason Varitek, who have
emerged as two of the team's top young stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't quite sure we knew what we had in Lowe and
Varitek,'' Duquette says. ``We knew what we had in Slocumb.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've made some good deals late in the year. The trick to
those deals is to get players who can help you right away without
giving up your star players. So the key is knowing who your star
players are, keeping them out of the equation, eliminating them
from consideration. If other teams won't make a deal, go on to the
next team.''
</P>
<P>
   The success of this season's team did not come as a complete
surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I liked our pitching staff,'' he says. ``I liked our core of
veteran players _ (Troy) O'Leary, (Nomar) Garciaparra, Stanley,
Offerman. Those are good players. I liked the potential of Varitek.
The big question was our offensive production.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fortunately, we got good contributions from Stanley and
(Brian) Daubach, Offerman and O'Leary. (Trot) Nixon and Varitek
developed, and along the way we picked up Huskey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jimy Williams did a great job putting (Tim) Wakefield in the
bullpen when Gordon was hurt. That stabilized the team and allowed
more time for Derek Lowe to come along in his role.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, Duquette said, should be Manager of the Year. That
doesn't mean, however, that he's ready to talk about giving
Williams a long-term deal. The manager, who was given a contract
extension at the end of spring training, is signed through next
season. But Duquette said there has been no talk of another
extension.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's already signed up,'' Duquette says. ``We're happy with
him. He's doing a nice job. We think he should be Manager of the
Year. But (an extension) is an offseason discussion. That's not
even on the radar screen.''
</P>
<P>
   What is on Duquette's radar screen is a World Series
championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be in this job when the Boston Red Sox win a World
Series,'' he says. ``The fans here embrace a winning team with a
passion like no other market. That's what makes it fun to have a
winning team in Boston.''
</P>
<P>
   But to be Red Sox general manager, the dream of a lifetime for
the native of Dalton, doesn't mean he wants it to be a lifetime
job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forever? No,'' he says. ``There are other jobs, other
challenges I'd like to pursue.''
</P>
<P>
   He was typically vague about what those might be: ``Inside the
industry? Maybe. Outside, too.''
</P>
<P>
   How about running for office?
</P>
<P>
   This time when he laughed, he enjoyed it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are just other challenges,'' says the Duke. ``They're
not really pertinent today.''
</P>
<P>
   Those challenges have to await another champagne bath. The one
that comes with winning a World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, we'll do it soon,'' he says. ``We've got a
chance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-99 1130EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991006.0098 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 11:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8108 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-LIFE-IN-AMERICA07-COX     10-06 2635
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIFE-IN-AMERICA07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    In Longview, 24 hands, 107 hours and one HardbodyBy Patrick
Beach
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONGVIEW, Texas _ It's silver. It has a 2.4-liter engine, a
five-speed manual transmission, cloth seats, A/C (for the first
time), AM-FM cassette and, when you throw in delivery fees and
such, a sticker price of $13,246.
</P>
<P>
   It's a new Nissan Frontier 4x2 XE, and recently two dozen people
were assembling at Joe Mallard Nissan here, resolving to hold on to
it longer than anybody else _ however long it takes.
</P>
<P>
   You saw a movie like this once? If you're in or around Austin,
you likely did. S.R. Bindler's documentary, ``Hands on a Hard
Body,'' opened at the Dobie Theater on the Drag about the time the
Earth's crust cooled and has been streaming through the projectors
there ever since. We very much get the film, or so we think. We go
laugh at the rednecks with their East Texas accents so impenetrable
the film could benefit from subtitles, and we watch them fight to
win an inexpensive truck.
</P>
<P>
   Listen. This is not about a truck.
</P>
<P>
   I. Prelude (not the Honda)
</P>
<P>
   The vegetable of the day at the Cotton Patch, in honor of the
contest, is ``extended cabbage.'' The 24 contestants are here,
across the street from the dealership, having had their names drawn
out of 2,000 entries. Now they sit (``now'' being the night before
the contest) and pay attention as the night-before meeting
commences. They include a cop from Houston who competed last year,
the winner of the very first contest, a red-haired 18-year-old who
knows all the words to all the country songs, the mother of a
9-year-old boy with cerebral palsy, the daughter of a past winner,
a snow cone magnate, a schoolteacher and a lanky stranger from
Mobile, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Mallard, the son of the dealership's owner and the guy who
runs the show, goes over the rules: no squatting, leaning or
cupping your hands. A six-minute break every hour, a 15-minute
break every six hours. Drug tests for the three finalists and
another one for the winner and the runner-up. Winner gets a new
truck; runner-up gets a used truck _ except it was stolen from the
lot the night before, so the runner-up will get some truck. Third
place gets a trip. If you're not there by 6:45 a.m. tomorrow,
alternates get drawn. J.D. Drew, who won the contest in the movie
and whose daughter, Melanie Lively, is a contestant, is an
alternate.
</P>
<P>
   Then Mallard, a big, booming, Foghorn Leghorn of a guy working
on at least one Skoal Bandit at all times, tells them they're a
part of something deeply historic and newsworthy. The Houston
paper's here. A crew from the British television show ``Yankee
Panky'' is en route. Mallard widens his eyes and holds two squat
fingers up, preparing to batter home the gravity of the situation:
</P>
<P>
   ``David Letterman's contacted us twice about this,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Calhoun, who won last year's contest in a record-busting
94 hours, offers advice: ``Don't eat nothin' greasy.''
</P>
<P>
   This does not dissuade about two-thirds of the group from
ordering chicken-fried steak. In Longview, if you don't eat nothin'
greasy, you don't eat nothin'.
</P>
<P>
   Every one of them is at the dealership well before the 6:45 a.m.
deadline the next day. Every one of them wears a gray Joe Mallard
Nissan Hands on a Hardbody T-shirt and gloves on their hands to
protect the truck's finish. The last-minute meeting breaks up, and
they dash outside under the portable tent where the prize waits.
</P>
<P>
   A local radio station (one that mostly plays the new kind of
country music, the kind that doesn't sound like country music)
blasts away from its remote truck in the corner of the lot. Travis
Tritt sings and spells ``T-R-O-U-B-L-E.''
</P>
<P>
   Warren ``Hands On'' Hearne, a Texas Alcoholic Beverage
Commission officer originally from Houston, has been acting like
Ali before the ``Thrilla in Manila,'' talking big, making everybody
laugh, pledging he will go the distance, which he predicts will be
105.7 hours. He says he's gonna shut up when the thing starts,
putting the other contestants off balance with his sudden silence
and determined visage.
</P>
<P>
   Hands on. Air horn blast. Tuesday, Sept. 21, 1999, 7 a.m.,
weather unusually cool and windy.
</P>
<P>
   Let the games begin.
</P>
<P>
   Let the chatter begin.
</P>
<P>
   In the crowd, a guy in a black cowboy hat draws attention. It's
Benny Perkins, the charismatic, hyperbole-prone star of ``Hands
On'' who, in the film, compares the contest to combat. He says he
could hardly sleep last night he was so excited, and he's not even
in the contest. He admires the resolve of those who've competed
before and are here again, and he pities those who don't know what
kind of pain and dementia they're about to endure.
</P>
<P>
   ``You slowly lose your mind,'' Perkins says. ``Slowly. You can
feel it.''
</P>
<P>
   J.D. Drew didn't make it past alternate status, but he's taken
the week off work anyway to support daughter Melanie Lively. The
sentimental favorite is Mary Edwards, a dining room hostess whose
son, Casey, has cerebral palsy. She has his picture pinned to her
shirt. She needs the truck to carry the boy's wheelchair to
doctor's appointments in Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   The routine sets in. Hourly breaks, rubdowns, dashes to the
bathroom, Brooks &AMP; Dunn covering John Waite's '80s schmaltz pop hit
``Missing You'' (who green-lighted that?) on the radio about every
eight minutes. Nobody's going anywhere. At the 11-hour break,
Hearne lies prone eating something out of aluminum foil:
</P>
<P>
   ``Ginseng, baby! Straight from Siberia. Our secret weapon.''
</P>
<P>
   It looks a lot like chicken.
</P>
<P>
   The first casualty, 20-year-old Joe Patrick Morris, drops at
4:27 Wednesday morning. He staggers over to a chaise longue, covers
up with a sleeping bag and passes out for five hours, sleeping
through air horns and temperatures that slip below 50. When he
wakes, he pulls a Marlboro out of a hard pack, lights up and
declares he will enter again next year.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Edwards, Casey's mother, is the fourth to give out, lifting
her hand off the truck about 11:25 Wednesday night as the
contestants watched a video of the movie. (They got rid of four
that way last year.)
</P>
<P>
   Jan Maynard _ the dealership's cheerleader and mother hen _
drops big news on the survivors. Letterman's still interested, but
he'd demanded an exclusive, and now Rosie O'Donnell has called. So
Maynard says perhaps it's time for Mr. Letterman to _ how to put
this delicately? _ unburden his colon or let someone else use the
bathroom. The group votes for the latter, and somebody from the
Rosie show is en route. The stakes go higher. The winner will get
the ultimate: a trip to New York for an appearance on Rosie's show
the Monday after the contest.
</P>
<P>
   This is serious. This is huge. This is not about a truck.
</P>
<P>
   II. Friday night lights
</P>
<P>
   The breaks are deadly, especially the 15-minute ones. After
80-some hours, if you're handling a consistent level of pain, it
becomes your companion and you forget ever being without it. Then
you lie down and your body remembers and your mind refuses to again
embrace the pain. Mothers who've competed say it's worse than labor
and childbirth.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the mental side, which is like your own private
freak show. The third dimension gets very arbitrary _ a row of
trucks stretches for miles, your legs seem to be 3 inches long. The
year J.D. Drew won, he spent six hours entertaining a delusion that
a jumbo jet had landed across the street from the dealership and
people were, in the commercial airline parlance, deplaning.
</P>
<P>
   The judges _ there are always two judges _ hover over
contestants about to slip, and sometimes suggest, very gently, that
it's OK, it's time to give in, that they fought nobly and well.
It's uncomfortably similar to watching someone die, and you say the
same things. Contestants collapse, cry and are led away. Then they
always, always come back after a few hours' sleep _ there's an
explicable connection to the event and the people. It is like
combat, and also love, and just as impossible to describe if you
haven't lived it. This is the mistake we have made about ``Hands on
a Hard Body.'' It's not a comedy. It's a drama.
</P>
<P>
   The players in this year's drama have boiled down to four. Brian
Root, the bearded beanpole from Mobile, Ala., who drove to Longview
and spent a week just to enter his name, is hanging tough. It's
been, uh, an experience. ``I've discovered doors to my psyche I
didn't know existed,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't look bad at all, but he's got an unusual level of
support. His brother David does rubdowns, encourages Brian to go on
quick jogs during 15-minute breaks or do jumping jacks on a
trampoline. Then there's this other guy people are calling the
Guru. He's always running to the Albertson's for supplies, which
include red bananas, pine nuts, melons, avocados and papayas. Other
contestants see nothing wrong with bacon and eggs. The health
freaks get plain spaghetti.
</P>
<P>
   Warren Hearne, the funny loud guy, went out under some
controversy at 5:07 a.m. Friday, taking his big package of Depends
undergarments (''NOW! 80% Better Leakage Protection'') with him. He
was going a little crazy, saying a fix was in. He returns to
apologize and root for Cathy Frazier, the flinty woman who won the
very first contest in '92, and who held the record time until last
year. No way is this about a truck for her. She's still got her
other truck. It's about being the first person to win twice.
Others, including Benny Perkins, have tried and failed.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Walker, he of Charlie's Sno-Cones &AMP; Seasonal Tanning, is
closing in on his time last year but looks fuzzy by late afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   A Comanche moon ascends in a bloodshot sky. There are perfectly
good high school football games going on, but this is the biggest
show in town and hundreds are crammed around the tent, pulling for
their favorites, attaching encouraging signs to the rope perimeter.
High school girls sport selections from the
You-Are-Not-Leaving-This-House-Dressed-Like-That collection; boys
wear Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch hats and those gigantic jeans that have
become ubiquitous, breaching even the Pine Curtain.
</P>
<P>
   Random free-associative thought: Charles Lindbergh flies alone
from New York to Paris in 33 hours and wins the world; Chris
Whitlock hangs on to a Nissan for almost 90 hours and wins a trip
to the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   He comes back later, after getting a rehydrating IV drip. They
always come back.
</P>
<P>
   So now there are three _ Brian Root, still hanging tough, very
deliberately changing hands every so often, not talking much,
conserving his energy, munching fruits and nuts on breaks. He cried
for a while, and his limbs seemed to seize up, but he's worked
through it. Word goes around the peanut gallery that Brian's done
things like this before. He's done seven or eight triathlons ``over
the years'' and has a resting pulse rate in the 40s. And there are
oblique references to other contests involving pain, insanity and
endurance, but neither he nor his brother David nor the
fruit-procuring guru _ Paul Rathe by name _ will specify.
</P>
<P>
   Cathy Frazier's hanging in. She stands where she always has, on
the passenger side over the hood, where she can stare down her
opponent _ plainly Brian by now.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangerettes from Kilgore College come to cheer on Charlie
Walker about 10 p.m., doing a variation on the ``Hokey Pokey''
(``You put your right hand on ...,'' you get the idea), and the
infusion of spirit buoys his corpus for a time, but he's teetering.
</P>
<P>
   A light rain begins to fall and, to accommodate the exposed
crowd _ still out in force _ the truck is moved under the overhang
of the dealership building. And this is where Charlie Walker makes
his stand as friends holler at him until they lose their voices.
Facing the truck head on, both hands on the hood, with maybe two
dozen stalwart observers looking on, Charlie Walker falls backward
just short of 4:30 a.m. Saturday _ nine hours to the minute longer
than he went last year.
</P>
<P>
   And it goes on a lot longer. At 7 a.m., Patsy Cline sings ``I
Fall to Pieces'' on the radio, but it's unclear to whom she's
singing. The rain stops, the sun rises, the truck goes back under
the tent, the rain returns, so does the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks,'' says Jan Maynard, surveying the people, equipment
and debris, ``like Woodstock.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody's betting against Cathy or Brian, who stand as they have
from the beginning, directly across from one another _ Cathy
staring down her foe, Brian watching the crowd, sometimes chatting
with a judge or fan or his brother or the Guru, who now totes a
digital timer to monitor the progress of breaks.
</P>
<P>
   They enter 100 hours at 10 a.m. Saturday. In the movie, J.D.
Drew wins in 78.
</P>
<P>
   Cathy Frazier, holding on, not so much wanting to win as wanting
not to lose: ``Them hours don't mean nothin' to me anymore. I just
want to solve it. It's gonna go my way. What do they call it when a
computer goes off? Crashed. I crashed. I didn't even remember what
all these people were doing here. I thought I was dreaming.''
</P>
<P>
   During a break a couple of bikers in black T-shirts and
bandannas approach. One of them gives Cathy a bunch of cut flowers
in a newspaper cone.
</P>
<P>
   Great drama at the 5 p.m. break. Cathy decides to go inside the
bathroom well into the six-minute break. The one-minute warning
horn blares. Everybody thinks, stick a fork in this one, it's done.
But she struggles out, makes it across the lot and puts a hand on
the truck with two seconds to spare. Cheers, applause.
</P>
<P>
   Paul the Guru can't believe the endurance of these two. He says
he's been shot in the neck and buried in a landslide, but nothing
compares to the pain he felt when he did one of these contests for
68 hours. Anybody who does this twice, he says, is insane. The guru
gig is cushier.
</P>
<P>
   Cathy to Brian: ``Do your legs hurt?''
</P>
<P>
   Brian, affecting nonchalance: ``Yeah, a little.''
</P>
<P>
   Cathy, pointing: ``Well, it's gonna get a lot worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary-Chapin Carpenter sings ``I Feel Lucky,'' but Cathy Frazier
soon doesn't look or sound lucky. Actual quote: ``Blah, blah, blah,
blah, blah, blah, blah, blah, blah....''
</P>
<P>
   She sits down for the 6 p.m. break, cries, shakes her head and
does not answer the horn six minutes later.
</P>
<P>
   The winner, after 107 hours and at least that many broadcasts of
``Missing You,'' is Brian Root, the skinny guy from Alabama, who
gets a little choked up. Even big old Jay Mallard gets choked up.
</P>
<P>
   What nobody knows is that Brian, his brother and Paul the Guru
have been at this for years _ they ride in circuit, go all over
looking for such contests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suffice to say this wasn't the first time,'' Paul Rathe says
later. ``The key to winning is management.''
</P>
<P>
   III. Epilogue: The kindness of strangers
</P>
<P>
   Mary Edwards went home and told Casey she didn't win him the
truck to take him to school and the doctor, and she cried and cried
and said, ``Momma tried.''
</P>
<P>
   She'd entered the drawing every day for almost a month to get a
shot. Then she made it and failed.
</P>
<P>
   Later, a stranger found her and handed her an envelope with a
letter inside from a famous movie star _ she won't say who, or
whether it's a male or female, a Texan, or, for instance, Matthew
McConaughey. The famous movie star requested anonymity, and Mary
Edwards is honoring that, not even telling her own mother who it
is. The letter said the famous movie star had heard about her
plight and wanted to buy her a van. And the next day, the famous
movie star called Mary Edwards' unlisted number, just to prove it
was all real.
</P>
<P>
   Casey is lobbying for a ``Blue's Clues'' paint job, but Mary
will take what she can get.
</P>
<P>
   For Mary Edwards, it was about a truck.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-99 1131EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991006.0099 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 11:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8109 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-CLEVELAND-HARGROV     10-06 1247
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-CLEVELAND-HARGROVE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARGROVE KEEPS IT TOGETHER THROUGH TRAGEDY, TRIUMPH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ First they rushed to Tim Crews's house, near where
the hideous dockside accident had occurred. Then they raced to the
hospital, to the room where Crews lay dying. They visited the room
where Bobby Ojeda was clinging to life. They did not need to stop
at the morgue; Steve Olin was already in there, dead.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, they wandered through the central Florida night,
driving and talking, driving and talking, general manager John Hart
and manager Mike Hargrove. Trying to absorb the devastating toll of
the boat crash that had killed two Cleveland Indians pitchers and
seriously injured a third. Trying to determine how they would deal
with the media, how they would console the families, how they would
help their surviving players cope. Trying to figure out how in the
world they would cope themselves.
</P>
<P>
   It was 6:30 or 7 a.m. by the time they arrived back at the
team's Winter Haven spring training headquarters; they weren't sure
of the time, but the sun was up.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed that time got away from them all during that 1993
season, which had been envisioned as the Indians' breakthrough
year. There was numbness instead of purpose; the specter of two
dead teammates was more powerful than the lure of a pennant, and
the Indians matched their record of the previous year, 76-86,
staggering home sixth in the American League East.
</P>
<P>
   It was hardest, perhaps, on Hargrove. It was he who had to try
to persuade the players that each day's game was important in a
locker room haunted by the echoes of sudden, inexplicable death. He
was forced to become a counselor more than a manager, even as he
tried to find a place where his own grief wouldn't hurt so much.
</P>
<P>
   Not until June did he stop Hart on the field one day in batting
practice and tell him, ``You know, I feel like we're just starting
out. I've sort of been drifting up until now.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet somehow he kept the team together.
</P>
<P>
   Hart was amazed at how his manager was able to endure and help
his players do the same ``as far as the meaningful things about the
situation were concerned _ consoling, focusing on what's important,
who we are.''
</P>
<P>
   First baseman Jim Thome remembers, ``He was a father figure, and
we needed that. He was a rock.''
</P>
<P>
   Hargrove, 49, smiles thinly, bittersweetly, at the description
six years later, fresh off his fifth consecutive division title,
primed to step over the Red Sox on the way to his third World
Series, hoping that this powerhouse team will be his first world
champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel like a rock,'' he says. ``I felt like a pebble
at times.''
</P>
<P>
   But he believes that he came out stronger on the other side of
the darkness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a chance to find out who Mike Hargrove is,'' he says.
``We all have an image of ourselves. I found out I'm the Mike
Hargrove I thought I was, the Mike Hargrove I want to be.''
</P>
<P>
   He'd like to let it go at that; he feels uncomfortable extolling
himself and acknowledges that his frequent forays into
self-deprecation ``are maybe a defense mechanism.''
</P>
<P>
   But he is pressed on the matter: Just who is this Mike Hargrove
he discovered?
</P>
<P>
   ``A guy of character,'' he says after a pause. ``A guy with
compassion but who _ I don't want to say tough because I don't
think that's the right word _ but who could see things through.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As they prepare to face the Red Sox at Jacobs Field in the
opener of their best-of-five Division Series, it is easy to forget
just how far these Indians and their manager have come. They are a
bona fide juggernaut, a lineup overflowing with offense, the first
team since the 1950 Red Sox to score more than 1,000 runs, and the
impression one gets is that Hargrove just opens the spigots, sits
back, and watches Kenny Lofton and Omar Vizquel and Roberto Alomar
and Manny Ramirez and Thome and Richie Sexson and the recently
acquired Harold Baines blast away. This year they clinched the
Central crown on Sept. 8; they annually seem to have the division
in their pocket before the frost is gone. A classic case of
pushbutton managing if ever there was one.
</P>
<P>
   It is in fact revisionist history in the extreme. When Hart
hired Hargrove, not long removed from a distinguished 12-year
playing career as a first baseman who hit .290, for his first major
league managing job in the middle of the 1991 season, Cleveland was
considered a baseball wasteland, with a tradition rich in
ineptitude and a vast godforsaken ballpark, Cleveland Stadium,
where fugitives could hide out for the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a bad team,'' recalls catcher Sandy Alomar. ``It was
different for Mike then. He would use a lot more lineups, trying to
find the right combination. But even then, he was a player's
manager.''
</P>
<P>
   That label has become attached to him like a middle name, but it
is too simplistic. Hargrove has achieved both longevity and success
because he has shown he is every kind of player's manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had Mike as a manager since I've been in the big
leagues,'' says Thome. ``He's been the same when we've lost 100
games and when we've won 100 games. Mike's nature is real
easygoing. He's a normal guy, but at the same time, he can be rough
when he needs to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Hart has employed only one manager during his tenure. Hargrove
has proven to be worth keeping around through the various Indian
incarnations, from their woebegone days through their watershed
success.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we came in, we had a different agenda,'' says Hart. ``We
were growing a team. Mike was patient, not reinventing the wheel.
He was very good at teaching the fundamentals.''
</P>
<P>
   That's no longer an issue with the plums reaped by Hart's shrewd
talent judgment and outgoing owner Richard Jacobs's bottomless bank
vault. Often a new cast requires a new director, but Hart
determined otherwise with this adaptable caretaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we got better,'' he says, ``I evaluated the situation and
said, `This is the guy I want for the next level.' ''
</P>
<P>
   There is more to life at this level than filling out the lineup
card in indelible ink.
</P>
<P>
   ``To manage a team like this is not easy,'' says Sandy Alomar.
``We've got a lot of star players.''
</P>
<P>
   To which his brother Roberto adds, ``He knows we have a lot of
guys who know how to play the game. He lets us play the game.''
</P>
<P>
   But a constellation of talent doesn't guarantee success.
Backstage bickering has been the ruin of many a team whose skills
were dynamic but whose chemistry was dynamite. It is here that
Hargrove truly excels.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an even-keeled man,'' says Hart. ``He can settle down a
diverse, enigmatic clubhouse.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, given the near inevitability of Indian summers stretching
into Indian summer, the tendency is to overlook the man at the top.
Perhaps this is Hargrove's major contribution. He is not obsessed
with forcing his imprint upon his players. He is content to manage
the Cleveland Indians, not Mike Hargrove's Cleveland Indians.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not brain surgery,'' he says. ``I suppose in some
respects, I don't want to be taken for granted. Anybody's ego is
big enough that you do care. But my job as manager is to put the
players on the team in the best position to do their job. People
don't come to the park to watch me manage.''
</P>
<P>
   No. They come to see a team he knows how to manage, through
tragedy and triumph.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-99 1131EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991006.0100 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 11:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8110 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-LIFE-IN-AMERICA07-COX     10-06 2635
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIFE-IN-AMERICA07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    In Longview, 24 hands, 107 hours and one HardbodyBy Patrick
Beach
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONGVIEW, Texas _ It's silver. It has a 2.4-liter engine, a
five-speed manual transmission, cloth seats, A/C (for the first
time), AM-FM cassette and, when you throw in delivery fees and
such, a sticker price of $13,246.
</P>
<P>
   It's a new Nissan Frontier 4x2 XE, and recently two dozen people
were assembling at Joe Mallard Nissan here, resolving to hold on to
it longer than anybody else _ however long it takes.
</P>
<P>
   You saw a movie like this once? If you're in or around Austin,
you likely did. S.R. Bindler's documentary, ``Hands on a Hard
Body,'' opened at the Dobie Theater on the Drag about the time the
Earth's crust cooled and has been streaming through the projectors
there ever since. We very much get the film, or so we think. We go
laugh at the rednecks with their East Texas accents so impenetrable
the film could benefit from subtitles, and we watch them fight to
win an inexpensive truck.
</P>
<P>
   Listen. This is not about a truck.
</P>
<P>
   I. Prelude (not the Honda)
</P>
<P>
   The vegetable of the day at the Cotton Patch, in honor of the
contest, is ``extended cabbage.'' The 24 contestants are here,
across the street from the dealership, having had their names drawn
out of 2,000 entries. Now they sit (``now'' being the night before
the contest) and pay attention as the night-before meeting
commences. They include a cop from Houston who competed last year,
the winner of the very first contest, a red-haired 18-year-old who
knows all the words to all the country songs, the mother of a
9-year-old boy with cerebral palsy, the daughter of a past winner,
a snow cone magnate, a schoolteacher and a lanky stranger from
Mobile, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Mallard, the son of the dealership's owner and the guy who
runs the show, goes over the rules: no squatting, leaning or
cupping your hands. A six-minute break every hour, a 15-minute
break every six hours. Drug tests for the three finalists and
another one for the winner and the runner-up. Winner gets a new
truck; runner-up gets a used truck _ except it was stolen from the
lot the night before, so the runner-up will get some truck. Third
place gets a trip. If you're not there by 6:45 a.m. tomorrow,
alternates get drawn. J.D. Drew, who won the contest in the movie
and whose daughter, Melanie Lively, is a contestant, is an
alternate.
</P>
<P>
   Then Mallard, a big, booming, Foghorn Leghorn of a guy working
on at least one Skoal Bandit at all times, tells them they're a
part of something deeply historic and newsworthy. The Houston
paper's here. A crew from the British television show ``Yankee
Panky'' is en route. Mallard widens his eyes and holds two squat
fingers up, preparing to batter home the gravity of the situation:
</P>
<P>
   ``David Letterman's contacted us twice about this,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Calhoun, who won last year's contest in a record-busting
94 hours, offers advice: ``Don't eat nothin' greasy.''
</P>
<P>
   This does not dissuade about two-thirds of the group from
ordering chicken-fried steak. In Longview, if you don't eat nothin'
greasy, you don't eat nothin'.
</P>
<P>
   Every one of them is at the dealership well before the 6:45 a.m.
deadline the next day. Every one of them wears a gray Joe Mallard
Nissan Hands on a Hardbody T-shirt and gloves on their hands to
protect the truck's finish. The last-minute meeting breaks up, and
they dash outside under the portable tent where the prize waits.
</P>
<P>
   A local radio station (one that mostly plays the new kind of
country music, the kind that doesn't sound like country music)
blasts away from its remote truck in the corner of the lot. Travis
Tritt sings and spells ``T-R-O-U-B-L-E.''
</P>
<P>
   Warren ``Hands On'' Hearne, a Texas Alcoholic Beverage
Commission officer originally from Houston, has been acting like
Ali before the ``Thrilla in Manila,'' talking big, making everybody
laugh, pledging he will go the distance, which he predicts will be
105.7 hours. He says he's gonna shut up when the thing starts,
putting the other contestants off balance with his sudden silence
and determined visage.
</P>
<P>
   Hands on. Air horn blast. Tuesday, Sept. 21, 1999, 7 a.m.,
weather unusually cool and windy.
</P>
<P>
   Let the games begin.
</P>
<P>
   Let the chatter begin.
</P>
<P>
   In the crowd, a guy in a black cowboy hat draws attention. It's
Benny Perkins, the charismatic, hyperbole-prone star of ``Hands
On'' who, in the film, compares the contest to combat. He says he
could hardly sleep last night he was so excited, and he's not even
in the contest. He admires the resolve of those who've competed
before and are here again, and he pities those who don't know what
kind of pain and dementia they're about to endure.
</P>
<P>
   ``You slowly lose your mind,'' Perkins says. ``Slowly. You can
feel it.''
</P>
<P>
   J.D. Drew didn't make it past alternate status, but he's taken
the week off work anyway to support daughter Melanie Lively. The
sentimental favorite is Mary Edwards, a dining room hostess whose
son, Casey, has cerebral palsy. She has his picture pinned to her
shirt. She needs the truck to carry the boy's wheelchair to
doctor's appointments in Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   The routine sets in. Hourly breaks, rubdowns, dashes to the
bathroom, Brooks &AMP; Dunn covering John Waite's '80s schmaltz pop hit
``Missing You'' (who green-lighted that?) on the radio about every
eight minutes. Nobody's going anywhere. At the 11-hour break,
Hearne lies prone eating something out of aluminum foil:
</P>
<P>
   ``Ginseng, baby! Straight from Siberia. Our secret weapon.''
</P>
<P>
   It looks a lot like chicken.
</P>
<P>
   The first casualty, 20-year-old Joe Patrick Morris, drops at
4:27 Wednesday morning. He staggers over to a chaise longue, covers
up with a sleeping bag and passes out for five hours, sleeping
through air horns and temperatures that slip below 50. When he
wakes, he pulls a Marlboro out of a hard pack, lights up and
declares he will enter again next year.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Edwards, Casey's mother, is the fourth to give out, lifting
her hand off the truck about 11:25 Wednesday night as the
contestants watched a video of the movie. (They got rid of four
that way last year.)
</P>
<P>
   Jan Maynard _ the dealership's cheerleader and mother hen _
drops big news on the survivors. Letterman's still interested, but
he'd demanded an exclusive, and now Rosie O'Donnell has called. So
Maynard says perhaps it's time for Mr. Letterman to _ how to put
this delicately? _ unburden his colon or let someone else use the
bathroom. The group votes for the latter, and somebody from the
Rosie show is en route. The stakes go higher. The winner will get
the ultimate: a trip to New York for an appearance on Rosie's show
the Monday after the contest.
</P>
<P>
   This is serious. This is huge. This is not about a truck.
</P>
<P>
   II. Friday night lights
</P>
<P>
   The breaks are deadly, especially the 15-minute ones. After
80-some hours, if you're handling a consistent level of pain, it
becomes your companion and you forget ever being without it. Then
you lie down and your body remembers and your mind refuses to again
embrace the pain. Mothers who've competed say it's worse than labor
and childbirth.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the mental side, which is like your own private
freak show. The third dimension gets very arbitrary _ a row of
trucks stretches for miles, your legs seem to be 3 inches long. The
year J.D. Drew won, he spent six hours entertaining a delusion that
a jumbo jet had landed across the street from the dealership and
people were, in the commercial airline parlance, deplaning.
</P>
<P>
   The judges _ there are always two judges _ hover over
contestants about to slip, and sometimes suggest, very gently, that
it's OK, it's time to give in, that they fought nobly and well.
It's uncomfortably similar to watching someone die, and you say the
same things. Contestants collapse, cry and are led away. Then they
always, always come back after a few hours' sleep _ there's an
explicable connection to the event and the people. It is like
combat, and also love, and just as impossible to describe if you
haven't lived it. This is the mistake we have made about ``Hands on
a Hard Body.'' It's not a comedy. It's a drama.
</P>
<P>
   The players in this year's drama have boiled down to four. Brian
Root, the bearded beanpole from Mobile, Ala., who drove to Longview
and spent a week just to enter his name, is hanging tough. It's
been, uh, an experience. ``I've discovered doors to my psyche I
didn't know existed,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't look bad at all, but he's got an unusual level of
support. His brother David does rubdowns, encourages Brian to go on
quick jogs during 15-minute breaks or do jumping jacks on a
trampoline. Then there's this other guy people are calling the
Guru. He's always running to the Albertson's for supplies, which
include red bananas, pine nuts, melons, avocados and papayas. Other
contestants see nothing wrong with bacon and eggs. The health
freaks get plain spaghetti.
</P>
<P>
   Warren Hearne, the funny loud guy, went out under some
controversy at 5:07 a.m. Friday, taking his big package of Depends
undergarments (''NOW! 80% Better Leakage Protection'') with him. He
was going a little crazy, saying a fix was in. He returns to
apologize and root for Cathy Frazier, the flinty woman who won the
very first contest in '92, and who held the record time until last
year. No way is this about a truck for her. She's still got her
other truck. It's about being the first person to win twice.
Others, including Benny Perkins, have tried and failed.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Walker, he of Charlie's Sno-Cones &AMP; Seasonal Tanning, is
closing in on his time last year but looks fuzzy by late afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   A Comanche moon ascends in a bloodshot sky. There are perfectly
good high school football games going on, but this is the biggest
show in town and hundreds are crammed around the tent, pulling for
their favorites, attaching encouraging signs to the rope perimeter.
High school girls sport selections from the
You-Are-Not-Leaving-This-House-Dressed-Like-That collection; boys
wear Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch hats and those gigantic jeans that have
become ubiquitous, breaching even the Pine Curtain.
</P>
<P>
   Random free-associative thought: Charles Lindbergh flies alone
from New York to Paris in 33 hours and wins the world; Chris
Whitlock hangs on to a Nissan for almost 90 hours and wins a trip
to the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   He comes back later, after getting a rehydrating IV drip. They
always come back.
</P>
<P>
   So now there are three _ Brian Root, still hanging tough, very
deliberately changing hands every so often, not talking much,
conserving his energy, munching fruits and nuts on breaks. He cried
for a while, and his limbs seemed to seize up, but he's worked
through it. Word goes around the peanut gallery that Brian's done
things like this before. He's done seven or eight triathlons ``over
the years'' and has a resting pulse rate in the 40s. And there are
oblique references to other contests involving pain, insanity and
endurance, but neither he nor his brother David nor the
fruit-procuring guru _ Paul Rathe by name _ will specify.
</P>
<P>
   Cathy Frazier's hanging in. She stands where she always has, on
the passenger side over the hood, where she can stare down her
opponent _ plainly Brian by now.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangerettes from Kilgore College come to cheer on Charlie
Walker about 10 p.m., doing a variation on the ``Hokey Pokey''
(``You put your right hand on ...,'' you get the idea), and the
infusion of spirit buoys his corpus for a time, but he's teetering.
</P>
<P>
   A light rain begins to fall and, to accommodate the exposed
crowd _ still out in force _ the truck is moved under the overhang
of the dealership building. And this is where Charlie Walker makes
his stand as friends holler at him until they lose their voices.
Facing the truck head on, both hands on the hood, with maybe two
dozen stalwart observers looking on, Charlie Walker falls backward
just short of 4:30 a.m. Saturday _ nine hours to the minute longer
than he went last year.
</P>
<P>
   And it goes on a lot longer. At 7 a.m., Patsy Cline sings ``I
Fall to Pieces'' on the radio, but it's unclear to whom she's
singing. The rain stops, the sun rises, the truck goes back under
the tent, the rain returns, so does the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks,'' says Jan Maynard, surveying the people, equipment
and debris, ``like Woodstock.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody's betting against Cathy or Brian, who stand as they have
from the beginning, directly across from one another _ Cathy
staring down her foe, Brian watching the crowd, sometimes chatting
with a judge or fan or his brother or the Guru, who now totes a
digital timer to monitor the progress of breaks.
</P>
<P>
   They enter 100 hours at 10 a.m. Saturday. In the movie, J.D.
Drew wins in 78.
</P>
<P>
   Cathy Frazier, holding on, not so much wanting to win as wanting
not to lose: ``Them hours don't mean nothin' to me anymore. I just
want to solve it. It's gonna go my way. What do they call it when a
computer goes off? Crashed. I crashed. I didn't even remember what
all these people were doing here. I thought I was dreaming.''
</P>
<P>
   During a break a couple of bikers in black T-shirts and
bandannas approach. One of them gives Cathy a bunch of cut flowers
in a newspaper cone.
</P>
<P>
   Great drama at the 5 p.m. break. Cathy decides to go inside the
bathroom well into the six-minute break. The one-minute warning
horn blares. Everybody thinks, stick a fork in this one, it's done.
But she struggles out, makes it across the lot and puts a hand on
the truck with two seconds to spare. Cheers, applause.
</P>
<P>
   Paul the Guru can't believe the endurance of these two. He says
he's been shot in the neck and buried in a landslide, but nothing
compares to the pain he felt when he did one of these contests for
68 hours. Anybody who does this twice, he says, is insane. The guru
gig is cushier.
</P>
<P>
   Cathy to Brian: ``Do your legs hurt?''
</P>
<P>
   Brian, affecting nonchalance: ``Yeah, a little.''
</P>
<P>
   Cathy, pointing: ``Well, it's gonna get a lot worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary-Chapin Carpenter sings ``I Feel Lucky,'' but Cathy Frazier
soon doesn't look or sound lucky. Actual quote: ``Blah, blah, blah,
blah, blah, blah, blah, blah, blah....''
</P>
<P>
   She sits down for the 6 p.m. break, cries, shakes her head and
does not answer the horn six minutes later.
</P>
<P>
   The winner, after 107 hours and at least that many broadcasts of
``Missing You,'' is Brian Root, the skinny guy from Alabama, who
gets a little choked up. Even big old Jay Mallard gets choked up.
</P>
<P>
   What nobody knows is that Brian, his brother and Paul the Guru
have been at this for years _ they ride in circuit, go all over
looking for such contests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suffice to say this wasn't the first time,'' Paul Rathe says
later. ``The key to winning is management.''
</P>
<P>
   III. Epilogue: The kindness of strangers
</P>
<P>
   Mary Edwards went home and told Casey she didn't win him the
truck to take him to school and the doctor, and she cried and cried
and said, ``Momma tried.''
</P>
<P>
   She'd entered the drawing every day for almost a month to get a
shot. Then she made it and failed.
</P>
<P>
   Later, a stranger found her and handed her an envelope with a
letter inside from a famous movie star _ she won't say who, or
whether it's a male or female, a Texan, or, for instance, Matthew
McConaughey. The famous movie star requested anonymity, and Mary
Edwards is honoring that, not even telling her own mother who it
is. The letter said the famous movie star had heard about her
plight and wanted to buy her a van. And the next day, the famous
movie star called Mary Edwards' unlisted number, just to prove it
was all real.
</P>
<P>
   Casey is lobbying for a ``Blue's Clues'' paint job, but Mary
will take what she can get.
</P>
<P>
   For Mary Edwards, it was about a truck.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-99 1132EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991006.0101 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 11:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8112 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-WILLIAMS-B     10-06 1820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-WILLIAMS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS TAKES LOW ROAD, BUT SOX ON COURSE FOR SUCCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Grady Little, John Cumberland, and Jimy Williams walked
to the entrance of Network Associates Coliseum in Oakland one day
this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Grady Little and John Cumberland walked through the entrance of
Network Associates Coliseum. They noticed something was missing.
The boss.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where's Jimy?'' asked Cumberland.
</P>
<P>
   Darned if they could find him. They looked in front of them and
beside them and around the nearby corridors of the concrete
mausoleum. No Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, they wandered back outside. Ah-ha. Two kids _ 13 or 14
years old, Little guessed _ were playing catch. One 55-year-old was
intently instructing them in the proper way to throw the ball _ two
fingers across the seams.
</P>
<P>
   Little shook his head. ``Let's go,'' he told Cumberland. ``God
knows how long he'll be out here.''
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen minutes later, the Red Sox manager joined his two
coaches in the visitors' clubhouse. Sorry about the delay, but,
well, he just couldn't help himself. Once a teacher, always a
teacher.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the second year in a row, a Red Sox team that supposedly has
no business playing in October is playing in October. For the
second year in a row, Williams is receiving accolades for somehow
getting them to Cleveland as the American League wild card for the
best-of-five Division Series. The credit is reluctant on both ends,
to be sure. Boston has never embraced the often inscrutable manager
during his three-year term. And Williams cringes at the mere
mention of the topic Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he can spare a couple of minutes for personal analysis
on the eve of the playoffs, he replies, ``Or less.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not too keen on talking about myself,'' he says. ``I'd
rather have you talk about us as a group. Our success is a
reflection of how everybody feeds off each other. Our coaching
staff is pretty special. And our trainers and clubhouse personnel
and players. Us as a group. That I'd feel comfortable with.''
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't mention the cab driver who dropped him off at the
ballpark hours before game time, but he'd undoubtedly salute him,
too. There is no caste system in Jimy Williams's world.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's consistent and level and as fair a man as you'd want to
see,'' says Little, whose association with Williams dates to the
mid-'80s when both were in the Toronto system and continued through
the glorious early '90s as coaches with the invincible Atlanta
Braves. ``There's no difference to Jimy Williams between a player
on this team making $10 milllion and a player making $200,000.''
</P>
<P>
   Except that he has far more of the latter. Williams has
jerryrigged a contender out of a nucleus numbering exactly two true
stars _ pitcher Pedro Martinez and shortstop Nomar Garciaparra _
and supplementary parts consisting of youngsters, retreads, and
role players. The team's unlikely success, he insists, is all their
fault.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feed off my players,'' he says. ``They inspire me by how
they play, how they pitch, what they bring to the park every day. I
don't like to talk at my players or to my players. I like to talk
with my players. A lot of times, I'll say, `Hey, I was thinking
this. What do you think? I need your help.' I value their input.
It's a two-way conversation, but one thing's for certain: When we
leave the clubhouse, we're going to be together.''
</P>
<P>
   The harmony is not a facade for the benefit of public opinion.
Possible explosions never reach the ignition stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the overall atmosphere he creates,'' says pitching coach
Joe Kerrigan. ``He talks to the players one-on-one if something has
to be discussed. Even if it's a negative, he's going to turn it
into a positive.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the negative seeps through the clubhouse doors,
anyway, such as the Saturday in late August when Martinez was tardy
for a start, arriving at the ballpark well after the two-hour
pregame deadline. Per his rules, Williams did not allow Martinez to
open the game. He used him in relief and Martinez got the win, but
the temperamental pitcher was clearly infuriated. Yet Williams
quietly endured his ace's displeasure, defusing a combustible
situation by refusing to allow it to escalate.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's honest,'' says hitting coach Jim Rice. ``Pedro's late?
Then it's `Pedro, you're not starting.' I stand by him. It's the
same for everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   All Williams asks in return is that his players share his
reverence for their line of work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baseball is a special game to me,'' he says. ``I try to treat
it with respect. In everything we do, we try to show respect for
the game. That means showing respect for each other, even the
opponents. You try to play the game the right way.''
</P>
<P>
   He assumes as much on the part of his players unless they prove
otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's successful to us starts with his belief in us _ his
belief in us enough to let us go out and play,'' says Jason
Varitek, who showed his gratitude when Williams made him the
everyday catcher after Scott Hatteberg was injured by turning into
a 20-homer slugger and masterful handler of pitchers. ``He's very
positive. Everything that comes out of his mouth is positive.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams takes a pointillist's view of the big picture. Each
game is a separate, sacred entity. That's the message he transfers
to his players: Just take care of today. Don't get distracted by
hindsight or foresight.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a very focused man,'' says veteran third baseman John
Valentin. ``All he asks is that you concentrate on the game you are
playing that specific day, that specific time. He doesn't talk
about going on to the next game or the next series. He prepares
only for that game. That makes it simple for him and simple for
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Simplicity, in fact, is the essence of his survival.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There was no defense; he was guilty. When Jimy Williams was
hired to replace the fired Kevin Kennedy as Red Sox manager on Nov.
19, 1996, he had to admit that he was not Jim Leyland, Whitey
Herzog, Jim Fregosi, Jeff Torborg, Larry Bowa, or any of the other
high-visibility candidates general manager Dan Duquette reportedly
had courted for the job _ and the list undoubtedly would have
included Connie Mack and John McGraw if Duquette could have located
their phone numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Duquette acknowledges the pursuit of more recognizable names,
``but it didn't come together,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   But Jimy Williams? During his one previous major league managing
stop, with the Blue Jays from 1986-89, he had compiled winning
records in each of his three full seasons but was best remembered _
or vilified _ for coughing up a 3 1/2-game AL East lead over the
Detroit Tigers in the last week of the 1997 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I've grown since then,'' he says. ``I keep my ears
open, my eyes open, an open mind.''
</P>
<P>
   It was debatable whether he would ever get a chance to show what
the new, improved Jimy Williams could do running a ball club. From
1990-96, he served as third base coach for his onetime Toronto
mentor, Atlanta manager Bobby Cox, on a team that won five division
titles, went to four World Series, and captured a world
championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I only thought about managing when (the media) would bring it
up,'' says Williams. ``I just wanted to be the best coach I could.
Hey, I was going to the ballpark very day, putting on a major
league uniform. What could be better?''
</P>
<P>
   The chance Duquette gave him, even if he wasn't on the GM's A
list. Despite appearances, Duquette wasn't simply desperate to fill
in a job title on the club directory. During his time as a Montreal
executive, the Expos had trained with the Braves at West Palm
Beach, Fla. And he noticed a certain Atlanta coach who daily seemed
to be spending extra hours on the field, helping whoever was
interested.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had the chance to observe him as an outsider,'' says
Duquette. ``He was always out working with the younger ballplayers
_ pitchers on bunting, infielders on fundamentals. He's an
excellent teacher.''
</P>
<P>
   That made not the slightest impression when Williams was
introduced to a Boston media firing squad. He was forever branded
by the image he portrayed. It was as if he had ridden into the big
city on one of the horses he rode as one of seven children of a
farmer in Arroyo Grande, Calif., kicking dust from his spurs and
chomping a blade of grass.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Williams has a college degree in agribusiness from
Fresno State. Yet the rube routine has served him well. His often
unfathomable answers to questions regarding players' performances
and managerial strategy keep his interrogators too busy trying to
translate them to stir up a ruckus about the team. Williams is
polite and gracious and as reticent as he can get away wth being.
His is a limited lexicon, by design. His team ``competes,'' win or
lose. His players are ``competitors.'' A certain exalted few are
``warriors.'' Just try to make something incendiary of that arsenal
of verbiage.
</P>
<P>
   ``He handles the media better than anyone I've ever seen,'' says
pitcher Bret Saberhagen, ``because he rarely gives a straight
answer. He'll say something that's totally off the subject. He
won't keep talking until you guys get what you want to hear.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor does Williams worry in the least about what he hears _ or
reads or sees _ about himself. Rice, a longtime Boston star whose
relationship with the media wasn't arm's length as much as armed
combat, has seen excessive concern about vox populi devour many a
manager; he believes it was the undoing of one of his favorites,
Don Zimmer. He can't envision Williams falling victim to the
syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jimy's more like a grandfather,'' says Rice. ``He's more
laid-back. One thing I've seen _ he believes that if he can't say
something nice about someone, he won't say anything.''
</P>
<P>
   In a town whose approach to baseball is both sophisticated and
savage, Williams has the perfect temperament to deal with the
scorching airwaves and doomsday newsprint. It's not necessarily
that he's impervious to it; he seems oblivious to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``What, because I live in Boston, I should listen to talk
shows?'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He claims to ignore newspapers, too, but he can't be unaware of
the prevailing sentiment that he's not the flavor of the month in a
city that craves celebrity leaders. It's just that he doesn't care.
He genuinely doesn't care.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell the guys who cover the team regularly, `If it's time to
rip me, go ahead and rip me,' '' he says. ``It doesn't bother me.
There's a human element involved: `OK, Jimy, it's time to make
another decision. So make it and live with it.' That's what makes
baseball so special, the controversy. That's OK. It's good for the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   And as a long as it's directed at him, it's not bothering his
players. Quite a bumpkin, that Jimy Williams.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
