<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 11:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8115 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-VARITEK-BO     10-06 1340
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-VARITEK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VARITEK HAS BEEN A STEAL FOR THE RED SOX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Jason Varitek refuses to undervalue himself.
</P>
<P>
   When the Minnesota Twins selected him in the first round of the
1993 draft, 21st overall, then informed him they had two other
picks who were priorities and that they'd get around to dealing
with him when and if they had some spare time, Varitek saved them
the trouble and returned to Georgia Tech for his senior season.
</P>
<P>
   When the Seattle Mariners made him their top choice, No. 14
overall, the following year, then offered him a contract he felt
wasn't befitting the 1993 College Player of the Year and a
three-time All-American, Varitek held out. And held out. And held
out. Finally, he agreed to the Mariners' proposal _ 10 months later
in April 1995, in essence having sacrificed a year of pro ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a matter of principle,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jason Varitek refuses to overvalue himself.
</P>
<P>
   The man anointed by one publication as the greatest college
catcher in history entered the minor leagues at the relatively
lofty Double A level with one nagging misgiving. He didn't feel he
knew how to catch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really struggled with my receiving,'' he says. ``As a
result, it affected my throwing. I worked with a guy (Seattle
roving minor league catching instructor Roger Hansen). He broke me
down. It was basically like a house. I had to find a foundation
that worked for me. My foundation was all wrong. I was really
spread out, sometimes sank when the pitch would come to me. I'd
collapse, make it tougher to throw.''
</P>
<P>
   Add the fact that Varitek, a switch hitter, could only seem to
make solid contact with air from the left side of the plate, and it
explains why he was available at the trade deadline July 31, 1997,
when Red Sox general manager Dan Duquette, frothing to unload
nitroglycerine closer Heathcliff Slocumb, shipped the righthander
to Seattle for Varitek and pitcher Derek Lowe.
</P>
<P>
   By then, The Greatest Catcher In College Baseball History had
acquired a new label. Disappointment. And he felt it was well
deserved.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a battle,'' says Varitek. ``Failure is a tough thing to
deal with.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Duquette wasn't ready to subscribe to that theory. ``I think
his lack of pro experience limited his production early,'' said the
GM. ``I also think he would've benefited from some time at the
introductory level. There was also a perception around baseball
that his stance on his contracts diminished his value as a catcher.
But he was a top talent coming up.''
</P>
<P>
   There was another consideration that made Varitek attractive.
Desperation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, we needed a catcher,'' says Duquette.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out he found one beyond his giddiest fantasies. After a
year of platooning with Scott Hatteberg, playing essentially only
against lefthanders, Varitek, 27, inherited the full-time job by
default May 18 when Hatteberg was sidelined by elbow surgery. Since
then, he has been a revelation with an exclamation point. He has
masterfully handled a patchwork pitching staff and provided latent
punch _ 20 homers, 17 of them lefthanded, and 76 RBIs while batting
.269 _ as one of the indispensable ingredients in the Red Sox'
arduous march to their second straight American League wild-card
playoff berth.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the second-best catcher in the American League (behind
only the Rangers' redoubtable Pudge Rodriguez),'' says pitching
coach Joe Kerrigan. ``He's the best catcher I've ever been around
on a daily basis. He's all about trying to make people better. He
cares first about taking care of the pitching staff rather than
hitting. He's conscientious. His throwing skills are right behind
Pudge. He's always in the game. He gets to the park early, he's
caught maybe 30 games in a row, and he's in the back room lifting
weights. He catches in pain.''
</P>
<P>
   But there's more to the reborn Varitek than durability.
Technically, Kerrigan finds him virtually faultless.
</P>
<P>
   ``His targets have settled down,'' says the coach. ``He gives a
good presentation of the pitch. He receives the ball nice and quiet
so the umpire can get a good look. He's not jumping all around.
That's a lost art today. Some of these guys, it looks like they're
trying for a double play, they're in such a hurry to get the ball
back to the pitcher.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Kerrigan has found the ideal caretaker for his staff,
because the catcher places as much of a premium on catching as the
coach does.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to,'' Varitek says. ``You can't win a game, 1-0, if
you give up the run. And when we lost Mo (Vaughn) in the offseason,
we knew we'd have to find other ways to win.''
</P>
<P>
   In that regard, Varitek also has done his unexpected part,
providing some of the thunder that departed to Anaheim with Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best way to describe Jason and the way he's matured is to
compare him to Todd Hundley,'' says former Met and current Red Sox
righthander Bret Saberhagen, a teammate of both catchers. ``Todd
didn't put up big offensive numbers for the first couple of years
because he was trying to learn the hitters, concentrating on
catching. It's the same with Jason _ he's starting to come into his
own offensively because he knows the hitters, more so than when he
started.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, for catchers, offense is considered strictly a bonus.
``Pitching coaches are selfish,'' says Kerrigan. ``We don't care if
a guy hits (expletive) .100 if he can catch.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox discovered almost by accident that Varitek is worth
much more than that at the plate. ``He has a knack for getting
clutch hits,'' says Duquette.
</P>
<P>
   Varitek wasn't sure he had a clue for getting any kind of hits
when he took over the job full-time. ``This is obviously beyond my
expectations,'' he says, ``because I had expected to play only
against lefthanders. I was fortunate that they believed in me,
didn't go out and get somebody else. Let's face it, there were a
lot of questions about whether I could hit lefty.''
</P>
<P>
   But hitting coach Jim Rice maintained an open mind on the
matter, despite Varitek's dismal track record.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know how a guy's going to do until he gets the
chance,'' says Rice. ``We got a chance to see him offensively from
both sides of the plate. He showed good power to both sides.''
</P>
<P>
   That, too, was a byproduct of Varitek's slavish work ethic. He
wore out the batting cage learning from Rice.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where the real work is done,'' says Rice, ``more than
on the field (in batting practice). And in the cage, he'd hit line
drives. I don't care if you're a power hitter or what. That's what
you like to see.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the talk of his struggles, success has become a habit
for Varitek at virtually every level. His suburban Orlando team
reached the Little League World Series final. Georgia Tech was the
College World Series runner-up during his four-year stay after he'd
rejected his first pro offer, when the Houston Astros selected him
in the 23d round out of Lake Brantley High School in Longwood,
Fla., ``because I had good parents who impressed upon me the value
of a college education.'' And now the Red Sox are back in the
postseason, which they'd likely have missed without Varitek.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he believes it was the flirtation with failure that may have
been his most valuable instrument for accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``If everything is always easy for you,'' says Varitek, ``then
when you're not doing as well as you can, sometimes things can get
worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Not when you start at rock bottom.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's come a long way,'' says Lowe. ``When he first got
drafted, he had a problem on pitches with movement. He'd have a
tendency to take them out of the strike zone. But he didn't just
accept the way he was catching. He wanted to get better. He knew he
could get better.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Varitek, his own toughest critic, would have to acknowledge
that he has done just that. And there's no chance he'll be
underappreciated in Boston.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
