<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 11:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8119 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-MARTINEZ-B     10-06 1263
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-MARTINEZ-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS ACE CAN BEAT ANYTHING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Red Sox fans thought 1986 was as good as it got for a
Boston starting pitcher. In '86, Roger Clemens started the season
14-0. He was MVP of the All-Star Game and finished 24-4 with a 2.48
ERA, 238 strikeouts, and only 67 walks in 254 innings. He won the
Cy Young Award, the MVP, and the seventh game of the American
League Championship Series. He took the Sox to the seventh game of
the World Series and his Series ERA was 3.18.
</P>
<P>
   Now along comes Pedro Martinez. In 1999, Pedro went 23-4 with a
2.07 ERA, 313 strikeouts, and 37 walks in 213 1/3 innings. He was
MVP of the All-Star Game, will certainly win the AL Cy Young Award,
has a shot at MVP, and Wednesday night takes the Red Sox into the
postseason when he starts against the Indians at Cleveland's Jacobs
Field.
</P>
<P>
   Starting with the infamous ground ball between Bill Buckner's
legs (a game started, but not finished by Clemens), the Red Sox
have lost 16 of 17 postseason games. The lone victory in this
hideous streak came in Game 1 of last year's Division Series, when
Pedro beat the Indians, 11-3, with seven innings of six-hit,
no-walk, eight-strikeout pitching.
</P>
<P>
   He is on a truly incredible roll. In his last seven starts,
Pedro went 6-0 with an 0.82 ERA, including 96 strikeouts and only
28 hits in 55 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Listen to Seattle's Jay Buhner, a grizzled vet who is 0 for 8
lifetime against Martinez, all strikeouts: ``There's no one like
him. He's in a class by himself. A lot of guys have one great out
pitch. He's got three out-pitches _ the best fastball, the best
curve, and the best changeup.''
</P>
<P>
   The legend of Pedro was solidified in New York on Friday night,
Sept. 10, when he fanned 17 Yankees, including eight of the last
nine, in a one-hit, 3-1 victory. It is considered by many the
greatest game ever pitched against the Bronx Bombers, and it sent a
message that the Red Sox will be difficult to beat in the playoffs,
particularly in a five-game series when Pedro can pitch (and win)
twice.
</P>
<P>
   Citizens of Red Sox Nation need not be reminded that Pedro
pitched only once in the four-game series loss in '98. The Sox
dropped Game 2 in Cleveland and Game 3 at Fenway, then manager Jimy
Williams was faced with the prospect of pitching Pedro in Game 4,
or holding him for a Game 5 clincher.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez was upset when it was announced that Pete Schourek
would get the ball for Game 4. The Sox resisted the urge to use
Pedro on three days' rest and went out in four games despite a nice
effort from Schourek (two hits, no runs in 5 1/3 innings). Boston
lost, 2-1. Pitching coach Joe Kerrigan has since admitted that they
considered using Pedro until he threw in-between starts and had
nothing.
</P>
<P>
   What if the same scenario arises this year? If the Sox trail in
games, 2-1, after Saturday, would Pedro get the ball in Game 4?
Management says it's doubtful, pointing out that Pedro has not
pitched on three days' rest this season.
</P>
<P>
   What would Martinez want?
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh yeah, I'd want to pitch that game,'' he said. ``I want to
pitch every day if I can. I'm gonna take my two painkillers, three
or four if I have to, and be in there. Every day. I want to be a
part of it. If not, I'm gonna be a big cheerleader and they'll have
to tie me to the pole again.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Ron Guidry and Sandy Koufax before him, Martinez is capable
of throwing the ball almost 100 miles per hour even thought he
weighs only 174 pounds. Pitching coaches attribute this to
mechanics while physicists chalk it up to torque and leverage.
Pedro has other ideas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a combination of both god-given ability and also hard
work,'' he said. ``I worked my butt off. You would never imagine
the things I do, the things I used to do. In the Dominican, I used
to run at 10:30 at night in the dark. I wasn't allowed to run in
the day. The coach said, `You are too skinny to run. You need to
build on weight.' So I ran in the dark field and there was a guard
with a shotgun. I had to give him 20 bucks to let me run and be
aware that I was there and not an intruder. Otherwise, in the dark
of night you see somebody running and you shoot.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``too skinny'' tag dogged him when he pitched for the
Dodgers. They used him as a reliever for parts of two seasons, then
dealt him to Montreal for the immortal Delino DeShields.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know who said that I was too skinny,'' he said. ``I
heard Tommy Lasorda, Dr. (Frank) Jobe, one of the top scouts. I
have no grudges about it. The one that should have grudges is them
because they were wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers were wrong and the Expos are sorry they couldn't
afford to keep Pedro. According to know-it-all Bill James,
Martinez's 1999 season was the best of the decade. With Roger
Clemens (1997), he is one of only two American League pitchers to
win the mythical pitcher's triple crown (leading the league in
wins, ERA, and strikeouts) since Hal Newhouser turned the trick in
1945. Martinez averaged 13.20 strikeouts per nine innings, best in
history. He averaged only one walk per 8.46 strikeouts. Pedro's ERA
was 2.07, compared to an American League average of 4.86. It is the
greatest disparity between a pitcher's ERA and the league average.
And he did it in a league with a designated hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what makes this so amazing,'' Williams said. ``When you
look at what he's doing in relation to the rest of the league, and
in this era of the home run. I'm not sure people appreciate what
they are seeing.''
</P>
<P>
   This is why he is also an MVP candidate. The Cy Young race is a
joke and should be unanimous. And Pedro may have won the MVP when
he stuck it to the Yankees on that stellar night in September. He
would become the 10th pitcher to win both awards in the same
season. The last two were Clemens in '86 and Dennis Eckersley with
the A's in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a great accomplishment, but it's not something I'm
ambitious of,'' said Martinez. ``I think I've done enough for
myself. What I want right now _ really, really want bad _ is a
World Series ring, just to complete my cap on the big leagues as an
achievement.''
</P>
<P>
   He says he doesn't believe in the Curse of the Bambino and feels
the Red Sox are close to the long-awaited championship season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Soon,'' said Pedro. ``I can't tell you how soon, but it's
gonna happen. I can tell by the way these players are developing
and the way Boston is getting closer and closer every year.''
</P>
<P>
   He hates the cold weather, but knows that the hitters hate it
more. Imagine trying to hit Pedro's 97-mile-per-hour heater if it's
45 degrees in Cleveland or Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a big fan of cold weather, but through the years, cold
is not bad to me. My numbers are pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   He matches up well with Wednesday's opponent, fellow Dominican,
Bartolo Colon. In four head-to-head matchups against the Cleveland
ace, Martinez is 3-0 with a 1.64 ERA, 42 strikeouts, and four
walks.
</P>
<P>
   It is a lot of pressre for one man. Pedro makes the Red Sox the
team no one wants to face in a five-game series. Conversely, if he
loses _ and that is possible, especially against the thumping
Indians lineup _ the Red Sox and their fans will feel that the
series is over. But if he wins, the Sox go into the next three
games feeling they need only to steal one victory, then hand the
ball to Pedro for the clincher.
</P>
<P>
   This must be what it felt like to root for the St. Louis
Cardinals when they had Bob Gibson in the 1960s.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-99 1135EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991006.0104 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 11:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8122 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-CLEVELAND-RAMIREZ     10-06 1306
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-CLEVELAND-RAMIREZ-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAMIREZ HAS BEEN THE DRIVING FORCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Over the weekend, he was Sandy Alomar, No. 15.
Tomorrow he might be Jim Thome, No. 25. Unless he's in a Roberto
Alomar, No. 12, mood. Or perhaps he'll decide that it's Omar
Vizquel, No. 13, time.
</P>
<P>
   Manny Ramirez has another habit besides driving in runs at a
more prolific pace than any major leaguer since the Depression.
Without notice, he'll summon a clubhouse kid, hand him a $20 bill,
and dispatch him to one of the souvenir stands at Jacobs Field to
purchase a red T-shirt bearing the name and number of one of his
Cleveland Indians teammates. Then he'll amputate the sleeves, the
better to reveal the mountaintops he calls biceps, and wear his
replica of preference around the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Manny wears anybody's shirt but his own,'' says Sandy Alomar,
shaking his head. ``There doesn't seem to be any pattern to it, but
I've been injured so I haven't been around him the whole year.
Someone like Vizquel might know.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you why he does it,'' says Vizquel, wearing a grin
that reveals he has no clue why Ramirez does it and doesn't really
care. ``He's crazy. He must be (expletive) up in the head. I think
he's making fun of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Vizquel well knows that the opposite is true. Ramirez is almost
reverential in his regard for his supporting cast, a term he would
never use to describe them. He says he chooses a shirt of the day
``for luck,'' but it just as easily could be his way of trying to
go incognito.
</P>
<P>
   If so, he's as much in a dream world as his season has been.
</P>
<P>
   Though he considers the limelight the equivalent of stranding a
runner at third, Ramirez, 26, can't possibly escape it after a
season in which he shredded entire chapters of baseball's record
book. His 165 runs batted in not only broke Hal Trosky's
63-year-old club record by three, they also represented the largest
major league output since Lou Gehrig's 165 in 1934. Only eight
players in the 20th century drove in more, and Ramirez ends the
millennium in the company of Ruth and Gehrig and Foxx and Greenberg
and DiMaggio.
</P>
<P>
   Humility prevents the Indians right fielder from considering his
place in that pantheon. He's much more comfortable invoking the
names of the Alomars and Vizquel and Thome and Kenny Lofton and
Richie Sexson and Harold Baines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't be able to drive in runs without the guys getting
on in front of me,'' he says. ``Sometimes I'll get the runner in
from third, sometimes not. If I don't, I've got the guys behind me
to pick me up. I'm not the man here. I prefer not to be the man.''
</P>
<P>
   Another futile fantasy. While it's true that five Indians,
including Ramirez, have scored 100 runs; five Indians, including
Ramirez, have driven in 100 runs; and Cleveland is the first team
since the 1950 Red Sox to have sent 1,000 men across the plate,
these Midwest maulers take their cue from their cleanup hitter.
</P>
<P>
   It's as if they all want to wear Manny Ramirez T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The quiet storm,'' Lofton calls him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The clutchmaster,'' Sandy Alomar salutes.
</P>
<P>
   Pure poison, American League pitchers chorus after they've
ducked for cover.
</P>
<P>
   It's difficult to put Ramirez's season in perspective, because
the Indians don't happen to have any 65-year-olds in their lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``You take a guy that, for example, drives in 120 runs,'' says
fellow 100-RBI man Thome. ``You have to have a tremendous year to
do that. To do what Manny has is mind-boggling.''
</P>
<P>
   Even 49-year-old manager Mike Hargrove, whose parents were kids
when Gehrig and Trosky were ringing up RBIs like cash registers, is
at a loss to come up with a frame of reference. ``I don't know if
there's anything to compare it to,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Considering the historic horizons he has reached while
complementing his run production with 44 homers and a .335 average,
Ramirez obviously has exceeded expectations. But he didn't just
fall to earth.
</P>
<P>
   He's been considered star material since his high school days in
New York, where he'd emigrated from Santo Domingo in the Dominican
Republic, and also where he'd spend many of his boyhood days making
the five-minute trip from his house to Yankee Stadium to watch Don
Mattingly and his colleagues at work.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland general manager John Hart remembers taking a trip to
Manhattan with scouting director Mickey White the week before the
June 1991 draft to watch a couple of prospects _ pitcher Allen
Watson and Ramirez.
</P>
<P>
   On the flight home, White told Hart, ``I saw my No. 1.''
</P>
<P>
   ```Which one?'' asked Hart.
</P>
<P>
   `I grew up in Pittsburgh,'' White answered in parable form. ``I
saw Roberto Clemente. I always said that if I got a chance to draft
Roberto Clemente, I would. Manny Ramirez is my Roberto Clemente.''
</P>
<P>
   He was in the majors for good by the time he was 22, and the
following year, he started racking up 30-homer, 100-RBI totals on a
veteran team that was in the process of claiming the American
League Central Division as its sovereign territory.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had the great good fortune to break in with a championship
club,'' says Hart. ``The first year, he hit No. 8. Then he was No.
7. Then he was No. 6. Then _ boom _ he was cleanup.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year became a portent when Ramirez cleaned up to the tune
of 45 homers and 145 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year he's built on that,'' says veteran hitting coach
Charlie Manuel. ``There isn't a pitch he can't handle. The many
things he worked on with his hitting started to come together.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez concurs. ``I'm always trying to work on something,'' he
says. ``Running the bases, playing the outfield, and hitting _
always hitting.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Ramirez's name never was associated with hard labor during
his early years. He was considered prodigiously talented and
equally lackadaisical.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember, he was learning to play baseball in the big
leagues,'' says Sandy Alomar. ``It's like being president and
running the White House at 22. He always worked hard.''
</P>
<P>
   The consensus that he didn't was a gross misconception, insist
his teammates. Ramirez's alleged carelessness masked the attitude
that has accounted for this season for the ages _ his carefreeness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never think about numbers or records or having men on
base,'' he says. ``I just go out and play. If I thought about it,
it probably wouldn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm surprised he even knew he was going for a record,'' says
Sandy Alomar. ``He doesn't worry about anything. He doesn't put any
pressure on himself. The whole world could be collapsing around him
and he'd say, `Oh well, we're all going to die.' World Series,
bases loaded _ to him, it's like playing in the backyard.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, there is one difference Lofton has noticed. ``When a guy's
in scoring position,'' says the center fielder, who bats leadoff
ahead of Vizquel and Roberto Alomar as Ramirez's setup men, ``his
face lights up.''
</P>
<P>
   Such expressions are undetectable to the general public. Polite
to an extreme, Ramirez makes diffidence look like egomania. Lofton
believes language could be a deterrent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Manny's English is there,'' he says. ``But he's afraid he
might say the wrong word.''
</P>
<P>
   He is particularly reclusive with the media, though his
visibility has increased along with his RBI figures. ``I've talked
to him about that,'' says Roberto Alomar. ``I tell him, `You've got
to talk to the media.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez maintains he has nothing against attention, and after
breaking Trosky's record last week, he even indulged his delirious
admirers with a curtain call.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes me proud because of the fans,'' he says. ``The way
they react, I'm very proud of the fans.''
</P>
<P>
   There he goes again, boomeranging compliments, still trying to
blend in with the crowd. And failing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-99 1137EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
