<DOCNO> NYT19991006.0105 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 11:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8126 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-ART-BOS &LR;      10-06 1535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX GAIN POST-SEASON ON TALENT, HARD WORK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Dave Jauss, the Red Sox first-base coach, is a city
guy. He rides the T to Fenway Park, lives in Boston year-round,
takes his kids to school, knows his way around the neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   When Dave Jauss puts his ear to Red Sox Nation, this is what he
hears:
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you how many times in the month of September, how
everybody, from the sisters at Mount Alvernia to the pizza delivery
boy to the cashier at Kiki's Quick Mart in Brighton Center, has
said, `Whatever you do this year, don't worry. We've had the
funnest time all summer. This is a great club.'
</P>
<P>
   ``These aren't the people reading the statistics every day, or
people who go to every game. This is from everyday walking around
Brighton and Watertown. They've just had a great summer watching
this club. It's quite a compliment to the type of players we had
this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Jimy Williams is sitting in the visiting manager's office in
Chicago's Comiskey Park. It is the day after the Red Sox put
themselves in the playoffs for the second straight season. He is
listening to someone tell him that this is a team impossible not to
enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the people in Boston, New England, like this team,''
he agrees. ``I think it's exemplified by the way they turned out to
watch 'em. It's a compliment to our fans. Maybe they're trying to
reward these kids.''
</P>
<P>
   It goes beyond an appreciation of winning. Red Sox fans always
support a winner. Something more is at work here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fans relate to hard-working, blue-collar type of players,''
says Mike Stanley. ``Even our superstars, they don't act like
superstars.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it is this: After a decade of divas _ the high-maintenance
soap operas involving talented and tempestuous types like Roger
Clemens and Mo Vaughn _ Sox fans were ready to embrace a group of
players not embarrassed to have a little dirt under their
fingernails.
</P>
<P>
   A bunch of guys who could just as easily stand out there in hard
hats as they do in batting helmets. Who might not have the pedigree
of some of their better-heeled rivals _ though Pedro Martinez and
Nomar Garciaparra would be royalty in any baseball crowd _ but who
like nothing more than showing up in the same neighborhoods,
privilege be damned.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're good,'' Garciaparra says defiantly, the night the Sox
clinched their wild-card spot.
</P>
<P>
   That they are, first and foremost. But they are endearing,
because whatever greatness has been allotted in the Boston
clubhouse, it has come in portions smaller than those meted out in
the Bronx or Cleveland, Atlanta or Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   But they have a manager who walks around with six baseballs
stuck in his back pockets, fungo bat at the ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can find people off the street who might work as hard and
put in as many hours as Jimy,'' Jauss says. ``But it's his
personality. Jimy is a very calm, straightforward guy who is easy
to get along with. His personality isn't anything you can write
down or another person can use. But he sets the tone.''
</P>
<P>
   A catcher, Jason Varitek, who absorbs more body blows than a
Mike Tyson sparring partner and cheerfully comes back for more. ``I
call him fearless,'' Williams says.
</P>
<P>
   A shortstop, Garciaparra, who on a daily basis takes dozens of
ground balls, committing to rote plays that are spectacular when
they take place in a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came up playing with Nolan (Ryan) and (Don) Mattingly,''
Stanley says of the Texas Hall of Famer and former Yankee captain
known as Donnie Baseball. ``Two of the greatest, two of the
hardest-working guys I've ever seen. Think of the impression they
made on young players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nomar is the same way, and he's still a young guy himself. But
think of the impact he makes.
</P>
<P>
   A left fielder, Troy O'Leary, who not only dedicates himself to
learning the vagaries of the Green Monster but becomes a better
hitter, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``It comes from playing every day and working beforehand and
taking pride in it,'' says Jauss, who works with the outfielder.
``The routine plays are always an out for O'Leary. That's very
important for all clubs, but especially our club.''
</P>
<P>
   A pitcher, Bret Saberhagen, who could be leading the life of a
millionaire yachtsman on Long Island but instead chooses the daily
torture of preparing his surgically reconstructed right shoulder to
tolerate more punishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a warrior,'' Williams says. ``He continues to go to
battle. What was he out for, 25 days, and he came back and pitched
that way? He could fit right into that MASH unit.''
</P>
<P>
   A first baseman, Brian Daubach, who nearly decided he had about
as much chance for a promotion as anybody else stuck in a dead-end
job, but refused to quit pushing until a door almost miraculously
opened.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe fans can relate to me a little bit,'' says Daubach, the
son of an Illinois mail carrier whose baseball shoes have collected
dust in places as far-flung as Virginia and Venezuela, ``because
there are a lot of people in Boston who work hard, and they haven't
had everything given to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Daubach smiled shyly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe they just feel sorry for me,'' he says, but he knows
better. ``These fans have been great to me, supporting us the whole
year.''
</P>
<P>
   According to general manager Dan Duquette, It is no accident
that these Red Sox embody virtues as old here as a Cotton Mather
sermon.
</P>
<P>
   ``A team reflects the personality of its manager,'' says
Duquette. ``Jimy created that kind of environment and recruits
those kinds of players to work in that environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what type of player he likes and the type of player
that can be integrated quickly into our operation. I think he likes
directed players, professional players who have defensive skills
that can support our pitching staff, players that have a certain
edge, a mental toughness.''
</P>
<P>
   Guys like Rod Beck, the closer who takes a plane coast-to-coast,
hops a cab at Logan that drops him off at the clubhouse door, puts
on a new uniform, introduces himself to his catcher, and
manufactures a save in his first night with the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, of course, deflects that kind of credit, because
pluggers don't take bows until the task at hand has been completed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do some little things,'' he says. ``Just this one game.
Let's go play this one game. Try to make it simple. Don't look at
it from the standpoint of the whole season, but one game. Then use
your skills and execute and help the team win this game. That's how
we focus it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we take a lot of pride in doing our best to execute
properly. They understand what their job is for that day. It might
change tomorrow, but today this is my responsibility and I'll try
to contribute that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim Wakefield comes to the ballpark as a starter, wakes up a
closer, returns as a long man, comes what he believes is full
circle back to starting, and is in the bullpen again for the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Happy about it? Of course not. Just as Stanley would like to
play more, or Reggie Jefferson, or the buried Jeff Frye. But do
they go public with their complaints? Rarely.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have personalities in here who bitch publicly,''
Stanley says.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, after a rained-out game in Chicago, called before most
players had arrived at the ballpark, Wakefield suggests the team
gather at a local watering hole to watch the Oakland game, knowing
that an A's loss means the Sox are in the playoffs. Most guys found
out about it from a message on their hotel answering machine.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-eight guys showed up.
</P>
<P>
   ``A night out in a city with great restaurants, great
entertainment places, and yet 28 guys came together for a common
goal,'' Stanley says. ``That tells you something about the
character of this team.''
</P>
<P>
   This, remember, is the same club that once lived by the slogan,
``25 cabs for 25 guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there was this. The night the Red Sox clinched their
playoff spot, they did so in the first game of a doubleheader.
There was bubbly on hand, plastic sheeting to protect street
clothes, a lineup card for the second game made up almost wholly of
reserves.
</P>
<P>
   Party time?
</P>
<P>
   Stanley shook his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were all there on the bench, for the first pitch of the
second game,'' he says. ``And when we lost that second game, we
were quiet afterward, out of respect for those guys who played.
Yeah, we had reason to celebrate, but how often do you see anybody
celebrate after a loss?''
</P>
<P>
   Don't confuse hard work with overachieving, Stanley says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who's overachieving?'' he asks. ``Troy is coming into his own.
Nomar is just being Nomar. 'Tek got a chance to play every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who's overachieving? We don't have any 30-home run or 130-,
140-RBI guys. But everybody's just going out and doing their
part.''
</P>
<P>
   That kind of approach hasn't gone unnoticed in the
neighborhoods, and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Boston,'' Jauss says, ``you usually have to win something
big to be embraced. This team has been embraced.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
