<HEADLINE>
VATICAN MAKES IT CLEAR: VIEWS ON SEX UNCHANGED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Vatican has reiterated its strong opposition to artificial
contraception and abortion, blasting UN programs that take an
``individualistic and permissive approach'' to sex.
</P>
<P>
   ``A permissive attitude to sexuality ruins the family, weakens
the responsibility of parents, goes against the good of children
and has a highly destabilizing effect on society as a whole,''
Vatican spokesman Joaquin Navarro-Valls said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Navarro-Valls released the statement to refute reports that the
Vatican had shifted its position on family planning issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``According to some organs of the press, the director of the
United Nations Population Fund (UNFPA), Dr. Nafis Sadik, expressed
the opinion on the occasion of the presentation of the 1999 World
Population Report in London on Sept. 22 that the Holy See no longer
opposes the techniques and policies of `family planning' propogated
by the UN agency,'' Navarro-Valls said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Holy See has not, in fact, changed its well known
position,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Navarro-Valls said the Vatican has accepted documents with the
words ``contraception,'' ``family planning,'' ``reproductive
rights,'' ``female-controlled methods,'' ``the widest possible
range of family planning services,'' ``new options,''
``underutilized methods'' and other terms referring to family
planning and the regulation of fertility.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, ``the Holy See's satisfaction over the consensus
reached in documents in which they are used cannot be interpreted
as a change in its noted position regarding `family planning'
services that do not respect the liberty of the couple, human
dignity and the human rights of those concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   Navarro-Valls said the Vatican does not support ``procreation at
any cost,'' and does ``recognize that sexuality is an important
aspect of personal identity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not difficult to understand that sexuality finds its
proper and deepest expression in a context of reciprocity,'' he
said. ``However, some programs promoted by the United Nations
inspire a vision of sexuality that does not give due consideration
to the dimension of reciprocity that is the expression of mutual
love and the making of a decision in the context of a stable
conjugal relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead,'' he said, ``they denote an individualistic and
permissive sexual comportment that corrodes an appropriate
comprehension of human dignity and the moral responsibility of
every person.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Religion Notes
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --An Evangelical Lutheran congregation in California has hired a
gay minister to be its pastor, opening itself up to possible
disciplinary action from the Evangelical Lutheran Church in
America.
</P>
<P>
   The University Lutheran Chapel of Berkeley, Calif. voted
unanimously to call the Reverend Jeff Johnson to the pulpit. The
chapel is both a parish ministry and the Lutheran campus ministry
for the University of California at Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson has been pastor of First United Lutheran Church in San
Francisco since his 1990 ordination. When he graduated from the
Pacific Lutheran Theological Seminary in Berkeley, Johnson was
regarded ineligible for placement in an Evangelical Lutheran
congregation because of church policy requiring a pledge of
celibacy from gay and lesbian pastors.
</P>
<P>
   When First United challenged the policy and named Johnson pastor
it was expelled from the national church.
</P>
<P>
   University Lutheran Chapel said it was fully aware of the
denomination's policy when it voted to hire Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our actions make it obvious that we disagree with this
policy,'' said Kathleen Gee, president of the chapel's council,
said in a statement. ``However, the chapel remains strongly
committed to serving as the campus ministry for UC-Berkeley and
supports the mission of the ELCA. We called Jeff Johnson because of
his gifts as a minister.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Comments may be sent to The Spiritual Life, c/o Diego Ribadeneira,
Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378; or via e-mail to
religion(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-99 1139EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
