<DOCNO> NYT19991006.0107 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 11:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8149 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-EGYPT-METRO-$ADV09-CO     10-06 0641
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EGYPT-METRO-$ADV09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SUBWAY UNDER THE NILE MAKES EFFICIENT TRAVEL BELOW CONGESTED
CAIRO
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (t) Travel categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sat., Oct. 9 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service(at) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt _ In this noisy, polluted and congested capital,
there is a place where the weary can seek peace and order _ the
subway.
</P>
<P>
   Underground, there are no donkey carts, blaring horns or
smog-belching buses. Instead, video monitors entertain riders as
they wait for punctual, air-conditioned trains.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, the first two train cars are reserved for women _ a nod
to Muslim conservatism. Riders, some women in head scarves, some
men in the traditional smock-like Galibiya and sandals, file neatly
through turnstiles onto the platform.
</P>
<P>
   This spring, Cairo's Metro snaked it's way under the Nile River,
enhancing a project worthy of the history around it. The new route
connects Giza and Cairo, a metropolitan area of 15 million people.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call it, in Egypt, the fourth pyramid,'' said rider Imad
Galal. ``It's a very daring project.''
</P>
<P>
   Galal, a 29-year-old vice president of a building materials
company, has a Fiat Uno but uses the subway because it cuts his
commuting time in half.
</P>
<P>
   The $7 billion Metro is the only subway in Africa or the Middle
East. The first line opened in 1987 and it has expanded to now
cover about 35 miles and 46 stations.
</P>
<P>
   The subway handles more than 1.7 million riders a day, providing
some relief to a dense metropolitan area.
</P>
<P>
   The streets of Cairo are notorious for the donkey carts, hobbled
buses and freestyle driving manners. Stoplights are optional,
traffic police fight for attention and lane lines are completely
ignored.
</P>
<P>
   Safety is largely maintained through a cacophony of honking and
the fact that traffic moves very slowly. The usual
unair-conditioned taxi or bus ride of 10 miles can take an hour in
stifling heat, leaving the rider with a face-full of sweaty grime.
</P>
<P>
   Not so in the Metro. On the new line below the river, silver
trains _ Japanese-made with French parts _ offer air-conditioned
efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   To make sure the Metro keeps its Egyptian flavor, stations are
tiled in local motifs. One shows pharaonic musicians and another is
decorated with a large ear and nose, for a famous ear, nose and
throat doctor who once worked in the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Near the Cairo Museum, a station named after slain Egyptian
President Anwar Sadat includes encased Egyptian artifacts.
</P>
<P>
   Most Egyptians use the train to commute. Special discounts for
students or government workers reduce the fares to pennies. But,
the train could also be useful for tourists seeking to get to the
Cairo Museum or Cairo's old Muslim and Christian quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, plans call for a line to the Cairo airport, now a
hot hour's drive from downtown.
</P>
<P>
   In the Metro headquarters, pinched between two highways always
packed with cars, there's a mixture of high- and low-technology.
</P>
<P>
   Computer panels monitor the trains' progress, but officials
still work in non-descript, linoleum-tiled offices with clunky
one-line telephones.
</P>
<P>
   And the bureaucracy is typically cumbersome. A reporter seeking
to take pictures of the subway can wait for hours and will
eventually be escorted by eight security officers.
</P>
<P>
   But, Mabrouk Abdel'azim, chief of operations for the new line
under the Nile, said the system itself has few delays. The only
problem, he said, is that when there are snags, riders do not file
away to taxis or buses as quickly as they might in Paris or New
York. They simply wait.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here, they insist on using the Metro,'' Abdel'azim said.
``They know it is the best system.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-99 1149EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991006.0108 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 11:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8150 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i BC-EGYPT-METRO-$ADV09-CO     10-06 0641
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EGYPT-METRO-$ADV09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SUBWAY UNDER THE NILE MAKES EFFICIENT TRAVEL BELOW CONGESTED
CAIRO
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (t) Travel categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sat., Oct. 9 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service(at) 
<TEXT>
