<SLUG> BC-APPLES-SIDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Apple growing season in Miami Valley met with mixed results
 &HT;    By Mark Fisher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Americans rate apples on crispness first,
juiciness second and flavor third, according to authors Frank
Browning and Sharon Silva in An Apple Harvest (Ten Speed Press,
$19.95, due in bookstores this month).
</P>
<P>
   In the 1999 growing season, local apple growers were rewarded
with at least two out of three, and perhaps three out of three, of
the important characteristics, depending on how much precious
moisture they received.
</P>
<P>
   The late-summer drought hit some orchards hard, local growers
say, reducing the size of the apple crop in two ways: smaller
apples and fewer apples per tree. But those orchards that enjoyed a
refreshing bath at a few opportune times when scattered showers
danced through the Miami Valley, or which had access to water
through irrigation, enjoyed a banner year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're picking 3-inch (diameter) Jonathans and 4-inch Cortlands
off of our irrigated orchards, and that's pretty good size,'' said
Bob Ullrich, general manager of Hidden Valley Fruit Farms in Warren
County.
</P>
<P>
   But apples from non-irrigated orchards are smaller, and overall
yield is down, Ullrich said.
</P>
<P>
   But the drought giveth as it taketh away: The flavor of the 1999
apples are ripe and sweet. The late-summer heat pushed the sugar
content of the fruit high, while the lack of moisture drained a bit
of the juiciness out of some apples, concentrating the sweet
flavors. Locally, a bushel of apples is selling for between $20 and
$28.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even the Granny Smiths are sweet,'' said Darke County orchard
owner Winston Brumbaugh, referring to the firm, greenish-gold and
usually very tart apple.
</P>
<P>
   That sweetness, Brumbaugh said, ``just makes the apple cider
that much better.'' And there are plenty of smaller apples
available to make cider.
</P>
<P>
   Both growers expressed concern about the drought's impact on
orchards, which need to replenish themselves to prepare for the
severe Ohio winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm more afraid of what could happen next year,'' Brumbaugh
said. ``I've never gone through a drought quite like this before.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
