<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-APPLES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Loyal to the core
 &HT;    By Mark Fisher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Hilda Mobley was a woman on a mission.
</P>
<P>
   Striding purposefully into Hidden Valley Fruit Farms on Ohio 48
in Warren County late on a hot September afternoon, Mobley knew
what she wanted _ Gala apples _ and she would accept no
substitutes.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that Hidden Valley has no less than 52 varieties of
apples, or that she'd have to wait a while for the farm market
folks to track down the apples and fill her order. Mobley is loyal
to her variety and proud of it.
</P>
<P>
   She even remembers the first time she bit into a Gala apple. It
was at a fruit stand on Wilmington Pike a decade ago, and the woman
who offered the sample of the then-brand-new variety told her,
``Once you taste these, you'll never go back to any other kind of
apple.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And she was right,'' said Mobley, a former Kettering resident
who now lives in Butler County. ``Even my kids are now hooked on
Galas.''
</P>
<P>
   As fierce as Mobley's allegiance is to Galas, other customers
are equally as enthusiastic and loyal to their varieties, be they
Melrose, Fuji, Cortland, Braeburn, Granny Smith or Golden
Delicious. We in the Miami Valley are kind of funny that way.
Growing up in Beavercreek in the 1960s, if it wasn't a Jonathan
apple, it wasn't allowed into our home.
</P>
<P>
   Still, subtle taste shifts do occur, nudged along by the
occasional revolution. New Zealand apple growers shook up the
American apple industry in the 1970s when they pioneered the firm,
mouth-puckering Granny Smith apple. Since then, other varieties
have been developed, including Gala, Jonagold and Gingergold, along
with two of the most recent arrivals, Mutsu (from Japan) and
Honeycrisp (American).
</P>
<P>
   ``Apple tastes are always changing. The younger generation
doesn't want Red Delicious anymore,'' said Winston Brumbaugh, who
grows 26 varieties on 20 acres of orchards outside Arcanum in Darke
County and helps supply apples to Fulton Fruit Farms in Miami
County.
</P>
<P>
   Hidden Valley planted Honeycrisp trees within the past five
years, along with other relatively new varieties such as Braeburn
and Fuji, ``and now we're getting more customer requests for
them,'' said Bob Ullrich, Hidden Valley's general manager.
</P>
<P>
   Ullrich points to a sales flier from a Michigan nursery that
lists an ``Inventory of Varieties Budded for 2000.'' It offers 76
apple varieties of buds (46 available in trees) on seven types of
root stock.
</P>
<P>
   Apple growers attend seminars and conventions to hear about new
varieties on the horizon to make sure they've got what customers
will want a couple years from now, Ullrich said.
</P>
<P>
   A few years back, Ullrich apparently made the right call on a
variety called Gala. At least, Hilda Mobley thinks so.
</P>
<P>
   A closer look at apples
</P>
<P>
   Variety Eating Pies Flavor/Texture
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Gala Excellent NA Very sweet
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  McIntosh Excellent Excellent Spicy, tender
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Cortland Excellent Excellent Tart, crisp
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Jonathan Excellent Excellent Tart, very crisp
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Mutsu Excellent Fair Very sweet, juicy, crisp
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Red Delicious Excellent Poor Rich, sweet, firm
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Melrose Excellent Excellent Sweet, firm
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Rome Beauty Good Excellent Mild, crisp
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Fuji Excellent Excellent Semi-tart
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Granny Smith Excellent Excellent Very firm, tart and juicy
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
