A8174 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-ANTS07-COX     10-06 0484
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WIMPY AFRICAN ANTS SHUN MEAN NEIGHBORS
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Strange behavior by a species of ant that lives in
trees on the savannas of east Africa has been explained: The
insects are dedicated isolationists.
</P>
<P>
   Biologists have known for years that the ants, one of four
distinct species that live in thorned acacia trees, have the
bizarre practice of systematically and severely pruning the trees
they inhabit.
</P>
<P>
   But until now the motive was known only to the ants.
</P>
<P>
   The behavior does not benefit the tree. In fact, the ants are so
diligent
</P>
<P>
   in the business of cutting off and discarding new growth that
the trees not only become stunted, but sterile as well.
</P>
<P>
   Reporting in the current issue of Nature, biologists at the
University of California at Davis, the University of Oregon and the
Mpala Research Center in Nanyuki, Kenya, say they have figured out
what's going on.
</P>
<P>
   The ants are attempting to keep the limbs of the trees they
inhabit from growing out and touching those of surrounding trees.
The other trees are occupied by more ferocious ants that, if given
the chance, will come over and evict the pruners.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers created access between neighboring trees. Then,
using statistical techniques, they determined that in subsequent
encounters with invaders, pruning ants had up to an 80 percent
chance of being defeated and evicted from their host tree.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're isolationists,'' Maureen Stanton, a professor of
ecology at UC-Davis, said of the pruning ants. ``They modify the
environment in such a way to minimize encounters with dominant
competitors.''
</P>
<P>
   The species that prunes its trees into sterility, is known as
``Crematogaster nigriceps.''
</P>
<P>
   All four species of ant make nests inside hollow, nut-like nodes
that form at the base of the trees' numerous thorns. The stinging
ants swarm by the thousands over browsing antelopes and goats and
help protect the tree, said Stanton. A goat that gets a snootfull
of ants will avoid their acacia tree for up to a month, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Such an arrangement, in which distinct species such as an ant
and a tree both benefit from an association, is known to biologists
as mutualism. The ant has a place to house workers and nest young
and the tree has a defender from browsing animals. In the case of
C. nigriceps, the mutualistic relationship has been
</P>
<P>
   distorted because of the ant's vulnerability to its dominant
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   But the web of life is even more complex than that, because the
pruner ants are dependent in an ironic way on the very neighbors
they fear. If left to themselves on the savanna, they eventually
would render all the acacia trees sterile and destroy their own
habitat.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're cheaters,'' said Stanton.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
