<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART EXHIBIT HAS A CONSTITUTIONAL HUE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ It wasn't the most compelling artistic
event in the 133-year life of the Canfield Casino. According to
local legend, that occurred around 1930, when a gloriously
inebriated Bing Crosby got busted for a performance art exercise in
public urination off the front steps.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the event the other night was notable enough. In this
Albany suburb, population 23,000, any gathering of 800 people not
involving race horses rates as an occasion. In this case, the
occasion was a fund-raiser to repair Spit and Spat. Those are local
nicknames for the two Carrara marble statues that reign over the
fountain in the northeast corner of Saratoga Springs' gracious
Congress Park.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, somebody took a steel rod and smacked up those
two statues of Tritons, Greek sea gods, that adorn the fountain.
Some 16-year-old kids are charged with felonies, but the statues
need about $20,000 of restoration work. The city also wants a
surveillance system to protect all the statuary in the 33-acre
park.
</P>
<P>
   State Senate Majority Leader Joe Bruno represents Saratoga
Springs. As a powerful lawmaker, he showed up with a blown-up check
for 20 grand to cover the repair work. Fund-raiser ticket sales and
a silent auction brought in enough for a camera system.
</P>
<P>
   Donors seemed to have a great time partying amid the casino's
19th-century elegance. What was interesting, though _ considering
this gigantic flap over the ``Sensation'' exhibit at the Brooklyn
Museum of Art and the firm conviction of so many in the arts
community that ordinary folks just don't care enough about art _ is
that this whole affair was rooted in the premise that art is indeed
important and deserving of broad public support.
</P>
<P>
   Understand this: The Brooklyn battle isn't really about art.
It's about the First Amendment. And even though he milked this mess
shamelessly as he eyes a run for the U.S. Senate, New York Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani finally has begun talking rationally about his
decision to withhold city funds to support display space for an
artwork seen by many Catholics as an affront to their faith.
</P>
<P>
   At issue in the ``Sensation'' show is a collage by Chris Ofili,
a British artist of Nigerian origin. It's an image of the Virgin
Mary as an African fertility goddess, complete with lacquered
clumps of elephant manure and 120 photos of female genitalia
clipped from porno magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Ofili claims to be a believing Catholic. He claims to have
harbored no intent to offend with this work. Take him at his word,
and it doesn't really matter. The problem is that any artist's
intent is irrelevant. We're all supposed to make of art what we
will. Many see this work as flagrant sacrilege _ none more so than
Giuliani, who denounced it as sick and twisted.
</P>
<P>
   The issue here, however, is not the mayor as art critic. Any
community looking to politicians for artistic guidance is a
community in direct and dire cultural jeopardy. No, the real issue
here is more subtle.
</P>
<P>
   The First Amendment protects religious freedom just as it
protects free artistic expression. Ofili's collage raises this
touchy legal question: What's the duty of the custodian of public
funds when that money ends up subsidizing what many people can
reasonably interpret as an artistic attack on their faith?
</P>
<P>
   On national television over the weekend, the mayor finally
stopped bellowing and started explaining himself. Yes, he said,
government must permit free artistic expression. But it also must
maintain neutrality toward religion. It can't sponsor religion _
through school prayer, for example _ and it can't finance attacks
on anybody's religious faith.
</P>
<P>
   In short, what we see in Brooklyn is a classic case of First
Amendment rights in conflict. That's why a federal judge is now in
the picture. And should be.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
