<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY STAR BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of Thursday,
Oct. 7. If you have any questions, please call The Star's News Desk
at (816) 234-4720.
</P>
<P>
   WHITE: Sen. Sam Brownback is upset about comments from President
Clinton saying that the failure of Judge Ronnie White's nomination
was due to race. Kevin Murphy and Steve Kraske.
</P>
<P>
   TEACH: The opening of charter schools has put the KC School
District in a bigger staffing quandary than usual. There's always
the problem of kids who move over the summer and who don't tell the
district until they show up for the first day of school in a new
place. But this year, the district had to guess how many kids would
defect to charters. It guessed wrong, leaving the district short of
teachers in many cases. As many as 40 or 50 students reportedly are
crowded into some district classrooms. Van Horn and Southeast high
schools have been particularly hard hit by students who didn't want
to attend Westport High after it converted to a charter. Trying for
a photo. Phil O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
   FAR: The state probation and parole's handling of Michael L.
Farris will be the subject of a hearing today in Jefferson City.
Farris cut off his electronic monitor and state probation officials
took nearly a month to get a request of an arrest warrant. While
Farris was on the loose, he allegedly killed a 76-year-old Kansas
City woman. State Sen. Ronnie DePasco will hold the hearing. The
story also will detail electronic monitors. A judge in New Mexico
got the idea for them from a comic book. They've been around for 20
years and have worked well. Studies show that few commit crimes
while wearing them. However, officials say if defendants cut them
off, authorities must move immediately to arrest the offenders.
Matt Campbell and Joe Lambe. 30. Graphic.
</P>
<P>
   CHIP: Since new state programs started in the past year, more
than 100,000 Missouri and Kansas children who previously lacked
health insurance have gotten coverage, and officials are
campaigning in creative ways to enroll thousands more. There's
another big signup day on Wednesday. It's all part of the nation's
largest single expansion of health insurance for children in 30
years. But enrollment in St. Louis lags far behind Kansas City.
Some Kansas families refuse to enroll because they don't want the
taint of welfare. And enrollment doesn't guarantee that children
actually have access to health care. Lack of dentists is a sore
spot in both states. Photos. Donna McGuire. 45.
</P>
<P>
   VIOL: Gov. Mel Carnahan releases the report from the Governor's
Task Force on School Violence. Will Sentell.
</P>
<P>
   FORCE: The National Association for Civilian Oversight of Law
Enforcement conference in KC features a program today on the use of
deadly force. Mary Sanchez.
</P>
<P>
   PLAQUE: The Springfield Landmarks Board will take up the issue
of whether to build a plaque on the town square to remember a 1906
racial lynching. It's the first public debate on an issue that has
drawn mixed opinions. Some say it's important to remember, others
don't want to reopen old wounds. Oscar Avila. 10.
</P>
<P>
   GOULD. Scientist Stephen Jay Gould holds an afternoon press
conference and then speaks tonight in Lawrence. Some creationists
have quoted Gould as supporting their position; we'll see what he
says. (After the Kansas board voted to downplay evolution, Gould
wrote that teaching science without evolution was like teaching
American history without Lincoln. Kate Beem and Diane Carroll.
Photo. 20.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS BUDGET OFFERS:
</P>
<P>
   PSYCH _ The pin that dropped this week for Sprint employees
might well have been from an emotional grenade, for all the
percussive fallout. As word of MCI WorldCom's acquisition exploded
in Kansas City, Sprint workers accustomed to constant challenge
braced for tremors unlike those felt before. Brush up your resumes.
Get ready for at least two years of roiling management and benefits
changes. Understand you're experiencing grief, as if a family
member died. And be prepared for promised synergies that fail to
synergize. By Diane Stafford
