<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PREGAMEPRAYER-TEXAS-1000(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT RULING SILINCING PREGAME PRAYER ROUSING PASSIONS IN RURAL
TEXAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BARRY SHLACHTER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   STEPHENVILLE, Texas _ At many rural Texas high schools, a prayer
before a weekend football game has been as much a part of the
autumn ritual as exuberant cheerleaders, die-hard boosters and
homecoming queens.
</P>
<P>
   But a recent ruling by the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
silences school-sponsored prayer at the games. The court action,
some local officials and pastors say, runs contrary to the deeply
held religious beliefs shared by many people in these Bible-belt
communities.
</P>
<P>
   Some schools openly defy the ruling, others use imaginative
maneuvers to get around it, and all bemoan the interference of
government in their Friday night rites. School board members find
themselves trying to protect their districts from costly lawsuits
while struggling to respond to constituents' demands.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's constantly on my mind,'' said Sid Miller, a member of the
Stephenville school board, which this season stopped the
long-standing practice of a pregame invocation. Before one recent
game, school officials literally pulled the plug on students trying
to rig a loudspeaker to amplify their prayers. Students had
succeeded at an earlier game.
</P>
<P>
   ``My phone constantly rings,'' Miller said of constituents
complaining about the court-ordered ban. ``It's a big issue in our
community and a lot of people are upset by it.''
</P>
<P>
   Few large urban districts continue the practice, so the court
decision hardly mattered to them. But many suburban high schools
and most rural ones saw a tradition as entrenched as Friday night
lights suddenly jettisoned.
</P>
<P>
   Not all are capitulating.
</P>
<P>
   A random survey shows that high schools in Archer City, Albany,
Brady, Breckenridge, Celina, Crawford, Klondike, Monahans, Mexia,
Ozona and Wall are among those defying the federal court ruling and
allowing pregame prayers.
</P>
<P>
   Some have gone to elaborate lengths to skirt the ruling, which
came in February, but which took effect when high school football
season began. The 5th Circuit, based in New Orleans, handles
appeals from Mississippi, Louisiana and Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not trying to be another Republic of Texas group,'' said
Clifton L. Stephens, superintendent of the Monahans-Wickett-Pyotte
schools. ``We're not trying to be rebellious. We're just a little
West Texas town and we think prayer is appropriate. It's important
to us.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no intention of rubbing the federal government's face
in it,'' Stephens said, adding that, should anyone be offended or
complain, the district ``will go to `Plan B,' '' which he said
hasn't been formulated.
</P>
<P>
   So far, there have been no complaints about the prayer, which is
student-led and nonsectarian and contains no proselytizing.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the first three games, we got applause from both sides of
the field,'' Stephens said.
</P>
<P>
   Some school administrators said they find themselves at odds
with their elected board and the community it represents.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the last meeting, my board voted in school-sponsored prayer
at games, 6-1, over my recommendation,'' said Scott A. King,
superintendent in Klondike, a 240-student Northeast Texas district,
which fields a six-man football team. ``I think it's illegal and
shows a lack of respect for somebody's religion. But that doesn't
bother a lot of people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am trying to protect the community and the board. Now I look
like some kind of atheist.''
</P>
<P>
   Other districts, such as Rockwall and Sonora, have substituted a
``moment of silence.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's close to a prayer, but it isn't a prayer, per se, because
that would offend Jewish people or Muslims, although we don't have
any of those in our community,'' said Bill Harlan, Sonora's
superintendent. ``It's sad that a court in Louisiana can tell us
what we can't do in Sonora, Texas. It does bother me what some
liberal court justice can do.
</P>
<P>
   ``But who knows? It's on appeal. I know Gov. Bush and other
Southern governors have petitioned to have struck it down.''
</P>
<P>
   In Coleman, authorities allow students and parents to assemble
at a flagpole near an end zone for prayers before kickoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not over the public address system,'' Superintendent
Anthony ``Skip'' Casey said. ``We didn't want to quit praying.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``moment of silence'' in the West Texas town of Andrews
isn't so quiet.
</P>
<P>
   The void is filled by radios tuned to a local AM station, KACT,
which at that precise moment broadcasts a prayer that has been
taped earlier by students.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not so much an end-run around the law _ it's within the
law,'' City Councilman Robert Zap told the Lubbock
Avalanche-Journal.
</P>
<P>
   Dissenting districts are not without their supporters.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
<P>
   Houston lawyer Kelly Coghlan has sent an advice packet to every
school district in Texas, suggesting that a pregame
``solemnization'' _ a statement of reflection _ would not violate
the 5th Circuit ruling. The Dallas-based Liberty Legal Institute,
the Texas Justice Foundation and the Rutherford Institute are
offering similar counsel.
</P>
<P>
   But the Texas Association of School Boards said districts
``really need to comply with the law,'' said Barbara Williams, an
association spokeswoman. ``A moment of silence, if it is not
religiously motivated, will pass muster.''
</P>
<P>
   Some districts have implemented their own creative approaches in
an attempt to satisfy both the courts and the community.
</P>
<P>
   Prayer happens at Hamilton High School home games, but it isn't
illegal, insisted Superintendent Gene Sheets.
</P>
<P>
   The Hamilton school board has taken what Sheets calls a
``neutral stance,'' leaving it up to students whether to pray. The
students can use the public-address system, but must state that the
prayer is not endorsed by the district, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at nearby Lorena and the Panhandle's White Deer said
they also leave prayer up to students.
</P>
<P>
   In Alto, 31 miles north of Lufkin, ``school-sponsored'' prayer
has been replaced by ``community-led'' prayer, Superintendent Lloyd
Worley said. Before home games, fans say the Lord's Prayer in
unison, Worley said.
</P>
<P>
   In Santa Fe, the district near Galveston from which the 5th
Circuit ruling stemmed, officials decided to allow a ``message
solemnization,'' with no prayer or reference to a deity.
</P>
<P>
   But the student elected to give the message, Marian Ward,
complained that the rule violated her freedom of speech. She
secured a temporary restraining order, then said a prayer at a home
game.
</P>
<P>
   The 10-day order has expired and U.S. District Judge Sim Lake of
Houston is expected to decide this week whether to renew it, said
Superintendent Richard Ownby.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 24, a 17-year-old senior at Northwest High in Justin
slipped into the press box before a game against Mineral Wells and
broadcast a prayer. District officials indicated that the student
was disciplined, but declined to disclose the punishment.
</P>
<P>
   Some administrators say allowing a religious invocation sends a
message to students that scofflaws are acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't want to say it was all right for the school district
to break laws, but you students couldn't break rules,'' Casey said,
explaining why his Coleman district won't allow use of the
public-address system for prayer.
</P>
<P>
   Christians who insist on the right to pregame prayer might be
surprised to find they've opened the door to prayer from such
faiths as Islam or Buddhism, said Bill Tillman, a former professor
of ethics at Southwestern Baptist Theological Seminary and now a
coordinator of theological education at the Baptist General
Convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really think we Baptists as a whole fail to see the cultural
changes going on, the extraordinary influx of other religious
traditions,'' Tillman said.
</P>
<P>
   The religious scholar said he finds pregame prayers potentially
offensive to non-Christians and questions the appropriateness of
the venue.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Jim Warmerdam of Stephenville's Grove Street Baptist
Church said he doesn't see it that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people are offended when the name of Jesus is mentioned,
well there's a lot of people offended when his name isn't
mentioned,'' Warmerdam said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating that one or two people can dictate to a whole
community or an entire nation how they would like their lives led.
Christian people are tired of being swept back into their churches,
not free to openly acknowledge the God that has given us our
freedoms. It seems hypocritical that they can have a prayer
breakfast in the White House, but we can't have a prayer before a
football game.''
</P>
<P>
   In Stephenville, several residents said they would risk arrest
for the right to pray.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one can sit there and tell my child she can't pray,'' said
Mike Dees, a Stephenville retailer. ``That's her constitutional
right. If she wants to go down onto the football field and pray,
I'll be right behind her and willing to go to jail for it.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the school district's attorneys met with a group of
Stephenville ministers and asked if the rhetoric and confrontation
could be toned down.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to do the best we can to defuse the situation,''
said Richard Don Coan, one of the lawyers who said the district is
engaged in a difficult balancing act.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
