<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTER-HELPLINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUTTING OLD HOME VIDEOS ON CD-ROM CAN BE DONE, BUT IT SURE WON'T BE
CHEAP
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clil~us)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I just got a writeable CD-ROM drive. Now I'd like to take
some old home videos and put them on CD-ROM. What do I need to do
this?
</P>
<P>
   A: Unless your computer already has what's necessary, you're
going to have to make another hardware investment, and probably
pick up some new software as well.
</P>
<P>
   You will need a video card that can accept video images, or an
add-on video capture card. Most of these come with at least
rudimentary versions of video editing software. If you want to get
fancy, you'll probably have to buy the full version.
</P>
<P>
   Some computers come with a special port that is excellent for
capturing video, called FireWire or iLink. With this, you can
bypass the video card and take the images in directly, but your
camera must have one of these ports as well.
</P>
<P>
   Among the video cards that include video-in capabilities are
3dfx's new Voodoo3 3500 TV; ATI Technologies' All-in-Wonder 128;
and Matrox's G200 TV. All of these are available in both AGP and
PCI versions, except for the Voodoo3, which comes in AGP only.
</P>
<P>
   There are several products out there that will augment an
existing graphics card if you don't want to replace your current
model. For example, Iomega makes a device called the Buz that
connects to a PC or a Mac. (Note that Iomega recently said it would
quit distributing the PC version via retail, but you may still be
able to find some in stores.)
</P>
<P>
   You'll also need software if the package that comes with your
hardware isn't adequate. Try Ulead's Video Studio 3.0, MGI
Software's VideoWave II or, if you're really serious (and
affluent), Adobe Premiere 5.0.
</P>
<P>
   How much moolah are we talking about here? The video cards with
capture capabilities will run in the $200-$300 price range; add-on
boards will be a little less. The software will start in the $100
price range, and go up to well over $600.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have a strange problem with Outlook Express 5. When I type
a line of text, it looks fine. It's in a normal font. When I type
the next line, it's much smaller. Then, when I type the third line,
it's back to normal. What can I do to stop this from happening?
</P>
<P>
   A: This is a known bug in Outlook Express, and it's easily
fixable.
</P>
<P>
   Click on the Tools menu, then click on Options. Go to the Read
tab, and then click on Fonts. Choose the Medium setting, and click
OK.
</P>
<P>
   You can find more information on this bug at the Microsoft
Knowledge Base at support.microsoft.com/support/c.asp. Enter
Outlook Express as the product you want to search on, and use the
keywords ``font changes.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Sometimes when I get an e-mail on America Online and it's
supposed to have an attachment, it comes through all garbled, with
a note that it's a MIME file. What is this, and how can I view the
attachment?
</P>
<P>
   A: This is a function of the way AOL's e-mail works. MIME, or
Multipurpose Internet Mail Extensions, is a way of converting a
file into a format _ a process called encoding _ that can be sent
via the Net.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, AOL's e-mail software doesn't always handle the
decoding of these attachments properly. Instead of getting the file
as it is intended _ say, as a JPG picture, a word processing
document or a program _ it comes through with a .MIM extension.
</P>
<P>
   It is suchue, in fact, that AOL has set up an area on its
Web site describing the problem and how to fix it. Use the keyword
MIME to read more about it.
</P>
<P>
   What you will have to do is grab a program that can translate
the .MIM attachment into the file it is supposed to be. A list of
programs is available at the MIME area on AOL.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-10-01-99 1701EDT &QL;
</P>
