<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   &HT;    Don't abandon logic when illogical problems crop up
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Most of my friends expect computers to be different
from the rest of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   They expect computers to follow logical laws. Computers are not
_ uh _ computerlike. Instead, they are catlike.
</P>
<P>
   When something is wrong with a computer _ at work or at home _
most of us look for an answer. But computers are not as reliable as
the sun and the moon or even the guy who sprays your home for bugs.
</P>
<P>
   Keep in mind that computers are magic. The programs that perform
your tasks are no more than a bunch of numbers. The computer chip
is no more than a hunk of silicon, treated with chemicals (they
call it doping the chip). So all this magic is performed by a
glasslike substance that is being fed a series of zeros and ones.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder computers can be contrary, refusing to perform some
routine task or freezing up like a pond in the winter.
</P>
<P>
   If you were dealing with a machine of logic, you'd figure that
the notion would be to find the problem and fix it. Not so. Not
when it comes to one-time glitches.
</P>
<P>
   But the most difficult thing for a computer novice to do is
nothing. Most of us can create real problems by trying to fix what
is essentially a one-time occurrence. Sure, if your computer
continues to exhibit the problem, then it needs examining. But the
best thing most of us can do with these one-time problems is to
just restart the computer if necessary and keep going.
</P>
<P>
   With real problems, it's a different story. But some of the
methods of diagnosing the problem involve the same sort of
common-sense attitude. Today we'll take a look at some of the ways
to gain some sort of control over your computer when it decides to
take a vacation from reality.
</P>
<P>
   The first suspect _ when you have a problem _ relies on the fact
that computers can hate change worse than the stodgiest middle-aged
person.
</P>
<P>
   So when a problem pops up, think back and mentally review any
change you've made _ adding software, changing the settings in
Windows, downloading a file, adding a new computer accessory _
between the time the computer worked correctly and the time the
problem popped up.
</P>
<P>
   You may have to uninstall (I hate the way computerese has
changed the language, but that's a topic for another day) the
offending program, or remove the new device to find out if it is
the culprit.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the trouble with tracing the cause of a problem is that
_ just as in life _ sometimes a lot of changes happen at once. So
you have to eliminate each potential suspect until you find the one
causing the problem.
</P>
<P>
   In about half the computer problems you face, you'll fix the
problem that way. You find the trouble spot and then either install
it again to find _ magically it seems _ that all is well, or
contact the manufacturer for help.
</P>
<P>
   But sometimes you'll do all that and your computer will still
refuse to talk to you, just like a cranky child. For many of you,
that's the time to seek outside help. But the more adventurous can
take the next step _ reinstalling Windows.
</P>
<P>
   If you've never done that, you may have all sorts of fears that
you'll be starting over and have to reinstall each program that you
own.
</P>
<P>
   But when you reinstall Windows without removing the old copy,
all your settings, all your programs, stay the same. (Be sure you
use a regular copy of Windows, not one of those CDs that come with
some computers that return them to the same condition that they
were in when you unpacked the box.)
</P>
<P>
   What I'm trying to say today is that, even if your computer
isn't logical, you still should be. Leave one-time problems alone
and _ when big problems come along _ check out the most logical
suspects first.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-10-04-99 1127EDT &QL;
</P>
