<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   &HT;    Civil War Experience offers expert tutoring
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ War interests me only in terms of the way it can draw
out the best and worst of its individual participants; the only
``good'' war I know of is the made-up and idealistic one I once
heard a young woman refer to as ``World War Eleven.''
</P>
<P>
   That was essentially a battle between the good to fairly good
folks and the shady to downright evil people, and the good guys
won. None of the other wars in my ken have that degree of nobility.
</P>
<P>
   The American Civil War, or the War Between the States, if you
insist, was our own contribution to the record of human savagery, a
bloody domestic dispute whose repercussions may never go away. Not
being a Southerner by birth or heritage, its conduct has never been
of great interest.
</P>
<P>
   I am, however, surrounded by friends who dwell on every detail
of every battle, who will argue for hours over which battle might
have had a different outcome had this blockhead or that ignoramus
only sent his troops hither instead of yon.
</P>
<P>
   To them I recommend a CD-ROM from Southpeak Interactive and the
History Channel called The Civil War Experience. It is a lavishly
produced teaching instrument which, while probably too elementary
for the died-in-the-wool amateur historian, should be more than
enough to get any student through this regrettable portion of our
history with ease.
</P>
<P>
   Civil War Experience is expertly produced. It follows the
current trend of providing only a small manual, but navigation is
so intuitive that I haven't even looked at the instructions.
</P>
<P>
   It provides the student with a basic grasp of the political
events that led up to the war, the condition of the nation and its
people at the time, and the personalities involved in the outbreak
of hostilities.
</P>
<P>
   For the strategic enthusiast, each major battle is presented
with the major troop movements animated on a battle map, with a
detailed spoken and written description. All the odd little corners
of the conflict, such as the ethnic regiments and the Zouaves,
along with the daily lives of Union and Confederate soldiers, their
equipment and logistics, is presented.
</P>
<P>
   There are hundreds of photographs to illustrate every element
and a very well-organized time line of the war, although it is
approached directly only by time and not by event. This is
mitigated, however, by a search function that will sift through the
entire CD-ROM for keywords.
</P>
<P>
   The only major segment of the program that might be questioned
is the ``Eyewitness'' portion, in which someone with a suitable
accent reads a paragraph about an event written by someone who
participated in it. Since the writer obviously isn't doing the
reading, it could just as well have been presented by text alone,
saving space for more information.
</P>
<P>
   A search for the word ``cannon,'' for instance, produces five
major hits, each of which has several subtexts.
</P>
<P>
   The program also provides plenty of good links to the Web _ the
search function can be aimed at either the CD or the Web _
including a year's membership in a Civil War subscription site.
</P>
<P>
   The bells and whistles are just fine, too, with a lot of rebel
yelling and musket firing at the right points, and ``original''
music largely consisting of medleys from popular tunes of the time.
</P>
<P>
   Also, for the kids and the bored, a couple of simple games that
have almost nothing to do with the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-10-04-99 1127EDT &QL;
</P>
