</HEADLINE>
 
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   &HT;    A modern touch for Williamsburg
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Colonial Williamsburg, an aristocratic slice of the
past preserved for future generations, is getting modern on us. The
southeastern Virginia tourist attraction is letting people plan
their vacations from its Web site, colonialwilliamsburg.org.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Plan Your Visit'' section lets people choose from
pre-planned tour options or create their own. Visitors can also
look at hotel and restaurant information for the Colonial
Williamsburg area, including seasonal rates and pictures of the
rooms.
</P>
<P>
   A map feature lets you move a cursor over an area and then watch
an image of the site pop up.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site still has its old features, including directions,
advice on where to sleep, eat and shop, and ticket and handicapped
access information.
</P>
<P>
   Colonial Williamsburg is run by the Colonial Williamsburg
Foundation, a nonprofit group. Williamsburg is about 150 miles
southeast of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   PAGER ANNOUNCES SCHOOL BUS ARRIVAL
</P>
<P>
   What if you could have a few minutes of advance notice that the
school bus was coming? Depending on the punctuality of the school
bus driver, those minutes could be a blessing. That's the logic
behind www.buspal.com, a paging service that notifies parents, for
a monthly fee, a few minutes before the school bus approaches the
stop.
</P>
<P>
   Parents can get the service by paying $80 for a pager, $50 to
set up the service and cover in-home training, and $40 per year. Or
parents can pay $20 for a 30-day trial.
</P>
<P>
   BOLT.COM TARGETS TEENS
</P>
<P>
   There once was a time, not so long ago, where one of the few
places a teen-ager could make power statements such as ``Hall &AMP;
Oates Rules'' was a notebook cover, a blackboard or the back of a
school bus seat.
</P>
<P>
   Now there's the Internet. And Web sites like bolt.com, designed
to appeal to the teen crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Bolt.com tries to be a Yahoo for kids. Visitors to Yahoo can
check stock market message boards and comparison shop for plane
travel. Things at bolt.com are a bit more demographic-specific. A
recent topic in the Style and Looks category is ``Streakmo's got
bad acne. Here's help.''
</P>
<P>
   The site tries to tap into some of that teen spending money.
Site advertisers include Apple Computer, Rolling Stone magazine,
Levis, Butterfinger and the U.S. Army.
</P>
<P>
   MADEMOISELLE THINKS INTERNET WILL CLICK
</P>
<P>
   Mademoiselle has developed a magazine supplement for all the
women out there who love the Internet but never had a publication
designed to nurture that love. Click Here debuts in the October
issue. The first cover features musician Alanis Morissette. It
tries to counter perceptions that most women are not as interested
in technology as men. How does it do that? For starters, it quotes
Alyssa Milano of TV's ``Charmed'' as saying, ``My Apple Powerbook
has 333MHz and 64 MB of RAM.'' The first issue includes a feature
about gadgets, how to decide what kind of computer you need and an
introductory piece on online shopping. A section on favorite Web
sites includes these recommendations: Best cooking site?
www.mymenus.com; Best health info? www.intelihealth.com,
www.navigator.tufts.edu and www.phys.com; Best laughs?
www.theonion.com; Best love and sex advice?
www.womenswire.com/emale; Best online magazine? www.salonmag.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-10-04-99 1127EDT &QL;
</P>
