 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   &HT;    `Command &AMP; Conquer' sequel magazine's focus
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Among the new computer games eagerly awaited by people
everywhere (especially those who like a good fight) is the sequel
of ``Command &AMP; Conquer,'' ``Tiberian Sun.'' Learn about this game
in a hands-on report in the October issue of Computer Gaming World.
The magazine sent two of its writers to a Las Vegas trade show,
where they got to play ``Tiberian Sun.'' Their article discusses
everything from strategy to new weaponry. There are also lots of
color screen shots.
</P>
<P>
   Are there no private corners left? Apparently not many,
according to the October issue of Yahoo Internet Life. It features
a cover story on the growing use of little digital cameras called
Web cams on the Internet. People are using them to photograph
themselves in real time and post that video on the Web. The amazing
thing is that people are surrendering their privacy willingly,
inviting complete strangers to view everything from the banal to
the intimate. Go figure.
</P>
<P>
   ON CD-ROM
</P>
<P>
   Who says you can't teach an old Mac new tricks? Mac developer
Connectix has perfected its software that emulates Windows 98 on
Apple computers. The latest version, called Virtual PC 3.0, has
just been released. This new version supports the new Universal
Serial Bus peripheral standard, runs faster and recognizes
AppleScript, the programming language. Virtual PC sells for around
$180.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE
</P>
<P>
   Looking for some comic relief from the ongoing marketing crush
of the coming holiday season? Then check out the site of Gobler
Toys. This bizarre site, a spoof on modern toy marketing, features
such things as a battery-powered ``smell amplifier.'' Or how about
Weiner Works, a device that lets you make your own hot dogs from
meat scraps. To quote a reviewer in Yahoo Internet Life, ``you'll
find something vaguely disturbing here.'' The site is at
www.goblertoys.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
