<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8305 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-CPT-MAC-REPORT05-COX &LR;      10-06 0424
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-MAC-REPORT05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   &HT;    Y2K problems lurk in software
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Apple is a bit smug about the year 2000, for good
reason. Even computers running the oldest version of its operating
system are Y2K-compliant.
</P>
<P>
   That means Macs can process dates after the beginning of the new
year. How far ahead they can read dates varies, though, depending
on what operating system your Mac is running.
</P>
<P>
   The operating system is the software that comes inside your Mac,
controlling everything from the way the screen looks to how
software runs. The original Mac systems can read dates through Feb.
6, 2040. The newer systems can read dates through the year 29940.
</P>
<P>
   Apple has been trumpeting the Y2K compliance of its machines
since the Super Bowl, when it ran ads noting this fact. The company
has also assembled online a formidable database about what machines
and components it has tested to date. You'll find this site at
www.apple.com/about/year2000.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, all of this doesn't mean Mac users are home free when it
comes to Y2K. Apple doesn't control software developed for its
computers, and not all of it has been upgraded to handle the turn
of the century.
</P>
<P>
   This is true especially of old programs that, although
discontinued, are still in use. I'm afraid the time has finally
come to junk that favorite, although badly dated, shareware
calendar program.
</P>
<P>
   Another potential problem is using files originally formatted in
PC applications. These files can't take advantage of the Macs'
built-in Y2K savvy.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows exactly what these files might do to your Mac.
There are no guarantees. Not all will have problems but, if some
do, it sure won't be pretty.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just PC files that could mess with your Mac's brain.
There are plenty of shareware and custom scripts written for big
programs such as Word, Excel and FileMaker that may not have been
designed to handle 2000.
</P>
<P>
   If you depend on any such scripts or shareware, be sure to
double-check them to ensure they're Y2K-compliant. Unfortunately,
that's no easy task _ especially if you receive this stuff from a
friend of a friend.
</P>
<P>
   The message here is not to panic but to be alert. Seek out
patches online for your favorite shareware and scripts. If you can
afford to, dump the stuff you can't upgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Good luck.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-10-04-99 1127EDT &QL;
</P>
