<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 13:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8306 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-CPT-CYBERSCENE05-COX &LR;      10-06 0560
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-CYBERSCENE05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   &HT;    Quoth a nameless author nevermore
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A rose is a rose is a rose.
</P>
<P>
   Shakespeare?
</P>
<P>
   Nope. Gertrude Stein.
</P>
<P>
   If you've ever tried to remember a famous quotation _ in
someplace far, far away from Bartlett's Familiar Quotations _
you've experienced the jumble that life can make of our memories.
Sometimes you may need the quotation for a speech or a report; at
others, you are simply haunted by a fragment of a memory and want
to trace the source.
</P>
<P>
   The Web can help, as you might guess. But if you are searching
for a searchable version of Bartlett's, you'll have to buy the book
or a CD. For years, Columbia University kept a 1901 version of the
famous book of quotations online and, if you search for Bartlett's
online, you'll still find many links to this site. The site still
exists at www.columbia.edu/acis
</P>
<P>
   /bartleby/bartlett/, but nowadays it will take you to another
searchable reference source, BartlebyVerse: American &AMP; English
Poetry: 1250-1920.
</P>
<P>
   The value of a searchable quotation site is obvious. Most of us
don't remember enough of the poem or quote to use an index by
author. Unlike a printed version of a list of quotations, you don't
have to fumble through an index to find the source.
</P>
<P>
   An even better site for quotations is at a Web page called Quote
Search at www24.pair
</P>
<P>
   .com/mgm/quotes/search
</P>
<P>
   .html. Just as you can at the Columbia site, you can search by
key words. But at Quote Search you can select _ from several
sources _ where you search.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, you can search a newsgroup specializing in quotes,
or sources for quotes by women, or 20th Century Quotations, or even
quotes from columnist Dave Barry. That's just a few of the possible
sources from this page. One of the flaws here is that you cannot
ask the search engine to check all the sources, you have to search
them one at a time.
</P>
<P>
   If the thought of such a cumbersome search depresses you, you're
in luck. There's a site called Non-Famous Pessimist Quotes
Guaranteed to Dim Your Day at www.geocities.com
</P>
<P>
   /(tilde)saulm/quote.htm.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a sampling: ``Death is never prevented ... just
postponed; the nice thing about having nothing is you don't have to
worry about losing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Feel better?
</P>
<P>
   Let's take a look at another searchable Web site now. It's
called Dictionary of Quotations: Inspirational, Famous and Humorous
Quotes at quotations
</P>
<P>
   .sm.to/. As with the other searchable quote sites, you can
simply type in a key word and look for your quote that way. But you
can also search several other ways, including by author or subject
or just check out the newest quotes.
</P>
<P>
   This site is not enormously deep, but it does a fair job on
really famous quotes and authors. It's easy to use, and if your
search isn't an obscure one, you may have some luck here.
</P>
<P>
   One parting thought. You are not limited to searching
``quotation sites'' ... the most obscure quotes probably will be
easier to find using a regular search engine. So don't ignore the
tried and true search engines such as Yahoo and AltaVista when you
are trying to find your quote.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-10-04-99 1127EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-99 1330EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991006.0133 </DOCNO>
