<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8308 &Cx1f; ttd-z
u a BC-CPT-LISTEN-NETMUSIC-S     10-06 1344
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-LISTEN-NETMUSIC-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LISTEN.COM SERVES UP MUSIC ON THE NET
</HEADLINE>
 
(Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   &HT;     By BENNY EVANGELISTA 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ On most days, the noise inside Listen.com's
offices reflects the current state of downloadable music on the
Internet: a cacophony of unfamiliar rock, hip-hop, soul, jazz and
classical music.
</P>
<P>
   But that's fine with the boss, chief executive Robert Reid. To
his ear, that swirl of noise represents the reason he launched
Listen.com, a San Francisco Internet startup that is trying to
become the Yahoo or the TV Guide of downloadable music.
</P>
<P>
   Searching for Internet music spread across different Internet
sites and servers without such a directory ``is like foraging for
nuts and berries by the side of the river,'' said Reid, an author,
former venture capitalist and garage musician.
</P>
<P>
   ``You find what you find. It can be interesting because you run
into neat things you might not have expected, but it's not a very
efficient consumer experience,'' he said. ``Our objective is to be
the place where you're going to go and navigate this incredibly
rich and exciting domain.''
</P>
<P>
   Listen.com, which went live in June, has its own researchers
scan the Internet for songs and CDs available for download for free
or for a fee in audio formats like Liquid Audio or the more popular
MP3.
</P>
<P>
   Listen.com's staff of 30 reviewers then listens to the songs,
writes short, snappy reviews and compares the music and artists to
others of their genre. Music fans, for example, may never have
heard of Wheels of Autumn but will know the Orange County band
``sounds like the Grateful Dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Because most of the music now available on the Internet is
performed by independent artists and garage bands that are not
well-known, Reid believes there is a demand for a site that can
guide consumers to songs they might enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   Listen.com only catalogs music posted legally by the record
labels or the artists themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The reviewers already have cataloged about 75,000 songs by about
20,000 artists. There are links to about 300 sites with legal
downloadable music, and Listen.com has marketing partnerships with
other online music companies like Audio Explosion, EMusic.com and
Riffage.com, sites that mainly are trying to sell the work of
smaller independent labels and lesser-known musicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``We listen to everything,'' said Nick Tangborn, Listen.com's
editor in chief and a former music-industry journalist and
self-described ``know-it-all record store clerk and really bad
keyboard player.''
</P>
<P>
   The company is one of dozens of new Internet music companies
that sprang out of nowhere in the past year as the music and
technology industries began seeing profits, and not just pirates,
in downloadable music. For example, MP3.com is trying to create an
Internet portal for songs, software and news about the popular
format for compressing, storing and transmitting audio files.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Reid, 33, believes that Listen.com stands out because it is
the only one trying to create an Internet-wide digital music
directory for average consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Listen.com has attracted an intriguing list of
high-profile investors _ Internet and technology pioneers whose
names and bank accounts lend credibility to Reid's contention that
Listen.com will rise above the MP3 noise.
</P>
<P>
   Today (October 4), for example, Listen.com will announce that it
has completed a second, $25 million round of financing led by the
Barksdale Group, a venture capital fund started by former Netscape
Communications Corp. chief executive Jim Barksdale.
</P>
<P>
   The other new investors are Sony Music Entertainment, a unit of
worldwide entertainment giant Sony Corp., and Access Technology
Partners, an investment arm of Hambrecht &AMP; Quist.
</P>
<P>
   They join Listen.com's original investors, who include Cnet
founder and CEO Halsey Minor, Gateway CEO Ted Waitt and Imagine
Media CEO Chris Anderson. The first round, which included the firms
August Capital and Austin Ventures, raised more than $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a huge believer in downloadable music,'' Minor said.
``Rob's a good entrepreneur. What you look for is the right person
with the right vision going after the right opportunity. That's why
I was so inclined to invest in his company.''
</P>
<P>
   The digital downloading of music is only in its nascent stage,
and the $40 billion-a-year recording industry has just begun to
explore ways to exploit it. But the Internet research firm of
Forrester Research Inc. estimates that digital downloading could
generate $1.1 billion a year by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's chaos out there, a lot of junk,'' said Mark Hardie, a
senior analyst for entertainment strategies for Forrester. ``Right
now, MP3 is a flea market of music.''
</P>
<P>
   So the idea of creating a directory to make sense of the chaos
is ``a sound strategy,'' Hardie said. ``I don't have a great
opinion of the flea market that is MP3, but I do believe Listen.com
is at least going at it the right way.''
</P>
<P>
   During the summer, a growing number of well-known musicians
began joining that digital flea market. Tracks by artists like
Alanis Morissette, Sarah McLachlan, Sean ``Puffy'' Combs, Red Hot
Chili Peppers, Barry White, Limp Bizkit and Tori Amos now can be
found for free or for a fee on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Listen.com adds about 100 new mainstream artists a week online
in its ``Big Shots'' section, Tangborn said.
</P>
<P>
   Reid, a Harvard Business School graduate, studied what the big
shots of the early Internet age did as he researched his book
``Architects of the Web.'' Published in 1997, the book chronicled
the creation and evolution of the Web, with interviews of
Netscape's Marc Andreessen, Marimba's Kim Polese and Yahoo's Jerry
Yang.
</P>
<P>
   Reid then spent two years with 21st Century Internet Venture
Partners, a Silicon Valley venture capital firm.
</P>
<P>
   Reid, who owns 800 old-style vinyl records, wanted to start a
company of his own. And in mid-1998, he began noticing the
grassroots growth of MP3-formatted songs being posted and traded
via the Internet, mainly by college students.
</P>
<P>
   ``When downloadable music began to happen, it really caught my
eye because it seemed like something that could be revolutionary
and empowering,'' Reid said.
</P>
<P>
   Last November, Reid said he got a phone call from Minor, with
whom he had met regularly in his role as a venture capitalist.
</P>
<P>
   ``He called me just out of the blue and said, `What's going on?'
'' Reid said. ``And at that very moment, I was thinking about this
company (Listen.com). And he said, `Well, I'm thinking of starting
an MP3 company. Let's have breakfast tomorrow.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Listen.com's first company Christmas party, two days after
incorporation, had just one guest: Reid himself. But it now has
about 85 employees and plans to reach 100 workers by the end of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   In July, the company moved from temporary quarters near 3Com
Park to a converted two-story brick warehouse on Utah Street in the
city's Potrero Hill neighborhood. The building's name sounds like
it came out of an breezy Conan O'Brien comedy skit: Nuevo Media.
</P>
<P>
   The reviews on the Web site also have a breezy tone. About
England's metal band Sheep on Drugs, the site says ``dance tracks
are like a long drive along the L.A. freeways at 4 a.m., moving
forward at high velocity through spaces skinned of any emotion,
leaving a cybernetic, inhuman distance.''
</P>
<P>
   Listen.com visitors who register to become free members also
have the chance to speak their minds. One member called Doctor
Gonzo wrote that ``after only an hour of listening, my IQ jumped 20
points, my hair loss stopped, my stomach became ripped and chicks
now dig me. And the music is good, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Reid believes that average consumers eventually will dig digital
downloading, as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``My expectation is there is some sort of sweet spot in the
market with the consumer who wants to access what they're looking
for, get it quickly and move on with their lives,'' Reid said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-10-04-99 0033EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-99 1332EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
