<DOCNO> NYT19991006.0135 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 13:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8309 &Cx1f; ttd-z
u a BC-CPT-OUTTAKES-COLUMN-S     10-06 0997
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-OUTTAKES-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECH NOVICES GET CRASH COURSE
</HEADLINE>
 
(Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   &HT;     By STAN BUNGER AND JAN BOYD 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Strange but true: There actually are people who
don't know how to retrieve e-mail or enter their day's schedule on
a Palm digital organizer. Why, some don't even have cellular
phones!
</P>
<P>
   We know, it seems impossible, but outside the tech-steeped
precincts of the Silicon Valley, plenty of folks just haven't
crossed the chasm and joined the Digital Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Five of them wound up in Menlo Park, Calif., the other day,
guests of AT&AMP;T. They were winners in a nationwide essay contest,
scoring a ``Communications Makeover'' under the tutelage of AT&AMP;T
Labs experts. The mission: to turn five avowed tech-newbies into
power users.
</P>
<P>
   The five were awarded new laptop computers, handheld organizers
and cellular phones, as well as two days' worth of instruction.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T helpfully had alerted the media, and no fewer than four
television camera crews crowded into the conference room, eager to
capture video of this rarest of species in action. While the five
students learned how to create and send an e-mail message, the
camera operators pressed in for close-ups.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T's Ritch Blasi, who filled the role of instructor, said,
``You sort of have to walk before you run, and that's what we're
teaching them here. We're teaching them how to walk.''
</P>
<P>
   Learning to walk probably was easier though none of the students
actually sustained any skinned knees. The camera crews had no
trouble capturing grimaces and furrowed brows, and more than once,
tech-support people had to be summoned to the room to figure out
why things weren't working.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Jesmer, who lives near Snohomish, Wash., and wants to be
able to keep track of her 11 grandchildren via e-mail, smiled
broadly as she sent and received the first e-mail messages of her
life. She's plenty happy with what she learned, but she says her
husband remains unconvinced about computers. ``He claims they're
not going to last,'' Jesmer said. ``He doesn't even know how to
turn them on.''
</P>
<P>
   NEW VIEWS ON NEWS: ``I feel like I'm at a gun-lobby meeting;
this is such an insular culture,'' said a nonjournalist at a forum
sponsored by the nonprofit New Directions for News.
</P>
<P>
   The three-day conference titled New Tools, New Journalism
recently brought together in Santa Clara, Calif., about three dozen
newspaper editors, newspaper Web site managers, a couple of
independent Web site developers and a lone television producer.
</P>
<P>
   The first couple of days were spent listening to speakers and
exploring the concept of ``New Journalism,'' meaning journalism
delivered via the Web. But by the third morning, listening and
general discussion gave way to a heated debate over the future of
news on the Internet. Here's the argument: Is news delivered over
the Web by nontraditional news sources as credible as news
delivered by well-established newspapers?
</P>
<P>
   One side, mostly nonjournalists, argued that news delivered by
Yahoo, Excite or even, in the future, Starbucks or Home Depot will
be considered just as credible as news delivered by The Chronicle
or any other newspaper. They argued that studies show increasing
distrust of the media, and a growing disconnect between the
audience and news gatherers.
</P>
<P>
   Arguments for the other side: truth, justice, the American way,
moral superiority and a profound belief that people eventually will
figure out that professional journalists hold to a higher standard
of ethics than their Web counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   SEARS ROAD WARRIOR: You would have to count Craig Hemsworth as a
member of the Road Warriors elite. He lugs a laptop computer with
him wherever he goes, uploads and downloads data from home and
works for a multibillion-dollar corporation.
</P>
<P>
   But Hemsworth is an appliance repairman, one of about 10,000
Sears maintenance technicians nationwide who carry ruggedized
portable computers complete with wireless communications
capability.
</P>
<P>
   Hemsworth works out of the Sears regional service center in
Concord, Calif. While he sleeps each night, his next day's worth of
service calls is downloaded to his computer. At the same time, the
machine uploads a list of parts used in the previous day's work. By
the time Hemsworth reports for work, a bin has been filled with
replacements for those parts, so he can replenish his service van.
</P>
<P>
   At each service call, Hemsworth fires up the laptop, establishes
a wireless connection with the Sears network and types in details
of the work he performs. The system automatically updates parts
inventories, customer information and even Hemsworth's actual
position. The wireless exchange of data replaces the old way: lots
of phone calls to dispatch centers and parts desks.
</P>
<P>
   All this clearly makes Hemsworth an information technology
worker, though he doesn't look the part.
</P>
<P>
   He has spent more than 30 years with Sears, taking a break at
one point for a tour of duty in Vietnam. He admits that he once
balked at the idea of becoming a computer jockey. Now, he's sold,
and his wireless laptop often becomes a conversation piece when his
route takes him to tech-savvy households. ``I have a lot of my
customers that say the same thing: `Boy, you've become very high
tech in this field,' '' he said.
</P>
<P>
   FORBIDDEN FRUIT: Shooting at Apple is always at bit problematic.
Apple has a bit of a media-persecution complex, and television
cameras probably are more welcome in CIA headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   The newest rule is: no shooting in offices _ not just because of
confidential material, but because there are ``legal issues''
involved in the filming of any pictures posted on the walls. So,
New Media News viewers will not be seeing our interviewee's poster
collection, which consisted of bands like Hole and Garbage, and, oh
yeah, that top-secret confidential picture of a Porsche.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-10-04-99 0033EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-99 1333EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991006.0136 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8310 &Cx1f; ttd-z
u a BC-CPT-ESERVICE-ECOMMERC     10-06 1501
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-ESERVICE-ECOMMERCE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
'TIS THE SEASON FOR E-TAILERS
</HEADLINE>
 
(Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   &HT;     By TOM STEIN 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Surfing the Web last holiday season, Thomas
Blauvelt decided to treat himself to a Christmas present: an
autographed copy of Tom Wolfe's latest novel, ``A Man in Full,''
advertised on Barnesandnoble.com
</P>
<P>
   The experience turned out to be anything but merry. After
several weeks, Blauvelt still hadn't received the book. He zapped
off a complaint via e-mail. In response, he got a canned e-mail
thanking him for his business and informing him that the book was
on its way.
</P>
<P>
   He waited and waited to no avail. He sent the company about 10
more e-mails _ each more incendiary than the last. In return, he
got the same boilerplate reply.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, in utter frustration, he phoned the customer service
hotline. ``The person on the phone had no record of my problem,''
said Blauvelt, a 35-year-old lawyer from Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   A total of four months later, he was informed that
Barnesandnoble.com no longer stocked autographed copies of the book
and he would just have to make another selection.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't done a lot of shopping on the Internet because of
this experience,'' said Blauvelt. ``It really soured me.''
</P>
<P>
   This holiday season, Web retailers are working overtime to make
sure customer-service horror stories like Blauvelt's remain a thing
of Christmas past.
</P>
<P>
   Their performance could be a litmus test for the future of
e-tailing. Sites with minimal glitches and maximum responsiveness
could win customers for life, analysts believe, while those with
problems might not have a second chance to prove themselves.
</P>
<P>
   It's an especially crucial time for e-tailers because the number
of Christmas shoppers on the Web is expected to explode. According
to a new report by Internet research Jupiter Communications,
consumers will spend an estimated $6 billion online this holiday
season, or nearly double what they shelled out a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Fogdog Sports, an online retailer of sporting goods, is
preparing for the holiday rush by giving all 95 employees _ from
the president to the mail-room guy _ a crash course in customer
service. That way, if the company's nine official customer service
reps are swamped, someone can step in quickly to pick up the slack.
</P>
<P>
   Fogdog in Redwood City uses a software package from Kana
Communications to manage the hundreds of customer e-mails it gets
each day. The software automatically can direct a customer e-mail
to the appropriate person so that it is answered quickly and
accurately. For example, if a customer has a question about what
kind of hiking boots to buy, the message will be routed to the
customer service rep specializing in outdoor activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``People shop online because they are strapped for time and are
looking for more convenience,'' said Tom Romary, vice president of
marketing at Fogdog. ``Customer service is integral to the online
experience. If we can't meet expectations, then we are in the wrong
business.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, this could mean investing millions of dollars in new
customer service technologies as well as in personnel costs. For
some, this may run counter to the traditional notion of an
e-commerce company as a lean operation with minimal overhead and
limited labor requirements. But a growing number of Web outfits are
singing a new tune _ namely, if they spend more on customer
service, customers will spend more on them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Successful Web companies are more focused on customer service
than they are on selling stuff,'' said Bob Chatham, an analyst with
Forrester Research. Still, too many e-tailers are ignoring customer
service outright, added Chatham.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the more disappointing examples, he said, are well-known
brick-and-mortar retailers like J. Crew and Victoria's Secret,
which also sell their products online. These companies do not allow
customers to return purchases made over the Web to their physical
stores. Instead, consumers must pack up the merchandise themselves
and send it back by post.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a major no-no,'' said Christopher Lochhead, chief
marketing officer at Internet consulting firm Scient. ``Customers
want to be treated the same, whether it's on the Web, in a store or
on the phone. Businesses that don't have these things tied together
will get killed.''
</P>
<P>
   RightStart.com, a new Web company in Westlake Village (Los
Angeles County) that sells child-care products such as baby seats
and personal playgrounds, is determined to be around for the long
haul. ``Seamless customer service is the key to our survival,''
said Gerald Mitchell, executive vice president of RightStart.com.
</P>
<P>
   When consumers order an item from the Web site, they immediately
get a message telling them that items can be returned hassle-free
to the nearest brick-and-mortar Right Start store, of which there
are 45 across the country. Consumers receive a map to retail
outlets within a 20-mile radius of their home address. The company
said it provides clear instructions for customers who need to
return items by post.
</P>
<P>
   Shelley Taylor, a consultant in Palo Alto, Calif., could have
used that kind of service when she bought a Palm V electronic
organizer from the ValueAmerica Web site two months ago. The
product arrived in a timely fashion, but Taylor had to return it
because it was not the version she ordered. That's where she ran
into problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were no instructions in the box about how, or even
where, to send it back,'' she griped. ``There wasn't even a phone
number.'' She finally tracked down the customer service number on
the Web site and then waited 20 minutes on the phone before getting
an agent who could help.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have thought there'd be tremendous improvements in
retail Web sites by now,'' said Taylor. ``But that's not the
case.''
</P>
<P>
   Most Internet shoppers would agree with her. A recent study by
Forrester Research found that about 70 percent of all shopping
carts are abandoned on the Internet. That means consumers start the
buying process but for a variety of reasons leave a site before
making any purchases. Of course, some people are just window
shopping, but analysts believe that e-tail sites are still too
frustrating for consumers and simply do not provide an engaging
experience.
</P>
<P>
   Furniture.com is trying to change that perception. The
Framingham, Mass., company, which sells high-end furnishings on the
Web, has adopted some leading-edge technologies to reinvent the
online customer experience. The most compelling weapon in
Furniture.com's arsenal is good old human interaction. The site has
about 20 online design consultants who carefully observe as
customers browse the site and then, using live chat software, send
out polite messages that pop up on the consumer's computer screen,
asking if they can be of assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to the site also can request a personal shopper. Using
the chat software, the personal shopper can browse side by side
with a consumer, answer questions and even offer design and
furniture-arrangement advice.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Brooks, CEO of Furniture.com, said about half of his
customers place their orders with the help of a design consultant.
``It's easy to get a customer for the first time,'' he said. ``What
separates a successful Web site from the hype is the ability to
deliver such a compelling experience that the customer becomes a
champion of electronic business.''
</P>
<P>
   EToys Inc. is another company trying to take online customer
service to new heights. The Santa Monica (Calif.) company, which
gets thousands of calls and e-mails each day, is ramping up for the
holidays by boosting its customer service staff from 30 to 160
reps, largely by hiring temporary workers.
</P>
<P>
   John Hnanicek, chief information officer at eToys, said the goal
is to answer all e-mails within 24 hours and never make a customer
wait on the phone more than three minutes.
</P>
<P>
   EToys takes both a high-tech and high-touch approach to customer
service. Customer service reps, for instance, sit cheek-by-jowl
with a cart of toys so that they actually can touch and play with
the products while answering questions. Service reps are trained to
answer questions about how to complete an online transaction as
well as questions about the toys themselves, like whether a
particular toy is suited for a 4-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   EToys also employs live chat and rapid e-mail-response
applications. Moreover, the company is working with a new
technology called voice-over IP that soon will allow customers
simply to click a button and begin talking with a customer service
or sales rep directly via PC.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Chatham of Forrester likes the eToy approach. ``Just like
the physical world, consumers need someone to browse with them and
hold their hand,'' he said. ``Companies cannot expect consumers to
just show up and send them money. They have to learn to service
customers online.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-10-04-99 0012EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
