<HEADLINE>
JACKSON CHALLENGES SILICON VALLEY TO BOOST DIVERSITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MATT BEER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ The Rev. Jesse Jackson is challenging Silicon
Valley enterprises to hire more minorities, saying that the booming
technology region's record on racial and cultural diversity is ``a
national disgrace.''
</P>
<P>
   The civil rights leader on Tuesday unveiled his action plan for
bringing an updated version of the 1960s civil rights movement to
the 1990s high-tech industry.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking before an enthusiastic crowd at a meeting in San Jose,
the civil rights leader and onetime Democratic presidential
candidate said he would soon open a Silicon Valley office of the
Rainbow/PUSH Coalition that he heads. From this outpost, Jackson
said his staff would force diversity onto an industry known for its
mostly white, male entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said the staff would monitor the top 50 technology
companies, issuing a report card in April to rank these companies
on their ethnic and racial diversity and contributions to education
for the disadvantaged.
</P>
<P>
   Companies that have government contracts, Jackson said, would be
closely monitored to ensure compliance with racial equality
regulations, and low-wage workers who do assembly work for the
high-tech industry would be unionized, Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson also said he would stage a Silicon Valley convention of
civil rights leaders and supporters to call attention to the nearly
``all-white board rooms'' of the technology industry.
</P>
<P>
   The announcements signal Jackson's intention to throw down an
anchor in the center of the region's robust economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We liked it,'' Jackson said about his recent visits to the
Silicon Valley. ``And we intend to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's visit follows an April 12 session when Jackson met
with dozens of power brokers, including Steve Jobs, the interim
chairman of Apple Computer Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said the Rainbow/PUSH Coalition would use its current
ownership of stock in 50 Silicon Valley companies to monitor
corporate performance. He added that Rainbow representatives would
attend shareholder meetings to express discontent with a particular
company's practices.
</P>
<P>
   To standing ovations, Jackson decried the overwhelmingly white
executive ranks of the country's high-tech companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Accept the moral challenge,'' he said. ``Include all in this
valley of hope and leave none behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's Silicon Valley visits have gotten the attention of
some companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really trying to work with him on developing a
dialogue,'' said Tracy Koon, a spokeswoman for the Intel Corp. the
Santa Clara-based computer chip-maker that employs some 66,000
workers worldwide. ``Companies shouldn't be threatened by what he
says.''
</P>
<P>
   But John Thompson of Cupertino-based Symantec, the only black
chief executive in the top 150 top ranked high-tech companies, has
not been an enthusiastic supporter of Jackson's Silicon Valley
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In May, Thompson said he would not be a ``poster boy'' for the
Silicon Valley high-tech companies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
