<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8312 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-CPT-INTERNET-TAXATION     10-06 1211
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-INTERNET-TAXATION-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPPOSITION GROWING TO INTERNET SALES TAX 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 (ART ADV.: A graphic is being sent to NYTNS clients. 
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.)  (w and f coding)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT   c.1999 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With Internet commerce expanding at an exponential
rate, many states are becoming panicked at the disappearance of
sales tax revenues and conventional retailers are incensed that
their sales are being taxed while cybersales are not.
</P>
<P>
   But the movement to collect taxes on the $20 billion Internet
commerce industry is floundering on Capitol Hill, opposed by a
growing coalition of officials who believe taxing the infant
industry will smother it. In recent weeks, in fact, the political
winds in Congress have shifted toward abandoning the idea of taxing
the Internet in any way _ in the United States and around the
globe.
</P>
<P>
   Internet entrepreneurs are cheering the trend, arguing that
their contribution to the booming economy compensates for any loss
in sales tax. A similar view is gaining currency in Congress, where
lawmakers are looking to outlaw Internet taxes to keep the
electronic marketplace healthy.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Senator John S. McCain introduced a bill that would
forbid US Internet sales taxes forever. And last week, over the
cries of municipal leaders, a bipartisan congressional coalition
launched an even more ambitious campaign: convincing the World
Trade Organization to ban Internet sales taxes worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we stifle Internet commerce before it even starts, we're
killing the goose that lays the golden egg,'' said Senator Patrick
J. Leahy, Democrat of Vermont, a cosponsor of the bill.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, Governor Paul Cellucci long has supported the
idea of forbidding an Internet sales tax regardless of what the
federal government decides, and members of the Massachusetts
Sofware Council say Cellucci is ``very much on the industry's
side.''
</P>
<P>
   But most governors and local officials around the country are
not. Their concerns are local; downtown music stores won't stay in
business, they argue, if people buy all their compact discs on the
Internet to save money on sales tax. Not to mention that, for all
local leaders, their own pocketbooks are at stake.
</P>
<P>
   The problem right now, according to state leaders, is that the
system ``discriminates against customers or businesses based on the
means by which they sell things,'' said Bret Hester, a policy
analyst for the National Governors Association. In the future, the
disparity is only likely to grow worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you buy a book from a bookstore, you should be treated the
same, from a tax perspective, as if you bought it over the
Internet,'' Hester said.
</P>
<P>
   Of greater concern to municipalities, however, is the revenue
generated by retail sales taxes. According to the most recent
estimates, states stand to lose a total of $15 billion a year in
sales tax revenues by 2003 if the laws are not expanded to include
the Internet, Hester said. Concerned about that figure, the US
Conference of Mayors is scrambling to devise a proposal that would
let states and cities levy taxes on Internet sales the same way
they now do on regular store sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're talking about is funds now going for schools, for
police, for fire protection, for parks,'' said Larry Naake,
director of the National Association for Counties. ``We are not
asking for new taxes. We are just asking for the ability to collect
the taxes that are legally due now.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet in a Congress where the very phrase ``tax cut'' can
spark a political firestorm, opposition to proposals banning
Internet taxation has been strikingly slow to form.
</P>
<P>
   In part, those who would tax the Internet have been frustrated
by one nagging fact: no one can quite figure out how to tax fairly
the virtual storefronts that crowd the information superhighway. A
blue-ribbon panel appointed to sort out the mysteries of Internet
taxation reportedly is stumped, just six months before it is
scheduled to report to Congress on how to proceed. And even the
lawmakers, such as Senator John F. Kerry and Representative Edward
J. Markey, who consider themselves sensitive to local business
needs, refuse to dismiss notion of banning Internet taxes while the
commission is still doing its work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very difficult task,'' Senator Ron Wyden, Democrat of
Oregon, said. ``All of us are wrestling with something we know very
little about.''
</P>
<P>
   When e-commerce started out, Internet retailers followed the
same basic rules as mail-order catalogs, collecting sales tax only
from consumers who lived in the same state as the company. But as
pressure from local leaders grew, Congress was forced to debate an
Internet tax. In October 1998, the Internet Tax Freedom Act was
passed, temporarily forbidding states from doing two things: taxing
the fee consumers pay to their Internet service providers, and
levying ``multiple or discriminatory taxes'' on electronic commerce
_ a sales tax, in other words.
</P>
<P>
   The three-year moratorium on sales tax was designed as a grace
period of sorts. During that time, the 19-member US Advisory
Commission on Electronic Commerce was ordered to assess the impact
of taxing the Internet. So far, the commission, headed by Virginia
Governor Jim Gilmore, has met twice, and is still fielding
proposals on how an Internet tax might work. It is supposed to
deliver its findings to Congress next April.
</P>
<P>
   Numerous questions are in play: should states tax consumers
based on where they live, or should taxes be based on where a
company is headquartered? If the tax is based on residency, what
happens if a consumer in Massachusetts buys a product and ships it
to a friend in New Hampshire, where there is no sales tax? And if
the tax is based on where corporate headquarters reside, what would
stop e-commerce companies in Massachusetts from moving to Nashua?
Or to a country with no Internet rules at all?
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of schemes floating around that could be
either very positive or very negative for us,'' said Chris
Gabrieli, general partner of Bessemer Venture Partners, a Wellesley
venture capital firm.
</P>
<P>
   But the commission has made little progress, according to Senate
aides. Last week, Representative Christopher Cox, a California
Republican, said there was a real possibility the commission would
need to extend its deadline.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, he said, Congress is not necessarily going to
wait.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this summer, Ernst &AMP; Young released a study concluding
that local governments were barely affected by Internet sales in
1998. Buttressed by those claims, McCain introduced a permanent
extension of the 1998 Internet Tax Freedom Act _ one that would
spell out precisely what taxes states cannot levy. Then, with the
administration gearing up for the World Trade Organization summit
in Seattle next month, Cox and Wyden proposed legislation urging
the organizaton to make a global ban on Internet taxation
permanent. The idea, Cox said, is to ``get there with the fire
engines before it's too late.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-10-05-99 1354EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
