<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 13:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8313 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u d BC-FOOD-WATERS-ART-BOS &LR;      10-06 1302
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-WATERS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WOMAN WHO'S LED A `DELICIOUS REVOLUTION' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALISON ARNETT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Alice Waters, one of the two most famous women in food (the
other is, of course, Julia Child), is seated at a table on the
pocket-sized outdoor terrace of Cafe Louis. A small woman with
clear blue eyes and brown hair flecked with gray, no makeup on her
lovely skin, she stands out among Boston diners boasting hard gold
jewelry and tautly lifted skin. Waters is unintimidating, smiling
serenely, ready to share a lunch and a conversation. Yet it's a
little hard to imagine the opening question of the interview.
</P>
<P>
   What exactly do you ask an icon?
</P>
<P>
   The need to figure that out is delayed a bit when the
restaurant's young chef, David Reynoso, comes out and asks if he
could relate a story to Waters. In his chef's whites, the tips of
his ears getting pinker with nervousness as he talks, Reynoso tells
of arriving in Chicago from his native Mexico at age 17, washing
dishes in a restaurant to get by. ``I was taking an English class
and read a book of essays about food,'' he says, his eyes intently
on Waters. ``Yours changed my life.''
</P>
<P>
   As he shyly departs, the first question becomes obvious: Do
these testimonials happen often? All the time, replies her
assistant, Cristina Salas-Porras.
</P>
<P>
   The conversation starts in a meandering way, from farmers to
winter vegetables to her new cookbook, ``Chez Panisse Cafe
Cookbook'' (Harper Collins). Waters, who speaks in a surprisingly
soft, fluting voice, is nevertheless a woman of strong opinions.
The change of seasons, colder climates, general lassitude on the
part of Americans about what they eat _ none of that fazes her.
``You just have to eat differently in the winter,'' says the
longtime champion of organic food, of eating seasonally and
locally. We start talking about vegetables, about what to eat in
fall and winter, while nibbling on thin grilled pizza blessed with
late-summer tomatoes and corn. Chez Panisse, her Berkeley, Calif.,
restaurant and cafe, is so much a part of Waters's persona that her
personal pronoun is invariably ``we,'' meaning the people, staff
and friends, who work with her in the restaurant. ``We make stews,
use winter greens. The last couple of weeks, we had pizza with wild
nettles, sliced very thin, and prosciutto.'' Delicious, she says,
as she thoughtfully eyes Cafe Louis's crust. ``Ours is puffier at
the edges,'' she notes.
</P>
<P>
   She talks passionately about vegetables, about radishes from the
Berkeley farmers' market _ ``I would be happy to pay $5, and I'm so
surprised when they say 50 cents'' _ about more and more people she
meets telling of their vegetable patches, their experience with
growing food.
</P>
<P>
   Her own food epiphany came early, when she went to France as a
college student. ``I sort of came to it so simply,'' says Waters,
who grew up in New Jersey and admits she had had no particular
interest in food or cooking before that year. ``It's just a way of
life I fell in love with.'' The French way of focusing on good
ingredients from local farms, on gathering together to cook and eat
and converse, simply seemed ``reasonable'' to her, she says.
</P>
<P>
   Although she returned from France, got a degree in French
cultural studies from the University of California at Berkeley, and
trained to be a Montessori teacher, those life lessons propelled
her to open Chez Panisse in 1971 with several friends. From the
beginning, the restaurant was very of-the-moment California, with
its collaborative methods of working _ more like friends gathering
to make dinner for friends than any formal restaurant model.
Waters's insistence on connecting with growers to assure the
quality of ingredients was also unusual. ``Really good restaurants
have to connect with the farmers,'' she says _ almost a truism now,
but revolutionary then. Chez Panisse, once an oddity, became the
trendsetter, and Waters the spokesperson for a movement that swept
the nation's restaurants. Now even casual eateries credit the
vegetables on the menu to a specific local farm.
</P>
<P>
   Her new book of recipes from the less formal cafe, which opened
in 1979, is the seventh Chez Panisse cookbook, all of them
extending Waters's philosophy to the home kitchen. Like its
predecessors, this book includes some recipes so simple as to be
mere sketches of an idea, and others that are startling in their
complexity. Asked about a recipe for headcheese, which starts with
a small pig's head, Waters calmly asserts: ``I think it's important
to have an idea of what it takes to make something.'' Cookbooks,
she adds, are read on many levels.
</P>
<P>
   Waters is on a national tour to promote the cookbook, and will
returns here in late November for a Schlesinger Library function
and possibly other appearances. She enjoys the bookmaking process,
down to choosing a typeface. She also enjoys writing the cookbooks,
she says, because it allows her to elaborate on the Chez Panisse
philosophy, exemplified by the fact that vegetables are the book's
first chapter.
</P>
<P>
   As she talks, another diner comes by, asking to say hello, to
profess admiration. By the time Waters and her assistant are
talking about Chez Panisse's family-friendly restaurant and cafe
staffing _ chefs work only three days a week in the kitchen and one
in the office, and no one works more than 40 hours _ the sun has
slipped behind the New England building next door. We move inside
Cafe Louis, where Waters, dressed simply in a pin-striped top and
pants, makes more heads turn.
</P>
<P>
   At the indoor table, she starts talking about another project
that is now dear to her, the Edible Schoolyard. It began five years
ago, after Waters, on her way to work each day, noticed how
uninviting a middle school looked. When she commented on its
bleakness to a reporter, the principal of the Martin Luther King
Jr. Middle School called her up and challenged her to get involved
in the ethnically diverse school, which didn't even have a
cafeteria for its 1,000 students. Out of that challenge grew an
entire curriculum. The Edible Schoolyard, so far mostly supported
by private donations and volunteer work, has evolved into a garden
where children grow food, and a cooking program where they learn to
cook what they've grown. The program also connects to other parts
of the school's curriculum, incorporating science, math, and
history. Despite kids' reluctance at first to try new foods, she
finds that ``when they grow it and when they cook it, they want to
eat it.''
</P>
<P>
   Although this project is still a fledgling, Waters hopes it
could be a model for other schools, and a way to get out the Chez
Panisse philosophy. ``I think they're hungry for good things to eat
and for companionship,'' she says of the Berkeley kids. That's true
of the nation as a whole, she believes, as she marvels at the
growth of farmers' markets and the change in the restaurant scene.
</P>
<P>
   By now, the afternoon is growing late. Jasper White, the Boston
restaurateur and an old friend, arrives to take her to the airport.
First, though, he pulls up a chair to help taste desserts. Joanne
Killeen and George Germon, who own Cafe Louis, come over to say
goodbye. The table has become Waters's ideal of companionship, of
sharing food and conversation.
</P>
<P>
   And Waters, an icon with indelible opinions, hits her points
once more. Americans, she says, are changing _ for the better _
their attitudes about food. ``By making the right choices in
everything you eat, it leads you to the land,'' Waters says. ``It's
a delicious revolution.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Alison Arnett is food critic for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-99 1336EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
