<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 13:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8341 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-TV-ROSWELL-BOS &LR;      10-06 0543
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-ROSWELL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WINNER LANDS IN `ROSWELL' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
ROSWELL 
Starring: Jason Behr, Shiri Appleby, Katherine Heigl, Brendan Fehr,
Majandra Delfino, Colin Hanks, Nick Wechsler, William Sadler 
On: The WB, Wednesday at 9 p.m. 
Rated: TVPG 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What with the networks' growing passion for teen angst, not to
mention jeans ads, it can't be easy for the ordinary American youth
to claim his or her natural-born right to alienation. How can kids
feel properly alone and withdrawn when there are some 10 TV dramas
currently processing their misery at the global hearth? And it
can't help that so many of these shows _ from ``Buffy the Vampire
Slayer'' to ``Popular'' and ``Freaks and Geeks'' _ are so clever
and well-observed.
</P>
<P>
   WB makes it even harder for the cause of youthful isolation by
delivering yet another sweet and intelligent series about the
impossible years. Called ``Roswell,'' it performs an etymological
trick on teen alienation by presenting a trio of teen aliens, as in
we-are-not-alone extraterrestrial beings. A genre-bender if ever
there was one, ``Roswell'' takes the ``Romeo and Juliet'' love
story, dresses it in ``Rebel Without a Cause'' Americana, and then
gives the whole thing an ``X-Files'' twist. The show is a long,
long way from ``My Favorite Martian'' and ``Mork &AMP; Mindy.''
</P>
<P>
   The human heroine is Liz Parker, a waitress at the Crashdown
Cafe in Roswell, N.M., site of the alleged 1947 spaceship crash.
Liz likes to goof on the UFO groupies who flock to her hometown,
until the day her life is saved by the mysterious healing touch of
Max Evans. Turns out Max, his sister Isabel, and their pal Michael
are outsiders that do ``Outsiders'' author S.E. Hinton one better:
They were hatched from pods on the spacecraft that crashed in 1947,
destroying their parents. Liz and Max fall in love, but, of course,
there's a major obstacle: These star-crossed lovers literally come
from different worlds.
</P>
<P>
   Like so many newer shows, the tone of ``Roswell'' is elastic, as
it stretches from heartfelt teen romance and self-discovery to the
adventure-conspiracy plot, which has the three aliens searching for
clues to their past and evading a suspicious sheriff. Rightly, they
fear they will become prisoners or worse if the authorities learn
their secret. In one science-class scene, Max gets a hall pass to
escape having to examine his own cheek cells under a microscope.
``Roswell'' also shifts easily from drama to sly humor,
particularly with the help of Liz's nutty pal Maria, who freaks
when Liz tells her about the aliens. By setting their show in
Roswell, creators David Nutter (``The X-Files'') and Jason Katims
(``My So-Called Life'') can also feature comic UFO kitsch,
including a crash festival that has the school camping it up in
space suits.
</P>
<P>
   The kids in ``Roswell'' aren't as hipped-out as many of TV's
other teens. As Max and Liz, Jason Behr and Shiri Appleby throw
lots of soulful looks, and Behr is particularly understated. He
doesn't act so much as radiate. Except for a few choice music
tracks, there is almost nothing MTV about ``Roswell'' _ no fast
edits or ultra-now lingo. Now that's otherworldly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
