<HEADLINE>
CHEF, COOKBOOK AUTHOR TURNS COOKING INTO A PARTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RUTH FANTASIA  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Emeril Lagasse likes to raise a ruckus. Arguably
one of the most popular television chefs in the country right now,
Lagasse entertains with gusto. He throws ingredients into the bowl
and yells, ``BAM.'' His signature phrase is ``Kick it up a notch,''
which means add more of the seasoning mix he calls ``Essence,'' and
he's prone to making ice cream with raw eggs and forming bocconcini
hands.
</P>
<P>
   The food-safety police ``are going to break down the door any
minute,'' Lagasse said in a phone interview from his restaurant in
Las Vegas last week. Now he's needling the company that published
his latest cookbook, ``Every Day's a Party'' (William Morrow), by
insisting that his book tour visit cities in middle America.
</P>
<P>
   ``They always want you to go to Miami and Chicago and Los
Angeles,'' Lagasse said. ``For two years, I've been pushing on this
thing. To get them to let me go to places like Buffalo, Albany,
Rochester and Syracuse. They think I'm crazy, but they're letting
me do it. It's great to get with the real people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is real. It's like it is in New Orleans,'' said Lagasse
of this, his fifth book. ``This particular book is very special.
There's a lot of family and friends that celebrated during this
whole thing.'' ``Every Day's a Party'' takes cooks through a year
of events, including the Sugar Bowl, Mardi Gras, the French Market
Tomato Festival, the New Iberia Gumbo Cook-Off and Christmas
dinner, Louisiana style.
</P>
<P>
   ``The inspiration came a couple years ago when people started
talking about this millennium nonsense,'' Lagasse said. ``I don't
want people to lose the tradition and the wonderful things that
have built over the last couple of hundred years.
</P>
<P>
   Lagasse worked on the book with co-writers Marcelle Bienvenu and
Felicia Willett, and photographer Philip Gould.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to take people through this journey month by month.
We traveled around the state and none of this stuff was staged,
this is the real deal.''
</P>
<P>
   As far as the recipes go, Lagasse says they too are for real
people. ``The recipes are solid and work, they've been home-tested.
I feel that for a lot of people there's a trust factor. I don't
want people to be intimidated about cooking, so we pay particular
attention to the number of ingredients and where they can get them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want people to have the trust and smudge the pages all up
and feel like they can really do something neat,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;
</P>
<P>
   SPINACH AND CHEESE QUICHE
</P>
<P>
   (Serves 8)
</P>
<P>
   2 cups bleached all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 teaspoons salt, divided 1/4 teaspoon plus
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon cayenne, divided
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup vegetable shortening
</P>
<P>
   4 to 5 tablespoons ice water, as needed
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   3 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon freshly grated nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped yellow onion
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons chopped garlic
</P>
<P>
   3 cups tightly packed, fresh spinach, stems removed, washed and
patted dry
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces Gouda cheese, grated
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces sharp white cheddar, grated
</P>
<P>
   Combine the flour, 1/2 teaspoon salt and 1/4 teaspoon of the
cayenne in a medium-size mixing bowl. Cut in the shortening with
two knives until the mixture resembles coarse meal. Add 4
tablespoons of the ice water and mix until the dough comes away
form the sides of the bowl. Add the remaining teaspoon of water, if
necessary. Form dough into a ball, cover with plastic wrap and
refrigerate for at least 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   Heat oven to 350 degrees. Remove the dough from the refrigerator
and let sit for 5 minutes. Lightly dust work surface with flour.
Roll the dough out into a 12-inch circle, about 1/4-inch thick.
Fold the dough into fourths, place it in a 10-inch quiche pan and
unfold it. Press the dough into the bottom and up the sides of the
pan. Roll a rolling pin over the pan to cut off the excess dough.
Prick bottom of the crust all over with a fork. In a large mixing
bowl, combine the cream, eggs, 1/2 teaspoon salt and cayenne, and
the nutmeg. Whisk to blend. In a large skillet over medium heat,
melt the butter. Add the onions, the remaining 1/4 teaspoon salt
and the black pepper and cook, stirring, until the onion is soft, 3
minutes. Add the garlic and spinach and cook until the spinach
wilts, 2 minutes. Remove from heat and set aside. Arrange the
spinach mixture evenly over the bottom of the crust. Sprinkle the
cheeses over the spinach. Pour the cream mixture on top. Bake until
the center is set and the top is golden, 45 minutes. Serve warm or
at room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;
</P>
<P>
   SWEET POTATO CHOCOLATE BARS
</P>
<P>
   (Makes 2 dozen)
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pounds medium-size sweet potatoes
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup firmly packed light brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon freshly grated nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   Pinch salt
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   3 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   3 cups milk
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 cups graham-cracker crumbs
</P>
<P>
   2 cups pecan pieces
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup unsalted butter, melted
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces semisweet chocolate morsels
</P>
<P>
   Heat oven to 375 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Rub the sweet potatoes with the vegetable oil and place on a
baking sheet lined with parchment paper. Bake until fork-tender, 1
to 1 1/2 hours. Remove from the oven and let cool, then peel and
mash in a large bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Add to the mashed potatoes the brown sugar, cinnamon, nutmeg,
salt, vanilla, eggs and 2 1/2 cups of the milk; mix well. Set
aside.
</P>
<P>
   Lower the oven temperature to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the graham-cracker crumbs and pecan pieces in a food
processor and process for 1 minute to make a fine meal. With the
motor running, gradually pour the melted butter through the feed
tube and process for 1 minute. Transfer the crumb mixture to a
13-by-18-inch baking pan and, using your fingers, firmly press the
crumbs evenly onto the bottom and up the sides of the pan.
</P>
<P>
   Pour the sweet potato mixture into the crust and spread evenly
with a rubber spatula.
</P>
<P>
   Put the chocolate morsels and remaining milk in a medium-size
saucepan over medium heat and stir constantly until the chocolate
melts and the mixture is smooth. Spoon the chocolate in 3 rows
about 2 inches apart, lengthwise over the sweet potato mixture.
Then, with a knife, make a zigzag pattern to marbleize the
chocolate and sweet potato mixture.
</P>
<P>
   Bake until the edges are browned and the filling is set, 20 to
25 minutes. Remove from the oven and let cool completely. To serve,
cut into bars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
