<HEADER>
A8350 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-POWERPUFF-GIRLS-BOS &LR;      10-06 1211
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POWERPUFF-GIRLS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POWERPUFFS MOP UP THE BADDIES, CAPTURE GIRLS' HEARTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA MATCHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They are three little pastel-colored sisters from suburban
Townsville, and they are just dripping with cuteness. They also
happen to be superheroes whose motto is ``saving the world before
bedtime.'' They play hopscotch, they fly, and their names _ can you
stand it? _ are Blossom, Bubbles, and Buttercup.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't know them yet, you will soon. Move over, Furby.
Make way, Pokemon. Pow! Pow! Pow!
</P>
<P>
   We're talking about ``The Powerpuff Girls,'' a half-hour
animated comedy series that has been winning fans on the Cartoon
Network. While barely big enough for kindergarten, these characters
_ who bust up baddies, kick up their Mary Janes, and shake their
pigtails _ are the embodiment of Girl Power.
</P>
<P>
   And they're trendsetters, too: Suddenly, little girls are
sticking bows in their hair and acting tough _ like Amanda Leone,
5, of Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   ``She stands with her hands on her hips and tells me she is
going to conquer someone today,'' says her mother, Denise.
</P>
<P>
   But Powerpuff fans aren't limited to Amanda's age group.
</P>
<P>
   Only a year after the show's debut, the Powerpuff Girls have
become to teenagers _ and even some older girls _ what Teletubbies
are to toddlers.
</P>
<P>
   Teens voted ``The Powerpuff Girls'' the best animated series on
TV, according to the latest issue of the Big Blue Dot Trend Update,
an on-line e-mail newsletter produced by Big Blue Dot, a Watertown
design firm dedicated to kids. The girls got 42 percent of the
vote, beating out the Simpsons (13 percent) and Pokemon (3
percent).
</P>
<P>
   And trend-conscious teenagers, who last year were swooning over
Leonardo DiCaprio and hooked on ``Dawson's Creek,'' are ordering
glittery Powerpuff angel T-shirts from the Alloy catalog, purveyor
of hot style trends for teens.
</P>
<P>
   Girls in their late teens and even young women in their early
20s are aligning with their favorite Powerpuff girl. Nicole Weaver,
19, of Maynard, whose tongue is pierced, says she likes ``the one
with black hair the best. She has an attitude problem.''
</P>
<P>
   There is also the 32-year-old graphic artist in Philadelphia who
has designed a Powerpuff Girls Web site just for the fun of it.
</P>
<P>
   Powerpuff merchandise is hot. You think Pokemon is saturating
the market? Just wait till you see what the Cartoon Network has up
its sleeve with the Powerpuff Girls.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of the spectrum of heat, this is our first breakout
for a real opportunity at the retail product level,'' says a nearly
breathless Bob Bryant, vice president for off-channel commerce at
the Cartoon Network. ``We're doing just about everything with them
in the development of what's become a really hot property for us.''
</P>
<P>
   He then outlines plans to roll out Powerpuff underwear, plush
toys, outfits, and accessories for young children and teenagers,
and he indicates this is only the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Powerpuff Girls have probably gone to market faster than
almost any made-for-television animated property, perhaps ever,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   The show's fans are buying into the marketing machine.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're cute and funny,'' says target audience member Rebecca
Manning, 14, a freshman at Newton (Mass.) North High School, who
considers the show to be ``neat'' and has bought herself a
Powerpuff T-shirt.
</P>
<P>
   ``And they have Girl Power,'' adds her friend Alyssa Sweet, 13,
of Newton, who spent a day at summer camp this year dressed as the
Powerpuff Buttercup.
</P>
<P>
   The teenage girl world, apparently, has been poised for Girl
Power. The Spice Girls foreshadowed it, with their freewheeling
feminism and attitude. The sports world has heralded it, with the
victories of female athletes like the Williams sisters in tennis
and the World Cup soccer players. Even the fashion world has hinted
at it, with the recent popularity of glittery Care Bear and
Strawberry Shortcake T-shirts, the girlie heroines of teen
yesteryear.
</P>
<P>
   Add a hint of the Japanese-style animation that's currently the
rage, and suddenly everything coalesces in the unexpected guise of
three doe-eyed kindergarteners who aren't allowed to stay out after
dark, yet fight evil menaces like Fuzzy Lumpkins and Mojo Jojo.
There is no moral ambiguity about these siblings, who are so
innocent and pure they sleep in the same bed, with no hidden
meaning whatsoever.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're superheroes,'' Blossom says, in a typical segment.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we do,'' says Buttercup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Duh,'' says Bubbles.
</P>
<P>
   How to account for their popularity?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is a backlash against the idea of sarcasm and
irony and the whole snotty attitude in American culture,'' suggests
Bob Thompson, founding director of the Center for the Study of
Popular Television at Syracuse University.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1999, there is something terribly appealing about the
extreme saccharine sincerity of the Powerpuff Girls. . . . They
have the feel of your feet in the pajamas you used to wear. They're
warm and safe.''
</P>
<P>
   The show is ``a way to go back (to childhood) and not have to
worry about what everyone else is thinking about you, and about
stresses like social life and popularity,'' theorizes Anna Grady,
16, who was recently seen riffling through the Powerpuff shirts at
the Hot Topic store in the Natick (Mass.) Mall.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Simensky, vice president of original animation for the
Cartoon Network, offers an opposing view: ``I think it's the idea
(that) girls always come out the winners.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though the show is produced by a man, it seems to be kind
of a commentary on feminism and role models,'' agrees Elizabeth
Nephew of Philadelphia, the graphic artist who designed a Powerpuff
Girls Web site (http://www.nephco.com/powerpuffgirls). ``It's not
that women want to become men, but that they want to become more
like powerful girls.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps no one is more surprised by the show's success than its
creator, Craig McCracken, 28, of Sherman Oaks, Calif. When he first
came up with the idea of a show about three mini-superheroines, he
presumed his audience would be little children. Still, he held out
hope that the subtleties wouldn't be lost on older people.
</P>
<P>
   ``My friends all liked it. We were hoping people would get it,''
McCracken says. ``It is a little bit tongue-in-cheek and campy.
It's the basic idea of these cute things being tough, beating up an
evil monkey. When you step back, you say, `Wait a minute, I'm
seeing little children beat up a monkey.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A PERSONALITY PROFILE OF THE POWERPUFF GIRLS &QL; 
 &QL; 
