<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-CASCADE CREW HOPES LIGHTNING STRIKES TWICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Desh Deshpande and Daniel Smith became stock market heroes
when they built Cascade Communications into a telecommunications
leader by going toe to toe with industry giants. Get ready for
their second public act.
</P>
<P>
   Deshpande and Smith, who sold Cascade for $3.6 billion in 1997,
are now running Sycamore Networks Inc. of Chelmsford, Mass.
Sycamore executives have just embarked on a road show that will
lead to a closely watched initial public stock offering later this
month.
</P>
<P>
   Despande and Smith, who split $150 million in the Cascade deal,
have made no secret of the fact they don't plan to sell this time.
Our question: Will they always be able to say no in such an
unpredictable corner of the market?
</P>
<P>
   The pair have brought in no fewer than seven senior executives
from their old Cascade management crew to build Sycamore's
business, selling fiber-optic network products.
</P>
<P>
   Together, they are developing the next generation of the
products they sold at Cascade. Again they will be going up against
much bigger competitors, including the likes of Cisco Systems Inc.,
Nortel Networks Corp., Lucent Technologies Inc., and Ciena Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``The management and staff have lived through this before and
survived as Cascade,'' said analyst Frank Dzubeck of Communications
Network Architects Inc. in Washington. ``They've gone through all
the negatives that are classically there (as a start-up) and grew
extremely well.''
</P>
<P>
   Those credentials are especially important to the big network
operators Sycamore is targeting as customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``A large company like AT&AMP;T or Bell Atlantic doesn't want to
take chances with young upstart vendors,'' said analyst Dana
Cooperman of Ryan, Hankin &AMP; Kent. ``It's difficult to get into this
market if you don't have that kind of background.''
</P>
<P>
   Sycamore executives hope to raise about $123 million by selling
less than 9 percent of the company, an offering that would value
their business at about $1.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   That would be an astounding feat for a company that shipped its
first product in May, has billed just one customer to date, and
recorded total revenues of $11.3 million. Even more amazing: Many
observers expect the stock to take off like a rocket after the IPO.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts and investors look at comparable networking stocks that
have soared by as much as fivefold over their IPO price in recent
months and believe that Sycamore can do the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's very realistic,'' said analyst Ken Fleming of
Renaissance Capital, which manages the IPO Plus Aftermarket fund.
``It's certainly going to be a hot IPO.''
</P>
<P>
   Despande and Smith, whose Sycamore stock would be worth about
$250 million apiece at the estimated IPO price, could become
instant paper billionaires in such a scenerio.
</P>
<P>
   For now, investors are unabashedly wild about telecommunications
stocks and none more so than companies that supply gear for
communications networks.
</P>
<P>
   The basic story line: The high-capacity communications
infrastructure being built to support vastly greater demand from
Internet users and other customers needs many pieces of equipment
and software. So much money is being spent so quickly to build
complicated networks that specialized companies are in demand and
command huge valuations.
</P>
<P>
   Consider some of the recent stock developments among
telecommunications companies:
</P>
<P>
   --Juniper Networks Inc., a company similar to Sycamore Networks,
went public at 34 per share in June and sold more stock at a price
of 190 three months later. It closed at 184 Tuesday, giving Juniper
a market value of $9.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   --Redback Networks Inc., which went public at 23 per share in
May, was priced at 114 1/2 Tuesday. With less than $17 million in
first-half sales, Redback's stock market value has zoomed to $4.9
billion.
</P>
<P>
   --Foundry Networks Inc. went public eight days ago at 25 per
share, boomed to more than 166 in its first day of trading, and
finished Tuesday at 158.
</P>
<P>
   One transaction that excited Sycamore followers never made it to
the public market. Cisco Systems opened its wallet like never
before when it purchased Cerent Corp. in August.
</P>
<P>
   Like Sycamore Networks, Cerent makes products for fiber-optic
networks and has recorded scant actual business so far. Its
revenues amounted to just $9.9 million for the first half of 1999.
But Cisco paid $6.9 billion to buy the company, the most it has
ever spent on an acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Cisco acquisition of Cerent speaks a lot for the
worth of Sycamore,'' said John Golden, a technology analyst at John
Hancock Mutual Funds.
</P>
<P>
   Sycamore's products are designed to improve the efficiency and
flexibility of fiber-optic networks that can transmit vast amounts
of information.
</P>
<P>
   Venture capital investors were drawn to the track record of
Sycamore's team of former Cascade executives, but the company's
starting technology is the product of two researchers at MIT's
Lincoln Laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Barry and Eric Swanson, who came from the lab's Advanced
Networks Group, had no commercial experience before they took some
space at the offices of Matrix Partners, the Waltham venture
capital firm.
</P>
<P>
   Matrix executives put them together with Deshpande and Smith,
and the business started to grow. At first, Matrix put $2.5 million
into Sycamore and eventually invested a total of about $10 million.
Its stake would be worth about $250 million at the estimated IPO
price range.
</P>
<P>
   Sycamore got off to a lightning start, designing a product,
recording its first sales, and getting an IPO in the works over
just 18 months. The next year and a half could be just as much of
an adventure.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
