 ENTERTAINMENT SUMMARY -- No. 446 -- Oct. 6, 1999 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We are offering the following articles for sale. Please contact
us for availability your country. Best regards, Karl Horwitz
</P>
<P>
   1. LOVE AT RANDOM : KIRSTEN SCOTT THOMAS ON LIFE,
</P>
<P>
   LOVE SCENES AND HARRISON FORD ``I think the movies have typecast
my life,'' says actress Kirsten Scott Thomas. ``I'm Mrs. Tragedy in
the movies and people expect me to be that way in real life. It's
like I want to scream ``But I am a lighthearted person!'' She says
she had a high-school crush on Harrison Ford - and now he is her
co-star in her latest film, ``Random Hearts.'' She believes the
film speaks to women who are fooling themselves about their mates'
fidelity. Even though she has worked with such heartthrobs as Ford,
Ralph Fiennes and Robert Redford, Scott Thomas says she has never
enjoyed filming the love scenes. By Cindy Pearlman. 1,300 words +
photo.
_____________________________________________________________ 2.
THE LIMEY SIDE OF TERENCE STAMP It's been almost 40 years since
Terence Stamp, then a 20-year-old neophyte actor, was nominated for
a best supporting actor Oscar for ``Billy Budd'' (1962.) ``I know
it's fashionable to put the '60s down,'' he says, ``but it was
heaven on earth for a few minutes.'' He didn't win an Oscar, but
almost four decades later he is a contender for the award again
with a powerful performance in the title role of a very different
kind of movie - ``The Limey.'' Stamp plays a lean, mean, senior
citizen just released from a British prison ... and bent on
vengeance. The movie is violent and intense. By Ivor Davis. 1,500
words + photo. N/A Great Britain and Australia.
_____________________________________________________________ 3.
'WEIRD AL' YANKOVIC FINDS THE
</P>
<P>
   FUNNY SIDE OF MUSIC There are many arbiters of success in the
pop-music world - hit singles, gold and platinum albums, adoring
crowds. But you aren't really a star until ``Weird Al'' Yankovic
parodies one of your songs. His songs may be funny, but that
doesn't mean he isn't serious about the music he makes. Even though
some critics dismiss his work, he says he always tries to deliver
something that works as a parody and as a song in its own right. By
Gary Graff. 1,000 words + photo.
_____________________________________________________________ 4.
BAD BOY CHIC : ALAN CUMMING AND THE ALLURE OF DECADENCE Alan
Cumming's resume is jammed with flamboyant and/or gay characters.
And the actor wouldn't have it any other way. In fact, he
emphasizes, no one - agents, manager, family or friends - has ever
dared suggest that it might help his career if he toned down his
characterizations. ``I'd just think they were stupid if they did,''
the bisexual actor says. ``The people around me know me well enough
to know I don't adhere to those types of rules and never have.'' By
Ian Spelling. 1,300 words + photo.
_____________________________________________________________ 5.
KING CLOONEY Is George Clooney a movie star? He is a sex symbol and
has been a talented actor in ``ER'' for many years. But he has yet
to break through on the big screen. despite a star-making
performance in last year's ``Out of Sight.'' Now he heads to the
desert with two rapper-turned-actors, Ice Cube and ``Marky'' Mark
Wahlberg. The unlikely trio are the ``Three Kings,'' in an off-beat
war story set during the Gulf War. By Joshua Mooney. BPI. 1,300
words + photos.
_____________________________________________________________ 6.
JAY ROACH, MAN OF MYSTERY Jay Roach is best known as the director
of both ``Austin Powers'' movies, but it seems there is more going
on inside his head than very silly comedy. Roach's latest film,
``Mystery, Alaska,'' teams him with screenwriter David E. Kelley
(the multi-Emmy-winning creator of ``Ally McBeal.'') The result,
filmed in the starkly beautiful Canadian wilderness, is a low-key
and heartfelt story of a small town that lives for its amateur ice
hockey team. By Joshua Mooney. 1,300 words + photos.
_____________________________________________________________ 7.
UNDERCOVER 'ANGEL' He is a handsome, centuries-old vampire. She is
a gorgeous vampire slayer. Theirs is the age-old story of opposites
in love. And though their love has already endured numerous
supernatural trials, this romanced is doomed. The new TV show
'Angel' begins with the dark, brooding vampire taking up residence
in Los Angeles, the City of Angels. By Tamara Conniff. BPI. 900
words + photo.
_____________________________________________________________ 8.
ROB REINER TELLS 'THE STORY OF US' It's been a decade since
actor/director Rob Reiner explored romance and relationships in his
hit comedy, ``When Harry Met Sally'' (1989.) His new film, ``The
Story of Us,'' takes that exploration one long step further. Bruce
Willis and Michelle Pfeiffer play a husband and wife who are on the
verge of divorce after 15 years of marriage and two children. By
Jeanne Wolf. 1,300 words + photo.
