<SLUG> BC-PROFILE-NYERERE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NYERERE, ILL IN LONDON, HAILED AS AFRICAN PIONEER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KURT SHILLINGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG _ That Tanzania is known more for Mount Kilimanjaro
than for ethnic violence, more for the migrations of the Serengeti
than mass flows of refugees, is largely the legacy of one man.
</P>
<P>
   News that Julius Nyerere lies gravely ill with leukemia in a
London hospital is causing people across Africa to reconsider the
work of one of this continent's most important sons.
</P>
<P>
   The founder of modern Tanzania, Nyerere is often remembered for
experimenting with a home-grown version of socialism that ended in
dubious results. But his political contribution to post-colonial
Africa is far-reaching and enduring. He coaxed his country into a
model of stability amid turbulent neighbors, nourished southern
Africa's major freedom movements, and asserted African causes long
before Western leaders were receptive.
</P>
<P>
   ``This individual has to be considered one of the great African
leaders,'' said Mahmood Mamdani, an African intellectual at
Columbia University. ``His vision of African unity was remarkably
inclusive'' and ``insisted that independent Africa support
decolonization _ politically and materially _ elsewhere on the
continent.''
</P>
<P>
   Africans call him Mwalimu, the Swahili word for teacher. Born in
1922, the son of a disreputable man with 22 wives, Nyerere showed
early integrity, determination, and political resolve. He worked
his way through Uganda's Makerere University and started the
Tanganyika African Welfare Association to improve the lives of
Africans under British colonization. In 1948 he traveled to
Edinburgh to study economics and politics. Four years later, he
returned to then-Tanganyika to teach.
</P>
<P>
   But his tenure in the classroom was short-lived. Three years
into his career, he formed the Tanganyika African National Union,
the organ through which he led his countrymen to independence. By
1960 he had become chief minister of the colony in a carefully
crafted deal with the British, and a year later prime minister of a
newly independent state.
</P>
<P>
   Once in power, he unified the country's more than 120 ethnic
groups under one language, Swahili. In 1967, Nyerere brokered a
plan to unite mainland Tanganyika with the Indian Ocean island of
Zanzibar, and modern Tanzania was formed. In 1985, after 24 years
in power, he ushered in an era of multiparty politics and became
the rare African head of state to step down peacefully.
</P>
<P>
   Recalling his visit to the east African state in early 1962,
Nelson Mandela, then an underground operative of the outlawed South
African liberation movement the African National Congress, wrote in
his autobiography of Nyerere's keen intellect and humility: ``We
talked at his house, which was not at all grand, and I recall that
he drove himself in a simple car, a little Austin. This impressed
me, for it suggested that he was a man of the people. Class,
Nyerere always insisted, was alien to Africa; socialism
indigenous.''
</P>
<P>
   That latter point formed the core of Nyerere's African
philosophy. He rejected capitalism as a scourge of colonial rule,
and vowed to found Tanzania on the principles of self-reliance,
self-sacrifice, and a moral commitment to the liberation of all
African peoples. The country lacked minerals and other resources,
so Nyerere built his socialist vision around the concept of
communal land ownership.
</P>
<P>
   Nyerere remains adamant that his system worked. When the British
left, he once noted, the new country had two trained engineers, 12
doctors, and an 85 percent illiteracy rate. By the time he stepped
down, he said, nearly every child was in school and 91 percent of
adults could read and write.
</P>
<P>
   Critics are less effusive. Nyerere's socialism ``kept Tanzania
underdeveloped,'' said Shadrach Gutto, a human rights lawyer at the
University of the Witswatersrand in Johannesburg. ``It generated
all these sentimental theories _ use a hoe rather than a tractor _
that were out of touch with major development trends. That kept
production at very low levels.''
</P>
<P>
   During the Cold War, Nyerere skillfully remained unaligned, and
reaped dividends. Patrons courted him from all sides, and Tanzania
became Africa's most-aided country by the early 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Nyerere's vision for Africa rested on a principle of unity. He
was a founding father of the Organization of African Unity in 1963,
and urged _ unsuccessfully _ his immediate neighbors to create an
integrated east African market.
</P>
<P>
   But Nyerere could also take a stand against his African
counterparts. Promoting human rights, he was the first African
leader to break with Nigeria and support the Biafran secessionist
movement in 1968. A decade later, he rolled his troops across
Uganda's border to oust dictator Idi Amin.
</P>
<P>
   Tireless in his efforts to promote stability, Nyerere during a
visit to the White House in 1963, badgered President John F.
Kennedy to apply sanctions against South Africa, and now, decades
later, has spent much of this year trying to defuse Burundi's
ethnic tensions. He influenced Africanists like Black Consciousness
leader Stephen Biko in the 1970s, and Uganda's Yoweri Museveni and
South Africa's Thabo Mbeki today.
</P>
<P>
   As Mandela said in a tribute in 1997, ``it is humbling to recall
the contribution that Mwalimu Nyerere has made to the liberation of
our continent. . .his burning desire for justice everywhere, and
his commitment to Africa's interests.''
</P>
</TEXT>
