<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 13:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8363 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-SMILEY-FACE-ART-BOS &LR;      10-06 0965
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMILEY-FACE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FACE IT: ICON KEEPS A SMILE ON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN BARRY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WORCESTER, Mass. _ Happiness existed before Harvey Ball, but it
was more difficult to communicate.
</P>
<P>
   When Ball, then a 42-year-old commercial artist, enclosed two
dots and a curved line in a yellow circle, he created an image that
became an icon so quickly, and with such penetration, that 37 years
later it is impossible to imagine that the ``smiley face'' didn't
come into existence on its own.
</P>
<P>
   But a person was necessary _ and as a variety of Worcester
officials and postal service dignitaries were at pains to point out
Friday, Ball is that person.
</P>
<P>
   As a chorus of schoolchildren sang ``The Ballad of Harvey
Ball,'' and postal service dignitaries unveiled a smiley-face
stamp, city fathers hailed the yellow button as Worcester's
greatest claim to fame _ supplanting such previous achievements as
barbed wire, shredded wheat, and the monkey wrench. Worcester is
also the only city in the United States where Sigmund Freud
officially lectured, but you can't put that on a postage stamp.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you think of Worcester's history, you think first,
always, of the smiley face,'' said Bill Wallace, curator of the
Worcester Historical Museum.
</P>
<P>
   If members of the assembled crowd had a certain ferocity in
their claim, they have reason. Ball never secured the trademark to
his design _ it didn't occur to him at the time _ and has fended
off a long series of challenges to his authorship.
</P>
<P>
   Especially reviled in Worcester is a Belgian named Franklin
Loufrani, who reportedly has registered the symbol in 80 countries
and promised to sue any US company trying to market the image
abroad.
</P>
<P>
   The way they tell it in Worcester, the smiley face was born out
of corporate discord. A Worcester-based insurance company, State
Mutual Life Assurance, had bought out an Ohio firm called Guarantee
Mutual, creating an office dynamic that Ball sums up as people
yelling at one other.
</P>
<P>
   State Mutual's vice president came up with the idea of an
in-house friendship campaign, and the company's marketing director
farmed out the graphic work to Ball. She suggested a smile. Ball
added eyes, so that ill-tempered employees couldn't turn it into a
frown.
</P>
<P>
   After Ball received $45 for his work and bade a permanent
farewell to his design, the smiley face took off in a way no one
had expected. State Mutual, which originally ordered 100
smiley-face pins, reordered them in batches of 10,000 and made
vague attempts to associate the logo with the company, at one point
dubbing it the ``Smile Insurance Companies,'' according to the
Historical Museum.
</P>
<P>
   But the firm couldn't pretend to control the phenomenon; the
yellow button had taken on a life of its own.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was looking around, and I said, `For God's sake, the
smiley's everywhere,' '' Ball recalled.
</P>
<P>
   When State Mutual finally inquired about securing rights to the
design, Ball said, managers were told that the image had been so
thoroughly absorbed into the public domain that it could not be
copyrighted. Although that judgment cut Ball off from legal
ownership, it is also, to some, the brass ring of graphic design _
proof that he created an image that's as universally recognizable
as a stop sign or a heart shape.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost like a blur in some ways,'' said Julie Townsend, a
graphic designer and president of Barrett Communications in
Cambridge. ``It's like the symbols for men and women you see on
airport bathrooms. In some ways, that's the ultimate logo, because
it was so ubiquitous that it really became part of the culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Ball's design has been mythologized in ``Forrest Gump'' and
abused by surly rockers like Kurt Cobain and Marilyn Manson, who
stormed off stage when he glimpsed a smiley-face sticker. The
Worcester Historical Museum, in exhibit notes, reported that ``the
smiley face came to symbolize mindless optimism and bland
conformity.''
</P>
<P>
   None of this makes much sense to Ball.
</P>
<P>
   The Worcester native went off to World War II, where duty
reached its low point with eight weeks storming the Japanese line
at Okinawa. One incident that stands out for him is the explosion
of a mortar shell in front of him and four other soldiers. Three to
his left were killed, one to his right was injured. Ball, 3 feet
away, was unharmed.
</P>
<P>
   When he got home, Worcester seemed so dreamlike, Ball said, that
he sat on a bus one day and wondered quite seriously if he had gone
to heaven. In that context, the money he could have earned off the
smiley face is not important, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not a money-driven man,'' said Charlie Ball, Harvey's son
and a Worcester attorney. ``It could be that nobody would have paid
money for that in 1963. Maybe its success has to do with the fact
that it was free, it was out there, nobody attempted to own it.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, his son says, it ``doesn't sit well with Harv'' when
others take credit for designing the smiley face. ``His attitude
is, `Damn it, this is my legacy and nobody else's. Let's be clear
on that,' '' Charlie Ball said. ``That absolutely motivates him.''
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, Harvey Ball came up with the idea of Friday's
World Smile Day, and he secured the rights to a smiley face with
his name signed in small cursive letters on the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   John Zamoida, education coordinator for the Worcester museum,
said city historians had followed Ball's high-minded lead and
concerned themselves only minimally with Belgian pretenders. But he
also said they had learned a lesson.
</P>
<P>
   ``World Smile Day,'' he said, ``is trademarked.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
