u a BC-LA-POLICE-BOS &LR;      10-06 1142
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-POLICE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOS ANGELES POLICE KEEP EYES ON THEIR OWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The stolen cocaine was only the start.
</P>
<P>
   The latest corruption scandal to unfold at the Los Angeles
Police Department now includes allegations of cops who stole
cocaine from evidence storage, cops who dealt drugs, cops who
planted guns on suspects, cops who beat a suspect inside the
station, even a cop who shot a suspect in the head, paralyzing him
for life. As ominous for a departmental image tarnished by the
Rodney King beating and the Los Angeles riots are all the police
officers accused of looking the other way.
</P>
<P>
   The ever-expanding probe, which began more than 18 months ago
but only came to light last month, also featured cops of another
kind: the ones who first reported the cocaine missing, as well as
the ones who pursued the case against the officer who this month
pleaded guilty to stealing it. In exchange for a lighter prison
sentence, he has been spilling department secrets ever since.
</P>
<P>
   ``All through this investigation, you have had a lot of people
policing their own, turning over every rock, and continuing even
when there were obstacles,'' said Edith Perez, the former head of
the Los Angeles Police Commission. ``It's an opportunity for the
LAPD to hold everyone involved accountable, including supervisors
who had reason to know or who knew what was going on and did
nothing about it. . . There's been a feeling for some time now that
the department is going to be called on the mat if its house is not
in order.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Police Chief Bernard C. Parks has relieved a dozen
officers of duty, with pay, from the Rampart Division, which
handles a part of town heavily populated by immigrants and is at
the center of the scandal. A somber Parks has also indicated others
might be implicated.
</P>
<P>
   It is still unclear how deeply the scandal reaches into the LAPD
in general and its Rampart Division in particular. The Los Angeles
Times has reported that the investigation has expanded into the
command ranks, with the police captain who ran the Rampart station
until last year now a focus of the probe. Another captain since
transferred out of Rampart reportedly was cited for failing to
supervise officers under his command.
</P>
<P>
   Rafael A. Perez, 32, the convicted officer whose testimony
touched off the city's worst police scandal in memory, has called
the corruption ``a cancer.'' He himself shot and framed a young
illegal immigrant from Honduras, who was released from prison on
Sept. 17 as the scandal broke open. Javier Francisco Ovando, the
victim, is now paralyzed and in a wheelchair.
</P>
<P>
   Perez is expected to serve five years in prison as part of his
plea bargain. Attorneys for Ovando's 2-year-old daughter are filing
a $20 million claim against the city.
</P>
<P>
   Although Parks said many of Perez's allegations against other
officers cannot be corroborated because evidence has been
destroyed, no one disputes that the problems appear to run deep.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Perez's former partner was recently fired on
unrelated charges that he planted evidence and made a false arrest.
Another officer is under investigation for allegedly beating a
handcuffed suspect so badly inside Rampart station that the suspect
vomited blood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, it's good the department uncovered this, but the
department also let it go on,'' said Erwin Chemerinksy, a
University of Southern California law professor who worked closely
with Parks as chairman of the city's elected Charter Reform
Commission. ``A lot of people in the department knew about this and
let it go on. There's increasing evidence that there was serious
illegality going on and that the code of silence was again
operative.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the already uncovered police abuses, criminal
cases are certain to be reopened. Some shootings that were ruled
justified are being reexamined.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're sorting through the evidence until we can get a handle
on how many or which declarations involved officers who may be
under suspicion and to verify information that may no longer be
credible,'' said Marty Vranicar, a supervising deputy city attorney
in the antigang section. ``We have to decide what's left, then
decide what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, the simplest of questions must be answered: What
exactly happened and how was it allowed to happen?
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no telling how far this went,'' said spokesman Ken
Ferber of the police commission, the department's civilian
overseer. ``My gut feeling is that it runs from incompetent
management from the captain's perspective to the sergeant looking
the other way to the cops who did these things. . . . They did weed
this out themselves, and that's to their credit. Now they've got to
take it as far as it goes.''
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging that the department's system of checks and
balances has failed, Parks has called for sweeping reforms embraced
by some other large police departments. He said he would push for
drug and polygraph testing of officers, as well as the right to
review their finances.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Police Protective League, which represents the
rank and file, has indicated it would support some of the changes
and probably resist others.
</P>
<P>
   With his take-charge, accept-no-excuses attitude, Parks has
helped to reassure Angelenos that the scandal can be contained. In
statement after statement, Los Angeles's police chief of about two
years has put officers across the city on alert that he will not
tolerate abuses on his watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chief Parks is determined to change the culture of the
department, the culture that thrived under (former chief) Daryl
Gates,' '' Chemerinsky said. ``That was a police department where
officers wanted to take the law into their own hands, a police
department where racism was prevalent, a police department where
officers would not expose the wrongdoing of other officers. This is
a chief who wants to have strict discipline within his
department.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, some observers worry that the police cannot police
themselves. The American Civil Liberties Union wants an independent
investigation into the corruption charges. The city attorney made a
point of asserting civilian control over the department last month
when it reaffirmed the police commission's role as overseer with
investigatory powers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does speak well of the department that they are
investigating these kinds of issues,'' said Angelica Salas, acting
director of the Coalition for Humane Immigrants of Los Angeles.
``The thing is how long it actually took them to discover that
these things were happening. This is years of misconduct and
criminal behavior. The police can't fix it alone. We all have to
take responsibility by demanding the utmost conduct so this doesn't
happen again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
