<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8370 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-IMPOSTER-COACH-BOS &LR;      10-06 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPOSTER-COACH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTRE DAME LIE LEAVES COACH FUMBLING FOR TRUTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARCELLA BOMBARDIERI  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCHESTER, Mass. _ An assistant football coach who claimed to be
a former All-American running back at Notre Dame has resigned after
it was revealed his story was a fraud.
</P>
<P>
   William Nicholas McMullen was hired at Old Colony Regional
Vocational Technical High School after saying he was Nick Eddy, a
former Heisman Trophy candidate in 1966.
</P>
<P>
   His charade came to light this week when the real Nick Eddy,
living in California, heard about McMullen's posturing and called
the New Bedford Standard-Times.
</P>
<P>
   ``He does express remorse,'' Eddy said. ``But I also sense that
the big reason he expresses remorse is that he got caught. He had
20 years to tell the truth, and he didn't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   McMullen said Tuesday he had told the team's head football coach
he was resigning, effective immediately.
</P>
<P>
   He said his days of assuming Eddy's identity began more than 20
years ago when he was in dire need of a job with only $15 in his
pocket, and he committed a ``desperate indiscretion'' and claimed a
college degree he didn't have.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in the boss's office for an interview at a New Bedford
manufacturing plant, surrounded by Notre Dame memorabilia, he said
that he, too, was a Notre Dame graduate.
</P>
<P>
   McMullen, now 58, said he could not fathom at the time that
moment of weakness would escalate, then dog him for the next two
decades.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday he patiently answered questions about why he'd spent a
third of his life claiming to be Eddy, the famed halfback for the
Fighting Irish during the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Old Colony Superintendent David Ferreira expressed bewilderment,
saying McMullen never had reason to lie. The coach, Ferreira said,
was hired for his obvious knowledge of football and later judged
for his skill with the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``The irony is that if he had never done this, he would have
been successful anyway,'' Ferreira said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to prove yourself with kids every day. They accepted
him for the motivation he provided, and I don't think they cared
about an All-American from 35 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   McMullen said he maintained the mammoth deception not for
personal gain, but simply because he had recklessly dug himself
into a hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``I needed a job. I needed a job badly. I took a left turn when
I should have taken a right turn, and I unfortunately kept going
instead of making a U-turn and coming back and doing it right,''
said McMullen by phone from his Fairhaven home.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, he had no intention of claiming to be Eddy, he said.
McMullen, who never attended college but played football and other
sports in high school, only wanted to impress his job interviewer.
</P>
<P>
   He made no mention of football. And he got the job at the
now-closed plant.
</P>
<P>
   Though Nick Eddy was about 6 feet tall and weighed 200 pounds in
his prime, it was perhaps too easy for the athletic McMullen, who
is about 5 inches shorter and weighs much less, to take on his
identity. A three-year starter on the school's powerhouse teams of
the mid-1960s, Eddy was on a team that won a national championship.
</P>
<P>
   Drafted by the Detroit Lions, Eddy overcame an early knee injury
and spent several years with the team until he retired. He now
sells insurance in Modesto, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   In a bizarre coincidence, McMullen actually had been known by
the name Nick Eddy, he said. Since his father was also a William,
McMullen had always been called Nick. And his stepfather's last
name was Eddy.
</P>
<P>
   McMullen said he never intended to claim Eddy's stardom. But the
explanation fit when, a few weeks after the initial lie, his boss
wondered why he wasn't listed in an alumni directory. McMullen said
Nick Eddy had been his nickname at Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   McMullen said he believed the falsehood would vanish because he
planned to move to California to help his ex-wife raise their three
sons.
</P>
<P>
   But while working in New Bedford, McMullen met his current wife,
who made the trip with him. The two returned to Massachusetts to be
near her family and raise their young son. Back home, some people
still knew him as Nick Eddy since the lie, as he said, had
``snowballed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I got involved with Little League, and people would come up
and say, `Are you Nick Eddy?'' he said. ``I would say, `Yes, I am,'
but I would never go into detail.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept it as low-key as I possibly could in the hopes that it
would become a nonissue,'' McMullen added. `` `That was a long time
ago,' as I would say to people.''
</P>
<P>
   McMullen lied about his past even to his wife and son, but they
never seemed particularly interested or impressed with the story of
his being a Heisman Trophy finalist, he said.,
</P>
<P>
   When McMullen happened to meet Old Colony head coach Kevin
Gonsalves several years ago, he hesitated to accept his offer of an
assistant coaching job, fearful that he would be forced to
perpetuate the masquerade. But his love of football overruled his
judgment.
</P>
<P>
   If McMullen is telling the truth, he had only been waiting for
the right moment to reveal his identity.
</P>
<P>
   He had started seeing a psychiatrist, he said, and planned to
admit his two-decade confabulation at the end of the season, when
it would be less disruptive to the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to live the rest of my life as a dual person,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   McMullen said Eddy, whom he described as very understanding, was
``exceptionally nice and pleasant'' in their conversations and was
concerned for McMullen's family. McMullen added that his wife and
son have been supportive.
</P>
<P>
   He said he hopes that school officials allow him to explain his
actions to them and to the players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could take each kid one by one and shake their hand
and hug them and express my regrets,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that someday they'll understand.''
</P>
<P>
   Eddy said he has forgiven McMullen and the deception caused him
no harm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three or four years ago, I heard rumors that I was divorced
and living in the Boston area,'' Eddy said. ``Now I know why.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-99 1357EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
