<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-OMON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOSCOW POLICE WAGE RACIST WAR AGAINST SUSPECTED TERRORISTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The Veshnyaki market, in Moscow's far eastern reaces,
is a marvel of bargain-basement capitalism, a sprawling maze of
wholesale fruit and vegetable vendors, cheap imported-clothing
stands, and kiosks that serve hot, greasy fast food.
</P>
<P>
   But when Alexander Grigorievich, a lieutenant colonel in a crack
Moscow police squad, stares out at the massive bazaar, he sees only
criminals and potential enemies.
</P>
<P>
   That is because most of the vendors at Veshnyaki are not
fair-skinned Slavs from Moscow, but dark-complexioned Azerbaijanis
from the Caucasus. And Alexander Grigorievich _ who asked that only
his first name and patronymic but not his surname be used _ and his
unit, known by its Russian acronym OMON, are in the vanguard of
Moscow's openly racist campaign against people with dark skin.
Soon, they know, they may be headed to the Caucasus on a new
mission: to fight in Russia's latest war against the Chechens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blacks,'' sputters Alexander, repeating the word many Russians
use as a slur to describe people from the Caucasus. ``Blacks,
blacks, blacks. Do you see any Russians here? That's what's wrong
with this city. That's what's wrong with this country. Nothing but
blacks. We ought to round them up and deport them all.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Muscovites _ 55 percent, according to a recent poll _ agree
with that. So would much of Alexander's police unit.
</P>
<P>
   These are tough-looking men with truncheons and shiny black
leather jackets inscribed with the insignia ``Team Special.'' They
are hardened special forces cops who are trained to break up riots
and rescue hostages, to round up crime gangs and intimidate
law-abiding citizens into staying that way. They seem to enjoy the
work, even at the below-average salary of $60 a month.
</P>
<P>
   With a new war breaking out in the breakaway Caucasus region of
Chechnya, every one of his men is likely to be sent to the front,
just like all of them saw time in the bloody 1994-1996 campaign in
Chechnya. About 350 of the unit's 2,000 members already have been
dispatched.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since the five apartment blasts that killed 300 peopole and
rocked this nation last month, the job of Alexander's unit has been
to raid markets, stop all the dark-skinned people, and check their
documents to see what crimes they might have committed.
</P>
<P>
   Chechens _ dark-skinned people from the Caucasus _ are suspected
by Russian investigators of setting off the four apartment building
blasts that killed nearly 300 people as they slept last month in
Moscow and other cities.
</P>
<P>
   Chechens are also the ones who invaded the southern Russian
region of Dagestan twice in August and September, killing more than
250 federal troops and wounding 800 others, including men from
Alexander's unit.
</P>
<P>
   It does not matter to any of these officers that there are no
Chechens at Veshnyaki market. For them, a ``black'' is a ``black.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You see, it's all connected,'' says Igor, an OMON officer and
Alexander's driver, whose specialty is coaxing his boxy, unmarked
Zhiguli through Moscow traffic jams at speeds over 100 miles per
hour. ``The Chechens, the Azerbaijanis, the Armenians. These people
are not from Russia. They are outsiders, and they are more likely
to commit crimes.''
</P>
<P>
   OMON's method is simple.
</P>
<P>
   Undercover officers approach a raid site, closing off possible
exits. Then the main OMON ``fighters,'' as they call themselves,
drive up in two or three of the rickety old buses that Russians use
for ritual services.
</P>
<P>
   The OMON swarm the market, stopping anyone who looks suspicious,
or like he's from the Caucasus, and demanding to see documents.
Inevitably, the search reveals people who have violated Moscow's
strict, Soviet-era residency rules, which have been declared
unconstitutional but are still observed in the Russian capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cast the net wide and see what we catch,'' Igor says during
a break in the day's action that allows him to read a few pages of
his paperback thriller, ``I Will Order A Hit On You.''
</P>
<P>
   During a daylong sweep of six major markets in eastern Moscow
last week, Alexander's OMON unit caught 200 violators of the
residency rules, only a small portion of the 6,000 who are detained
each day in the citywide operation. Each one will be fined 8 rubles
(about 30 cents) then let go. Someday, the OMON men hope, City Hall
will follow through on a promise to mark deportation mandatory in
such cases.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander is upset. Many of the vendors' documents have been
registered properly. The OMON officers have no choice but to let
them go.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trouble is, many of them are marrying Russian women,''
says Yura, a senior lieutenant, as he, Alexander, and Igor enjoy a
free lunch from a fearful Azerbaijani cafe owner at the Vehnyaki
market whose documents, as well as those of his clients, had just
been checked. ``Soon, they'll have children who will speak
Azerbaijani and Armenian and Chechen. Soon, people won't be able to
talk Russian in school.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a depressing conversation, so the men quit lunch and go
back out to search for more criminals. But that gets boring after a
while. They have been doing this, seven days a week, since the last
bomb exploded in Moscow on Sept. 13.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the kind of work we should be doing,'' says Yura.
``OMON has lost respect in the eyes of people from the Caucasus.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You should see us sometime when we do crowd control!'' Igor
chimes in.
</P>
<P>
   The conversation is interrupted by a man who runs up and tells
the two OMON officers of a crime in progress: Three men are
drinking vodka in public, in clear violation of Mayor Yury
Luzhkov's recent decree outlawing the sale and consumption of
spirits at market places. But by the time the OMON arrive, the men
have finished the vodka.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need Augusto Pinochet,'' says one OMON officer, referring
to the former Chilean military dictator under house arrest in
Britain. The officer gives his name as Colonel Petukhov. ``We need
London to hand us over Pinochet for six months. That will put
everything in order. In America, if you buy a beer, you have to put
it in a bag. Here, people drink it on the street. You have
democracy, we have anarchy.''
</P>
<P>
   The men are convinced that the disorder in Chechnya is a result
of this anarchy. OMON units were accused of atrocities in fighting
in the 1994-1996 war, and the men say that if they go back, they
will be no more forgiving.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we should just use the atom bomb on Chechnya and be
done with the problem,'' says Yura, a senior lieutenant in
Alexander's unit. ``Look, the Chechens are a bandit nation.''
</P>
<P>
   However well-trained they are, police detachments like OMON are
not military units. They do not train with the army, and they are
not intended to be used as front-line battle troops.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent conflicts between Russian forces and Islamic
rebels, the federal command has relied on OMON detachments. This
has often led to confusion.
</P>
<P>
   During the fighting in Dagestan, OMON detachments were shelled
by Russian artillery and bombed by Russian planes, according to
Alexei Arbatov, deputy chairman of the defense committee in the
Russian State Duma, the lower house of parliament, who recently
toured the battlegrounds in Dagestan.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Grigorievich's unit finally catches some crooks: a
group of swindlers running a scheme called ``Lokhotron.'' Like
three-card monty, the scheme is a way to separate unknowing players
from their money. Two undercover officers watch the players to make
sure, then close in.
</P>
<P>
   All of them protest. But they are caught red-handed. A number of
them have Ukrainian or Georgian passports. That is good luck. The
few that have Moscow passports are let go.
</P>
<P>
   An OMON officer also catches a young man with a passport that
has been tampered with. The man is obviously working as muscle for
a large flower stand at one end of the market. But the police let
him go, because there's nothing illegal about that, and he has a
Moscow residency stamp. Later, they sit in the car and watch as the
man badgers and shoves old ladies selling wildflowers until they go
away.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-99 1400EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
