<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-WRECK _ LONDON _ Rescue workers clad in white plastic
coveralls entered the charred and mangled commuter rail car
Wednesday morning that officials fear may contain many more bodies
of people killed Tuesday in one of Britain's worst ever rail
disasters. Developing. (Roughton, Cox Bews Service).
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   CLINT0N-TREATY _ WASHINGTON _ Using the bully pulpit to try to
salvage a key foreign policy initiative, President Clinton appealed
to the American people Wednesday to get behind a nuclear test ban
treaty that appeared headed for defeat in a Senate sharply split
along partisan lines. (Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   ANTS _ WASHINGTON _ Some of the isolationist views of Republican
presidential candidate Pat Buchanan appeared to be shared by a
group of ants that live in acacia trees in Africa. For years,
entomologists have puzzled over the ants' strange behavior of
pruning the trees they occupy, even to the detriment of the trees.
Now, in a paper published in this week's Nature, biologists say
they prune the trees to separate them from surrounding trees, which
are occupied by several different, fiercer species of ants.
(Nesmith, Cox News Service). 15.
</P>
<P>
   TUTU _ WASHINGTON _ Archbishop Desmond Tutu, chairman of the
Truth and Reconciliation Commission in South Africa, addresses a
National Press Club luncheon. (Hill, Cox News Service). 15.
</P>
<P>
   CHEM-BIO _ WASHINGTON _ Military and civilian authorities are
responding to the threat of chemical and biological terrorism with
Cold War approaches that are doomed to failure, an expert on
unconventional threats told a conference of government officials
and technology companies this week. The two-day meeting, sponsored
by Jane's Information Group, the London-based publisher of
information on weapons systems, ends Wednesday. It is being
attended by representatives of the Secret Service, the Central
Intelligence Agency, various military agencies and a few local
officials, including Austin, Texas, police detective Jim Neilson
and fire department hazmat chief David Fiero. Neilson says Austin
is somewhat unique in the cooperative preparation fire and police
departments are attempting to make to chem-bio dangers. (Nesmith,
Cox News Service). 25.
</P>
<P>
   MANAGEDCARE _ WASHINGTON _ Developments in the debate on
competing managed care bills. (Carr, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   GORE _ NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ Vice President Al Gore, emphasizing
his desire to start his campaign afresh, opens his new headquarters
here Wednesday. (Shepard, Cox News Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY _ Democrat Bill Bradley, who has shown surprising
strength against Vice President Gore, appears to have trumped Gore
in an area close to the vice president's heart: online fundraising.
Analysts say that the $650,000 Bradley has raised on his internet
site has shattered previous fundraising records for online
contributions. His success reflects both his clever on-line
strategy and the nature of his constituency. (Foskett, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 25'.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   MEMPHIS-MAYOR _ The way Memphis Mayor Willie Herenton sees it,
his main opponent in Thursday's election isn't even on the ballot.
City Council Chairman Joe Ford, considered the top challenger in a
crowded field, is just a figurehead for his big brother, former
U.S. Rep. Harold Ford Sr., according to Herenton. The animosity
between the outspoken Herenton, the city's first elected black
mayor, and the fiery Ford, patriarch of the city's most politically
powerful black family, is only part of the intrigue of this year's
mayoral election. Fifteen candidates are on the ballot in the
nonpartisan election, including professional wrestler Jerry ``The
King'' Lawler, who gained notoriety in 1982 when he slapped
comedian Andy Kaufman on ``Late Night With David Letterman,'' and
Pepper Rodgers, the former Georgia Tech football coach who led
Memphis' failed attempt to get an NFL franchise. (Konigsmark,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   KOCH-TRIAL _ TULSA, Okla. _ Testimony continues in the trial
that has become the latest legal battle between the warring
millionaire Koch brothers, William Koch of Palm Beach and the
company led by two of his brothers _ one of them his twin, David,
also of Palm Beach. The brothers inherited a fortune generated by
the second-biggest privately held company in the United States,
Koch Industries of Wichita, Kan. The low-profile company operates
oil refineries and pipelines and engages in numerous other
businesses, from cattle to asphalt. It does not release earnings,
but published reports put its annual revenues at $30 billion to $35
billion. The trial is about largely technical issues _ how the
company measured oil it obtained under leases from the federal
government and American Indian tribes, particularly the Osage
Nation in Oklahoma. Neither side has said how much money is at
stake, but published reports say William alleges the shortages
amounted to millions of dollars. (Cohen, Palm Beach Daily News).
WITH PHOTOS (Mugs of David and William).
</P>
