<HEADLINE>
SILICON VALLEY BUSINESSMAN CONSIDERS SENATE BID 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ Silicon Valley entrepreneur Ron Unz, who
wrote a successful 1998 ballot initiative banning bilingual
education in California, says he will seek the Republican
nomination to challenge Democratic Sen. Dianne Feinstein for
re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Unz, 38, is the most prominent statewide figure to challenge
Feinstein so far. But Feinstein, with more than $2 million in the
bank, high popularity in voter polls and a tested campaign
operation, is a formidable candidate.
</P>
<P>
   In his announcement Tuesday, Unz said he would spend $6 million
or less on the primary campaign, much of it from his own bank
account. The figure is the spending limit contained in a campaign
finance measure that is sponsoring on the statewide ballot in March
2000.
</P>
<P>
   He said the current system is corrupt to the core. ``Many of our
elections are bought and sold for cash payments,'' Unz said, ``and
the politicians do nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Ray Haynes of Riverside and San Diego County
Supervisor Bill Horn, both conservatives, already have announced
they are running against Feinstein. U.S. Rep. Tom Campbell, a
moderate Republican from San Jose, is expected to announce soon.
</P>
<P>
   Kam Kuwata, Feinstein's campaign spokesman, said he takes every
candidate seriously, including Unz.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our biggest opponent is complacency,'' Kuwata said. ``We have
been dogged about setting up our shop and getting ready and raising
money and putting the structure in place. It doesn't really change
whether you put in Campbell, Horn, Haynes or anybody else. We know
what we have to do.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, when he was 32, Unz ran against then-Gov. Pete Wilson
during his re-election bid. At the time, Unz called himself a true
Republican and said Wilson was an ``ideological cross-dressing
Democrat.''
</P>
<P>
   Unz opposes abortion rights, saying abortion should be
restricted only in cases of incest, rape or when the life of the
mother is threatened. He doesn't believe in strict gun control and
thinks gays and lesbian should not have ``special rights.'' Unz
said he would have voted to convict President Clinton if he had
been in the Senate during the presidential impeachment trial
earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Unz, a graduate of Harvard University, studied quantum
gravitation under Stephen Hawking at Cambridge University and began
but did not complete a doctoral program in theoretical physics at
Stanford University.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, he took his first job, at First Boston Bank on Wall
Street, and on the resume he submitted he listed his IQ as 214.
</P>
<P>
   Unz made millions after co-founding Wall Street Analytics Inc.,
a Palo Alto software company.
</P>
<P>
   Unz spent $750,000 on Proposition 227, last year's initiative to
ban bilingual education in California, just as the state GOP was
struggling to attract Hispanic and other minority voters.
</P>
<P>
   Unz could face his most serious challenge in the primary against
Campbell.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
