<HEADER>
A8430 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d BC-FOOD-CHAPMAN-COLUMN-T     10-06 0977
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CHAPMAN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COOKBOOK SAYS WE'VE NOTHING TO FEAR BUT BLANDNESS ITSELF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Austin is as close as Texas gets to having a Berkeley, Calif.
The Texas capital is where all the remaining men with long hair
live; it is the only place where people two-step to rhythm and
blues, and where crushed-straw cowboy hats can be worn with
low-quartered shoes.
</P>
<P>
   No tennies with colored socks after Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   There are free spirits in Austin, but not as many as there used
to be. You can still find a few down on Sixth Street. Or you can
travel out toward Lake Travis and the limestone house that serves
as the restaurant hideout for Jeff Blank and Jay Moore. Blank owns
the restaurant _ Hudson's on the Bend _ and Moore is its executive
chef.
</P>
<P>
   The two men have developed a reputation for in-your-face food
preparation, specializing in use of the grill, and high-octane
taste.
</P>
<P>
   They have also been known to set their toques on fire. No,
really, they actually set their big chef's hats aflame. It is kind
of a PR gimmick, but it works. The two smiling pyrotechnicians are
on the cover of their new cookbook _ shoulder to shoulder, burning
hat to burning hat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cooking Fearlessly, Recipes and Other Adventures From Hudson's
on the Bend,'' (Fearless Press, $32.95) is a delightfully clever
and interesting cookbook. ``Sometimes you don't know if you've gone
too far, until you've gone too far,'' it advises.
</P>
<P>
   Also, ``Some people march to the beat of a different drummer,
other people tango.''
</P>
<P>
   The book is bold and colorful, the way the chefs want their
readers to cook. They even add to each recipe the name of a
specific song, or piece of music that will help you get in the
right mood.
</P>
<P>
   Those selections, we're told, are the work of a
``gastromusicologist.'' That's something you'll find only in
Austin.
</P>
<P>
   There are several pretentious aspects of the book. Hudson's on
the Bend is well-known for its exotic meats, so the chefs felt
compelled to add recipes like wild boar schnitzel, and elk or
caribou backstrap stuffed with chorizo.
</P>
<P>
   Such items are not easily accessible at your local Piggly
Wiggly. In fairness, they do offer substitutions.
</P>
<P>
   There are a few recipes that just sound pretentious: toasted
pinon-coriander crusted goat cheese atop garden greens tossed in a
poblano-almond-lime vinaigrette.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, right.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cooking Fearlessly'' does come back to earth with recipes such
as rib-eye steak in a bock beer marinade, and green chile corn
crawfish soup. They sound fantastic and promise jam-packed flavor.
</P>
<P>
   The book is also instructional. Especially in its use of the
cook's body parts to judge the doneness of meats.
</P>
<P>
   Don't poke the meat, or slice it open to see how well-done it
is, the authors warn. The juices will run and the meat will dry.
Learn to poke it with your fingers. Compare the firmness of the
meat with points on your face.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a `straight face' (no smiling or you'll be overdone),
touch your cheek _ that'll be `rare,' '' the advice goes.
</P>
<P>
   Touch your chin; that's medium rare. The end of your nose is
medium; the area just above the bridge of your nose on your
forehead is medium-well.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom of your shoe is well-done.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cooking Fearlessly's'' greatest value is that it doesn't take
itself too seriously. In the introduction, the chefs explain:
``Cooking Fearlessly is about cookin' with a boogie back beat. The
mood is upbeat and festive with recipes that beg to party and which
make the chef look good as well as the food.... Cooking Fearlessly
is about trusting your instincts, breaking the rules, using your
hands, and inventing new tools.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's one of the ``Cooking Fearless'' recipes. It is for corn
pudding, one of the restaurant's most popular dishes. The batter
can be made a day in advance and stored in the refrigerator. Just
give it a whisk before putting it in a greased and floured
casserole dish at baking time. One of the beauties of this recipe
is that it is flexible and can be modified with various
ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   CORN PUDDING
</P>
<P>
   Serves 10-12
</P>
<P>
   Dry mix:
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 cups flour
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 tablespoons baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   Wet mix:
</P>
<P>
   6 whole eggs
</P>
<P>
   1 stick butter, melted
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   1 8-ounce can cream-style corn
</P>
<P>
   Veggie mix:
</P>
<P>
   1 medium poblano pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 medium red bell pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 Anaheim pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 pound fresh-cut corn
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Combine all dry ingredients in a bowl. Mix well and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   In a second bowl, whisk the eggs until blended, then add melted
butter, cream, and cream-style corn.
</P>
<P>
   Blend the dry ingredients into the wet ingredients using a wire
whisk.
</P>
<P>
   Clean all three peppers, discarding the seeds and stems. Dice
into 1/4-inch pieces. Add fresh-cut corn kernels and the diced
peppers to the mixing bowl. Blend together.
</P>
<P>
   Coat a medium-size casserole dish with butter or light vegetable
oil and dust with flour.
</P>
<P>
   Add the mix to the casserole dish. The depth can vary from 1
inch to 2 inches. If the mix is 1 inch deep, it will cook 5 to 10
minutes faster.
</P>
<P>
   Place in a preheated oven at 350 degrees and bake for 40 minutes
or until it is golden brown and firm.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 258 calories, 15 grams fat, 28
grams carbohydrates, 6 grams protein, 141 milligrams cholesterol,
690 milligrams sodium, 51 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes on food for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Write to him at: Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX
76101. E-mail: artc(at)star-telegram.com. Web Site:
www.startext.net/interact/chapman.htm. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
