<DOCNO> NYT19991006.0162 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 14:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8445 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-BOB-EDWARDS-HNS &LR;      10-06 0940
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOB-EDWARDS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUINTESSENTIAL VOICE OF NPR GETS A MORNING RUSH FROM THE NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BERNADETTE FAY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Bob Edwards is a grown man with a bedtime of 6
p.m. That is so he can rise in the dark five days a week to be in a
Washington studio by 2 a.m. to host the early-morning radio news
program ``Morning Edition.''
</P>
<P>
   With his wave of graying hair and nondescript tie, he doesn't
look like a news anchor. Yet when he opens his mouth to speak, out
comes the familiar voice that National Public Radio listeners have
been hearing in the morning five days a week for two decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always a disappointment,'' Edwards, 52, says with a
laugh. ``People have an idea of what you should look like, and you
should never mess with that. They should never take my picture.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards, who was recently in San Francisco to celebrate the 20th
anniversary of the radio show, is usually on the other side of the
table _ asking the questions.
</P>
<P>
   But he says, ``I love talking about `Morning Edition.' It's my
life for 20 years.'' And, yes, he says, the schedule is getting
old; the schedule was old after the first week. So what gets him
out of bed in the middle of the night when sensible people are just
turning off late-night TV?
</P>
<P>
   ``I love doing the program,'' Edwards says. ``It never gets old.
The news changes every day. And I'm doing what I've always wanted
to do: Be on the radio with a national audience. That never gets
old.''
</P>
<P>
   Breaking news never gets old, either. ``The adrenaline is almost
intoxicating,'' he says of the challenge of jockeying a breaking
news story on live radio. He recalls the morning in 1981 when
Egyptian President Anwar Sadat was assassinated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't leave the chair until noon, except when Carl (Kasell)
was doing the newscast and I could sneak a quick bathroom break. By
noon, when `Morning Edition' ended, they still hadn't confirmed
(Sadat) was dead. They were very tight with information because, in
Cairo, they didn't know whether this was a revolution, a coup,
whatever, so they weren't being terribly forthcoming.''
</P>
<P>
   Another big day was the 1981 presidential inauguration of Ronald
Reagan, coupled with the release of American hostages in Iran:
``Two parallel stories intersecting right as we go off the air, and
still no resolution. We still didn't have the hostages out. But
that was a hell of a show.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards was drafted into the job at the inception of the show.
He had been hosting NPR's afternoon news show, ``All Things
Considered,'' when he was asked to step into the a.m. show for 30
days. But a funny thing happened in those early-morning hours: He
started enjoying it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a challenge to make something of this morning program
that would be as good, as professional, as well-received as `All
Things Considered.' I said, what the hell. Let's roll the dice.
Let's see if this can happen.''
</P>
<P>
   And happen it did. ``Morning Edition'' has the most listeners of
any program on NPR. And in large part, this is because of the
nondescript guy with the floppy hair and the voice now familiar to
the show's roughly 8 million listeners.
</P>
<P>
   His calm, wry tones have guided us through tragedy and chaos:
``That's my job, to be calm, or to sound that way when there's
chaos going on amongst the staff, trying to bring in a last-minute
report and people are running around, cussing each other out,
tripping and falling, and I've got the microphone. I'm just
`Bob.'''
</P>
<P>
   Part of being ``just Bob'' is bringing listeners something
called, in NPR parlance, the return. It's the 23-second happy news
spot that signals the return to ``Morning Edition'' from the
affiliates. As Edwards says, ``There's so much death, destruction,
famine, pestilence, war that you've got to lighten the load for
people once in a while.''
</P>
<P>
   One spot of relief over the years, of course, was the Friday
chat with the late baseball announcer Red Barber. Edwards turned
his years of talks with Barber into the 1993 book, ``Fridays with
Red.'' The easy repartee between the two on everything from sports
to camellias didn't start that way. Edwards remembers many a
white-knuckled chat, on his end, until he learned to get in the
groove.
</P>
<P>
   ``Red would throw me curveballs. He would ask me questions. You
spend a lifetime not having opinions, and he'd ask me about my
family and now I've got to censor myself before I answer _ what is
going to make my wife angry? But it was great fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``For an interviewer who's used to doing news interviews, I
wasn't in control,'' he says with a laugh. ``And when you're not in
control in a live radio broadcast, it can be a panicky thing. It
took me probably a couple of years before I said, `To hell with
that. Let's have some fun.' I thought the listener was enjoying it,
though I thought probably the listener enjoyed train wrecks, too.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, his favorite interviews have been those that
captured the spark of spontaneity, ``great talkers'' such as Lauren
Bacall, George Shearing, Dave Brubeck. Some of his least-favorite
interviews have been with politicians. This could have something to
do with one of his worst moments: When a Minnesota senator (now a
``former senator,'' Edwards says pointedly) put Edwards on hold in
the middle of an on-air telephone interview: ``It was bizarre _ I'm
thinking, `Did he really do that?' so I'm saying, `Senator.
Senator.' And then he was back. It wasn't very long.''
</P>
<P>
   Just long enough to get the adrenaline pumping.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
