<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 15:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8470 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-NILE-STYLE-ART-NYTSF &LR;      10-06 1334
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NILE-STYLE-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STYLE OF THE NILE  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from DISCOVER
magazine, contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!----------------------
 &HT;    THREE COLOR SLIDES are available FREE OF CHARGE to purchasers of
this article. The art can be sent ELECTRONICALLY by e-mail. Please
specify that you want the art when you order the article.
 &HT;    ----------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``l'' lifestyle news and ``a'' general news files.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----- This article is also available in Spanish.-----
 &HT;    
 By ROBERT KUNZIG  
 c.1999 Discover magazine  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Nefertiti had large thighs, a decidedly fertile-shaped belly,
and ample hips accentuated by the smallness of her chest.
</P>
<P>
   In Egypt in the 14th century B.C., she was a paragon _ her name
meant ``the beauty has come'' _ and yet Nefertiti did not rely on
her natural looks alone. She applied makeup in bold strokes,
outlining her almond-shaped eyes in black and darkening her brows.
So did her husband the pharaoh.
</P>
<P>
   From the pyramid-builders of the Old Kingdom (2700 B.C. to 2200
B.C.) to Nefertiti and her son-in-law Tutankhamen of the New
Kingdom (1554 B.C. to 1080 B.C.) the ancient Egyptians pampered
their bodies _ from massaging themselves with scented oils to
battling body odor by mashing little balls of incense-scented
porridge into their armpits. They even applied the blood of black
animals to strands of telltale gray.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, they cared for their eyes _ so much so, it now seems,
that they went to the trouble of inventing chemistry.
</P>
<P>
   In Paris, chemists at the Louvre Museum and at L'Oreal, the
French cosmetics manufacturer, recently analyzed eye-makeup
residues preserved in tiny alabaster vases and hollowed-out reeds
dating back to the second millennium B.C.
</P>
<P>
   They discovered that the black or gray makeup _ which the
Egyptians called mesdemet but which later acquired the name kohl
from the Arabic _ contained compounds nearly nonexistent in nature.
</P>
<P>
   Ancient chemists, the researchers say, must have painstakingly
synthesized these substances.
</P>
<P>
   It has been known for more than a century that the main
component of mesdemet was galena, a dark sulfide of lead extracted
by the Egyptians from a mine near the Red Sea. Sometimes they
lightened the galena by mixing in cerussite, a white carbonate of
lead obtained from the same place.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's where the analysis stopped,'' says Philippe Walter
of the Laboratory of the Museums of France. ``The older studies
were very superficial.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Louvre _ his lab is in the basement _ Walter had no
shortage of material for a more probing analysis. The museum owns
roughly 500 ancient Egyptian vessels that were used for toiletries
of one kind or another.
</P>
<P>
   Some arrived in France as booty from Napoleon's ill-fated
invasion of 1798 (its one positive legacy was the scholarly
discipline of Egyptology; a soldier in Napolean's army brought back
the Rosetta stone).
</P>
<P>
   Many of the vessels still contain residues of their original
contents.
</P>
<P>
   But the Louvre's Egyptologists allowed Walter and his colleagues
to take no more than a single cubic millimeter from each of 49
containers. That made the work rather challenging.
</P>
<P>
   The L'Oreal chemists discovered that the Egyptians made mesdemet
creamy by mixing in nearly the same proportion of fat _ between 7
and 10 percent _ that's found in most eye makeup today.
</P>
<P>
   While L'Oreal uses vegetable fat, the Egyptians favored the fat
of animals, possibly geese.
</P>
<P>
   Their choice of minerals was even more surprising. Examining the
powdery residues with an electron microscope and X-rays generated
by a synchrotron particle accelerator, Walter and his colleague
Pauline Martinetto discovered that mesdemet usually contained two
components besides galena and cerussite: laurionite and phosgenite.
They, too, are lead compounds, but contain chlorine as well.
</P>
<P>
   The ancient Egyptians certainly knew how to cook, so it may seem
natural that they should have mastered other types of chemistry as
well. But creating these cosmetic solutions required a very
different process.
</P>
<P>
   ``To make laurionite and phosgenite, they couldn't use fire and
high temperatures,'' Walter says. ``Those compounds are not stable
above 170 degrees Celsius. So they had to use much gentler methods
involving wet chemistry.''
</P>
<P>
   The exact recipe the Egyptians followed has not been found, but
a millennium or two later the Greeks created the same compounds by
first heating galena to drive off the sulfur and form lead oxide,
and then mixing in water and salt while maintaining a low
temperature. Adding water several times a day for 40 days or so
keeps the PH neutral and yields laurionite.
</P>
<P>
   Using a little ground-up natron produces phosgenite.
</P>
<P>
   That would have been a lot of trouble for the Egyptians _
especially because the results would not have been visible. Both
laurionite and phosgenite are white. If the goal was to lighten the
galena, why didn't the Egyptians simply use white cerussite?
</P>
<P>
   Yet most of the mesdemet samples Walter and his colleagues
examined contained the two synthetic compounds as well. What was
the point?
</P>
<P>
   Walter thinks mesdemet must have been medicinal as well as
cosmetic. The Greeks and Romans treated eye diseases with
laurionite and phosgenite, he says, and the Egyptians might very
well have used the compounds for medical purposes too.
</P>
<P>
   Now that lead compounds are known to be toxic _ at least when
ingested _ pharmaceutical researchers aren't interested in
experimenting with them.
</P>
<P>
   But Walter is sure the Egyptian chemists must have been onto
something worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a hard time believing that several civilizations over
3,000 years would have used these substances if they only had a
placebo effect,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Judging from statues of them, says Lise Manniche, an
Egyptologist at the University of Copenhagen, rich Egyptian women
sometimes powdered their faces white with cerussite. On occasion
they may have applied red ocher rouge.
</P>
<P>
   Lipstick too: The Turin papyrus, a kind of Egyptian Kamasutra,
shows a woman painting her lips with a brush.
</P>
<P>
   The famous bust of Nefertiti also has painted lips. So far no
one has ever found a sample of ancient Egyptian lipstick, but
Walter intends to try; there are some vases in the Louvre
collection, he says, whose brownish contents may once have been a
fetching red.
</P>
<P>
   Nefertiti's lips were full and perfect. And though by today's
harsh standards she was plump in places, she also had exquisite
cheekbones and those fabulous eyes. No doubt she was aware of these
assets.
</P>
<P>
   As she aged (it is reasonable to speculate), her desire to
highlight them may only have increased.
</P>
<P>
   Some Egyptologists think her husband, Akhenaton, lost interest
in her (or was it she in him?) and started hanging out in a
separate palace with its own harem.
</P>
<P>
   The essentials of the human life cycle haven't changed. The
Egyptians, as Walter says, were surely driven by some of the same
motives that impel us to use cosmetics: in youth, the desire to
seduce; in later years, the desire to forestall age.
</P>
<P>
   And for the ancient Egyptians, these motives extended to the
grave. That's why perfume and makeup were indispensable funerary
gifts.
</P>
<P>
   ``They enhanced the atmosphere,'' Manniche says.
</P>
<P>
   Cosmetics were a ticket to the cosmos: They promoted sex after
death as a way of achieving eternal life.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to think of a better excuse for inventing makeup _ or
chemistry for that matter.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Kunzig is European Editor of Discover magazine.)
</P>
<P>
   -0-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
