<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLICE-PROFILING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNOR VETOES BILL ON RACIAL PROFILING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MATTHEW YI  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ Angry elected officials said it was ``racist''
for Gov. Gray Davis to veto legislation that would have required
police officers to track the race of motorists they stop.
</P>
<P>
   Racial profiling has become a prominent national issue this year
with several states and the U.S. Congress considering bills to
track it.
</P>
<P>
   Critics have charged that a disproportionate number of minority
motorists, especially blacks and Hispanics, are pulled over by the
police on minor traffic violations or even without cause in hopes
of finding evidence of crime. This practice of targeting minorities
is known as racial profiling.
</P>
<P>
   While Davis, who is a Democrat, vetoed the bill by Sen. Kevin
Murray, D-Los Angeles, at least two other states, Connecticut and
North Carolina, have passed their own versions.
</P>
<P>
   In California, the bill would have required officers who make
traffic stops to record the race or ethnicity of the driver; the
reason for the stop; whether there was a search; and whether there
was an arrest, citation or warning issued.
</P>
<P>
   More than three dozen county and city officials, business
leaders and representatives of minority organizations, gathered at
the steps of the Alameda County Courthouse on Tuesday to denounce
the veto.
</P>
<P>
   The governor had said ``there is no evidence that this practice
is taking place statewide'' and that such sweeping legislation
would be too costly and would place a heavy burden on the police.
</P>
<P>
   But those reasons are unwarranted and poor excuses for not
signing the bill, officials here said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a racist action,'' said Alameda County Supervisor Mary
King. ``In my experience, those who participate in racist actions
are racist, and he has an opportunity to prove that he is not.''
</P>
<P>
   Supervisor Keith Carson also blasted Davis, adding that he would
not forget the governor's veto.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time Governor Davis comes into our community, we're
going to ask him the hard questions. Why did he veto this
legislation? Why has he been so inactive ... in trying to bridge
the gap of racial divide?'' Carson said.
</P>
<P>
   Davis spokesman Michael Bustamante said it was ``laughable'' to
say that the governor is racist because he vetoed the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``This governor has spent his career defending the rights of all
individuals, be they women, minority or anyone else,'' Bustamante
said.
</P>
<P>
   He said Davis believed it would not be appropriate to force
every police agency in the state to collect the data when they may
not have the resources to carry out the mandate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rather, he has ordered the law enforcement agency under his
care, the California Highway Patrol, to look at the issue,''
Bustamante said. ``If local law enforcement agencies want to do it,
there's no reason why they can't do it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
