<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 15:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8475 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-CANADA-FILMS-BOS &LR;      10-06 1481
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-FILMS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOORAY FOR CANADA-WOOD? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ The signs rerouting traffic and warning off
pedestrians have become nearly ubiquitous in this French-flavored
city of gray granite and silver church bells: ``Tournage
Cinematographique'' _ film crew at work.
</P>
<P>
   Travolta is in town, doing ``Battlefield Earth.'' Bruce Willis
has come and gone for ``The Whole Nine Yards.'' And Eddie Murphy's
``Pluto Nash'' is in the wings. All headed for a theater near you,
though you won't have a clue that French Canada is the real setting
for these ostensibly American flicks.
</P>
<P>
   Look out, Los Angeles: There's yet another ``Hollywood North''
looming across the border. Montreal is suddenly hot, vying with
archrivals Toronto and Vancouver as a Canadian shooting set for
anyplace _ standing in for gaslit Manhattan circa 1890, the tawdry
gaming pits of present-day Las Vegas, even a far-future Earth
occupied by a plundering alien race.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fashionable to do American movies in Canada,'' Travolta
told a Montreal news conference. ``I don't register a
controversy.''
</P>
<P>
   Perk up your ears, John. The warning drums are thudding loud in
Tinseltown, and the natives are astir.
</P>
<P>
   Montreal's soaring film fortunes come just as the real Hollywood
is getting seriously rattled by the stunning northward flight of
film and television productions over the past decade, mainly to
British Columbia, Ontario, and Quebec.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, several thousand California film folk _ directors,
actors, camera operators, set designers, lighting technicians,
grips, and gofers _ thronged down Hollywood Boulevard waving Old
Glory and jeering the Maple Leaf.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bring Hollywood home!'' roared the marchers.
</P>
<P>
   Home from Canada, that is. This stolid northern neighbor, better
known for salmon fishing than sex appeal, is siphoning off billions
of dollars and tens of thousands of jobs from the world's most
glamorous industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting massacred,'' said Jack De Govia, a motion
picture art director and chairman of California's Film and
Television Action Committee. ```Canada is hijacking the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   For their part, Canadians can't seem to decide whether to crow
or cower as Hollywood roars its anger like MGM's famous lion.
</P>
<P>
   ``C'mon, relax, Americans, Hollywood is still center of the
universe,'' said Mark DesRochers, a spokesman for the British
Columbia Film Commission. ``Our industry has grown quickly, grown a
lot, but compared to California, we're not even on the radar.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the closeup, Canada's movie modesty rings a trifle false.
</P>
<P>
   According to one recent study, conducted by the Cambridge-based
Monitor Company, Hollywood suffered $2.8 billion in lost production
expenditures in 1998, plus an estimated 60,000 jobs over the past
three years, to so-called runaway productions _ American films or
TV shows shot mostly in foreign places. Canada attracted the huge
majority of the runaways, more than 80 percent, worth some $2.2
billion last year, according to the study, commissioned by the
Screen Actors Guild and the Directors Guild of America.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian officials insist that figure is inflated.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Explosive increase
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But no one denies that the cross-border expansion of the film
industry during the 1990s has been explosive, and that Canada's
gain has been at least partly Hollywood's loss. Last year, for
instance, Ontario alone saw ``foreign film and TV production'' _
read: American _ jump by 57 percent, to $243 million.
</P>
<P>
   In Quebec, Travolta may be the star of ``Battlefield Earth'' _ a
big-money science-fiction epic _ but much of the cast and nearly
all of the production crew are Canadian.
</P>
<P>
   That's bad news for Hollywood, especially for the front-line
workers _ the technicians, heavy lifters, film editors, bit actors,
equipment operators, hairdressers, and others who form the real
backbone of the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a significant, alarming shift away from
traditional production centers in the US to foreign locations,
especially Canada,'' said Rafe Greenlee, a spokesman for the Guild.
``This is a national problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, three of the top seven production centers for what is
seen as a quintessentially American industry are now in Canada:
Vancouver, Toronto, and Montreal join Los Angeles, New York City,
Orlando, and Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   In Hollywood trade magazines, Canada has become the new Evil
Empire. Typical of the accusations hurled across the 49th parallel
these days is the ad placed recently in Variety by a committee of
directors and actors: ``Canada is killing the television and
feature film industry in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   That's hyperbole, of course, from the world capital of hype. But
it's a sign of how much Hollywood is feeling the big chill from
Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Some industry analysts say Canada is just an easy scapegoat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Major studios are cutting back on the number of films, there's
intense focus on costs, and jobs are being lost,'' said Jack Kyser,
chief economist for the Los Angeles Development Corp., a business
association. ``Canada is a part of Hollywood's problem. But just
one part.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, California politicians are rallying around
Hollywood's cause. ``We in the United States cannot permit the loss
of production jobs without a struggle,'' said Representative Howard
L. Berman, a California Democrat, in a letter to Canada's
ambassador to the United States, Raymond Chretien.
</P>
<P>
   Canadians see Hollywood's alarm as overwrought. And insulting.
</P>
<P>
   Said Kim Campbell, Canada's consul general in Los Angeles, ``The
world film industry is not an American industry. We don't see it as
something that belongs to California, and that Canada is not
entitled to a share.''
</P>
<P>
   And Andre Lafond, film commissioner of Montreal, referring to
Americans angered by Canada's emergence, said: ``They have a
feeling we're stealing something from them, and they are perhaps a
little right. We have a word for that in Quebec _ competition.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A smaller price tag
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Never mind Travolta's assertion that shooting in Canada is
``fashionable.'' The real attraction is the bottom line. The
Canadian dollar has plummeted to historic lows against the
greenback. That means most everything comes cheaper across the
border, from snacks for the extras to trailers for the stars.
</P>
<P>
   Even more appealing are lavish tax credits, rebates, and other
incentives offered by Canada's federal government and most
provinces.
</P>
<P>
   With the 1-2 combination of the exchange rate and tax credits, a
director shooting in Canada can knock anywhere from 10 percent to
30 percent off production costs, compared with a similar shoot in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, cheapness isn't everything; otherwise movies would
all be made in Mexico City or Budapest. Canada also offers high
production values, first-rate infrastructure, proximity to the
United States, skilled film crews, actors who can pass for
Americans in smaller parts (Americans of all colors _ another bonus
is that Canada is as multi-ethnic as its neighbor), as well as
urban, suburban, and rural backgrounds that make convincing
stand-ins for Anywhere USA.
</P>
<P>
   How convincing? Did you catch ``Good Will Hunting''? The 1997
film, in which Matt Damon plays a tormented blue-collar math
genius, won praise for the way it depicted the authentic ``feel''
of metropolitan Boston, from Southie to Harvard Square. But while
the skyline and a few wide-angle street shots were filmed around
the city, the bulk of the movie was made in Ontario.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, in the two most recent ``Spenser'' TV movies,
Boston's hard-nosed private eye is really sleuthing his way down
the mean streets of, um, Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Hollywood has been pulling the same trick for
decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't that the whole idea of movies? They make you believe a
reality that isn't real,'' said Lafond. ``If Montreal can be more
Boston than Boston, it's just movie magic.''
</P>
<P>
   Magic, sure, but Canada is getting more out of the deal than
fairy dust.
</P>
<P>
   In British Columbia alone, American filmmaking accounted for
more than 70 percent of Vancouver's $565 million TV and film
industry _ an industry projected to soar past $700 million this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Moviemaking has become so intensive, so pervasive, that
passersby in the country's three major cities hardly gawk anymore.
</P>
<P>
   In Montreal, there's even grumbling that American moviemakers
are much too thick on the ground, causing traffic congestion,
forcing up rents, and hogging all the seats at the fancier
restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome to Montrealywood,'' wrote Josh Freed, a columnist for
the Montreal Gazette. ``American crews have already rented every
vacant house and cappuccino maker in town, and will soon be closing
a street near you . . .''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-99 1511EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991006.0171 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 15:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8476 &Cx1f; tth-z
r a BC-GENE-THERAPY-SPI &LR;      10-06 1178
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENE-THERAPY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESURRECTING GENE THERAPY'S PROMISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 (With GENE-THERAPY-LUCAS, GENE-THERAPY-FROHNMAYER,
GENE-THERAPY-GLOSSARY)  
 (Art available for New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CAROL SMITH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Ever since molecular biologists figured out how to
clone genes, the concept of ``fixing'' malfunctioning genes to cure
disease has been a siren call for science.
</P>
<P>
   But despite a promising start, there were no quick or complete
cures.
</P>
<P>
   ``People had a lot of unrealistic expectations for gene
therapy,'' said Dr. Bonnie Ramsey, director of the Cystic Fibrosis
Center at Children's Hospital and Regional Medical Center in
Seattle and co-director of the Gene Therapy Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``People assumed the first time they put a vector (carrying a
new gene) in, there would be a cure. But like any new area of
research, it takes several permutations.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, a group of Seattle scientists has found a way to slip new
genes into cells at a much higher rate, fixing one of the key flaws
in early approaches. A few patients are undergoing experimental
therapy trials which, if successful, could be expanded.
</P>
<P>
   The Seattle scientists, from the Fred Hutchinson Cancer Research
Center, the University of Washington, Children's and the Veterans
Affairs Medical Center in Seattle, are in the vanguard of
researchers around the country who are trying to resurrect the
early promise of gene therapy.
</P>
<P>
   The first gene therapy trials were conducted in 1990 on two
patients with a genetic immune disorder called adenosine deaminase
deficiency (ADA), also known as the ``boy in the bubble'' disease.
Patients with ADA have a genetic defect that shuts down their
immune systems.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers were able to insert a new copy of the corrective
gene into a significant number of cells in the patients, and bring
about therapeutic improvement in one of them. But not enough of the
enzyme was produced to effect a cure, said A. Dusty Miller, a
virologist at Fred Hutchinson and a UW professor of molecular
biology who worked on that early trial. Miller pioneered some of
the altered viral particles used for delivering genes. Since then,
gene therapy has produced many more false starts, but no cures,
Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   The disappointments have driven gene therapy from the headlines
and researchers back to the bench.
</P>
<P>
   But the Hutch team's work, using a disarmed virus as a kind of
Trojan horse to get more ``good'' genes into the cells, could
provide the push that gene therapy needs to become reality. Some of
the most exciting work is being done in Dr. Hans-Peter Kiem's lab
at Fred Hutchinson.
</P>
<P>
   By refining the process of infecting cells with one of Miller's
viral vectors created to deliver the new genes, researchers have
been able to get genes transferred into 10 percent to 20 percent of
cells.
</P>
<P>
   ``That range is sufficient (to correct) for many genetic
diseases,'' said Kiem, an oncologist and assistant professor of
medicine at the University of Washington. In the past,
gene-transfer rates were less than 0.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's 10 to 100 times better than it was three to four years
ago,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The technique borrows the ability of a ``retrovirus'' to insert
its own DNA into the genome of a host cell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Viruses have evolved over millions of years to do this job,''
Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists use the viral ``envelope'' to deliver the new genes
to the cells by removing the viral replication genes and replacing
them with the genes they want transferred into the cell. They've
also perfected new techniques for getting more of the virus to
infect the target cells.
</P>
<P>
   A new trial using those techniques on patients with leukocyte
adherence deficiency, a fatal genetic blood disorder, currently is
under way in Seattle. If it proves successful, that could help
expedite trials in other diseases.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking at other diseases that can be corrected by
replacing a single gene,'' Kiem said. Such diseases could include
hemophilia, a bleeding disorder; Fanconi anemia, a DNA repair
defect that predisposes patients to cancer; Gaucher's disease, a
disorder that affects the body's ability to process fat; and a
number of other immune deficiency diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, single-gene disorders could yield insights that will
help scientists tackle more complex diseases, such as cancer or
cardiovascular disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely, it will help us deal with diseases with more than
one gene,'' Kiem said.
</P>
<P>
   Many questions remain, however. Researchers are watching the
current trial to see whether patients develop immune reactions to
proteins made by the new genes. They also want to see the
population of corrected cells increase over time as the cells
carrying the new genes divide and multiply.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the death recently of a young man who died four
days after participating in a gene therapy experiment at the
University of Pennsylvania in Philadelphia may weaken support for
the technique.
</P>
<P>
   Jesse Gelsinger, an 18-year-old who died Sept. 17, had received
an infusion into his liver of altered viral particles carrying
genes intended to correct a rare metabolic defect. Other patients
treated in the clinical trial so far have done well, with some
reporting improvement.
</P>
<P>
   Gelsinger's defect, called ornithine transcarbamylase, was not
life-threatening and it had been controlled through diet and drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question this will put a damper on gene therapy for
a while,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   But any invasive therapy, even routine day surgeries, carries
risk, he said. The primary obstacles in gene therapy have been
mostly technical and not due to any unusual safety concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Early disappointments surrounding gene therapy have plenty of
precedent in the history of medicine, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Surgery was first attempted without the benefit of anesthesia or
sterile technique. It took decades to perfect the bone marrow
transplant, now one of the most powerful treatments for cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, gene therapy could deliver the same kinds of payoff.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers are already exploring other vectors, besides
retroviruses, to widen the range of diseases that could be
addressed by gene therapy.
</P>
<P>
   Targeted Genetics Corp., a Seattle-based biotechnology company,
for example, is developing gene therapy approaches to cystic
fibrosis and cancer that use different vector systems.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at the University of Pennsylvania are hoping to
start new trials for muscular dystrophy and hemophilia within a few
months. Groups at the University of Indiana, Harvard University and
the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill are gearing up for
gene therapy studies in other diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Work is even under way at the Salk Institute for Biological
Studies in La Jolla, Calif., to harness HIV, a virus known for its
aggressive invasion of a wide range of cells, as a gene-delivery
tool.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't understand everything right now,'' Miller said. ``But
that doesn't mean we won't.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-99 1513EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991006.0172 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 15:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8480 &Cx1f; tth-z
r a BC-GENE-THERAPY-LUCAS-SP     10-06 1082
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENE-THERAPY-LUCAS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEST GENE-THERAPY PROCEDUCE MAY OFFER HOPE FOR BLOOD DISEASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CAROL SMITH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lucas Parks spent his 16th birthday hooked up to intravenous
lines and monitors in Room 318 at Children's Hospital and Medical
Center in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   For some kids, that would be a major disappointment. For this
Tennessee teenager, it was a gift.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas has leukocyte adherence deficiency, a rare genetic blood
disorder that often kills children before age 5. On Aug. 28, he
became the second person in the world to receive an experimental
gene-therapy treatment that researchers hope will restore his blood
to normal.
</P>
<P>
   In LAD, the white cells _ one of the body's main armaments
against invading pathogens _ lack a ``sticky'' protein they need to
attach to bacteria. Without that protein, even minor scratches can
turn into gaping wounds and life-threatening infections.
</P>
<P>
   The white blood cells never leave the bloodstream and go to the
site of the infection, said Dr. Dennis Hickstein, a professor of
medicine at the University of Washington and LAD expert at the VA
Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a convoy of ambulances without brakes screaming past
the site of the accident,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Simple wounds can take months to heal, often requiring painful
and disfiguring skin grafts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eleven is supposed to be a long lifespan,'' said Dana Parks,
Lucas' mother. Lucas was diagnosed at age 1 after a mysterious
fever put him in the hospital for two months. At first doctors
thought he had leukemia, but a chance encounter with a doctor from
the University of Tennessee revealed the rare diagnosis. At the
time, there were only 100 known cases of the disease worldwide, and
doctors knew almost nothing about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were afraid we were going to lose him,'' Dana Parks said.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, infections have put Lucas in the hospital for
weeks at a time, every other month or so, she said. ``But we try to
let him lead as normal a life as we can.''
</P>
<P>
   Normal for Lucas means building model cars, a favorite hobby,
and getting outside to hunt, fish and camp as often as possible. He
tries not to let his disease get in the way of being a freshman in
high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Lucas, things are either good or bad, there's nothing in
between,'' said his father, Steve Parks. ``He keeps going so hard,
it's sometimes a few days before we realize things have gotten bad
again. He keeps on a good front.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucas, who was struggling with several nasty sores during his
Seattle visit, was too weak to talk much, but still glad to be
here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was good when I first heard about it (the
treatment),'' he said in a long Southern drawl.
</P>
<P>
   Current treatments are limited to white cell transfusions,
antibiotics, and bone marrow transplantation. But bone marrow
transplants, which involve massive doses of chemotherapy and
radiation that wipe out the body's immune system, are toxic and
potentially life-threatening for patients with LAD.
</P>
<P>
   The new gene-therapy protocol offers the potential of a cure
without the risks of a bone marrow transplant. LAD, which afflicts
about 200 people worldwide, is caused by a defect in a single gene.
Doctors hope they can correct the disease by inserting a good copy
of a gene into the patient's cells.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists will try to slip the correct gene into stem cells,
the master cells made in the bone marrow that give rise to all the
other cells of the blood and immune system. If the re-engineered
stem cells persist and multiply, they should give white cells that
descend from them the ability to produce the sticky protein and
ward off bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   If successful, the new technique could be used to cure other
genetic blood diseases, such as hemophilia, Fanconi anemia, a
disease that causes the bone marrow to fail, or Gaucher's disease,
a disorder that affects the body's ability to metabolize fat.
</P>
<P>
   It may also signal a rebirth in the gene-therapy movement,
giving new life to attempts to cure other genetic diseases such as
cystic fibrosis.
</P>
<P>
   The protocol being used on Lucas Parks was developed through a
collaboration between Fred Hutchinson Cancer Research Center, the
University of Washington, the Veterans Affairs Medical Center, and
Children's Hospital and Regional Medical Center. Much of the work
to develop a gene therapy for LAD was done by Tom Bauer, a
researcher at the VA who helped spearhead the clinical trial.
</P>
<P>
   Although Hickstein originally cloned the missing gene for LAD,
it was Bauer who spent the past seven years developing the protocol
using gene therapy to treat the disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's worked hard on this,'' Hickstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas' treatment involved drawing blood, isolating the stem
cells and then treating them in the laboratory with a specially
engineered virus designed to ``infect'' his own cells with a new
gene.
</P>
<P>
   The genetically altered stem cells were then reintroduced into
Lucas' bloodstream.
</P>
<P>
   The technique is based on the ability of a special class of
viruses, called retroviruses, to insert their own genetic material
into the genomes of the cells they infect. For gene therapy, the
retrovirus has been modified so instead of transferring its own
disease-causing genes, it transfers a piece of foreign DNA, in this
case a correct copy of the gene that will tell Lucas' body how to
make the missing protein it needs to fight infections.
</P>
<P>
   A 20-year-old woman, the first patient ever officially diagnosed
with LAD, was the first to receive the treatment last summer.
Initial reports are positive. One month after receiving her
genetically altered cells, her body was showing signs that the
treatment was beginning to work.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors use a ``skin scraping'' to test how well the white cells
are working, Hickstein said. In the first patient's case, the
number of white blood cells responding to the scraping site had
more than doubled, compared with a similar test done before
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Patients don't need 100 percent restoration of gene function to
fight infection. ``Even if you have 2 percent of normal (white cell
response), it would help,'' he said. ``You don't need much.''
</P>
<P>
   It will be several months before scientists have a good read on
whether gene therapy has worked for Lucas.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas, who has been anxious to get the treatment since first
hearing about it, is hoping for the best.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm lucky to be in this research,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
