<HEADER>
A8482 &Cx1f; tth-z
r a BC-GENE-THERAPY-GLOSSARY     10-06 0317
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENE-THERAPY-GLOSSARY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TERMS USED IN GENE THERAPY 
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bone marrow _ The spongy, inner tissue of bone that generates
all the cells of the blood and immune system.
</P>
<P>
   Bone marrow transplant _ The process of killing a patient's
diseased bone marrow with high-dose chemotherapy and radiation,
then replacing it with new marrow from a healthy donor.
</P>
<P>
   DNA _ Abbreviation for deoxyribonucleic acid, the molecules that
carry genetic information.
</P>
<P>
   Fanconi anemia _ A genetic disease that causes cells in the bone
marrow to die.
</P>
<P>
   Gaucher's disease _ A genetic disease that affects fat
metabolism.
</P>
<P>
   Gene _ Pieces of DNA that encode genetic traits and information.
</P>
<P>
   Gene cloning _ The process of identifying the gene responsible
for a particular disease and synthesizing copies of it for use in
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Gene therapy _ A technique for correcting genetic diseases by
introducing a ``correct'' copy of the gene into the patient's cells
to compensate for their own defective gene.
</P>
<P>
   Genome _ The complete set of genes in the chromosomes of each
cell.
</P>
<P>
   Hemophilia _ A hereditary bleeding disorder caused by the lack
of certain clotting factors in the blood.
</P>
<P>
   Leukocyte _ Immune system cells, also called ``white cells,''
that fight infection.
</P>
<P>
   Leukocyte adherence deficiency _ A genetic immune disease in
which the white blood cells lack a protein that allows them to
attach to bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   Retrovirus _ A class of viruses that infects cells by inserting
its own DNA into the genetic material of a host cell.
</P>
<P>
   Stem cell _ A progenitor blood cell made in the bone marrow that
can give rise to all the cells of the blood and immune system,
including red blood cells, white cells to fight infection, and
platelets for clotting.
</P>
<P>
   Vector _ A biological carrier, often a virus, capable of
delivering genetic material to a cell.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
