<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 15:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8502 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-RATTO-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      10-06 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RATTO-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRUNKEN FANS ARE THE FOUL ODDBALLS IN SPORTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RAY RATTO  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Dale Carter has a huge knot near his right eye,
and potential permanent damage to his vision. He got hit by a metal
object thrown by one of the fans at Denver's Mile High Stadium as
he came off the field Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Carter plays for the home team. That is, if his eye isn't so
damaged that the sentence should read, ``Carter played for the home
team.''
</P>
<P>
   This story has been somewhat underreported given its
ramifications, not to mention its most recent antecedents: the fans
at the Ryder Cup in Brookline, Mass., performing the Dance of the
Drunken Swine for an entire weekend, and Houston's Billy Spiers
being literally mugged while playing right field in Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   In short, fans have gone beyond just abusive, and one wonders if
maybe we aren't closing in on the day when fans finally outlive
their usefulness on site.
</P>
<P>
   There have been plenty of examples where the athletes have
baited fans into bad behavior, but Carter did nothing more
provocative than come off the field after the Broncos' 21-13 loss
to the New York Jets. The victims in the Ryder Cup mess were the
European golfers, who had the bad breeding to be bred in another
country. Spiers was standing in right field minding his own
business, which was with his back to the fan who jumped him.
</P>
<P>
   Some smart people suggest that the common denominator here is
alcohol, and that makes sense as far as it goes. These people
suggest that selling beer, wine or mixed drinks at events is just
asking for trouble, and of course that is true.
</P>
<P>
   If the man who jumped Spiers wasn't drunk, he ought to be
looking at jail time, and the same goes for the guy (at least we
assume it's a guy) who clocked Carter. And remember, there is no
constitutional right to be served beer at a sporting event, so
don't start with that, ``But it's an American tradition'' nonsense.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but the resourceful ticket-buying creep can get around a
potential alcohol ban by coming in drunk (and if you've seen a
tailgate at any 49ers or Raiders game, you know how common that
is). And without Breathalyzers and metal detectors at every gate,
said creep will still be a threat.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, at some point, we can pretty much expect someone to up
the ante some day and bring a firearm and foul mood to a game.
</P>
<P>
   More precisely, though, the problem lay not in the bottom of the
bottle but in the heart of its user. Somewhere in the recent past,
fans decided that, at the prices they're paying, they have a right
to impact the game in more than the cheer-as-loud-as- you-can way _
as though the whole idea of going to a game is to impress your pals
with the limits you will disregard to get noticed.
</P>
<P>
   And this is where the line that properly separated fans from the
objects of their affectionshas become blurred. Players are now
being attacked for the affront of plying their craft, and if those
are the new rules of engagement, then the days of fans in the
stands are seeing their end.
</P>
<P>
   You think not? You think we overstate? The three incidents
described above all happened in the last three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   You think we generalize where we should specify? Well, as we
approach the day a player is killed on the field, what makes you
think that the people running the games we watch will be any less
sweeping in their assumptions? How many athletes, confronted with
the growing possibility they could be beaten, or worse, while
performing, are going to stand quietly and take it because of the
sometimes broadly applied notion the customer is always right?
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, we have three fresh incidents where the customer
was dead wrong, and in the Spiers and Carter cases, ought to be
dead wrong in prison. Nobody's going to worry about the 75,000 at
Mile High who didn't throw a piece of metal at an athlete's head,
or the 11,000 at County Stadium who stayed in the seats they paid
for. If this is where we're heading, maybe banning beer is only a
half step. We may be heading, incrementally, toward the day when
the sixth man, the seventh man, the 10th man and the 12th man teams
prize so highly will be invited to stay home and buy the games on
pay-per-view, or submit to full body searches on the way in and out
of stadiums.
</P>
<P>
   And when it happens, don't complain about another lost slice of
Americana. Dale Carter and Billy Spiers showed how much closer we
are to that day than we want to believe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
