<SLUG> BC-RECIPES-BUNDY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENJOY CORNY DOGS AT HOME, TOO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's State Fair time in Texas, so we thought we'd salute the
Lone Star State by hoisting a corny dog.
</P>
<P>
   But you don't have to go all the way to Fair Park to enjoy one.
Jennie Johnson sent in her homemade version.
</P>
<P>
   CORNY DOGS
</P>
<P>
   12 hot dogs
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups skim milk
</P>
<P>
   3 eggs
</P>
<P>
   1 cup cornmeal
</P>
<P>
   2 cups flour
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   Vegetable oil, for frying
</P>
<P>
   Boil, then dry hot dogs (this is important). Mix remaining
ingredients, stir until smooth. Dip hot dogs in batter (you can use
skewer sticks in the hot dogs) and lower gently into 350-degree oil
in a deep fryer. Cook until golden brown. Drain on paper towel.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 490 calories, 30 grams fat, 41
grams carbohydrates, 15 grams protein, 89 milligrams cholesterol,
1,191 milligrams sodium, 55 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   Another restaurant: And here's another dining-out special made
at home. This recipe is reprinted from the Miami Herald.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   OLIVE GARDEN'S TUSCAN SOUP
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6
</P>
<P>
   1 pound (about) spicy sausage
</P>
<P>
   1 slice of bacon, diced into 1/4-inch pieces
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup onions, diced 1/8-inch thick
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 teaspoons minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   1 quart rich chicken stock, or 1 fluid ounce chicken base mixed
with 1 quart water
</P>
<P>
   2 medium potatoes, cut in half lengthwise, then cut into
1/4-inch slices
</P>
<P>
   2 cups kale, cut in half, then sliced into 1/16-inch strips
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup heavy whipping cream
</P>
<P>
   Place the sausage on a baking sheet and lightly prick the skins.
Bake in a 300-degree oven for 15 minutes, or until well-done. Cut
in half lengthwise, then slice. Measure out 1 1/2 cups. Place bacon
and onions in a 3- to 4-quart saucepan and cook over medium heat
until the onions are almost clear. Add the garlic and cook 1 more
minute. Add the chicken stock and potatoes. Bring to a boil. Reduce
heat to simmer and cook 15 minutes. Add the sausage, greens and
whipping cream, and simmer 5 more minutes before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 316 calories, 24 grams fat, 14
grams carbohydrates, 11 grams protein, 60 milligrams cholesterol,
930 milligrams sodium, 68 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
