<HEADER>
A8519 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-ARTMUSEUM-TEXAS-TEX     10-06 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTMUSEUM-TEXAS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN ANGELO TAKES ART TO HEART WITH NEW MUSEUM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARK LOWRY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When architect Malcolm Holzman says the new San Angelo Museum of
Fine Arts and Education Center is ``unusual for a number of
reasons,'' he's not kidding. It's a decidedly unconventional
structure for the West Texas town of 90,000 known more for mohair
exports than for visual art _ but that's also why the town has
embraced it.
</P>
<P>
   Marked by its curved copper roof, the building has drawn
comparisons to a saddle, a covered wagon, and, if you listen to
museum director Howard Taylor, a Pace picante sauce bottle on its
side. In any case, it is a deceptively subtle visual impression of
West Texas _ exactly what the architects wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was one of our first questions,'' Holzman says. ``How do
we make this building look like San Angelo?''
</P>
<P>
   The museum is the latest in a long history of Texas projects
done by architectural firm Hardy Holzman Pfeiffer Associates, which
has offices in New York City and Los Angeles. Most recently,
Holzman headed projects for the Lucille ``Lupe'' Murchison
Performing Arts Center at the University of North Texas and the
Walsh Center for the Performing Arts at Texas Christian University.
</P>
<P>
   His partners' endeavors include the recent Radio City Music Hall
renovation, which opened Monday, and the Brooklyn Museum of Art,
home of the art world's latest controversy, over its ``Sensations''
exhibit.
</P>
<P>
   The San Angelo museum includes four galleries, not all directly
connected. A central atrium, which provides breathing space, is
overlooked by walkways on the upper levels that lead to an outdoor
sculpture terrace. Here stand works by Luis Jimenez, Jesus Bautista
Moroles and others.
</P>
<P>
   The largest gallery features pan-European Old Master paintings
from the 17th to 19th centuries, lent by Houston's Sarah Campbell
Blaffer Foundation. An adjoining and more intimate space with low
ceilings highlights landscape and still-life paintings by
Cuban-born Texas artist Lilian Garcia-Roig.
</P>
<P>
   Another gallery showcases an exhibit of projects by Hardy
Holzman Pfeiffer Associates, plus a retrospective look, if you
will, at the museum's design process. Models of previous roof ideas
_ from peaked to rounded _ show why the current look is indeed the
best choice: It's functional and a little irreverent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normally we wouldn't'' show old models, Holzman says. ``It's
more like office gossip.''
</P>
<P>
   The wood ceilings are supported by beams, all of which rest on
parallel cement walls unified by five square windows in an arching
design. The floors are of West Texas mesquite, as are the benches,
which are cushioned in natural Texas wool from Alvaredo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to (use) materials from the region,'' Holzman says.
</P>
<P>
   The exterior sports a typical Holzman-in-Texas material _
limestone. There are three levels to this, the middle section a
rougher, sedimentary layer replete with meteorite and fossil
pockmarks.
</P>
<P>
   Adjacent to the building is the Paseo de Santa Angela, a walkway
connecting historic Fort Concho to the downtown area. From the
paseo, foreboding, conical steps lead to the museum's main
entrance.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at every major museum in the world,'' Taylor says,
``there are steps. And always, there are people sitting on them. I
project that in 10 years, this will be a popular place.''
</P>
<P>
   In all, the museum slopes 25 feet from end to end. ``It really
conforms to the site,'' Taylor says.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the atrium, one wall is lime green, a color that connects
to the exterior, and not just because ``limestone'' and ``lime
green'' share a word. Both exude a cool, calm confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``HHPA really likes to expose the character of a building,''
Taylor says.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most interesting aspect of the museum is its
connection with nearby Angelo State University. An additional back
area, funded by the university, provides educational facilities for
the school's ceramics program _ classrooms, outdoor and indoor
kilns, supply areas, etc.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the museum, an auditorium serves as a place
for public receptions. Eventually, the museum will screen films,
hold the city's chamber music series and, the most intriguing idea,
offer culinary classes.
</P>
<P>
   The art museum doesn't have a permanent collection yet _ but
it's working on it. It recently acquired a piece from Fort Worth
artist Vernon Fisher. Exhibits will be encyclopedic, showcasing
classical works and Texas contemporary artists such as Robert
Wilson. Every two years, the museum will host an international
ceramics exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor recognizes there's a long way to go, but a fresh new
building is definitely a great start.
</P>
<P>
   ``San Angelo will never be a major art market,'' he says. ``But
it can be a wonderful place to make art.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   The San Angelo Museum of Fine Arts
</P>
<P>
   Hours are 10 a.m.-4 p.m. Tuesday through Saturday and 1-4 p.m.
Sunday. The museum is at 1 Love St. in San Angelo.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets: Admission is $2; $1 for senior citizens and children.
</P>
<P>
   Information: Call (915) 653-3333.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
