<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER MAKEOVER FOR AOL 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PETER H. LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   America Online, the world's largest Internet service, this week
announced the worldwide debut of a new version of the basic
software used by its 18 million subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   AOL customers do not need the new software, AOL Version 5.0, but
it is actually a pleasant improvement over earlier versions. It
maintains AOL's traditional emphasis on ease of use instead of
jazzy, cutting-edge innovation, but it does add a handful of new
features intended to appeal to a Norman Rockwell audience.
</P>
<P>
   The new features on the AOL welcoming screen include My Calendar
and My Places (right below My Weather) and, inexplicably breaking
syntax, You've Got Pictures.
</P>
<P>
   AOL has also made changes behind the screen. It has expanded
both the number and length of the screen names available to
subscribers, improved its search engine for finding information not
just within AOL but also on the wider World Wide Web, and bolstered
the reliability of the service to reduce the number of busy signals
and broken connections.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, with version 5.0, America Online has succeeded in its
declared attempt to ``make the connected experience even more
central to members' everyday lives,'' assuming that your life was
somehow incomplete without having access to an online picture
album, and a digital calendar, plus a witty new screen name.
</P>
<P>
   With its new My Calendar feature, in fact, AOL goes so far as to
urge subscribers to ``plan your life online!''
</P>
<P>
   That is essentially the same vision described last month by the
closest thing America Online has to a direct rival, the MSN.Com
online service from the Microsoft Corp., which pithily calls its
new vision the Everyday Web.
</P>
<P>
   AOL wants to be the window through which its customers get the
most current news and weather, check up-to-the-minute stock prices
and investment portfolios, share letters and pictures with Grandma,
search for information, find out what time Sally has to be at
soccer practice, go shopping on line, play games, check Billy's
school lunch menu, set up a family Web site, make plans for weekend
entertainment, pursue hobbies, and trade gossip and jokes with
friends.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if you are doing all this at standard dial-up modem
speeds, you probably don't have time left in the day to have much
of a life.
</P>
<P>
   The agenda is ambitious, but AOL 5.0 manages to pull it off with
a newly redesigned welcome screen that cleverly organizes all these
activities, and more, into a relatively simple and orderly
rectangle.
</P>
<P>
   My Calendar may turn out to be the most popular new feature. It
is a server-based calendar, which means the calendar does not
reside on the user's own computer, but rather in a giant digital
brain floating in a vat of goo at AOL's headquarters, with
tentacles stretching out to any computing device it can reach.
Well, perhaps that is overly dramatic, but you get the idea.
</P>
<P>
   What it means, really, is that AOL subscribers can check their
personal calendars from any computer that has an Internet
connection and a Web browser. It can be checked from home, from
work and on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Later, when AOL figures out how to do it, the personal calendar
will be available on noncomputer devices like smart digital phones,
pocket-size organizers or even automobile dashboard screens.
</P>
<P>
   AOL asserts that it will use all its skills to protect this
private information from computer criminals and snoops. But I would
probably not make intimate or sensitive entries like, ``Tuesday
3:30 p.m.: Drive gold bullion to the bank.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the calendar is server-based, AOL can ``push'' local
event information, like the weather or local music and television
listings, down to the subscriber's calendar. The information is
based on the user's zip code.
</P>
<P>
   But even though it had already asked for my zip code, My
Calendar still asked me to choose my personal weather and concert
choices from a long list of cities. The only explanation I can
think of is that people who enter a zip code for Buffalo, say, are
graciously being offered a chance to pretend that they can order
weather from San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   AOL is famous for its You've Got Mail! alerts, and now, for
better or worse, it has added You've Got Photos. AOL, in
partnership with Eastman Kodak and a joint AOL-Kodak venture called
Picturevision, wants America to throw away its shoeboxes and store
photographs instead in online digital photo albums.
</P>
<P>
   People with digital cameras can easily take advantage of this
new service, but so can people with conventional film cameras.
Thousands of drugstore and photo finishing centers around the
country will soon offer customers the choice of getting pictures
back as conventional prints, as digital pictures posted directly to
a private photo album on AOL, or both.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The owner then can discard bad shots, order special prints and
copies of the good ones, send photos to friends and relatives, and
_ this is the scary part _ set up slide shows of vacation photos to
share with millions of unsuspecting viewers all over the world.
</P>
<P>
   The You've got Pictures feature in AOL 5.0 works only with newly
developed pictures. AOL says future releases of the software will
enable people to upload their existing digital pictures, either
from digital cameras or from scanned prints.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is My Places, a corner of the welcome screen where
the user can set up one-click access to five favorite online
destinations. This is something of a dud for anyone even vaguely
familiar with the concept of Web bookmarks because My Places allows
links only to AOL's own content.
</P>
<P>
   It is like being offered trips to anywhere in the world, as long
as you stay in Iowa. There are many delightful places in Iowa, of
course. But still.
</P>
<P>
   And, as mentioned here last week, AOL has a new search engine
that prowls not just AOL content, but also the entire Web. Other
search engines cannot search AOL content, because AOL blocks them.
</P>
<P>
   The new AOL 5.0 software is available for Windows computers
only. AOL says a Macintosh version will be available ``later.'' A
preview version of the Windows software was made available late
last month.
</P>
<P>
   The easiest way to get the software is to wait for AOL to
carpet-bomb your neighborhood with free CD-ROM disks, as it is wont
to do. Those in a bigger hurry can download it from the AOL.com Web
site, but beware: The basic software is a 13-megabyte bolus that
takes about 40 minutes to squeeze through a 56-kilobit modem. With
a slower 28.8-kilobit modem, it takes 1 hour 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   America Online is also distributing a special version of AOL 5.0
that comes with _ surprise! _ a copy of Microsoft's Internet
Explorer 5.0 Web software. That is surprising because AOL owns
Netscape, Microsoft's bitter rival in the Web-browser category. The
AOL 5.0 with Internet Explorer 5.0 browser combo weighs in at 25
MB, so double the downloading times given above.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, the software is free. The catch is that it costs
$4.95 to $21.95 a month to use it, depending on how much time is
spent on line.
</P>
<P>
   Of immediate concern to all those people who have been saddled
with drab AOL screen names like Bill836283 (please do not try to
send e-mail to this address, I made it up) is that AOL has now made
screen names 16 characters long, instead of 10. That will enable
Bill to change his screen name to something less common, like
Bill836283652049, although I suspect that he is more likely to want
to change it to something like BillThePresident.
</P>
<P>
   Also, AOL now allows seven screen names per account instead of
five, which is welcome news to large families, and to small
families where everyone wants to have multiple screen names. There
are many valid reasons to have more than one screen name. A person
may wish to have one screen name for a home-based business, and a
different one for personal use, for example.
</P>
<P>
   But this is AOL, after all, where a quick search of member
profiles reveals that more than 100 subscribers answer to ``sex
moron.'' (AOL simply stopped counting at 100.) There is reason to
suspect that other subscribers may simply need the extra screen
names for their multiple personalities, so they can participate in
online chat sessions with themselves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
