<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-AGING-NINERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
49ERS NEED TO TAKE A LOOK AT THE YOUNG CROP OF PLAYERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN CRUMPACKER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA CLARA, Calif. _ On a team deep in the throes of ancestor
worship, the time is as ripe as a summer peach for the San
Francisco 49ers to look to the future by seeing if the young
players populating the lower economic rungs on the roster can
actually play the game.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the first month of the season, it's apparent some can
while others are badly miscast as football players.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers have relied on the inspiration of Steve Young and the
polished brilliance of Jerry Rice and the valiant leadership of Tim
McDonald while legions of draft picks have trotted through the
doors on the road to Wal-Mart employment.
</P>
<P>
   These are the final, wheezing days of the old 49er superstars.
Enjoy them while they last because their time is dwindling. Young
is another concussion or two from becoming the chief executive of
an Internet start-up. Rice's average gain per catch is down to 9.3
yards, a career low.
</P>
<P>
   To the club's credit, management _ that is to say, Bill Walsh _
recognized the need for a rapid infusion of young talent as a way
to stave off the inevitability of decline. Steve Mariucci, whose
job security ultimately depends on how well the team's young
players develop, recognizes it, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to be able to replace our superstars because they're
not going to play forever,'' Mariucci said. ``We've got to find
these rising stars. Not just new players; not just guys. You can't
win your division with just guys. You need good players.''
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers took an emotional hit when Merton Hanks was released
(he does look good in Seahawk blue, though), but the man who
replaced him at free safety, Lance Schulters, looks to be a
long-term starter. Schulters has two interceptions in four games,
one of which he returned for the winning touchdown against New
Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   The next such proactive step is to insert Fred Beasley into the
starting lineup at fullback. Based on what he did Sunday against
Tennessee, there's no reason why Beasley should be languishing
behind Tommy Vardell. Conversely, there's no reason why Vardell,
30, should be starting ahead of Beasley, who's five years younger
with a bigger upside.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL is all about production on game day, and Beasley's
teammates took notice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, my God, he came out and played great,'' Rice said. ``He
made plays, caught the ball, he did everything. That's a great
addition right there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of us were impressed with him,'' Ken Norton said.
``Playing like that, they might try to find a place for him weekly.
I go against him in training camp all the time. I've always known
his potential. Hopefully he'll get more opportunity from now on.''
</P>
<P>
   Mariucci said Beasley had a chance to be a starter. ``Fred's
going to be a good one. He's a tough kid. He's a good blocker and a
capable pass receiver. Let's fit him in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Fit him in there now. On Charlie Garner's 53-yard run that set
up the winning touchdown against Tennessee, Beasley took out middle
linebacker Barron Wortham with a terrific lead block to make the
play go. He also caught two passes for 27 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love it here,'' Beasley said. ``There's a chance to be
around a lot of great guys. I hear a lot of horror stories about
other places. I hope I have a good future here. I feel great about
the whole situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Another second-year player having an impact with the 49ers is
Jeremy Newberry on the offensive line. He was tried at tackle in
the first two games but appears to be better suited for guard,
where at 315 pounds he can be the levee that holds back the flood.
</P>
<P>
   Newberry, Schulters and Beasley are products of the 49ers' draft
class of 1998, which is shaping up as the club's best since '94.
</P>
<P>
   Guard Phil Ostrowski also is a member of the '98 class. He's a
skilled interior lineman who should take over when Ray Brown,
closing in on 37, decides to call it a career.
</P>
<P>
   That brings us to the dismal Class of '99, a fallow yield
indeed. Top pick Reggie McGrew, who was supposed to get significant
playing time at defensive tackle, was placed on injured reserve
with a bum elbow, ending a rookie year that was just clearing its
throat to holler ``Bust!''
</P>
<P>
   Defensive end Chike Okeafor is getting a few turns with the
starters but has yet to make an impact. Cornerback Anthony Parker
tore a knee ligament in training camp and is done for the year.
</P>
<P>
   Another cornerback, Pierson Prioleau, is running around on
special teams, as is running back Terry Jackson. Guard Tyrone
Hopson is injured. Wide receiver Tai Streets is on injured reserve.
Linebacker Kory Minor was waived. Not much to build on.
</P>
<P>
   But it becomes more promising when Jeff Garcia is included in
that group, since he came to the 49ers in '99, albeit as a
29-year-old free agent. That's an age when many quarterbacks are
just starting to learn how to play the game. If the 49ers do not
find their idealized Quarterback of the Future in next year's
draft, they could do worse than prepare Garcia to take over when
Young, finally, inevitably, moves on to an occupation where people
don't hit him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-99 1629EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
