<SLUG> BC-NEW-WINE-SITE-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINE-SELLER AMBROSIA LAUNCHES WEB SITE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By TED APPEL   
 THE PRESS DEMOCRAT ,  Santa Rosa (Calif.)   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA ROSA, Calif. _ Napa direct marketing company Ambrosia
jumped into the growing market for Internet wine sales Tuesday,
launching an e-commerce site, www.ambrosiawine.com.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco investment banker William R. Hambrecht, who owns
Belvedere Winery outside Healdsburg, provided capital for
Ambrosia's expansion with a minority investment in the company.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1991, Ambrosia was based on a class project by
co-founder Lesley Berglund while attending Harvard Business School.
The company's catalogs sell wine and gourmet food through the mail.
</P>
<P>
   Its Internet site, created with Lucent Technologies'
``CentreVu'' system, will allow users to browse Ambrosia's Web site
and simultaneously talk with a company representative over the same
telephone line.
</P>
<P>
   A half-dozen companies have announced plans this summer to sell
wine over the Internet. Ambrosia hopes to differentiate itself by
focusing on customer service and offering top-notch wines, Berglund
said. To expand from catalog sales to e-commerce, Ambrosia doubled
its staff this summer and quadrupled its office and warehouse
space.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ambrosia is not trying to be the Wal-Mart of wine sales. Our
benchmark is closer to Nordstrom _ the best products and
knowledgeable, passionate customer service,'' she said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
