<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 16:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8536 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-EBAY-EXHIBITION-A     10-06 0517
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-EBAY-EXHIBITION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ITEMS FOUND ON THE INTERNET DRESS UP A MUSEUM'S EXHIBITION 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By ELIZABETH HAYT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As if New York museums needed more publicity the Whitney Museum
recently
</P>
<P>
   revealed that it had been involved in a fierce bidding war for a
25-year-old copy of Playgirl magazine.
</P>
<P>
   This auction didn't take place at Christie's. It took place on
the Internet. A guest museum curator, Maurice Berger, needed
everyday objects _ campaign buttons, album covers and vintage
magazines _ to include in the show ``American Century: Art and
Culture, 1900-2000.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of spending years traveling, sifting through flea
markets and other museums' collections, Berger assembled the
objects in less than six months by making bids on Ebay and other
auction sites.
</P>
<P>
   Berger said this was the first time a major art institution had
curated part of an exhibition by buying artifacts on line. The
experience had a powerful effect on his co-workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've addicted half the museum to Ebay,'' he said. ``I guess
I've become Ebay's most famous curator.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the 350 items he collected, 160 were purchased online,
including a hotly contested copy of High Times, a magazine of drug
culture that began in the '70s, and the special Las Vegas Holiday
issue of Playgirl, dated January 1975. The items provide a social,
political and commercial context for the art in the show.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Berger was able to use the Web to find a number of
banned books, including ``The Tropic of Capricorn'' by Henry
Miller, to illustrate the themes of blacklisting and censorship in
earlier decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found a 1957 edition of `Tropic of Capricorn' through
Bibliofind.com and located a bookstore in Normal, Ill., that
happened to have a copy,'' Berger said. ``It was the very edition
printed in Paris in English with the censor's mark on the back
cover. The Internet gives you pinpoint accuracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Curators usually organize an exhibition by selecting from the
museum's own collection and by visiting other museums, galleries,
artists' studios and collectors' homes to borrow works of art.
</P>
<P>
   But the Whitney does not own popular-culture artifacts. Berger
said he had purchased the items from online auctions because it was
more efficient than filling out hundreds of loan forms and saved on
travel costs. He spent $5,000 for objects purchased on the Net and
estimated that he would have spent three times that amount had he
gathered them off line.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was less serendipity in locating what he was looking
for,'' said Maxwell Anderson, the museum director. ``He was more in
the driver's seat, with ample selection to choose from.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever critical reaction the Whitney show may receive, Berger
will have at least secured his reputation in another forum. ``I am
now considered an excellent Ebay-er,'' he said. ``The vendor
feedback on Ebay told me I was a reputable, prompt payer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-99 1634EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991006.0195 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 16:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8539 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-GAMES-NYT &LR;      10-06 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-GAMES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAME THEORY: THE LITERARY MYTH UPDATED WITH HIGH-TECH
PRESENTATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: La.)   (Editors: Product notes at end of review ;  Campbell excerpt should
be italicized . )  
 (bl)  
 By J.C. HERZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The mythological hero, setting forth from his commonday hut or
castle, is lured, carried away, or else voluntarily proceeds, to
the threshold of adventure. There he encounters a shadow presence
that guards the passage. The hero may defeat or conciliate this
power and go alive into the kingdom of the dark, or be slain by the
opponent and descend in death. ... When he arrives at the nadir of
the mythological round, he undergoes a supreme ordeal and gains his
reward.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Joseph Campbell, ``The Hero With a Thousand Faces''
</P>
<P>
   Computer games are the primal myths of the digital age. Despite
what hundreds of ivory tower deconstructionists might say about
displaced identity and post-modern media culture, yadda yadda
yadda, most video-game adventures are a deep-dish slice of
archetypal heroism greedily consumed by young people who crave
mythic drama (though they're too cool to admit it).
</P>
<P>
   Most action-adventure games stage a descent into hell by
funneling the player into a labyrinth filled with gothic demons. In
Shadow Man, the mythic descent is more literal and more literary.
The hero, Mike LeRoi, is an erstwhile English major from New
Orleans who has been forcibly transformed into a voodoo
warrior-slave by his girlfriend, a 200-year-old priestess in the
body of a lissome 20-year-old barmaid.
</P>
<P>
   At her behest, the reluctant hero descends from the Louisiana
swamp to Deadside, where he becomes Shadow Man, a more powerful,
supernatural version of his real-world self. After a brief chat
with Jaunty the gatekeeper (a talking skull with a snake's tail, a
top hat and a thick Irish brogue), he passes into Deadside proper.
</P>
<P>
   There he discovers an apocalyptic prophecy involving serial
killers employed by the ultimate incarnation of evil. To keep the
demons of Deadside from overrunning the world, he has to track down
the killers on Earth and face the ultimate enemy in hell. For the
rest of the game, he alternates between Liveside and Deadside,
surfacing as Mike LeRoi and descending as Shadow Man, gathering
strength below for his battles above, and vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the symbolism, this dynamic creates a very strong
cyclical narrative because it's not possible for Mike or Shadow Man
to ``die'' in the traditional sense. Should Mike's life force be
exhausted, he passes across the veil into Deadside, where as Shadow
Man he has the power to return to the land of the living.
</P>
<P>
   There is no stop-and-start repetition, no interruption, no blind
alleys. Every action taken, in death or in life, pushes the story
forward. As the hero confronts each killer in turn, he gets closer
to the center of Deadside. As he gains strength, he is pulled
toward forces that are even more powerful. The horror at the core
is like a black hole _ the closer he gets, the more force it
exerts. Like all unknown horrors, it's deeply attractive and
terrifying at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   As the plot thickens, so does the knot in your stomach. In this
world, you feel fear. And it's not survival fear. It's not chase
scene, blockbuster, blood-and-guts fear. It's moral fear, ``Silence
of the Lambs'' fear, and profound dread.
</P>
<P>
   That's partly because of the way the place looks; all the
surface textures were lifted from an illustrated encyclopedia of
skin diseases. The patterns are blurred, but you know
subconsciously that the walls and floors are festering.
</P>
<P>
   Underneath the eczematous wallpaper, the landscape is modeled
after the industrial north of England.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was driving back from playing soccer at lunchtime, and I saw
this huge disused factory that was being broken up because the
northeast is quite depressed in the U.K.,'' said Guy Miller, Shadow
Man's producer. ``And I thought that's exactly what parts of
Deadside should look like, this place of misery and desperation.
We're actually based up in Teesside in the northeast of England.
But people call it Deadside now.''
</P>
<P>
   The sound design is also exquisitely creepy (and more than makes
up for mediocre voice-overs). Shadow Man's audio effects are pure
nightmare material.
</P>
<P>
   But most of the game's emotional wallop stems from the story
structure. Primal narratives have survived thousands of years for a
reason: they work. People want to experience a heroic ordeal, and
computer games deliver, big time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The player has gone through 70 hours of game play,'' Miller
said. ``And in the end he's achieved an apotheosis. That is part of
the myth: the hero achieves godhead _ he must die and return. And
in sort of a shamanic way, he has. He's gone to Deadside and back
again.''
</P>
<P>
   In an age of channel surfing, ``Pop-Up Video'' and attention
deficit disorder, hundreds of thousands of people are willing to
invest two working weeks in this myth.
</P>
<P>
   High school English teachers, take heart.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCT NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   Shadow Man, published by Acclaim; for Nintendo 64, Playstation,
Dreamcast and PC; CD-ROM for Windows 95 and 98 (needs graphics
accelerator card); $44.95; for ages 17 and up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
