<HEADLINE>
GEEK NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW iMAC OFFERS MORE THAN A CHOICE OF COLORS
</P>
<P>
   With its announcement of new models of this week, Apple has
significantly redesigned and improved the iMac, its popular
computer for home and school users.
</P>
<P>
   Breaking with its original philosophy of making only one version
of the iMac _ the hard part was choosing the color _ Apple has
created three models. All have features that makers of
Windows-based computers are probably already scrambling to try to
copy.
</P>
<P>
   The new iMac that most closely resembles the original has a
faster processor (a 350-megahertz G3), a faster system bus (100
MHz), more standard memory (64 megabytes), a better 3-D graphics
card for games (ATI Rage 128) and a pair of built-in Harmon Kardon
hi-fi stereo speakers, a new trap door slot on the bottom to make
it easy to add as much as 512 MB of RAM, and a simple slot that
replaces the sliding CD-ROM tray. Even with the improvements, the
new model, which comes only in blue, costs $999.
</P>
<P>
   The new iMac case, which still comes in five colors, is now
fully translucent and about an inch shorter, front to back. The
carrying handle is ringed by ventilation holes, enabling Apple to
get rid of the noisy internal fan. Apple says that the new iMac is
not only the most powerful consumer PC on the market, but also the
quietest.
</P>
<P>
   The new iMac trapdoor slot can also accommodate a $99 wireless
network card, which, when it is coupled with a $299 Apple Airport
base station, will allow two Macintoshes to communicate wirelessly
at distances up to 150 feet. Another cool iMac option is a
subwoofer from Harmon Kardon mounted in a transparent enclosure
that resembles the severed head of Robbie the Robot. It will cost
$99 when it goes to market in November.
</P>
<P>
   The next new model, for $1,299, is the iMac DV, for digital
video. Besides the other new iMAC features, the DV has a 400-MHz G3
chip, a 10-GB hard drive, a slot-loaded DVD-ROM drive instead of a
CD-ROM, a pair of Apple's Firewire high-speed connection ports for
attaching digital video cameras and other high-speed peripherals,
and connectors for attaching to color televisions, video recorders
and other video devices. It will come with Apple's Final Cut Pro
video editing software, which promises to do for home video what
desktop publishing software did for newsletters.
</P>
<P>
   The third new iMac is the DV Special Edition, which will be
available only in a translucent gray color scheme that was
introduced last month in the new G4 professional desktop
Macintoshes. The Special Edition will have a 13-GB hard disk and
128 MB of RAM, and will cost $1,499.
</P>
<P>
   Apple said all three models would be available this week. But
the company has been hurt by product shortages and shipping delays
for almost all of its most important recent products, including the
G4 desktops, the iBook portables and the Airport wireless
networking system.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've pretty much just about caught up with demand,'' said
Apple's top executive, Steve Jobs.
</P>
<P>
   _ PETER H. LEWIS
</P>
<P>
   TALKING TO THE WEB ON YOUR TELEPHONE
</P>
<P>
   To most people who follow wireless communication, phone-based
Web browsing means reading two or three lines of text on tiny
display screens. But Nuance, a voice-recognition company based in
Menlo Park, Calif., has created an invisible Web browser called
Voyager that responds to voice commands instead of pushed buttons
or mouse clicks. It is designed to be used by people speaking
through a regular or mobile phone.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if you dialed into Voyager, you could gain access
to a series of audible bookmarks for say, your favorite travel
site, a search engine, or a news page. If you wanted to book a
flight on the travel site, you could simply speak into the phone
and ask for one. The travel site might ask you to confirm arrival
times or airport locations and, instead of requesting a code number
or password, could verify your identity by listening to your voice.
</P>
<P>
   When you were done with that transaction, you would not have to
hang up the phone to continue Web browsing. You could simply ask
Voyager to take you to a news page, list your bookmarks, or even
dial a specific number for you.
</P>
<P>
   Nuance's officials are now talking with representatives from Web
sites so that they may format their Web pages to handle voice-based
browsing. And it has signed deals with telephone companies, like
British Telecom, to begin trials next year.
</P>
<P>
   But will people really want to browse the Web by voice? Ronald
Croen, president and chief executive of Nuance, thinks so _
especially if they are in a car or somewhere that a computer screen
is not available or safe to look at. Croen equates the convenience
of Voyager with voice-mail boxes in which people can leave long
messages without having to ask a receptionist to write everything
down. ``In some cases,'' he said, ``we really do prefer to talk to
machines rather than people.''
</P>
<P>
   _ LISA GUERNSEY
</P>
<P>
   A BOOK THAT TEACHES CHILDREN HOW TO READ
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Johnny can't read, but if he can crack open the latest
booklike electronic gadget, there may be hope.
</P>
<P>
   Leap Pad, from Leap Frog, an educational toy company in
Emeryville, Calif., is a learn-to-read tool that on the outside, at
least, resembles an iBook laptop computer. Open it up, though, and
there is not a keyboard or screen to be found _ just an electronic
pen and the blank plastic inside the covers.
</P>
<P>
   But fit a special spiral-bound book into the plastic covers,
touch the pen to the pages, and Leap Pad becomes an interactive
storybook. Children can hear each page read aloud, or tap
individual words to hear their component phonemes. The pages also
feature games and other activities to help maintain interest in
reading. (A green ``go'' circle on each page must be tapped to
synchronize the paper book with the electronic book.)
</P>
<P>
   The Leap Pad is intended for children 4 and older and is
available in two versions. Both the basic (about $60) and deluxe
(about $90) models include a 32-page starter book; the deluxe
version adds two more books narrated by Whoopi Goldberg, with
accompanying plug-in cartridges. Other book-cartridge combinations
are available for about $11 and up.
</P>
<P>
   The starter book features a story about three frogs and a loose
tooth, as well as excerpts from a Richard Scarry book and a Winnie
the Pooh tale. It also includes an interactive map of the United
States and a human skeleton to teach the Latin names for the bones
of the body. So even if Johnny never learns to read, maybe he can
still become a doctor.
</P>
<P>
   _ HENRY FOUNTAIN
</P>
<P>
   COMPAQ SLIMS DOWN A NEW DESKTOP PC
</P>
<P>
   Compaq Computer Corp. has never been known for sleek PC designs,
and until now its line of Presario consumer computers have taken up
more desk space than most of competitors. But earlier this week
Compaq introduced the Presario 3550, a supermodel-thin system that
includes a 15-inch flat-panel LCD monitor, a ``slim tower'' case
that is less than half the size of other Presarios, and a set of
flat-panel speakers from Monsoon, all in a metallic, midnight-blue
casing.
</P>
<P>
   The Presario 3550 is based on a 500-megahertz Intel Celeron
processor and comes with a CD-RW drive as standard equipment. The
list price is $1,999.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq has been hinting lately that the Presario 3550 is just
the first of several new computer systems that will break the
company's beige-box tradition.
</P>
<P>
   _ PETER H. LEWIS
</P>
</TEXT>
