<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 16:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8542 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-ROCKEFELLER-GARDEN-AR     10-06 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROCKEFELLER-GARDEN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SPOT OFF FIFTH AVENUE THAT CRADLES THOSE WHO PAUSE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Australia, Mich . )  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By ANNE RAVER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Standing on Rockefeller Plaza, looking across the
skating rink toward Fifth Avenue, it looks as if a prairie has
flown in and landed on the Channel Gardens. Grasses the color of
wheat nod their seed heads in the breeze, and sparrows swoop across
the water channels. The yellowing leaves of crape myrtles drift
across the slate walkway, as fall moves through the city.
</P>
<P>
   This garden, as ephemeral as the changing season, will last only
until next Thursday, and it's a gift to a city always rushing to
make deadlines and corporate decisions and Broadway shows.
</P>
<P>
   Designed by David Kamp, a landscape architect, in collaboration
with other designers interested in restorative gardens, it
transforms this grand stone space of vertical buildings and sky,
for a fleeting two weeks, into a softer, more natural place of calm
and meditation.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you are calm, you experience more,'' said Kamp, whose
firm Dirtworks specializes in therapeutic design. ``There's so much
visual clutter in the city, so much noise. This garden might seem
boring in a sense, but it's calming.''
</P>
<P>
   There are no jazzy orange pumpkins here this year, no purple
ornamental cabbages. In fact, the branches of those crape myrtles
have been carefully unpruned, and their seed pods, as black and
wrinkled as raisins, look a bit ratty. Which is intentional,
because this is fall, and nature doesn't go around tidying up for
the tourists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish they would stop sweeping up the leaves,'' Kamp said
wistfully, as we watched them float down from the trees. But, of
course, they will, because this is Rockefeller Center.
</P>
<P>
   These trees and grasses are planted with the same elegant
formality. The tall grass, Miscanthus sinensis Nippon, forms a
buff-colored wall on either side of the water channel, echoing the
color and lines of the limestone buildings that flank the space _
as well as the tower of 30 Rockefeller Center that soars over the
skating rink to the west.
</P>
<P>
   Kamp points out how the 20 crape myrtle trees frame the Fifth
Avenue entrance, punctuate a cross-axis walkway and finally frame
the west end of a central bed of white daisylike chrysanthemums.
The mottled gray and orange-red bark of the trees picks up the
subtle tones of limestone, slate and granite. Their placement, in
deep planter boxes set at right angles to the water channel, turn
what is essentially a promenade into a restful series of garden
nooks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We added the boxes to close off the garden a little more,''
said Nancy Gerlach, a garden designer specializing in healing
landscapes. ``They invite you to walk into the garden and sit down
on a bench and have a conversation.''
</P>
<P>
   Kamp, whose work includes grand spaces like the Parliament house
in Canberra, Australia, said: ``This is the essence of design: You
ask yourself, `What is the space? What is the scale and context?
And how do you relate plants to it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Kamp talked of the effect of Rockefeller Plaza on the emotions:
the way the buildings ``pull back'' and allow a space that cradles
the humans pausing here.
</P>
<P>
   The seed heads of the miscanthus nodded slightly in the wind.
``I can't tell you how many people have come along and drawn their
hands up these seed heads,'' Kamp said, doing just that. And as the
sun rose over the buildings, the silky tassels glowed with a white
light.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Kaplans call this soft fascination,'' Ms. Gerlach said,
referring to the work of Michigan environmental psychologists
Stephen and Rachel Kaplan on nature's restorative effects. ``It's
like watching squirrels in the park. It takes your mind off things,
but it's not enough to stimulate you. It's the garden equivalent of
fishing.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the miscanthus echoes the verticals of the buildings,
it's more like a veil, allowing you to see people strolling along
the opposite side. Shorter grasses (Pennisetum alopecuroides
Hameln) form another soft wall to look through, if you are sitting
on a bench, and a blue-green aquatic grass, Juncus, frames the
fountains of Triton and Nereids riding their spouting dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   It is this contrast of soft and hard that is so arresting _ and
restful at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's why you put an antique in a modern room,'' Kamp said.
</P>
<P>
   We sat for a while, watching the dappled light and shade move
across the Channel Gardens and we almost forgot to go to work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
