NYT-10-06-99 1651EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991006.0199 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 17:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8561 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e BC-BOOKS-FOLEY-SPI &LR;      10-06 1224
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-FOLEY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
URBANE, HUMANE BIOGRAPHY DOES JUSTICE TO TOM FOLEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As longtime aide Jeff Biggs worked on a biography of former
House Speaker Tom Foley, friends wondered about the outcome of a
gentlemanly tug-of-war: Biggs wanted humor and insight, while Foley
seemed inclined toward pontifical reflection.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, this is one instance in which staff set the agenda.
``Honor in the House: Speaker Tom Foley'' has emerged as a humane,
urbane book, an accurate depiction of the Spokane Democrat
described by GOP Sen. Slade Gorton as ``the number one citizen of
the state that I represented.''
</P>
<P>
   ``One was a fighter, the other a healer,'' Biggs writes,
contrasting House Speaker Jim Wright with his successor. For most
of his 30 years in the House, Foley was a symbol of civility and
the coexistence of partisan fervor with personal good will.
</P>
<P>
   As an anti-Congress populism took hold in the early 1990s,
however, this man who quoted DeToqueville proved no match for the
cut-and-slash, confrontational politics of Newt Gingrich, who urged
his followers to read such books as ``Panzer Leader,'' the memoirs
of Nazi Germany's tank commander Heinz Guderian. In 1994, Foley
became the first House Speaker in 134 years to lose his bid for
re-election.
</P>
<P>
   House Energy and Commerce Committee chairman John Dingell put it
accurately, in a telling reflection on Foley, when he said: ``He's
a gentleman _ perhaps too much so for the circumstances he finds
himself in.''
</P>
<P>
   The book is structured so that Biggs' analysis alternates with
Foley's reflections. The former speaker, who now serves as U.S.
ambassador to Japan, has an ear for the revealing anecdote.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Foley tells how Ronald Reagan, early in his
presidency, began to regale congressional leaders with his oft-told
(but untrue) story about the Chicago ``welfare queen'' with two
BMWs and a Mercedes. One of the Gipper's ideological allies, House
Republican Conference chairman Jack Kemp, whispered to Foley:
``This is all campaign (bleep). I wish he'd get off this stuff.
Nobody cares about this anymore. And it's all in his imagination
anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Foley recalls the bullying of powerful chairmen in the closed
Congress of the 1960s. A powerful old pork barreler, Rep. Mike
Kirwin of Ohio, admonished freshmen on the greatest mistake they
could make at the start of a career in Congress. ``That great
danger, above all else, is ... thinking for yourselves,'' Kirwin
declared.
</P>
<P>
   Congress would become a lot more open and democratic, but a lot
more ideological, during Foley's time on Capitol Hill. But aside
from a 1989 decision to shed 80 pounds and start pumping iron,
Foley was changed little by three decades of public life or the
assumption of high office.
</P>
<P>
   Son of a judge and protege of the late Sen. Henry Jackson, Foley
was careful, deliberate and resistant to moods of the moment. Power
sought him out, not vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   Ignoring a plea from Foley, the upstart 1974 class of House
Democratic freshmen deposed reactionary Texas Rep. W.R. Poage as
chairman of the House Agriculture Committee. They promptly elected
Foley to take his place. Foley graciously eased Poage's humiliation
by naming him committee vice chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, in 1989 Foley supported the embattled Jim Wright
until the moment Wright was forced to resign the speakership.
Although the subject of personal smears, he took no retaliation.
</P>
<P>
   A life in politics can change people in strange ways. One of
Foley's aides in the 1960s, newspaperman Dick Larsen, was to become
a conservative polemicist, emerging in the 1990s as an
image-shaping Henry Higgins to Jennifer Dunn's Eliza Dolittle.
</P>
<P>
   Some members of Congress rise in self-esteem and acquire a
retinue of sycophants of the type that surrounded Jim Wright.
Incumbency can instill impatience with ordinary folk. More than one
veteran Washington congressman has left a meeting with angry
constituents muttering, ``What those people don't know is. ...''
</P>
<P>
   None of this happened to Foley. He maintained a fine
self-deprecating sense of humor. He surrounded himself with a
brainy staff, several of them (including Biggs) former
Congressional Fellows. He made the rounds of town meetings in
Eastern Washington, never leaving until the last question was
answered.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, Foley was anchored by beliefs. A civil libertarian,
he opposed a stream of what he called ``unnecessary and unneeded''
constitutional amendments, including such popular proposals as a
ban on flag burning. He paid a political price by serving as lead
plaintiff to a successful legal challenge against an initiative
that imposed term limits on federal elected officials. The
well-heeled Americans for Term Limits would pump $300,000 into an
anti-Foley advertising campaign in his district.
</P>
<P>
   To those on the political right who promoted such amendments,
Foley gave a stinging rejoinder: ``If it is not conservative to
protect the Bill of Rights, then I don't know what conservatism is
today.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Honor in the House'' is, at times, a candid book. It discusses
in-House resentment at Foley's wife, who served as unpaid chief of
staff to her husband. A lawyer of strong opinions, Heather Foley
refused to heed unwritten Capitol Hill rules of conformity. She
found sandals comfortable, often wore her hair in pigtails and took
on the administrative burdens to which her husband was oblivious.
</P>
<P>
   The result was plenty of old-boy grumbling. When Heather Foley
interrupted a meeting to deliver a message to her husband, House
Ways and Means Committee chairman Dan Rostenkowski sneered: ``Who
was that? Pocahontas?'' The anecdote appears in the book, along
with the famous story of the distaff Foley, who suffered from
asthma, asking then-Speaker Tip O'Neill to put out his smelly
cigar.
</P>
<P>
   Nor does the book downplay the ugliness of the '94 campaign, in
which ``hot talk'' programs carried a steady drumbeat of anti-Foley
hate. The low point of excess was Todd Herman of KSBN radio, who
labeled Foley ``the Sphincter of the House.''
</P>
<P>
   In places, however, Biggs and Foley hold their fire. Endless,
tedious endorsement editorials from the Spokane Spokesman-Review
are quoted. But nowhere is it mentioned that Foley's hometown
newspaper shut down its Washington, D.C., bureau just as he was
becoming House Majority leader. It is not for nothing that the
Inland Empire is sometimes called the ``Ingrown Empire.''
</P>
<P>
   Foley delivers a cerebral critique of Gingrich's leadership
style, but no sense of the raw partisan ugliness that has gripped
the House over the past four years. Biggs and Foley make no
reference to the fact that GOP Rep. George Nethercutt, the man who
beat him, has reneged on his pledge to serve only three terms.
After running on the slogan ``a listener, not a Speaker,''
Nethercutt has made himself far less open to constituents and
criticism than was his predecessor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honor in the House'' makes the reader long for the lost comity
and bipartisanship of Capitol Hill. One hopes that Foley's style
has not gone out of style.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ufboox &LR; Honor in the House: Speaker Tom Foley. By Jeffrey Biggs
and Thomas S. Foley. Washington State University Press. $35
(cloth), $25 (paperback) 338 pages.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
