</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV10-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BEATTY PRESIDENTIAL RUN WOULD SPICE UP THE RACE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Oct. 10)   (For Use By New York Times News Service Clients)  
 By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Warren Beatty's decision to sip provocatively of
the aphrodisiac of presidential politics recalls an incident that
occurred when another Hollywood actor drank heartily of that
pungent potion.
</P>
<P>
   The year was 1966. Ronald Reagan had just been elected governor
of California, and I asked the state's junior senator, Republican
Thomas Kuchel, how he thought the former actor would fare in
Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   ``Poor fellow,'' replied Kuchel, shaking his head. ``In two
weeks, he'll fall flat on his ass.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Americans, in and out of politics, shared that assessment
of the handsome, 55-year-old actor who had been propelled into
elective politics by wealthy conservatives following his eloquent
televised appeal on behalf of Barry Goldwater's disastrous
presidential bid in 1964. But, as we all know now, their judgment
was totally wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan went on to serve two successful terms as governor and two
as president. Among conservatives nationwide, he has become a folk
hero. Among current presidential hopefuls, he is the president most
often cited as a role model.
</P>
<P>
   As for Kuchel, a delightful human being and a very good senator,
he was defeated in the GOP Senate primary two years later by
Reagan's conservative operatives under the command of Caspar
Weinberger. They did so by mounting a strong campaign behind the
state's right-wing superintendent of public instruction, Max
Rafferty.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Rafferty was defeated in the general election by
Alan Cranston, a liberal Democrat, at the same time California
Republican Richard Nixon was elected president.
</P>
<P>
   As for Kuchel, he not only misjudged Reagan, he also declined to
support the former actor's candidacy for governor beyond a lukewarm
declaration that he would vote for him. To the staunch Reaganites
of that era, he carried an additional burden. The moderate
Republican benefactor who named Kuchel to Nixon's Senate seat when
Nixon was elevated to vice president in 1953 was California's
then-governor, Earl Warren, who was anathema to the conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   That long-ago conversation with Kuchel came to mind as Beatty
appeared before an audience of liberal Democrats in Los Angeles to
accept the Americans for Democratic Action Eleanor Roosevelt award.
</P>
<P>
   Where Reagan entered the political arena from the right, Beatty,
a youthful 62, is entering from the left. His concern, he told his
audience, is that the Democratic Party ``is drifting'' and ``being
enslaved by big money.''
</P>
<P>
   He described himself as a Franklin Roosevelt-Harry Truman-Adlai
Stevenson-Hubert Humphrey-John Kennedy Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   All of that might appear unimportant had Reagan not made it
acceptable for an actor to leap from a Hollywood sound stage to the
White House.
</P>
<P>
   When Reagan first took the plunge into elective politics, Beatty
was a promising young actor who had appeared opposite Vivien Leigh
in ``The Roman Spring of Mrs. Stone'' and Natalie Wood in
``Splendor in the Grass.'' While Reagan was in his first term in
Sacramento, Beatty scored heavily as the Depression-era bank robber
in ``Bonnie and Clyde.'' In 1981, he won an Oscar for his direction
of the movie ``Reds.''
</P>
<P>
   He had an additional claim to fame: he was the brother of screen
star Shirley MacLaine, a member of the Frank Sinatra's ``Rat Pack''
that partied with President John Kennedy on his journeys to
California.
</P>
<P>
   Helen Gahagan Douglas, the musical comedy star who was married
to actor Melvyn Douglas, may have been the pioneer in traversing
the road from Hollywood to Washington. She served three terms in
the House in the 1940s and was defeated by Nixon when she sought to
move up to the Senate in 1950. A down-the-line liberal Democrat,
she was labeled the ``Pink Lady'' by Nixon, who implied that her
votes in Congress followed the communist line.
</P>
<P>
   Motion picture song-and-dance man George Murphy, a conservative
like Reagan, served one undistinguished term in the U.S. Senate in
the 1960s. Sonny Bono, in his post-Cher persona, was a member of
the House when he died on a California ski slope.
</P>
<P>
   Now other celebrities are toying with public office, following
in the footsteps Jesse Ventura, who lunged from the professional
wrestling ring to the governorship of Minnesota last year.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Schwarzenegger has indicated his desire to follow in
Reagan's footsteps and seek the California governorship in 2004.
But even if he wins, Schwarzenegger cannot hope to move into the
White House because he is not a native-born American. He was born
in Austria 52 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Cybill Shepherd, the lanky blonde star of both the big and
little screens, has indicated an interest in seeking the presidency
so that she can guarantee a woman's ``right to choose'' on the
abortion issue.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is that other celebrity who is not a paid actor,
developer Donald Trump.
</P>
<P>
   As the field gets crowded with non-politicians seeking to become
politicians, it recalls another story from the past.
</P>
<P>
   When movie producer Samuel Goldwyn, who had been wholly
indoctrinated into Hollywood type-casting, was informed that Reagan
would run for president, he reportedly replied, ``No! Jimmy Stewart
for president, Ronald Reagan for best friend.'' If he were around
today and were told that Beatty might seek the presidency, Goldwyn
might declare, ``No! Harrison Ford for president. Warren Beatty for
the first lady's lover.''
</P>
<P>
   Beatty cannot be kissed off lightly. He has an unusual advantage
over other presidential hopefuls, with the possible exception of
Trump, who appears eager to become the Reform Party candidate. If
Beatty could garner the votes of all his former girl friends, he
probably could win hands down.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-99 1708EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
