<HEADER>
A8582 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BOX-MACGREGOR-NYTR &LR;      10-06 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-MACGREGOR-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POUND FOR POUND, GO WITH THE GAL
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wash., Nev.)  (rk) 
 By BOB PADECKY   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like you, I was concerned when I heard that this Saturday night
in Seattle a woman is going to fight a man in the first officially
sanctioned mixed-gender boxing match in the sport's history.
</P>
<P>
   As mixed genders go, you can't mix 'em any more dangerously than
this, unless a woman asks her husband to clean up after himself. So
it was natural to wonder if maybe the wee lass Margaret MacGregor
from Bremerton, Wash., was in over her head a bit on this one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Margaret? Shoot, she's a rough customer,'' said Bob Jarvis, a
Seattle trainer and promoter who made the fight happen. ``She has a
long record of assault in Bremerton. She'd get drunk, pick fights
with sailors and then beat the hell out of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's definitely not your everyday girl.''
</P>
<P>
   Hey, mom, I want to introduce you to my girlfriend, Margaret,
who has a terrific right cross.
</P>
<P>
   What would you expect of a woman who, when Jarvis first
suggested the idea, jumped at the chance? This is a 35-year old
woman who grew up as a street fighter, was nicknamed ``Tiger''
because of her aggressiveness, knocked out a drunk who was sassing
some kids on a street corner, even served some time in the joint.
</P>
<P>
   When she was a kid and her older sisters would torment her, as
older siblings tend to do, Margaret would bite off the heads of
their Barbie dolls, according to boxing writer Scott Pope.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, you do not want to tease Margaret.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would you be afraid to aggravate Margaret?'' I asked Jarvis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nah,'' Jarvis said, ``I'd hook the hell out of her. Go ahead
and print that. We're good friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Geez, can you tell this is a boxing story?
</P>
<P>
   Margaret stopped talking to the media last Monday to concentrate
on the fight. Her opponent, Loi Chow, still will speak publicly if
you pay him. According to Jarvis, Chow charged the London Daily
Mail newspaper $150 for an interview and stopped talking to the
producers of the television show ``Extra!'' when they refused to
pay his cab fare.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a wad of bills on him that would choke a horse,''
Jarvis said.
</P>
<P>
   Only in America. Only in boxing. Where the outrageous is the
norm because what passes for the norm usually is boring and
unquotable. And how can you promote a fight that way?
</P>
<P>
   Chow claims, for example, that he speaks several languages, does
two-finger push-ups with one hand tied behind his back, is a
commodities broker in Vancouver, B.C., and a horse jockey. Chuck
Stark of the Bremerton Sun, however, has talked to jockeys who have
been in the Pacific Northwest for the last 25 years and none of
them have heard of Chow, who is a year younger than MacGregor.
</P>
<P>
   Stark is still checking out Chow's claim he can turn sourdough
into salmon.
</P>
<P>
   All of this, of course, irritates Marc Ratner, executive
director of the Nevada State Athletic Commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am adamantly opposed to that fight,'' Ratner said. ``I would
go to court to prevent it here. Boxing is a brutal sport. The issue
is safety. But you also have a sport which has suffered enough
indignities without this.''
</P>
<P>
   A sham. A joke. A travesty. What are we talking about here? Mike
Tyson saying he'd bite off Evander Holyfield's ear again if he had
the chance? The decision in the Oscar De La Hoya-Felix Trinidad
fight? A woman fighting a man? You want mockery? Where do you draw
the line? Boxing doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   If boxing wasn't around, you might say, we'd invent it so we
could have for our amusement a sport so excessive, flamboyant and
absurd. No, we couldn't. We couldn't get boxing past the censors,
the religious right or people who specialize in common sense. If
boxing was a bill, it would never get out of the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   But a woman with a colorful past will fight a man with a
colorful past this Saturday night at Seattle's Mercer Arena. Media
from all over the world have applied for credentials. With the
circus in the background, a line has been crossed. As Forrest Gump
might say, outrageous is as outrageous does and so, in this case, I
take the woman, by a TKO, in the third round.
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-99 1727EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991006.0208 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 17:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8586 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d BC-CENTURYINFOOD-1970S-3     10-06 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENTURYINFOOD-1970S-3rdTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: 4 pounds) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a medium bowl, mix apricot preserves, dressing and dry soup
mix until well-blended. Arrange 3 chicken breast halves in bottom
of a 3 1/2-quart electric slow cooker. Spoon 1/4 of apricot mixture
on top. Add 3 more layers of chicken with apricot mixture in
between and on top.
</P>
<P>
   Cover and cook on high-heat setting 1 hour. Reduce heat setting
to low and continue cooking, covered, 2 1/2 to 3 hours or until
chicken is tender and white throughout; do not overcook, or chicken
will toughen. Serve sauce over chicken.
</P>
<P>
   Serve over wild rice or white rice.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 414 calories, 15 grams fat, 26
grams carbohydrates, 43 grams protein, 119 milligrams cholesterol,
557 milligrams sodium, 32 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Best Slow Cooker Cookbook Ever'' by Natalie Haughton
(Harper Collins, $18.95)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   WHISKEY (OR RUM) CAKE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 20
</P>
<P>
   Cake:
</P>
<P>
   18 1/4-ounce package yellow cake mix
</P>
<P>
   4-ounce package instant vanilla pudding
</P>
<P>
   4 eggs
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup rye whiskey or dark rum
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped pecans or walnuts, dusted with flour
</P>
<P>
   Glaze:
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup butter
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup water
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup rye whiskey or dark rum
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Grease and flour 12-cup bundt pan.
</P>
<P>
   Combine all cake ingredients except nuts and beat with a mixer
on medium for 5 minutes. Stir in nuts. Pour batter into prepared
pan. Bake until cake pulls away slightly from edges of pan and
toothpick inserted in center of cake comes out clean, about 50
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   While cake is baking, make the glaze. In small saucepan over low
heat, melt butter, then stir in sugar, water, and whiskey or rum.
Boil 5 minutes, stirring constantly. Remove from heat and keep
warm. Remove cake from oven and immediately pour half the glaze
over cake. Leave cake in pan for 25 minutes. Remove from pan and
pour rest of the glaze over it.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 299 calories, 16 grams fat, 35
grams carbohydrates, 3 grams protein, 52 milligrams cholesterol,
234 milligrams sodium, 49 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Fashionable Food'' by Sylvia Lovegren (Macmillan, $25)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   CARROT CAKE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 12-16
</P>
<P>
   2 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   2 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   3 cups finely shredded carrots
</P>
<P>
   1 cup vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   4 eggs
</P>
<P>
   Cream cheese frosting, recipe follows
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Grease and lightly flour two 9-by-11/2-inch round baking pans or
grease one 13-by-9-by-2-inch baking pan; set pans aside.
</P>
<P>
   In large mixing bowl, combine flour, sugar, baking powder,
baking soda and cinnamon. Add carrots, oil and eggs. Beat with
electric mixer until combined. Pour batter into prepared pan.
</P>
<P>
   Bake for 30 to 35 minutes for round pans or 35 to 40 minutes for
single pan, or until a wooden toothpick comes out clean. Cool layer
cakes on wire racks for 10 minutes. Remove from pans. Cool
thoroughly on wire racks. Or, place 13-by-9-inch cake in pan on a
wire rack; cool thoroughly. Frost with cream cheese frosting. Cover
and store in refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   Cream cheese frosting:
</P>
<P>
   6 ounces cream cheese, softened
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup butter or margarine, softened
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons vanilla
</P>
<P>
   2 cups sifted powdered sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 to 2 3/4 cups additional powdered sugar
</P>
<P>
   Beat together the first 4 ingredients. Gradually beat in
additional powdered sugar to reach spreading consistency.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 508 calories, 25 grams fat, 69
grams carbohydrates, 4 grams protein, 65 milligrams cholesterol,
226 milligrams sodium, 44 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Better Homes &AMP; Gardens New Cookbook Limited Edition
1930-2000'' (Meredith, $26.95)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   SOURCES: Louis Rukeyser's ``Book of Lists,'' (Owl, $15.95); John
Mariani's ``The Dictionary of American Food and Drink'' (Hearst,
$19.95); ``Soda Pop! From Miracle Medicine to Pop Culture'' by
Gyvel Young-Witzel &AMP; Michael Karl Witzel (Town Square Books, $35);
``The Food Chronology'' by James Trager (Owl Books, $22.50);
``Fashionable Food'' by Sylvia Lovegren (Macmillan, $25);
``Mechanical Brides'' Cooper-Hewitt National Museum of Design
(Princeton Architectural Press); ``Jewish Cooking in America'' by
Joan Nathan (Knopf, $30); American Frozen Food Institute; ``The
Motley Fool's Rule Breakers, Rule Makers'' by David and Tom Gardner
(Simon &AMP; Schuster, $25); ``Revolution at the Table: The
Transformation of the American Diet'' by Harvey Levenstein (Oxford,
1988); ``Neighbor, How Long Has it Been?'' by Wallace O. Chariton
(Self-published; $14.95); ``Eating in America: A History'' by
Waverley Root &AMP; Richard De Rochemont (Morrow, 1976); McDonald's;
Kraft; ``We Remember'' by Jeanne Marie Laskas and Lynn Johnson
(Morrow, $25).
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-99 1728EDT &QL; 
