<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8590 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BOOK-TRAPPISTS-NYTR &LR;      10-06 0599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TRAPPISTS-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: S.C., N.C.) 
 `BEYOND THE WALLS' : WRITER TACKLES SPIRITUALITY EARNESTLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Publication notes appear at end of article.)  (DW) 
 By BEN STEELMAN   
 Morning Star, Wilmington, N.C.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For more than a year, writer Paul Wilkes spent a few days each
month in Moncks Corner, S.C., at Mepkin Abbey with Cistercians of
the Strict Observance _ the Trappists, reputedly the strictest
order of monks in the Roman Catholic church, the ``shock troops of
holiness.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many other ``cradle Catholics,'' Wilkes had wondered if he
had a vocation in the church. One of his heroes as a teen-ager had
been Thomas Merton, author of The Seven-Story Mountain and probably
the best-known Trappist of the 20th century. He had even directed a
PBS documentary on Merton's life.
</P>
<P>
   Yet his new book, ``Beyond the Walls,'' is not strictly about
the Trappists. (Some good recent studies of the order include Frank
Bianco's ``Voices of Silence'' and Esther de Waal's ``The Way of
Simplicity,'' which Wilkes quotes respectfully.)
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Wilkes, a faculty member of the University of North
Carolina at Wilmington, tries to take some of the Trappists'
hard-earned lessons of spirituality and apply them to the everyday
life of the ordinary lay Christian.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Wilkes is no Thomas Merton, yet he approaches his task
earnestly, with a welcome, self-deprecating sense of humor, and his
observations are usually worth heeding.
</P>
<P>
   In short, spry essays, he tackles such issues as prayer,
discerning God's will and finding community in a commercialized
society of atomized individuals. He ponders the concept of chastity
from the standpoint of a husband and father, and finds, beyond
sexuality, a rule of relationships in all aspects of life:
</P>
<P>
   ``After all, is not chastity modesty? Modesty in conversation,
when we need not dominate, but instead invite others to the true
intimacy that the honest sharing of thoughts can allow. Modesty in
thought and desire _ regarding other people, yes, but also
extending to the things of this world that we might hungrily seek,
mistakenly believing that they will bring us deep and lasting
satisfaction. Modesty in our very demeanor ... modesty in our
expectations, both of others and ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   As in such previous books as ``The Good-Enough Catholic'' and
``The Seven Secrets of Successful Catholics,'' Wilkes writes
primarily for readers within his church, but other Christians can
study ``Beyond the Walls'' with profit.
</P>
<P>
   The author himself takes an ecumenical approach, following the
example of Thomas Merton, who spent his last years exploring
Buddhist spirituality. Beyond the Walls quotes Frederick Buechner,
the Presbyterian pastor and author (whom John Irving cited as an
influence in ``A Prayer for Owen Meaney'') on the subject of faith
and Orthodox rabbis on the practice of meditation upon scripture.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bradley _ as basketball player, not as presidential
candidate _ provides lessons in stability. Even that decidedly
un-Christian rake, Woody Allen, has something to offer: ``Ninety
percent of life is just showing up.''
</P>
<P>
   While Wilkes' mind is on other things, as a journalist whose
work has appeared in Atlantic Monthly and The New York Times
Magazine cannot help but provide fascinating glimpses of the
50-year-old community of monks and their daily lives.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `BEYOND THE WALLS: Monastic Wisdom for Everyday Life'
</P>
<P>
   By Paul Wilkes
</P>
<P>
   Doubleday, $21
</P>
<P>
   (Morning Star is part of the New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-99 1730EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
