<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WASTELAND-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN `WASTELAND,' SESQUIPEDALIAN VOCABULARY GROWS WEARISOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gimme an er! Gimme an um! Gimme a y'know! What does it spell?
</P>
<P>
   Inadequacy.
</P>
<P>
   At least in Kevin Williamson's world. As a term paper,
Williamson's new series, ``Wasteland,'' might get an A if it were
graded by a nervous teaching assistant intimidated by big words,
long sentences and nonstop adjectives. But a seasoned professor
looking for a little substance in ``Wasteland'' would probably have
tenure by the time she found it.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Dawson's Creek,'' the sort of staircase wit that
Williamson's teenage characters exhibit was charming in its first
season because no kid, aside from 11-year-old prodigies with 1600s
on their SATs and Rhodes scholarships in their ``Pokemon'' packs,
ever talks like that. But in ``Wasteland,'' an um-free zone where
articulateness is the only significant measure of a man or a woman,
it is tiresome. Enervating. Exasperating. Annoying. Irksome.
</P>
<P>
   Did we mention wearisome? Galling? Vexatious?
</P>
<P>
   Williamson knows a lot of words. He could stand to know an
editor, lest anyone watching ``Wasteland'' should switch over to
``Frasier,'' where the writing is supportive of the characters, not
contemptuous of them.
</P>
<P>
   The premise of ``Wasteland'' is offered by Dawnie (Marisa
Coughlan), a grad student, in the early going of tonight's
premiere. Speaking to her anthropology professor, Dawnie says:
``I'm 25 years old, actually 26 today, and profoundly lost as a
human being. I've spent my entire life in school, my parents still
support me, human relationships baffle me and I am acutely
self-aware to the point where I'm clueless and slightly suicidal.''
</P>
<P>
   The professor, still awake at this point, says: ``And you
represent today's generation?''
</P>
<P>
   Dawnie replies: ``Absolutely. In generations past the window
into adulthood began at 18, and now it's 30. ... I believe that
this second coming of age is representative of a kind of barrier, a
wall that we hit, a manifestation of a certain type of fear that
immobilizes us. For some it's professional, for others it's
relational, emotional, sexual, et cetera.''
</P>
<P>
   Et cetera? Kevin Williamson put ``et cetera'' in a script? Did
he run out of words?
</P>
<P>
   Alas, no.
</P>
<P>
   Dawnie has more to say, as do her former college buddies Sam,
Jesse, Ty, Vandy and Russell, all trying to make their way in New
York City without slipping on this prime-time soap. FYI, in that
pile of names, Sam and Jesse join Dawnie (sounds like Donnie) as
women with guy-sounding names, Ty and Vandy are guys with
dog-sounding names, and the one with the most guy-sounding name,
Russell, is gay.
</P>
<P>
   Oh. There's also Vince, a black man who is Sam's boorish boss in
the D.A.'s office. He was added to the cast because the network
discovered NYC is a multiethnic place, but his role is like
everything else in ``Wasteland'': slick, artificial and hard to
like.
</P>
<P>
   Wasteland. Hourlong drama series about young adults who were
friends in college and are now struggling to find themselves in the
real world. Starring Marisa Coughlan, Rebecca Gayheart, Sasha
Alexander, Brad Rowe, Eddie Mills, Dan Montgomery and Jeffrey D.
Sams. Series premiere Thursday night on NBC. Parental guideline
rating: TV-PG.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
