</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-BLINKING-SNEAKERS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLINKING SHOES HAVE MANY YOUNG FANS, BUT ADULTS HAVE BEEN LESS
KEEN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Va., Minn.)   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Technological advances, it has often been noted, can bring both
good and bad. Take, for example, what happened to Alfred Acree one
night in April 1993, in Charles City, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Acree was being chased on foot by police officers, who suspected
him of dealing in drugs. At the time, Acree was wearing the latest
in footwear technology: a pair of running shoes from L.A. Gear
featuring red light-emitting diodes in the heels that flashed with
each step.
</P>
<P>
   The shoes were designed to help runners be seen easily on
darkened roads at night, but on this night they enabled Acree to be
easily spotted as he fled through the woods.
</P>
<P>
   Good for the police, bad for Acree.
</P>
<P>
   For millions of children, the experience of wearing sneakers
with lights that blinked as they walked has been a happier one. The
battery-powered children's sneakers were a sensation in the first
three years after they were introduced by L.A. Gear in 1992, said
Mark Goldston, a former chief executive of the company.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, L.A. Gear offered 30 to 40 different models. ``We
took the market by rage,'' Goldston said. ``We sold millions of
these things.''
</P>
<P>
   L.A. Gear's adult shoes did not fare as well (``It was a hot
idea for six months, like many products in the adult market,''
Goldston said), and sales of lighted children's shoes eventually
dipped too. But the children's market remains steady today, and
L.A. Gear has been joined in it by several other companies,
including Stride Rite and Skechers.
</P>
<P>
   The basic red lights have been supplemented by green and other
colors. Some models blink in patterns up and down the outside of
the sole, some flash around the heel, and some even have diodes
sewn into the uppers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're like little red wagons _ every kid has to have them,''
said Robert Greenberg, who created L.A. Gear in the 1980s and went
on to co-found Skechers in 1992. At Skechers, Greenberg said,
lighted sneakers account for 5 percent to 10 percent of sales of
children's shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Just who had the inspiration for sticking light-emitting diodes
in the soles of sneakers is a matter of some dispute. Goldston said
the concept first came to him in the late 1980s. He said he was
inspired by light sticks, those plastic tubes that contain a liquid
that glows in the dark when activated.
</P>
<P>
   Goldston wondered what would happen if he had a sneaker with a
clear heel into which light sticks could be inserted. ``It was a
great idea,'' he said. ``But light sticks only last a couple of
hours, and cost about a dollar each. But it got me thinking, what
about lights?''
</P>
<P>
   Goldston's account is disputed by others in the industry, but in
any case, inventors had struggled for decades to marry lights and
footwear. Often the intention was safety: a lighted shoe makes the
wearer more visible. But just as often the goal was simple novelty,
or entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   A 1979 patent for ``flashing discoshoes,'' for example, featured
lights embedded in a clear plastic shoe with four-inch heels.
</P>
<P>
   Patents for lighted shoes with an on-off switch in the sole or
heel were issued at least as far back as 1933, but early designs
suffered from a common drawback, as described in a later patent:
rapid depletion of the battery when the lights are continuously on,
``such as occurs in activities involving much standing.''
</P>
<P>
   Various switch designs were developed to get around this
problem, including one with a ball bearing that would roll in a
tube as the foot moved, completing an electrical circuit when it
reached contacts at the tube's end.
</P>
<P>
   In its first models, L.A. Gear used a mercury switch, in which a
small amount of the liquid metal functioned like a ball bearing,
moving within a capsule as the foot moved. But mercury is a toxic
metal, and when environmental regulators in Minnesota learned in
1994 that thousands of children were walking around with it in
their shoes, they took action.
</P>
<P>
   The state legislature voted to ban sale of the shoes, and L.A.
Gear negotiated an agreement with state officials in which the
company agreed to pay for disposal costs associated with the
roughly 20,000 pairs of sneakers it had sold in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Similar bans were considered in other states, but by then L.A.
Gear had shifted to a different switch, the kind that is used in
most lighted footwear sold today. Called an inertial switch, it
consists of a metal spring that is connected to the electrical
source on one end, and is close to, but not touching, a metal
contact at the other end.
</P>
<P>
   When the shoe is at rest or during a steady movement, the spring
remains stationary. But if the shoe moves violently or strikes an
object (such as the floor, when a step is made) the spring vibrates
enough to touch the contact, completing the circuit. A simple chip
produces the pattern of electrical pulses to the various
light-emitting diodes.
</P>
<P>
   L.A. Gear experimented with other kinds of switches too,
including a pressure switch that would turn on when the wearer
jumped. They were incorporated into a model the company called Leap
Gear, which sold for about $125 a pair and were endorsed by the
basketball star Karl Malone.
</P>
<P>
   The National Basketball Association promptly banned them, and
Leap Gear went nowhere. But all the publicity helped L.A. Gear's
other models, Goldston recalled. ``It made little Johnny in Peoria
want to buy the other lines. It's an old story _ using the Corvette
to sell Camaros,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
