<SLUG> BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-art-ADV24-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR RELEASE: SUN., OCT. 24, 1999. 
 HOME IMPROVEMENT QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
  By BERNARD GLADSTONE 
 Includes illustration. 
 Copyright 1999 Bernard Gladstone 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: As a first time homeowner I was told to keep a rubber
plumber's ``plunger'' handy in case one of my sinks got clogged.
However, when my bathroom sink did clog recently, I tried to use my
plunger but it didn't seem to be very effective.
</P>
<P>
   I finally called in a plumber who cleared the drain (by using a
plunger) and he told my wife (I wasn't home) that I probably did
not use my plunger properly.
</P>
<P>
   Is there some special method or technique I should know about
before I have this type of problem again?
</P>
<P>
   A: There are a few points to keep in mind when using a plunger.
In a bathroom sink be sure you first plug the overflow hole near
the top of the rim by forcing a wet rag in as shown here. If the
sink has a pop-up drain plug, remove this.
</P>
<P>
   Then fill the basin about half way up with water and coat the
rubber rim of the plunger with a light film of petroleum jelly so
it will form an airtight seal with the inside bottom of the sink.
</P>
<P>
   Press the rubber cup firmly over the drain opening and pump up
and down on the handle a few times without actually breaking the
seal or lifting the rubber cup from the drain opening. Finally,
give the handle a sharp yank upward to break the seal and create a
sudden suction on the drain.
</P>
<P>
   Although this will usually do the trick, in stubborn cases you
may have to repeat the process two or three times to completely
break up the clog.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have an old family picture frame that has a gold finish
which I believe is gold leaf. However, the gold has tarnished and
turned dark so that it no longer looks like gold. How can I restore
this finish and bring it back to the original gold color?
</P>
<P>
   A: Gold leaf does not tarnish or change color, regardless of how
old it is. Your frame was obviously finished with a gilt or gold
paint of some kind, or with a type of metal leaf that is not
actually real gold.
</P>
<P>
   You can try refinishing the frame by first wiping down with a
rag moistened with paint thinner to clean it, then sanding it
lightly before you apply a gold paint or wax-type gilt finish of
some kind (sold in many paint stores, as well as in most art supply
stores).
</P>
<P>
   You could also bring the frame in to a professional to have it
refinished with actual gold leaf _ but this will be quite
expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My roof is covered with asphalt shingles that are about 10
years old and still in pretty good condition. During a severe
windstorm recently a couple of the shingles on one side of the
house got lifted up and torn, and one shingle has a little piece
missing. How can I repair those damaged shingles without having to
call in a professional roofer?
</P>
<P>
   A. Assuming you can find shingles that match in color, you can
do the job by first lifting the damaged shingles up slightly, then
sweeping out any dirt and debris underneath them.
</P>
<P>
   Spread a liberal coat of roofing cement under the shingle, then
slide a new shingle under the old one and on top of the layer of
cement.
</P>
<P>
   Drive in one or two roofing nails up near the top of the
replacement shingle. Spread another layer of cement over the nail
heads and over part of the new shingle _ the part covered by the
old shingle when it is pressed back down.
</P>
<P>
   If the shingle tends to curl back up it may be necessary to
weight it down with a brick for a day or two until the cement bonds
it in place.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The walls inside our old house have a sand finish on them,
although they have been painted many times. This rough surface is
hard to wash or clean so I would like to smooth it down. Sanding
would be very messy and very difficult for me, so can you tell me
if there is any other way I can smooth these walls?
</P>
<P>
   A. There are two possibilities that I can think of. One is to
have a paperhanger cover the walls with one of the special heavy
duty lining materials (usually a canvas or vinyl) that is sold for
use on rough or textured walls. They leave you with a smooth
surface that can be painted or papered.
</P>
<P>
   Another is to have a contractor install new drywall panels over
the existing wall surfaces.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about home-repair problems should be addressed to
Bernard Gladstone, care of The New York Times Syndication Sales
Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168. Questions of general
interest will be answered in this column; Mr. Gladstone regrets
that unpublished letters cannot be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Drawing captioned ``SUCCESSFULLY UNCLOGGING DRAIN'' goes
with this column.
</P>
<P>
   CAPTION: After overflow hole has been plugged, plunger is pumped
up and down a few times before it is yanked up from the drain
opening.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
