<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
 (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, Oct. 7, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call 212-556-4204.) 
(th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A very chilly day is expected in New England as sunshine mixes
with a few clouds. A blustery breeze will gust over 30 mph in
northern sections, which will enhance the day's chill. A few
sprinkles or flurries are likely in northern Maine.
</P>
<P>
   High pressure near Toronto will produce a killing frost Thursday
morning over much of the northern Appalachians. Sunshine will
dominate from southern New England through the Middle Atlantic
States.
</P>
<P>
   The boundary with tropical air over the Gulf of Mexico will be
activated by a jet stream disturbance moving east from New Mexico.
High level winds from the south will draw clouds and rain into the
central Gulf Coast. More showers will dampen central and south
Florida. Increasing onshore winds in the Carolinas will cause rough
surf.
</P>
<P>
   A wedge of very warm air will move from Texas into the central
Plains. As warmer air glides northward into the Great Lakes,
showers and a few thunderstorms will develop. Cold winds from the
northeast will make an inclement day around Lake Superior.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific air will stream eastward across the northern Rockies
with broken clouds and slightly above seasonal temperatures. A
large disturbance moving through the southern Rockies will trigger
numerous showers from Colorado to central New Mexico. Offshore
winds, circulating around high pressure in Oregon, will draw warmer
air into southern California.
</P>
<P>
   A moist onshore flow in northern Washington will bring abundant
clouds and some rain to the Olympic peninsula. Clouds will stream
into the Bitterroots.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: UTAH UNDULATIONS
</P>
<P>
   A casual observer of the weather would have been struck by what
appeared to be a dramatic cold front straddling the state of Utah
on Tuesday. An Oct. 5 record minimum of 26 degrees was set in Park
City in the northeast section, while the afternoon brought record
heat of 92 degrees to Delta in the southern part of the state.
Actually, the sky was clear across the region and no front could be
found. The chill in Park City was a residual shallow cold air mass,
lingering with the lengthening nights. The hot air in Delta
signaled a resumption of an air flow from the deserts of the
Southwest.
</P>
</TEXT>
