Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   MEMPHIS-MAYOR _ The way Memphis Mayor Willie Herenton sees it,
his main opponent in Thursday's election isn't even on the ballot.
City Council Chairman Joe Ford, considered the top challenger in a
crowded field, is just a figurehead for his big brother, former
U.S. Rep. Harold Ford Sr., according to Herenton. The animosity
between the outspoken Herenton, the city's first elected black
mayor, and the fiery Ford, patriarch of the city's most politically
powerful black family, is only part of the intrigue of this year's
mayoral election. Fifteen candidates are on the ballot in the
nonpartisan election, including professional wrestler Jerry ``The
King'' Lawler, who gained notoriety in 1982 when he slapped
comedian Andy Kaufman on ``Late Night With David Letterman,'' and
Pepper Rodgers, the former Georgia Tech football coach who led
Memphis' failed attempt to get an NFL franchise. (Konigsmark,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   GINGRICH-DIVORCE _ ATLANTA _ As promised, Newt Gingrich kept the
pressure on his wife Wednesday by asking a Cobb County judge to
hold Marianne Gingrich in contempt. (Stanford, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   KOCH-TRIAL _ TULSA, Okla. _ Testimony continues in the trial
that has become the latest legal battle between the warring
millionaire Koch brothers, William Koch of Palm Beach and the
company led by two of his brothers _ one of them his twin, David,
also of Palm Beach. The brothers inherited a fortune generated by
the second-biggest privately held company in the United States,
Koch Industries of Wichita, Kan. The low-profile company operates
oil refineries and pipelines and engages in numerous other
businesses, from cattle to asphalt. It does not release earnings,
but published reports put its annual revenues at $30 billion to $35
billion. The trial is about largely technical issues _ how the
company measured oil it obtained under leases from the federal
government and American Indian tribes, particularly the Osage
Nation in Oklahoma. Neither side has said how much money is at
stake, but published reports say William alleges the shortages
amounted to millions of dollars. (Cohen, Palm Beach Daily News).
WITH PHOTOS (Mugs of David and William).
</P>
