<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991006.0235 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8660 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BOOK-COLUMN-ART-NYT &LR;      10-06 1117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-COLUMN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING BOOKS COLUMN: WHOSE STORY IS IT ANYWAY? 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By MARTIN ARNOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The lives of friends and acquaintances are as necessary to
fiction writers as the runaway slave was to Huck Finn, so beware of
the novelist or short-story writer as friend. If you don't, then
sooner or later you might be pridefully reading your chum's work
and the light bulb of recognition will pop in your head and you'll
say, ``Whoa, that's me.''
</P>
<P>
   The writer will have confiscated your character and stolen your
life story, and there you are, rendered exposed and helpless. Or
perhaps even exposed and feeling pretty good about yourself. Either
way, watch out. That's what fiction writers often do, and have
always done: snatch what doesn't belong to them.
</P>
<P>
   And there's no way to wrest your personal chronicle back from
the writer, and only very, very seldom is there any way to get
recompense for the appropriation of the property that is you.
</P>
<P>
   Case in point. Over the weekend, there was a lengthy item in the
gossip columns of The New York Post alleging that Melissa Bank,
fiction writer, had plucked a piece of the life of a friend, Judith
Keller, a playwright and filmmaker, and turned it into a short
story that was included in her best-selling collection, ``The
Girls' Guide to Hunting and Fishing'' (Viking).
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Keller's play ``The Club Med Account'' has had a staged
reading conducted by Nigel Noble, and she is writing another play,
but what she is really afraid of, she says, is that now people will
think she stole her own life from Ms. Bank rather than vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   She said she and Ms. Bank had agreed in writing that when the
story, ``The Best Possible Light,'' appeared in a book, it would be
introduced this way: ``As told to me by Judith Keller.'' It wasn't.
But by Ms. Keller's account, the ``agreed in writing'' was a rather
singular ceremony in which the two women, sitting together, each
wrote on a scrap of paper the proposed story introduction and each
signed her own scrap, which each of them then tucked away without
exchanging them. Surely that's a scene worthy of a short story.
</P>
<P>
   Hello. A playwright and filmmaker should know that writers
shamelessly ingest what they see, what they hear, what you tell
them, and, if they are truly good, somehow they make all that their
own. That's their magic. Or, as Ms. Bank put it: ``Every story you
write has something to do with real life. Yours, or someone else's.
That's where you start. It's never where you end up if the story is
any good.'' She would say no more.
</P>
<P>
   The history of writing is rich with examples of the
extraordinary adventurousness with which authors make others' lives
the stuff of their writing. For instance, Flaubert's ``Madame
Bovary'' did more than tap the rhythms and idiom of French
petit-bourgeois village life. Flaubert's father was a physician,
and the novel is largely based on the marriage of one of Dr.
Flaubert's medical students, Eugene Delamare, and the suicide of
his wife, Delphine, after an adulterous affair.
</P>
<P>
   In Zola's most overtly autobiographical novel, ``L'Oeuvre,'' the
main character, an artist, was based almost entirely on the
novelist's lifelong friend Cezanne. The novel concluded that the
fictional artist, and therefore the great master, was, in the end,
a creative failure. Cezanne was deeply hurt, and there is no record
that the two men ever spoke to each other again after the work's
publication in 1886.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, the main character in Saul Bellow's ``Humboldt's
Gift'' (Viking Press, 1975), the sumptuous Von Humboldt Fleisher,
poet, thinker and manic schemer, was based on the poet Delmore
Schwartz. The very conceit of a writer's pilfering someone else's
life seems to fascinate writers.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Margulies' play ``Collected Stories,'' very popular off-
Broadway last year, was about two women, an older writer and her
young disciple, a plot eerily similar in some ways to the
Bank-Keller flap. (Schwartz had a whole second life in other
writers' work. The older woman in the play also had a love affair
with Delmore Schwartz.)
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bank is obviously not Flaubert or Zola or Bellow. But did
she rip off someone's life the way they did? Ms. Keller says yes,
and there are those who would agree. Did Ms. Bank veer too close to
Ms. Keller's experience? Perhaps, but one publisher, not Ms.
Bank's, shrugged off the question when asked about the ethics and
said: ``That's what fiction writers do. They write not only their
own experiences but what they learn from other people.''
</P>
<P>
   Is this appropriating legal? In 1994, Viking canceled the novel
``While England Sleeps'' by David Leavitt in both Britain and the
United States after Sir Stephen Spender, the poet, sued in English
courts, charging that Leavitt had stolen the story of a doomed
homosexual love affair from the 1951 Spender memoir, ``World Within
World.'' Furthermore, the poet said that by adding explicit
imagined details, Leavitt had violated Spender's ``moral right'' to
control how his own material was used, the latter point arising out
of a British copyright law that was new at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Even in this case the publisher's surrender was extremely
unusual. But pillaging someone's memoir is different from borrowing
someone's experiences. Generally if a person is identifiable, in
the sense that her friends and acquaintances recognize her, and she
is defamed, then there is a cause for libel action. But in the
practical world it is hard to prove that a fictional character
defamed a real person, short of the shock of an allegation of
terrible horror _ incest with one's father, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   Can the plaintiff claim that a contract existed with the writer,
as Ms. Keller implies? It can be claimed, but the burden of proof
of a contract is on the plaintiff. A prominent publishing house
lawyer said that these cases were not usually very successful for
the plaintiffs.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are cases in which the novelist should beware.
Years ago a novelist, Gwen Mitchell, went to a nude encounter group
and signed a firm contract that she wouldn't disclose what happened
there. Despite that, a couple of years later she wrote a novel
about it. The leader of the encounter group was tall, thin and
clean-shaven. To disguise him and the group, the author depicted
him in her book as bearded. But people change, and by the time the
book was published he was bearded. He sued, and Ms. Mitchell and
her publisher, Doubleday, were held accountable and had to pay
damages.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-99 1804EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991006.0236 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8662 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-CHILD-WEBSITES-AR     10-06 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-CHILD-WEBSITES-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLINE HELP FOR INQUIRING YOUNG MINDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By MICHELLE SLATALLA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is a partial list of questions that the two most curious
humans on this planet asked me the other day while they were eating
an after-school snack: What are the stages of a solar eclipse? When
is the Backstreet Boys' next concert? What are the definitions of
mean, median and mode? How can we get tickets to a Backstreet Boys
concert? Why do some bees have longer legs than others? Can we buy
a color printer, go online, find color photos of the Backstreet
Boys, print them out and tape them to our bedroom walls?
</P>
<P>
   As I looked at my two older daughters, ages 10 and 8, I realized
that for once I had got lucky. While there are some days when Zoe's
and Ella's unrelenting need to know everything about everything
stumps me completely, this time I knew the answer: No, you may
never, ever put tape on the walls.
</P>
<P>
   As for the rest of their queries, I decided that this would be a
good time for them to use some Internet search sites that are
designed for children _ and which in theory should know a broader
range of answers than I do. ``OK,'' Ella said. ``But we can only do
it for an hour because we want to watch `The Simpsons.'''
</P>
<P>
   Fine, I said, because I secretly had my own agenda: I wanted to
see how easily they navigated each site. I had spent a few hours
earlier in the week conducting test searches at five children's
search sites, but as a mere adult, what did I know about what kids
like? All five sites promised to have the best collection of online
information for children, and all five employed human or software
filters to block pornographic, profane and violent sites. I wanted
to put both claims to a test.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, my children's opinions differed from mine. They were
charmed by all five sites, found each intuitively easy to navigate,
never ran across a single inappropriate link and got so diverted
when their queries led them onto intellectual tangents that they
forgot to log off in time to watch ``The Simpsons.''
</P>
<P>
   YAHOOLIGANS
</P>
<P>
   www.yahooligans.com
</P>
<P>
   Yahooligans looks like a junior version of its parent site at
Yahoo, with a home page that has both a prominent query box and a
list of general categories that you can click on to start delving
into more specific topics. Information is organized in a manner
that mimics Yahoo as well; when a user submits a query, it searches
for answers from among its own proprietary directory of sites,
which have been screened and organized by category, topic and
subtopic.
</P>
<P>
   The site differs from its parent mainly in the amount of
information available _ filtering blocks many adult sites available
on Yahoo _ and the way information is categorized. For instance,
two of Yahooligans' biggest categories are School Bell and Sports
and Recreation, with information geared to 7- to 12-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   How big is the site's directory? I can't say for sure, because
Catherine Davis, Yahooligans' managing editor and producer, told me
that Yahooligans doesn't release that information because ``we
don't want to start some kind of competition where another site
claims to be more comprehensive by claiming they have one more site
than we do.'' But in any event, my daughters found plenty of
relevant responses to their queries here.
</P>
<P>
   When, for instance, Ella typed ``Backstreet Boys'' in the query
box, the site responded in two ways: with a list of four categories
and a list of 62 sites where she could find information on tour
dates, band members and photos. And when Zoe typed ``sharks'' in
the query box on the home page, she was so overwhelmed by the
number of responses _ 24 categories and 143 specific sites _ that
she immediately went back and narrowed the search to ``shark attack
pictures,'' which led her two clicks later to a shark attack fact
sheet. Did you know that more people are killed annually by bees
than by sharks? Zoe does.
</P>
<P>
   To check the filtering, I searched for the word ``sex.''
Yahooligans responded with a list of three sites _ a technical
discussion of the process of fertility and two links to a separate
site guide for parents.
</P>
<P>
   Our only complaint: this heavily trafficked site, which had
463,000 visitors in August, according to the Media Metrix research
company, may be too popular. During a return visit on a subsequent
weeknight, the site was unable to process Ella's identical requests
for information about the Backstreet Boys. After the site told her
four times in a row that ``a connection to the server could not be
established,'' she got frustrated and signed off.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ASK JEEVES FOR KIDS
</P>
<P>
   www.ajkids.com
</P>
<P>
   Ask Jeeves for Kids has a very uncluttered home page, dominated
by an image of an intrepid butler on safari and a query box that
directed Zoe and Ella to ``please type a question and click
`Ask!''' This format is different from the searching techniques _
keyword searches or clicking on topics _ common at the other search
sites. My daughters immediately preferred this format; after all,
their inclination is to seek information by asking questions, not
by using Boolean logic to search on key phrases.
</P>
<P>
   When a user poses a question _ Zoe typed, ``What are stars?'' _
the site tries to match the wording against a list of two million
questions for which the site has answers. This technique of gently
nudging a child in the right direction is a very effective way of
teaching the site's intended audience _ 7- to 12-year-olds _ how to
pose thoughtful questions that will lead them to the answers they
really want. Instead of searching the Web for answers, the site
serves up responses that have been preselected and archived in a
directory. (My query about sex elicited two reasonable,
child-friendly alternatives: ``Where do babies come from?'' and
``Where can teens get advice online?'')
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Zoe's question, the site responded by asking
whether Zoe really had meant to ask ``Where can I see a star
chart?'' Within seconds, Zoe was examining a globe-shaped chart of
the night sky.
</P>
<P>
   The site focuses more on academic subjects than on
entertainment. Penny Finnie, the site's executive producer, said:
``Based on the questions we see children asking, we specialize in
answering questions about science and history. We don't offer as
much information about games.'' For my daughters, using the site
was as entertaining as any game.
</P>
<P>
   SEARCHOPOLIS
</P>
<P>
   www.searchopolis.com
</P>
<P>
   Designed for older children, ages 10 to 18, Searchopolis looks
and operates much more like a typical search engine than the other
children's search sites. The search results, for instance, list the
addresses of specific sites, not just text descriptions of their
contents. The search and filtering strategies are less restrictive
than the other sites'. ``Our philosophy is much different from the
other kids' search sites,'' said Peter Nickerson, chief executive
of N2H2, which owns Searchopolis. ``Our approach is to think that
kids will use the Web in ways we cannot even imagine, and so we
need to provide them access to as much information as possible, as
long as it's safe.''
</P>
<P>
   So instead of answering queries with selections from a
relatively limited, pre-edited directory of sites, Searchopolis
uses the same powerful Inktomi search technology utilized by
general search sites like Hotbot. After filtering, 90 percent of
Inktomi's database of 100 million pages is available to
Searchopolis users.
</P>
<P>
   The result is an abundance of information _ on topics ranging
from the Backstreet Boys (the site offered a list of 6,669 sites)
to sex (with a list of 172 sites). ``Our own feeling is that an
awful lot of sites that have `sex' in them are not only appropriate
but also have information designed for kids,'' Nickerson said,
adding that a team of editors reviews each site with potentially
inappropriate content before deciding whether to filter it.
</P>
<P>
   When I searched for ``sex,'' for instance, the first 20
responses covered a wide range of topics, from ``Somatic
sex-determining signals act on XX germ cells in Drosophila
embryos'' to ``Massachusetts Sex Offender Registry Information.''
</P>
<P>
   And when Zoe asked the site to find ``pictures of the moon,''
Searchopolis responded with a list of 47,045. But the responses
weren't always as relevant as those from the pre-selected sites.
When Zoe clicked on the first response, the home page for a company
called Full Moon Pictures filled the screen.
</P>
<P>
   AOL NETFIND/KIDS ONLY
</P>
<P>
   This is a children's version of America Online's proprietary
search engine, and, like the rest of AOL, it has a design so simple
and clean that even a beginner can navigate it without much
trouble. Version 5.0 of the service made its debut this month, but
no changes were made to the way the children's search engine works.
</P>
<P>
   Zoe greeted this site like an old friend and informed me that
this is the search engine she uses at school, where she learned
tricks like how to narrow a search by adding more specific keywords
to her query. ``Most people in my class figured out how to use it
pretty fast,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Aimed at children from ages 6 to 12, AOL Netfind/Kids Only uses
the Cyber Patrol software filter from the Learning Company to block
access to sites that are considered pornographic, profane or
violent. Using adult wiles and trying really hard, I managed to
find a link to a single inappropriate site: a search on the keyword
``breast'' led me to a college research paper called ``Kids
Online,'' which linked to both the Playboy and Penthouse home
pages.
</P>
<P>
   However, my standardized test for dirty words _ a search on the
word ``sex'' _ produced no responses on Kids Only, a result that
seems almost too restrictive. After all, I want my daughters to
know that sex exists, as long as that's all they know until
they're, say, 25.
</P>
<P>
   If you do happen to stumble across something you think is
inappropriate for children, enter the keyword Parental Controls and
click on the button that says Recommend or Report Web sites. I made
a report on Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Ginny Wydler, AOL's director of standards and policies, said the
number of sites in the service's directory was ``in the tens of
thousands,'' a relatively small number compared with the other
children's search sites. And this was the only one of the five
sites that turned up no results when we followed its search tips to
conduct a search on ``mean AND median AND mode.''
</P>
<P>
   AOLNetfind/Kids Only is also the only search among the five we
tested that carries no advertising _ although search results may
include sites that carry ads.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
