<DOCNO> NYT19991006.0238 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8665 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-VIEW-OPERA-ART-2TAKES     10-06 1022
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIEW-OPERA-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REALITY HITS SINGERS IN THE HOME STRETCH
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By BRUCE WEBER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ As it approaches, the premiere of an opera, almost
unbearably languorous in its gestation, gallops toward opening
night with frightful speed.
</P>
<P>
   It has been four years since Lyric Opera of Chicago commissioned
an adaptation of Arthur Miller's 1955 play, ``A View From the
Bridge,'' from composer William Bolcom and librettist Arnold
Weinstein. The last of the principal roles _ Eddie Carbone, the
Brooklyn dockworker whose lust for his niece, Catherine, brings
about his tragic death _ was cast a year ago. The set was designed
by early summer. The singers, who have had their parts since
spring, began rehearsals in August. The orchestra came in three
weeks ago. The costumes had their fine-tunings last week.
</P>
<P>
   The opera opens on Saturday night at the Civic Opera House here
to a sellout crowd of more than 3,600. But the first full-dress
run-through with the orchestra and all the creative elements in
place was only Tuesday. Wednesday, another dress rehearsal adds an
audience of invited guests.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a collision of forces,'' said Frank Galati, the stage
director. ``We're not careening out of control, but we are being
jettisoned toward the living event.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it is the singers who will be propelled before the
public with the most stirring immediacy, which makes the last
rehearsals a swift pivot, from a concern with ingesting a role _ to
use the word of Catherine Malfitano, the soprano who plays
Beatrice, Eddie's wife _ to a concern with sharing and projecting
it.
</P>
<P>
   As a consequence, in these final days, seemingly minute changes
don't seem quite so minute. When the pronunciation of one
character's name was altered from Louis to Louie (Arthur Miller was
consulted on this) there was consternation among the singers, whose
musical interpretations of text are affected by such things.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, the hardest thing is to go from the notes on the page
to the organic place inside of me where the words and music
suddenly come together and become my creation,'' Ms. Malfitano
said. ``To take something foreign to you and ingest it and make it
a part of you so that when you perform it nobody ever realizes it
was ever anywhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   During the home stretch, the singers are also making the
disorienting move from the rehearsal room to the theater, where the
larger stage requires a different spacing among the performers, and
the vast auditorium, with its own acoustics, demands a new
attention to projection. And as the singers work with the
orchestra, their hearing needs to be attuned anew as well. To
locate a pitch on the oboe or trombone after being accustomed to
hearing it on the piano is an adjustment; so is singing with brass
players, whose volume and tone may compete with those of a voice,
or with pianissimo strings, which an overly forceful voice may
threaten to obscure.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time I've sung in this house,'' said Gregory
Turay, 26, who plays Rodolpho, the immigrant swain who steals
Catherine's heart. ``I've sung in the Met, and that has a warmer
feeling. In this house it's hard to feel my voice. I don't know if
I'm pushing.''
</P>
<P>
   In a world premiere, of course, the pressure on opening night is
heightened by the notion that it is a defining occasion. This is
the first premiere for Turay, something he prefers not to think
about (``You can fill your head with that stuff and
self-destruct'') but that the singers acknowledge has complicated
their task all along.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overcoming the technical obstacles, getting the part in your
voice so it's a consequent expressive outpouring _ it's more
difficult with a new role because there's no other standard,'' said
Ms. Malfitano, whose 30-year career has included a number of new
works, including Bolcom's ``McTeague,'' at Lyric in 1992. ``We're
proving that the opera is eminently learnable, singable, doable,
enjoyable.''
</P>
<P>
   The most obvious handicap, perhaps, is that there is no
recording of the work; in learning their roles the singers were on
their own, and as with much of contemporary composition the musical
vocabulary has an unbridled range. Chords of varying dissonance
mingle with those of wrenching sentimentality; leaps and dives in
pitch of more than an octave, not the easiest for even trained
singers to hear, are frequent, which can be grueling for the voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``In spite of the fact that we all make a great case for modern
music, the truth is it is more anti-vocal than the older stuff,''
said baritone Kim Josephson, who plays Eddie Carbone. ``It's
harder.''
</P>
<P>
   And indeed, many singers simply steer clear of contemporary
operas altogether. But those who don't relish the challenge
precisely because it allows them to unveil the thrill, the
sensuousness and the lyricism of unfamiliar sounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``That thrill is learned, to a certain extent,'' said Dawn
Upshaw, who will sing the role of Daisy Buchanan in John Harbison's
adaptation of ``The Great Gatsby'' at the Metropolitan Opera in New
York in December. ``By listening to singers of the past, we've
learned what the thrilling moments are supposed to be. It is true
that there are many composers today who are struggling to find a
new way to write for voice, and in so doing have lost a sense of
what is vocal and lyrical. But when they are written well, I love
singing leaps. They can be incredibly expressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Bolcom's score has its idiosyncrasies, the singers say; he's
fond of ninths and tritones, particularly discordant intervals. And
as difficult as the music can be, in learning it, the predilections
of the composer are revealed. ``Like Mozart or Bellini, Bolcom has
a musical language,'' said Juliana Rambaldi, the soprano who plays
Eddie's niece, Catherine. ``Once you understand the language, it's
easier; you start to hear like he does. You can expect a ninth
here, or a tritone there.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In a new piece, Ms. Malfitano added, it's part of her job to
help the audience stretch their ears in order to find the beauty
she has worked to discover for herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``People always say, `Is there something you can walk out of the
opera humming?''' she said. ``What they have to learn to appreciate
is the virtuosity of what we are doing, to try and make a ninth
sound as consonant as a second, to try and build a melodic line.''
For both singer and listener, she said, ``it's possible to find the
line there, but it's a little more work.''
</P>
<P>
   They are helped by the presence of Bolcom, a luxury generally
unavailable in a work from the classic repertory. ``When we come
across a section of the music that seems odd, we can ask him, `What
did you mean here?''' Josephson said. ``I have a line at the end of
a fight scene, the tessatura'' _ the general range of the passage _
``is high, and it comes on what feels like the wrong part of a
beat. It just seemed awkward, and finally I looked over at Bill,
and I said, `What is this?' And he said, `Oh, Kim, you're supposed
to be panting after this fight. It goes like this.' And he panted
it for me, and it made perfect sense.''
</P>
<P>
   They are helped as well by the very Americanness of the work.
Not only does Bolcom draw on an identifiably American musical idiom
(the influence of pop and show music is intermittently felt) but
the play, of course, is a standard repertory piece from the
American theater. The language is English of a particularly
American vernacular, that of working-class post-World War II
Brooklyn. (Hence: Louie.) The cultural familiarity is a boon to the
singers, particularly in their acting, which is of paramount
importance in a contemporary work that has no familiar music with
which to palliate an audience and needs all its available modes of
seduction: story and character as well as song.
</P>
<P>
   In recent decades, singers themselves have increasingly
acknowledged and concentrated on the dramatic elements of their
stage work, and lip service is often paid to the totality of
performance. But it was a bit of a surprise to discover how focused
these singers have been on the melding of text and music into
drama. In interviews they had to be pressed to discuss music at
all; acting was foremost on their minds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Catherine is between a girl and a woman,'' Ms. Rambaldi said,
``and for me it's been interesting to find when she's a girl and
when she's a woman. How much does she realize what's going on
between her and Eddie? It was tempting to approach her as too wise
a person, because I'm older than 17. I had to check back a little
bit and find the moments when she was a girl.''
</P>
<P>
   (Ms. Rambaldi, who is 32 and pregnant, will sing only the first
six performances; for the final three she will be replaced by a
Canadian singer, Isabel Bayrakdarian.)
</P>
<P>
   Mark McCrory, the bass baritone who plays Marco, Rodolpho's
brother and the agent of Eddie's demise, has only one significant
musical moment, but it is a doozy; an aria (with lyrics by Miller)
in which he channels the pain of immigrant life into his disgust
with Eddie, the man who has betrayed him. The furious emotion of
the moment is tempered by Marco's innate dignity and self-control.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's really pouring out his soul in that aria,'' McCrory said.
``What he feels, where he's coming from, and that gets channeled
into his hate for Eddie. With all that emotion, maintaining that
stoicism in the character is the difficult part. That's what I've
been struggling with throughout rehearsals, trying to sing it well,
balance out the emotions and still not let them get in the way of
the vocalism.''
</P>
<P>
   How the opera will be received by the opening night audience is,
of course, a drama in itself. But anyone witnessing recent
rehearsals would come away aware that the drama is working at least
for the performers, who have frequently been reduced to tears by
the tragic finale.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hoping everybody loves it like we do,'' Ms. Malfitano
said. ``We have the good fortune to become intimate with it, and
the audience will not have that chance.''
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, is often the plight of new operas, the vast
majority of which go unperformed a second or third time. The
frequent lament is that composers suffer and that audiences are
left the poorer. But singers have bet on a work with their time and
effort, and risk never having a chance to reprise their roles and
grow in them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just beginning to taste this piece,'' Ms. Malfitano
said. ``And every night it will get deeper, more exotic, more
sensual. The sad part of this is that I've done over 100
performances of `Madame Butterfly.' I doubt I'll ever do 100
performances of Bea. I hope I'll do more than nine.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
