<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8671 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-WALL-BOOK-REVIEW-ART-     10-06 1193
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALL-BOOK-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`A GREAT WALL': THE LONG DELICATE DANCE WITH CHINESE LEADERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(Eds: Andrew J. Nathan is a professor of political science at
Columbia University and co-author of ``The Great Wall and the Empty
Fortress: China's Search for Security'' (W.W. Norton, 1997).) 
(JT) 
 By ANDREW J. NATHAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The recent crisis in the Taiwan Strait makes Patrick E. Tyler's
account of three decades of U.S. policy-making toward China
especially welcome, for Taiwan has always been at the center of the
U.S.-China relationship. China insists on its sovereignty over the
island and reserves the right to use force to prevent it from going
independent. The United States is committed to protect Taiwan from
the mainland's use of force, but does not want it to claim
independence.
</P>
<P>
   This might be a formula for peace if the people of Taiwan wanted
unity with the mainland, but they don't. So the American position
on Taiwan resembles that on Kosovo _ we defend your right to
autonomy as long as you don't want it _ but it is more troublesome
in some ways. How did we get here? Tyler's ``investigative
history'' is based on thousands of government documents, scores of
interviews, and a thorough mining of archives and memoirs.
</P>
<P>
   Tyler, a correspondent for The New York Times and its former
Beijing bureau chief, tells a complex story with impressive
clarity. He brings us deskside to the policy makers and shows us
their strategic visions and private manipulations. His material is
richer on the American side, but he tells us as much as possible
about the Chinese side as well.
</P>
<P>
   In these memoir-drenched times it is hard to come up with a
major revision of our understanding of how China policy was made.
President Richard M. Nixon ``opened'' China partly to balance the
power of the Soviet Union, but mainly to get help exiting from the
Vietnam War, a hope in which he was disappointed. President Jimmy
Carter normalized relations because he needed a big achievement
before the next presidential campaign. President Ronald Reagan
downgraded the role of China in his global strategy, over the
objections of his secretary of state, Alexander M. Haig Jr.
President George Bush tried to rescue the relationship from the
wreckage of Tiananmen. President Clinton bluffed China on human
rights and lost.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Tyler's narrative concerns the fine-grain machinations
of the policy process, sometimes down to the banquet menus. Nixon
prevailed on the Chinese to delay invitations to Democrats until he
could get there first. His national security adviser, Henry A.
Kissinger, kept White House talks with China secret from the State
Department, hero-worshiped Mao Zedong and Zhou Enlai and flattered
the president.
</P>
<P>
   Zbigniew Brzezinski, Carter's national security adviser, gave
about as much energy to defeating Secretary of State Cyrus R. Vance
as to defeating the Soviet Union. Haig yelled at State Department
staff members. The U.S. ambassador J. Stapleton Roy gave a
newspaper interview to Tyler that undercut State Department policy
on human rights abuses in China.
</P>
<P>
   One can deplore the pettiness of the policy process, much of
which has long been known, but what about the results? In ``About
Face'' (Knopf, 1999), which covers the same history, James Mann
argues that the Americans were bamboozled by Chinese bluster and
dazzled by exaggerated visions of China's greatness. Tyler does not
believe China poses a substantial threat to America so he does not
make this criticism. He has a few tactical complaints, some larger
(Kissinger encouraged a Chinese attack on India in 1971,
fortunately without result) and some smaller (Kissinger might have
probed the Chinese position more forcefully in 1974). But he seems
largely to accept the wisdom of American policy on China as it has
evolved.
</P>
<P>
   Reading not too far beneath the surface of Tyler's account, one
can argue that it was the Chinese, not the Americans, who got
snookered, not once but twice. First, in the high-tension
negotiations over the normalization of diplomatic relations in
1978, the Americans only at the last minute told the Chinese
leader, Deng Xiaoping, that the United States intended to continue
arms sales to Taiwan. Because the American military link is all
that prevents China from gaining control over Taiwan, this point
was of fundamental importance. The Chinese had reasonably assumed
that the Americans would cease arms sales to a country they no
longer recognized.
</P>
<P>
   Deng was apparently shocked, but having started preparations to
invade Vietnam partly on the strength of the upcoming
normalization, he went ahead, telling the Americans that he would
readdress the question later. Meanwhile Congress _ that annoying
additional branch with which it is impossible for foreign
governments to negotiate _ added injury to insult by passing the
Taiwan Relations Act, which has been generally interpreted (rightly
or wrongly) as requiring extensive arms sales to Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   In 1982 the Chinese forced the Reagan administration to agree to
reduce arms sales to Taiwan step by step. Yet the Americans soon
weaseled out of this commitment, partly by twisting the language of
the accord and partly by simply violating it. Today, Tyler points
out, United States arms are flowing into Taiwan in higher
quantities and quality than ever, potentially creating the
conditions for a high-tech war.
</P>
<P>
   Tyler's close review of the negotiating record makes clear that
the Americans thought the Chinese would have to compromise on
Taiwan because of their strategic needs, and the Chinese thought
the Americans could be weaned from their commitment to the
strategically secondary island. But despite decades of ingenious
draftsmanship on both sides, the positions on this issue have never
fundamentally changed.
</P>
<P>
   Neither side ever fully understood the depth of the other's
strategic interest in Taiwan. Americans tended to attribute the
Chinese position on Taiwan to emotional nationalism and still do,
and the Chinese seem to think (and often hear from Americans) that
the United States position on Taiwan is determined by the need to
cater to the Republican right and the pro-Taiwan lobby. In fact,
the Taiwan issue is more nonnegotiable than this on both sides.
China's territorial security depends on control of the island, and
the Pax Americana in Asia depends on the United States' ability to
prevent resolution of the issue by force.
</P>
<P>
   As Tyler points out, the United States has worked itself into a
trap in which Taiwan is in charge of our China policy. He might
have added that the Chinese are in a similar trap because they need
unification and good relations with the United States. Thirty years
of effort have only consolidated this mutual dilemma and 30 years
more may not be enough to work ourselves out of it.
</P>
<P>
   A GREAT WALL
</P>
<P>
   Six Presidents and China, An Investigative History
</P>
<P>
   By Patrick E. Tyler
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 476 pages. Public Affairs. $27.50.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
