<P>
   &UR; FEATURE story &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MARTIN-GUERRE-MUSICAL (Minneapolis) _ ``Martin Guerre,'' the
British musical that has returned more often than, well, Martin
Guerre, finally had its American premiere here on Sept. 29. It was
the fourth opening for the show, counting its first one in London's
West End in 1996, and a climactic night for Alain Boublil and
Claude-Michel Schonberg, who first brought the idea to the producer
Cameron Mackintosh a full seven years ago. The tale is based on the
often-told true story of the 16th-century Frenchman who, left for
dead on the battlefield, returns home to find his identity _ his
standing in the village and his place in the marriage bed _ assumed
by his friend and fellow soldier. By Bruce Weber. &UR;  &LR; (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM AND VIDEO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TAIWAN-FILM-DIRECTOR (Undated) _ Could it be that one of today's
most important film artists _ the critic J. Hoberman calls him
``the world's greatest active narrative filmmaker'' _ is a
Taiwanese director virtually unknown here? American audiences,
accustomed to gauging a movie's importance by its advertising
budget and buzz, may understandably scoff at such a claim.
Regardless, the director in question, Hou Hsiao-hsien, is a star of
the international circuit. Six of his last seven pictures have been
shown at this year's New York Film Festival, which ends Sunday, yet
none were released in the United States theatrically. By Phillip
Lopate. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THEATER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LIFE-DREAM-THEATER (London) _ Imagine a play that suggests
Shakespeare _ ``Hamlet'' or ``The Tempest,'' particularly _
filtered through a Pirandellian prism, with an enormous gilt-edged
mirror suspended forbiddingly above the action and a gravel-strewn
set providing its own aural soundscape. That is one way of
describing the production of ``Life Is a Dream'' by the Royal
Lyceum Theater Company of Scotland that arrives in New York on
Tuesday at the Brooklyn Academy of Music. The Spanish director
Calixto Bieito's fevered staging of the defining 17th-century play
by Pedro Calderon de la Barca will have six performances at the
Harvey Theater as part of 1999 Next Wave Festival. By Matt Wolf.
(Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLASSICAL MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GIGLIO-OPERA-COMPANY (Lucca, Italy) _ Small opera companies like
the Teatro del Giglio here worry that their centuries-old trueness
to themselves marks them as provincials unable to cope with any art
but their own. American opera companies, long dependent on private
philanthropy and fund-raising prowess, look across the Atlantic,
envying countries like France and Germany, where federal money for
the arts has flowed almost endlessly. With financial faucets
closing, Europeans now wish they had developed the money-generating
skills that Americans have refined into an art. These matters are
particularly acute in a small Tuscan city like Lucca and a country
like Italy, where opera is not a plaything for the well heeled but
government business. By Bernard Holland. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   PITTMAN-JENNINGS-MUSIC (Undated) _ Piecing together the clues,
the astrologically challenged reporter gathers that Sagittarians
are orderly, methodical, not to be hustled. At 48, the
Oklahoma-born, Paris-based baritone David Pittman-Jennings
exemplifies the sign. Since choosing voice over the oboe as his
vehicle for artistic expression at the end of the Vietnam War, he
has gone on to master repertoire ranging from Bach to the most
mandarin of the moderns. On Saturday he celebrates what seems to be
a tardy New York debut in the title role of Luigi Dallapiccola's
``Il Prigioniero'' (``The Prisoner''), in concert with the Montreal
Symphony Orchestra under Charles Dutoit. By Matthew Gurewitsch.
(Moved).
</P>
<P>
   NY-PHILHARMONIC (New York) _ The New York Philharmonic's ``An
American Celebration,'' is the latest of its CD compilations of
archival recordings. By Allan Kozinn. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CORTAZAR-ART (Mexico City) _ The painter, Roberto Cortazar,
regards this city, where he was born 37 years ago, as ``a kind of
body.'' Cortazar's preoccupation with the human figure and his
meticulous rendering of it helped draw attention to his work soon
after he graduated from the National School of the Arts here in
1983. For his drawings, he won a prize that year named after the
important Mexican modern artist Jose Luis Cuevas. An exhibition of
Cortazar's new paintings opens on Thursday at Praxis International
Art on the Upper East Side of Manhattan. By Edward M. Gomez.
(Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   MASKS-ART (St. Louis) _ For 30,000 years, all sorts of people
have felt the need to create masks. From cavemen to astronauts,
they have worn them for protection, as a disguise or as a way of
transforming themselves spiritually. Masks reflect a range of human
expression: funny, sinister, ascetic, wild or haunting. ``Masks:
Faces of Culture,'' an exhibition at the St. Louis Art Museum that
is the first to survey ancient through modern masks. The show,
which opens this weekend and remains through Jan. 2. By Rita Reif.
(Moved).
</P>
<P>
   CHARDIN-ART (Paris) _ Twenty years after the last major
exhibition of his work in Paris, Chardin, the 18th-century French
still-life and genre painter, is the subject of yet another big
retrospective at the Grand Palais through Nov. 22. Why so soon for
someone who is not exactly a household name? Well, no one, it
seems, can resist round numbers: 1979 was the 200th anniversary of
Jean-Baptiste-Simeon Chardin's death; 1999 is the 300th anniversary
of his birth. By Alan Riding. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TELEVISION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TV-THAT-70S-SHOW (Studio City, Calif.) _ Think smiley faces,
perky rust-and-umber polyester sweater vests, Gerald Ford, John
Travolta, Carl Bernstein, Chevy Chase, Werner Erhard. When the
topic of the 1970s comes up, as it seems to so often these days,
thoughts may drift to those obvious icons of the Me Decade. That's
one reason that Mark Brazill, 37, a former stand-up comedian turned
sitcom writer, is an executive producer and co-creator of the hit
Fox series ``That 70's Show.'' By Andy Meisler. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   BESTSELLERS (Undated) (Moved.)
</P>
<P>
   PAPERBACKS (Undated) (Moved.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRAVEL (`t' category) &LR;
