<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8676 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MOBYDICK-OPERA-REVIEW     10-06 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOBYDICK-OPERA-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SONGS AND STORIES FROM MOBY-DICK': THE WATER, THE WHALE AND A BOLD
BASS GUITAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By BERNARD HOLLAND   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Water, the mother of metaphors, means music,
narrative writing or for that matter just about anything else you
can think of. The sea is legato, Wagner's endless melody. Waves are
the phrases within it, establishing meter and rhythm. Currents
determine tempo.
</P>
<P>
   Melville's ``Moby-Dick,'' subject of Laurie Anderson's latest
theatrical meditation, presented at the Brooklyn Academy of Music
on Tuesday, is both water and about water. From it our primeval
ancestors emerged, and we, their descendants, harbor urges to
return. Ahab's white whale calls to him and he responds.
</P>
<P>
   These are big, heavy themes, and ``Songs and Stories From
Moby-Dick'' thinks about them in one form or another. In an hour
and a half of music and dance _ elegantly lighted and illustrated,
fastidiously organized and presided over in a spirit of somber
whimsy _ Ms. Anderson and a small troupe of players and musicians
give us what amounts to a book of essays. We learn the habits of
whales and their problems in the modern world. We hear Melville's
words and words about him. The fishing industry is touched on;
Hollywood on ``Moby-Dick'' is explored. ``What does it all mean?''
we are asked.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Anderson's art plays a dangerous game. For her the
metaphysical stakes are high, and a fatal fall from those heights
is never that far away. Indeed, not much distance separates
profundity from pretension. Negotiating big ideas requires careful
footwork and considerable courage, and there is something else: for
want of a better word, call it humor.
</P>
<P>
   It is not the type of humor that makes one laugh or even smile.
Here, dead seriousness and wry commentary on dead seriousness are
made to coexist. Melville's world is touched up with rock 'n' roll
surreality. Great, bass-heavy amplification surrounds the audience
and sets the chair underneath you to vibrating. Ahab's stovepipe
hat, whimsically elongated, is a major theme. The dancing veers
from frenetic outburst to slow-motion silhouette to the bandstand
choreography of the 1950s and '60s.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Anderson, who sings, talks and performs on a variety of
electrified violins, ``talking sticks'' and keyboards, plays
technology for all it is worth. With the flip of a computer switch,
her voice dives to the depths of a Russian basso or accompanies
itself in two-part harmony. The music itself ranges from simple
balladry to rock to extensions of rock: namely, a ritual
repetitiveness hovering somewhere between the concert hall and
CBGBs.
</P>
<P>
   Rarely absent from the stage, and an extraordinarily subtle
performer on the bass guitar, is Skuli Sverrisson, whose shifting
rhythmic emphasis represents both change and stability. He is the
heartbeat of ``Songs and Stories From Moby-Dick.'' He and Ms.
Anderson are surrounded by four very effective singers and dancers:
Tom Nelis, Price Waldman, Anthony Turner and Miles Green.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Anderson's other saving strength is the utter
professionalism of her production. At one moment surf rolls
photographically from back-lighted screens; at the next texts crawl
across them; later individual letters tumble by. The metaphoric
connections sound obvious, but they have been perfectly worked out,
function flawlessly and always know when to quit. Michael
Chybowski's lighting is striking.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Anderson sings and plays with great style, but above all it
is her double personality that makes ``Songs and Stories'' a
worthwhile entertainment. We see only one of her, but there are
two. The first earnestly contemplates a world 150 years old and all
the mysteries of creation; the other is coolly up to date, with
just a touch of a smile on her face.
</P>
<P>
   There are more performances Thursday through Saturday and Oct.
12 through 16.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
