<HEADER>
A8677 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-AUDIO-BOWIE-COX     10-06 0279
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-BOWIE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Relaxed pace puts Bowie back on course
 &HT;    By Doug Hamilton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   He's rock's most celebrated poseur. From glam androgyne to
ambient alien to suntanned pop star, David Bowie has donned and
doffed enough identities over his three-decade-plus career to
outfit an army of Madonnas.
</P>
<P>
   But increasingly, the guises have seemed ill-fitting. ``Tin
Machine,'' Bowie's foray into torqued-up arena rock, drew
raspberries from critics and fans alike. And while the 1997
electronica-driven release ``Earthling'' had its moments, the
52-year-old singer at times had to strain to keep up with the
skittering drum-and-bass beats.
</P>
<P>
   It is nice to report, then, that, on his 20th solo album, Bowie
has struck his most comfortable pose in eons: He sounds like
himself. Much of ``hours...'' glides on the mid-'70s, epic-ballad
vibe of songs like ``Word on a Wing'' and ``Heroes,'' though with a
contemporary trip-hop gloss. The album's relaxed pace allows
Bowie's vocals to stretch to full languor as he wistfully croons
such reflective musings as ``All of my life I've tried so hard/
Doing my best with what I had/Nothing much happened all the same''
(from the melancholy opener ``Thursday's Child'').
</P>
<P>
   ``hours...'' isn't the fully formed artistic comeback Bowie
might have hoped to produce. It's pleasant without being
particularly arresting, intimate, but only intermittently moving.
Still, it's great to hear this rock chameleon once again finding
his true colors.
</P>
<P>
   ``hours...''
</P>
<P>
   David Bowie. Virgin. 10 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
