A8678 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-AUDIO-COLE-COX     10-06 0239
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-COLE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Amen': Cole goes over to dark side
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The darling of the 1998 Grammys is back with the follow-up to
``This Fire,'' the phenomenally successful CD that spawned the hits
``Where Have All the Cowboys Gone'' and ``I Don't Want to Wait''
(which became the theme to TV's teen soap ``Dawson's Creek''). If
you're expecting another video-friendly pop soundtrack, don't hold
your bubble gum breath. Cole has decided to eschew commercial pop
to be a ranting/rapping voice in the wilderness, more John the
Baptist than Elton John.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly every tune on the album is a downer, from lyrics about
drive-by shootings to therapy to Dr. Jack Kevorkian. There is
actually a verse about a girl ``that doesn't answer the phone and
eats like a tapeworm.'' On top of it all, nearly every tune is
layered over the same droning beat that sounds like a call to a
Viking funeral. Cole envisions herself as Venus Earth Mother but
has paid more attention here to her angry scribbles of poetry than
the coherency of the music.
</P>
<P>
   The only tune that might possibly be a single is the
out-of-place ``I Believe in Love,'' which is essentially a remake
of Taylor Dane's ``Love Will Lead You Back.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Amen''
</P>
<P>
   Paula Cole Band. Warner Bros.
</P>
<P>
   Nine tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
