NYT-10-06-99 1817EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991006.0246 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8679 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-AUDIO-MINIS07-COX     10-06 0568
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-MINIS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini reviews of the latest sounds
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   -- R&AMP;B
</P>
<P>
   ``Black Diamond''
</P>
<P>
   Angie Stone. Arista. 14 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Being best known as the mother of much-touted R&AMP;B savior
D'Angelo's babies must be a good and bad thing for Angie Stone. On
the good side, hey, if they could create a life together, it's easy
to think that the least the talents could do together is create a
hit record. But the bad thing is people who've only known her since
she sang back-up for D'Angelo aren't taking into account her early
rap career in Sequence and more memorable turn in R&AMP;B group
Vertical Hold (``Seems You're Much Too Busy''). Oh well, this solo
debut should serve as a more than adequate education on her
abilities. Though it is occasionally as rough as the title implies
_ sometimes offering style (``Bone 2 Pic'') over substantive lyrics
(``Black Diamonds &AMP; Blue Pearls'') _ hang with it, dig deeper and
discover an emotive ability rivaling Chaka Khan's.
</P>
<P>
   _Sonia Murray
</P>
<P>
   -- ROCK
</P>
<P>
   ``Cobra and Phases Group Play Voltage in the Milky Night''
</P>
<P>
   Stereolab. Elektra. 15 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   There's always been something otherworldly about Stereolab
that's difficult to put into words. Describing the repetitive,
cyclical keyboard and guitar riffs, the breathy vocals of French
chanteuse Laetitia Sadier and a plastic '60s-era futurism only
hints at the (space) oddity of it all. Mentioning that they
actually rock live just muddies the waters further. After a couple
of mellower, poppier efforts the London-based band makes a slight
return to its early experimental efforts without losing the pop
appeal. ``Fuses,'' with its busy bass line and off-kilter jazz
feel, co-exists alongside the mellower lounge-pop vibe of tunes
such as ``The Spiracles.'' Within the space of one song, these
audio explorers can traverse the musical map. The opening minutes
of ``Caleidoscopic Gaze'' recall the acid-dazed ``Smile''-era Brian
Wilson right down to the jaunty piano and Theremin sound alike, the
electric saw. Those opening minutes give way to a choppy wah-wah
guitar riff, Sadier's lovely accented vocals and a little blurting
synthesizer before circling back to the beginning. It's an
eight-minute everything-but-the-kitchen-sink opus, something that
only Sterolab manages to do well.
</P>
<P>
   _Shane Harrison
</P>
<P>
   -- POP
</P>
<P>
   ``Big City Rhythms''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Feinstein with the Maynard Ferguson Big Band. Concord.
16 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   This recording is surprisingly good. From the syncopated delight
of ``Close Your Eyes'' to the swoony ``Lullaby in Rhythm,'' Michael
Feinstein does something he hasn't done since his earliest Irving
Berlin and George Gershwin discs. He swings, and does so within the
limits of his voice. No more pinched-off high notes. Here they
float, and Feinstein's cords are more pliable, playful and rangy
than ever. Add to the mix the deep-down rumbling (``You Can't Lose
Them All'') and the blessed squealing (``Girl Talk'') of the
Maynard Ferguson Big Band, and you've got a party that will bring a
smile to your lips and a shiver to your spine. There's only one
stinkeroo in this whole 16-pack: Skip the inane lyrics of ``Swing
Is Back in Style,'' and like Feinstein, you'll be back on track.
</P>
<P>
   _Kathy Janich
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
