<HEADER>
A8680 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-VIDEO-TIN-COX     10-06 0279
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-TIN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    VIDEO OF THE WEEK
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Pushing Tin'' (R)
</P>
<P>
   Like ``Donnie Brasco,'' his last movie, director Mike Newell's
new comedy-drama takes us into a high-stress, high-testosterone
parallel universe where men make life-and-death decisions and their
women are accustomed to being treated like steam valves.
</P>
<P>
   While ``Brasco'' was a fact-based slice of mafia life, ``Pushing
Tin'' (also fact-based) introduces us to another kind of family:
the sweaty fraternity of air traffic controllers who keep 747s from
colliding every few seconds in the super-crowded sky above
Manhattan. (``Pushing tin'' is controller slang for routing
planes.)
</P>
<P>
   John Cusack plays Nick, the star cowboy in the tower whose sense
of competition kicks into high gear with the arrival of his polar
opposite, the brooding, Harley-riding Russell (Billy Bob Thornton),
whose luscious young wife (Angelina Jolie) makes Cusack lose
appreciation of his own fine spouse (Cate Blanchett, doing fine
work as a Long Island hausfrau).
</P>
<P>
   For its first third, ``Pushing Tin'' is a fascinating look at
this obsessive-compulsive world. But it turns into something much
more routine, a comedy of discomfort as Nick's and Russell's
competitive streaks start to have repercussions in their bedrooms.
The movie becomes a domestic melodrama that could be unfolding in
just about any high-stress situation; it sheds the specifics that
make the film so interesting. Think of it as a juiced-up ensemble
showcase that loses its bearings midflight.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
