<HEADER>
A8681 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-ALANGILBERT-COX     10-06 0441
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALANGILBERT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ASO Likes what it sees in Gilbert
 &HT;    By Judith Green
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _The Atlanta Symphony Orchestra clearly wants to get a
good look at Alan Gilbert from all sides.
</P>
<P>
   This week's ASO guest conductor, Gilbert conducted the orchestra
last season, to good reviews, and was asked back for two concerts
this season. This week's concert is orchestral; the second, Nov.
4-6, features a difficult choral/orchestral program of Stravinsky's
``Symphony of Psalms'' and the Mozart ``Requiem.'' Gilbert is the
first out-of-town conductor to lead the ASO Chorus since Robert
Shaw died in January.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he's playing with the Emory Chamber Music Society
on Sunday. This is, in effect, is another audition. At least one of
the musicians _ violinist Jun-Ching Lin _ is an old friend from the
Curtis Institute of Music; but three of them _ Lin, flutist
Christina Smith and violist Paul Murphy _ are on the search
committee for a new ASO music director.
</P>
<P>
   What everyone will see is a rising conductor with strong
credentials and an interesting personal side. Gilbert has a
Japanese mother and an American father, both violinists with the
New York Philharmonic. ``I practically grew up in the orchestra,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   He knows the ASO situation is not without past conflicts and
present stresses. ``You can find that out just by signing onto the
Internet,'' he says. ``But I'm under the impression there's a very
positive attitude here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel anything negative in my dealings with the
orchestra last time, and I was encouraged by the music we made,
which is the way it should be. If there's anything to be dealt with
outside the music, it should stay outside.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilbert's schedule for the week is ``crazy,'' he admits, with
ASO and chamber music rehearsals, as well as the non-public events,
such as meeting with the ASO board's search committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always get enthusiastic when I make up my schedule,'' he
says, ``and then I kick myself when I have to live it.''
</P>
<P>
   ALAN GILBERT
</P>
<P>
   -- Age: 32
</P>
<P>
   -- Roots: Parents Michael Gilbert and Yoko Takebe are New York
Philharmonic musicians.
</P>
<P>
   -- Education: Harvard University and Curtis Institute of Music
</P>
<P>
   -- Orchestra: Royal Stockholm Philharmonic
</P>
<P>
   -- Instruments: Violin and viola. He will play both at Emory. He
brought his viola but will borrow a violin. ``I couldn't carry
everything, so the violin lost out to the golf clubs. But things
are so busy this week that golf is probably going to lose out,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
