A8682 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-BEER-SKUBE07-COX     10-06 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEER-SKUBE07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN:Craft brews on a roll with Thunderhead
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When a small but ambitious brewery in Florida harbored
hopes earlier this year of coming to Atlanta, it knew better than
to call on one of the area's major distributors. They have bigger
fish to fry, and a brewery unknown outside its own neighborhood
won't get its foot inside the door.
</P>
<P>
   The Florida people instead called Peter Marte of Thunderhead
Distribution, a David in a crowd of Goliaths.
</P>
<P>
   Since Marte and Joel Gregory founded the company two years ago,
Thunderhead has become a magnet for craft brewers trying to crack a
highly competitive market controlled by eight or nine distributors,
few of whom want to spend the time or money marketing boutique
beers.
</P>
<P>
   The result: Beers widely available in other cities _ Trappist
ales from Belgium, barley wine-style beers from the West Coast,
high-potency German maibocks _ weren't available in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Most still aren't, thanks to the state's antiquated 6 percent
alcohol-by-volume cap on beer. But the landscape has changed
dramatically, all because a pair of inexperienced upstarts wanted
to add color and variety. From a warehouse in Norcross, Marte,
Gregory and Thunderhead's small sales force work 12- and 15-hour
days making cold calls, filling orders and trying to interest
restaurateurs and retailers in something out of the ordinary.
</P>
<P>
   Thunderhead's still a small player in the game, but it's made a
difference. You want La Trappe, the only Trappist ale brewed in
Holland? Belhaven Scottish Ale? Red Seal ale from California?
</P>
<P>
   You can find them at larger package stores and supermarkets
because Thunderhead brought them to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The Florida beer, as it turned out, was drinkable enough but no
more so than a dozen other craft beers. The best guess was that it
would sit on shelves unnoticed, like many others. ``That's when you
have to be brutally frank,'' Marte says. ``We had to tell them it
wasn't quite ready for this market.''
</P>
<P>
   But for other beers, such as the Flying Dog line from Aspen,
Colo., or the gold medal-winning Tuppers' Hop Pocket Ale and the
companion Hop Pocket Pils, Thunderhead has opened new markets and
given beer enthusiasts more choices.
</P>
<P>
   And it's not just imported beers or beers from other states.
Thunderhead is also distributing beer from area brewpubs, notably
Percy's Fish House and Max Lager's, for special order from retail
stores, to Vickery Creek restaurant in Cumming and to the Taco Mac
tap emporiums in Snellville, Sandy Springs and Cumming.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're crusaders, and they're going about it the right way,''
says J.K. Kenny, proprietor of Wild Wing Cafe in Marietta, one of
the area's more popular multitap bars. ``For the specialty beer
market, they've made some inroads. But they're also experiencing
some resistance because many bar owners don't understand the
variety of beer styles or how to make pairings of beer with food.
So they stick with the standbys _ Bud, Miller, Coors.''
</P>
<P>
   For Marte, a 36-year-old Rhode Island native, the biggest
challenge is interesting restaurateurs in something besides the
usual. ``They think Bud or Miller is all customers need,'' he says.
``We take the approach that if the only wine they sold was white
zinfandel, they'd never be known for a good wine list.''
</P>
<P>
   Marte credits Andy Klubock, proprietor of the Taco Macs in Sandy
Springs, Snellville and Cumming and a nationally known beer expert,
for pointing him in the direction of La Trappe, Tuppers' Hop
Pocket, McAuslan Oatmeal Stout from Quebec and other offerings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thing they've done,'' Klubock says, ``is bring in
styles that weren't here two years ago. It shows you that people
will buy great beer if it's available. Tuppers' does fabulous here,
the Schneider Weissen (a German hefeweizen beer) does well, the
Duckstein (a German alt beer). It confirms what I've been saying
for a long time _ Atlanta is a lot more sophisticated a beer market
than people realize.''
</P>
<P>
   PICK OF THE WEEK
</P>
<P>
   People addicted to making bad puns will call it a whale of a
beer, but the newest addition to the Thunderhead portfolio is
notable for other reasons. When people ask what beer is brewed in
Boston, they're apt to say Samuel Adams. But so is Harpoon, and the
Harpoon India Pale Ale is one of the better ones around.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, it's not quite hoppy or full-bodied enough to be
called an IPA. But there are many excellent pale ales that call
themselves IPAs for marketing reasons, and Harpoon falls into that
category. Copper in color, with a pleasing hop aroma and finish,
it's well-balanced in the manner of Sierra Nevada Pale Ale, but
with slightly more hop character.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel Adams has also come out with an India Pale Ale (look for
a report on it in this column next time). Harpoon is the much
smaller of the two Boston breweries, but its beers set the same
high standard of excellence in all styles. Besides the IPA,
Thunderhead will be distributing four Harpoon seasonals _ an
Octoberfest, a Winter Warmer, a Maibock in spring and an ESB in
summer.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
