<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRIEFCASE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A brief (case) encounter
 &HT;    By Marylin Johnson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ After Christina Couret of Marietta, Ga. wrote to the
``Where Can I Find It?'' column wondering where to locate the
perfect briefcase, we immediately got on her case.
</P>
<P>
   To get a handle on what's out there, we took Couret shopping.
Her dictates were clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want a lawyer-ly looking case,'' said Couret, 26, an
assistant editor with American City &AMP; County Magazine. ``Rather, I
want something with a strap that looks feminine and in which I can
put a variety of things, including my planner, floppy disks and
notebook. But I will still carry a handbag.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I want leather. I have a pleather (faux leather) case
but am thinking about upgrading. I realize a leather case or bag
will probably cost about $200. But as part of my job I attend trade
shows, and everyone has such a great bag. I've just been getting
by. Help!''
</P>
<P>
   While shopping with Couret, we found that there are a zillion
types of briefcases and totes, available in basic black or brown,
in leathers and faux leathers, nylons, microfiber and canvas. Boxy
cases, it seems, have lost their appeal, while large-size totes, in
which you can carry a computer, credit cards and cosmetics, are
gaining in popularity. Prices start at about $65 and can go to $300
for the leather cases.
</P>
<P>
   At Rich's in Lenox Square Mall, Couret went through the cases
and bags that had been culled by personal shopper Frann Beato. Our
intrepid shopper was almost fooled by a black Liz Claiborne tote
($64), thinking it was leather. She liked Calvin Klein's black
leather case with a strap ($200) but decided the flap closing was
not thief-proof. A Kenneth Cole leather case ($175), which she
could sling over her shoulder or carry by the handles, was deemed
``hip yet professional.''
</P>
<P>
   Then a 9 West microfiber briefcase ($89) caught her eye. It was
filled with slots for a cell phone, business cards, legal pads and
sunglasses as well as a comfy shoulder strap and outside pocket. It
was then she began to waver just a bit about wanting a leather
case.
</P>
<P>
   Looking over the offerings at Mori Luggage &AMP; Gifts, Couret
spotted a ``professional-looking'' oversize tote ($129) by U.S.
Luggage, as well as Travelon's business tote ($149.99), which even
had compartments for a water bottle, computer, umbrella and room
for an extra pair of shoes. ``Well designed,'' said Couret. Our
shopper also was stopped by Hobo International's three-sided zip
case in a sleek black microfiber ($130). It had the requisite
pockets and compartments and was super lightweight. Again, the
dilemma: microfiber vs. leather.
</P>
<P>
   Couret also reviewed two bags from Sam Flax. A classic Jack
Georges' tan leather case ($283.50) was ``in beautiful leather but
very heavy with nothing in it.'' And she thought a brown tote case
in lightweight microfiber ($70) was a ``good price'' and that it
would hold all the necessities.
</P>
<P>
   After mulling over the possibilities, Couret bought the black
leather case from Kenneth Cole for $175. ``I liked many of the bags
I saw,'' she said, ``but I really fell in love with this
all-leather case. And if you carry it everyday, you must love it.''
</P>
<P>
   A few words from the pros on briefcases:
</P>
<P>
   ``Women are looking for stylish yet practical briefcases but
will settle for practical over stylish. The size of the case and
how it looks, when worn or carried, is also a consideration. Some
love leather and won't buy anything else. Others, who are
vegetarians or animal rights activists, won't touch leather. They
simply want a good quality fabric case.''
</P>
<P>
   DAVID KELLER
</P>
<P>
   Senior manager, Sam Flax
</P>
<P>
   ``For years, manufacturers simply took a man's briefcase and
made it in a fabric for women. They thought this was feminine.
However, these cases were heavy and structured and did not have the
functions that women demanded: zippered pockets, compartments for
cell phones and computers. Some of today's cases, which are
lightweight, can even serve as overnight bags. Function is key.''
</P>
<P>
   JEFF ARON
</P>
<P>
   Buyer, Mori Luggage &AMP; Gifts
</P>
<P>
   ``Women, I find, are doing more oversize totes than briefcases,
especially to carry on casual Fridays. And manufacturers have
responded by making totes in soft expandable leathers or fabrics,
with briefcase features, including lots of pockets and
compartments. For many women, security is a concern, so they are
leaning toward more zippered pockets.''
</P>
<P>
   FRANN BEATO
</P>
<P>
   Personal shopper, Rich's
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
