<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYBERSPICE07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Munch on a Mallomar to celebrate October
 &HT;    By Betty Parham
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   October may be the best month of all. Beauty abounds. The air is
crisp and clean and the pressure of all that holiday cooking is not
yet upon us. We can enjoy the apples, pears, mushrooms, oysters,
squash, brussels sprouts, Concord grapes and pomegranates that are
all part of the abundance of this beautiful month.
</P>
<P>
   And then there are the Mallomars. Any fan of these
chocolate-and-marshmallow indulgences knows they are not available
in the warmer months. They don't do well in the heat so Nabisco
distributes them to supermarkets beginning in October.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some of the month's other culinary milestones that may
provide some kitchen inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   -- Oct. 1. The new Waldorf Astoria hotel on Park Avenue in New
York opened in 1931, after the original, which was built in 1893,
was demolished to make way for the Empire State Building. For
generations the name Waldorf Astoria reigned as the epitome of
elegant and opulent hotels. The original Waldorf Salad, which has
been re-created by chefs countless times, began there. (See
recipe.)
</P>
<P>
   -- Oct. 6. German American Day. Germany is the quintessential
land of meat and potatoes _ its diet designed for cold weather and
hard work. Meat loaf, braised beef and horseradish, sausages and
wursts, sauerkraut and potato pancakes are just some of Germany's
contributions to American cuisine. Why not try Beer-Basted Sausage
With Caramelized Onions and German Mustard for your own
Oktoberfest? See www.globalgourmet.com/destinations/germany/ for
this recipe, plus a great wrap-up of the country's culinary
contributions.
</P>
<P>
   -- Oct. 11. Columbus Day. Whether Christopher Columbus actually
discovered America is disputed, but that he made a major impact on
Western cuisine is not. By the time he had retired from his
explorations, he had introduced tomatoes, chocolate, pineapples,
potatoes, paprika, peanuts, green beans, chiles, yams and turkeys
to Europe. In return he brought to America sheep, goats, cattle and
pigs, olives and walnuts, wheat and rice, peaches, apricots and
oranges. Despite all this he was known for his simple tastes in
food. See an Edible Bio of Columbus at www.wnol.com/L3/biocolum.htm
</P>
<P>
   -- Oct. 12. ``One of the very nicest things about life is the
way we must regularly stop whatever it is we are doing and devote
our attention to eating.'' A wonderful sentiment put forth by none
other than the reigning operatic tenor, and world class gourmand,
Luciano Pavarotti, born this day in 1935 in Modena, Italy, a
medieval city in Northern Italy. Salute the singer, the sentiment
and Northern Italian cuisine by trying your hand at polenta, a
staple of Northern Italian cuisine. See
www.polenta.net/Recipe1.html for some great recipes and
www.cuisinenet.com/glossary/itlnorth.html for a brief review of
Northern Italian cooking.
</P>
<P>
   -- Oct. 16. Since the creation of the United Nations Food and
Agricultural Organization in 1981, this day has been declared World
Food Day. The motto of the organization _ ``Let there be bread'' _
illustrates the need for education and efforts to recognize
malnutrition and diseases caused by lack of food around the world.
</P>
<P>
   To appreciate the most basic of foods, why not bake some bread?
See members.aol.com/meadowscd/recipes/read00.htm
</P>
<P>
   for recipes, www.cyberspaceag.com
</P>
<P>
   /breadhistory.html for a short history of bread, and
members.aol.com/acalendar/October
</P>
<P>
   /WorldFood.html for more on World Food Day.
</P>
<P>
   -- Oct. 28. This is the birthday of Auguste Escoffier
(1846-1935), the celebrated culinary genius whose books, recipes
and philosophy of cooking have had a lasting impact on the art of
cooking and the culinary world. Called the Father of Modern
Cuisine, Escoffier began his career at 13 as a lowly helper in his
uncle's restaurant. Cooking schools still teach his methods, and
his many books are indispensable references for the serious chef.
Among his well-known creations are peach Melba and Melba toast,
which he named after operatic diva Nellie Melba, after she
requested a light snack. For the story of the creation of Melba
toast, see www.onlygourmet.com/ezine/9706
</P>
<P>
   /articlesnack.html. For a biographical sketch of Escoffier and a
look at a lovely portrait of the man known as the ``Emperor of
Chefs and the Chef of Emperors'' visit
www.wnol.com/L3/bioescof.htm. If you want to give a variation of
peach Melba a try, see SOAR's version at
soar.berkeley.edu/recipes/desserts/peach-melba1.rec
</P>
<P>
   -- Oct. 31. We all know it's Halloween _ lots of inspiration
there _ but it's also the birthday of Savannah native Juliette
Gordon Low, founder of the Girl Scouts. Why not try your hand at
the original recipe for Girl Scout cookies? See the 1922 version of
the shortbread cookies at
www.our-hometown.com/NY/Ontario/CliftonSprings/
</P>
<P>
   Scouts/cookies.html. Low initiated the home-baked cookie sale in
the 1920s as a way to fund activities. It wasn't until 1934 that
Girl Scouts sold commercially baked cookies.
</P>
<P>
   SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Chicken Waldorf Salad
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20-25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1pound skinless, boneless chicken breasts
</P>
<P>
   1large red-skinned apple, such as Macintosh or Red Delicious,
cored and cut in chunks
</P>
<P>
   2celery ribs, sliced
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup raisins
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup walnut pieces
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup reduced-fat mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup reduced-fat sour cream
</P>
<P>
   2teaspoons lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   Romaine lettuce leaves
</P>
<P>
   2ounces crumbled blue cheese (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Bring 2 inches of water to boil in a skillet. Add chicken
breasts, reduce heat to low and let simmer 8 to 10 minutes. Do not
let water boil or chicken will toughen. Cool and cut in 1-inch
chunks. In a large bowl, combine chicken, apple, celery, raisins
and walnuts.
</P>
<P>
   In a small bowl, stir together mayonnaise, sour cream, lemon
juice and salt. Pour over chicken mixture and toss well to coat.
</P>
<P>
   Serve chilled on Romaine lettuce leaves sprinkled with blue
cheese, if desired. Serve with crusty bread or rolls.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving (with blue cheese): 356 calories, 33 grams protein,
17 grams fat (percent calories from fat, 42), 19 grams
carbohydrates, 101 milligrams cholesterol, 612 milligrams sodium, 2
grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
