r d BC-FOOD-RECIPESWAP07-COX     10-06 0493
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-RECIPESWAP07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Creativity works with punch cake
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There may be as many versions of the Punch Bowl Cake as there
are of punch.
</P>
<P>
   We published this combination three years ago and offer it again
for Barbara Roberts' starting point when she needs dessert in a
hurry for a crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after Roberts requested the recipe, we learned that it is
largely a matter of opinion and taste starting with the basics: a
boxed cake mix, instant pudding, pie filling and whipped topping.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Punch Bowl
</P>
<P>
   Cake
</P>
<P>
   Makes 24 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 35 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: about 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1(8.25-ounce) golden butter cake mix, baked in layers according
to package directions
</P>
<P>
   1(3.4-ounce) package pistachio instant pudding, prepared
according to package directions, using 1/3 cup additional milk
</P>
<P>
   1(20-ounce) can crushed pineapple, drained
</P>
<P>
   1(21-ounce) can strawberry pie filling
</P>
<P>
   1(16-ounce) container nondairy whipped topping
</P>
<P>
   1cup chopped nuts
</P>
<P>
   Optional toppings (see note)
</P>
<P>
   In a large clear punch bowl, crumble half the cake. Spread with
half the pudding. Continue layering with half the crushed
pineapple, then half the strawberry pie filling, then half the
whipped topping. Sprinkle with half the nuts and repeat layers,
ending with nuts.
</P>
<P>
   Note: If desired, put all the nuts in the center of the cake and
sprinkle on as the final layer one or a combination of the
following: shaved coconut, colored sprinkles, colored sugar or
edible glitter.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 299 calories, 3 grams protein, 15 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 44), 41 grams carbohydrates, 21
milligrams cholesterol, 169 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Recipe request
</P>
<P>
   -- Frances Fowler of Cumming, Ga. has lost her recipe for a
quick bread with applesauce, oatmeal and raisins. She got it in the
1970s and used to make several loaves for gifts.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Every fall we have a huge amount of chestnuts from our two
big trees. I've heard of marrons glacees, the chestnuts made in a
sugar syrup or sugar glaze, but have never been able to find a
recipe for them. Can you help me or your readers? Any recipe making
them in sugar will be appreciated,'' writes Mrs. Richard Price of
Mountain City, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Many years ago I made Dilly Bread, a casserole bread with
dill seeds, cottage cheese and grated onion. I think the recipe
came from a Gold Medal Flour bag, and it makes a really great
bread.... Surely someone out there must have it and be willing to
share,'' says C.A. Johnston Folds of Decatur, Ga..
</P>
<P>
   Contacting the column
</P>
<P>
   Recipes or requests for this column should be sent to Recipe
Swap, Food Department, The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box
4689, Atlanta, GA 30302. Include a daytime telephone number.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: mlanghenry(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
