r e BC-VIDEO-DVD-COX     10-06 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-DVD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Increasingly popular DVDs divulge secrets, insights
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's gone from flirtation to a genuine love affair.
</P>
<P>
   Only a year ago, digital video discs (DVDs) were still
cautiously viewed as a techno novelty, something only for
hard-wired geeks or rabid movie fans. Studios took a wait-and-see
attitude before committing their titles to the format. Not anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood quickly saw the bottom line as the flexible,
crystal-clear technology took off, and consumers started purchasing
DVD players for their homes. Analysts predict DVDs will be in 4
million U.S. homes by the end of the year, and up to 50 million by
2007. The future of the format seems so strong, Blockbuster Inc. is
getting in on the act, introducing DVDs for rental in 3,800 of its
stores by year's end.
</P>
<P>
   But enough with statistics. Let's look at some recent releases
and see what makes them cool:
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Monty Python and the Holy Grail'' ($24.95). The bad news
is, there aren't any real goodies on this disc. You get English,
French or Spanish subtitles, bonus trailers and a wide-screen
format. It looks great. Unfortunately, there's no audio commentary
by any of the Monty Python members. But the clopping sound of
coconuts comes through crystal clear.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``A Nightmare on Elm Street'' ($24.98). Freddy Krueger
fanatics will be glad to know that all the ``Elm Street'' flicks
are on DVD. I say stick with the first and best. A very clean,
restored transfer of the film offers full-screen and wide-screen
versions. The feature-length audio commentary from writer-director
Wes Craven, actors Heather Langenkamp and John Saxon, and the
director of photography makes for an amusing contrast with the
onscreen mayhem. They explain some of the secrets behind the gory
effects (including the full-revolve set to shoot the
murder-on-the-ceiling scene), reminisce about Johnny Depp (this was
his film debut) and, rather pointedly, don't talk much about Robert
Englund, the fellow who got famous as Freddy. DVD-ROM users can
also access the screenplay, play a New Dream World trivia game, and
see updated cast, crew and trivia information.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Lost Horizon'' ($27.95). The digital transfer of Frank
Capra's recently restored 1937 epic is crisp and clean. The disc,
like the theatrical release, includes about seven minutes of
``missing'' scenes, which were trimmed during a World War II
re-release to tone down on the film's message of pacifism (kind of
ironic, since that's what the movie is really all about). Though
the original film for some of these scenes was never recovered, the
restoration inserts still photos while the dialogue continues on
the soundtrack. Startling at first, the device becomes less
jarring.
</P>
<P>
   Extras include an alternative ending, three deleted scenes,
photo documentary with narration by historian Kendall Miller,
restoration commentary by film critic Charles Champlin and UCLA
film restoration expert Robert Gitt. And how's this for a choice of
subtitle languages: English, Spanish, Portuguese, Chinese, Korean
and Thai.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Tommy'' ($24.95). Ken Russell's phantasmagoric version of
the Who's rock opera gets a clean restoration that retains the
movie's unique audio ``Quintaphonic'' mix. (If you want to know
what that entails, there's an essay about the audio restoration on
the disc that explains it.)
</P>
<P>
   The musical has French, English and Spanish subtitles, but there
aren't any real goodies, which is a big missed opportunity. In
other words, if you never understood what all the pinball symbolism
meant way back in 1974, nobody's around to explain to you now. It
would've been nice to have some audio commentary, explaining how
Elton John stayed afloat on his giant shoe-stilts, what church
allowed Russell to shoot his Marilyn Monroe worship sequence, and
why nobody bothered to find out if Oliver Reed and Jack Nicholson
could sing before they were cast.
</P>
<P>
   And am I the only one who'd like to know what, exactly, went
through Ann-Margret's mind the day she had to shoot the scene where
she wallows in a room full of baked beans?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
