<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8689 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-VIDEO-MINIS-COX     10-06 0390
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-MINIS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MINI VIEWS: Short reviews of the latest on video
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Lost &AMP; Found'' (PG-13) _ There's something about David Spade's
new movie that's way too much like last summer's over-the-top _ and
better _ comedy, ``There's Something About Mary.'' Like gross humor
that'll kick your gag reflex into gear. Still, Spade's flick has
its moments _ especially his knockout impersonation of Neil
Diamond. Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   ``The Thirteenth Floor'' (R) _ A ``what is reality?'' sci-fi
thriller that doesn't measure up to earlier and better films like
``The Matrix'' and ``Dark City.'' It's about a modern-day computer
whiz team that creates, then walks around in, a digitized version
of 1937 Los Angeles. What follows is murder, intrigue and too much
flat acting. Your ultimate warning: The movie's from some of the
creative team that earlier flubbed ``Godzilla.'' Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   ``This Is My Father'' (R) _ A burnt-out teacher (James Caan)
travels to Ireland to unravel the mystery of his father. What
unfolds is a small-scale tragedy, tinged with romance and regret.
In rural '30s Ireland, a headstrong young beauty (Moya Farrelly)
falls in love with a shy tenant farmer (Aidan Quinn) nearly twice
her age. But everything conspires against the lovers _ from curses
and small-town snobbery to the kind of timing that makes Romeo and
Juliet look lucky. The movie is somewhat muddled overall, but the
leads' mutual yearning is achingly clear. Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _Eleanor Ringel Gillespie, c. 1999 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   (backslash)``Young Frankenstein: Special Edition'' (PG) _ If you
want to see what made movies funny before hair-gel jokes,
electrocuted dogs and violated apple pies, don't miss the
re-release of Mel Brooks' black-and-white 1974 classic. As much
affectionate homage as parody of James Whale's ``Frankenstein''
flicks, it stars Gene Wilder as the mad inventor's ancestor,
Madeline Kahn as his frigid fiancee, Teri Garr as a Transylvanian
lass, Peter Boyle as the monster and, of course, Cloris Leachman as
Frau Bluecher (cue the horses). The new edition features deleted
scenes and bloopers. $14.98 VHS, $34.98 DVD. Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray, c. 1999 Cox News Service
</P>
