<HEADER>
A8691 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-SEX-DISEASE-COX     10-06 0388
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEX-DISEASE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Women with partners in multiple relationships likely to get
sexually transmitted diseases
 &HT;    By M.A.J. McKenna
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ At least 17 million women in the U.S. have a higher
than usual risk of acquiring a sexually transmitted disease because
they or their sexual partners are in multiple relationships,
according to a new study. And 3.5 million women don't know they're
running the risk, because they think they're in monogamous
relationships, but they're not.
</P>
<P>
   A study published today by the Alan Guttmacher Institute, a New
York nonprofit organization whose research focuses on reproductive
health, analyzed data from seven national surveys for two types of
risk: the number of sexual partners a person is exposed to, and
that person's willingness or disinclination to practice safe sex.
</P>
<P>
   The study, in the journal Family Planning Perspectives, found
that eight out of every 10 sexually active Americans have only one
sexual partner per year, a rate that hasn't changed much in a
decade. However, the remaining 20 percent - one-third of the
sexually active women and one-fourth of the sexually active men -
are running significant risks. Almost 17 million women bwteeen the
ages of 15 and 44 were found to be at risk; 5.4 million have more
than one partner in a year, and 6.3 million have partners who are
also sleeping with other people. Another 5 million both had
multiple partners and also knew that their partners were not
monogamous.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, though women who have more than one partner use
condoms more than average, those who knew that their partners were
not monogamous paradoxically used condoms less than average.
</P>
<P>
   The study comes as the Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention prepares today to mount a major national prevention
effort on syphilis, which has declined sharply in the U.S. in
recent years and is considered a marker for other sexually
transmitted diseases.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message is that it is not always possible to know all the
ways in which one is exposed to risk,'' said Lawrence Finer, a
senior research associate at Guttmacher. ``It argues for increased
communication about sex and increased use of protection as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-99 1819EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
