<SLUG> BC-SHOPPING-GUIDE07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Looking for a plastic egg beater or a plastic coin holder? We
know where you can find it
 &HT;    By Marylin Johnson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Having trouble finding a particular item? We'll try to help you
locate it. But due to the volume of mail, we cannot track down
every request. Readers whose queries are answered in the column
will receive a blue-and-cream canvas Buyer's Edge tote bag. Write
us at Buyer's Edge Find It, Atlanta Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box
4689, Atlanta, GA 30302; e-mail us at buyersedge(at)ajc.com (please
include your name, the city you live in and daytime phone number);
or call 404-582-7642.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I had a two-piece plastic egg-breaker (for breaking
soft-boiled eggs in half), which, after many years of use, finally
broke, and I have been unable to find another one anywhere. It's
amazing how much I need it now that I don't have it!
</P>
<P>
   _ Barbara Van Horn, Marietta, GA.
</P>
<P>
   A: The yolk's on you! The Pedrini shell cutter for boiled eggs
($4.99) is at Lechters stores. The plastic gizmo is simple to
operate. Pull out the blade and put the sheath on the egg top. Push
blade back, remove the top. Presto, a perfectly cut egg that's easy
to scoop out and eat.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where can I find a pliable plastic coin holder to put into my
pocket? You pinch the edges to open it.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bob Kolody, Lithonia, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   A: You will no longer have to pinch pennies. They will fit
snugly in your red plastic coin holder ($1.59) from Artlite Office
Supplies &AMP; Pens. These handy-dandy gizmos also come in green and
would make great holiday stocking stuffers.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have been looking for Stretch-tite, a food wrap. It's the
greatest. I was first introduced to it about 15 years ago while
visiting a friend in Connecticut. Although it has been available
locally, it seems to have disappeared from store shelves. The name
on the box is Polyvinyl Films, Sutton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   _ Marie R. Perrotta, Roswell, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   A: We were stretched thin on this request but managed to snag
the clear, plastic stretch wrap at Costco Wholesale. A two-pack _
two 500-square-foot rolls _ is about $8. Note: Costco is a
wholesale membership club. Cost to join is $40, which includes a
free spouse card. Or order Stretch-tite directly from the company:
1-800-343-6134. A single 500-square-foot roll is $6.95. Two or more
rolls are $6.50 each. In addition to covering foods in the fridge,
Stretch-tite can also be used for microwave cooking, as a freezer
wrap and as a cover for sterling silver to keep it from tarnishing.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have been trying to find a book that shows the ways to tie
a knot in a tie. I know of only one way but would like to learn
about others, including how to tie a bow tie.
</P>
<P>
   _ W.R. Shivers, Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   A: Soon you will be tied up in knots, all kinds of knots,
including the classic four-in-hand, the Windsor and half-Windsor,
as well as the bow tie. The Neckwear Association of America in New
York will send you a free pamphlet, The Tie Game, complete with
directions on how to tie these knots. Send a self-addressed,
business size, stamped envelope to: The Neckwear Association of
America, 151 Lexington Ave., New York, NY 10016.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
