u e BC-WASTELAND-TV-REVIEW-N     10-06 0658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WASTELAND-TV-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WASTELAND': ANTHROPOLOGY PROJECT: STUDY YOUR OWN FRIENDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Program notes at end of review. Time, channel are for New
York area. Check local listings.) 
(js) 
 By CARYN JAMES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Wasteland'' wants to be a dramatic version of ``Friends'' with
Zeitgeist pretensions. Those pretensions will cause trouble every
time. The series, about six college friends now in their 20s and
still huddled together in New York City, was created by Kevin
Williamson, who so entertainingly combined adolescent
soul-searching with soap opera gloss in ``Dawson's Creek.'' But in
``Wasteland'' the soul-searching seems artificial and the dialogue
borrowed from generations of bad daytime soaps.
</P>
<P>
   The central character in this group isn't Dawson but Dawnie, who
has the most serious case of arrested adolescence on this show full
of Peter Pans. She is played by Marisa Coughlan with a perpetual
frown, which is probably meant to signal deep thought, because
Dawnie is a graduate student in anthropology who proposes studying
her circle of friends. ``In generations past, the window into
adulthood began at 18 and now it's 30,'' she tells her adviser. Or
maybe she just looks like a sad sack because she's 26 and still a
virgin, a state that makes her confused and unhappy.
</P>
<P>
   She uses this to comic effect at the start of Thursday's first
episode, when she willfully scares off an unctuous man trying to
pick her up in a bar by announcing what a big deal sex would be for
her. With this wry opening and its glossy quick cuts of New York
City, ``Wasteland'' gets off to a slick but appealing start. The
appeal is replaced almost at once by a sense of how off-putting
these people are. The women are brittle. With one exception, the
men are wimps. All their behavior is unbelievable.
</P>
<P>
   Dawnie's virginity scares off her old college love, Ty, who is
back in town. As they are rolling around on her bed, he stops and
says: ``You've given me a chance here. I can be noble.'' Then he
leaves.
</P>
<P>
   Their friend Jesse owns a public relations company. She is meant
to be the hard-as-nails character who shows us her vulnerable side,
but she interferes in other people's lives so much it's a wonder
this obnoxious woman has any friends at all.
</P>
<P>
   Sam, a woman with a Southern belle accent, works as a clerk for
the assistant district attorney, Vince. So far Vince is peripheral,
written in after the NAACP's complaints about the lack of major
black characters this season. His role will become more important,
which doesn't guarantee it will become more credible than anyone
else's.
</P>
<P>
   Sam once dated Vandy, now a bartender and aspiring musician.
Toward the end of the first episode, the show has deteriorated so
much that she actually says: ``It wasn't working, Vandy. We stopped
being good together.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the actors, only Dan Montgomery is natural and likable, as
Russell, a closeted gay soap opera star and Dawnie's roommate. He
worries incessantly about how to have a private life while
preserving his heartthrob public image. Maybe Williamson, who
recently came out himself, simply had more emotion and sympathy to
pour into this character. But Montgomery also gets a lot of credit
for making us wonder why Russell seems the only human in the midst
of these Barbie and Ken figures.
</P>
<P>
   A later episode in which the friends go on dates confirms the
worst fears. Some shows grow on you; ``Wasteland'' grows more
off-putting as it goes along.
</P>
<P>
   PROGRAM NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `WASTELAND'
</P>
<P>
   ABC, Thursday night at 9
</P>
<P>
   Created by Kevin Williamson. Williamson, Bob Weinstein, Harvey
Weinstein and Billy Campbell, executive directors. A production of
Outerbanks Entertainment in association with Miramax Television.
</P>
<P>
   With: Sasha Alexander (Jesse), Marisa Coughlan (Dawnie), Rebecca
Gayheart (Sam), Eddie Mills (Vandy), Dan Montgomery (Russell), Brad
Rowe (Ty) and Jeffrey Sams (Vince).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
