<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8697 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-BUSH-2000-HNS &LR;      10-06 0700
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH CUSHIONS CRITICISM OF GOP'S RECORD ON SOCIAL ISSUES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Republican presidential candidate George W. Bush
tried to assuage the hurt feelings of some Republican congressional
leaders Wednesday by softening his criticism of the GOP's record on
social issues.
</P>
<P>
   Bush angered some in Congress on Tuesday by saying his party put
too much emphasis on economic growth at the expense of human need.
Last week he criticized a congressional Republican plan to slow
down the payment of earned income tax credits as an effort to
balance the budget ``on the backs of the poor.''
</P>
<P>
   But Wednesday the Texas governor said his remarks had been
intended to outline how the Republican Party often is
``mischaracterized'' as lacking compassion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was making the case that our philosophy is changing America,
but often times people only hear the stale numbers of economic news
we talk about, often times people only hear gloom-and-doom
scenario,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm talking from my heart, and I hope the Republican Party
appreciates it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush noted that it was a Republican Congress that relaxed
federal regulations on the states to allow for state-by-state
welfare reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a Republican Congress that freed states to make the
right decisions when it comes to welfare reforms,'' Bush said.
``The Republican Congress deserves great credit for that.''
</P>
<P>
   If nominated and elected president, Bush said he looks ``forward
to working in a constructive, reform-minded way with the Congress.
I hope, I hope there is a Republican speaker and a Republican
majority leader.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he does not believe it was any one thing or any one
election that gave the Republican Party its image of lacking
compassion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, '88 was a great election and '92 stunk,'' Bush said,
joking about the presidential elections that his father won and
lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not so much presidential elections as its an attitude
that's crept into people's minds, that somehow if you are a
conservative you don't care about people,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Bush again refused to be drawn too far into
the criticism of presidential rival Patrick Buchanan, who has been
criticized for statements he made about Hitler in a new book. As he
did last week, Bush said he hopes Buchanan stays in the Republican
Party rather than jumping to the Reform Party so GOP voters can
``reject'' Buchanan's philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look forward to whipping him,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Though declining a direct attack on Buchanan, Bush said: ``I
decry racism and I decry anti-Semitism''
</P>
<P>
   Bush campaigned in New York on Wednesday along with Gov. George
Pataki and New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani. They toured a
welfare-to-work training facility and a firefighters memorial
service and ate lunch in Little Italy in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   Bush referred to Giuliani as the ``future senator,'' a reference
to his expected race for the Senate against first lady Hillary
Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The trip completed a three-day swing through the Empire State
for Bush. He held a series of receptions and galas for people who
had contributed more than $2 million for his campaign. And Bush
came away optimistic that he can win New York in both the
Republican primary next March and in the general election.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a chance to win New York in 2000. I believe that
because this Republican Party is unified,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   No Republican presidential candidate has carried the state since
Ronald Reagan in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, a former owner of the Texas Rangers baseball team, joked
to one New York audience about the Rangers 8-0 loss Monday to the
Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've greeted me a little more warmly than the Yankees
greeted the Rangers,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   As a crowd of television cameras crushed in on Bush in Little
Italy, he shook hands and gave some of the older women friendly
kisses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because he gave me a kiss, I'd vote for him any day of the
week,'' said a frosted-haired Patricia Walls, who gave her age as
39. ``I'm not a political person, but I like this man.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
