<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8700 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-RANDOM-HEARTS-REVIEW-     10-06 0660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RANDOM-HEARTS-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWEET AND SOUR ROMANCE FEELS CONTRIVED 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use  Friday, Oct. 8  by NYTimes News Service clients)  
OUR RATING: 2 1/2 STARS 
By GLENN WHIPP 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Taking the tried-and-true movie concept of ``meet
cute'' and standing it on its ear, director Sydney Pollack has some
pretty interesting aspirations for his latest movie, ``Random
Hearts,'' but his good intentions are mostly lost in a
fundamentally ridiculous construct.
</P>
<P>
   The filmmakers assume that the audience will root for its
unlikely lovers, who meet courtesy of a double whammy _ a tragedy
and a betrayal. The movie's deliberate pace, along with some rather
strained attempts to build romance out of disaster, winds up
sabotaging its aims, however, reducing ``Random Hearts'' to a
rather high-minded adult misfire.
</P>
<P>
   Harrison Ford stars as Dutch Van Den Broeck, a taciturn
internal-affairs sergeant in the Washington, D.C., police force.
He's married, comfortable, respected. One night, waiting for his
wife to join him for dinner, Dutch hears of an airliner crash in
the Chesapeake Bay. He gives no thought to it until he checks his
messages and learns that his wife might have been on the plane.
</P>
<P>
   In short order, Dutch learns that not only was his wife on the
plane, she was traveling as the ``wife'' of another man. Both died
in the crash. Ever the investigator, Dutch tracks down the man's
widow, a well-bred congresswoman from New Hampshire, Kay Chandler
(Kristin Scott Thomas). Dutch wants to learn as much as he can
about why his wife strayed and, equally important, why he didn't
have a clue. ``I get paid to know who's lying,'' Dutch says. He's
tortured by his ignorance.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler is in the middle of a re-election campaign and wants
nothing to do with Dutch or his discoveries. She's afraid of how
the revelations might play on the evening news and is protective of
her teen-age daughter (Kate Mara, in a nicely finessed turn). It
doesn't take long for Dutch to wear her down, however, and they
soon begin a love affair that has Dutch asking pointedly, ``Are you
sorry the plane went down?''
</P>
<P>
   The screenplay, written by frequent Pollack collaborator Kurt
Luedtke (``Out of Africa,'' ``Absence of Malice'') and based on
Warren Adler's 1984 best seller, takes its sweet time arriving at
the emotional core of its story, wandering off needlessly into a
sorry subplot involving a crooked cop Dutch is investigating. But
when it stays on track, ``Random Hearts'' possesses a brutal
honesty about the gut-wrenching devastation felt by those betrayed
by their spouses. The film makes you feel their pain.
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, it's curious that Pollack chose to give the
movie a high-end, glossy romantic sheen, a look common to most of
his work, including his last effort with Ford, ``Sabrina.'' Ford,
in fact, has become Pollack's de facto stand-in for Robert Redford
(Pollack and Redford teamed for six movies, including ``Out of
Africa'' and ``The Way We Were''), playing his part with the same
remote impassivity that characterized Redford's work.
</P>
<P>
   Ford doesn't quite pull it off, although he makes clear the
inner demons that drive his character's painful (and ultimately
impossible) quest.
</P>
<P>
   That Dutch's personal mission should include a furtive romance
is what eventually makes ``Random Hearts'' feel like a fake. While
it's certainly possible to make lemonade out of lemons, this
sweet-and-sour romance tries to be all things and winds up being
not quite satisfying in the process. &UR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
The film: ``Random Hearts'' (R; brief violence, sexuality and
language). &QL; 
The stars: Harrison Ford, Kristin Scott Thomas, Charles S. Dutton,
Sydney Pollack. &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Directed by Sydney Pollack. Screenplay by Kurt
Luedtke, based on Darryl Ponicsan's adaption of Warren Adler's
novel. Released by Columbia Pictures. &QL; 
Running time: Two hours, 11 minutes. &QL; 
Our rating: 2 1/2 stars &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
