u e BC-VISITOR-MOVIE-REVIEW-     10-06 0528
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VISITOR-MOVIE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`VISITOR FROM THE LIVING': A MAN WHO SAW EVIL, AND PREFERRED NOT TO
FOCUS 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Production notes appear at the end of the review. This film
is being shown as part of the New York Film Festival.) 
(th) 
 By JANET MASLIN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``A Visitor from the Living,'' a 65-minute
documentary by Claude Lanzmann, is a transfixing addendum to this
filmmaker's ``Shoah.'' Filmed in 1979, it essentially consists of a
single conversation between Lanzmann and the elderly,
distinguished-looking Maurice Rossel.
</P>
<P>
   In 1944 Rossel was a Swiss member of an International Red Cross
inspection party that was sent to view the Theresienstadt
concentration camp in what is now the Czech Republic. Rossel was to
understand what he could about a sanitized, spruced-up detention
camp that was to real camps what Disney World is to real life.
</P>
<P>
   Rossel tells how he came to do this in patient, measured
fashion, with only the occasional interruption. (At one point, he
matter-of-factly shoos a small child out of the room, commenting,
``Sorry, can't have him coughing on camera.'')
</P>
<P>
   He speaks of brazenly visiting Auschwitz as a form of espionage,
of chatting with German officers there about bobsledding in the
Alps as he tried to perform a reconnaissance mission. Gradually,
Lanzmann leads him into a discussion of Theresienstadt, which
appeared to be a much higher order of concentration camp. It had a
bandstand, an orchestra and park benches. It passed Rossel's
inspection with flying colors.
</P>
<P>
   This documentary gains intensity as Rossel begins to repeat his
idea that the Jews at Theresienstadt were privileged characters,
wealthy enough to be given VIP treatment by the Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   And it gradually becomes clear that Rossel found these Jews
appalling, complaining of ``that passivity, that sterility that I
couldn't stomach.'' Lanzmann points out that if the residents
behaved unnaturally while their camp was being inspected that was
perhaps understandable. After all, the camp boasted attractive,
fake children's facilities even though abortion was mandatory for
its Jewish inmates.
</P>
<P>
   Although he eventually presents Rossel as someone who sanctioned
a terrible lie, Lanzmann is not one to play ``Gotcha!'' with such
sobering subject matter. He expresses a consideration for Rossel's
feelings in the film's opening credits, and he does not violate
that on camera.
</P>
<P>
   But he quietly dissects the consequences of a ghastly deception,
one in which 5,000 inmates turn out to have been killed just before
the visit so the place would not look too crowded. This strong,
troubling film does not overemphasize such details. It doesn't have
to.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Visitor from the Living'' is being shown Thursday night as
part of the 37th New York Film Festival.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `A Visitor From the Living'
</P>
<P>
   Produced and directed by Claude Lanzmann (in French, with
English subtitles); directors of photography, Dominique Chapuis and
William Lubtchansky; edited by Sabine Mamou; released by New Yorker
Films. Running time: 65 minutes. This film is not rated.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Maurice Rossel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-99 1823EDT &QL; 
