<HEADER>
A8704 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-POPULATION-$ADV10-COX     10-06 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPULATION-$ADV10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SIX BILLION HUMANS TUESDAY; CAN THE WORLD HANDLE BILLIONS MORE?
 &HT;    With POPULATION-DATE and POPULATION-DATA for release Sunday,
Oct. 10.
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Earth officially becomes a planet inhabited by
6 billion human beings Tuesday, an event that would have gone
unnoticed but for a blizzard of press conferences and news releases
trumpeting the fact.
</P>
<P>
   Why isn't such a milestone more obvious? The main reason is that
the 6 billionth person, whether he or she is born in China or
Topeka or Togatabu, will arrive in the midst of unprecedented
global prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly available clean drinking water, better sanitation,
more abundant crops, and life-saving antibiotics and vaccines have
put the world in a position to feed, clothe and care for 6 billion
people with little noticeable stress. Life expectancy is higher and
infant mortality lower than ever in history.
</P>
<P>
   However, by the end of this week, we will have been joined by a
million more people, and in 14 years another billion.
</P>
<P>
   If the planet is to comfortably accommodate a projected
population of 7 billion by 2013, several key trends will have to be
adjusted, according to some experts.
</P>
<P>
   One trend suggests that the steady increase in irrigated
cropland over the past 30 years is about to come to an end.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our irrigation base is showing numerous signs of
vulnerability, just as we are about to become even more dependent
on it,'' says Sandra Postel, director of the Global Water Policy
Project of Amherst, Mass. Problems such as land salting, silt and
the simple fact that only so much water is available water are
``rearing their ugly heads,'' she says in the book, ``Pillar of
Sand.''
</P>
<P>
   By 2025, the world must find additional irrigation water
equivalent to the annual flow of 110 Colorado Rivers, she
estimates, to maintain current per capita food output.
</P>
<P>
   There are several other worrisome indications: that the
expansion of available cropland is reaching its limits, that grain
harvests are starting to decline, and that some of the world's most
productive fisheries are being harvested at the maximum sustainable
level.
</P>
<P>
   Add to the list the unpredictable effects of climate change and
the inability of countries with rapidly rising populations to cope
with such problems as disease and famine _ an effect often called
``demographic fatigue.''
</P>
<P>
   For these reasons, says Lester Brown, president of the natural
resources research center Worldwatch Institute, the world is
unlikely ever to reach a population of 10 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even as world population continues to climb, it is becoming
clear that the several billion additional people projected for the
next half century are not likely to materialize,'' Brown and
Worldwatch researcher Brian Halweil wrote recently in the
institute's magazine World-Watch.(cq)
</P>
<P>
   ``What is not clear is how the growth will be curtailed.
Unfortunately, in some countries, a slowing of growth is taking
place only partly because of success in bringing birth rates down,
and increasingly because of conditions that are raising death
rates.''
</P>
<P>
   The most dramatic example is the AIDS epidemic in sub-Saharan
Africa. While developed countries such as the United States are
able to keep the incidence of HIV, the virus that causes AIDS, at
around 1 percent of adults, the infection rate in Zimbabwe is
around 26 percent of the adult population. In Botswana, it is 25
percent.
</P>
<P>
   In such countries, life expectancy is not rising but falling
rapidly, down to age 44 in Zimbabwe and 47 in Botswana.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rapid population growth in many of these countries during
the last several decades has had a terrible impact on national
budgets,'' said Halweil. ``There has been an inability to put in
hospitals and generally develop, while trying to educate growing
numbers of children, create jobs and deal with deforestation and
soil erosion and that sort of thing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The arithmetic of emerging resource shortages is not
difficult,'' he and Brown write in the World-Watch article. ``The
mystery is not in the numbers, but in our failure to do what is
needed to prevent such threats from spiraling out of control.''
</P>
<P>
   Other experts are more confident that the same human ingenuity
that improved crop yields and discovered antibiotics and vaccines
will have the world ready for 7 billion people, and more, when the
time comes.
</P>
<P>
   ``All you can see is growing wealth around the world, increased
caloric intake, increased life expectancy, increased per-capita
wealth,'' said Jerry Taylor, director of natural resource studies
for the Cato Institute, a Washington research center that opposes
most government intervention.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are increasingly conquering death around the world,'' he
added. ``A century ago, human life expectancy was about 30 years.
Now it's 60 or 70 years. People are not starving to death. They are
getting better food and they are living longer.''
</P>
<P>
   Because they are living better, Taylor said, people are having
fewer children.
</P>
<P>
   And even though population continues to grow, the world can
accommodate a lot more people, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor worked with the late Julian Simon, a Cato researcher and
University of Maryland professor, in compiling Simon's writings in
a new book, ``Hoodwinking the Nation.''
</P>
<P>
   In the book, Simon argues that ``the current gloom and doom
about an environmental crisis is all wrong on the scientific
facts.''
</P>
<P>
   It has always been wrong, he says, and it is wrong now. But
journalists, ignorant of statistics and science, gather data in
ways that lead to inaccurate conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians misuse statistics in the service of their own policy
goals, he said. Eventually, ``psychological and cultural
mechanisms'' make people more receptive to bad than to good news.
</P>
<P>
   The good news, Taylor says, is that only about one-third of the
earth's land mass is developed and with additional wealth, there is
plenty of room left.
</P>
<P>
   ``The globe is becoming wealthier and it can take a lot more
people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
