<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPULATION-DATE-$ADV10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HOW OCT. 12 BECAME THE DAY OF SIX BILLION
 &HT;    150&AMP;add. With POPULATION. For release Sunday, Oct. 10.
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Day of Six Billion will be observed around the
world on Tuesday, Oct. 12.
</P>
<P>
   Why that day? The United Nations Population Fund puts it this
way: ``On 12 October 1999, six billion people will be alive in the
world, an addition of a billion in only 12 years.''
</P>
<P>
   But in a different agency, the U.N. Population Division, the
demographers whose calculations were used to choose Oct. 12 give a
more guarded answer: The milestone will be reached ``around that
date.''
</P>
<P>
   How close? Six billion was reached back in June, according to
their high-growth projections. It won't be reached until next
February, according to their low-growth projections. They used
their middle projections to choose Oct. 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``People like to have one number and one date,'' said U.N.
demographer Thomas Buettner. ``We know, of course, that the date is
an approximation, a symbol, used rightfully to create awareness
around the world.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows)
</P>
<P>
   The 1995 world population figures are the most recent numbers
solid enough to be described as ``estimates'' rather than
``projections.'' Every two years, U.N. demographers polish the 1995
numbers and revise their projections for each year after that.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, they added together their middle projections of the
1995 estimates for 228 countries and said the 6 billion mark would
be reached this year on June 16.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, they pushed the date back to Oct. 12.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Fresh census data lowered the 1995 estimates for some
countries. Use of lower birth rates and higher AIDS death rates
slowed down the projections for the years after 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Their middle projection then showed that on June 30, 1999, the
world would be about 22 million short of the six-billion mark.
</P>
<P>
   But if the population continued to grow by roughly 214,000 a
day, it would reach six billion 104 days later, on Oct. 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``Technically, at about 2 p.m., if you want to be totally
over-precise,'' Buettner joked.
</P>
<P>
   In which time zone? ``In any time zone,'' Buettner said. ``The
date is based on simplifications that assume that the time is the
same for every person everywhere in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-99 1825EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991006.0270 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8706 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-POPULATION-DATA-$ADV1     10-06 0419
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPULATION-DATA-$ADV10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With POPULATION. For release Sunday, Oct. 10.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRRIGATION NEARING ITS LIMIT?
</P>
<P>
   The area of world cropland under irrigation has increased every
single year since 1961. Yet on a per-capita basis, it has remained
almost constant because of population growth.
</P>
<P>
   Year,,Total Irrigated Cropland (millions of acres),,Irrigated
Acres per 1,000 People
</P>
<P>
   1961,,348,,112.5
</P>
<P>
   1970,,417.5,,113
</P>
<P>
   1975,,472.5,,115
</P>
<P>
   1980,,522.5,,117.5
</P>
<P>
   1985,,560,,115.5
</P>
<P>
   1990,,602.5,,114.5
</P>
<P>
   1995,,647.5,,114
</P>
<P>
   Required for 7 billion people, at present rates
</P>
<P>
   2013,,798,,114
</P>
<P>
   Source: Worldwatch Institute in ``Vital Signs, 1999'' (data
converted from metric measures)
</P>
<P>
   WORLD GRAIN HARVESTS
</P>
<P>
   With the ``Green Revolution,'' world grain production has grown
rapidly since the mid-1950s, but so did population. Since peaking
at about 745 pounds per person in 1985, per capita production has
declined slightly.
</P>
<P>
   Year,,Total (millions of tons),,Per capita (pounds)
</P>
