<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8709 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-GINSBERG-AUCTION-ART-     10-06 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GINSBERG-AUCTION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GINSBERG: THE MAN, THE POET, THE AUCTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By KATHRYN SHATTUCK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Don't make a museum out of me,'' the poet Allen
Ginsberg admonished his staff in his final days. ``When you die,
you die.''
</P>
<P>
   Not quite. Two years after his death, Ginsberg's estate is
carrying out his wishes and auctioning off his belongings, Thursday
at Sotheby's in Manhattan. While his literary archives remain
intact at Stanford University, souvenirs of literary and social
currents that have swept the nation since the 1950s are up for
grabs.
</P>
<P>
   The auction also includes unpublished writings and personal
items from the estates of Ginsberg's fellow Beats Jack Kerouac,
William S. Burroughs and Neal Cassady and from friends like Lucien
Carr, Gregory Corso, Keith Haring and Lawrence Ferlinghetti. They
are expected to bring around $500,000, with Ginsberg's share going
to his companion, Peter Orlovsky, and the five children of
Ginsberg's brother, Eugene Brooks.
</P>
<P>
   While some items may end up under lock and key in institutions,
most are likely to be snatched up for safekeeping by the disparate
souls who found common ground in their admiration for Ginsberg.
</P>
<P>
   At a Beat poetry reading at Sotheby's on Sunday night, a
cross-section of Ginsberg's followers gathered to sip a liqueur
reminiscent of illegal absinthe and imbibe the words. Afterward
they sifted through his legacy, homing in on objects that might
best summarize his influence. Across the room from where the
historian Ann Douglas held court, Goldie Hawn, the actress,
scurried from case to case with her daughter, Kate Hudson, and Kurt
Russell, the actor, in tow. In a quiet corner, the poet Edward
Sanders tapped out an elegy to his departed friends on Kerouac's
conga drum.
</P>
<P>
   ``No other poet in our time has been memorialized to the extent
of Ginsberg,'' said the writer John Tytell, whose recent book,
``Paradise Outlaws,'' chronicles the Beat generation with his
essays and photographs by his wife, Mellon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ginsberg is the present-day incarnation of Walt Whitman,'' he
said. ``It will never die down because it is connected to the
antimaterialist tradition in American letters. Ginsberg carries
that on.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many of the objects that pass through Sotheby's doors,
Ginsberg's belongings are a tattered lot, well worn from their
owner's handling. But as the embodiment of a man who inspired
America to howl at the middle class, they could be considered
priceless.
</P>
<P>
   ``The harmonium is the one item that's truly an extension of
Allen,'' said Bob Rosenthal, Ginsberg's secretary and the estate's
trustee. ``People sigh and say, `Oh, not the harmonium,' when they
hear it's up for sale. He played it at all of his poetry readings
since the 1960s. People say the harmonium changed their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Also weighted with historical import is Richard Avedon's
photograph of a naked Orlovsky and Ginsberg, which helped galvanize
the gay pride movement when it was plastered around New York and
San Francisco in the early '60s.
</P>
<P>
   The auction may begin to define the dollar value of Kerouac's
drawings and paintings, the first to be sold publicly. Other
belongings offer insights into the workings of a mind, like the 19
unpublished letters by Cassady, the muse behind the Beat generation
and a central character in Kerouac's ``On the Road.''
</P>
<P>
   Still others are valuable primarily for the sentiment attached
to them: the private photographs of the Beats in far-flung locales;
two organs on which Ginsberg composed musical accompaniments to
William Blake's ``Songs of Innocence and Experience''; the poem
written by Ferlinghetti upon learning of Ginsberg's terminal
cancer; the desk of Ginsberg's father, a high school English
teacher and poet, which his son later took as his own.
</P>
<P>
   Even after their deaths, the words of the Beats reverberate.
Ginsberg's masterpiece ``Howl'' is among the most widely read and
translated poems of the 20th century. ``On the Road'' sells more
than 90,000 copies a year worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Next year, ``Deliberate Prose,'' a collection of Ginsberg's
essays from the last three decades, and ``Last Words: The Final
Journals of William S. Burroughs'' are expected to land in
bookstores. In a posthumous nod to the grandfather of the movement,
Grove Press will publish ``The Complete Naked Lunch,'' a revised
edition of Burroughs' landmark work featuring about 15 percent more
of the original manuscript, once thought to be lost. Edited by
James Grauerholz, Burroughs' companion and manager, and the
biographer Barry Miles, the work is scheduled for release in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his complaints about cults of personality, Ginsberg
would be delighted at the attention, Tytell said. ``Ginsberg is
like Warhol, Marilyn Monroe and Joe DiMaggio,'' he said. ``Ginsberg
was always eager to be known, even now, even afterwards.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
