<HEADER>
A8711 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-MCCAIN-2000-HNS &LR;      10-06 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFORM 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
McCAIN URGES GOP CANDIDATES TO JOIN FIGHT FOR CAMPAIGN FINANCEBy GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. John McCain called on Texas Gov. George W.
Bush and other Republican presidential candidates Wednesday to join
in the fight for campaign finance reform as the Senate prepares to
take up his proposal next week banning so-called ``soft money''
contributions to political parties.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who has made his proposal the centerpiece of his
presidential bid, made the appeal in a letter to Bush and the six
other candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging that he needs ``all the help we can get,'' the
Arizona Republican said at a speech before the Committee for
Economic Development that it was time for other GOP candidates who
have embraced the call for ending the influence of soft money in
national campaigns to back up their words with action.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm calling on them to put into action, fundamentally, what
they've stated,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain singled out Bush as the candidate most capable of
ensuring passage of an overhaul of finance laws because of the
support Bush's candidacy has on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   In his letter to Bush, McCain wrote: ``If even half of the
members of Congress who endorsed your candidacy were to honor your
request, (the ban on soft money donations) would pass with votes to
spare.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush campaign officials said they were flattered that McCain
recognizes Bush's ability to influence others on important issues.
But they were noncommittal in their response.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has gone on record against soft money contributions to the
parties. But his objections to soft money centers on corporate,
union and other special interest donations, not on contributions
from individuals. The McCain legislation would ban unlimited
contributions to the parties from individuals, as well as those
from unions, corporations and other special interests.
</P>
<P>
   The bipartisan measure, sponsored by McCain and Sen. Russell
Feingold, D-Wis., was killed in the Senate last year. But passage
of a similar measure in the House last year and again just a few
weeks ago by an overwhelming majority has revived the issue in the
Senate. McCain's focus on it as he travels around the country
campaigning has also given it a higher profile with the American
people, who, according to recent polls, are in favor of overhauling
the laws that now govern how money is raised and spent by political
parties.
</P>
<P>
   The McCain-Feingold bill still faces tough odds in the Senate;
however, where Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., and Senate Majority
Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., say they have enough votes to continue
to filibuster the measure.
</P>
<P>
   McCain and Feingold plan to offer a stripped-down version of the
bill that was filibustered last year. Since then, they have dropped
several controversial provisions, including one that would have
imposed strict limitations on so-called negative ``issue ads.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain said issue ads, normally used by anonymous groups to
mount an attack on a candidate in the closing days of a campaign,
are a major concern. But he said the soft money contributions,
which allow special interests and the wealthy to circumvent the
federal limits on donations to individual candidates, is more
important.
</P>
<P>
   By dropping the issue ad provisions, he and Feingold hope to
attract more support.
</P>
<P>
   In his appeal to Bush, McCain wrote that Republicans have an
obligation to reform ``a campaign financing system that is
perceived by the public as selling political speech to the highest
bidder.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the party of conservative reform,'' McCain wrote. ``The
obligation falls on us to urge the removal of the greatest
impediment to other reforms that we both support and are important
to our country's progress.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain said that without removing the financial influence of
special interests over politicians, it will be nearly impossible to
make significant changes in tax laws, education, the judicial
system, defense and numerous other government programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know you support these reforms,'' McCain wrote to Bush and
the other candidates. ``I believe that campaign finance reform is
the first reform and the gateway through which each of them must
pass.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
