<SLUG> BC-COURT-HAWAII-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT EXAMINES HAWAIIAN NATIVES' SPECIAL RIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a case mixing history, race and the
Constitution, the Supreme Court grappled Wednesday with a Hawaii
law that bars whites and other groups from voting for trustees who
oversee a fund that benefits Hawaiians whose ancestors date back to
the 18th century.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a case about ballot box discrimination, clear and
simple,'' said Theodore Olson, an attorney for Harold Rice, a white
rancher from Honolulu who challenged the law.
</P>
<P>
   At issue are elections held by the quasi-state Office of
Hawaiian Affairs (OHA), established in 1978 to run a $300 million
trust that distributes money to the islands' estimated 200,000
residents of original Hawaiian descent. The office oversees various
economic, social, health and education programs.
</P>
<P>
   The state's law says only residents whose ancestors were living
in Hawaii before 1778 _ when the English explorer and navigator,
Capt. James Cook, became the first westerner to visit there _ can
serve on the board of nine trustees or vote in OHA elections.
</P>
<P>
   About 20 percent of the state's population have some original
Hawaiian blood, according to the OHA.
</P>
<P>
   Rice, a fifth-generation Hawaiian, sued, claiming that the
elections violated the 14th Amendment's guarantee that all citizens
must have ``equal protection of the laws'' and the 15th Amendment's
rule that the right to vote cannot be denied on account of race or
color. But his lawsuit was rejected in 1997 by a federal district
court and a year later by the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   More than a dozen political interest groups and constituencies
are closely watching the case. The Clinton administration, which
formally apologized in 1993 for the annexation of Hawaii in 1898,
and several states have argued for Hawaii's law. But some civil
rights and pro-Indian groups as well as conservatives such as
former appellate judge and unsuccessful Supreme Court nominee
Robert Bork have publicly called for the eradication of OHA's
voting restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   While no other state program resembles the Hawaii trust, the
case raises broader questions about making race a condition of
eligibility for public benefits. The justices could structure a
narrow decision specific to Hawaii, but they also could produce a
ruling that would call into question the legality of federal and
other state programs benefiting American Indians.
</P>
<P>
   ``The right to vote is the bedrock of a democratic society,''
Olson told the court during Wednesday's arguments.
</P>
<P>
   But John Roberts, a Washington, D.C., attorney representing
Hawaii, argued that the state enjoyed a special trust relationship
with the federal government that justifies the voting requirements.
</P>
<P>
   He added that the voting restriction is not based on race but on
whether a voter is a beneficiary of the trust.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Rice was not denied the right to vote because he's
white,'' Roberts told the court. ``He was denied because he does
not receive any of the trust's money or other benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   Several justices questioned Robert's assertion that the Hawaii
law had nothing to do with race.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Oklahoma set up a program for children of descendants of
ranchers who lived in the state before 1900 that sent them to
special schools, we'd all know that it was meant for white kids and
wouldn't be allowed,'' Justice Anthony M. Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Antonin Scalia said: ``Saying this is anything other
than a racial classification is simply word games.''
</P>
<P>
   Representing the administration, Justice Department lawyer Edwin
Kneedler said the law was allowed under Constitution because
Congress and the state of Hawaii treat native Hawaiians the same as
American Indians, who are permitted to control assets given to them
by the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``You must allow the government to treat Hawaiians as just
another tribe,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The court is expected to rule on the case by late June.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
