<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOTTERY-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER A LOTTO COMPLAINTS, TEXAS COMMISSION DROPS PLAN TO CHANGE
GAME 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Unwilling to gamble with an unpopular proposal,
the Texas Lottery Commission announced Wednesday that it was
scrubbing a plan that would have increased Lotto jackpots but made
winning the on-line game more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``A single message we have heard loud and clear ... is, `Don't
mess with Lotto Texas.' I want to assure the public and all of our
players that message has not been ignored,'' said Linda Cloud, the
commission's executive director.
</P>
<P>
   She said the proposed changes, which were designed to boost
lagging ticket sales, were being pulled down. She said commission
officials would try to find a more acceptable alternative.
</P>
<P>
   Cloud also said that the commission may have to lower the
minimum Lotto jackpot from $4 million to $3 million because the $4
million payout wasn't generating enough ticket sales to pay for
itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing about the Lotto game is that it is
jackpot-driven, and if you can't build the jackpot, that's what
deters your players. They want to play for the bigger jackpot,''
Cloud said.
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, lottery officials recently unveiled a plan
that would have increased Lotto jackpots by increasing the number
of balls in the twice-weekly drawings from 50 to 54.
</P>
<P>
   That would have increased the odds of winning the jackpot from
the current 1 in 15.8 million to 1 in 25.8 million because players
would have had to correctly choose six numbers from 1 to 54 rather
than six numbers from 1 to 50.
</P>
<P>
   The lottery commission believed the proposal not only would have
sparked more interest in the game but also would have generated an
additional $20 million a year in revenue for the state, which gets
32 percent of lottery sales.
</P>
<P>
   But the commission was swamped with protests from players, who
objected to making the game more difficult to win.
</P>
<P>
   Cloud said the commission received more than 1,000 letters,
e-mails and verbal responses from the public, most of which opposed
the changes. Only four people testified at a public hearing on the
plan last week in Austin, but all four spoke against it.
</P>
<P>
   Cloud said she believed there was ``widespread confusion and
misunderstanding'' about the proposal but was yielding to public
sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   She said the commission was canceling public hearings that had
been scheduled for later this month in Houston and other cities.
Instead, the commission will arrange future ``town-hall meetings''
for a ``meaningful, one-on-one dialogue with players.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This will help us learn first-hand what our players want or
don't want, and how together we can continue to make the Texas
Lottery the No. 1 lottery in the country,'' Cloud said.
</P>
<P>
   The lottery director said the minimum $4 million Lotto jackpot
needed to generate $6.7 million in ticket sales to pay for itself.
Recent sales for that size jackpot have been running at about $4
million, which requires the commission to dip into its prize
reserves, which it cannot afford to do indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   Lowering the minimum jackpot ``may be something we have no
choice about,'' Cloud said.
</P>
<P>
   Total lottery sales, including the on-line and scratch-off
games, slumped to $2.57 billion during the fiscal year that ended
Aug. 31, a drop of 16 percent. Officials put much of the blame on a
1995 law that forced a reduction in game prizes.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature repealed that law last spring, and lottery
officials responded with several new scratch-off games with better
winning odds.
</P>
<P>
   The state comptroller's office has forecast an increase in
lottery sales to $3.35 billion this fiscal year. Cloud said she
believed that estimate was based on the level of lottery sales
before the Legislature reduced the prize payout four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
