r f BC-BIZMAGS07-COX     10-06 0500
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZMAGS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fortune ranks most powerful businesswomen
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Internet has changed the landscape of American business in
still another unexpected way _ by elevating more women to the top
levels of management, Fortune (Oct. 25) reports.
</P>
<P>
   Carly Fiorina, who ranks first on the magazine's ``50 most
powerful women in American business'' list for the second straight
year, is an example.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998 she headed the core division at Lucent Technologies.
This year she made history by becoming chief executive of
Hewlett-Packard, the first female to hold that position at one of
America's 20 biggest corporations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year's Power 50 is remarkable for the fact that newcomers
make up one-third of the list _ half of them in tech-related jobs,
showing once again the Internet's limitless capacity for creating
power, opportunity and wealth,'' Fortune says.
</P>
<P>
   Others in the top five of Fortune's list after Fiorina are Heidi
Miller, chief financial officer of Citigroup; Mary Meeker, managing
director, Morgan Stanley Dean Witter; Shelly Lazarus, chairman and
chief executive officer, Ogilvy &AMP; Mather; and Meg Whitman,
president and chief executive officer, eBay.
</P>
<P>
   Cosmetic surgery at Forbes
</P>
<P>
   A Forbes (Oct. 18) by any other look is still a Forbes, as its
redesigned format shows.
</P>
<P>
   It's the magazine's first redesign in 10 years and leads with a
cover story on cable TV titan John Malone, the largest individual
shareholder of AT&AMP;T. He may be about to lock horns with AT&AMP;T
Chairman Michael Armstrong over the flagging performance of AT&AMP;T
stock, the magazine says.
</P>
<P>
   As for what's new at Forbes, Editor William Baldwin says it's
``more visual,'' and its various departments will always be in a
consistent order of appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Chill out, mom
</P>
<P>
   Working Mother (November) tried to settle the home vs. career
conflict for working moms by asking their children what they think.
A survey of more than 1,000 kids and 600 parents by the Families
and Work Institute in New York found that a majority of the kids
felt they had ``ample time with their parents.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Other reassuring results show that working has little to do
with how children view their parents and that the majority of kids
think their working mothers are doing a great job,'' the magazine
says.
</P>
<P>
   Worth mentioning
</P>
<P>
   Business Week (Oct. 11) profiles Ford's chief executive officer,
Jacques Nasser, who is ``off to a jackrabbit start in his quest to
transform the stodgy giant into a consumer-oriented powerhouse.''
</P>
<P>
   The end of blue-collar work may be near as more businesses move
from making things to marketing services and other intangibles, The
Futurist (October) says. Researchers say the growing disparity
between high-skill, high-wage workers and low-skill, low-wage
workers ``may have serious implications for social cohesion in many
advanced nations.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
