</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-RAILCRASH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEATH TOLL RISES IN TRAIN CRASH IN BRITAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By ALAN COWELL    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The death toll from Tuesday's train crash in London,
Britain's worst in more than four decades, rose to at least 70 on
Wednesday, police said. An intercity express hit a three-car
commuter train that apparently ran a red light, investigators
reported.
</P>
<P>
   The fate of 100 more people remained unclear, according to a
police spokesman, Andy Trotter.
</P>
<P>
   And the crash rekindled a passionate debate over the safety of
Britain's trains since the formerly state-owned system was sold in
May 1996 to private companies, which have been accused by union
officials of skimping on safety equipment in their pursuit of
profit.
</P>
<P>
   In a rending twist for relatives of the dead, rescue officials
said the remains of many bodies are still not recovered,
incinerated in the burned shell of a first-class buffet car at the
front of the express.
</P>
<P>
   One official described the 48-seat carriage as ``knee-deep in
ash'' from a devastating fire that erupted almost immediately after
the express, heading into London from western England with 500
travelers, hit the smaller train, which was heading out of London
at 8:11 a.m., the height of the morning rush-hour.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the dead may never be identified or even recovered,
Trotter said. ``We do not believe, given the devastation caused by
the fire, that it will be possible to recover any more bodies from
the train,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The stricken carriage, which has not yet been searched, lay
lopsidedly along the track Wednesday night, covered in drab gray
tarpaulins. Rescue officials said they may begin a detailed search
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Thompson, an officer of the British Transport Police, said
that both trains were carrying diesel fuel and that when they
collided, ``it was a fireball.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All the seats are gone, everything is gone,'' Thompson said.
``It's just a shell.''
</P>
<P>
   One survivor, Brendon Bentley, a 24-year-old New Zealander who
works as an accountant, was on the commuter train.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember just a big surge and everyone being knocked down
and then bits of seat and everything coming from over my shoulders
and then just darkness,'' he said from his bed at St. Mary's
Hospital, where he is being treated for damage to his spleen and a
broken wrist.
</P>
<P>
   When the fire began, he said, `'I could see the flames and there
were some people trapped underneath the seats. We had to try and
get over them and try to give them a hand, but we couldn't. So then
the first priority was just to get off the carriage.''
</P>
<P>
   Trotter told reporters at the crash site, near Ladbroke Grove,
that the death toll was ``70-plus,'' with a further 100 people who
`'might have been on that train'' and were not satisfactorily
accounted for. Of the 70 people known to have boarded the express,
he said, 28 bodies had been recovered but not positively
identified.
</P>
<P>
   Police are basing their calculations on accounts from friends
and relatives who have identified 70 people who definitely boarded
one of the trains and have not been heard from since. Trotter said
the other 100 were people whose travel arrangements were unclear or
who may have survived the crash without informing police.
</P>
<P>
   Britain's worst crash before Tuesday's was in 1957, when 90
people died in a collision between a commuter train and an express
in southeast London. Since then, though safety devices have
proliferated in many parts of Europe, British railroad operators
have shied from installing them.
</P>
<P>
   British labor leaders say several accidents could have been
avoided if rail operators had invested in a safety system called
Automatic Train Protection, which automatically stops trains at red
signals.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent such accident occurred two years ago, on the
same stretch of track, when another Great Western train slammed
into a freight train, killing seven people. The company was fined
$2.5 million after acknowledging inadequate safety measures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all know if the railways were in public ownership, ATP
would have been installed in trains by 1994 or 1995,'' said Mick
Rix, a spokesman for the rail drivers' union. ``I think the public,
rightly, is now making a clear demand that safety must be put
before cost.''
</P>
<P>
   The argument became louder when union officials disclosed
Wednesday that a signal near the site of the crash _ Signal 109 _
had been cited in eight incidents over six years when train drivers
complained that they could not see th lights because of power
cables and gantries.
</P>
<P>
   Under private ownership, Britain's rail service is divided among
the train operators and Railtrack, which owns the tracks, stations
and signaling system. The companies are profitable, especially
Railtrack, but the profits have been accompanied by growing worries
about safety.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Prime Minister John Prescott said Wednesday night, for
instance, that there had been 600 incidents of trains running red
signals in the past 12 months. ``I want complete assurance that the
industry is doing enough to reduce the dangers,'' he told reporters
as he announced plans for an inquiry into rail safety.
</P>
<P>
   The three companies involved in the accident _ Railtrack and the
two operators, Thames Trains and First Great Western _ said in a
statement that the Great Western express had been ``authorized to
proceed under green lights'' and that ``the signals concerned were
in full working order.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Investigations will now concentrate on the behavior of the
Thames turbo train following reports that it had passed a signal at
danger,'' the statement said. It also said the workings of Signal
109 would be examined.
</P>
<P>
   Thames Trains said its driver had been driving for two months
after 11 months of training.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-99 1842EDT &QL; 
