u w BC-SCOTUS-HAWAII-540&AMP;ADD     10-06 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-HAWAII-540&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH COURT HEARS CASE ON ANCESTRY-BASED VOTING RIGHTS IN HAWAII 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Harold F. Rice is a native of Hawaii, but he is not
a ``Native Hawaiian'' or even a ``Hawaiian'' under the law of a
state that reserves those terms for descendants of the people
living on the islands in 1778, when British Capt. James Cook and
his crew arrived.
</P>
<P>
   As such, Rice is barred from voting for the trustees of the
Office of Hawaiian Affairs, a state agency that dispenses millions
of dollars a year on behalf of ``Hawaiians,'' the roughly 20
percent of the state's population that can claim at least one
indigenous ancestor, and Native Hawaiians, a considerably smaller
group with at least 50 percent Native blood. Under Hawaii's
constitution, only the members of these groups, as beneficiaries of
the agency's largesse, may vote for its leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Rice, whose Caucasian ancestors arrived in Hawaii in 1831,
brought an unusual discrimination case before the U.S. Supreme
Court on Wednesday, asking the justices to find him _ and, by
extension, some 80 percent of Hawaii's population _ the victims of
unconstitutional racial discrimination and to open the agency's
elections to all voters in the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a case of ballot box racial discrimination plain and
simple,'' Theodore Olson, Rice's lawyer, told the court. Olson
maintained that the limitation violates both the 14th Amendment's
guarantee of equal protection and the 15th Amendment's promise that
the right to vote shall not be denied ``on account of race, color,
or previous condition of servitude.''
</P>
<P>
   The state's lawyer, John G. Roberts Jr., tried to persuade the
justices that this was not a case about race but rather about a
``distinct and unique indigenous group'' for which Congress and the
Hawaii state government have assumed a special obligation tied not
to race but to history. Rice, Roberts said, ``was not denied the
right to vote on account of race'' but because ``Congress has
singled out Hawaiians as the beneficiaries of a trust relationship
just like its relationship with American Indians.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration supported Hawaii in the case. Deputy
Solicitor General Edwin Kneedler told the justices that the
structure of the Office of Hawaiian Affairs reflected not a concern
with race but a ``historic continuity to the sovereign nation that
existed at the time of European contact.''
</P>
<P>
   But persuading the justices was an uphill battle. ``There are a
lot of groups like that, with their own continuity, their own
history, who might even have been aggrieved,'' Justice Antonin
Scalia objected.
</P>
<P>
   By their questions and comments, it was clear that race remained
the lens through which the justices viewed this case, Rice vs.
Cayetano, No. 98-818, making it quite likely that they will strike
down the voting restriction. By the end of the argument, the only
real question appeared to be what path the court might take toward
that end, and what impact such a decision would have.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on the court's approach, a decision for Rice might be
limited to the particularities of Hawaii, or might produce a
decision casting doubt on numerous special benefits that now exist
in federal and state law for Native Americans, or might even say
something generally about official policies that take account of
race.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``What are the ramifications of the position you are arguing?''
Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg asked Rice's lawyer, Olson.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's impossible for me to say,'' Olson replied. He said the
narrowest ground of decision would be to strike down the
restriction as a violation of the 15th Amendment right to vote,
adding that he was unaware of any other state or federal law that
conditioned the right to vote on membership in a racial group.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't mean to suggest that if you win, there won't be a
lot of litigation,'' said Justice John Paul Stevens, and Olson
conceded the point.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. District Court in Honolulu and the 9th U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals in San Francisco both rejected Rice's position,
with the appeals court concluding last year that ``the voting
restriction is not primarily racial, but legal or political.''
</P>
<P>
   The 9th Circuit said that elections for the agency's trustees
were like elections for special-purpose irrigation and land-use
districts, which the Supreme Court has ruled may be
constitutionally limited to landowners within the district.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court's decision also relied on the fact that the
Office of Hawaiian Affairs administers and dispenses the revenue
from a trust consisting of land that was set aside for public
purposes beginning with Hawaii's annexation to the United States in
1898. At statehood in 1959, the ``betterment of the conditions of
Native Hawaiians'' became one of the purposes of the trust.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see why you can't say that only beneficiaries of the
trust can vote for the trustees,'' Justice Stephen G. Breyer told
Olson.
</P>
<P>
   Olson replied that ``trust is an arbitrary term'' that could not
justify discrimination in voting.
</P>
<P>
   Most justices appeared unreceptive to the state's effort to
anchor Hawaii's special provisions for its natives in the body of
Indian law, under which many special provisions for Native
Americans have been upheld. Scalia said that Indian law, based on
the concept of tribal sovereignty, was irrelevant to Hawaii, where
the natives were never organized into tribes.
</P>
<P>
   Ginsburg disagreed. ``But Hawaii was a sovereign kingdom, and
the United States had a large hand in destroying that
sovereignty,'' she said, adding: ``The analogy seems to me quite
strong.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-99 1843EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991006.0286 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8726 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-ART-N     10-06 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN FORCES CONTINUE THRUST INTO CHECHNYA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GROZNY, Russia _ Russian forces have expanded their operation in
Chechnya, moving more troops in from the west, after seizing
control of the entire northern part of the republic, Chechen
commanders here said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Chechen fighters have withdrawn from north of the Terek River,
the last fighters pulling out of the village of Naurskaya just
before dawn Wednesday, said Apti Batalov, chief of the presidential
administration in Grozny.
</P>
<P>
   ``They bombarded the village heavily last night. The men
probably withdrew to save the village from complete destruction,''
he said. Another Chechen commander, who asked to remain anonymous,
said that Russian units had nearly encircled the Chechens who
decided to escape rather than be trapped.
</P>
<P>
   The men left at 4 a.m. after mining the approaches to the
village , and slipped away across a gas pipeline suspended above
the Terek River, he said. The northwestern district above the
Terek, known as Shelkovskaya, has also been abandoned, and the
bridges mined, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The news of the Chechen retreat came as little surprise to
commanders based in Grozny. It was widely expected and seemed
preferable to expending ammunition and even losing a large number
of men at this stage, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Although seizing the land north of the Terek appears to have
been one of their main aims, Russian forces immediately pushed on
with their offensive, moving troops in from Ingushetia, well south
of the Terek.
</P>
<P>
   Batalov said Russian troops occupied high ground above the
settlement of Goragorsk, some 15 miles west of Grozny, the capital.
They also moved in on the village of Bamut, in the far southwestern
corner of Chechnya, crossing in from positions in Ingushetia.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians have only advanced a few miles into Chechnya from
the west, but Batalov said he expected them to try to storm Bamut,
after bombarding it Tuesday night. ``It will probably start soon,''
he said. He agreed that the Russians may be aiming to create a
buffer zone around the edges of Chechnya, to enforce a tight
economic and security blockade.
</P>
<P>
   Yet none of the commanders in Grozny rule out the possibility of
Russian troops trying to storm Grozny. A few suggest that they
might let the Russian troops in and then hit their positions once
they are established.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can then surround them and fight them much more easily, as
we did in August 1996,'' said Salamgir Gabatayev, a commander who
fought in the last battle for Grozny when Chechen fighters trapped
thousands of Russian troops in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Few civilian residents are waiting to see what will happen. They
were leaving the city in droves again Wednesday, in cars and trucks
piled high with baggage and furniture, heading out west to
Ingushetia.
</P>
<P>
   A triple line of cars stretched back two miles at the border.
Prices in Grozny have risen sharply.
</P>
<P>
   Shelling could be heard from the direction of Goragorsk to the
north. Chechen officials reported more shelling in two villages
north of Grozny, Znamenskoye, where seven people were reported
killed Wednesday morning, and Chervlyonnaya, where fighting was
reported.
</P>
<P>
   One spark for the latest exodus was the news that 40 people,
mostly women and children, were killed when their bus was hit by a
Russian shell near Chervlyonnaya on Tuesday. Chechen fighters who
came to their rescue were also killed when a second volley of
rockets hit the same spot.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the pervading nervousness, Chechens celebrated the
shooting down of up to three Russian ground attack jets. A wing of
one of the planes, shot down Monday, was put on display in central
Grozny and drew a crowd who tore off fragments as souvenirs.
</P>
<P>
   The Chechen government has introduced martial law, ordering all
men of fighting age to report to their local army command point,
and for all factories and enterprises to assist the war effort with
supplies and food.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
