<HEADLINE>
HINDU NATIONALISTS LEAD AS COUNTING OF 350 MILLION BALLOTS BEGINS
IN INDIA  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By CELIA W. DUGGER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ The colossal job of counting more than 350
million ballots in India's national elections got under way
Wednesday, and partial results showed that the Hindu
nationalist-led coalition had taken a lead against the alliance
headed by the Congress Party.
</P>
<P>
   Most political analysts said it was likely that the Hindu
nationalist Bharatiya Janata Party and the more than 20 other
parties that have joined the alliance it heads would emerge with a
majority. The last coalition government, also led by the BJP,
toppled this spring, just 13 tumultuous months into a five-year
term, when its most temperamental partner pulled out.
</P>
<P>
   The Congress Party, led by Sonia Gandhi, the Italian-born widow
who inherited the mantle of the Nehru-Gandhi dynasty, was trailing
badly. But Mrs. Gandhi herself, who was seeking a seat in
Parliament for the first time, won from a poor, rural district in
the southern state of Karnataka. Her opponent, the BJP stalwart
Shushma Swaraj, had portrayed herself as the native Indian battling
the ``foreigner,'' Mrs. Gandhi, but that theme failed to sway the
voters.
</P>
<P>
   All across India, people crowded around their television sets to
watch the early results of the third national election in three
years. Almost 6 out of 10 adults voted across the nation, the
world's biggest democracy, despite the wearying frequency of
elections that seem only to produce more unstable governments.
</P>
<P>
   The state television network, which reaches the humblest mud
huts in the remotest villages, kept a continually updated tally of
results rolling across the bottom of the screen.
</P>
<P>
   In central New Delhi, just a short walk from Parliament, people
pulled off the road to gaze at a huge board where men regularly
climbed a ladder to update the vote tallies. After losing the city
badly in state elections, the Hindu nationalists swept every seat
in Delhi, even defeating Manmohan Singh, the sober Congress Party
economist who was thought to be a possible candidate for prime
minister.
</P>
<P>
   S.N. Chanchal, a retired teacher who had watched the returns all
afternoon on television walked over after dinner to look at the
board. J.K. Bhatia, a survey engineer, stopped on his way home from
work. ``We're very pleased,'' Bhatia said. ``We want a stable
government. There should not be elections every year. It's a waste
of time and money.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was far from clear just how stable a new government will
be, even if the Bharatiya Janata Party-led coalition wins a
majority.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, as poll workers were still opening the locks on metal
boxes and laboriously hand counting paper ballots, two of the
partners were speaking out against a decision made by the BJP-led
coalition government that has ruled as a caretaker government since
April. They objected to a decision the government made Tuesday to
raise the controlled price of diesel fuel 40 percent in response to
a 60 percent increase in international prices of diesel.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee, 73, looked chipper
and rested this evening and voiced confidence that the alliance he
leads will have the votes to form a government. The lower house has
543 elected members and it takes 272 to form a simple majority.
</P>
<P>
   As of 12:30 a.m. India time, the Hindu nationalist-led alliance
had won 107 seats and was leading in 179 more, for a total of 286.
Vajpayee, leader of the Bharatiya Janata Party, won his
parliamentary seat from Lucknow, the state capital of Uttar
Pradesh.
</P>
<P>
   The Congress Party and its allies had won 51 seats and were
leading in 83 others, for a total of 134. Other parties had won 11
seats and were leading in 93. There were no results yet in the
remaining seats.
</P>
<P>
   The vote counting will be over by Friday, election officials
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
