<HEADER>
A8728 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-LEBANON-ART-35     10-06 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-LEBANON-ART-350&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL HAS SHIFTED TO LOWER-RISK TACTICS IN SOUTHERN LEBANON 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ The operational nature of the chronic, low-level
warfare in southern Lebanon has changed markedly over the past two
months as both Israeli and Shiite Muslim guerrillas look ahead to
the Israeli troop withdrawal pledged by Prime Minister Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has increased its bombardment of suspected guerrilla
targets in response to an intensification of attacks by Party of
God (Hezbollah) forces, military officials say. By Wednesday
afternoon, for instance, Israeli planes had carried out six air
strikes within 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has also scaled back deployment of ground troops with the
specific aim of avoiding casualties, even if it means foregoing
attacks that would inflict damage on the guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual admission Wednesday, Army Chief of Staff Shaul
Mofaz acknowledged a new reticence to take risks, saying he
preferred to ``keep our losses down'' and ``kill fewer Hezbollah
fighters'' if it meant protecting more Israelis soldiers from
danger.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli military officials also said they have been able to
reduce the use of ground troops because the accuracy of their
weapon systems has improved with new technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are really doing is introducing technologies that
partially substitute for the physical presence of soldiers,'' said
Deputy Defense Minister Ephraim Sneeh in an interview. ``The bottom
line is that it has improved the efficiency of our presence in
southern Lebanon. We can stave off the guerrillas from our border
with a lower price.''
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear whether this amounts to a tailored strategy of
preparation for Barak's promise to pull out of southern Lebanon by
next summer. Some military experts suggested Wednesday that it
could represent nothing more than the latest tactical shift in a
21-year-old conflict.
</P>
<P>
   But it is difficult not to see this as a shift of tactics geared
to a political goal. It is undeniable that the Israeli army, like
it or not, is facing a nine-month deadline for withdrawal as Barak
moves to extricate Israel from an unpopular and seemingly
unwinnable fight.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Barak's pledge to bring home the boys was a centerpiece of his
campaign, and some believe it catapulted him to his overwhelming
victory in May. But he did make the pledge on the assumption that
he would quickly renew a dialogue with Syria, which effectively
controls Lebanon and holds sway over the guerrillas. And that
renewal has yet to happen, at least openly. (Back-channel
conversations through third parties, including the Americans, have
taken place.)
</P>
<P>
   But for political reasons, Barak seems to consider himself bound
to withdraw anyway, even without Syria's help. Last week, when Sneh
suggested that the deadline need not be rigid, Barak sent out a
pager message to Israeli reporters within 25 minutes, distancing
himself from the comment.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli Defense Forces did not fulfill a request Wednesday
to release full statistics on air strikes. But Yediot Ahronot, one
of Israel's top three newspapers, reported Tuesday that the air
force had conducted 100 sorties in Lebanon in the past month. The
paper called it a record number, and said the bombing has
intensified since June, when Israel, in retaliation for rockets
fired at northern settlements, conducted its most severe
bombardment of Lebanon since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The paper also quoted senior officers in Lebanon who said that
neither Israeli troops nor special units had been sent on ambushes
or offensives deep inside Lebanon ``for some time.''
</P>
<P>
   In describing the army's current approach, Sneh said: ``The
policy is very prudent, not in the sense of cautious, but clever.
We are not going toward danger. When there is something efficient,
we do it. And we have had some nice successes destroying the
artillery of the Hezbollah in the last couple of months.''
</P>
<P>
   Israel first dispatched troops to Lebanon in 1978 to attack
Palestinian guerrillas. Since 1985 it has occupied a 9-mile-deep
border zone in southern Lebanon to protect its northern towns from
attack. But the steady loss of Israeli soldiers and the poor
prospects of an end to the conflict have embittered many Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has lost 13 soldiers in Lebanon so far this year. In
1998, 23 died in the conflict, and in 1997, 39 were killed, not
including 73 who died in a helicopter collision.
</P>
<P>
   Brig. Gen. Shlomo Brom, who recently published a study on
Israel's engagement in Lebanon for the Tel Aviv University Jaffe
Center for Strategic Studies, said the army is indeed bettering its
ability to use aerial force, particularly by becoming quicker to
locate guerrilla strongholds and retaliate. But he said: ``I'm
afraid it's not the end of the story. Hezbollah will now look for
tactics that will make it less vulnerable to airborne attacks, and
then we're back to the drawing board.''
</P>
<P>
   He continued: ``There is no silver bullet that will allow us to
withdraw to the international border and have everything be OK.
Prime Minister Barak is a very intelligent person with vast
military experience, and I can't imagine he's thinking in such
simplistic terms.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
