<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA DEVELOPER SUES TO STOP APARTMENT FORECLOSURES IN
HOUSTON 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Calif.) 
 
By RON NISSIMOV 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Beleaguered California developer Alfred Antonini,
indicted last month by a Houston grand jury on charges of money
laundering and threatening an employee, has filed a lawsuit to try
to stop the foreclosure of a local apartment complex he owns.
</P>
<P>
   Antonini, 53, of Hayward, Calif., says in the state district
court suit he filed earlier this week that two associates have
conspired to try to fraudulently take away two Houston apartment
complexes from Antonini worth millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The associates denied any wrongdoing Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Antonini sold one of the apartment complexes, the 432-unit
Natchez House Apartments in southwest Houston, this spring to Gary
Gates of Rosenberg for $4.5 million. Antonini contends in the
lawsuit that Gates, through his company Gatesco, also had promised
to buy the 340-unit Woodland Forest Apartments in southwest Houston
and give Antonini one-third ownership in both complexes.
</P>
<P>
   Both facilities were in bankruptcy protection earlier this year
because Antonini owed millions to lender Ireland Family Limited
Partnership.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit said the total sales price of both complexes was to
be $7.8 million, with the understanding that Antonini would pay off
the debts at the complexes in return for part ownership.
</P>
<P>
   But the sale of Woodland Forest Apartments never materialized,
and lender Ireland Family Limited Partnership planned to foreclose
on the complex this week because it was owed more than $2 million
on the property, said John Quinlan, a part-owner of the limited
partnership who also represents it as an attorney.
</P>
<P>
   According to the lawsuit, Quinlan and Gates would both have
received one-third ownership of the two complexes if the sale of
both had gone through, but they conspired to prevent the sale of
the second complex in order to deprive Antonini of ownership in
either one.
</P>
<P>
   Antonini's lawsuit asked a judge to prevent the foreclosure of
Woodland Forest Apartments. He is seeking unspecified actual and
punitive damages from Gates and Quinlan, and their respective
companies.
</P>
<P>
   State District Judge John Devine refused Monday to issue a
temporary restraining order preventing the foreclosure of Woodland
Forest Apartments.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Antonini sought bankruptcy protection for the
complex in California court, preventing foreclosure until the
bankruptcy issues are resolved.
</P>
<P>
   Antonini could not be reached for comment. His attorney Jess
Mason said that during the negotiations, Gates told Antonini that
another partner would be the ``money man'' but refused to disclose
his identity. He said Antonini repeatedly asked it the third
partner was Quinlan, but Gates told him no.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were shocked at his (Quinlan's) involvement and tried to
work things out,'' Mason said. ``There was a squeeze play going
on.''
</P>
<P>
   Quinlan said he will fight Antonini's bankruptcy filing in
California because the issue has already been resolved in a Houston
federal court. Mason said the California filing is proper.
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors have said Antonini, 53, was involved in two
check-kiting schemes involving nearly $24 million and in illegal
real estate and bank transactions. Antonini's wife, Alva J.
Antonini, 52, and James G. Lomonaco, 51, were also indicted. All
three have entered pleas of not guilty before U.S. Magistrate Judge
Calvin Botley in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   According to the indictment, the three used computers and
``hand-drawn ledgers'' to artificially inflate bank accounts,
including accounts in Houston banks, ``with the goal of gaining
interest-free loans.''
</P>
<P>
   The indictment also alleges that the three threatened a former
employee who knew of the conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   The three are accused of conspiracy, money laundering, bank
fraud and using the mail to make extortion threats in a federal
indictment returned last week. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
