<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELLSOUTH07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BellSouth CEO reassures employess
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATANTA _ A day after conceding defeat in the bidding for Sprint,
BellSouth's top executive sent a message to 90,000 employees
offering an explanation, reassurance and optimism.
</P>
<P>
   In an e-mail message Wednesday, Chairman and Chief Executive F.
Duane Ackerman said the company was justified in reaching for
Sprint. But he argued that coming up short was not a sign that the
company was in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth remains strong and profitable, with a vibrant future,
he wrote. ``We have the resources to compete against anyone ... I
want you to know that we are still committed to our strategies for
growing our business.''
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of the frantic, but failed bid for Sprint,
Ackerman's only other public statement was a terse, two-sentence
release Tuesday. That statement acknowledged that BellSouth's
eleventh-hour, $100 billion bid had been trumped Monday by MCI
WorldCom, which threw $115 billion on the table and won the nod
from Sprint.
</P>
<P>
   A BellSouth merger with Sprint was seen as providing instant
credibility as a national player in all manner of
telecommunications services. But Ackerman reminded employees the
company still has a solid base in the Southeast, a growing wireless
business, promising investments in Latin America and a solid
Internet unit. Ackerman said: ``We have the tools we need to
compete ... except one, long distance.''
</P>
<P>
   That lack of long-distance apparently proved a hurdle in making
BellSouth's case. Company bargainers were frustrated in the past
few days to find that naysayers at Sprint could cite the problem of
forming a combination while BellSouth was still banned from
long-distance in its region.
</P>
<P>
   At least the merger of MCI WorldCom and Sprint adds ammunition
to the argument of the regional Bells that they should be granted
entry. Ackerman said he expects the Federal Communications
Commission to approve long-distance for BellSouth early next year.
</P>
<P>
   Once the company has regulatory approval, Ackerman said, the
BellSouth alliance with Qwest Communications will provide a solid
start into long-distance voice and data. And while BellSouth will
weigh other acquisitions, there is no urgency, he wrote. ``We don't
have to merge or acquire another company to increase shareholder
value. While this merger may have accelerated our growth
strategies, we can accomplish the same thing by forming alliances
with other companies.''
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth has been criticized both for rushing to bid for
Sprint, but also for staying aloof while merger mania swept the
industry. A series of huge combinations has turned BellSouth from
the largest regional Bell to second-smallest. Federal regulators
Wednesday approved SBC Communications' purchase of Ameritech, which
makes that company twice the size of BellSouth.
</P>
<P>
   In his letter, Ackerman defended the decision to make a run at
Sprint, a decision made as MCI WorldCom approached an agreement
with Sprint. BellSouth lost, but its bids forced MCI WorldCom to
pay an estimated $13 billion more than planned. And Ackerman argued
in effect that nothing has changed since financial analysts
endorsed BellSouth as a solid investment among the Bells.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Paine Webber recently wrote BellSouth ``is the
most attractively valued stock in the group based on its superior
growth rate. We expect BLS to once again lead the group with the
best operating results ... and believe that the stock is worth $54
per share.'' BellSouth stock closed Wednesday at 42.68 3/4 per
share.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
