<SLUG> BC-CINNABON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cinnabon set to make first Caribbean foray
 &HT;    By Shelia M. Poole
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Cinnabon continues to expand its presence overseas
with a deal to open 18 bakeries in Puerto Rico, the U.S. Virgin
Islands and the Dominican Republic.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, with franchisee Cinnamon Rolls Caribbean Inc., marks
the brand's first entry into the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of interest overseas,'' said David McDougall,
director of operations. He said further deals may be possible with
Cinnamon Rolls Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   Cinnabon has looked overseas for much of its expansion efforts
since it was acquired by Atlanta-based AFC Enterprises last
October. Previously, the company had decided not to focus on
franchising. That was revived under AFC, which is a major franchise
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a two-pronged development strategy,'' McDougall said.
He estimates overseas bakery openings represent half of the
company's growth.
</P>
<P>
   Within the last year, the company has signed agreements for more
than 300 Cinnabon units to be built in 20 additional countries.
Overall, Cinnabon operates and franchises 411 retail cinnamon roll
bakeries in 39 states, Canada and Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   AFC also owns Churchs Chicken, Popeyes Chicken &AMP; Biscuits,
Seattle's Best Coffee and Torrefazione Italia Coffee. AFC, which
had 1998 sales of $1.8 billion, has more than 3,300 restaurants,
bakeries and cafes in 25 countries.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
