<P>
   CONGRESS-HEALTH (Washington) _ Developments. House Republicans
set up a procedure that reduces the prospects for enactment of
landmark legislation to define patients' rights and regulate HMOs.
By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   DNA-SOLVING-CRIMES (Chicago) _ In a novel legal gambit that
stretches the law to match the developing science of DNA, a
prosecutor in Wisconsin has filed rape and kidnapping charges
against a defendant who has no name. John Doe is known only by
semen samples from three rapes. The case shows how hopeful
prosecutors are that DNA can solve old crimes, even when no suspect
is known. But it also illustrates some of the legal and practical
issues that surround the burgeoning science, particularly whether
it will render irrelevant the notion of a statute of limitations.
By Bill Dedman.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-CAMPAIGN-ASSESS (Washington) _ These are uneasy days for
Republicans on Capitol Hill. Once again they are locked in a
chaotic, down-to-the-wire budget battle with President Clinton.
They have been forced into a debate over managed health care
legislation that offends the anti-regulatory sensibilities of many
Republicans. And now the party's front-running presidential
candidate seems to be defining his own credentials as a
``compassionate conservative'' by distancing himself from them. By
Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-YELTSIN-FAMILY (Omsk, Russia) _ Leonid Dyachenko,
son-in-law of President Boris Yeltsin and husband of Yeltsin's
daughter and right-hand strategist, Tatiyana Dyachenko, was once so
anonymous that even prying reporters were unsure of his first name.
But Dyachenko turns out to have a colorful life indeed. He is a
participant, if not a key figure, in a network of politically
blessed companies that ship Siberian oil products to Ukraine and to
eastern Europe. The disclosure of his dealings is at the least
embarrassing to the Kremlin. At worst, it could plunge the Yeltsin
family into a corruption sinkhole over which, so far, they have
managed only to teeter. By Michael Wines. 1,300 words.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-THATCHER (Blackpool, England) _ The posters announcing
Wednesday night's talk at the Conservative party conference by
former Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher announced, ``She's back,''
but the Tories learned with a mixture of delight and dismay that
she never really went away. By Warren Hoge. 1,400 words.
</P>
<P>
   FCC-TELECOM-MERGERS (Washington) _ Looking at what the
regulatory philosophy is that ties together the disparate
businesses of telecommunciations today in light of the FCC
chairman's apparent hostile stance toward the $115 billion deal
between Sprint and MCI Worldcom. By Stephen Labaton. 1,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   Reefer:
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-RAILCRASH (London) _ The death toll from Tuesday's train
crash in London, Britain's worst in more than four decades, rises
to at least 70. An intercity express hit a three-car commuter train
that apparently ran a red light, investigators report. By Alan
Cowell. 1,000 words. (MOVED)
</P>
</TEXT>
