<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 19:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8737 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-HISTORY-NYT &LR;      10-06 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-HISTORY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASSACRE OF ISRAELI-ARABS SHOULD BE RECOGNIZED IN CLASSROOMS,
OFFICIAL URGES
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Originally slugged ISRAEL-LESSON) 
(js) 
 By JOEL GREENBERG  
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Urging Israeli teachers to face a dark chapter in
their country's past, Education Minister Yossi Sarid has
recommended that a massacre of Israeli Arabs 43 years ago this
month be marked for the first time in the nation's classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   The request to commemorate the killings of 47 Arab villagers by
Israeli border policemen at the village of Kafr Kassem on October
29, 1956, was made in a letter sent by Sarid on Tuesday to civics
teachers across the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not seek to hide and obscure, we do not seek to cover up
the shame, but to deal with it openly and honestly,'' Sarid, a
former civics teacher and the leader of the leftist Meretz party,
wrote to the teachers. ``Whoever is sure of himself and his path
will not hesitate to expose his flaws as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Sarid's message does not mean that the Israeli government is
taking responsibility for the killings, as Arab leaders of the
village have demanded. But the letter was the latest sign of a more
critical examination of Israeli history that has filtered down from
academic circles to the media and the schools, setting off a lively
national debate.
</P>
<P>
   New high school textbooks introduced this year challenge
traditional Israeli historical accounts, acknowledging the
expulsion of Arabs during Israel's war of independence in 1948 and
questioning depictions of Israeli fighters as outnumbered by the
Arabs. An Israeli television history series aired last year to mark
the country's 50th anniversary included scenes of expulsion and
Palestinian perspectives on the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Sarid wrote that the purpose of marking the massacre was to
teach Israeli children that illegal orders must be refused.
</P>
<P>
   At Kafr Kassem, border policemen under orders to shoot to kill
curfew-breakers fired on villagers returning from their fields,
killing men, women and children. Eight of the policemen were tried
and convicted, despite their claims that they were merely following
orders. However, their sentences were later reduced, and none
served more than three-and-a-half years in jail.
</P>
<P>
   Sarid quoted from the verdict, which asserted that soldiers must
refuse a ``patently illegal order'' that carries a ``black flag''
of criminality.
</P>
<P>
   Citing another verdict against a soldier who beat a man to death
in the Gaza Strip in 1988 during the Palestinian uprising, Sarid
noted that ``good soldiers, `the best of our youth', have carried
out patently illegal orders.'' Such behavior was the result of
``educational neglect,'' Sarid asserted. ``We do not want to
descend, God forbid, to crimes born of blind obedience,'' Sarid
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``Precisely those who are proud as we are of the
rebirth of Israel and totally identify with it, precisely those who
like us see military service as a national and personal mission of
unparalleled importance, it is precisely we who must remember and
commemorate the Kafr Kassem massacre _ and this year, for the first
time, in our educational system _ to insure that our pupils will
know how to listen and discern an illegal order, to keep their eyes
open and identify the black flag.''
</P>
<P>
   The school commemoration would also send an unequivocal and long
overdue message to Israel's Arab citizens, Sarid's letter said.
``We are ashamed of what happened in Kafr Kassem,'' he wrote.
``Your pain is our disgrace.''
</P>
<P>
   The first official gesture of sympathy was made last year by the
rightist government of Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, when
Moshe Katzav, a cabinet minister responsible for Israeli Arab
affairs, went to Kafr Kassem to attend its annual commemoration of
the massacre.
</P>
<P>
   Sami Issam, the head of the village council in Kafr Kassem,
welcomed Sarid's letter but cautioned that the issue could not be
laid to rest until the Israeli government either accepted
responsibility for the killings or appointed a commission of
inquiry into the massacre.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope that this will be a first courageous step to finally
bring the truth to light, so that we won't have to go on living
with this for many more years to come,'' Issa said.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Minister Yossi Beilin told Issa on Tuesday that Israel
could not take responsibility for the massacre, saying that the
government at the time did not order the shootings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
