<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 19:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8738 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-WRESTLING-APPEAL-COX     10-06 1235
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRESTLING-APPEAL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wrestling has crushing appeal
 &HT;    By Amy Kincheloe
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Waco, Texas
</P>
<P>
   It's Thursday night and many of the neighborhood children, 7 to
13 years old, have gathered at Tyler Meek's home to watch another
installment of the professional wrestling program ``Smackdown.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's cool,'' said 8-year-old Tyler. ``I watch it whenever it
comes on _ Monday, Thursday, Saturday and Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyler, whose bedroom walls sport pictures of stars from the
World Wrestling Federation and whose closet is full of wrestling
T-shirts, is not alone in his love for this form of entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   As wrestling's popularity among adult Americans has increased in
the past couple of years, spurred by the WWF's increasingly
provocative shows, so has wrestling's popularity increased among
children. And despite the protests by wrestling promoters that they
aren't trying to appeal to children, children do find the shows
appealing, as they do the accompanying merchandise of T-shirts,
action figures and so on.
</P>
<P>
   According to Nielsen Media Research, which compiles television
ratings, on a typical Monday night, 7 million homes are tuned in to
the two most popular wrestling shows. And about 4 million of those
viewers are younger than 18.
</P>
<P>
   David White, a men's fashion sales associate at Kmart Super
Center, said he has definitely noticed that more customers seem to
be interested in wrestling, especially children.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the first thing they run to,'' White said of the
store's pro-wrestling clothing and toy sections. ``They love it.
The little kids go crazy over it. `Star Wars' has nothing on
wrestling.''
</P>
<P>
   But White said he personally isn't fond of wrestling. ``I find
it boring. I think it's a lot of hype on something that's so
overrated and over-exaggerated. Wrestling promotes violence, to
me.''
</P>
<P>
   How the depiction of violence affects children is a subject of
debate in the child-development field.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Robinson, a professor of educational psychology at Baylor
University, said he understands why children like wrestling, but he
doesn't think that's such a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's popular with children because the wrestlers are like live
cartoons _ muscular and painted faces,'' Robinson said. ``It's a
very exciting event to see with all the action, music and flashing
lights. It has to do with the cartoon mentality with children and
they get to see real, live people getting hit over the head with
chairs without being hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``That can be a bad message to send to kids. The message being
said is you can have major violence and not get hurt,'' he said.
``Kids try to emulate these things and could possibly be hurting
others because they're trying out what they see.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the case in at least two cases across the country this
year, police believe.
</P>
<P>
   In August, a 4-year-old boy in Warner Robins, Ga., kicked and
beat a toddler to death while a wrestling video played on the TV,
authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We suspect the child was acting out from watching a wrestling
video,'' said Capt. Jerry Stewart of the Houston County sheriff's
office in Middle Georgia. The video was of the WWF's ``Summer
Slam'' event, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The 15-month-old died of a fractured skull and suffered liver
damage and other injuries, Stewart said.
</P>
<P>
   The 4-year-old, along with the 15-month-old and five other
youngsters, were watching the video with their baby sitter, Stewart
said. The baby sitter told police he put the 15-month-old to sleep
in another room, then left the older children watching the video
while he went to a neighborhood store for 10 to 15 minutes. The
4-year-old struck the toddler with a hard plastic toy and kicked
him off the bed, Stewart said.
</P>
<P>
   Two Atlanta psychologists said violent videos can provoke
children to violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference between fantasy and reality is not that clear
at age 4,'' said Steve Garber of the Behavioral Institute of
Atlanta. ``Children this age still believe in Santa Claus and the
Easter bunny.''
</P>
<P>
   Psychologist Cathy Blusiewicz said some wrestling programs are
powerful enough to influence even teenagers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wrestlers are portrayed as heroes if they're successful in
knocking someone out,'' Blusiewicz said. ``It's really a
glorification of violent behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   She said such programs can mislead youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't get that this is entertainment,'' she said. ``Until
puberty, and that can be age 14 or 15, children take things very
literally. They don't recognize window dressing or media hype.''
</P>
<P>
   In July, a 7-year-old Texas boy accidentally killed his
3-year-old brother after watching wrestling on television. The
older boy, asked to demonstrate what he'd done, backed up about 10
feet and ran toward a police detective who was holding a
toddler-sized doll. The boy forcefully stiff-armed the doll in the
neck, knocking it backward. The 3-year-old died of brain injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Back at Tyler Meek's house, the 8-year-old was asked if he would
ever try out any of the moves he saw on wrestling shows. His reply:
``No-o-o! That would hurt!''
</P>
<P>
   Tyler's father, Ken Grubbs, watches professional wrestling with
his son as a part of their ``together'' time. He says that because
they watch it together, he has made sure Tyler understands it's not
real.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's entertaining,'' Grubbs said. ``To me it's like a soap
opera _ one day it's one thing, and the next day it's something
else. Everyone at work talks about what they saw the night
before.''
</P>
<P>
   Grubbs says the violence is not an issue for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no guns on wrestling, nobody dies on wrestling,
except for accidents, and, unless you're watching pay-per-view, you
don't see blood,'' Grubbs said. ``There's blood, sex and violence
on the other channels.''
</P>
<P>
   Dean Valentine, head of UPN, the network that broadcasts ``WWF
Smackdown,'' and Vince McMahon, the WWF's head honcho, don't agree
with the volence label, even though the show has a TV-14 rating.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't believe there is anything sexist or violent about
WWF,'' Valentine said. ``There's no one getting knifed on WWF.
There is no gun going off.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're Sunday school compared to what action/adventure shows
do,'' McMahon said.
</P>
<P>
   But what Grubbs does have a problem with is the scantily clad
women who often accompany the wrestlers into the ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the female women come out and start taking half their
clothes off, I change the channel, because in my mind he doesn't
need to see that,'' Grubbs said.
</P>
<P>
   But as long as Tyler's wrestling viewing is supervised, Grubbs
said he will continue to let him watch it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think wrestling has dirtied his mind,'' Grubbs said.
``If you know what your kids are watching and you're watching it
with them, then there's nothing wrong with it. I don't think it's
what they watch or what they read; it's how they're raised. I take
my kids to church and I raise them right, and as long as he gets
good grades, doesn't miss school and keeps his room clean, then he
can watch wrestling and wear the shirts.''
</P>
<P>
   Professor Robinson called Grubbs' supervision policy a good
idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good practice for parents to be aware of what their
children are watching,'' he said. ``It's also beneficial to discuss
what they're seeing.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
