A8739 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-WRESTLING-GRAPEVINE-C     10-06 0485
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRESTLING-GRAPEVINE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WRESTLING GRAPEVINE
 &HT;    John Allen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mankind will appear in the Oct. 10 episode of the USA network
series ``G vs. E.'' Mankind has received a lot of extra TV time
this month, appearing in ABC's series ``Boy Meets World'' last
week.
</P>
<P>
   Changes continue with the WCW, which appears ready to break its
ties with Sturgis, S.D., for its ``Road Wild'' pay-per-view.
They're apparently not making enough money to continue having the
matches at the motorcycle rally.
</P>
<P>
   The WWF won a battle with Playboy over the use of the name Sable
and has withdrawn the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   One of the fallouts of Taz's move to the WWF is what ECW will do
for a training site for future wrestlers. Taz owns and currently
trains up-and-coming wrestlers for ECW at his facility in
Philadelphia. Chances are that ECW will continue to use the
facility. Also, Taz will be wrestling in ECW for most of the rest
of 1999 before making his switch.
</P>
<P>
   Jesse Ventura is rumored to be returning to the WWF one more
time to referee ``Wrestlemania 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   Former ECW valet Kimona Wanalaya has reportedly been looking for
work from the WWF and may show up soon. The WWF is also looking to
boost its women's division with the addition of Madusa, who was
recently released by the WCW.
</P>
<P>
   Shawn Michaels is expected to do a guest referee spot with FMW
in Japan with the WWF's blessings. But the WWF is also looking to
break its contract with the Heartbreak Kid, since they are paying
him wrestling money and he will probably never wrestle again after
back surgery this year.
</P>
<P>
   On the WWF injury front, Ken Shamrock had an MRI on his injured
neck. Shamrock actually broke his neck in high school and has
aggravated an old injury. A quick return to the ring is termed
``very questionable'' by WWF's Jim Ross. Also, the Undertaker is
expected to be out of the ring for at least six weeks to let a
groin tear heal. And Brian Christopher should return from his torn
ACL in the next month.
</P>
<P>
   Early reports are that Bill Busch has saved the WCW $4 million
since taking over the reins last month. Of course, the low ratings
of ``Fall Brawl'' won't help bring any money into the WCW coffers.
Injured Scott Steiner and AWOL Scott Hall have been put on notice.
If they don't return to the ring soon, the free meal they have been
living on will be gone. Hall should return in November when he is
to reform the Outsiders with Kevin Nash.
</P>
<P>
   Fit Finley was backstage at ``Nitro'' in Atlanta recently. He
had a brace on his leg that was injured in July and is just now
regaining some feeling below his knee. He is slated for more
surgery, but his career is in jeopardy at this point.
</P>
<P>
   Twins Ron and Don Harris, a.k.a. DOA, will return to ECW after
losing their gimmick with the WWF.
</P>
<P>
   _ John Allen
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
