<DOCNO> NYT19991006.0302 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 19:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8748 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e BC-TV-WASTELAND-REVIEW-S     10-06 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WASTELAND-REVIEW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A `WASTELAND' OF SEX, SEX AND MORE SEX 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Because we are bored and watch TV, we are eavesdropping as a
graduate student named Dawnie chats with an anthropology professor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm 25, actually 26 today, and profoundly lost as a human
being,'' Dawnie (Marisa Coughlan) tells him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've spent my entire life in school, my parents still support
me, relationships baffle me and I am acutely self-aware, to the
point where I'm clueless and slightly suicidal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And you represent today's generation,'' the prof says, more as
a comment than a question.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, absolutely.''
</P>
<P>
   This baffled, acutely self-aware, clueless and slightly suicidal
generation happens to be in control of the tube these days. Most
television shows are made for the Dawnie demographic, and that
certainly includes ``Wasteland,'' premiering Thursday night on ABC.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wasteland''? Let's scratch the ABC nomenclature and call it by
its rightful name: ``Below the Waistland.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Below the Waistland'' is about sex and single, impossibly
attractive twentysomethings in big, bad, super-glam New York City.
</P>
<P>
   The show occasionally makes head feints and little jive moves to
indicate an interest in something else, but Disney is selling sex.
Buy the large size and you can come back for a free refill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Below the Waistland'' is on opposite ``Frasier,'' in the heart
of NBC's high-flying Thursday schedule. Quick, more sex.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Williamson, who has maybe lost a little zip on his
fastball, is the show's creator and producer. Williamson's vaunted
oeuvre includes ``Dawson's Creek'' on the WB. This show presumably
represents his mature period.
</P>
<P>
   Williamson packages heavy breathing about as well as anyone this
side of the skinny old master himself, Aaron Spelling.
</P>
<P>
   And look what he's given us here: Dawnie (Coughlan), a drop-dead
gorgeous virgin; Sam (Rebecca Gayheart), a drop-dead gorgeous grunt
working in the Manhattan district attorney's office; Russell (Dan
Montgomery), a drop-dead gorgeous actor and closeted homosexual;
Vandy (Eddie Mills), a drop-dead awful musician and bartender; Ty
(Brad Rowe), Dawnie's drop-dead gorgeous ex-boyfriend, and Jesse
(Sasha Alexander), a drop-kick brassy publicist who wears a cell
phone on her ear.
</P>
<P>
   Getting right to the virgin, Williamson is obviously going to
make much of this ``Below the Waistland'' freak of nature.
</P>
<P>
   The show _ the series, actually _ begins with Dawnie being hit
upon by a self-assured jerk in a bar. She gives him a look that's
maybe a teensy bit virginal, but pretty gosh-darned knowing and not
all that baffled or clueless.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, she tells him, let's get it on. Find a bedroom, forget the
preliminaries and cut straight to the copulation, and ``we should
do it fast because I do have dinner plans.''
</P>
<P>
   Then she informs the guy that she's a virgin and, well, he'd
better be the best ever at what he's proposing to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``To put it bluntly,'' she says, ``you better rock my world.''
</P>
<P>
   He dissolves, of course, into a puddle of flaccid anxieties.
</P>
<P>
   Which isn't the case about 45 minutes later, when Lowe's Ty
wants to revive his college-years affair with Dawnie.
</P>
<P>
   At her apartment, they do a little song-and-dance routine that
involves lip-synching and pelvic thrusts. (Ah, the mating rituals
of the profoundly lost!)
</P>
<P>
   Then she's got him lying on the couch, pours wine on his bare
chest and licks it dry. (And the acutely self-aware!) Good time to
tell him she's a virgin, and she does.
</P>
<P>
   But Ty's no shrinking violator, so it's off to the bedroom.
Where they grind a bit on the bed until ... nothing happens. (And
the baffled!)
</P>
<P>
   That's pretty much your first installment of ``Below the
Waistland.'' By the November sweeps, the whole cast should be
slightly suicidal.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
