<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 19:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8750 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-SPOT-BUDGET-SUB-BOS &LR;      10-06 0568
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPOT-BUDGET-SUB-BOS </SLUG>
  
 (Adds UN-TALIBAN story)  
 For Release THURSDAY AMs, October 7, 1999  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following stories for use by
NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta  &LR; at the
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of graphics
or photos please call 212 556-4204 or -1927.
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   UN-TALIBAN (New York) _ Emboldened by Russia's new hard line
toward Osama bin Laden, the United States introduces a UN Security
Council resolution that would seize assets and ground international
flights of Afghanistan's ruling Taliban rebels until the terrorist
leader is arrested and turned over to US authorities. The
resolution, expected to pass easily, could presage more pressure on
the Taliban, including a worldwide weapons embargo, diplomats said.
By Joe Lauria. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   GALILEE-DRYUP (Capernaum, Israel) _ The sea of Galilee, a
crucial water source, has hit its lowest levels in at least 75
years, triggering a water crisis in heavily agricultural northern
Israel and raising questions about whether Israel will be able to
deliver promised water to Jordan under the developing peace plan.
By Charles M. Sennott. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON (w) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-NUCLEAR (Washington) _ Despite a feverish campaign by
the White House, a global nuclear test ban treaty appears doomed,
depriving President Clinton of a critical foreign policy win and
indicating that the chief executive's personal clout is all but
depleted. By Susan Milligan. 1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE-HEALTH-CARE (Washington) _ House debates regulation of
managed care health plans, a debate President Clinton says is
filled with ``poison pills'' inserted at the behest of the
insurance industry. By Bob Hohler. 1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-DOLE (Washington) _ Elizabeth Dole angrily denies
rumors, which her aides say are being spread by rivals Steve Forbes
and John McCain, that she is about to drop her bid for the GOP
presidential nomination. By Mary Leonard. 900 words. (w and a
coding)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HARVARD-FUNDRAISE (New York) -- Harvard University breaks all
records in higher-education philanthropy, raising a staggering
$1.25 million a day, or a total of $2.35 billion, in its five-year
fundraising campaign. By Kate Zerenike. 1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-BRADLEY (Manchester, N.H.) _ Bill Bradley,
acknowledging he has thrown ``raw meat into a cage of wolves'' by
outlining a detailed health-care plan, says Vice President Al
Gore's criticism of the proposal is ``ridiculous.'' By Michael
Kranish. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (f) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   OCEAN-SPRAY (Undated) _ Looking to rebound from a year of
troubles, Ocean Spray Cranberries is trying to stimulate flat
demand by increasing its marketing budget to about $100 million,
roughly a 15 percent increase. By Chris Reidy. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   ATT-HINDERY (Undated) _ Leo J. Hindery Jr.'s abrupt resignation
as chief of AT&AMP;T's cable TV empire hints at a few wrinkles in the
company's bet-the-farm gamble on using cable systems for phone
calls and the Internet. By Peter Howe. 900 words.
</P>
