<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-NUKE-ACCIDENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPANESE AUTHORITIES TAKE ACTION AGAINST FUEL-REPROCESSING PLANT 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By HOWARD W. FRENCH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ The police seized records Wednesday from the company
that runs the fuel-reprocessing plant where Japan's worst nuclear
accident occurred last week. Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi, vowing to
make his country ``once again feel secure,'' visited the site
later.
</P>
<P>
   As he has done before, Obuchi acknowledged his government's slow
response to the accident on Thursday in Tokaimura, 80 miles
northeast of Tokyo. More than 50 people were exposed to radiation
in the accident, in which workers who were violating standard
operating procedures set off a chain reaction.
</P>
<P>
   Two hours before Obuchi arrived by helicopter in Tokaimura, 200
police officers raided the factory and were shown on television as
they took bundles of administrative records and other documents.
The officers wore prominent yellow radiation-detecting armbands.
</P>
<P>
   Officials told the Kyodo news agency that the government had
decided to revoke the operating license of the plant, which is run
by the JCO Co., a subsidiary of the Sumitomo Metals Mining Co. JCO
offices here were also searched.
</P>
<P>
   The permanent closing would deprive Japan of 40 percent the
uranium that it uses to fuel nuclear power plants. Officials said
companies that operated nuclear reactors would be encouraged to
reach contracts with overseas suppliers to make up for the loss.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to forcing more than 300,000 people to remain
indoors overnight and causing the removal of many others, the
accident heightened fears about the accident-prone nuclear-energy
program. Pledging new regulations, Obuchi said, ``With the measures
currently in place alone, accidents like that will not be
prevented.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials said they would seek to let the government order
evacuations in nuclear accidents. The government was castigated by
local authorities, who said they were left alone in organizing the
emergency response to the crisis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
