<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUCHANAN-2000 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUCHANAN STILL UNDECIDED ABOUT REFORM PARTY 

</HEADLINE>
 -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JIM HENDERSON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Pat Buchanan, who has been flirting with the Reform
Party for several weeks, came to where that political movement was
born this week, but said Wednesday he is still undecided whether to
seek its nomination for president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been with the Republican Party through the worst crisis
of the last 30 years,'' said the former aide to Presidents Richard
Nixon and Ronald Reagan. ``That's not an easy thing to leave.''
</P>
<P>
   A failure in two previous attempts to win the Republican party's
nomination, Buchanan came to Dallas for a Tuesday night fund-raiser
and book signing Wednesday. While in Dallas, he met with Reform
Party Chairman Russell Verney to discuss a possible party switch.
</P>
<P>
   At an impromptu press conference at Borders Books, Buchanan said
Verney explained ``the bumps and hurdles'' in the road to the
party's nomination. Ross Perot, the Dallas billionaire who founded
the Reform Party and has not ruled out another run for the
presidency under its banner, did not attend the luncheon.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan said he will decide by the end of the month whether to
make the switch or run in the Republican primary, where Gov. George
W. Bush, with a campaign nest egg of more than $50 million, is
considered the front-runner.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has urged Buchanan to stay in the Republican Party. Judging
from the crowd that surrounded Buchanan in Dallas, Bush's fears
that a strong third-party candidate would siphon more votes from
the Republicans than the Democrats appeared to be well founded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sick and tired of Bush and (Vice President Al) Gore
telling me what they think I want to hear,'' said Lee Pepper, who
works for a computer data company in Dallas. He described himself
as a disgruntled Republican who would follow Buchanan to the Reform
Party.
</P>
<P>
   More than 300 people showed up to buy and have autographed
copies of Buchanan's book, ``A Republic, Not An Empire,'' and most
of those interviewed fell into the same category: Republicans who
could be swayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a problem,'' said Jim Gordon, who works for Blockbuster
Video. ``Here we are a year away from the election and George W.
Bush is already nominated.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan appeals to him, he said, because, ``He would be
president of the United States, not the world. That pretty well
sums it up.''
</P>
<P>
   The book the Buchanan supporters came to purchase spells out the
candidate's isolationist views in ways that have led some
high-ranking Republicans, such as Arizona Sen. John McCain, also a
presidential candidate, to invite him to leave the party.
</P>
<P>
   In the book, Buchanan argues that Adolf Hitler was no threat to
the United States after 1940 and had the United States and Britain
not made a commitment to Poland, ``the first great blows of
Hitler's war machine would have fallen on Stalin's empire.''
Fascism would have destroyed communism, he argues, and Americans
would have been spared World War II.
</P>
<P>
   His critics, especially Republican Party regulars, have blasted
him for those opinions.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Buchanan was invited to speak at the North Texas Oil
and Gas Association meetings in Dallas and Wichita Falls, but the
events were canceled when no one registered in Dallas and only
eight signed up in Wichita Falls. The controversial passages in the
book offended many members of the industry group, a spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   The book buyers in Dallas, however, were unmoved by them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't read it yet,'' said Fritz Schaner, ``but it sounds
like those things were taken out of context.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've read it,'' said Wes Anderson, standing in line behind
him, ``and it was taken out of context.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan reveled in the controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about his reception in Dallas, he smiled and said, ``The
attention is partly because of the controversy in the book and
partly because I may switch to the Reform Party.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
