<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-HANLEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TERRY HANLEY, 41; WAS DRUMMER FOR THE NEATS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Terry Hanley, former drummer for the Boston band the Neats, died
Monday in Colorado after a fall from his fourth-floor apartment
balcony. He was 41.
</P>
<P>
   The Neats, a new wave and later blues-based rock band, played a
prominent role in the local music scene from 1979 to 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Hanley, who relocated to the Denver area after the band's
breakup, came to Boston from Pittsburgh with friend and guitarist
Phil Caruso. They had met while attending Kent State University and
came here to study at the Boston Architecture Center in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   That education was short-lived, however, as the Neats took off
the following year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had just spoken to him three weeks ago, for the first time
in three years,'' Caruso said from Pittsburgh, where he lives and
works. ``He sounded great; he was happy with his work.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Hanley, who had worked as a cook at the Rat while in Boston,
lived in Aurora, a Denver suburb, and was working for Sky Chef, an
airline food service company.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was something about him; people really loved him, and a
lot of people watched over him,'' Caruso said. ``He was a pro and
fun to be around. He held it together, and was smart as a whip
despite (his problems).''
</P>
<P>
   Hanley had battled alcoholism for years. At the time of his
death, the percentage of alcohol in his blood was 0.243, according
to a spokeswoman for the Arapohoe County coroner's office.
</P>
<P>
   Another former bandmate, singer-guitarist Eric Martin, said:
``When he was on, he was an incredibly sharp, and such a character.
He had a lot of pain inside, he had a lot of trouble, but he never
missed a gig.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Hanley, who was divorced, leaves a son, Tom Henry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
