<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8760 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-HARVARD-FUNDRAISE-BOS     10-06 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARVARD-FUNDRAISE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARVARD FUNDRAISING SETS RECORD $1.25M-A-DAY PACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE ZERNIKE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Harvard University has broken all records in higher
education philanthropy, raking in $2.35 billion, or a staggering
$1.25 million a day, in its five-year fundraising campaign.
</P>
<P>
   With three months still to go before the campaign officially
ends, the money raised as of Wednesday exceeds the goal Harvard set
in 1994, which in itself was the most ambitious amount ever
attempted by any university, and one even many within Harvard
doubted it could meet.
</P>
<P>
   But with the money in hand, Harvard and higher education
watchers characterized this as merely the new price of maintaining
a prestigious national university, an amount top schools will be
expected to raise if they want to stay on top -- in some ways, not
so much a record as a new norm.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford was the first to raise $1 billion in 1991, but since
then, many institutions have followed suit, with Yale raising $1.6
billion, Duke now in a $1.5 billion campaign, and Columbia
University aiming for $2.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   With the public angry over rising tuitions and the federal
government cutting back on funds to university hospitals and
research, officials say universities will have to rely more and
more on fundraising _ donations at Harvard will pay for 28 percent
of the operating budget, up from 18 percent a decade ago. Schools
have become more aggressive in their fundraising methods,
consciously going after more women, younger alumni, and donors who
did not attend the school, all of whom contributed in unprecedented
and unexpected amounts to the Harvard campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's what all major universities believe they need to do, this
needs to be seen in that context,'' said President Neil L.
Rudenstine, after announcing the new record to a gathering of major
donors at the Harvard Club here. ``Given that the pace of change is
so fast, and the fields in which it is happening are so expensive,
given the needs of society and what it demands from universities
and colleges _ we're spending at unprecedented levels in higher
education. The world isn't going to stop, and the university either
has to accept the challenge or fall behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Rudenstine and others were trying Wednesday to deflect
attention from the sheer amount of money, realizing that amid
public revolt over high tuitions and salaries for star faculty,
it's not necessarily a good thing for a university to be seen as so
rich. With its endowment already at $14.4 billion, Harvard is the
second-wealthiest not-for-profit in the world, behind only the
Catholic church. And it has been criticized for not spending enough
of that endowment, especially on improvements to undergraduate
education and financial aid.
</P>
<P>
   Officials took pains to note that the largest amount of money
raised during the campaign _ $230 million _ is going toward
increasing financial aid to undergraduate and graduate students.
The money allowed Harvard to increase its average annual financial
aid package by $2,000 last year. The size of the average
scholarship grant _ money that does not have to be repaid _ has
increased from $11,700 to $17,200 because of money raised during
the campaign. The campaign has also allowed for loan forgiveness
programs for law students entering the public sector, and financial
aid for 70 percent of the masters degree candidates at the Graduate
School of Education.
</P>
<P>
   Fundraising will also go to 90 professorships across the
university's nine schools, with 25 of those slots going toward
shrinking class sizes at Harvard College. Another $65 million has
gone to renovating undergraduate dormitories, $55 million to
renovations to Widener library, and other large gifts to a new
dining hall and student commons. An additional $150 million to $200
million will be spent on new interdisciplinary science programs for
undergraduates. And Harvard has also spent $20 million in making up
federal cuts to its teaching hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   The money spent under the new campaign also reflects the new
kinds of features students applying to college are expecting, even
demanding. When the campaign started five years ago, the university
was poorly wired for the Internet, now, every course has a Web
site, and email has become a way of life.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to just send students to the library for an
assignment, we don't do that anymore,'' Rudenstine said. ``Parents
don't expect their children to come to Harvard and use the same
equipment we had five years ago. We're just expected to be in a
state of constant renewal.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not, officials insisted, simply the rich getting richer.
</P>
<P>
   ``From my perspective, I see responsibility, I don't see
wealth,'' said Jeremy Knowles, dean of the Faculty of Arts and
Sciences. ``If Harvard stood still it would remain quite impressive
for some years, but it would not be long before the edges became
frayed, before the students felt that elsewhere was more desirable,
before the faculty felt there was better opportunity for
scholarship elsewhere. Standing still is not an option.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Knowles and other senior administrators said Wednesday
they recognize that the new fundraising record will likely increase
pressure to do even more on financial aid and prevent an increase
in tuition, which is still rising faster than inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The original campaign goal of $2.1 billion was six times what
Harvard had attempted to raise in previous fundraising drives. But
it was significant in several other ways, as well.
</P>
<P>
   For one, more money came from women. In the early stages of the
campaign, officials met with women in seven cities to ask why women
did not traditionally contribute to Harvard, which has had co-ed
classrooms since World War II. Two years ago, the campaign started
a women's matching fund, setting aside $15 million to match, dollar
for dollar, any donation over $25,000 from a woman. Donors matched
that money within 60 days, and then matched an additional $4
million within another month, with 231 total women contributing
more than $25,000. Overall, 29 percent of donors were women.
</P>
<P>
   Donations poured in from the West Coast for the first time, for
a total of $190 million. Alumni abroad also contributed in
unprecedented amounts, with about 50 giving gifts of more than $1
million. The campaign included 480 gifts of more than $1 million,
making up 72 percent of the total raised.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
