<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8763 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-BRITAIN-WRECK-1007-CO     10-06 1271
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-WRECK-1007-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CAUSE OF DISASTROUS TRAIN WRECK, MAGNITUDE OF DEATH TOLL
BECOMING CLEARER: Number may climb above 70
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ As investigators tried to piece together the cause of
one of Britain's worst rail tragedies, officials said Wednesday
that the death toll may rise above 70.
</P>
<P>
   Another 100 people were reported missing late Wednesday as
officials tried to determine which commuters who started out for
London Tuesday morning never made it home. Parking lots and decks
at stops on the line from in Cheltenham to London held dozens of
cars apparently left by crash victims.
</P>
<P>
   One car near the front of the London-bound Great Western train
that may have been full of passengers was a burned out shell.
Investigators found little inside it Wednesday besides ``ashes and
debris.'' The temperature in the car was estimated to reach 1,800
degrees within seconds of the crash.
</P>
<P>
   The confirmed death count stood at 28 late Wednesday. Another 40
people remained in area hospitals, many of them suffering severe
burns.
</P>
<P>
   As police and forensic specialists continued to examine the
crash site, at least some clues to what may have caused the
accident began to surface. The outbound Thames train ran through a
red light and crossed into the path of the much bigger Greater
Western train, which had a green light, according to a statement
issued Wednesday by the two train operators as well as Railtrack,
the company that owns the track and other infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   The Thames train, westbound for nearby Bedwyn, had just pulled
out of Paddington Station when the two collided. Reports indicated
both trains were traveling about 60 mph when they collided and
burst into flames.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the train driver's union said the signal on the
Thames train's approach was notoriously difficult for train
operators to see. The train companies said they were studying the
signal. Trains have passed through the red light there at least
eight times since 1993, the union said.
</P>
<P>
   Thames Trains earlier said its driver had been working for two
months after completing 11 months of instruction.
</P>
<P>
   One of two data recorders from the Thames train was reported
found. However, officials said the Great Western train probably was
not equipped with the device known as a ``black box.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, a mechanical digger was demolishing a small
building near the site of the crash where authorities want to erect
a 1,000-ton crane to begin removing the mangled cars. The crane is
expected to begin its work Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be a long and laborious task,'' said Deputy
Assistant Police Commissioner Andy Trotter.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the destruction was so complete, officials are
struggling to determine how many people perished in the crash.
Dental records, jewelry and other personal belongings that may have
survived the crash and fire are thought to be the only way many of
the bodies will be identified.
</P>
<P>
   Police said they had confirmed that at least 70 people boarded
the trains. Additionally. another 100 people have been reported
missing by friends and relatives. A special telephone center at New
Scotland Yard is trying to determine how many of the missing were
aboard train.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said they were only just grasping the magnitude of the
accident a day after it occurred. ``Yesterday's train crash was a
terrible tragedy, the scale of which is only just becoming
apparent,'' Trotter told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   A somber British Prime Minister Tony Blair seemed moved by his
visit to victims at St. Mary's Hospital Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This clearly has been the most appallingly dreadful tragedy,''
Blair said. ``I think we have to brace ourselves now for an even
higher death toll. Our hearts and our sympathies and our
condolences go out to the families of those who have died and the
injured.''
</P>
<P>
   Prince Charles also paid a private visit to the wards of St.
Mary's. ``These terrible occasions often bring the best out of
people and I hear wonderful stories about passengers helping other
passengers, rescuing them,'' the prince of Wales told reporters as
he left the hospital. ``I have nothing but the deepest sympathies
for them all.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's accident was Britain's worst rail crash since December
1988, when three trains collided outside London's Clapham Junction,
killing 35 people.
</P>
<P>
   Early Wednesday, search teams clad in white plastic coveralls
probed the charred and mangled Great Western car that had been
shrouded by tarpaulins. The burned-out car was so damaged that
officials worried they will be unable to discern the human remains.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing inside but ash and debris,'' said Tony
Thompson, the superintendent of the British Transport Police,
during a news conference earlier Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Goodall, managing director of Demon Internet, was one of
the few to escape the Great Western car. Goodall told reporters
that as many as 50 passengers could have been in the car at the
moment of impact. He estimated that only five got out.
</P>
<P>
   Goodall said the train's operator was still semi-conscious but
``looking in a very bad way'' after the horrific collision. ``I
went over to him to try and get him out, but he was wedged in what
remained of the cab,'' he told Channel 4 News.
</P>
<P>
   On impact, the lights went out and the carriage seemed to catch
fire even before it stopped, he said. ``It was completely dark, it
was getting hot, although some of the windows had opened and there
was air coming in, the carriage was already full of smoke before I
was able to do anything.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he was ``full of sympathy'' for the families of the
dead. ``I know it was 20 minutes between my wife hearing of the
accident and hearing my voice at the end of a mobile phone,'' he
said. ``For those people who did not receive that call I have the
most extraordinary sympathy.''
</P>
<P>
   The trains collided two miles from busy Paddington Station at
8:11 a.m. (local time) Tuesday sending smoke and flames into the
sky over a west London neighborhood. The accident occurred on the
same rail line as 1997 crash that killed seven, and prompted
concerns about the safety of the city's aging rail system.
</P>
<P>
   Train drivers on Wednesday threatened a possible strike unless
rail companies respond positively within seven days to demands for
a package of improved safety measures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not tolerate any more unsafe working practices and we
will not tolerate our members, or the public, being put at risk,''
said Mick Rix, a leader or the drivers' union. ``Failure to respond
within seven days will bring the train companies into dispute with
this union.''
</P>
<P>
   The union is demanding the installation nationwide of a
fail-safe automatic train protection system as well as in-cab
radios. The sophisticated, but expensive, automatic train
protection system is fitted on only a few British lines. Its
network-wide installation could cost as much as $1.6 billion, the
primary obstacle to its construction.
</P>
<P>
   Among the flowers left on a rail bridge overlooking the scene of
the disaster was a bouquet bearing a card dedicated to one of the
engineers. It began ``For Dear Brian,'' and was signed, ``God bless
you, Gerald and Maureen.''
</P>
<P>
   Further, it read: ``Today is the saddest day of my life when my
brother was taken away from us. . . . My only wish is that he never
suffered.''
</P>
<P>
   The engineer's last name has not yet been released by the rail
company because his body has not been officially identified.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
