<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8764 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-COELHO06-COX     10-06 0475
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COELHO06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    GORE CAMPAIGN CHAIRMAN REPAYS CONTROVERSIAL LOAN
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore's campaign chairman Tony
Coelho wired a Portuguese bank $119,000 to pay off a personal loan
connected to his controversial role in last year's world's fair,
his lawyer said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Coelho repaid the balance of the original $300,000 loan ``out of
his own personal funds,'' his attorney Stanley Brand said.
</P>
<P>
   The funds were sent after publication of a U.S. State Department
inspector general report which sharply questioned lavish spending
and improper financial arrangements made by Coelho, who served as
U.S. commissioner general at the Lisbon, Portugal, Expo '98.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the U.S. participation, Coelho had taken out a loan
from the Banco Espirito Santo to pay for a stainless steel and
blue-tile wave-shaped sculpture to commemorate
Portuguese-Americans. Coelho founded the Luso American Wave
Foundation to raise the funds to repay the loan. Donors were
promised that their names would be inscribed on the sculpture.
</P>
<P>
   The inspector general report disclosed last weekend that the
loan was not yet repaid and that the government might be held
liable if it was unpaid.
</P>
<P>
   The loan has been criticized by the private watchdog group, the
Center for Public Integrity, which first announced that Coelho had
not listed the liability on his June 1998 public financial
disclosure form required for his temporary, non-paid post for the
world's fair.
</P>
<P>
   Coelho's disclosure form, which indicated an income of $1.7
million, should have listed the loan if it was made by May 10 of
that year to comply with federal ethics law.
</P>
<P>
   Brand, who had earlier confirmed that Coelho owed $109,000 on
the loan, said he had been unable to obtain his client's loan
documents and could not confirm details, including the date on the
bank note. The State Department's inspector general office also
declined Wednesday to give the date, although its audit report
indicates that the bank forgave a $10,000 interest payment as of
June 23.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Center for Public Ethics said Wednesday that it
had dispatched an emissary to inspect the ``wave'' sculpture, which
is still standing in Lisbon, and the inspection revealed that no
names had been inscribed on it. An official Internet site for Expo
'98 (http://www.usexpo98.org) continues to post a notice inviting
the public to join the foundation and make donations.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation has apparently gone out of business. The
toll-free number offered on the Internet has been transferred to a
photographer's office. Efforts to reach the foundation officers on
Wednesday evening were unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-99 1930EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991006.0315 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 19:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8765 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-GALILEE-DRYUP-BOS &LR;      10-06 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GALILEE-DRYUP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALILEE DRIES UP; ISRAELI AGRICULTURE HIT HARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPERNAUM, Israel _ On the bone-dry banks of the Galilee,
ancient stones of a harbor believed to date to the time of Jesus
have surfaced as a result of record low water levels brought on by
one of the worst droughts in recent history.
</P>
<P>
   The remnants of what was an ancient fishing port may prove not
only a significant finding for historians and archeologists, but
for Israeli water experts as well. Some experts see it as proof
that the Galilee once held much less water than it does today.
</P>
<P>
   That belief was part of a calculated risk by Israeli water
commissioner Meir Ben Meir to continue pumping from the lake even
after it had receded past the ``red line'' _ a water level at which
it has long been believed the lake could begin to suffer
irreversible ecological damage. On Tuesday, the fresh-water lake
hit its lowest level since records were first kept in the early
1920s, according to Ben &UR;  &LR; Meir.
</P>
<P>
   ``No damage,'' he insisted, ``has been done to the lake so
far.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the discovery of the ancient harbor, he added,
``These finds show that already four times during the last 2,000
years the level of the lake was lower than now. The problem is that
in hydrology the only data you have is from the past, there is no
data about the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Israeli environmentalists fear the continued siphoning of
the Galilee could lead to ecological disaster. They say the
evidence of the ancient ports is a shaky argument in favor of
lowering the water levels beyond the red line established about 30
years ago by Israel's top hydrologists and scientists.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are beginning to take serious risks,'' said Hillel
Shuval, a professor of environmental studies at Hebrew University
of Jerusalem. ``There are salt water springs under the lake, and if
the level goes too low it could altar the salinity of the lake. The
potential is there for irreversable damage to the lake and its
ecology, so they should tread very lightly.''
</P>
<P>
   Israel has cut back dramatically on the amount of water it has
pumped from the Galilee this year. Normally, 200 million cubic
meters a year are pumped from the lake. But this year Israel has
pumped approximately 60 million cubic meters, a conservation effort
that has hit the politically powerful Israeli agricultural sector
hard.
</P>
<P>
   In a region where scarce water resources form the undercurrent
of politics, the precipitous drop of the Galilee's water line is
also straining Israeli-Jordanian relations. During the long summer
drought, Jordan protested Israel's plan to cut back on the water
quota for Jordan under the terms of the 1994 peace agreement signed
by the two countries.
</P>
<P>
   In that agreement, Israel committed to supplying 50 million
cubic meters per year of the Galilee's water to Jordan. The
document made no provision for years of drought. But three months
ago Israel announced it would only pump approximately 30 million
cubic meters, citing the drought as a reason. The Jordanians are
insisting that the Israelis live up to the agreement, and at least
for now Israeli officials privately say they will do their best to
provide the remaining 20 million cubic meters of water sometime
after the rainy season replenishes the lake. But they are not
making any promises.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, the Hebrew-language newspaper Ha'aretz cautioned
against violating the agreement with Jordan because of the
political discord it will engender at a fragile moment in the peace
process. In an editorial, the newspaper also said the dangerously
low levels of the lake highlighted the need for a regional plan for
water conservation in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   But for the historians and archeologists, the drought has
produced a kind of bitter fruit, revealing new evidence of the
ancient ports.
</P>
<P>
   One of the key findings is in Capernaum on the northern shore of
the Galilee. There, on land once covered water, lay a parched plain
of cracked mud and rocks. And on this dried bank, near the holy
site where it is believed Jesus had his ministry for many years, is
an outcropping of rocks that once formed a foundation for a harbor.
</P>
<P>
   Mendel Nun, who has lived on the lake for 60 years and has
become its resident historian, revealed the findings in the August
issue of the Biblical Archaeological Review.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always knew the harbors must be there,'' Nun wrote, ``but
we had no idea we would find so many remains.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-99 1931EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991006.0316 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8766 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-MARTIN-GUERRE-MUSICAL     10-06 1169
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARTIN-GUERRE-MUSICAL-3TAKES-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN THE COMMERCIAL THEATER MOVES IN ON NONPROFITS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 10) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BRUCE WEBER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ ``Martin Guerre,'' the British musical that has
returned more often than, well, Martin Guerre, finally had its
American premiere here on Sept. 29. It was the fourth opening for
the show, counting its first one in London's West End in 1996, and
a climactic night for Alain Boublil and Claude-Michel Schonberg,
who first brought the idea to the producer Cameron Mackintosh a
full seven years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been as long as it took Martin Guerre to go to war and
come back,'' said Schonberg, who wrote the score. The show _ based
on the often-told true story of the 16th-century Frenchman who,
left for dead on the battlefield, returns home to find his identity
has been assumed by his friend and fellow soldier _ has been
streamlined, reordered and rewritten by its persistent creators.
Forty percent of the current material was not in the original,
Mackintosh said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's it,'' said Boublil, co-writer of the book and lyrics.
``That's the show they get.'' The creators sounded relieved, but in
the theater world ``Martin Guerre'' has been perceived as something
of an obsession for its legendary producer. Mackintosh, who, as the
man behind the musicals ``Cats,'' ``The Phantom of the Opera,''
``Les Miserables'' and ``Miss Saigon'' (the last two written by
Boublil and Schonberg), is perhaps the world's most successful
theater producer. ``Martin Guerre'' has yet to garner the same
acclaim; it was revised and re-opened in mid-run in London, then
revamped and re-opened at the Yorkshire Playhouse in Leeds.
</P>
<P>
   That version, the first to be praised by critics, is the one
Mackintosh has brought here to the venerable Guthrie Theater, one
of the nation's leading nonprofit houses, where the opening of
``Martin Guerre'' is a striking anomaly. Even though the show has
been trimmed down considerably, this is a theater that has
historically focused on classic drama on its thrust stage.
</P>
<P>
   With ``Martin Guerre,'' the Guthrie has joined the lengthening
list of nonprofit regional theaters to collaborate on expensive
productions with commercial producers. Never in its 36-year history
has the theater given its subscribers a show with the glamour and
extravagance of this one.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's really blowing our audiences away,'' said David
Hawkanson, the Guthrie's managing director, ``is that it's like
having a 100-piece orchestra in your den.''
</P>
<P>
   But does a 100-piece orchestra belong in your den? The arrival
of ``Martin Guerre'' has further obscured the increasingly murky
distinction between nonprofit and commercial theater enterprises
and stirs, with particular vigor, the debate over whether
collaborations between the two entities are appropriate or even
desirable.
</P>
<P>
   The show is headed for Broadway in the spring, though it does
not yet have a theater, which is one reason the top officers of the
Shubert Organization and Jujamcyn Theaters, leading theater owners
in New York, made the trip out here for opening night.
</P>
<P>
   It will be the second musical Mackintosh brings to Broadway this
season: the Stephen Sondheim revue, ``Putting It Together,'' which
he has been nurturing since 1991, is to open next month at the
Ethel Barrymore Theater, starring Carol Burnett, in an incarnation
that was developed in collaboration with the Mark Taper Forum, the
nonprofit house in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over here, this seems to be my year for nonprofit theater,''
said Mackintosh, still chubbily boyish at 52, explaining that the
simultaneous arrival of the two shows is only a coincidence, and
that his partnerships with nonprofits are nothing unusual for him;
he has been working with state-subsidized theaters in England for
more than two decades.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why he has clung so tenaciously to ``Martin Guerre,'' he
responded with only a hint of exasperation. ``My tenacity with this
show is no different than my tenacity with any show,'' he said.
``I'll keep going until I feel there's no more to be done. It's
just that `Martin Guerre' had to be developed in the public eye.
The fact of the matter was the show I put on in London wasn't
finished. It was still a work in progress, and at every stage it
has gotten better. People forget that `The Music Man' took 12 years
to get together. `Guys and Dolls' had 10 or 12 different
librettos.''
</P>
<P>
   Though economy-size by comparison to ``Ragtime'' and ``The Lion
King,'' Broadway's current eight-figure extravaganzas, and even by
Mackintosh's own long-running hits, ``Martin Guerre,'' with a cast
of 24 and a set designed by John Napier (who landed the helicopter
onstage in ``Miss Saigon''), cost $2.1 million to stage here. That
is about two and a half times the budget of an average Guthrie
show. Mackintosh paid for just over half.
</P>
<P>
   ``Martin Guerre,'' with Hugh Panaro in the title role, received
a mostly positive review in The Minneapolis Star-Tribune (``Though
the musical will engage the intellect only slightly, it speaks
loudly, earnestly and passionately to the heart'') and a more
skeptical one in Variety. But in any case, ticket sales have been
brisk for its seven-week run at the Guthrie, where the excitement
of a Broadway-style production has seemingly justified the
financial risk.
</P>
<P>
   And so, the argument goes, collaborations such as this one work
to the benefit of both partners. The economics of mounting a
musical for Broadway are so forbidding that for a commercial
producer, trying out a show in a nonprofit house where costs are
more modest is a way of preparing it for the make or break scrutiny
of critics in New York and audiences who will judge it with their
wallets.
</P>
<P>
   ``That seems to be the only way to go,'' said Hal Luftig, a
producer working on a musical version of the film ``Thoroughly
Modern Millie.'' ``We're going to try and do what Cameron is doing,
start it in a regional house.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the resources a commercial producer can
provide for a nonprofit enable the theater to put on a more
elaborate production, giving its local audience a taste of opulent
show business that the theater could otherwise not afford. And
bigger, it need be said, does sometimes mean better.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the participating theater generally shares in
profits gleaned by the show after it moves on, a powerful
inducement for institutions that are perennially scratching for
funds.
</P>
<P>
   In the last decade or so, the new musicals ``Big River'' and
``The Who's Tommy'' and the revival of ``How to Succeed in Business
Without Really Trying'' all had successful premieres at the La
Jolla Playhouse in California, partly financed by commercial
producers, before their turns on Broadway. The new musical ``Jane
Eyre'' recently completed its run there, selling out 62
performances, and its producers are currently seeking additional
financing _ and a theater _ to open it in New York.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, such collaborations strike many as
antithetical _ or at least threatening _ to the very nature of
regional nonprofit theater, a movement that took hold nationally in
the 1950s and 1960s largely as a revolt against the commercially
driven enterprise that American theater art, as exemplified by
Broadway, had become. (The Guthrie, founded by the director Tyrone
Guthrie in 1963, was among the movement's seminal institutions.)
</P>
<P>
   These days, few in the theater object to collaborations on
principle (current economics make it difficult to support such
rigid church-and-state separation), but the issue remains one of
control. When a commercial producer with an eye on profit-making
contributes to a production in a nonprofit house, who is making the
artistic decisions? Whose interests are a priority? The theater,
which is devoted to its local audience and which has a history and
an artistic vision to uphold? Or the commercial producer, whose
main concern is generating momentum for a long run elsewhere?
</P>
<P>
   ``The minute you get somebody else calling the shots about how
the work evolves, somebody with an eye on the brass ring, you've
molested the enterprise,'' said Zelda Fichandler, the founding
director of Arena Stage in Washington and its artistic director
from 1950 to 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Control is always a difficult proposition to sort out, made more
complicated recently as commercial partners have escalated their
financial involvement. Five years ago, Lincoln Center Theater put
on a revival of ``Carousel'' with Mackintosh; last year it staged
the new musical ``Parade,'' with Livent, the Canadian company then
being run by Garth Drabinsky, Mackintosh's equal in showmanship if
not financial acumen. (Livent went bankrupt just before the opening
of ``Parade,'' embroiling Drabinsky in allegations of fiscal
misdeeds. ``Carousel'' was originally at the Royal National Theater
in London, a nonprofit theater; Mackintosh maintained the
commercial rights.)
</P>
<P>
   Both shows were produced at Lincoln Center for about $5 million
apiece, and the collaborators split the costs. Contractually, in
both cases, said Bernard Gersten, the theater's executive producer,
``we were in control of the production.'' But in both cases, the
directors (Nicholas Hytner and Harold Prince, respectively) were
chosen and the productions designed and developed by the commercial
partner. None of those involved are known as shrinking violets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who's in control on paper is clear and who's in control in
fact is not so clear,'' Gersten said. ``That's when the 400-pound
gorillas come into play.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, when the Disney company opened its new musical,
``Elaborate Lives: The Legend of Aida,'' at the Alliance Theater
Company in Atlanta, Alliance's artistic director, Kenny Leon, in
two separate interviews with The New York Times, said, first, that
he had no influence over the production, and then that he did.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the actual case, the initial production was a critical
failure but, for Alliance, a financial success, and it maintains a
share of the show, which, in a revised incarnation (it is now
called simply ``Aida''), is scheduled to open at a commercial
theater in Chicago in December, before moving to Broadway in
February.
</P>
<P>
   For years, commercial theater and nonprofit theater existed in
entirely separate orbits. That began to change in 1967, when Arena
Stage in Washington put on ``The Great White Hope'' and the
producer Herman Levin bought the rights from the playwright Howard
Sackler and moved the production _ its stars James Earl Jones and
Jane Alexander included _ to Broadway the following year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It changed the American theater because it changed the flow of
material,'' said Ms. Fichandler, who now heads the graduate acting
department at New York University's Tisch School of the Arts. ``Up
until that time,'' she said of regional theaters, ``we were little
outposts.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Fichandler said, it was such a new and startling development
that she neglected to maintain any rights to the show, the largest
the Arena had ever put on up to that point. As a result, Arena lost
money on its own production and received nothing from the show's
long run on Broadway. In retrospect, she said, she was terribly
naive. ``My focus was so on the thing itself that I hadn't attended
to the theater properly,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the move of ``The Great White Hope,'' the New York
Shakespeare Festival accepted $50,000 from the producer Michael
Butler and moved its production of ``Hair'' to a disco near Times
Square; Butler subsequently moved the show to Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   In 1971, the Shakespeare Festival entered the commercial arena
on its own, moving its musical version of ``Two Gentlemen of
Verona'' from Central Park to the St. James Theater on Broadway.
Most famously, the festival produced ``A Chorus Line,'' whose
15-year Broadway run, ending in 1990, poured a nearly $39 million
bounty into the theater's coffers, supporting less commercially
viable works on its downtown stages for years and providing a
pot-of-gold model for nonprofit theaters across the country.
</P>
<P>
   A recent example, ``The Civil War,'' the Frank Wildhorn musical
that flopped on Broadway last season, was developed by the Alley
Theater in Houston (with financial help from Pace Theatricals, the
tour-organizing company). Productions of the show in New York and
on the road were already part of the plan during development.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two decades, several varieties of theatrical
partnerships have evolved; commercial producers keep close tabs on
work being developed in regional theaters (as they do on shows in
London), with an eye toward moving them. In recent years, such
Tony-winning plays as ``Angels in America,'' ``The Kentucky Cycle''
and ``Death of a Salesman'' were developed in one or more regional
theaters before producers attempted to mount them commercially.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the most rewarding way, and the most creative,'' said
Gordon Davidson, the artistic director of the Mark Taper Forum in
Los Angeles, which helped develop ``Angels in America'' and ``The
Kentucky Cycle.''
</P>
<P>
   But that has rarely happened with musicals because they are
often too expensive for regional theaters to develop on their own.
Musicals have also grown too expensive for commercial producers to
finance alone; the old system of getting a show on its feet in
Boston or New Haven in a pre-Broadway run has almost entirely
disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the most common strategy today makes use of what is
known as ``enhancement money''; that is, a commercial producer
helps finance a musical in a regional house in exchange for the
rights to produce it when the local run is complete.
</P>
<P>
   The amount of influence exerted by the commercial partner over
the theater's production is, at that point, up for grabs. Or, put
more kindly, a matter for the partnership to work out. ``It's not
the dollar amount of the enhancement that determines the policies
behind doing these productions,'' said Terrence Dwyer, the managing
director of the La Jolla Playhouse, who said the enhancement money
the theater had received ranged between $400,000 and $1 million,
but was never more than half of a show's total cost. ``Whether it's
$50 or $2 million is irrelevant. The key thing is, are
not-for-profits doing these things for the right reasons? Do they
serve your audience and your mission? And do you maintain the
character and the integrity of the institution during the
process?''
</P>
<P>
   In the case of ``Martin Guerre,'' both Mackintosh and the
theater's artistic director, Joe Dowling, say the show and the
theater are a good match. The Guthrie, which has an auditorium
seating 1,300 and about 30,000 subscribers, is on the verge of a
capital campaign for a new building that would house three
different auditoriums and allow the theater to expand its mandate
by developing new works and engaging more frequently in
co-productions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been expanding our programming the last two or three
years,'' said Dowling, the former head of the Abbey Theater in
Dublin who took over in 1996 from the Guthrie's previous artistic
director Garland Wright, who died last year. ``I've been accused of
being populist, and I say, `Guilty as charged.' But no one's going
to tell me that Cameron lacks esthetic values, and the notion that
we're selling out to commerce is a faulty one. If Boublil and
Schonberg had offered me their new musical, would I have taken it?
Of course. Could we have afforded it on our own? No.''
</P>
<P>
   But that's not the entire story. At the show's last major
opening in England, at the Yorkshire Playhouse, a nonprofit theater
in Leeds (``If there's a British equivalent to the Guthrie, that's
it,'' Dowling said), critics admired it as a triumphant turnaround
from the show that many had judged bloated and confusing in London.
Trimmed down, rewritten, its story clarified and songs replaced, it
had also been completely restaged by two young Irishmen, Conall
Morrison, the director, and David Bolger, the choreographer.
</P>
<P>
   Dowling had worked with Morrison in Dublin. ``When I heard
Cameron was going to do another `Martin Guerre' with those two
guys, I was very excited,'' Dowling said. ``I immediately called
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Mackintosh said he was attracted to the Guthrie because of its
resemblance to the theater in Leeds and because he felt the
Minneapolis audience would be appreciative; the Guthrie, after all,
he said, attracts theatergoers from hundreds of miles around. And
though staging the show in a nonprofit house keeps costs down (by
union contract, actors are paid less in nonprofit houses than in
commercial ones), it isn't exactly a money-saving venture for him.
</P>
<P>
   Before Broadway, the show will be moving from Minneapolis to
engagements in Detroit, Washington, Seattle and Los Angeles, and it
will have to be restaged, at a cost of some $2 million, Mackintosh
estimated, for the proscenium houses there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe really wanted to do this,'' Mackintosh said. ``Even before
he saw it. He smelled it would be good for his theater. It's a
cousin of `The Crucible,' a cousin of Shakespeare. And it has the
added bonus of a really terrific score. Why shouldn't it be on a
stage like this?''
</P>
<P>
   The most complicated hardware for the set _ which includes a
steel wall resembling wood that seems, at one point, to be consumed
by fire _ and the Broadway-style lighting and sound machinery were
brought over from England. The Guthrie made the costumes and the
props and participated in casting.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been some tensions,'' Dowling said, ``in terms of
what we can afford. Their natural instinct is to add people and
ours is to cut them. They think of the long-term life of the work
and we're focused on the next seven weeks. There's a difference in
culture there. But there's been no difference in how we approach
the work.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Mackintosh added, the issue over whether such
collaborations are appropriate is an artificial and particularly
American one. ``I just think there's so little good material out
there anyway,'' he said, ``that the best people, in whatever
sphere, have to get together to put on a show in the best possible
circumstances.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
