<HEADER>
A8770 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-KOCH-TRIAL07-COX     10-06 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOCH-TRIAL07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Oil measurements debated at Koch trial
 &HT;    By Fred Cohen
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TULSA, Okla. _ Both sides expressed optimism Wednesday as
testimony continued in U.S. District Court in William Koch's
multimillion dollar case against the giant oil company run by two
of his brothers.
</P>
<P>
   Koch alleges Wichita, Kan.-based Koch Industries systematically
shortchanged the federal government and Indian tribes of royalties
by failing to pay for all the oil it bought from producers with
leases on their land.
</P>
<P>
   William, the only Koch brother at the trial, said Wednesday
morning he thought the case was going ``exceptionally well'' and
that the company's own documents were the strongest evidence
against it.
</P>
<P>
   The company, in a written statement, said, ``We categorically
deny that the thousands of people who measured oil for Koch were
involved in a scheme to steal oil. The fact is that our record of
measurement accuracy was very good _ within fractions of a percent
_ and our customers chose us, over and over, despite the many other
options open to them and even after Bill (William) Koch first began
making these claims 11 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   In the early stages of a trial now expected to last eight to 12
weeks, the six jurors and two alternates have heard several former
Koch employees say they routinely put down altered measurements on
paperwork from which producers were paid.
</P>
<P>
   Continuation of the testimony of Jack Crossen took up most of
the morning. Company lawyers showed him _ and the jury _ numerous
``run tickets'' that he had not altered in ways he had said he
routinely did. Run tickets are the paperwork showing the
measurements used in calculating the amount of oil in a tank.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for William Koch then introduced other run tickets that
had been altered according to what Crossen had said was his
standard procedure.
</P>
<P>
   Two other former ``gaugers'' _ workers who take the measurements
of oil in a tank for the buyer _ also said they routinely altered
run tickets for Koch Industries. But their testimony was not
entirely favorable to William Koch.
</P>
<P>
   Although Koch has alleged that the policy of cheating sellers
was known at all levels of the company, two former gaugers for Koch
Industries said they were told to alter measurements by other
gaugers. In some cases, the specific instructions were
inconsistent.
</P>
<P>
   Both former employees said they were unaware of any written
company policy and neither had received any formal training from
the company on how to conduct and record measurements during the
time in question.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, both of the other witnesses said they had
worked as gaugers for other oil companies, which did not require
them to record adjusted measurements on their run slips. Koch
Industries says it is sometimes necessary to adjust for variables
to avoid paying for more oil than it receives.
</P>
<P>
   Under cross-examination by Koch Industries lawyer Mark Grossman
of Tulsa, Crossen said he sometimes bought oil kept in tanks with
excessive sediment or other problems to accommodate producers and
prevent them from selling their oil to other companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you write down measurements exactly as you observe them (in
such cases), Koch is going to lose, aren't they?'' Grossman asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``They could, yes,'' Crossen replied.
</P>
<P>
   William Koch, who brought the case on behalf of the United
States of America under a whistle-blower law, denied he is out to
ruin Koch Industries. He has sued the company numerous times since
he was fired after trying to take over its leadership from his
brother Charles in 1980. William Koch's twin brother David of Palm
Beach and New York is the company's executive vice president.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of history behind this case and the parties
involved,'' the company's statement said, ``but it's now up to a
court and a jury to evaluate the facts here. And when that's said
and done, we're confident our integrity will be affirmed.''
</P>
<P>
   William Koch called company executives ``crooks,'' but said the
litigation ``is a small part of my life.'' With a younger wife, six
children and his own business, he said, ``I've got my hands full in
Palm Beach.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
