<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-HEALTH-CARE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE OKS HEALTH INSURANCE TAX-BREAK MEASURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House, opening a fractious debate over the
future of the nation's health care system, Wednesday passed a
measure Republican leaders said would expand access to medical
coverage for 44 million uninsured individuals. President Clinton
denounced the bill as part of an ``11th-hour gimmick'' to kill
patients' rights legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Amid a massive lobbying and advertising blitz, the House voted
227-205 to provide $48 billion over 10 years in new
health-insurance tax breaks for several categories of consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The action came on the eve of Thursday's scheduled vote on a
sweeping patients' rights bill that would broadly expand
regulations on health maintenance organizations and grant patients
the new right to sue their providers for damages resulting from
poor care or denied treatment.
</P>
<P>
   GOP leaders, under fire for opposing the patients' rights
measure, said the tax breaks would make medical coverage more
affordable and accessible without driving up costs by increasing
patients' rights to sue their providers.
</P>
<P>
   With polls ranking health care as a top concern among voters,
both parties scrambled for the high ground in the volatile buildup
to Thursday's showdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans want to spend more time in ambulances and less time
with ambulance chasers,'' said Representative Bill Archer, a Texas
Republican who is chairman of the House Ways and Means Committee,
on the House floor. ``And they want to spend more time in front of
doctors and not in front of judges.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, backed by a bipartisan group of House members pressing
for the broader patients' rights bill, said the tax-break measure
was part of an effort by GOP leaders and insurance lobbyists to
devise ``some procedural way to tie everything up in knots'' and
kill the patients' rights bill.
</P>
<P>
   Under rules crafted by Republican leaders, the patients' rights
bill, if it passes Thursday, would be appended to the tax-break
measure. The package then would be used by House negotiators in a
conference with the Senate to produce final legislation to send to
the White House.
</P>
<P>
   But the tax-break bill proposes no offsets for its $48 billion
cost, which, critics said, would prompt the Senate to reject the
entire package out of fear they would need to pay for the breaks
with Social Security funds. The Senate has passed a version of the
patients' rights bill that would give consumers the right to sue if
they are covered by federal programs but not HMOs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a travesty,'' Clinton said of the House action. ``It's
the sort of thing they did to kill common-sense gun legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the lack of offsets in the tax-break bill could drain
support from Democrats for the patients' rights bill, seriously
jeopardizing its chances of passing the House.
</P>
<P>
   Under the GOP-sponsored rules, the patients' rights measure also
would die if any of three less sweeping substitute measures
receives more support in preliminary votes Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The votes are not going to be there to pass this,'' warned
Representative Richard A. Gephardt of Missouri, the House
Democratic leader, of the patients' rights bill.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP tax-break measure would provide full deductions for
taxpayers who pay more than 50 percent of their health insurance
and long-term care premiums. The self-employed would receive full
deductions for health insurance in 2001, two years earlier than
current law allows. And individuals who care for elderly family
members in their homes would receive an additional exemption of
$2,750.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the proposal would expand medical savings accounts
and permit small businesses to buy health insurance under federal
rules rather than state regulations. Large businesses already are
permitted to avoid the state regulations.
</P>
<P>
   House Democrats, citing a Joint Tax Committee study requested by
Senator Edward M. Kennedy, also said the $48 billion measure would
add only 160,000 families to the ranks of the insured, at an
average annual cost of $30,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to talk about wasting money, trust the Republicans to
do it,'' said Representative Pete Stark, a California Democrat and
senior member of the House Ways and Means Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Stark and others also argued that the proposed tax breaks would
favor ``the wealthy and the healthy'' at the expense of the poor.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders disputed the assertions and said the bill
would achieve its purpose of broadening access to health care in an
era when the number of uninsured continues to grow despite a
booming economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anybody says that is unfair, then they have a warped sense
of what's fair in this country,'' said Representative Porter J.
Goss, a Florida Republican who is a senor member of the House Rules
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Only five Republicans opposed the measure Wednesday, including
two physicians who played key roles in pressuring GOP leaders to
permit a vote on the patients' rights bill: Representatives Charlie
Norwood of Georgia and Greg Ganske of Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Every New England Republican voted for the tax-break measure, as
did all but one Democrat from the region: Representative James H.
Maloney of Connecticut. In all, 11 Democrats voted for the
GOP-sponsored measure.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
