<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-NUCLEAR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON APPEARS ABOUT TO LOSE NUCLEAR TEST-BAN EFFORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Despite a feverish campaign by the White House, a
global nuclear test-ban treaty appears doomed, depriving President
Clinton of a critical success on a foreign policy issue he had
hoped would highlight his presidential legacy.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear Wednesday whether the treaty would go down with a
bang _ meaning the Senate would vote it down on the floor next week
_ or a whimper, with the Senate agreeing to delay the vote on the
condition Clinton not raise it again before he leaves office.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, both opponents and backers of the test ban agree,
the president has almost certainly lost the fight to ratify the
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty, a document he called ``the
longest-sought, hardest fought prize in arms control history'' when
he picked up a pen used by President John F. Kennedy and signed the
treaty three years ago at the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes him look weak to the rest of the world. It makes him
look like he is not really in charge of US foreign policy,'' said
Lawrence Korb, a former Reagan administration official who is now a
scholar with the New York-based Council on Foreign Relations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really important for Clinton's foreign policy legacy that
he gets the test ban treaty passed,'' said Douglas Brinkley, a
professor of history and director of the Eisenhower Center at the
University of New Orleans. The failure to get the 67 Senate votes
needed to ratify the treaty ``really shows he is a complete
lame-duck president,'' Brinkley said.
</P>
<P>
   The treaty, which would ban underground and above-ground nuclear
wepoans testing, would not damage the United States strategically,
supporters say, since the nation already operates under a voluntary
1992 moritorium on testing.
</P>
<P>
   The White House hopes that US ratification of the treaty would
encourage other nations to sign it. But failing to OK the document
would deprive the United States of moral authority to complain if
other countries conduct nuclear testing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would have something of a no-man's land,'' Defense
Secretary William S. Cohen, the only Republican cabinet member,
told the Senate Armed Services Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the treaty worry that current technology is not
sophisticated enough to monitor other nations' compliance with the
treaty.
</P>
<P>
   But a substantial part of the fight against the treaty is
political, Democrats on Capitol Hill say, because Senate
Republicans are determined to deprive the president of any foreign
policy success in his final months in office.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of Republicans just want to embarrass Clinton,''
Brinkley said.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Republicans, ``some of them have legitimate kinds of
concerns, but others would deny the president a success on the
agreement,'' said Senator Edward M. Kennedy, a member of the Armed
Services Committee. Kennedy and Senator John F. Kerry, both
Democrats, back the treaty.
</P>
<P>
   A defeat on the Senate floor would be especially dramatic,
marking the first time a foreign policy treaty was killed since the
League of Nations was voted down during the Woodrow Wilson
administration.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Republican leaders, whom the White House accused of
rushing the vote to the floor, suggested they would cancel the
vote, but only if Clinton promised not to bring it up again during
his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, wisdom dictates that we pull back and give this
more careful scrutiny,'' said Senator Jack Reed, a Rhode Island
Democrat who supports the treaty. ``We're now looking for a
face-saving solution. It's intensely partisan. . . . The
Republicans' hope is to deny the president any kind of credible
success on issues important to the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Senate majority leader Trent Lott, John
Czwartacki, said, ``The president has been looking for a way out.
There's an easy way, and a hard way.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans were not willing to budge on the demand that
Clinton pass the issue on to the next president, Czwartacki said,
but Senate Democrats were still hopeful they could convince the GOP
to hold a vote next year.
</P>
<P>
   The White House continued its aggressive lobbying campaign.
Cohen called Republican senators at home, and Secretary of State
Madeleine K. Albright put in a call to wavering Senator Olympia
Snowe, Republican of Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton hosted a dinner for on-the-fence senators at the White
House Tuesday night, and gathered prominent scientists there to
argue the treaty's merits.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton indicated he would be willing to accept some delay in
the vote but vowed to continue fighting for ratification if the
vote goes ahead as scheduled, next Tuesday or Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``After two long years of inaction, one week is very little time
for considered action,'' Clinton told reporters in the Rose Garden,
referring to the two years the treaty has been languishing in the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   But Senate Armed Services Committee Chairman Jesse Helms,
Republican of North Carolina, said, ``We're ready to vote'' and
insisted Clinton not be given extra time to lobby for ratification.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats are ``trying to dictate the terms of their own
surrender,'' Helms said.
</P>
<P>
   A delay until the next administration would still be a loss for
Clinton. With post-impeachment animosity still strong between the
White House and congressional Republicans, it is not likely,
political analysts say, that Clinton will be able to make his mark
with a domestic policy initiative.
</P>
<P>
   A failure to pass the treaty ``sort of puts the period at the
end of the foreign policy sentence of Clinton's history,'' said Dan
Doure, deputy director of political and military studies at the
Center for Strategic and International Studies.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a few foreign policy successes, Doure said, ``It's been
a dramatic failure.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
