<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8775 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-NFL-REACTION-HNS &LR;      10-06 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-REACTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL OWNERS SING PRAISES OF NEW HOUSTON OWNER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN McCLAIN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ After voting 29-0-2 to award the 32nd franchise to
Houston, NFL owners talked about how impressed they were with the
$700 million expansion fee, the solid financial plan for what will
be the league's only retractable-roof stadium, the $195 million in
public money, and the combined efforts of the city's political and
business leaders.
</P>
<P>
   But every owner agreed that the most impressive thing about
Houston's expansion bid was owner Bob McNair, who showed remarkable
patience and perseverance during a process that was often
frustrating and confusing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me tell you how I feel about Bob,'' said Dallas Cowboys
owner Jerry Jones, who lobbied hard to get the expansion franchise
for Houston. ``I would have carried him piggyback across the desert
to have him as a partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we'd have gone another way, I don't think it would have
been very smart. Bob's got the potential to be one of our best
owners in a city where we had to be.``
</P>
<P>
   Arizona and St. Louis abstained from voting.
</P>
<P>
   McNair, who considered buying the Miami Dolphins and Minnesota
Vikings and looked into failed expansion bids in St. Louis and
Baltimore, spent the last 2 1/2 years trying to get a team for
Houston to replace the Oilers. The owners liked his low-key style,
his deep pockets and the way he played their game while the Los
Angeles situation played out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since I've been in this league, I haven't seen anyone who
worked the room better than Bob, and I'm not just talking about
today,'' Jones said. ``Whenever he would appear at a league
functions or a league meeting, he would always give (owners) a
comfortable feeling about him.
</P>
<P>
   Early last month, Indianapolis Colts owner Jim Irsay called
McNair and praised his efforts to win the expansion team for
Houston. Irsay said McNair could count on his vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not just picking a city _ we're picking a partner,''
Irsay said. ``I've been impressed with Bob, and I'm glad he got the
team. He respects what the NFL was built on and what's made us the
most successful sports league. And that means a lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``You worry about some owners coming into the league thinking
they're going to change the landscape. But we should want people
with vision and creativity, people who respect the virtues we got
from our founding fathers. Bob's that kind of guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another thing I like about Bob is that he's a sportsman first
and a businessman second.``
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota owner Red McCombs, who resides in San Antonio,
promised to support McNair and Houston weeks ago. McCombs has the
worst lease in the NFL and wants a new stadium. The Twin Cities
media has speculated for months that if he doesn't get a new
stadium McCombs would move to Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Now, McCombs' only legitimate threat would be to move to San
Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob's an excellent choice, and all of Texas is excited to have
a team back in Houston, which is one of the great football
markets,'' McCombs said. ``Speaking for the Vikings, we're
delighted to have the expansion issue over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it ($700 million expansion fee) really played
any role. We had a long time to study the proposals, and we
understood the issues. There were no questions left as far as
Houston is concerned.``
</P>
<P>
   Oakland owner Al Davis has been coming to Houston since the
Oilers' inaugural season of 1960, the same year McNair moved to
Houston. Davis was an assistant coach on Sid Gillman's Los Angeles
Chargers staff. The Oilers beat the Chargers in the first two AFL
championship games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got so many fond memories of Houston,'' Davis said. Davis
was voted commissioner of the AFL in Houston. Two of his greatest
players, quarterback/kicker George Blanda and running back Billy
Cannon, began their careers with the Oilers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm real happy for Houston,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh owner Dan Rooney, whose father, Art Rooney, founded
the Steelers, knows more about Houston fans than any of his
partners. Since the late 1970s, the Oilers considered the Steelers
their No. 1 rival. Rooney witnessed more sold-out crowds in the
Astrodome than any owner.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is great for Houston and the league,'' Rooney said.
``We're (Steelers) excited about it. We had some of our greatest
games against the Oilers. We both had tremendous teams in the late
'70s, and we were two of the best teams in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who'll ever forget that AFC Championship Game (after the 1979
season)? I think it was one of the greatest games of all time. You
guys in Houston still believe he (Mike Renfro) made the catch,
don't you?``
</P>
<P>
   New Orleans owner Tom Benson, a member of the expansion
committee that voted 14-0 to recommend Houston to the rest of the
owners, has studied Houston's proposal carefully.
</P>
<P>
   I pushed hard for this recommendation and have always believed
that Houston is not only good for the NFL but also good for the New
Orleans Saints as it strengthens our region in the South,'' Benson
said. ``Houston has brought to the table not only a great owner in
Robert McNair, but a serious commitment from the city as well as
the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Houston ownership group will spend in excess of $850
million to get this franchise off of the ground. The city and state
will outlay nearly $900 million in public funding, infrastructure,
land, a new light rail system and exhibit hall. That breathtaking
number is an acknowledgment by government leaders of the positive
energy and economic impact generated by a hometown NFL club.
</P>
<P>
   ``When an ownership group comes together with local and state
government to the tune of $1.75 billion to bring the NFL to a city,
it demonstrates the many positives of having an NFL team in your
city.``
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City Chiefs owner Lamar Hunt was a co-founder of the AFL
with Bud Adams. Hunt is a Dallas resident.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is great for Houston and the state of Texas,'' Hunt said.
``Texas is the second-biggest state in terms of population, and it
deserves to have more than one team. I'm so pleased that we've got
Bob McNair. He's worked so hard. He's a good person and an
accomplished businessman.``
</P>
<P>
   Denver Broncos owner Pat Bowlen has been a McNair fan for more
than a year, but he also pushed hard to help Los Angeles get the
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob's going to be a great owner,'' Bowlen said. ``Looking at
the economics of Houston's situation, where they stood as far as
their stadium and what they were willing to pay, you didn't have
that in Los Angeles. I feel bad for Los Angeles because a lot of
people worked hard to put a team there, but I'm sure happy about
Houston.``
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
