<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8777 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SCI-ACID-RAIN-ART-700     10-06 1069
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-ACID-RAIN-ART-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENTISTS REPORT LIMITED PROGRESS ON CURBING EFFECTS OF ACID
RAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Maine, Vt., N.Y., Midwest, Canada, Europe)  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
1-888-603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) (th) 
 By CAROL KAESUK YOON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Over the last two decades, countries in northern Europe and
North America have been enacting regulations to reduce smokestack
emissions of sulfur in an effort to curb acid rain and its harmful
effect on the environment.
</P>
<P>
   In what researchers say is the first comprehensive look at the
effect of those reductions on rivers and lakes, an international
team of scientists plans to report on Thursday that they have found
a nearly universal decrease on both continents in the levels of
sulfates _ the major acidifying pollutant deposited by acid rain in
surface water.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the reductions in sulfates, however, the researchers did
not see a decrease in overall acidity, the sign of true recovery,
in all regions. In Europe and in one region of North America that
includes Quebec and Vermont, researchers did see the expected trend
toward decreasing levels of acidity. In four regions in North
America from Maine to the Midwest, however, they did not.
</P>
<P>
   The message for policy makers, scientists said, is that the path
to recovery from acid rain is not going to be as simple or as quick
as scientists had thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good news is that we reduced sulfate deposition and acid
rain,'' said Dr. Gary Lovett, an ecologist at the Institute of
Ecosystem Studies in Millbrook, N.Y., praising the quality of the
study, which is being published in Thursday's edition of the
journal Nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sobering news that this hasn't given us the recovery that
we might have hoped for,'' Lovett said. ``It's going to promote
rethinking of our acid rain policies.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David Schindler, a freshwater ecologist at the University of
Alberta in Edmonton, called the list of authors of the study a
``who's who in acid rain research.'' He said the research ``clearly
indicates that if we want sufficient recovery from a wide variety
of lakes to support fisheries, we're going to have to take another
pretty large cut'' out of sulfur dioxides, the sulfur emissions
caused by the burning of coal, oil and natural gas that produce
acidifying sulfates.
</P>
<P>
   But other researchers said it was still unclear whether recovery
would indeed require further reductions in emissions or simply more
time, or both. The researchers who were interviewed agreed,
however, that any further decreases in emissions would speed
eventual recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Bailey, vice president of environment at the Edison
Electric Institute in Washington, which represents electric
utilities _ a major producer of sulfur emissions _ viewed the
results more optimistically and noted that the Clean Air Act
required further reductions in emissions beginning next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The theme appears to be that things are getting better,''
Bailey said, ``and things are going to continue to get better.''
</P>
<P>
   Previously, researchers studying the effect of acid rain on
lakes and rivers had confined their studies to more limited
geographic areas, coming up with what were often conflicting and
confusing results as to how surface waters were responding in
general.
</P>
<P>
   In what researchers say is the broadest geographic study to
date, 23 scientists compared data from about 200 sites across
northern Europe and North America. The data were gathered by the
International Cooperative Program on Assessment and Monitoring of
Acidification of Rivers and Lakes, a system of regular monitoring
carried out by national agencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of little dots,'' said Dr. Michael
Oppenheimer, chief scientist for the Environmental Defense Fund.
``They've connected them all up.''
</P>
<P>
   In the new study, researchers reported that the reason many
regions in North America were not recovering despite declines in
sulfates was that important compounds known as base cations _
substances like calcium and magnesium, which counteract the
acidifying effects of sulfates _ were also declining.
</P>
<P>
   Any gains to lakes in sulfate declines, the researchers said,
were overwhelmed by an accompanying rapid decline in base cations,
leading to an overall lack of change in acidity in these lakes and
rivers.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists say it is still not known why base cations are in
short supply and how quickly they will be replenished. But
researchers suspect that the decline is a result of years of acid
rain leaching these compounds out of the soil at a faster rate than
they are replaced.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A major source of base cations is the breakdown of rocks in
soil. The researchers note that three of the regions in North
America where recovery was expected but not seen and where there
were large decreases in base cations _ south-central Ontario,
midwestern North America and the Adirondack and Catskill mountains
in upstate New York _ are close to significant sources of sulfur
emissions and acid rain, which could have exacerbated the losses of
these crucial compounds over the years. Researchers also say
climate may affect levels of base cations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not as simple as turn something off, get something else
to happen,'' said Dr. Steve Kahl, director of the Water Research
Institute at the University of Maine in Orono and an author on the
report. ``This is an overwhelming conclusion. We can't just make a
policy implementation and walk away and assume that we've fixed the
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Scientists say little is known about what, if any, biological
recovery has occurred. Testing water chemistry, they note, is much
simpler and faster than accounting for changes in the presence or
number of many different kinds of animals and plants. But the
scientists who were interviewed agreed that biological recovery
would be much longer in coming.
</P>
<P>
   Schindler said that in experimentally acidified lakes in which
plants, fish, crustaceans and other life had disappeared, some
species returned within days when the lakes were later allowed to
recover, while others still have not returned after more than a
decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been creating acid rain for a long time,'' Lovett said.
``It may take a long time to recover from its effects.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
