<HEADER>
A8780 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-CLINTONCONGRESS06-COX     10-06 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTONCONGRESS06-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   ANGRY PRESIDENT BLASTS HOUSE REPUBLICANS
</P>
<P>
   By Bob Deans
</P>
<P>
   Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Political squabbling between the White House and
Capitol Hill erupted into open hostility Wednesday, when an angry
President Clinton accused House Republicans of selling out to the
powerful health insurance industry to try to kill proposed consumer
protections.
</P>
<P>
   After accusing Senate Republicans of playing politics with
national security policy and discriminating against minority
judicial appointments _ charges he reiterated on Wednesday _
Clinton turned his furor toward the Republican leadership in the
House.
</P>
<P>
   He said his House foes cooked up a legislative scheme ``in the
dead of the night'' Tuesday to tack on rules and amendments
amounting to ``poison pills'' that ``practically guarantee'' the
defeat of a bill that Clinton contends would strengthen consumers
in their dealing with large health care providers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a travesty,'' Clinton told reporters, charging that
the Republican leadership in the House had ``blatantly put special
interests ahead of the interests of the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spoke as though the White House had given up on the
prospects for passage of the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today was supposed to be the day the American people have long
waited for, the day a bipartisan majority passed a strong patients'
bill of rights,'' said Clinton. ``But, unfortunately, as a result
of an 11th hour appeal by the insurance industry lobbyists, which
all of you reported on yesterday, once again it appears that the
will of the American people will be thwarted.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Clinton's spokesman, Joe Lockhart, was even more blunt,
suggesting that insurance lobbists had influenced House Speaker
Dennis Hastert, R-Il., by each contributing $1,000 to his political
action committee at a breakfast Tuesday morning on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``They sat down over bacon and eggs and they hatched a plan to
make sure that the majority of Americans were thwarted in their
belief that they should have more rights in dealing with their
HMOs,'' said Lockhart, referring to health care plans offered by
health maintainence organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he was suggesting that Hastert, was bought off at
the breakfast, Lockhart replied: ``I'm suggesting that it was
probably a pretty productive meeting.''
</P>
<P>
   Hastert has denied that the donations affected his decision to
oppose the proposals, contained in legislation sponsored by Rep.
John Dingell, D-Mich., and Rep. Charlie Norwood, R-Ga. The House is
scheduled to vote on the measure today.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's broadside marked a sharp escalation in what has been
an increasingly contentious season for Clinton and the
Republican-controlled Congress. Democrats and Republicans have
accused each other of political posturing on issues to position
themselves for the presidential and Congressional elections next
year.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past several weeks, Clinton has vetoed the Republicans'
$792 billion tax cut plan and haggled publicly over Congressional
spending proposals on programs ranging from education to health
care.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday Clinton launched a full-court press to try to counter
Republican opposition in the Senate to the Comprehensive Test Ban
Treaty, which would ban the testing of nuclear weapons in the
United States and 153 other countries.
</P>
<P>
   And on Tuesday he railed against the Senate for quashing his
nomination of Ronnie White to the federal district court in
Missouri. The Senate's Republican majority rejected White, the
first African-American to sit of the Missouri Supreme Court, in a
straight party-line vote, 54-45, on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing White House reporters in the Rose Garden, Clinton
called White's defeat, ``a disgraceful act of partisan politics.''
The move, said Clinton, ``is adding credence to the perceptions
that they treat minority and women judicial nominees unfairly and
unequally.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans claimed that White had shown insufficient support
for the death penalty during his career, a charge the White House
went to pains to refute.
</P>
<P>
   The White House press office put out a statement saying that, as
a justice on the Missouri State Supreme Court, White had affirmed
the imposition of the death penalty in ``almost 70 percent of the
cases that came before him,'' and that he acted in unanimity with
the rest of the court in 10 of the 18 instances in which he voted
against imposing the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   With Clinton still trying to persuade Senate Republicans to back
the nuclear test ban treaty _ he held an East Room event Wednesday
to appeal again for its ratification _ and many of the spending
bills for the fiscal year that began last Friday still being
negotiated, the air of mounting discord between the White House and
Capitol Hill bodes poorly.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart insisted that Clinton stands ready to deal with his
Republican antagonists, but he made no effort to sugarcoat the
animosity that broke out into the open on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Said Lockhart, ``The president is upset.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
