<SLUG> BC-OCEAN-SPRAY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OCEAN SPRAY TO MOUNT INTENSIFIED MARKETING CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Looking to rebound from a slump, Ocean Spray Cranberries Inc.
said Wednesday it hopes to stimulate demand for its products, which
has been flat, by increasing its advertising budget by nearly 35
percent, from about $34 million to $46 million.
</P>
<P>
   The overall marketing budget, which includes advertising and
distribution of coupons and free samples, will grow to between $75
million and $100 million, a 10 percent to 15 percent jump.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the increase will go to a new ad campaign with the
theme, ``You know it's good,'' a successor to such Ocean Spray
taglines as ``Crave the wave'' and ``Refreshingly honest.''
</P>
<P>
   The ad campaign's first job is to relaunch a 100-percent juice
line whose debut last year under the brand name of Wellfleet Farms
was a big disappointment. The product will now be known as Ocean
Spray Premium 100% Juices.
</P>
<P>
   After a year of layoffs and management turnover, the marketing
changes arrive as the embattled Lakeville, Mass. cooperative is
reviewing a number of options, from an internal restructuring to
selling all or part of its business.
</P>
<P>
   Ocean Spray reiterated Wednesday that this review is unlikely to
be completed for at least several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   All this turmoil gives the new ad campaign added urgency.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Ocean Spray ad campaigns have consisted largely of
television ads aired during prime time. Now there will be more
emphasis on print and cable television, as Ocean Spray looks to
more precisely target its customers, said Stewart Gallagher, who
took over in February as vice president of marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's ads, created by Arnold Communications of Boston,
were a ``bit generic,'' he said. New ads, also from Arnold, will
focus on specific products and their health benefits. Ads will also
talk up new products, such as Ocean Spray Cranberry Juice Cocktail
Plus, which is fortified with vitamins and calcium.
</P>
<P>
   Previous ads suggested that Ocean Spray, which also includes
citrus growers in its membership, was a fruit company. New ads
proclaim the cooperative's cranberry heritage.
</P>
<P>
   As cranberry growers approach the midpoint of this year's
harvest, much of the industry is hurting as supply exceeds demand.
</P>
<P>
   About 3 million barrels of cranberries still remain from last
year's North American harvest, said David Farrimond of the US
Department of Agriculture. This year's harvest has been projected
at about 6.4 million barrels.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, cranberry consumption has remained flat, at just over
5 million barrels a year, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Partly as a result, Ocean Spray's revenues have stagnated. Chris
Phillips, Ocean Spray's manager of public affairs, said the
revenues for the fiscal year that ended in August will be below the
previous year's $1.48 billion. Precise figures won't be disclosed
for another few weeks, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ocean Spray doesn't only compete with other cranberry companies;
it also competes with nearly every beverage that can be found on a
supermarket shelf, from bottled water to soft drinks. In many
cases, these rivals have behind them the marketing muscle of a big
conglomerate, such as PepsiCo Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Bottled water may be the hottest beverage category at the
moment. Consumption is up sharply in the last 10 years, said John
Sicher, editor and publisher of Beverage Digest, a trade journal.
And Americans are drinking nearly seven gallons per year more of
carbonated soft drinks than they did a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   But annual consumption of juices and juice drinks rose only from
8.2 gallons per capita in 1988 to 8.7 gallons in 1998, Sicher said.
</P>
<P>
   At least one small juice company reports it is gaining at Ocean
Spray's expense. A few years ago, Wisconsin-based Northland
Cranberries Inc. began marketing a cranberry product as 100-percent
juice: a cranberry beverage sweetened and diluted by other juices.
</P>
<P>
   Ocean Spray's Cranberry Juice Coctail, in contrast, is 27
percent juice; the rest is water and fructose syrup.
</P>
<P>
   Northland has come on strong, eating away at Ocean Spray's
market share, said Northland chief executive John Swendrowski.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Ocean Spray countered with the launch of its own
100-percent juice line, Wellfleet Farms. But the line didn't catch
on, despite a big ad campaign and lots of promotions.
</P>
<P>
   Now the line has a new name _ Ocean Spray Premium 100% Juices _
a new label, and a new and even bigger ad campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a clean break'' from last year's campaign, said Sheff
Halsey, the Ocean Spray account director at Arnold.
</P>
<P>
   In Swendrowski's view, a name change and a bigger marketing
budget won't be enough to solve Ocean Spray's problems.
</P>
<P>
   But Ocean Spray's Phillips contends it's a start.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we can change the mix,'' he said. ``We think there's
demand waiting to be tapped.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
