<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8794 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-LEHIGH-ON-THE-RISE-AR     10-06 1094
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEHIGH-ON-THE-RISE-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON STEEL INDUSTRY'S RUINS, HIGH-TECH MECCA SPROUTS IN LEHIGH
VALLEY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic map is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By CLAUDIA H. DEUTSCH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BETHLEHEM, Pa. _ When Christopher Reed left here nine years ago
to study engineering at Penn State, he figured he was gone for
good. A steelworker's son, he had had firsthand experience with the
havoc that the steady decline of Big Steel had wreaked on the
area's job market. ``I figured I'd be in California by now,'' Reed
said.
</P>
<P>
   Reed came back when he graduated in 1994, but only to use his
parents' home as a base for job hunting. Five months later, though,
he was working at QED, a Bethlehem company that makes gallium
arsenide wafers for the semiconductor industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't believe something like QED existed in my
backyard,'' Reed, a systems engineer, said. ``I just never thought
of this as a high-tech area.''
</P>
<P>
   So much for the persistent perception of the Lehigh Valley _
whose economic woes were immortalized by Billy Joel in his angry
1982 ballad ``Allentown'' _ as a place whose time has come and
gone. Just drive through the area, visit its schools, talk to its
entrepreneurs. Lucent Technologies has even gone so far as to put
up a billboard over nearby Route 22 proclaiming, ``Move over,
Silicon Valley, here comes Lehigh Valley.''
</P>
<P>
   That's certainly an exaggeration. Still, slowly but steadily, a
high-technology phoenix is rising on the steel shards of Easton,
Bethlehem and Allentown, the towns that comprise eastern
Pennsylvania's Lehigh Valley. The region's unemployment rate, which
four years ago was 7.7 percent, is now only 3.7 percent, according
to the August data. Some 65 high-technology companies have moved
into the valley or been founded there in the last five years,
representing 38,500 jobs _ or about 12 percent of the area's total
employment. It is a striking example of the extent to which high
technology is transforming some of the most damaged areas of the
Rust Belt's industrial economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting past the stigma of the Billy Joel song,'' said
Thomas Kucharski, president of the Lehigh Valley Economic
Development Corp. ``We're breaking through the perception that this
area is coal and cows, and gray and brown.''
</P>
<P>
   A survey by a state-financed economic agency indicates that
technology companies accounted for 3,500 new jobs in the valley
last year, and are expected to create another 4,000 over the next
two years.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent, the communications equipment maker that is the area's
biggest technology employer, has gone from 5,000 jobs in the region
in 1996 to 5,600 today. It will have 5,900 here after it finishes
expanding a plant in nearby Briningsville and completes a $165
million divisional headquarters complex in Allentown in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Newcomers include ComputerAid, a computer software developer
with 1,200 employees; AANetcom, a small chip maker founded two
years ago by a former Bell Laboratories scientist; STC
Technologies, a developer of medical products for testing
immune-system problems, which employs 85 people, and Applied
Separations Inc., a producer of advanced biotech laboratory
equipment with 62 employees.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But the drawn-out erosion of the steel industry has left its
scars. At its 1950s peak, Bethlehem Steel employed 30,000 people in
a five-mile stretch of steelmaking facilities here. When it closed
its last local plant last year, the work force had dwindled to 800.
Many of the workers found jobs with other local companies, but the
pay was nowhere near the $30 an hour they had made with Big Steel,
let alone the 13 weeks' paid vacation and full package of health
benefits they had garnered.
</P>
<P>
   Steel's demise meant the end of a way of a life. By the early
1980s, for the first time in more than 100 years, sons could no
longer follow fathers into the steelworker's life.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a noticeable and painful flight of young people from
this entire area,'' recalled Bruce Davis, a former Bethlehem Steel
lawyer who is now in private practice.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those who returned still feel pangs for the old days.
``I look at the blast furnaces now, and what strikes me most is the
eerie silence,'' said Jeffrey Lowmaster, a 41-year-old former
steelworker who left the Lehigh Valley when he was laid off in
1982, got some technology training, and returned last year to a
technician's job at QED.
</P>
<P>
   He is not alone. In September, a local theater group used the
skeleton of an old steel mill as the backdrop for a play called
``Steelbound,'' which dramatized how widespread the longing for the
old life was.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seeing the plant as a ghost town, flat tracts and rubble where
buildings used to be, was even sadder than the day we closed the
forge,'' said Leonard Christman, a former steelworker who acted in
the play.
</P>
<P>
   But, Christman noted, the play ended with a strong message:
``It's time to stop looking back, and to move on.''
</P>
<P>
   And that, clearly, is what the region is doing.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw high, we saw low, and now we're seeing high again,''
said David Hartzell, a 26-year-old steelworker's son who is
director of operations for QED, which employs 70 people.
</P>
<P>
   The change is tangible. Easton is metamorphosing into an art and
tourist center, home to several galleries and two interactive
children's museums. Allentown, which has suffered badly from
middle-class flight to the suburbs, is being reborn as a government
and financial center, with a large dab of high technology.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, there is Lucent's planned new group
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been adding people for the last few years, and we're
finally ready to put down bricks and mortar,'' said John T.
Dickson, the president of Lucent's $3 billion Microelectronics
Group, the division that makes electronic components here. The
region's drawing cards, Dickson said, include the ``magnificent''
countryside and affordable housing. And Lucent's Route 22 billboard
notwithstanding, Dickson sees benefit in the fact that the Lehigh
Valley does not really rival other high-tech centers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't attract good people if we were the only high-tech
company in town,'' he said. ``But it's still harder for our talent
to walk out the door to a new job than it would be in Silicon
Valley.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
