u a BC-CAMPAIGN-BRADLEY-BOS &LR;      10-06 0635
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-BRADLEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE CRITICISMS `RIDICULOUS,' BRADLEY SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANCHESTER, N.H. _ Democratic presidential candidate Bill
Bradley acknowledging he has thrown ``raw meat into a cage of
wolves'' by outlining a detailed health care plan, Wednesday
bristled at criticism of the proposal by Vice President Al Gore,
saying Gore's complaints are ``ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He is just wrong,'' Bradley said in an interview, delivering
his first public response to criticism of the plan by Gore. The
vice president said Monday that the former New Jersey senator's
proposal would eliminate Medicaid and threaten the solvency of
Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   In defending his $65 billion-per-year health care plan, Bradley
underscored the challenge he faces in the coming months as he tries
to outline a series of specific, costly proposals while fending off
attacks about the details.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, shown an article outlining Gore's criticism of his
health care plan, visibly bristled at the vice president's remarks,
saying Gore was misrepresenting the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not taking away anybody's Medicare,'' Bradley said in
the interview. Bradley said he would detail his proposal on
Medicare later this year. In addition, Bradley emphasized that his
plan would provide additional prescription coverage for senior
citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley also said Gore was misstating his position on Medicaid.
``We're not abolishing it, we're replacing it,'' Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   Later Wednesday, Bradley continued to defend his health care
plan, appearing just up the street from Gore's campaign
headquarters here to promote his proposal at the Manchester
Community Health Center. Bradley met with doctors at the clinic who
told one story after another about the difficulty of finding
treatment for uninsured patients, a setting intended to highlight
the benefits of Bradley's plan to provide insurance for 95 percent
of Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley also appeared Wednesday night at a Town Meeting in
Bedford attended by about 300 people, many of whom enthusiastically
supported him.
</P>
<P>
   The health care plan is just the first of many detailed family
and health-related proposals that Bradley intends to announce.
Thursday, in a speech in Peterborough, Bradley plans to unveil
plans to help families balance work and home life, including a
``senior corps'' program that would pay senior citizens to mentor
young people.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has devoted considerable time to the first-primary
state, where a series of polls have shown him in a statistical tie
with Gore. It is these New Hampshire polls that convinced Gore last
week to reorganize his campaign, moving the headquarters to
Nashville and challenging Bradley to a series of debates.
</P>
<P>
   While Bradley has not agreed to the debates, both Democratic
candidates are scheduled to appear at a ``Town Meeting'' in New
Hampshire later this month. The event is considered by both
campaigns to the most important event so far of the primary, and it
is likely to be attended by hundreds of members of the media.
</P>
<P>
   At a press conference, Bradley declined to get into an exchange
about Gore, saying he didn't want to engage in what he called
``dart board politics.'' At one point, a reporter asked Bradley to
respond to Gore's comments that the senator had quit the Senate and
had considered leaving the Democratic Party to run as an
Independent candidate. Bradley responded by pretending to be hit
with a dart, then carefully removing it and putting it on the
podium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand what happens in a campaign,'' Bradley said.
``Someone makes a charge and then you're asked to make a charge. I
don't think the American people want the politics of the dartboard.
I think they're tired of that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-99 1950EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991006.0335 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8797 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-LEHIGH-ON-THE-RISE-AR     10-06 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEHIGH-ON-THE-RISE-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 BETHLEHEM, Pa.: Silicon Valley.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The renaissance is most apparent in Bethlehem, once the heart of
the steel district. New eating establishments and boutiques are
replacing ramshackle businesses on 3rd Street, the main drag. And
it is not possible to eat at the Apollo Grill, a trendy new
mid-priced restaurant, without a reservation. ``In the old days, it
would have opened and closed in a week,'' said Bethlehem Mayor
Donald Cunningham, a steelworker's son.
</P>
<P>
   Bethlehem Steel still makes its world headquarters here, even
though its closest steel mill is now in Steelton, about 100 miles
west. Meanwhile, the old local steelmaking site _ at 1,800 acres
the largest singly-owned ``brownfield,'' or environmentally
problematic site, under redevelopment in the country _ is being
reincarnated.
</P>
<P>
   The company has spent nearly $25 million on cleaning up and
marketing the site, but has priced the parcels low enough so that
they are selling quickly. ``We're not trying to profit from
redevelopment; we'd love it if we break even,'' said Curtis H.
``Hank'' Barnette, the company's chairman since 1992. ``Our goal is
to bring our site back to decent use.''
</P>
<P>
   The new uses include a museum of industry run by the Smithsonian
Institution, an entertainment park with skating rink and swimming
pool, a transportation facility where shipments are switched
between trucks and railcars, a hotel and conference center, and a
commerce center for light manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
   Barnette said he expected the various operations that occupy the
old steelmaking site to eventually provide 10,000 jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, the company has helped finance five industrial parks
on Bethlehem's outskirts that have become homes to some 400 small
businesses, and to a mix of 14,000 technology and non-technology
jobs. A sixth park is under construction now.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, all along the valley, dozens of companies with ties
to the fast-growing semiconductor chip industry have sprung up.
Many have been helped along by the state-financed Ben Franklin
Technology Center, an incubator for new companies and a nurturer
for small ones trying to grow big.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without Ben Franklin's help, we'd have never found financing
to get started,'' said William Weisbecker, a co-founder of QED,
which recently merged with a Welsh company to form a $35 million
multinational called IQE PLC, whose stock trades on the Brussels
exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The Ben Franklin Center was one of various initiatives promoted
in the early 1980s by Pennsylvania's Republican governor at the
time, Dick Thornburgh. While it was clear that steel was on the way
out, Thornburgh defied the conventional wisdom by refusing to woo
other types of heavy industry with the promise of tax breaks and
land, concentrating instead on luring small companies with growth
potential.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `Let's not chase smokestacks, let's turn our
resources into something with a future,''' said Mark Lang, the Ben
Franklin Center's executive director.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   High technology was not an outlandish choice. The first
transistor was manufactured in Allentown in 1951 by Western
Electric, the old AT&AMP;T manufacturing arm, which originally located
in the area because of its proximity to New York and Philadelphia
and to AT&AMP;T's Bell Labs, 60 miles away in Murray Hill, N.J. And
there was Lehigh University. Today, many of the current start-ups
are run by Lehigh alumni.
</P>
<P>
   ``It made sense to set up near a high concentration of technical
talent,'' said John Plunkett, a Lehigh graduate and co-founder of
Millbrook Inc., a new Bethlehem company that provides software to
the insurance industry. Millbrook rents office space from Lehigh,
and employs many Lehigh students as interns.
</P>
<P>
   Lehigh University itself is undergoing a metamorphosis of sorts.
To counter its lingering reputation as a bastion of manufacturing
skills, it is beefing up its liberal arts offerings, and will soon
introduce a bioengineering course. It also is setting its students
up with internships and consulting jobs at local technology
companies. ``Most of our graduates still don't stay in the area,
but we'd like them to,'' said university president Gregory
Farrington.
</P>
<P>
   The changes in Bethlehem's local schools are more dramatic. The
school district was never particularly starved for cash, since
Bethlehem _ unlike Allentown and many other U.S. cities _ has
folded its affluent suburban and inner city schools under the same
district umbrella. But, in the steel-supremacy days, it was not
under pressure to provide a good education.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knew you could be a high school dropout and have a
middle class lifestyle, that you could lean on a broom and make $15
an hour,'' said Thomas Doliusio, the district superintendent for
the last 13 years. ``Our minimum requirements for graduation were
too minimum.''
</P>
<P>
   Not anymore. Three years ago Doliusio began what he calls an
``international benchmarking'' project, to glean educational tips
from Japan and other countries. He has since introduced new ways to
teach English and math, as well as intensified reading skills
programs. He has instituted a stringent code of conduct that has
resulted in the expulsion of 100 children ``whose behavior
interfered with our efficiency,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The cost has been high. ``Many teachers retired, and we've spent
millions to train others,'' he said. ``And we've had to deemphasize
social studies and science and music. But gosh darn it, our kids
will know how to read!''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But the area's transformation is far from complete. Barnette,
the Bethlehem Steel chairman, figures it will take more than a
decade to complete all of the facilities planned for his shuttered
plants. There are still many rutted, muddy roads on and around the
site.
</P>
<P>
   And, according to Mayor Cunningham, while enough companies have
come in to keep the tax base from declining, ``it's stayed flat
when our expenses have kept going up.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, even as he stood at the window of his office and
surveyed the reborn town of Bethlehem, there was an air of
nostalgic wistfulness in Cunningham's voice. ``My job would be a
lot easier,'' he conceded, ``if there were a working steel plant
out there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
