<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8808 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w BC-CAMPAIGN-DOLE-BOS &LR;      10-06 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-DOLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOLE `OUTRAGED' BY RUMORS SHE'S   RUNNING OUT OF FUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ An angry Elizabeth Dole is denying rumors, which
her aides say are being spread by the rival camps of Arizona
Senator John McCain and Steve Forbes, that she is about to drop her
historic bid for the GOP presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Dole is ``outraged'' by reports circulating in New Hampshire
this week that she is running out of money, canceling appearances
and charter flights, and will soon end her campaign, her press
secretary, Kathleen Harrington, said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why would they do this kind of thing?'' Dole asked when told
of the rumors, Harrington said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no truth'' to Dole withdrawing, said Harrington,
noting that the candidate was heading to San Diego Thursday to give
a get-tough-on-drugs speech, doing a weekend of fund-raising in
California and McCain's home state of Arizona, and then campaigning
in Iowa next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am out there running hard, working hard,'' Dole told
reporters after speaking to 600 businesswomen at a fund-raising
lunch in Lexington, Ky. Dole, in the speech, criticized the US
Justice Department for filing a lawsuit against tobacco companies,
seeking to recover billions of dollars that taxpayers have spent on
smoking-related health care.
</P>
<P>
   Harrington said that because Dole is running second to Texas
Governor George W. Bush in most national polls, ``it is clearly in
the interest of McCain and Forbes to knock us out'' and be
positioned as the most likely alternative if the GOP front-runner
falters. She also suggested McCain has a gender gap _ he is more
popular with men than women voters _ and would like to see the only
female candidate leave the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``McCain's people have been very overt, telling people the Dole
campaign is falling apart,'' said Ari Fleischer, Dole's former
spokesman. ``I think some of these male candidates are frustrated
to be losing to a woman like Elizabeth Dole. So they engage in the
art of discrediting their opponent.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's spokesman, Howard Opinsky, denied his campaign was
spreading rumors about Dole's demise and insisted its focus is only
on the senator. ``This campaign is not about other candidates, it's
about getting out the message of John McCain,'' Opinsky said,
adding that McCain was now besting Dole in polls in New Hampshire,
New York, and South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Mueller, a Forbes adviser, called it ``a bunch of
nonsense'' that the publisher's campaign would undermine Dole. ``We
feel that this is, by and large, down to a two-person race between
an establishment candidate and the conservative alternative, which
Forbes has become,'' Mueller said. ``I have no idea what Mrs.
Dole's intentions are, but we encourage her to stay in the race.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite her denials, some key Republicans still are not
convinced Dole is serious about continuing her presidential
campaign, the first by a Republican woman. They say Dole failed to
capitalize on her third-place finish in the Iowa straw poll in
August and has been unimpressive in raising money, bringing in $1.7
million in the last three months. Dole has not officially declared
her candidacy, either, an event that aides have now pushed back to
November from October.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Rath, a New Hampshire GOP committeeman who is supporting
Bush, said sources close to the Dole campaign _ not those in a
rival camp _ have told him that Dole is running out of money and
will withdraw from the race by the end of the week. According to
Rath, Dole has about $200,000 on hand, not the $850,000 the
campaign reported last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mrs. Dole has labored mightily, but there is no easy way to
say it: If you don't have the money, you can't go on,'' said Rath,
who had been an adviser to former Tennessee Governor Lamar
Alexander before he left the GOP race for a lack of money.
</P>
<P>
   Bonnie McElveen-Hunter, Dole's finance chairman, said the Dole
campaign has close to $850,000 in the bank _ ``though I wish it was
$85 million.'' McElveen-Hunter said she is organizing fund-raising
events through December and into January, a sign that Dole is in
the race, at least through the Iowa caucuses and New Hampshire
primary.
</P>
<P>
   Still, McElveen-Hunter acknowledged the perception that Dole is
preparing to drop out of the race makes money-raising harder.
``Nobody wants to give to a candidate they believe is going to pull
out of the race,'' McElveen-Hunter said.
</P>
<P>
   Friday Dole will be in Phoenix for a fund-raiser and to get the
endorsement of Mayor Skip Rimsza. ``We're going into McCain's
territory, and we aren't ceding it to him,'' Harrington said.
</P>
<P>
   John Zogby, a New York pollster, said that because Dole is
well-known and has the celebrity of being the woman candidate, she
does not need to raise as much money as her rivals to stay in the
race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why would Dole drop out?'' Zogby said. ``Above and beyond
winning, she wants to make history. . .She won't make history if
she drops out too soon, and if she doesn't compete at least in Iowa
and New Hampshire, the `coulda, woulda, shoulda' questions about
her will never be answered.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-99 1953EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991006.0341 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8810 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-UN-TALIBAN-BOS &LR;      10-06 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UN-TALIBAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US MOVES AGAINST BIN LADEN WITH UN RESOLUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE LAURIA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Bolstered by Russia's new hard line toward
Osama bin Laden, the United States Wednesday introduced a Security
Council resolution that would seize assets and ground international
flights of Afghanistan's ruling Taliban rebels until the terrorist
leader is turned over to US authorities.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution, expected to sail to passage as early as Friday,
could presage more pressure on the Taliban, including a worldwide
weapons embargo, diplomats said.
</P>
<P>
   Taliban officials say the measure will hurt Afghanistan's
people, not their Islamic fundamentalist movement.
</P>
<P>
   Bin Laden, indicted by a US court for masterminding the August
1998 bombing of American embassies in Kenya and Tanzania that
killed more than 200 people, has been accused by Russian
authorities of funding what they call an Islamic bombing campaign
in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   US and Russian intelligence say Bin Laden is being sheltered by
the Afghan Islamic militants, who have controlled most of
Afghanistan since 1996. US officials said the Taliban has rejected
more than 20 requests from Washington to turn over bin Laden or his
associates.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's support of the measure is critical, because it holds an
automatic veto on the 15-member UN council.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe terrorism is a threat and the Taliban is violating
all possible decisions of the United Nations,'' Sergei Lavrov,
Russia's UN ambassador, said in brief remarks. ``We support the
resolution.''
</P>
<P>
   An air embargo would be devastating to the landlocked country.
Under the resolution, all assets held by the Taliban would be
frozen. The US imposed its own sanctions against flights by the
Taliban-controlled Ariana Afghan airline in August.
</P>
<P>
   Washington decided to extend its sanctions into a worldwide ban
because of Russian support in the effort to stop bin Laden, said a
Western diplomat, who asked not to be named. Britain, France and
China, the other permanent council members, also support the
resolution, the diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
   The Taliban's designated representative to the United Nations,
Abdul Hakeem Mujhaid, called the resolution strange because it
comes against a group not recognized by the world body. The
international flights now are ``taking the commodities of the
people to Pakistan, and nothing else. This impacts the common
people, the traders,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Russian Prime Minister Vladimir Putin said bin Laden
has been in Chechnya several times, helping that Russian republic
as well as the Dagestan region to break away from Moscow with
financial and material support. The Russians have also accused the
Saudi dissident of being behind apartment building bombings in the
Russian capital last month that left nearly 300 people dead.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration believes bin Laden, who fought in
Afghanistan's war against the Soviet Union, is planning more
attacks against Americans or American interests. Last week,
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright designated bin Laden's
organization, al-Qa'ida, a foreign terrorist organization, which
gave the US more authority to freeze its assets. Al-Qa'ida's
headquarters is in the southern Afghan city of Kandahar.
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago, the United States said it would seize the Afghan
airline's US assets, estimated at $500 million. Since the Taliban
seized power in Afghanistan the airline's only international
flights have been to Pakistan and the United Arab Emirates.
Pakistan is the Taliban's chief ally and have not cooperated with
US efforts to bring bin Laden to justice, US officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Like all countries, Pakistan would be bound by the UN sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   The Taliban denies bid Laden is involved in terrorist activities
and also says it has no extradition treaty with the United States.
Bin Laden is on the FBI's 10-most-wanted list. The United States
has offered a $5 million reward for his arrest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
