<HEADLINE>
GORE CRITICIZES BRADLEY RECORD ON FAMILY ISSUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILL ZUCKMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As Bill Bradley prepares to deliver a major address on work and
families Thursday in Peterborough, N.H., Vice President Gore's
campaign is trying to poke holes in the former New Jersey senator's
legislative record on protecting families.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign highlights the fact that Bradley was the only
Democrat to vote in 1995 against a budget amendment to provide
federal dollars to rural hospitals and health care providers
treating Medicare patients, as to maintain funding for education
and child care in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
   The vote came on a Democratic amendment _ one among many offered
_ to reduce the Republicans' proposed tax cut by $48 billion to
help pay for rural health care, education, child care and
agriculture. Senator Olympia Snowe, the Maine Republican, joined
with Democrats, while Bradley sided with the Republicans on the
amendment. He ultimately voted with his party against the GOP
budget and tax cut package.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign considers the Bradley vote a sign of weakness
in his record on family issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The focus of this presidential campaign should be on America's
working families, and especially the families of New Hampshire,''
said Douglas Hattaway, Gore's New Hampshire press secretary. ``But
Senator Bradley's voting record differs greatly from his rhetoric
as a presidential candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony Wyche, a spokesman for Bradley, said their campaign is not
going to respond to any ``mudslinging.'' He declined to explain why
Bradley broke with Democrats and voted the way he did.
</P>
<P>
   ``As Senator Bradley said, he's not going to engage in dart
board politics, where you're basically trying to throw darts at
people and hope some of them hit,'' Wyche said.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign's effort to chip away at the Bradley record
comes at a time when the vice president has been slipping in the
polls in New Hampshire, and has called for a series of issue-center
debates with his opponent. Gore campaign staffers have been poring
through Bradley's record in recent weeks, looking for issues that
will undermine the former senator's rising support throughout the
first-in-the-nation primary state, as well as nationally.
</P>
<P>
   The vote Bradley cast in October of 1995 occurred at a defining
time for Democrats and Republicans in Congress. Republicans had
recently taken over the Congress and were intent on passing a plan
to balance the budget by 2002 and cut taxes. The bill would have
slashed projected spending by $894 billion and lowered taxes by
$245 billion, according to Congressional Quarterly's Almanac.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, disagreements over the Republicans' budget led to
two vetos by President Clinton and the shutdown of the federal
government on Nov. 14 and again on Dec. 16.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
