<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEMPHIS-MAYOR07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Memphis to elect new mayor
 &HT;    By Anne Rochell Konigsmark
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The most colorful mayor's race in Memphis, Tenn.,
history ends today as residents choose between 15 candidates,
including the incumbent, who is the city's first black mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Two-term Mayor Willie Herenton is in the lead, according to a
recent poll in the Memphis Commercial-Appeal, but as many as 37
percent of voters were undecided less than two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   In second place is City Council Chairman Joe Ford, a member of
the most powerful black family in Memphis. His older brother,
Harold Ford Sr., was the first black U.S. congressman from
Tennessee. Harold's son, Harold Ford Jr., now has his father's seat
in Washington. Several other Ford men hold local and state elected
offices.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is no historical precedent in Memphis for having two
strong African-American candidates in the mayor's race,'' said
Steven Ethridge, a pollster. Memphis, population 650,000, is more
than 50 percent black. ''The incumbent has substantial support
among the black and the white communities but he may not have
enough of either to win. It's just a very volatile situation here.
It's very unpredictable what will happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Herenton has spent more than $800,000 on his campaign, a Memphis
record. Ford has spent about $500,000.
</P>
<P>
   All summer and into the fall, Herenton and Ford have slung
enough mud at each other to damn up the Mississippi River flowing
through downtown Memphis. Each has dragged out the other's ancient
arrest records: Ford for drunken driving and assaulting his wife,
and Herenton for rape. Herenton has called Ford unqualified and
immature and Ford has called Herenton inefficient and cold.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the 13 remaining candidates are hoping to benefit
from the fight at the top. Pete Sisson, a well-known white
politician who has the backing of the Republican Party, has said he
can woo voters fed up with the Herenton-Ford feud.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry ''The King'' Lawler, a professional wrestler, is trailing
badly in the polls, but has said he hopes people will think like
this: If former wrestler Jesse Ventura can become governor of
Minnesota, then he can become mayor of Memphis. Lawler was indicted
last month for getting angry at a Memphis airport officer and
running over her foot with his car. He said the timing of the
indictment seemed suspicious.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's candidate Pepper Rodgers, former Georgia Tech
football coach and former coach of the now-defunct Memphis
Showboats.
</P>
<P>
   No one's holding out much hope of him being elected, including
Rodgers himself. He admits he didn't make a serious bid for the
city's top job.
</P>
<P>
   Turnout will be a major factor in who wins, since there are so
many candidates and so many people still making up their minds.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think a lot of people won't make up their minds until they
get in the voting booth,'' Ethridge said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
