u f BC-CREDIT-NYT &LR;      10-06 0495
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TREASURY PRICES WAIT FOR FRIDAY'S EMPLOYMENT REPORT  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)   By ROBERT HURTADO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Treasury prices were little changed Wednesday as
investors failed to follow through on early buying. Market
participants wound up instead focusing on the employment report
coming on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The oversold condition of the market could have been a factor
behind Wednesday's early bounce in prices as some investors sought
attractive yields, which are hovering near two-month highs.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the decision by the Federal Reserve on Tuesday to
leave short-term interest rates unchanged helped ease some fears
about inflation. However, the central bank's indication that it is
leaning toward an increase in the future is also keeping economic
data squarely in the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Ablin, president of Colonial Asset Management Inc. in
Jacksonville, Fla., said investor sentiment traditionally played a
large role in trading, ``and it's that sentiment that has pushed
the limit on the low side of prices over the past few days, a
definite negative for bonds. However, near term, it has become a
positive because investors probably have oversold, and that leaves
some buying opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   The price of the benchmark 30-year bond rose 2/32, to 99 13/32.
Its yield was unchanged at 6.17 percent. A two-year note, on the
other hand, slipped 2/ 32, to 99 22/32. Its yield rose to 5.79
percent from 5.76 percent on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, the underlying concern is with wages and labor and
consumer spending,'' Ablin said. ``People are spending at a faster
clip than they are earning, which is a concern for the Fed. I don't
see much happening between now and Friday, when the September
employment report is released.'' He said a big number would hurt
bonds and was not so sure a low number would change the negative
psychology of the bond market.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts expect a gain of 225,000 jobs, with the unemployment
rate at 4.3 percent, up from 4.2 percent in August.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Pugliese, senior vice president and director of the
fixed-income department at the J.W. Genesis Financial Corp., Boca
Raton, Fla., said the employment data had the potential to give the
Fed the impetus to raise rates even before its next meeting, which
is on Nov. 16. ``Yesterday, the Fed issued its
bias-toward-tightening warning, and in my opinion it will indeed
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Today the trading was thin, with some hedge-fund selling,'' he
added. ``But in reality, market participants were basically in a
wait-and-see mode.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, the Treasury auctioned $7 billion of 29{-year
Treasury inflation-indexed securities, or the reopening of the 3~
percent 30-year inflation-indexed bond originally issued April 15,
1999. The auction itself was on the weak side as the bid-to-cover,
an indication of demand, came in at 1.92 to 1. Traders said the
bonds were awarded with a high yield of 4.138 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
