<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8820 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     10-06 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: PATIENCE SAVES PETTITTE AND YANKEES 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By HARVEY ARATON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Andy Pettitte pitches for the Yankees on Thursday
night, entrusted with the responsibility of sending the Texas
Rangers home knowing the odds of their winning this division series
equate to Elizabeth Dole's chances of pulling out the Republican
presidential nomination against George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   That Pettitte is the Game 2 starter is, granted, due to Joe
Torre's reluctance to pitch him in Texas. That Pettitte is still a
Yankee and is throwing in the post-season at all is more a tribute
to the way the Yankees have operated since their mid-1990s
renaissance following 15 years of Let's Make A Deal. Who would have
believed a mere half-dozen years ago that in George Steinbrenner's
eruptive world, the organization's watch word, indeed its governing
principle, would be patience?
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's anything I learned from Joe Torre, it's that you
have to trust people, and that a track record is something you can
trust,'' General Manager Brian Cashman said.
</P>
<P>
   We can all still visualize Steinbrenner's ranting at the
television or into his telephone, and lighting fire to the trading
card of those failing under pressure. But let's be fair; it has
been awhile since a Yankee has been given the Jim Beattie or Bobby
Meacham treatment, fallen through the trap door to Columbus, or
been forever banished from the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   Winning two World Series in three years and more games than any
team in history last season has had something to do with becalming
the Boss. But so have self-assured men such as Torre and Cashman,
and Buck Showalter and Bob Watson before them.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees had good reason to worry about Pettitte's declining
performance and financial considerations about coming arbitration
for the pitcher who had the second-most victories combined in the
major leagues the three seasons past. As Pettitte struggled and
this season's trade deadline approached, Torre's two cents said it
was the wrong time to pass judgment on a 27-year-old only months
removed from seven-and-a-third shutout innings in the clinching
game of the 1998 World Series.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees came to the logical conclusion that Pettitte was
worth more to them than what they could get for him. Steinbrenner
began most of his justifications with lines like, ``The manager
assures me ...''
</P>
<P>
   Besides paying a good buck, he is still quite adept at passing
it. Whatever. Torre stayed with his sensitive left-hander, who
pitched reliably, if not formidably, in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was easy for me to be supportive of him because I never
played in the post-season and I always respected the guy who would
go out there and perform,'' Torre said. ``He bottomed out in a game
at Chicago, but once he had two good starts under his belt, it just
became a mind game and he had his confidence back.''
</P>
<P>
   No longer interested in trading theories about the hows and
whys, Pettitte said, ``The first half of this season seems like
last year.'' He takes the ball Thursday night and tries to reward
the Yankees for their patience, the way Bernie Williams did in Game
1 on Tuesday night with six runs batted in and a sliding catch that
prevented two Texas runs.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees might have jettisoned Williams, too, when he refused
to sign before the 1998 season for less than half of what he
eventually would get. The popular notion blowing hard through New
York then was that the Yankees couldn't let their center fielder
take a free-agent hike and get nothing in return. How ridiculous
that position seems now, not to mention last November's brainstorm
to pollute the clubhouse with Albert Belle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pitches that Aaron Sele threw with two strikes on him, 95
percent of the hitters swing at those,'' said Doug Melvin, the
Rangers' general manager, who as the Yankees' director of scouting
signed Williams for $15,000 in 1985. ``The thing I admire about
Bernie is his patience at the plate. Great patience.''
</P>
<P>
   On that score, Williams is not alone in the lineup. A team once
embodied by an impetuous man in a turtleneck knit is hailed now for
its intelligent hitters who torture pitchers deep into the count.
By a manager who strikes a dugout pose so relaxed you occasionally
wonder if he's indifferent, or asleep.
</P>
<P>
   Patience is more than a virtue, it's virtually the essential
staple of this sport. These Yankees did not panic earlier this
season when left field looked bare, or when the second baseman
couldn't throw the ball, or when their division lead wasn't very
big. These Yankees tend to bank on track record, on trust. That's
no guarantee they will win the World Series, or even Game 2
Thursday night. Only that they have given themselves their very
best shot. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
