<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
  The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following sports
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Oct. 7 and thereafter. For questions about stories, resends or
inquiries, call Eddie Ibardolasa at (818) 713-3602. 
 
 
FBN-NFL (Atlanta) _ Houston was awarded an NFL franchise. So what's
next for Los Angeles as far as getting an existing team? Michael
Ovitz has the option on the Hollywood Park land until Friday. The
Coliseum people are still trumpeting their venue, but it is more
than clear to everyone except them that the Coliseum is
unacceptable to the NFL. How about other sites? 
By Steve Dilbeck. (Will move on the ``s'' sports file.) 
 
 
FBN-CANDIDATES (Atlanta) _ If L.A.'s hope of getting a team is one
that is already playing in another city, which teams are wanting to
move? Obviously, Al Davis wants back in L.A. Is this feasible? The
Arizona Cardinals, Minnesota Vikings, New Orleans Saints, Buffalo
Bills and San Francisco 49ers have been mentioned as possible teams
moving to L.A. 
By Steve Dilbeck. (Will move on the ``s'' sports file.) 
 
 
FBN-MODESTI-COLUMN (Los Angeles) _ Everyone came out a winner when
Houston was awrded an expansion franchise. Obviously Houston won,
the NFL won because it got an unbelievable franchise fee, Al Davis
won because this leaves the L.A. door open; and L.A. won, because
it showed that it really didn't want a team. 
By Kevin Modesti. (Will move on the ``s'' sports file.) 
 
 
FBN-CROUSE-COLUMN (Los Angeles) _ Just say NO to the NFL. We're
happy we didn't get an expansion team, and we don't want to be used
as leverage for every owner who wants a new stadium deal. 
By Karen Crouse. (Will move on the ``s'' sports file.) 
 
 
FBN-TORTURE (Los Angeles) _ NFL owners put Los Angeles' prospective
owners, city and state officials through torture and considerable
expense when, in the end, the city never stood a chance because
there was no political will to spend public money on a team. 
By Rick Orlov. (Will move on the ``s'' sports file.) 
 
 
FBN-NFLSIDEBAR (Los Angeles) _ Why did the NFL need a franchise in
L.A.? TV revenue. 
Los Angeles Daily News. (Will move on the ``s'' sports file.) 
 
 
