<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WORLD'S GREATEST DESTINATION: HERE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Money magazine named San Francisco the best big city in the
country to live in. The magazine, which is apparently geared toward
readers with moolah to spare, said the city has good air quality,
first-rate museums, sports and the most restaurants per resident of
any city in the country. The story also mentioned a ``wide range of
recreational opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, the latest edition of National Geographic Traveler
magazine _ whose editors are more moved by poetry than quantities
of menus and racketball courts _ includes San Francisco in the 50
Places of a Lifetime listed in its ``World's Greatest
Destinations'' issue. Writes  &UR; George Leonard &LR; :
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometime after midnight, you are awakened from a deep sleep by
the sensation that your house has been jarred by something
shockingly heavy. A second later, the familiar motion begins. ...
Crescendo becomes diminuendo. You start breathing again. You lie
there in the stillness, and it seems the moon is drifting ghostly
music down the starlit sky into the room, turning the bureau, the
chair, the mirror a pale silver. The sounds of the city float in to
blend with the moonlight's silent song.''
</P>
<P>
   And now, a selection of headlines from this week's Chronicle:
``City Cited S.F. Hotel Before Fatal Blaze''; ``Solving S.F.'s
Housing Crunch''; ``Police Pull Body From S.F. Lake''; ``Peninsula
Gets Ready for `Killer' Bees''; ``Wasting Transit Money.'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LETTERS FROM GEORGE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Former President  &UR; George Bush &LR; , who says he'll never write a
memoir, is out with ``All the Best, George Bush'' (Scribner; $30),
a collection of letters and diary entries.
</P>
<P>
   The political material includes this July 1991 diary entry:
 &UR; Al Gore &LR;  is ``an attractive guy, but he says he is a worse speaker
than I. Poor guy's in real trouble if he's worse than I.''
</P>
<P>
   The personal material includes this fragment from a letter to
his mother in the mid-1950s, after the death of the Bushes'
daughter of leukemia left the family (temporarily) with four boys:
</P>
<P>
   ``We need someone who's afraid of frogs. We need someone to cry
when I get mad _ not argue. We need a little one who can kiss
without leaving egg or jam or gum. We need a girl. We had one once
...''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SUNNY AND WARM &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The challenge: Find a word device that will bring to mind
1-831-656-1725, the telephone number for San Francisco Bay Area
weather information. Most suggestions stumbled over the number 1
(which doesn't have a dial letter). Readers suggested trying
www.phonespell.org, &LR;   &LR;  which didn't improve on their own brains.
</P>
<P>
   Then came  &UR; Rick Robinson &LR; , a professor at Laney College.
Immortalizing his daughters,  &UR; Mollie  &LR; and  &UR; Kathryn &LR; , Robinson
presented a poetic solution:
</P>
<P>
   ``Mollie Kate's/ had three blind dates,/ A disappointed gal .../
1 VD, 1 OK, 'N' 1 PAL.''
</P>
<P>
   (Respectful bows to runners-up  &UR; Peter Stein &LR; , &UR; Michael Jarvis
 &LR; and
 &UR; Joni Hinkan &LR; ).
</P>
<P>
   P.S. Three thousand pounds of sand have been carted into
Flyswat, a South of Market software startup company, to create an
artificial in-house beach. Chief executive  &UR; John Rodkin  &LR; said the
beach, which has a telephone, has been used for a few meetings and
a party last week featuring fruity drinks.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Rodkin says he's from San Diego, loves the beach, &LR;  and
wanted to give employees who work ``a lot of hours'' the feeling
that they have access to nature.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Dan Mankin  &LR; saw a panhandler in San Jose with a sign: ``Will
work for thousands of dollars and stock bonus.'' And
 &UR; Andrew Hoyem &LR;  saw a panhandler at Geary and Franklin with a sign
that read, ``Out of Work Fashion Model Needs Help.'' He looked
messy, said Hoyem, but he had the height.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Marilyn Green  &LR; forwards a personal ad in the Palo Alto Weekly
in which a ``loving father'' says he's interviewing candidates for
a mate for ``36-year-old son who is too busy and too remote to find
the right life companion.'' Pops will interview candidates and
promises to fly ones he deems suitable to Southern California to
meet Sonny Boy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really looking forward, as I get older and older, to being
less and less nice. I meant it. That's really my agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Annette Bening in US magazine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
