<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8836 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-NFL-HNS &LR;      10-06 1346
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL AWARDS HOUSTON, NOT LOS ANGELES, 32ND FRANCHISE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Photo available on the NYT database) 
(Eds.: Optional trim and ending included) 
 
By JOHN WILLIAMS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The National Football League awarded its 32nd
franchise to businessman Bob McNair on Wednesday, agreeing to
return to Houston in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   As part of a record $700 million transaction, the NFL agreed to
McNair's stipulation that Houston get the first available Super
Bowl, likely in 2004.
</P>
<P>
   NFL owners, tired of debating expansion for more than two years,
chose a firm deal in Houston over a speculative one in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great day for Houston and I hope a great day for
football,'' McNair, founder of Cogen Technologies Inc., said upon
winning the franchise. ``Houston is in the hotbed of football, as
you all know. And Texas is a great area for football.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just delighted that we're able to bring the NFL back to
Houston,'' he said. ``We're going to have a world-class stadium.``
</P>
<P>
   League owners voted 29-0-2 to award McNair the franchise, with
the St. Louis Rams and Arizona Cardinals abstaining, during a short
meeting Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The owners initially courted Los Angeles because it has about
three times as many television viewers as Houston. Last March, they
voted 29-2 to award Los Angeles the franchise, provided it could
come up with a satisfactory ownership team and stadium deal.
</P>
<P>
   But with no public money forthcoming, neither developer Ed Roski
nor Hollywood deal maker Michael Ovitz could complete a firm
proposal.
</P>
<P>
   The owners said McNair's offer _ the highest ever made for any
U.S. sports team and at least $150 million more than the bids by
Roski or Ovitz _ was a major factor in the rapid conclusion of the
process.
</P>
<P>
   ``He put up the biggest price there has ever been, that did the
job,'' said Tennessee Titans owner Bud Adams, who initially held
out for $1 billion but eventually supported McNair. Adams moved the
Houston Oilers to Tennessee after the 1996 season and later changed
the name to Titans.
</P>
<P>
   McNair, who 18 months ago thought the fee might be as low as
$400 million, said he made the $700 million offer to distinguish it
from any of the vague proposals from Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   In the words of Steve Patterson, executive vice president of
McNair's Houston NFL Holdings, ``If you're in a heavyweight bout,
you can't outpoint the champion, you have to knock him out.``
</P>
<P>
   But owners and league officials said other considerations put
Houston ahead of Los Angeles. McNair was able to promise the city
would use public financing to help build a state-of-the-art stadium
and the ownership team would be of a quality that Los Angeles had
not shown it could match, said NFL Commissioner Paul Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue praised Houston's plans for a retractable-roof
stadium, allowing games to be played in comfort whatever the
weather. Coupled with anticipated improvements at the Astrodomain
Complex and a rail linking downtown with the complex, Houston
likely could get several Super Bowls in the future, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue also said Houston's fan base appears to be stronger
than Los Angeles', an indication the city can sell out more games
and avoid the television blackouts the league loathes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the overall sense that (Houston) was virtually certain
to be a guaranteed success and that we didn't have that kind of
pulse in Los Angeles,'' Tagliabue said.
</P>
<P>
   Owners also complimented McNair, lauding the patience and
perseverance he has shown in the two-year process. They also said
he is a visionary businessman who can help the league find new ways
to market the sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob's such a class act, and Houston's a great football town,''
said Expansion Committee Co-Chairman Bob Kraft, owner of the New
England Patriots. ``It's a first-class stadium. The ownership and
stadium speak volumes about the future of the NFL.``
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   McNair, at a Houston press conference with Mayor Lee Brown,
said, ``It's especially pleasing to me for us to win this victory
because I don't think Houston's been shown the proper respect in
this process.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to bite our tongue a few times and be very patient. But
we felt like that we would prevail in the end and that we had the
best opportunity for the NFL, and the proposal that we submitted to
them was clearly superior to any others.''
</P>
<P>
   Owners said there was little discussion in the Wednesday meeting
about Houston's bid, especially after Tagliabue had been unable to
get Ovitz into a bidding war the night before. Instead, the owners'
hourlong talk Wednesday centered on how to restructure a 32-team
league.
</P>
<P>
   They agreed to begin the 2002 season with eight divisions, four
each in the American Football and National Football Conferences.
The exact alignment is to be determined later, but one current AFC
team will have to move to the NFC. Each conference now has three
divisions, one with six teams and the others with five.
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue said a decision will be made later about the makeup of
the eight divisions, but the Houston franchise will play in the AFC
and the Cowboys will remain in the NFC.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Cleveland Browns owner Al Lerner, who paid his $470
million franchise upon receipt of the 31st expansion franchise last
year, McNair will have five years to pay the $700 million. He will
make $150 million payments every Jan. 15 from 2000 until 2005, then
a final $100 million Jan. 15, 2004.
</P>
<P>
   On April 1, 2002, McNair will begin collecting television and
marketing revenues, giving him almost three years of earnings to
help pay the franchise fee.
</P>
<P>
   McNair's fee is the highest for a professional franchise in this
country. In May, Daniel Snyder paid $800 million for the Washington
Redskins, but in that deal he got $50 million in cash and a stadium
valued at $160 million.
</P>
<P>
   McNair said he realized he was paying a premium, but he expects
the team to earn a profit after the start-up years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly more than I ever anticipated,'' McNair said.
``But I think that we can have a successful football operation and
if I didn't think we could do that, I would not submit that bid.
But I think it raised . . . the expectations to a new level.``
</P>
<P>
   Dallas Cowboys owner Jerry Jones said the decision was based
more on the league wanting to expand rather than owners splitting
an expansion fee. He noted that team owners will give up about $1
billion in revenue to McNair in his first 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed to have 32 teams to create a competitive balance,
and we needed to be in Houston,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Other terms of the deal:
</P>
<P>
   _ McNair's team will get the first pick in the 2002 NFL draft
and an additional pick in each round during 2002 and 2003 drafts.
The arrangement is the same as Cleveland's.
</P>
<P>
   _ The league will waive a requirement that he share 34 percent
of permanent seat license sales with the other franchise owners.
</P>
<P>
   McNair said he now must set up an office to sell at least 75 of
the proposed 110 luxury suites at the stadium by mid-January, a
requirement set by the NFL. The marketing office will also begin
selling Personal Seat Licenses, which are expected to provide $50
million toward stadium construction and design.
</P>
<P>
   A phone line already has been established for fans seeking to
get on a priority list for season tickets. Requests to be placed on
the list will be accepted beginning at 9 a.m. today. The number is
1-877-635-2002.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston NFL Holdings will eventually seek community input for a
team name and colors. McNair said he doesn't have one in mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would like to have a name that is reflective of the area of
the country that we represent, and we will go through that process
and ask our fans to help out with our selection,'' McNair said.
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue said the Oilers name ``has been retired, like the
jersey of a great player.``
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
