<SLUG> BC-CHEM-BIO07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    OUTDATED APPROACHES SEEN TO TWENTY-FIRST CENTUIRY WAR THREATS
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The U.S. defense establishment is responding to
rapidly changing 21st century threats with outdated Cold War
concepts, according to an expert on non-standard defense systems.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at a conference on chemical and biological threats,
Robert Carnes, former director of the Marine Corps' ``Deep
Futures'' combat planning progam, warned that defense planners and
weapons developers continue to rely more heavily on ideas that were
relevant to the nation-against-nation struggles of the past than on
military realities ahead.
</P>
<P>
   The conference was sponsored by Jane's Information Group, the
London-based publisher of books and periodicals on military
technology. Particpants, who paid over $800 each to attend,
consisted primarily of officials of the U.S. Secret Service, the
Central Intelligence Agency, Defense Department intelligence
agencies and other federal departments.
</P>
<P>
   Austin, Texas, police Detective Jim Neilson and hazardous
materials Fire Chief David Fiero were among a handful of local
public safety officials to at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are returning to the state that existed in the pre-1600s,
when wars were fought over race or religion or within countries,''
said Carnes, now a research associate professor at Georgetown
University School of Medicine. Europe is ``replete'' with
circumstances leading to such warfare, he said, but military
establishments continue to prepare as if planning to fight a war
against another country.
</P>
<P>
   He also warned that developers of the technology on which
federal, state and local officials must depend in cases of
terrorist attacks with chemical or biological weapons are still too
wedded to outdated concepts.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is the threat and what are we trying to achieve?'' he
asked. ``The threat could be stolen phosgene gas or anhydrous
ammonia or some guy in his basement, stirring up a biological
agent.''
</P>
<P>
   Phosgene was a nerve gas used during World War I and is now used
as a commercial feeder chemical. More than 3.2 billion pounds will
be produced legally in the United States this year.
</P>
<P>
   Anhydrous amonia is the fertilizer ingedient used to manufacture
the bomb that blew up the federal office building in Oklahoma City.
</P>
<P>
   Neilson said he thought the Austin fire and police departments
were somewhat unusual among U.S. cities in the advance cooperation
they have undertaken to prepare for a potential chemical or
biological terrorist incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can jointly get together the equipment and procedures
worked out in advance, we won't end up at some disaster, trying to
decide who does what, `` said Neilson, who said he works out of the
police department bomb squad.
</P>
<P>
   endit
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
