<HEADER>
A8842 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-DIVIDENDS-MARKETPLACE     10-06 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIVIDENDS-MARKETPLACE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKETPLACE: FADING DIVIDENDS DON'T ALWAYS SIGNAL RECESSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: A graphic is  being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If the measure of corporate America's financial
health is its ability and willingness to increase dividends to
shareholders, then you might think the country is in a recession.
</P>
<P>
   Standard &AMP; Poor's Corp. reports that 117 companies announced
dividend increases in September, 10 fewer than had raised their
payouts a year earlier. It was the 15th consecutive month that the
number of dividend increases was down year-over-year.
</P>
<P>
   By itself, such a long string of relative bad news is not
extraordinary, even though you might expect that more and more
companies would raise dividends every year simply because the
number of stocks traded rises every year.
</P>
<P>
   What is unusual is that the economy is doing so well even while
companies are growing more reluctant to raise their dividends. This
is the seventh such streak of at least 15 months since S&AMP;P began
counting dividend increases back in 1955. In all but one of the six
previous runs, there was a recession in the period. Recessions, of
course, usually mean sharp falloffs in corporate profits. So a
dearth of dividend increases in such periods should be expected.
</P>
<P>
   The exception _ the time when companies cut back on dividend
increases even as the economy continued to grow _ is the most
interesting case, with perhaps the most relevance to the current
situation. From August 1966 through March 1968, there was a string
of 21 months in which the number of dividend increases kept
falling.
</P>
<P>
   That came during the longest expansion in American history,
which began in 1961 and ended in 1969. The current expansion is the
second longest, and will take over the top spot if, as seems
likely, no recession starts by February.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the late-1960s market, memorably called ``the go-go
years'' by the business writer John Brooks, bears more than a
passing resemblance to this one. The stock market had been going up
steadily for the better part of two decades, amid increasing public
participation and interest. Mutual fund managers became media stars
as their funds soared through the purchase of small technology
stocks that zoomed in price. There was a huge wave of mergers, many
financed by issuing highly valued stock.
</P>
<P>
   In 1968, however, the good days were nearing an end. It was not
just that a recession hit at the end of 1969. It was that the stock
market was also entering a long period of poor returns that would
lead to widespread public rejection of stocks as an investment
vehicle. While the major indexes would move to marginal new highs
the next few years, the big gains were over. Fourteen years after
1968, in 1982, stock prices were still below the 1968 highs.
</P>
<P>
   There are differences, of course. An important one now is the
spread of stock options as a major form of compensation for
corporate executives. Option holders benefit from price rises in
the stocks of their companies, but not from dividends that are paid
while they hold the options. That provides an incentive for
companies to hold down dividends and, instead, distribute money to
shareholders by repurchasing stock. Such stock repurchases are
popular and many companies have borrowed money to buy back stock.
</P>
<P>
   Another difference is that dividends are now far lower than they
were in 1968, at least as a percentage of the price of stocks. In
1968, the dividend yield on the Standard &AMP; Poor's index of 500
stocks when the index peaked was 2.8 percent. That was, in fact, a
very low figure by historical standards. But now the yield is about
1.3 percent, well below half that level.
</P>
<P>
   Dividends can go so low because investors do not care much about
them. It is capital gains that have made them rich, and it is the
pursuit of capital gains that drives stock investments now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Companies love this flexibility, not being tied into a fixed
dividend that may be a struggle to pay,'' said Arnold Kaufman, the
editor of Standard &AMP; Poor's Outlook, a newsletter that tracks
dividends.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, companies have always loved such flexibility. What is
different is that investors have gradually come to believe that
payouts are unimportant, and so have not fought very hard for
higher payouts. ``It is working quite well for everyone involved,
except for those poor people who have come to depend on dividends
for living expenses,'' commented Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   After 1968, as it became clear that capital losses were also
possible, investors came to value dividends, and the pressure grew
on companies to pay them. By the time the stock market hit bottom
in 1974, the dividend yield on the S&AMP;P 500 was up to 5.8 percent.
Part of the reason was that dividends had risen since 1968, but
most of the change reflected a fall in stock prices.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
