u a BC-YOGURT-SLAYINGS-HNS &LR;      10-06 1143
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOGURT-SLAYINGS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOUR ARRESTED IN CONNECTION WITH YOGURT SHOP SLAYINGS IN 1991 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Optional ending included) 
 
By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Nearly eight years after the crime stunned the
city, four men were arrested Wednesday in connection with one of
Austin's most painful memories _ the gruesome murders of four
teen-age girls during a 1991 yogurt shop robbery that netted $50.
</P>
<P>
   All four suspects were charged with capital murder in the
slayings of Eliza Hope Thomas, 17; Amy Ayers, 13; Jennifer
Harbison, 17, and her sister, Sarah, 15.
</P>
<P>
   Still calling it an unfinished investigation, officials shared
few details about the arrests or precisely what led them to the
suspects.
</P>
<P>
   However, affidavits said one of the suspects, who was not
identified by police because he was a juvenile at the time of the
murders, first told authorities about their involvement eight days
after the grisly slayings, but police assumed he was lying.
</P>
<P>
   A second suspect also was not identified in the affidavits
because he was a juvenile when the crimes were committed Dec. 6,
1991.
</P>
<P>
   Although not identified by police, prosecutors identified them
in a detention hearing as Maurice Pierce, 24, and Forrest Wellborn,
23.
</P>
<P>
   Pierce was arrested in the Dallas suburb of Lewisville and
Wellborn was picked up in Lockhart, about 30 miles south of Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Pending indictment, both of the then-juveniles were placed in
the Travis County Jail in lieu of bonds of $1 million and $1.5
million. A judge will decide later whether to certify them for
trial as adults. If convicted as adults, their maximum sentence
would be life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Facing possible death sentences are two men who were 17 at the
time of the killings. Police said they arrested former Austin
resident Robert Burns Springsteen Jr., 26, in Charleston, W. Va.,
and Michael James Scott, 26, in Buda, about 20 miles south of
Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Both men, who were held without bond, provided police with
written statements last month confessing their guilt, according to
the arrest warrants filed in Travis County district court with the
juvenile's names blotted out.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the confession,'' the affidavit stated, ``Michael Scott
admits that he and (blank) Rob Springsteen and (blank) had planned
the robbery that evening and went in when the business was open to
case the place and unlock the back door.
</P>
<P>
   ``They went back after it was closed and while (blank) waited in
the car as a lookout, the others went inside the unlocked back
door, stole money from the store and shot and killed all 4 &UR;  &LR; of the
girls inside.''
</P>
<P>
   It continued: ``In his confession, Michael Scott gave details of
the crime that should have been known only by the killers,
including the items used as ligatures on the victims and placement
of the victims' bodies.''
</P>
<P>
   Further, the affidavit by an Austin police detective said that
when Springsteen was interrogated Sept. 15 in West Virginia, he
``confirmed that he was carrying a semiautomatic handgun of the
same caliber as the shell casing that had been found at the
scene.''
</P>
<P>
   All four of the girls had been bound, gagged and shot twice in
the head before their bodies were nearly incinerated in a fire that
was deliberately set to conceal the crimes, police said. At least
one of the girls was sexually assaulted before being slain, police
said.
</P>
<P>
   The brutality of the case spread panic through the city, still
associated with Charles Whitman's 1966 sniper attack from the
University of Texas tower that left 16 dead and 31 wounded. And 10
months later, the public got a sense of relief when two Mexican
citizens were arrested in Mexico City and supposedly confessed to
the crimes.
</P>
<P>
   However, the men were never charged and claimed they were
coerced into making false admissions. They remain incarcerated on
other charges.
</P>
<P>
   In the years that passed, family members won a $12 million civil
judgment against the shop owners and others for failing to provide
a safe workplace for the two victims who worked in the shop.
</P>
<P>
   One of the victim's parents became an outspoken critic of
workplace safety laws, while others tried to move on by moving away
from Austin to as far away as Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   ``There probably has been no single event in our community that
has made us feel less like a sleepy college town than the murders
of those four young girls,'' said Mayor Kirk Watson.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time, we all asked how could something horrific, so
unexplainable, happen here. And no one could answer the question,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``For eight years, we've all waited for the word that our police
department is close to a point of solving a crime that has haunted
our very souls, that they've been able to identify and arrest
suspects that they allege are responsible for one of the most
heinous crimes that our community has ever experienced. Today, we
finally get to hear those words,'' the mayor said.
</P>
<P>
   Added Police Chief Sam Knee: ``That is what this case is about _
bringing to justice four individuals for the brutal murder of four
little girls.''
</P>
<P>
   He hailed the investigative team work shown by his department,
state and federal prosecutors, the Texas Rangers and the U.S.
Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have all taken it personally, just as this entire community
has taken it personally,'' said Travis County District Attorney
Ronnie Earle.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Knee said the arrests resulted from a fresh look at the case
that was made possible by a downturn in Austin homicides, freeing
up investigators to re-examine old leads.
</P>
<P>
   One of those leads resulted from a simple arrest that occurred
Dec. 14, 1991, at a mall close to the yogurt shop, which never
reopened after the murders.
</P>
<P>
   According to the arrest warrants, one of the then-juveniles was
arrested at the mall that day for unlawfully carrying a weapon _ a
.22-caliber revolver that was in the waistband of his pants. Since
police knew that was the kind of gun used in the quadruple homicide
the previous week, detectives questioned the teen-ager.
</P>
<P>
   ``During that questioning, (blank) told them that his gun had
been used in the murders, but that he had loaned it to (blank) that
night and (blank) had it at the time of the murders.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Blank) also told detectives details of what occurred inside
the yogurt shop during the murders, but said (blank) had just told
(blank) those things.
</P>
<P>
   ``The police questioned (blank) and decided that (blank) had not
done the murders and assumed that (blank) was lying and had just
made up the whole story about his gun being used,'' the detective's
statement said.
</P>
<P>
   It was not immediately clear what happened to the gun or whether
it was tested at the time.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
