<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 20:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8848 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-DNA-SOLVING-CRIMES-(T     10-06 1414
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DNA-SOLVING-CRIMES-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WANTED FOR RAPE: JOHN DOE, WHO IS KNOWN ONLY BY HIS DNA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wis., Ohio, Ill., Calif., Ala., Va., Fla.)  (bl) 
 By BILL DEDMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ In a novel legal gambit that stretches the law to
match the developing science of DNA, a prosecutor in Wisconsin has
filed rape and kidnapping charges against a defendant who has no
name. John Doe is known only by his DNA code, extracted from semen
samples from three rapes, samples which have been tested after six
years of storage in a police property room.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that one person raped these three women,'' said the
prosecutor, Norman Gahn, assistant district attorney for Milwaukee
County. ``We just don't know who that person is. We will catch
him.''
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor's strategy is an attempt to keep the six-year
time limit for bringing a charge from running out in the only one
of the three cases where that has not already happened. A warrant
must identify the person to be arrested, and this one names ``John
Doe, unknown male with matching deoxyribonucleic acid profile.''
The warrant, signed by a judge in September, will keep the statute
of limitations from expiring, which in this case would otherwise
happen in November. Now, every month, an FBI computer will compare
the numbers that describe John Doe's DNA with thousands of samples
from felons and crime scene evidence.
</P>
<P>
   The case reveals several gaps between the law and science. Can a
person be identified on a warrant by biometric evidence, such as a
DNA code or fingerprint, or is a more traditional behavioral
identification required, such as a name and date of birth? And is
the legal concept of a statute of limitations relevant in an age of
DNA testing of old evidence? Legal experts said the case would be
challenged, but has merit.
</P>
<P>
   The case also reveals the promise and limitations of the
national DNA databank, which is one year old this month.
</P>
<P>
   Much attention has focused on the promise. The FBI says the DNA
databank has helped solve 583 cases, such as the serial rapist in
Washington, D.C., linked with a serial rapist in Florida. Police
routinely collect DNA evidence not only in rape cases but from
saliva on beer cans left behind by a burglar, from sweat on a
baseball bat used in a beating, from blood on a bullet that passed
through a suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Less attention has been paid to the holes in the system. Only 18
of 50 states are hooked into the FBI databank, known as the
Combined DNA Index System (CODIS), while the rest are working on
the technology and the funding. The databank is still far smaller
than the FBI's fingerprint bank. State crime labs are far behind in
their work. Much DNA evidence that is collected is never analyzed.
</P>
<P>
   Approximately 180,000 rape kits _ evidence from only one type of
crime _ sit unexamined on shelves in police departments across the
nation, according to a new survey of police agencies commissioned
by the National Commission for the Future of DNA Evidence. These
flat rectangular boxes include blood vials, swabs of semen, a lock
of hair, and fingernail scrapings _ evidence collected from rape
victims in a humiliating ritual.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   New York City alone has 12,000 unexamined rape kits, and is
trying to reduce the backlog by contracting with private
laboratories. It has stopped destroying untested kits after five
years, but other police departments continue the practice.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the technology to solve these crimes, and we're not
doing it'' said Christopher Asplen, executive director of the DNA
commission.
</P>
<P>
   Many police departments still use DNA evidence as they have used
fingerprints and tire tracks, to rule a suspect in or out. But the
new DNA databanks make the evidence useful for matching cases to
convicted offenders, or to other cases in which a suspect may be
known.
</P>
<P>
   About 40 percent of the police agencies in the survey reported
that they test all or nearly all samples for DNA. About one-third
of the agencies test less often. And about one-quarter weren't
sure.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Cities vary widely in their use of DNA testing. In Cleveland,
``We only do DNA testing when there's an identifiable suspect,''
said Lt. Edward Thiery, spokesman for the Cleveland Police
Department.
</P>
<P>
   In Chicago, ``We now submit every sample for testing, but we
still have a backlog of untested samples,'' said Pat Camden,
spokesman for the Chicago Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   In Los Angeles, the police department buys a new, 40-foot
refrigerated trailer truck every six months, just to hold DNA
evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Los Angeles Police Department, right now, if you didn't
have a suspect in custody and a court date, that thing is not going
to get analyzed, whatever it is,'' Maria Foster, a detective
supervisor, told the DNA commission. ``When you got a court date,
when you go to trial, then it will happen.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The three DNA samples that identified a serial rapist in
Milwaukee were collected in 1993. In each case, on the city's north
side, a man grabbed a woman from behind, told her that he had a
knife, took her to a quiet place, raped her, and demanded money,
police said. After she reported the crime, vaginal and cervical
swabs of semen were collected at a hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The samples waited at the police evidence room, along with 2,300
other unexamined rape kits. To test them all would have swamped the
state crime lab, which already has a backlog.
</P>
<P>
   So Detective Lori Gaglione and her colleagues in the city's
Sensitive Crimes Unit winnowed down to the best cases, based mostly
on human factors, such as the availability of victims and
witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   From the 53 samples that were tested, one case matched a
convicted rapist in Minnesota. Another matched a convicted rapist
elsewhere in Wisconsin, allowing charges to be filed only eight
hours before the statute of limitations expired.
</P>
<P>
   And the three samples were found to match each other.
</P>
<P>
   The law in Wisconsin, as in other states, requires that a
warrant identify the accused. If the name is not known, the law
allows identification ``by any description by which the person to
be arrested can be identified with reasonable certainty.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My argument is going to be that genetic code goes well beyond
reasonable certainty,'' Gahn said. ``We're pushing the envelope as
far as we can. It does something for the victim of the sexual
assaullt, to know that someone cares and to know that we're out
there working on the case.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The forensic science supervisor in the state crime lab, Dirk
Janssen, said that the probability of randomly selecting an
unrelated individual who would have a DNA profile matching the
three samples would be approximately 1 in 7.25 billion _ more than
the world's population _ in the U.S. Caucasian population, and 1 in
1.96 billion in the African-American population.
</P>
<P>
   Such a John Doe warrant has been used at least one other time,
in a Kansas case in 1991. No one was caught, so the issue has not
been tested.
</P>
<P>
   The warrant appears to have merit, said Myrna Raeder, a
professor of law at Southwestern University in Los Angeles and the
former head of the criminal section of the American Bar
Association.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is not frivolous,'' Professor Raeder said. ``It's clearly
novel and therefore courts are really going to have to struggle
with the intention of the statute and whether the clear meaning of
the statute would cover this.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   As in most states, only people convicted of sexual offenses in
Wisconsin are required to give samples for DNA testing. The
Legislature is on the verge of expanding that to all felony
offenses, as Alabama and Virginia have done. In addition, the
Legislature is considering eliminating the statute of limitations
in cases of rape, as Florida has done.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Doe warrants are most commonly used when the accused is know
by an alias or by a physical description. The Milwaukee case,
however, used only DNA information.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors hope that someday, perhaps even 20 years from now, a
man will leave a cigarette behind at another rape, or cut himself
on broken glass at a burglary. His saliva or blood will be tested,
its DNA catalogued and entered in the FBI databank.
</P>
<P>
   And he will be charged with raping and kidnapping a woman in
Milwaukee on Nov. 9, 1993.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
