<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 20:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8849 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-NIXON-ANTI-SEMITISM-N     10-06 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIXON-ANTI-SEMITISM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAPES REVEAL NIXON'S USE OF ANTI-SEMITIC REMARKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By IRVIN MOLOTSKY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The release of the latest batch of conversations
secretly taped by President Nixon depict him again as
un-self-consciously anti-Semitic, informing his aides at one point
that the communist conspiracy against the United States was made up
entirely of Jews except for Whitaker Chambers and Alger Hiss.
</P>
<P>
   The tapes also show the depth of his anger against The New York
Times for its publication in 1971 of the Pentagon Papers, the
government's secret history of activities that led to America's
involvement in the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon's anti-Semitism and his anger at The Times came together
when he demanded that no one in the White House provide any
information to the newspaper's Washington bureau, which was headed
at the time by Max Frankel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't give them anything,'' he tells his staff. ``And because
of that damned Jew Frankel all the time _ he's bad, you know. Don't
give him anything.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Frankel, who retired as executive editor of The
Times and now writes a column for the Times Sunday Magazine, said
of Nixon's comment: ``It's a vulgarity that puts me in very good
company. Almost a badge of honor.''
</P>
<P>
   But Frankel added that after Nixon left office and was trying
rehabilitate his image he wrote letters complementing Times
editorials and invited Frankel and other editors to his home for
lunch.
</P>
<P>
   The gist of what is in the tapes has been depicted before as a
result of court decisions that made the recordings available to the
public through the National Archives.
</P>
<P>
   The latest batch of tapes consists of 445 hours of conversations
from February through July 1971, a period that includes publication
of the Pentagon Papers by The Times and the Supreme Court decision
upholding the newspaper's right to publish them.
</P>
<P>
   One person the White House suspected of supplying the Pentagon
Papers was Daniel Ellsberg, the Defense Department analyst.
Speaking of Ellsberg, Nixon says: ``Incidentally, I hope to God,
he's not Jewish, is he?''
</P>
<P>
   Another, unidentified voice, answers, ``I'm sure he is.
Ellsberg?''
</P>
<P>
   Nixon then says: ``I hope not, I hope not,'' adding, ``It's a
bad thing for us.'' The president then turned the conversation to
people targeted in investigations against communists.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only two non-Jews in the communist conspiracy,'' he said,
``were Chambers and Hiss. Many felt that Hiss was. He could have
been a half, but he was not by religion. The only two non-Jews.
Every other one was a Jew. And it raised hell with us.''
</P>
<P>
   Alger Hiss, a high-ranking State Department official, was
convicted of perjury for denying that he was a communist, and
Nixon's early reputation was built on his determination to get Hiss
convicted.
</P>
<P>
   The Richard Nixon Library and Birthplace Foundation in Yorba
Linda, Calif., issued a statement declaring that the president was
not anti-Semitic. Noting that he had many Jewish advisers, it said,
``The president's words about the Jewish community on these tapes
show that his basic sense of compassion and support for these
communities tends to coexist with terminology from an earlier
time.''
</P>
<P>
   The library added that Nixon appointed many Jews to high
positions in his administration and was a strong supporter of
Israel. ``The actions of the president, as well as the substantial
documentary record of the Nixon administration, should always be
kept in mind when evaluating his words on the White House tapes.''
</P>
<P>
   The tapes provide additional evidence that Nixon, who in public
criticized people who used foul language, used similar language in
private.
</P>
<P>
   On June 16, 1971, Nixon again showed his penchant for singling
out Jews when an aide said Judge Murray I. Gurfein had been
assigned the case brought by the Nixon administration to halt
publication of the Pentagon Papers by The Times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like Gurfein fine,'' Nixon says. ``He's a Jew, a liberal.
But I think tough. I think tough. But he may be sucking up to the
liberal left. In New York, you just can't tell what happens to
those guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Nixon also wondered out loud whether Leslie Gelb, who had been
the director of policy planning at the Defense Department and was
then a senior fellow at the Brookings Institution, had put copies
of the Pentagon papers in a safe at Brookings.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to his aide H.R. Haldeman, Nixon says: ``My point is,
Bob, my point is, we have got, we have here now, this, this is a
very bad situation, this guy is a radical that did it.''
</P>
<P>
   Haldeman suggests that it was Ellsberg.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon responds, ``Yeah, well, we don't know who the hell it is,
but maybe it's him, or maybe it's Gelb, one of the two, either's a
radical.'' He added, ``Somebody's got to go to jail for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Gelb, who was later a reporter and then an editor for The Times
and is now president of the Council on Foreign Relations, said
Wednesday that Nixon's mistrust of him was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no Pentagon Papers,'' Gelb said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
