<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFL-EXPANSION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL GOES BACK TO HOUSTON FOR $700 MILLION  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The value of professional sports teams took another
dramatic boost Wednesday when the National Football League approved
Robert McNair's $700 million bid for an expansion franchise in
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   McNair's purchase of the franchise will be the most expensive in
American sports history, and the approval ended for now rival
efforts to win a new NFL franchise for Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   League officials also voted to realign from six divisions _ five
with five teams and one with six _ into eight divisions of four
teams each. While no details were given, the realignment may
resolve some of the league's geographical anomalies. The new
Houston franchise will begin play in 2002. It seems likely that the
realignment will occur then, too, but league officials did not say
when realignment would take place.
</P>
<P>
   As an expansion fee, the $700 million sum is staggering, because
McNair's team has no past, no players, no name, no logo, no fan
clubs. Only six years ago, Jacksonville and Carolina paid $140
million expansion fees. Last year, Alfred Lerner paid $530 million
for the renascent Cleveland Browns franchise, which has revived the
team's history, colors and fan base. The Redskins were sold to a
group led by Daniel Snyder in May for $805 million, but $160
million is earmarked to pay the debt on the team's privately owned
stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an awful lot of money,'' McNair said after the 29-to-2
vote here by the league's owners. ``But we've got a tremendous
product in NFL football, and a stadium that'll knock your socks
off.''
</P>
<P>
   The Houston team will play in a planned $310 million stadium to
be built next to the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, McNair, an energy billionaire, said his offer ``went
higher than any reasonable person would go.'' But Wednesday, as he
carried a football after his bit was approved, he said, ``I'm more
than happy with the number.''
</P>
<P>
   McNair's bid knocked two Los Angeles rivals out of the running.
Groups led by Michael Ovitz, the talent manager, and Eli Broad, a
financial-services billionaire, competed, sometimes rancorously, to
return a team to the city for the first time since the Raiders left
in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 700 million shocked the league,'' Ovitz said. ``I couldn't
compete with that. I went in there feeling very good, and I'm
incredibly disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that the $195 million public investment McNair had
obtained for his proposed stadium gave him an insurmountable
advantage in the bidding. Ovitz said that he and his partner, Ron
Burkle, a billionaire financier, could not raise their proposed
expansion fee above $550 million. By choosing Houston, the league
went with the 11th largest television market, with 1.7 million
households over Los Angeles, the No. 2 market, with 5.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``On balance,'' said Paul Tagliabue, the NFL commissioner,
``Houston was superior.''
</P>
<P>
   McNair's franchise, which has not been named, will replace the
Oilers, who left in 1996 for Tennessee and who now play in
Nashville as the Titans. The Oilers' name was retired with the
move.
</P>
<P>
   The skyrocketing prices of NFL teams are attributable to the new
eight-year, $17.6 billion network television contracts signed by
the league early last year and the financial strength provided by
new stadiums awash in revenues from luxury suites, club seats,
personal-seat licenses and naming rights.
</P>
<P>
   McNair's new stadium will have nearly 75,000 seats, 110 luxury
suites and 7,700 club seats. In recent weeks, McNair became more
confident that the team would sell enough suites, club seats and
40,000 seat licenses (fees for the right to purchase season
tickets) to justify a $700 million bid. The league sweetened the
deal by guaranteeing a Super Bowl in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Burguieres, vice chairman of McNair's holding company,
the McNair Group, said, ``Seven-hundred million was the only number
the league would do the deal at, but of course, it would have been
better at $600 million.''
</P>
<P>
   At $700 million, McNair said, ``We knew we differentiated
ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What this says is that if you get the ultimate stadium
situation, this is what you'll pay,'' said Michael Ozanian, a
sports valuation expert at Forbes magazine.
</P>
<P>
   McNair's fee guarantees that each of the NFL's 31 teams will
receive $33.3 million. McNair and his partners will pay their fee
in installments of $150 million on Jan. 15 of the next four years,
and $100 million on Jan. 15, 2004.
</P>
<P>
   McNair, 62, can well afford the team. He recently sold his four
co-generation energy plants in New York and New Jersey for $1.5
billion.
</P>
<P>
   The road to approving McNair was paved Tuesday night when he
answered the 14-man expansion committee's lingering questions while
Tagliabue told Ovitz and Ed Roski Jr., Broad's partner, that they
were out of the running. ``I said 24 votes for L.A. was not
possible,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The league had tried desperately since March to fashion a
fundable stadium plan in Los Angeles with the Ovitz and Broad
groups. The league had focused heavily on a renovation plan for the
Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum. But last month, when the Coliseum
project proved too expensive, the league flirted briefly with
Ovitz's hope for a stadium at the Hollywood Park race track in
suburban Inglewood. But that short effort proved too little, too
late. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-99 2037EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
