<DOCNO> NYT19991006.0366 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 20:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8853 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      10-06 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: THE MONEY MACHINE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By BOB HERBERT    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The George W. juggernaut rolled through New York this
week, with the candidate taking some brilliantly aimed shots at his
own party, brokering an end (at least temporarily) to the nasty
feud between Gov. George Pataki and Mayor Rudolph Giuliani,
visiting a black church upstate and a black school in Harlem,
making an educational policy speech at the right-leaning Manhattan
Institute, and visiting for more than an hour with Cardinal John
O'Connor, who has not been well.
</P>
<P>
   That's the high-profile stuff, and Bush is very good at it. But
his real strength, his genius, is raising money. At that, he's a
wizard. He has taken the art of presidential fund-raising to
heights never before seen.
</P>
<P>
   A fund-raiser Tuesday evening at the Sheraton New York Hotel
featured food that was unappetizing, an even worse band (a
five-piece combo struggling with Gershwin one moment and Motown the
next) and Giuliani and Pataki forcing themselves to say, in effect,
``I love you, man.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't matter. The floor of the Imperial Ballroom was packed,
mostly with men in suits. Bush spoke and he was charming. The
evening was short. The take was $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   In just seven or eight months, Bush has raised nearly $60
million, a figure that astounds most political observers. ``No
one's ever seen money like this,'' said Charles Lewis, who heads
the nonpartisan Center for Public Integrity. ``People can't even
comprehend it, the amounts are so large.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Makinson, executive director of the Center for Responsive
Politics, said: ``He's wrapping up the nomination simply by virtue
of the money he's been able to collect. He's sucked the oxygen out
of the air for all of the other candidates.''
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing illegal or improper about Bush raising such
awesome amounts of cash. He is doing the same thing other
politicians do, just on a larger scale. But the fact that one
candidate can raise so much money is deeply troubling to those who
believe that big money in politics concentrates power in too few
hands and thus undermines the very idea of participatory democracy.
</P>
<P>
   The overwhelming influence of money in politics is excluding
from public service those men and women who are qualified but are
not independently wealthy and are unable or unwilling to raise what
often are obscene amounts of campaign cash. It has made raising
money an obsession for those who hold or seek major office. And it
has profoundly discouraged millions of ordinary Americans who
believe their voices are never heard because the politicians are
too busy dancing to the music of the big contributors.
</P>
<P>
   Said Makinson: ``The average American understands that politics
these days is more of a spectator sport than a participatory
sport.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush and his aides have noted, with some justification, that his
campaign receives money from a wide cross-section of the public,
including individuals of ordinary means. But it is also fair to
point out that tens of thousands of individuals have given Bush the
maximum $1,000 you can contribute to a presidential candidate. That
is a lot of money, especially when you consider that in many cases
a husband gives $1,000, a wife gives $1,000, etc.
</P>
<P>
   Makinson put the matter in perspective when he pointed out that
less than one-tenth of 1 percent of all Americans contribute that
kind of money to a candidate or party.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis said 96 percent of Americans do not contribute any money
at all, ``not a dime,'' to politicians at the federal level.
</P>
<P>
   So whether the candidate is George W. Bush or Bill Clinton or
Bob Dole or Al Gore, the big money comes from the nation's elite.
</P>
<P>
   What is both unusual and significant about the Bush campaign is
that Bush's ability to raise such prodigious amounts of cash
enabled him to thumb his nose at the post-Watergate campaign
finance reforms. Bush has decided not to accept Federal matching
funds and therefore will not have to abide by state spending limits
during the primaries.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush funding surge, as thrilling as it must be for the
Governor and his supporters, is pulling the entire nation in the
wrong direction. The true spirit of democracy cannot survive where
cash is king. There were no poor people in the ballroom of the
Sheraton on Tuesday night, just a bad band and big bucks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-99 2040EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
