<SLUG> BC-DELL07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Analysts to gather at Dell's autumn meeting
 &HT;    By Jerry Mahoney
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Dell Computer Corp. plays host to almost 200
analysts at the Four Seasons hotel today in a fall rite designed to
display the company's confidence that it will play a growing role
in an Internet-driven industry.
</P>
<P>
   Executives are expected to outline plans for services aimed at
helping customers expand their use of the Internet from e-commerce
to day-to-day operations such as product design and employee
recruiting.
</P>
<P>
   While there is a consensus among analysts that Dell is doing
many things right, this year has been a disappointment for many
investors and company management because of the stock's
performance.
</P>
<P>
   Dell closed down $0.50 Wednesday at $43.31 1/4 on the Nasdaq
stock exchange. That is 20 percent off the all-time high closing
price of $54.31 1/4 set Feb. 2. While the company continues to lead
the industry in growth and profitability, the closest the stock has
gotten to the February high is $49.56 1/4 on Sept. 10.
</P>
<P>
   It's a notable departure for a stock that has been one of this
decade's top performers.
</P>
<P>
   This year is the first time since 1994 that Dell's board of
directors did not declare a stock split in the second half of the
year. The last split, Dell's seventh in six years, was March 5.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts say they're cautious about the stock's prospects.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Dube of Wasserstein Perella Securities in New York said
wide quarter-to-quarter variations in growth make it hard to
forecast what Dell's revenue will be. Sales growth ranged from 5
percent in the first quarter of last year to 11 percent in the most
recent quarter, which ended July 30. ``What investors are trying to
figure out is what is the annualized revenue growth we should
expect from Dell,'' Dube said.
</P>
<P>
   Lou Mazzucchelli of Gerard Klauer Mattison in New York, who
rates the stock a ``buy,'' said Dell is expensive based on its
price-earnings ratio of 68. By comparison, shares of IBM, a much
bigger and more diverse computer-systems company, are trading at a
P/E ratio of just more than 29.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people still think it's in nose-bleed territory,
relative to its peers,'' Mazzucchelli said.
</P>
<P>
   While sophisticated institutional investors such as pension
plans have been concerned for several years about the premium they
paid for Dell, they continued to buy it because of its gravity-
defying performance.
</P>
<P>
   That changed in February, when the company reported revenue
growth of 38.4 percent. While still high for a company whose annual
sales were more than $18 billion, it marked the first time in eight
quarters that revenue growth slipped below 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The stock hasn't been able to rebuild the momentum in an
industry undergoing sometimes rapid declines in prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not seen the institutional money flow back in,'' said
Ashok Kumar of U.S. Bancorp Piper Jaffray in Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
