<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEST-BAN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS URGE CLINTON TO ISSUE WRITTEN REQUEST TO DELAY TREATY
VOTE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a mounting battle of wills, Republicans demanded
Wednesday that President Clinton issue a written request to
withdraw the global nuclear test ban treaty from the Senate
calendar and to refrain from another vote during his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton indicated a willingness to postpone the vote, but the
White House rejected a written capitulation. Instead, the president
suggested Senate Republicans were sending dangerous signals
throughout the world that other nations were free to continue
atomic testing.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides stepped up their confrontation as each tried to
place the onus for the treaty's demise on the other.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate plans to open debate Friday and vote Tuesday, perhaps
Wednesday, on the two-year-old treaty that likely will fall far
short of the 67 votes needed for ratification. All 45 Democrats and
two of 55 Republicans have expressed support for it.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., chairman of the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee, said supporters of the treaty ``are hoping to
dictate the terms of their own surrender. They want us to say
something like this: `OK, let's call it a draw.' And I say to them,
that ain't going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Helms, joined by other key Senate Republicans, said the only way
he would allow the treaty to be withdrawn from the Senate calendar
is if Clinton requests in writing that the vote be postponed and
that it not be considered during the rest of his presidency.
Otherwise, Helms said he would force a vote on the treaty, and it
will be defeated.
</P>
<P>
   ``So the decision, you see, is the president's, and the
president's alone,'' Helms said during a rare news conference with
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   The administration expressed dismay that partisan politics was
playing a role in the treaty consideration.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue of debating (the treaty) should be dictated by the
national security interests of the United States, not the political
calendar,'' said White House spokesman David Leavy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not aware of any plans for the president to send a letter,
whatsoever,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents contend the United States lacks the ability to detect
low-level atomic tests and worry about the reliability of the
United States' current nuclear stockpile.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters contend the treaty would be verifiable because it
calls for on-site inspections and 321 monitoring stations around
the world. They also contend that current technology allows for the
computer simulation of the U.S. stockpile.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., and Senate Minority
Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., met throughout the day in an attempt to
fashion some compromise that would allow the vote, and the certain
defeat, to be postponed. But a compromise that allowed both sides
to save face proved elusive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're comfortable going forward with the vote,'' said John
Czwartacki, Lott's spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, early in the day, suggested he was open to a delay.
``After two long years of inaction, one week is very little time
for considered action,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said the Senate process, with
its rushed vote, was inadequate for such an important issue. But he
said the Senate leadership, not Clinton, controlled the Senate
calendar.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart also said the administration continued to prepare for a
vote next week. ``We're going to work as hard as we can between now
and next Tuesday to get as many votes as we can,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton continued lobbying for the treaty, surrounding himself
with Nobel Prize winners and former military leaders who endorse
the treaty. But he also acknowledged the uphill fight, saying ``I
thank the senators who are here with us today, and pray that they
can swell their ranks by next week.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the best way to stop nuclear proliferation is to
stop nuclear testing.
</P>
<P>
   ``A vote, therefore, to ratify is a vote to increase the
protections of our people and the world from nuclear war. By
contrast, a vote against it risks a much more dangerous future,''
Clinton said. He suggested those nations with nuclear power were
watching the current debate ``with some measure of bewilderment.''
</P>
<P>
   He said to ``walk away'' from the treaty would mean a ``green
light to all these other countries in the world.'' The United
States has operated under a self-imposed moratorium since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Helms, Sen. John Warner, R-Va., chairman of the Senate Armed
Services Committee, and Jon Kyl, R-Ariz., a member of the Senate
Intelligence Committee, promoted a letter from six former
Republican secretaries of defense who oppose the treaty.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Helms, they contended the treaty would mean
``confidence in the reliability of our nuclear weapons stockpile
would inevitably decline, thereby reducing the credibility of
America's nuclear deterrent.''
</P>
<P>
   Defeat of the treaty would be a major political setback for
Clinton who pushed other nations to adopt the test ban. His was the
first of 154 signatures on the treaty. More than 40 nations have
ratified it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
