r e BC-LIMEY-REVIEW-LADN     10-06 0618
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIMEY-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVENGE EXECUTED WITH FLAIR IN `THE LIMEY'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
By GLENN WHIPP 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Tight, energetic and filled to overflowing with a
grab bag of visual stylistic tricks, ``The Limey'' is a solid
revenge movie done with fabulous flair. Director Steven Soderbergh,
coming off last year's acclaimed ``Out of Sight,'' has fashioned
another winner, creating a fish-out-of-water story that works
wonderfully as a subtle showcase for the acting of Terence Stamp.
</P>
<P>
   Stamp plays the title character, a career criminal who is more
or less an extension of the thief he played 32 years ago in Ken
Loach's ``Poor Cow.'' The Limey (Wilson to his acquaintances _ the
man has no friends) has flown to Los Angeles to investigate the
death of his estranged daughter. Police reports say she died in a
car crash, but Wilson suspects something more sinister.
</P>
<P>
   A howlingly funny confrontation with some low-rent hoods reveals
a name _ Valentine (Peter Fonda), a record producer who was
romantically involved with Wilson's daughter. ``Tell him I'm
coming!'' Wilson shouts, clearly enunciating each word in his
Cockney accent. ``Tell ... him ... I'm ... coming!''
</P>
<P>
   And that's all you really need to know about this lively film's
minimalist plot. What distinguishes ``The Limey'' from dozens of
other similarly themed movies is its singular style and marvelously
expressive acting. Soderbergh plays with reality in much the same
way he did in ``Out of Sight'' and past films, running the same
scene from different angles, moving back and forth in time, always
explaining, expanding and elaborating on his characters'
motivations.
</P>
<P>
   Take Wilson's first meeting with Valentine at the latter's
insanely ostentatious home in the Hollywood Hills. (``You could see
the sea out there _ if you could see it,'' Valentine says to a
guest, in one the movie's many comical jabs at Los Angeles.)
Wilson's first instinct is to kill Valentine immediately. So we see
him do just that. Then the movie returns to the party (leaving
Wilson's fantasy) before moving into another dream sequence and,
once again, back to reality.
</P>
<P>
   These crazy collages of make-believe and real life can be a bit
much at times, but, for the most part, they creatively reveal the
haunted psyche of the film's protagonist. Soderbergh even inserts
shots of a young Stamp from ``Poor Cow.'' It could have been a
gimmick in less-accomplished hands, but here it helps explain
Wilson's love for his daughter and the regrets he has about their
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Supporting Soderbergh's masterful visual style is some nice
acting from both Stamp and Fonda, both of whom riff on their 1960s
personas to fine effect. Stamp can play rage with the best of them,
and he also fills in the cracks of his character with a tormented
sense of grief and remorse.
</P>
<P>
   Fonda's Valentine no longer feels the pangs of conscience,
having sold out his idealism long ago for the pursuit of pleasure.
You sense the loss in Fonda's performance, even as we watch his
character obsessively groom his teeth. Lesley Ann Warren, Luis
Guzman, Amelia Heinle and Barry Newman fill out a strong supporting
cast.
</P>
<P>
   It's these ambiguities, as well as the film's vigorous
storytelling, that makes ``The Limey'' such smart fun. The movie is
proof positive that revenge can indeed be sweet. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR;  &QL; 
The film: &LR;  ``The Limey'' (R; violence and language). &UR;  &QL; 
The stars: &LR;  Terence Stamp, Peter Fonda, Lesley Ann Warren. &UR;  &QL; 
Behind the scenes: &LR;  Directed by Steven Soderbergh. Screenplay by
Lem Dobbs. Released by Artisan Entertainment. &UR;  &QL; 
Running time: &LR;  One hour, 31 minutes. &UR;  &QL; 
Our rating: &LR;  3 stars &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
