<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 20:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8871 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSH07-COX     10-06 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush says GOP has been misunderstood
 &HT;    By Jena Heath
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Gov. George W. Bush on Wednesday softened his rebuke
of the Republican Party, telling an audience at a welfare-to-work
center that the party isn't bad, just misunderstood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said often times our party has been mischaracterized,'' Bush
said the day after he lambasted Republicans for focusing too much
on the economy and not enough on social issues. ``I was making the
case that the conservative philosophy is a compassionate philosophy
... I'm talking from my heart and I hope the Republican Party
appreciates it.''
</P>
<P>
   That was a gentler tone than Bush used Tuesday, when he diverged
from the topic of education policy to offer his critique of the
party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too often, my party has focused on the national economy, to
the exclusion of all else, speaking a sterile language of rates and
numbers,'' Bush said during a speech before a conservative think
tank. ``Too often, my party has confused the need for limited
government with a disdain for government itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Phil Gramm (R-Texas) said Bush's criticism of the
Republican Party was well-taken.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is too much occupation with what is happening to the Dow
and the GDP and those things are critically important because they
affect real people and real families,'' he said. ``But a government
has got to have more as a policy than just a high GDP. I thought it
was very appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   The GOP presidential front-runner has repeatedly called for a
new conservative face, one that shows as much interest in the poor
as it does in the economy. His rhetoric sharpened last Thursday
when he criticized House Congressional Republicans over their plan
to save $8 billion by stretching into monthly payments a lump sum
tax credit for the poor. Stunned House Republicans reacted
bitterly, and the leadership ditched the idea Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm said Bush was right to criticize the tax credit scheme. He
said Senate Republicans had rejected the plan as ``phoney savings''
in a closed meeting last Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got to define what he believes,'' Gramm said. ``I applaud
the fact that when people in Congress, Republicans or Democrats,
have a bad idea he needs to stand up and say something ... I think
it was the right thing to do and a good move politically, too, to
show he's willing to take on the Republican Congress and say when
they're wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Reaction from House Republican leaders was muted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The media is trying to create a story where there is no
story,'' said Emily Miller, spokeswoman for House Majority Whip Tom
DeLay. ``He is looking forward to a George W. Bush presidency and
all the things they can get done.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Buchanan, a University of Texas government professor, said
the Bush team is employing the strategy that worked for President
Bill Clinton _ jettisoning the extremes of his party in favor of
broader appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's feeling safe and trending toward a general election
strategy to go to the center,'' Buchanan said.
</P>
<P>
   That strategy angered some conservative leaders Wednesday _ and
left others feeling pragmatic.
</P>
<P>
   Christian Coalition founder Pat Robertson said Bush's call for a
gentler Republican party could ``alienate the core conservatives of
the Republican Party.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bush has not written off the party's right wing. He appeared
before the Home School Legal Defense Association and the Christian
Coalition recently in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Michael P. Farris, president of the Home School Legal Defense
Association, echoed other conservatives Wednesday when he said that
while they may not agree with everything Bush has to say, they know
he's their best ticket to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   `George W. Bush is more like Ronald Reagan than his father,
Farris said. ``That doesn't mean he's all the way to Reagan on
political philosophy, but he's close enough for many of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
