A8874 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-METS-LEFTIES-NYT &LR;      10-06 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-LEFTIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEFT-HANDERS WHO DEALT WITH THE MIGHTY JOHNSON  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ When John Olerud was flirting with a .400 batting
average in 1993, the Toronto Blue Jays were playing a series in
Seattle, and Randy Johnson was pitching one of the games against
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people were saying, `John's going to duck Randy,'''
Olerud said. ``I wasn't in the lineup and Cito came up and said his
reason for not playing me was Randy can sometimes get a little wild
up and in to left-handers and he didn't want to take a chance on me
getting hurt, but if I really wanted to get in there he'd put me in
there. I said, `Well, I'm not going to beg to hit against that
guy.'''
</P>
<P>
   Most left-handed hitters want no part of the left-handed
Johnson, so Cito Gaston, the Blue Jays' manager, was doing Olerud a
favor. In the first game of the division playoff series between the
Mets and the Arizona Diamondbacks on Tuesday night, Bobby Valentine
left only two left-handed batters in the Mets' lineup, Olerud and
Robin Ventura. The results were unexpected and stunning.
</P>
<P>
   Olerud and Ventura each rapped two hits against Johnson, giving
them four hits in eight times at bat. The Mets' right-handed
hitters collected 4 hits in 24 at-bats against the wicked
left-hander. Olerud singled and hit a home run, a two-run shot in
the third inning. Ventura lashed a double, and his second hit, a
single, triggered the ninth-inning burst that Edgardo Alfonzo
climaxed with a game-winning grand slam off Bobby Chouinard.
</P>
<P>
   The pitching performance was not vintage Johnson. He struck out
11, but he was responsible for seven of the eight runs the Mets
scored. His often menacing style did not intimidate the Mets, whose
survival in this three-of-five-game series was said to be linked
directly to what Johnson would do to them. Now that they have shown
what they can do to him, the Mets don't necessarily have to face
him again.
</P>
<P>
   Buck Showalter, the Arizona manager, has said that Johnson would
pitch the fifth game. What if there is a chance that the series
could end in four games? Would he pitch the fourth game?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd do anything to win for this team,'' Johnson said. ``And to
have an opportunity to win a game in the playoffs is all I've ever
wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was the winning pitcher twice in the 1995 division
series against the Yankees, once as a starter, once in relief. He
has not been the winning pitcher in a post-season game since. He
lost to Cleveland in that year's league championship series, lost
twice to Baltimore in the 1997 division series, twice to San Diego
in the division series last year while pitching for Houston, and
now once to the Mets. No other pitcher has suffered six successive
post-season defeats.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely something getting a win off him,'' Olerud
said, ``because he's such a dominating pitcher and such a tough guy
getting runs off.''
</P>
<P>
   Olerud's home run was the first by a left-handed batter against
Johnson in two years. In fact, of the 199 home runs that Johnson
had allowed in his career only 10 had been struck by left-handers.
So Olerud was asked to explain himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't explain myself,'' the soft-spoken first baseman said.
``I don't say this very often, but I definitely have to give the
glory to Jesus Christ because he's got such good stuff _ good
fastball, good slider _ that you just have to be ready to pull the
trigger quick.''
</P>
<P>
   Early in his time at bat in the third inning, Olerud related, he
was looking for a slider and Johnson threw fastballs. ``Then,''
Olerud said, ``I got two strikes on me, so I've got to look for a
fastball and he throws the slider and I'm out in front, but somehow
I got the barrel of the bat on the ball and got enough of it to go
out of the ball park.''
</P>
<P>
   Before this game, Olerud had batted only five times against
Johnson and had no hits; Ventura had had 6 hits in 34 at-bats for a
.176 average. During this season, left-handers batted only .103
against Johnson and had nearly four times as many strikeouts, 35,
as they had hits, 9, in 87 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked a little bit about how we were going to approach
him, that sort of thing, but there's not a whole lot you're going
to tell the other guy,'' Olerud said. ``He's got a good fastball
and if he's throwing the slider over for strikes, that makes him
real tough. You try to get a pitch to hit, try to see the ball as
early as you can and be real quick to the ball. You have to be real
quick with your decision and with swinging the bat.''
</P>
<P>
   Ventura said he was fortunate this time to get a couple of hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we went in with any special plan,'' the third
baseman said. ``He's just tough on left-handers. You have to hang
in there so long. He gets a good angle on you. I've seen him when
he's just blown teams away. I don't think he was throwing quite
that hard, but I didn't feel very comfortable up there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets generally did feel more comfortable at bat than they
had when they were losing some games and struggling to win others
in the past two weeks. In that period they abandoned their pattern
of taking pitches and forcing pitchers to go deeper into the count,
and they gained undesirable results.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went through that stretch, swinging at a lot of first
pitches, not working the count,'' Ventura said. ``Nobody said this
is what we have to do, but going up there and having a good at-bat
goes hand in hand, making sure you get a good pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said he didn't ``make my pitches.'' The ones he referred
to were the ones the Mets hit. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
