<HEADER>
A8876 &Cx1f; tth-z
u p BC-GORE-NORTHWEST-SPI &LR;      10-06 1207
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-NORTHWEST-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE FEELING INCREASING HEAT FROM BRADLEY IN PACIFIC NORTHWEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Vice President Al Gore, once considered to have a lock
on the Democratic presidential nomination, is facing increasing
pressure in Washington state and the West from his fast-rising
challenger, former Sen. Bill Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's campaign in the Pacific Northwest is showing signs of
catching on as rapidly as in the East, where polls show the former
New York Knicks forward narrowly leading Gore in New Hampshire and
New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Gore is in serious trouble,'' said Tim Hibbitts, an
independent Portland, Ore.-based pollster. ``I'm not saying Bradley
is going to take away the nomination, but I sense Clinton fatigue
even in the Democratic Party. The irony is that those who may wind
up paying the price are Al Gore and Hillary Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   Don McDonough, a Seattle-based Democratic pollster, added: ``I
happen to think this is more a Bradley-type state than a Gore-type
state.''
</P>
<P>
   At a recent Democratic State Committee meeting, former state
Chairwoman Karen Marchioro asked for a show of hands of Gore
supporters, Bradley backers and undecideds. ``It was one-third,
one-third, one third,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The shift toward Bradley represents an earthquake on a political
landscape that Gore has cultivated non-stop. The vice president has
paid 10 visits to Washington since the 1996 election, and will
formally kick off his state campaign with a $1,000-a-plate dinner
at Seattle's Benaroya Hall Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has stood atop the 14,411-foot summit of Mount Rainier,
inspected a flood-caused sinkhole in Shoreline and run a
10-kilometer race against breast cancer. He has attended more than
a dozen fund-raisers, chaired a salmon forum and spoken at an
election-eve rally last year.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Bradley has courted the Northwest on deliberately,
deceptively low-key visits. He did not invited TV cameras to film
him playing basketball with Central Area teenagers, nor did he
publicize a Seattle luncheon held the day that the
Bradley-for-president committee officially came into existence.
</P>
<P>
   But he has won converts with what former Washington Rep. Al
Swift describes as ``a marvelous, old-shoe style. He is non-puffed
up. He projects a relaxed quality which contrasts well with vice
president's stiffer personality.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley had an hourlong talk with Seattle Mayor Paul Schell when
he visited Seattle on a bookselling tour last fall. In April,
Schell became the first big-city mayor to support Bradley for
president.
</P>
<P>
   Schell felt some heat at the time. Rep. Norm Dicks, D-Wash., a
Gore intimate, insisted that Schell put in a call to the vice
president and explain reasons for endorsing his rival.
</P>
<P>
   But now, the mayor said Wednesday, ``I don't feel at all alone.
We have a real race now.''
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't take a political scientist to understand why
increasing numbers of Democrats would give Bradley a serious look.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats want to hold onto the White House. And while this
state's top officials are in Gore's camp, officeholders lower on
the totem pole _ particularly in competitive districts _ are
sensing they should offer a fresh face.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have major problems with Gore, I just ... want to
win,'' said state Rep. Dave Anderson, D-Langley, a Bradley backer.
``Bill Bradley has a lot of fresh ideas we really need. And there's
a combination of disgust and malaise around Clinton's presidency.''
</P>
<P>
   A few prominent Northwest Democrats are speaking up along
similar lines.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is ``perceived correctly as a consummate Washington, D.C.,
insider'' and Bradley ``doesn't have to carry that baggage,'' said
Oregon Gov. John Kitzhaber, who has made no endorsement in the
race.
</P>
<P>
   Former four-term Idaho Gov. Cecil Andrus is more outspoken,
saying Gore would be a ``disaster'' for Democratic candidates
sharing the ballot in Western states.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see Al Gore carrying anything west of the Mississippi
River with the possible exception of California, which is a land
unto itself,'' Andrus said. ``In the Rocky Mountain West, he won't
even make a respectable showing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Bradley would do quite well, particularly against young
Bush,'' Andrus added. ``Many young Republican businessmen like him.
Bradley is a clear fresh face without smudges.''
</P>
<P>
   The view is vigorously disputed by Dicks, who has been lining up
endorsements from fellow House members. He predicts that Gore will
come out fighting and lay to rest the campaign malaise long before
voters go to the polls 13 months from now.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd do fine, he'd carry both Washington and Oregon,'' Dicks
said. ``He is an outstanding debater, who will do extremely well in
upcoming forums with Bradley.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor does Dicks see any signs of ``Clinton fatigue'' in the
Northwest, citing the region's pace-setting job growth over the
past seven years, and the president's hands-on involvement in
issues from Boeing jet sales to forest policy.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the fatigue factor, Gore can still bring formidable
strengths to a one-on-one showdown with Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   He has the backing of party leaders and interest groups. The
invitation to Gore's Benaroya Hall fund-raiser bears the names of
Gov. Gary Locke, Sen. Patty Murray, three members of Congress, five
state elected officials and State Democratic Chairman Paul Berendt.
The state's most powerful union, the Boeing Machinists, is set to
formally endorse the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   The White House also is anything but reluctant about showing its
support for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle political consultant Cathy Allen has come out for
Bradley, saying the former senator ``gives us a chance with
undecided, only-presidential-year voters.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen says she has been ``bugged mercilessly'' for her stand. As
she departed a recent White House conference, Allen was followed to
the car by presidential counselor Ann Lewis, making the quiet
argument that she should reconsider and back Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Swift, who is neutral in the race, warns against ``writing off
Gore. ... He has been in our state a lot. He knows a lot about
Northwest issues, I would suspect more than Bradley.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley is far less organized, although he has broken through
with endorsements ranging from 14 Democratic state legislators to
business leaders. The host committee for his April Seattle
fund-raiser bore such names as Starbucks Chairman Howard Schultz,
developer David Sabey, new Seattle Mariners Chairman Howard
Lincoln, Chris Larson of Microsoft, and former Burlington Northern
executive Gerald Grinstein.
</P>
<P>
   The Northwest has smiled on reformist insurgents, dating back to
the 1968 anti-war candidacy of Minnesota Sen. Eugene McCarthy. In
1992, Washington's precinct caucuses went for ex-Sen. Paul Tsongas
and former California Gov. Jerry Brown, with Clinton finishing a
weak fourth. Gary Hart upset former Vice President Walter Mondale
in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bradley is picking up good vibes on both sides of the
mountain,'' said former Washington Gov. Mike Lowry, who divides his
time between Renton and Kettle Falls. ``He is raising the right
issues. He is a person with credibility.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
