<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNETCONF07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    E-commerce hot topic at Fall Internet World
 &HT;    By Heather Cocks
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Five years ago, Intel Corp.'s only Web presence was a
bare-bones site boasting little more than company propaganda.
</P>
<P>
   Five years from now, Intel will not only get all of its profits
off of Internet sales, but the Web will define the No. 1
chipmaker's business, predicted Chief Executive Craig Barrett.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that time, no one will single out Internet companies any
more because everyone will be doing all their business over the
Net,'' Barrett said Wednesday at Fall Internet World 1999, held
through Friday at the Jacob K. Javits Convention Center. ``Either
get in this process or get left behind, because competition is only
a mouse click away.''
</P>
<P>
   To a crowd of representatives from both small startups and major
market leaders, Barrett tagged business-to-business e-commerce as a
lucrative opportunity for growth _ and he made it clear Intel will
jump in quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, customers buy roughly $1 billion worth of Intel
processors over the Internet each month _ at sites ranging from
Intel's own to those of major computer makers, Barrett said. Within
one year, he said, Intel will sell almost all its processors
online.
</P>
<P>
   With e-commerce firmly entrenched in the Internet arena, most of
the 600 companies exhibiting at Internet World are vying to be the
technology that powers those sales portals.
</P>
<P>
   ``In e-commerce, there's a lot that goes into a transaction, and
that can be a huge cost for companies,'' said David Munaretto of
the Association of Internet Professionals trade group. ``We're
seeing a lot of companies trying to get online with the big
companies and handle their reliability, transaction volumes and
even inventory.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest eye-catchers at Internet World was an army of
actors in Santa Claus suits hired by an Austin, Texas, Internet
software company that makes software that can be used by Internet
retailers to create gift registries.
</P>
<P>
   Ivebeengood.com, a subsidiary of Austin-based Trilogy Software
Inc., is hoping the Santas will help raise awareness of its product
in advance of what is expected to be a record year for holiday
sales over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Other Internet software companies dominated the exhibit hall at
Internet World.
</P>
<P>
   CyberCash Inc., for example, showed off software aimed at
security and speeding up transactions, while ComAlliance Inc.
pitched software used to adjust and monitor a Web company's
inventory.
</P>
<P>
   Austin-based Pervasive Software Inc. used its booth to debut
Tango 2000, a software suite that helps companies monitor activity
on their Web sites. Balancing Barrett's emphasis on businesses,
Oracle Corp. Chief Executive Larry Ellison used his afternoon
keynote to some of the almost 50,000 Internet World attendees to
predict the Internet's impact on all computer users.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll move from personal computing to network computing, all
via the Internet,'' Ellison said. ``It will be the new model for
computing. Everything will mirror the Web.''
</P>
<P>
   He called for online storage of both applications and data,
making Web browsers the only software tool users need on their PCs.
</P>
<P>
   In trying to underscore the ease of Web-based computing, Ellison
took a series of familiar potshots at rival Microsoft Corp.
</P>
<P>
   He blamed the company's operating systems for making computing
too complex, and criticized it for loading PCs with software that
requires costly and often troublesome upgrades.
</P>
<P>
   ``To all the programmers out there: Build for the Web, not for
Windows,'' Ellison urged. ``That's the future.''
</P>
<P>
   To that end, Oracle is preparing to debut a $150 network
computer _ essentially a plastic shell equipped only with a modem
and a Web browser _ and of course, a basic operating system by
Linux, the upstart alternative to Microsoft's Windows.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
