<HEADER>
A8881 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BRAZIL-DEBT-ART-NYT &LR;      10-06 1119
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-DEBT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANDIDATE'S INTEREST IN DEBT RENEGOTIATION WORRIES BRAZILIAN
FINANCIERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By SIMON ROMERO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAO PAULO, Brazil _ Investors in Brazil are beginning to get
nervous over the future possibility that the government might try
to renegotiate its domestic debt, which has nearly doubled in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
   The possibility has grown in part because the idea of a debt
renegotiation has been promoted by a rising presidential candidate,
Ciro Gomes, a 41-year-old former finance minister. He has made debt
renegotiation part of a broader economic proposal that, he says,
would encourage long-term growth.
</P>
<P>
   His proposal would lengthen the maturities and lower the
interest payments on the domestic debt _ the government bonds and
notes that are denominated in the Brazilian currency, the real. By
doing so, Gomes said, he hoped to narrow Brazil's growing budget
deficit. He would also hope to redirect money now fueling profits
at financial institutions that buy high-yielding government bonds
into areas in need such as education, housing and jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The idea has attracted a mixture of bemusement, anger and
anxiety among Brazilian financiers, especially since Gomes' rising
popularity makes him one of the main contenders in the presidential
election, to be held in three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a crazy idea that would cripple the economy, creating
capital flight and bringing back the risk of inflation,'' said
David Gotlib, managing director of Deutsche Bank Asset Management's
Brazilian operations. ``I can only hope the gravity of doing such a
thing will be perceived in time for the proposal to be withdrawn.''
</P>
<P>
   With the election that far in the future, many things can
obviously happen in the meantime. Still, Gomes' proposal has
generated energetic discussion here over the dynamics of Brazil's
domestic debt.
</P>
<P>
   That debt is different from debt owed by the governments in
advanced economies such as the United States, which are able to
sell bonds with maturities of up to 30 years. Brazil, by contrast,
is only able to sell bonds domestically with maturities up to five
years. The average maturity of all Brazilian government debt is
only about nine months.
</P>
<P>
   The main reason for such short maturities is a reluctance by
investors to buy longer-maturing bonds, given a history over the
last couple of decades the national and some state governments
reneging on obligations.
</P>
<P>
   From 1982 to 1990, a period of hyperinflation and economic
crisis, Brazil restructured its domestic debt three times. The last
of these took place by surprise shortly after Fernando Collor de
Mello became president in 1990, and the government froze and then
seized bank deposits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brazil's track record is not particularly stellar in this
regard,'' said Fergus McCormick, a debt analyst at the Duff &AMP;
Phelps Credit Rating Corp..
</P>
<P>
   A country's domestic debt rating is usually higher than the
rating on its foreign debt, or debt owed in foreign currency to
lenders in other countries. But in Brazil's case, Duff &AMP; Phelps
rates its domestic debt B, three notches below its foreign debt
rating of BB.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the financiers' and bond analysts' apprehension reflects
a worrisome growth of Brazilian domestic debt, which is held almost
entirely by Brazilians. In the last two years, the domestic debt
has ballooned to nearly 400 billion reais _ now about $205 billion,
from 210 billion reais. By contrast, the foreign debt grew 13
percent in the same period, to $97.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The main reason for the near-doubling of the domestic debt load
is the government's reliance on bonds that pay a variable rate of
interest. So when the central bank raised interest rates during the
financial crises in Asia, Russia and earlier this year at home,
debt-servicing costs soared.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil's debt makeup is still largely dependent on moves in
interest rates, with more than half of domestic debt linked to the
main overnight-lending rate, now around 19 percent. An additional
26 percent of the debt is linked to the real's value in relation to
the dollar. That means a sharp weakening in the Brazilian currency
would sharply increase the cost of servicing these bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Gomes' debt-restructuring proposal reflects the thinking of
Roberto Mangabeira Unger, a legal theorist who is his principal
adviser. Unger, a Brazilian who has been teaching at Harvard Law
School since 1971, argues that the nature of Brazil's domestic debt
means that it is vulnerable to potential negative developments
abroad, such as a correction on Wall Street or apprehension over
Year 2000 computer problems. Turbulence abroad can spur the
Brazilian central bank to raise rates, which means that the
government's financing costs also rise.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government has made a very dangerous bet by not
considering the eventuality of an internal debt reorganization,''
Unger said in a telephone interview. ``First, it means that almost
the totality of projected federal revenue will be used in servicing
the debt, and second, the commitments to economic opening and
fiscal realism are put at risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Unger's views on government finances and other subjects such as
the possibility of using controls to limit short-term capital flows
have been known for some time. But recently, they have gained
prominence as Gomes, the 2002 presidential aspirant, became
something of a darling in the Brazilian news media after his
separation from his first wife and much-publicized romance with
Patricia Pillar, a soap-opera actress.
</P>
<P>
   Unger began to influence Gomes' thinking when the politician was
a visiting scholar at Harvard in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Skeptics say that a debt renegotiation would be exceedingly
complex and do more harm than good. Mailson da Nobrega, a former
finance minister, said about 80 percent of Brazil's domestic debt
is indirectly held by the country's middle class, either through
mutual funds, pension funds or insurance policies backed by
government bonds. ``How do you renegotiate with crowds that would
fit into several soccer stadiums?'' he asked rhetorically. ``This
is an idea thought up in a Harvard library, far from Brazilian
reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Brazil's central bank has said that the debt situation is
improving. For example, in August the government was able to
increase to 11.7 percent the share of debt that is not subject to
variable rates, from 1.2 percent in March. With the authorities
forecasting a decline in interest rates to single-digit rates by
next year, debt-servicing costs should decline as a result.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
