<SLUG> BC-BUCHANAN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Buchanan considers cost of joining Reform Party
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS - Pat Buchanan, a presidential candidate in search of a
party, huddled privately Wednesday with Reform Party National
Chairman Russ Verney to discuss the ups and downs of seeking the
support of the political group that Ross Perot built.
</P>
<P>
   The up side is $13 million in federal money the Reform Party
nominee will get. The down side is the cost _ as much as $6 million
_ of getting that nominee on the ballot in all 50 states.
</P>
<P>
   Those are the key factors in the equation Buchanan, now a
Republican, is using to decide what the Reform Party nomination is
worth. But the outspoken conservative sounds interested in
undertaking the effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a formidable challenge,'' he said after meeting with
Verney. ``No doubt about it. To get on the ballots in 50 states
with the obstacles and hurdles is difficult. Is it prohibitive? I
didn't get the impression it is prohibitive.''
</P>
<P>
   What is prohibitive for Buchanan at this point are his chances
of winning the GOP nomination. Like all Republican contenders,
Buchanan is being buried by Gov. George W. Bush's massive
fund-raising effort.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan now is packaging himself as a choice he believes
America is seeking. The two major parties don't offer ``a dime's
worth of difference,'' he said _ especially on foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, when it comes to foreign policy and using America's
military forces abroad, some of Mr. Bush's advisers make me more
nervous than Mr. Clinton's advisers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``On foreign policy and trade policy and immigration policy and
on restoring American sovereignty, I think there is very little
difference between Mr. Bush and what the Democratic Party at the
national level offers America,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But, that said, Buchanan indicated he is not inclined to mount a
third-party presidential bid if its major effect would be to spoil
some other candidate's chances of winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would not do this unless I genuinely believed there was a
fighting chance to get in the debates and then come out of those
debates as a real alternative and choice to the American people and
win the presidency,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not interested in going in and just trying to muck up an
election by getting on a few ballots,'' he added. ``I can do that
in journalism. If I go for this thing, I'm going for the presidency
of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Top Bush advisers don't believe Buchanan would be a shoo-in for
the nomination of the Reform Party, an organization which, to date,
has staked its claim on economic issues, not the social ones
championed by Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   But Buchanan, who shares the Reform Party's stand against NAFTA,
said Wednesday that only ``another gigantic bankroll'' could
prevent him from getting the Reform Party nod if he wants it. New
York real-estate magnate Donald Trump, who has such a bankroll,
might seek the Reform Party nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan's potential party switch has drawn questions from the
Reform Party's only major elected official, Minnesota Gov. Jesse
Ventura.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Mr. Buchanan is certainly direct in many of the issues
he talks on, but I don't think that he fits the role of the Reform
Party today ... because we're very much a centrist party. Fiscally
conservative and socially on the liberal side, and I don't think
Pat fits very well into that,'' Ventura said recently.
</P>
<P>
   Verney said the meeting with Buchanan was an effort to make sure
Buchanan understands the challenge in getting the Reform Party
nomination and then working to get the party's nominee on ballots
across the nation. Laws vary from state to state. The states that
offer the biggest obstacles _ both in terms of number of signatures
needed and time allowed to gather them _ are Texas and North
Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, the Reform Party would have to mount a petition drive
among registered voters who do not vote in next March's major party
primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Perot, the party's 1992 and 1996 nominee, was on the ballot
nationwide. In 1996, he spent $12 million of his own money to make
it happen. Verney said the 2000 nominee would have to spend about
$6 million to get on all ballots.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very big job,'' said Verney, ``but manageable.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
