<HEADLINE>
FCC MOVES TO SET CONDITIONS FOR TELECOMMUNICATIONS MEGAMERGERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Federal officials this week began setting the
conditions they will impose on a wave of proposed mergers that
promise to consolidate, blur and redefine the nation's telephone,
cable and broadcasting industries in a matter of months.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Communications Commission on Wednesday approved SBC
Communications Inc.'s $72 billion takeover of Ameritech Corp., but
imposed conditions that officials said were intended to force SBC
to be more competitive with other regional and local telephone
companies.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the FCC is set to announce new ownership
concentration rules for cable companies that will determine whether
AT&AMP;T can complete its $58 billion acquisition of Mediaone without
shedding any assets.
</P>
<P>
   And Tuesday, FCC Chairman William Kennard questioned how MCI
Worldcom's $115 billion bid for Sprint Inc. could benefit
consumers, suggesting the companies have to shed Internet
components and long-distance properties to gain regulatory
approval.
</P>
<P>
   FCC officials said Wednesday that in drawing the lines on these
deals and a handful of others _ valued at almost $250 billion in
all _ the commission was trying to balance economies of scale,
which could result in lower prices to consumers, against
large-scale consolidations that could result in less competition
and higher prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are certainly not per se against consolidations,
particularly those that achieve the kinds of economies of scale
that can help consumers,'' Kennard said in an interview Wednesday.
``On the other hand, we are against those consolidations that raise
the barriers to entry by competitors.''
</P>
<P>
   One issue complicating the deliberations of Kennard and the FCC
is the state of local telephone service, which in many pockets of
the nation has remained largely resistant to competition.
</P>
<P>
   In broadly deregulating the industry, the Telecommunications Act
of 1996 required that regional Bell companies that seek to enter
the highly lucrative long-distance business must first establish
that there is true competition in their local service areas. To
promote that provision, the commission required SBC, as part of its
merger with Ameritech, to enter 30 cities outside its region within
18 months or else face fines of more than $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   SBC chairman Edward Whitacre said in an interview Wednesday that
Texas regulators had notified SBC that it had shown sufficient
local competition to qualify to offer long-distance service in
Texas. Whitacre said he expected SBC would be filing an application
with the FCC in coming weeks to offer long distance to Texas
customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an interesting, exciting and great day,'' Whitacre
said. ``We've worked long and hard for this.''
</P>
<P>
   SBC's previous application to the FCC to be allowed to enter the
$80 billion long-distance market have failed. But Whitacre said
that consolidation resulting from the MCI Worldcom-Sprint deal
would place greater pressure on Washington regulators to open the
long-distance market to the Bells.
</P>
<P>
   ``The obvious answer to all this,'' he said, ``is let everybody
do everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's action by the FCC means that the seven Baby Bells
originally created by the 1980s breakup of the old American
Telephone &AMP; Telegraph Co. will soon be reduced to four. And if the
MCI Worldcom-Sprint deal is approved, four dominant long distance
carriers will be reduced to two.
</P>
<P>
   Kennard's remarks about the MCI Worldcom and SBC acquisitions
were notable for more than what they said about the deals
themselves. The resulting level of concentration would be stunning,
not only for the telephone industry, but also for the broadcast and
cable industries.
</P>
<P>
   Two other deals now before the FCC _ Viacom's acquisition of CBS
and AT&AMP;T's purchase of the Mediaone cable television company close
on the heels of its purchase of Telecommunications Inc. _ would
break the current caps that were supposed to limit market
domination. In general terms, no more than 30 percent of either
industry can be controlled by one company, and both mergers far
exceed that.
</P>
<P>
   There is a strong expectation that the FCC and the Justice
Department's Antitrust Division will, at the very least, require
some of these deals to be significantly scaled back by requiring
the sale of major components of the companies as a condition of
regulatory approval.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the FCC is set to hand down new cable concentration
rules, and the industry is watching whether the agency will relax
its standards to permit AT&AMP;T to complete the acquisition of
Mediaone.
</P>
<P>
   Kennard and other officials at the FCC also suggested that the
rules under consideration for the cable industry might be different
than those for other industries. That is because a convergence of
telecommunications, computer and broadcasting technologies now
enables cable companies to offer television programs, high-speed
Internet access and telephone services over a single cable.
</P>
<P>
   The officials said the aim of the rules to be announced Friday
would be to prevent further consolidation of traditional cable
service _ television _ while encouraging AT&AMP;T and its smaller
competitors to continue to invest heavily in developing networks
capable of offering high-speed Internet and telephone services as
well.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cable industry is both mature and moving into a new
market, trying to compete with the Bells in local telephone and
broad-band telephony,'' Kennard said. ``It's like the Yankees
baseball team deciding that they want to now compete in basketball.
You want them to be competitive. At the same time, you don't want
to give them the ability to totally dominate their traditional
market.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-99 2109EDT &QL; 
