<SLUG> BC-BBA-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
 
Rangers batters becoming a national choke joke 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
NEW YORK _ It was an unfair question to ask an honest man.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But these are drastic times, and it's also hunting season, with
everybody now taking yet another October shot at the ``Bambies'' in
the Rangers' batting order.
</P>
<P>
   Above all else, hitting instructor Rudy Jaramillo is an honest
man. Honest and tough. ``Oak Cliff tough,'' as in the section of
Dallas where he grew up and still lives.
</P>
<P>
   So as Jaramillo nursed a $3 cup of coffee in the team's New York
hotel lobby yesterday morning, he didn't seem surprised that an
unfair question was lobbed his way.
</P>
<P>
   Is this a gag-job by his guys? A full-blown choke? Why else does
one of the best, if not the best, regular-season run-production
machines just flat disappear against the Yankees in October?
</P>
<P>
   After a Game 1 shutout here Tuesday night, the Rangers have one
run in the last 42 postseason innings. That, and seven straight
October losses to the Yankees have reduced the Rangers to joke
status in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Choke? Gag?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, not at all,'' answered Jaramillo, but for public
consumption what else could he say?
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly though, it has become a mental thing, and it's my
responsibility to change any negative doubts into positives,''
Jaramillo continued. ``The last thing I want to do is be
overbearing at this point. I keep thinking all it will take is one
breakthrough inning _ put some runs on the board, and then we
explode.''
</P>
<P>
   That wait, of course, now ranks up there with O.J.'s search for
the real killer. Game 2 here tonight is obviously critical for the
Rangers. It doesn't seem to matter who the Yankees pitch, but lefty
Andy Pettitte is up next.
</P>
<P>
   Each hitter will study tapes of past at-bats against Pettitte.
The scouting report will be extensive. But Jaramillo spent four
days preparing the batting order for Game 1 starter Orlando
Hernandez, and well ...
</P>
<P>
   There were two hits, both by Pudge Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   An autopsy of the Rangers' postseason offensive burial came in
the top of the first in Game 1. This could have been that
breakthrough inning Jaramillo spoke of. The possibility was there.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez, however, knew exactly what his escape route would be.
Gene Michael of the New York front office spent most of September
following the Rangers, just as he did in 1998. Hernandez fed off
Michael's scouting report. But with all due respect to Michael that
same scouting report could have been prepared by any Rangers fan.
They've seen it all before.
</P>
<P>
   The key out in the first inning involved Juan Gonzalez. ``He
wouldn't take the walk.''
</P>
<P>
   Runners at first and second, one out, and Hernandez never threw
Gonzalez a strike. It was all off-speed stuff on the outside.
Quickly down 0-and-2, the count went to 2-and-2 before Juan swung
weakly and missed a breaking ball that was out of the strike zone.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez had pitched around left-handed hitter Rusty Greer,
walking him with Rodriguez at second. He wanted Gonzalez, and
fanned him. Hernandez, however, then dodged Rafael Palmeiro. He
gladly gave up the walk to load the bases and get to Todd Zeile,
who struck out, ending the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Go back to Gonzalez. If he lays off those pitches, the bases are
loaded with one out for Rafael.
</P>
<P>
   ``Juan sees runners on base, and sometimes the desire is so
strong, he loses focus,'' said Jaramillo.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez destroyed the Yankees in the '96 playoff series, but
since then they haven't thrown him an October strike. In the past
four postseason games, he's 1-for-15 with no runs batted in.
</P>
<P>
   Juan is always a lightning rod for criticism, so in fairness,
it's not just him. It's everybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``Juan came back in his next at-bat, drove a ball up the gap,
and if it gets through, that's two RBI, and we wouldn't be having
this conversation,'' said Jaramillo. ``But Bernie \RWilliams, the
center fielder\S makes the great catch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Todd Zeile came back in his next at-bat and drove the ball to
the 399-foot marker. It's caught at the wall. Rafael smoked the
ball twice, and got nothing out of it. Pudge doubled off the wall,
and only the dead air kept that one in the park. We did have good
contact, but with no results.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``no results'' have stretched into four postseason games
over two Octobers. And after Game 1, the Rangers again looked like
a sweep victim waiting to happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``But \Rtoday\S, I'm gonna show up at the park thinking tonight
is the night,'' said Jaramillo. ``I really believe that. I'm
confident.''
</P>
<P>
   An honest man has spoken. Unfortunately, a case of reality is
also coming in loud and clear.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
