<HEADLINE>
BUSH SOFTENS CRITICISM OF GOP AFTER OUTCRY BY CONSERVATIVES 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also BUSH-CAMPAIGN-ASSESS) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(th) 
 By FRANK BRUNI    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Facing a backlash from some conservative Republicans,
Gov. George W. Bush of Texas softened his stern appraisal of the
Republican Party on Wednesday. Only Tuesday he had characterized
the party as too fixated on affluence and not sensitive enough to
people's needs.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference in New York City, Bush, the front-runner
for the Republican presidential nomination, suggested that the
party suffered primarily from voters' misperceptions of it, not
from its own mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oftentimes, people only hear the sterile numbers and economic
news we talk about, or oftentimes people only hear our
gloom-and-doom scenario,'' he said. ``That's an image that our
party must battle, and we must battle it by making sure people
understand that we care a lot about people.''
</P>
<P>
   But on Tuesday, in the middle of a formal policy speech
outlining his education proposals, Bush had seemed to find fault
not with what people were hearing, but with what Republicans were
saying.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too often, on social issues, my party has painted an image of
America slouching toward Gomorrah,'' Bush said in that speech.
``Too often, my party has focused on the national economy, to the
exclusion of all else _ speaking a sterile language of rates and
numbers. Too often, my party has confused the need for limited
government with a disdain for government itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Those remarks drew harsh repsonses from several prominent
conservatives and a few of Bush's opponents for the Republican
presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Pat Robertson, founder of the Christian Coalition,
released a statement saying: ``For his own good, he would be well
advised to avoid statements which tend to alienate the core
conservatives of the Republican Party, which will either drive them
into the arms of Pat Buchanan, to support other candidates or cause
them to stay home on Election Day.'' Only last week, Robertson
lavishly praised Bush at the coalition's convention.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, two of Bush's conservative opponents for the
Republican presidential nomination, Steve Forbes and Gary Bauer,
essentially derided him as a traitor to conservative ideals.
</P>
<P>
   ``He clearly comes across as being embarrassed by the basic
principles of his party _ more freedom and less government,''
Forbes said Wednesday. ``And if he is apologetic and embarrassed by
his party, why does he seek its nomination?''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's recasting of his earlier remarks suggested that while he
is intent on establishing himself as a new breed of Republican _ a
strategy that could pay off handsomely with swing voters down the
road _ he does not want to go too far toward alienating both
conservatives in the party and the very congressional Republicans
he may need to enact legislation if he is elected president.
</P>
<P>
   ``After you hit a dog,'' said one of Bush's advisers, ``you pet
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The adviser added that over the last few days, the Bush campaign
had received calls from congressional Republicans expressing alarm
that Bush was forgetting a promise not to campaign against them.
</P>
<P>
   The chorus of disapproval underscored the risk that Bush seems
to be taking. Although Republican candidates generally veer toward
the right in primaries, Bush is already leaning toward the center.
</P>
<P>
   That may reflect his enormous lead over other Republicans in the
polls and his confidence that he will be the party's nominee. Some
advisers said he was simply articulating his genuine beliefs.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Bush reprimanded fellow Republicans twice in less than a week.
Last Thursday, he said that a House Republicans' spending plan that
would delay payments of the earned income tax credit for
working-class Americans was an attempt to ``balance their budget on
the backs of the poor.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Bush rendered his broader appraisal of the
Republican Party as too negative in its oratory and too focused on
wealth.
</P>
<P>
   That appraisal had been a part of his education speech before he
came out against the House Republicans' spending plan. His stated
opposition to that plan guaranteed that the additional criticism in
the appraisal would draw extra scrutiny, but several advisers said
they were surprised by the attention.
</P>
<P>
   In his remarks Wednesday, Bush made a point of praising
congressional Republicans for several legislative efforts in the
last few years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the Republican Congress that freed the states to make
the right decisions when it comes to welfare reform,'' Bush said.
``And the Republican Congress deserves great credit for that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
