<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Compromise would give F-22 program $1.3 billion
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The controversial F-22 fighter jet program emerged
a winner Wednesday night in the final round of negotiations over
Defense Department spending.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement calls for spending an additional $1.3 billion on
the stealth fighter built by Lockheed Martin Corp. at its Marietta,
Ga., facility. The funds would be in addition to $1.2 billion that
already has won approval, bringing the program's total funding to
$2.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``While I'm delighted, we're not going to break open the
champagne until it is signed by the president,'' said Rep. Bob Barr
(R-Ga.), whose district includes Marietta. ``It does move us steps
closer to protecting this vital program.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal gives the Air Force $723 million in research and
development funds to buy up to six test planes. An additional $277
million would be set aside for advanced purchase orders to start
buying the first lot of 10 planes in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Another $300 million would be added to cover liability costs
associated with contract termination for subcontractors. Any money
not used can go toward the purchase of additional planes.
</P>
<P>
   The F-22 was one of the biggest stumbling blocks in the Defense
Department's spending bill. Final figures for the entire bill,
which is estimated to be upward of $267 billion, were not released
Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Max Cleland (D-Ga.) said he was pleased that the program
had survived its most aggressive attack in its 15-year history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the way it turned out is the Senate prevailed, and
that's the proper position for our country,'' Cleland said. ``I
think the F-22 will help us win wars and save lives.''
</P>
<P>
   That attack on the F-22 fighter jet was led by Rep. Jerry Lewis
(R-Calif.), chairman of the House Defense Appropriations Committee.
He argued that the $70 billion program was too costly and untested,
and he successfully waged a campaign to eliminate $1.85 billion
from the House version of the spending bill.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the debate, Lewis has urged a ``pause'' in production
to bring the plane in line with expectations.
</P>
<P>
   The deal includes a major concession to Lewis in that the
funding used to purchase the planes would not set the production
cycle in motion. Instead, the money would be pooled from research
and development funds for testing the plane. ``We are pleased that
the House and Senate conferees recognized that it is necessary to
delay procurement of the F-22 this year,'' Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Sen. Paul Coverdell (R-Ga.) said he intended to keep
an eye on Lewis and his band of critics during next year's budget
deliberations. ``We're now alert to a contingent in the House that
could be trouble,'' Coverdell said. ``I'm pleased that we are
proceeding with six aircraft.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
