<HEADLINE>
MERGERS CAN BE A MENTAL BURDEN TO EMPLOYEES, STUDIES SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Published studies of recent mergers and
acquisitions sound cautionary notes about the psychological fallout
on workers.
</P>
<P>
   In an international review by Hewitt Associates of 500 corporate
merger, acquisition and joint venture participants, 69 percent of
U.S. human-resource directors said their biggest difficulty was
meshing corporate cultures.
</P>
<P>
   In that study, only one-fourth of the human-resource executives
said the combined company was ``very successful'' at creating a new
culture. Among the unsuccessful majority, most blamed employees'
fear of change as the chief impediment.
</P>
<P>
   ``While these deals may look good on paper, the fact is that
changes in management, policies and programs can be very
threatening to employees,'' said Pete Sanborn, merger and
acquisition consultant at Hewitt's Connecticut office, when the
report was released in April.
</P>
<P>
   In another study, three-fourths of 65 merged companies admitted
to Hay Group consultants that they had failed to put employees in
the right jobs within the first six months of their merged
operations.
</P>
<P>
   Those mistakes led to subsequent employee turnover and
reassignments. The report was published in February.
</P>
<P>
   In another survey, which was taken by Right Management
Consultants, fewer than a third of 179 merged companies said they
had successfully combined corporate cultures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most companies are having a very difficult time with people
issues across the board,'' said the Right report, released in
March. ``On average, only 30 percent of respondents said their
companies had succeeded in areas such as cultural integration,
employee retention or communication.''
</P>
<P>
   The report observed that attainment of financial objectives is
``highly correlated'' to work force issues. Thus, only about 30
percent of merger and acquisition participants are likely to reach
the goals that sparked the combination.
</P>
<P>
   In a September newsletter, compensation and benefits consultants
at Towers Perrin reported that post-merger adoption of common
benefit plans also may cause problems.
</P>
<P>
   When the benefit plans at two companies vary significantly,
equalizing them sometimes alienates employees who had been getting
a better package and, seemingly unfairly, rewards others, the
consultants said.
</P>
<P>
   In January, the Conference Board, a business research
organization, reported that mergers and acquisitions exacerbated
competitive stress felt by workers.
</P>
<P>
   While merging companies are preoccupied with combining,
competitors frequently step in to capture market share, research
shows.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
