<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-BUSH-CAMPAIGN-ASSESS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME HOUSE REPUBLICANS CHAFE AT BUSH'S CRITICISM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeats to add art note)  
 (ATTN: S.C, Calif., Con)  (Political Memo; see also BUSH-CAMPAIGN) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT31 has been sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ These are uncomfortable days for Republicans on
Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Once again they are locked in a chaotic, down-to-the-wire budget
battle with President Clinton. They have been forced by Democrats
into an uncomfortable debate over managed health care. And now the
party's front-running presidential candidate seems to be defining
his own credentials as a ``compassionate conservative'' by
distancing himself from them.
</P>
<P>
   The unease is so palpable, said Rep. Mark Sanford, R-S.C., that
when he came onto the House floor Wednesday morning for the first
vote of the day, another Republican walked up to him and said, ``if
Bush keeps going at the rate he's going at, he'll guarantee his
presidency and a Democrat controlled House.'' Sanford, added,
``Then the follow up was, `I guess you can't blame him. He's
probably reading the same poll numbers we are.'''
</P>
<P>
   This was not how Republicans expected things to be. When Speaker
Dennis Hastert this year replaced the fiery and polarizing Newt
Gingrich, Republicans said they had a few simple and pragmatic
goals that recognized the limits of their very tenuous majority:
They would be more disciplined and less confrontational. They would
concentrate on basics like passing spending bills on time. And they
would ride Bush's coattails next year to keep control of the House
and Senate.
</P>
<P>
   But that may be harder to do if Bush, who has now criticized
fellow Republicans twice in the span of a week, continues to take a
page from President Clinton, who defined himself as a ``New
Democrat'' by standing far apart from congressional Democrats.
Clinton's 1996 political strategist, Dick Morris, called it
``triangulation'' because Clinton tried to stand equally distant
from Republicans and Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Clinton has done by triangulating has taken the spirit
out of the Democratic party,'' Rep. Lindsey O. Graham, R-S.C, said
Wednesday, making clear his own irritation with Bush. ``That's not
the model to govern well.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Bush Wednesday was far more conciliatory than in recent
days, praising Republicans in Congress for measures such as the
1996 overhaul of the welfare law and saying he hoped and planned if
elected to work with a Republican speaker and a Republican House.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the Republicans' problems result inevitably from the
balance of power in Congress. The House is virtually split in two,
making it nearly ungovernable. And in the Senate, the Republicans
hold 55 seats _ five short of the 60 they would need to cut off
debate each time the Democrats embark on another filibuster against
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   And the Democrats, fervent about taking back the House, are
fighting the Republicans at every turn. With the help of
like-minded Republican moderates, they have successfully pushed
onto the agenda issues that they believe favor them _ gun control,
campaign finance overhaul and regulation of health maintenance
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``When half the Congrss wants to rock the boat, the boat is
going to rock,'' said Rep. Brian Bilbray, R-Calif., arguing that
Republicans were not to blame for the turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   But it is also the case that on the fiscal issues that they have
made their priority the Republicans have lurched from idea to idea.
They have not found a way to meet their basic promise to cut taxes,
remain within the spending limits of the 1997 bipartisan balanced
budget agreement and avoid dipping into Social Security trust fund
money to pay for the governments operations.
</P>
<P>
   In the summer they proudly passed a large $792 billion tax cut
and there was some talk of a grand compromise with Clinton in which
Republicans would win a somewhat smaller tax cut in exchange for
enacting a new Medicare prescription drug program the president
wanted.
</P>
<P>
   But in September, Republican leaders abruptly said they would
not sit down with the president to negotiate a smaller tax cut once
Clinton vetoed their measure. Nor had they passed the 13 annual
spending bills on time by the Oct. 1 start of the new fiscal year.
Instead the government was kept running for three more weeks with
temporary legislation.
</P>
<P>
   As the fiscal debate goes into its final weeks, Republicans are
hoping to win politically by portraying themselves as the ones
cutting spending enough to avoid eating into the Social Security
surplus. (Usually it is the Democrats who campaign on protecting
Social Security.)
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans themselves have yet to figure out how to hold
the line on spending and not spend billions of dollars from the
Social Security surplus. One idea House leaders had was to save
$8.7 billion next year by paying a tax credit to the working poor
on a monthly basis instead of a lump sum payment. That strategem is
what prompted Bush last week to shock House Republicans by calling
that an effort to ``balance the budget on the backs of the poor.''
</P>
<P>
   If Bush is now denying he wants confrontation with congressional
Republicans, there are political imperatives that still seem bound
to pull them apart. Many House Republicans, in particular, believe
they win elections by appealing to their most hardcore conservative
base. Bush, with his commanding lead over other Republican
candidates in the polls, is by contrast fashioning his
``compassionate conservatism'' to appeal to the independents and
moderates that he would need in the general election.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans were hopeful Wednesday that Bush might actually
help their own prospects of keeping control of the House by
occasionally criticizing them. ``The American people need to know
that George Bush needs to stand up to a Republican Congress if he
doesn't agree with us,''said Rep. Christopher Shays, a moderate
Connecticut Republican. ``If they think he will fall under our
spell, there will be less of an inclination to have both him and a
Republican Congress and one of us will have to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Others were angrily predicting that Bush would hurt himself and
them too _ pointing to an outpouring of criticism from conservative
figures like Rush Limbaugh, Paul Weyrich, and Pat Robertson, the
Christian Coalition leader who all but endorsed Bush last week.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats _ who long had to grapple with Clinton's own efforts
to distance himself from them _ were enjoying the Republican
divisions. Rep. Richard Gephardt, the House minority leader even
sent a letter to Bush asking him to ``steer House Republicans
toward the mainstream'' on other issues before Congress.
``Unfortunately, your allies in the Republican leadership just
don't get it _ compassion isn't at the top of their agenda,'' he
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   But the amusement was tempered for some by the memory of how
Clinton's definition of himself as a New Democrat led to his
election and re-election. ``Remember the end result,'' said Rep.
Sam Gejdenson, D-Conn. ``The last guy who triangulated won.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
