<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR THURSDAY, OCTOBER 7
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Thursday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-U.S.-U.N.-DUES-NYT (moved on Tuesday, Oct. 5)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, Oct. 5,
about dues owed by the United States to the United Nations referred
incorrectly to a statement by Joseph E. Connor, the Under Secretary
General for Management. He said that without cash reserves, the
United Nations had lost financial flexibility, jeopardizing its
existence. He did not speak specifically of cash reserves due by
Dec. 30.
</P>
<P>
   BC-OVERCOMING-FAILURE-NYT (moved on Tuesday, Oct. 5)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, Oct. 5,
about failures that have been an asset for some executives
misspelled the surname of a professor at the Stanford Business
School who said managers who had made errors were increasingly
sought by Fortune 500 companies. He is Irv Grousbeck, not
Grousebeck.
</P>
<P>
   BC-TVGUIDE-GEMSTAR-NYT (moved on Monday, Oct. 4)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, Oct. 4,
about the sale of TV Guide to the Gemstar International Group and
the creation of a merged company, TV Guide International, misstated
the publication's future relationship to News Corporation, the
Rupert Murdoch company and a 44 percent shareholder. The company
will keep a 20 percent stake, not end its association with TV
Guide.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-PORN-SITE-NYT (moved on Wednesday, Sept. 29)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, Sept.
29, about the diversion of Web surfers to pornographic sites while
they are looking for legitimate sites misidentified the Federal
statute that covers individual suits over deceptive business
practices. A person can sue under the Lanham Act, which, among
other things, deals with unfair competition, not the Federal Trade
Commission Act.
</P>
</TEXT>
