<HEADLINE>
OFFICER TESTIFIES THAT DRUNKEN SINGER WAS KICKING DYING MAN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JAMES PINKERTON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UVALDE, Texas _ Country western singer Johnny Rodriguez was
drunk and repeatedly kicked and cursed a man who was shot and lying
on the kitchen floor of his mother's house, a Sabinal police
officer testified Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The testimony opened Rodriguez's murder trial, and defense
attorney's told the jury the singer will take the witness stand to
give his account of last year's shooting, which they insist was in
self defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody comes into my house. I'll shoot you and I'll shoot
anybody who comes into my house,'' Sabinal Officer Guillermo
``Willie'' Quirova quoted Rodriguez as shouting as he kicked the
mortally wounded man who lay moaning on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriquez, 47, is on trial in the Aug. 29, 1998, slaying of
Israel ``Bosco'' Borrego, 26, a local man with a long criminal
record and a reputation as a hard drinker.
</P>
<P>
   The singer faces up to life in prison if found guilty of killing
Borrego, who died in a Uvalde hospital several hours after he was
shot once in the lower abdomen.
</P>
<P>
   District Attorney Tony Hackebeil, in opening remarks to the
jury, said Rodriguez should be held accountable for his actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did not have good reason to do it,'' the prosecutor told
the jury.
</P>
<P>
   Hackebeil said Borrego was invited by Rodriguez to join drunken
parties that lasted for days at the simple woodframe house. He told
the jury he would call witnesses to show Borrego had been invited
to spend the night at the Rodriguez home on several occasions.
</P>
<P>
   But the outcome was different when Rodriguez found Borrego in
the kitchen shortly after 4 a.m., making breakfast for himself and
the singer, the prosecutor said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Johnny, in his drunken stupor gets mad at him for being in
there, and the rest is history,'' Hackebeil said.
</P>
<P>
   Sabinal Police Chief James ``Red'' Evans testified he observed
an intoxicated Rodriguez in the backseat of Quirova's patrol car
soon after he arrived at the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very irate, belligerent, ballistic,'' Evans replied after
being asked to describe the singer's condition. ``Very out of it,
just screaming and hollering.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorney Jay Norton told jurors that Rodriguez suspected
Borrego had broken into his home two weeks before the shooting, and
had told him he was not welcome there.
</P>
<P>
   Norton said Rodriguez was staying across the street with
neighbor Carlos Tovar because the sewer system was not working, and
he went to check on the house around 4 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   The door was unlocked, and inside the kitchen Rodriguez saw ``a
shadowy figure, a silhouette,'' Norton said, adding Rodriguez fired
after he recognized Borrego and saw him reach for something.
</P>
<P>
   ``He points (the gun) down at Bosco as he comes and shoots him
one time in the leg, to stop him,'' Norton told the jury.
</P>
<P>
   The defense attorney said Rodriguez had reason to fear Borrego,
and outlined a long criminal history to the jury.
</P>
<P>
   He said the shooting victim had been arrested for beating his
wife, assaulting a 14-year-old niece, for public intoxication, for
driving under the influence, for a rash of burglaries, including
stealing a box of steaks from the Sabinal restaurant where he
worked as a cook.
</P>
<P>
   ``He acted in self-defense. He acted in defense of his
property,'' Norton said of the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   He also said a sum of money had been taken from the Rodriguez
home that night, and that it was found on Borrego after the
shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Quirova, the first officer to arrive at the Rodriguez home, said
Rodriguez was kicking the victim while his neighbor, Tovar, was
trying to pull him off.
</P>
<P>
   He said Rodriguez resisted his efforts to handcuff him, and that
Tovar attempted to keep the officer from reaching a loaded revolver
lying on the kitchen table.
</P>
<P>
   The officer, who acknowledged being a second cousin of the
victim, said he removed four live rounds and one spent bullet from
the .357-caliber Smith &AMP; Wesson revolver he found on the table. He
said during an arraignment before a magistrate, five more bullets
were found in Rodriguez's pants pocket.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, whose hits such as ``Pass Me By'' (If You're Only
Passing Through) soared into the top 10 on the country charts in
the 1970s, expressed optimism after the first day of his trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it went well,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
