<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DIVIDEND INCREASES SLOW EVEN AS ECONOMY SOARS
</P>
<P>
   If the measure of corporate America's financial health is its
ability and willingness to increase dividends to shareholders, then
the country might appear to be in a recession. Standard &AMP; Poor's
reports that 117 companies announced dividend increases in
September, 10 fewer than in the month a year earlier. That was the
15th consecutive month that the number of dividend increases was
down year-over-year. By itself, such a long string of relative bad
news is not extraordinary. What is unusual is that the economy is
doing so well even while companies are growing more reluctant to
raise their dividends.
</P>
<P>
   SUPPORT GROWS FOR SOME TAX BREAKS
</P>
<P>
   Support is growing in Congress for a vast expansion of
retirement tax breaks for business owners, executives and highly
paid workers, moves that Republicans and Democrats alike think
would be popular with voters.
</P>
<P>
   EARNINGS RISE 6.7 PERCENT AT PEPSICO
</P>
<P>
   Pepsico reported a 6.7 percent increase in third-quarter profit
on the strength of higher earnings at its Frito-Lay and Tropicana
units, a performance that beat analysts' estimates by one cent a
share. The announcement sent the stock prices of both Pepsico and
its archrival, Coca-Cola, higher. Shares of Pepsico rose $1.75, or
5.6 percent, to $33.1875. Coke rose $4, to $51.9375.
</P>
<P>
   METABOLIFE POSTS INTERVIEW ON WEB
</P>
<P>
   Metabolife, a diet-product company, posted on the Internet a
complete, unedited videotaped interview between an ABC News
correspondent and the company's chief executive to publicize its
concerns that ABC would broadcast an unfair report on the medical
risks of its popular dietary supplement.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS GAIN AS RATE WORRIES EASE
</P>
<P>
   Stocks rose as investors shifted their attention to earnings and
away from the prospect of higher interest rates. The Dow Jones
industrial average rose 187.75 points, or 1.81 percent, to
10,588.34. Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index rose 24.05 points, or
1.85 percent, to 1,325.40. The Nasdaq composite index climbed 57.54
points, or 2.06 percent, to 2,857.21.
</P>
<P>
   Bond prices were little changed as investors awaited an
employment report expected Friday. The yield on the 30-year issue
was unchanged at 6.17 percent.
</P>
<P>
   DEBATE STIRRED ON DEBT IN BRAZIL
</P>
<P>
   Investors in Brazil are beginning to get nervous over the
possibility that the government might try to renegotiate its
domestic debt, which has nearly doubled in recent years. The
possibility has grown in part because the idea of a debt
renegotiation has been promoted by a rising presidential candidate,
Ciro Gomes, a 41-year-old former finance minister. He has made debt
renegotiation part of a broader economic plan that he says would
encourage long-term growth.
</P>
<P>
   LOSS NARROWS AT ADVANCED MICRO
</P>
<P>
   Advanced Micro Devices reported a smaller-than-expected
third-quarter loss as sales of its Athlon line of chips
accelerated. Executives said they were on track to achieve their
goal of breaking even in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ASARCO ACCEPTS PHELPS DODGE OFFER
</P>
<P>
   Asarco said it had accepted a $1.1 billion cash-and-stock
takeover bid from Phelps Dodge in a deal that would make Phelps
Dodge the world's largest copper company.
</P>
<P>
   UNION PACIFIC ORDERS LOCOMOTIVES
</P>
<P>
   Union Pacific said it had ordered 1,000 locomotives worth more
than $2 billion from a Canadian division of General Motors as it
seeks to improve its railroad network.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
