<SLUG> BC-PSYCH-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPRINT WORKERS EXPECT TO FACE MORE CHANGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Sprint Corp. this week dropped an emotional
grenade on its employees.
</P>
<P>
   As word of MCI WorldCom's intended acquisition exploded in
Kansas City, Sprint workers accustomed to constant challenge and
change braced for more.
</P>
<P>
   Those who study the human side of mergers and acquisitions say
recent merger history indicates Sprint workers should:
</P>
<P>
   - Brush up their resumes.
</P>
<P>
   - Get ready for at least two years of roiling management and
benefits changes, assuming the merger is approved.
</P>
<P>
   - Understand they are going to pass through stages of grief for
the loss of their independent, homegrown logo, almost as if a
family member died.
</P>
<P>
   - Be prepared for expected synergies that fail to synergize.
About two-thirds of all mergers do not produce the expected
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Those were among warnings from human-resource and merger
analysts and merger veterans about the psychological or emotional
fallout from mergers and acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Headhunters and chaos will come calling,'' predicted Robert
Lamb, author of merger books and professor of management and
finance at New York University's Stern School of Business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until the merger is final and has all the approvals, and
certainly afterward, you will have attrition from those plucked by
headhunters on overdrive or from those who are consumed by fear.''
</P>
<P>
   With months of work ahead before the purchase details are
completed, much less approved by regulators, the area's 18,789
Sprint workers are in for a protracted period of uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   That uncertainty was fueled by MCI WorldCom President Bernard J.
Ebbers, who was asked Tuesday in New York about staff redundancies
with Sprint. ``Do we have redundancies? Yes,'' Ebbers said, but he
immediately followed that by saying he did not know where they
were.
</P>
<P>
   That lack of specifics _ which will continue for months _ tends
to spread fear throughout a work force, consultants said.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Grubb, a Maryland consultant specializing in post-merger
integration, said loyal Sprint employees might be working through
shock, or first-stage grief, because the brand they toiled for was
being consumed by a bigger fish.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, Grubb said, that stage is replaced quickly by
second-stage fear or anger about the possibility of losing their
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Third-stage reaction commonly involves ``negotiation,'' or
positioning, as workers try to find their place in the new
organization. Gossip, jockeying for power, formation of new
alliances and anointing of new leaders characterize that stage.
</P>
<P>
   The end stage is acceptance.
</P>
<P>
   ``That reality is you've been bought,'' Grubb said. ``Get used
to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Merger veterans echo that alert and emphasize the emotional need
for speed in carrying out the details.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Haney, a Kansas City management consultant who specializes
in corporate-culture training, weathered the Merrell Dow
acquisition of Marion Laboratories in the 1980s and, a few years
later, the Hoechst acquisition of Marion Merrell Dow. He said
Sprint workers should expect ``continued pain and uncertainty about
who the new leaders are and what direction they're going to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Haney, who held executive positions in sales, marketing and
manufacturing, said his experience showed that the sooner new
management was put in place, the less employee unrest there was.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both organizations don't _ maybe can't _ work side by side,''
Haney said. ``Someone always prevails. If, right from the
beginning, new leaders can be put in place to articulate their
vision, it will help. If leadership confusion drags on, employees
lose confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Haney said mergers guaranteed some employee displacement, at
least in the short term.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to hurt some people, no question about it, so you
might as well get to it quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Haney did what many merger-weary executives have done. He
transferred his skills to self-employment.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Maurer, author of Beyond the Wall of Resistance:
Unconventional Strategies that Build Support for Change, said now
was a good time for Sprint workers at all levels to begin assessing
their career options.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't panic,'' Maurer said. ``The regulators are making noises
like the acquisition may never go through. But this presents the
perfect occasion to start looking around, take classes. Investigate
options. Don't chuck your job, but pay attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Maurer particularly cautioned Sprint workers against paying too
much attention to rumors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Read the paper. Listen to the news,'' Maurer said. ``Don't
listen to rumors. It will kill you.''
</P>
<P>
   Maurer predicted an acquisition would ``be wildly disruptive on
people,'' even for those who kept their jobs and were not asked to
move. Merger and acquisition experience shows they probably will
wrestle with new health insurance plans, new benefit structures,
new supervisors and new policies.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Lucas, an outplacement and executive counselor, experienced
the loss of local control that comes with out-of-town ownership
when he was at Drake Beam Morin. Now, at his own executive search
and coaching firm, he works to help others get through job loss and
reassignments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Change is difficult for everyone,'' Lucas said. ``It's human
nature. But it's easier for some than others. I would urge everyone
to look on the positive side and watch for opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be wrong to be too Pollyannaish about it, because in
the short run, Sprint may find that it's overstaffed in some areas.
But, in the long run, if growth projections are met, there may be
more opportunities for skilled workers in the telecommunications
field.''
</P>
<P>
   The best bet, Lucas said, is for Sprint workers to use the
coming months to analyze what is important to them and what kinds
of losses they fear. Income stability? Job title? Location of
residence? Turf? Corporate identity?
</P>
<P>
   Whatever bubbles up as a worker's biggest concern should be
addressed through career planning and study of options, he said _
and try not to let the uncertainty overwhelm emotions.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Beyer is proof that mergers and acquisitions may cause
tumultuous job changes, but that it is possible to flourish.
</P>
<P>
   Beyer, appointed in April by Gov. Bill Graves as secretary of
human resources for the state of Kansas, survived two decades of
change as his employer bank kept changing hands.
</P>
<P>
   Beyer's employer, Columbia Union, became Centerre in 1982, which
became Boatmen's in 1988, which became NationsBank in 1997, which
now is Bank of America. One of the changes transferred him to North
Carolina; all of them brought new policies and plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to take one day at a time,'' Beyer advised.
``Remember that, when you're in a swirling sea of changing
circumstances, you've gone through many changes in your lives
before. Remember what's worked well for you throughout your
lifetimes. Remember not to repeat the things that didn't work
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Workers in an acquired company should know that they are not
navigating change alone, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``Be aware that everyone's riding an emotional roller coaster,''
Beyer said. ``Otherwise, you might feel there's something wrong
with you, that you feel so uncomfortable. There's not.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very normal to feel uncomfortable when you let go of the
old and buy into the new. But you can manage your reaction, and
that's liberating to know that. You may not be able to manage the
change, but you can manage your reaction to that change.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-99 2121EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
