<HEADER>
A8908 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-LOWE-ART-NYT &LR;      10-06 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-LOWE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALEX LOWE, AMERICAN CLIMBER, AND DAVID BRIDGES, CAMERAMAN, MISSING
IN TIBET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mont., Wyo., Pakistan, Canada, Switzerland, Indonesia,
Peru)  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By CHRISTOPHER S. WREN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Alex Lowe, an American climber whose versatility and tenacity in
pushing the limits earned him a reputation as perhaps the country's
finest all-round mountaineer, was presumed killed on Tuesday after
vanishing in a massive avalanche on Shishapangma in Tibet. He was
40 and lived in Bozeman, Mont.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe had reached an altitude of about 19,000 feet on
Shishapangma, the world's 14th highest mountain _ also known as
Gosainthan, when he was swept away with David Bridges, 29, a
high-altitude cameraman, who also remains missing.
</P>
<P>
   They had planned to make the first descent by skis of the
mountain's southwest face after reaching the 26,291-feet-high
summit.
</P>
<P>
   A third climber, Conrad Anker, who last May discovered the
long-missing body of George Mallory on Mount Everest, was tossed
100 feet and was ``pretty beat up'' by the crashing snow, but
escaped serious injury, the expedition's leader, Andrew McLean,
said.
</P>
<P>
   McLean reported the accident by satellite phone to
MountainZone.com, a Web site that features outdoor adventures.
Hazardous conditions forced other expedition members to abandon
their search for Lowe and Bridges.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart Alexander Lowe was born on Dec. 24, 1958, into a Montana
family that started him hiking soon after he learned to walk; he
began his rock-climbing career wearing tennis shoes. His academic
training was in mathematics, but his forte was climbing.
</P>
<P>
   He was widely admired for excelling in every aspect of
mountaineering, from rock- and ice-climbing to ski descents. Galen
Rowell, another climber, described Lowe as ``a renaissance mountain
man in all regards.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many other serious climbers, Lowe also resolved to put
his wife and children first. He acknowledged that mountaineering
entailed risks, but said that experience increased the margin of
safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's only one way to gain mountain sense, and that's to be
in the mountains a lot,'' Lowe said. ``Unfortunately, when you're a
young climber, you have none. You're out there and your risk level
is high.''
</P>
<P>
   Climbing light, fast and often alone, Lowe pulled off feats that
left other climbers in awe. ``We're all at this one level,'' Anker
said once, ``and then there's Alex.''
</P>
<P>
   In late July, at an age when most climbers are slowing down,
Lowe led the first ascent of the northwest face of the Great Trango
Tower, a 6,000-feet-high wall in the Karakorum range of Pakistan
that no one else had even attempted. He was ill at the time, fell
50 feet and injured his elbow, but pushed on to the west summit at
20,410 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, he achieved a solo ascent of the north face of the
Matterhorn, the first solo ascent in winter of the north face of
the Grand Teton in Wyoming, and no fewer than 16 routes up the
sheer granite of El Capitan in Yosemite. Lowe scaled the nose of El
Capitan, a climb that once took days, in 10 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe climbed Mount Everest twice. A fascination with remote
places also took him to Antarctica, Baffin Island in the Canadian
Arctic, the Carstenz Pyramid in Indonesia and the Cordillera Blanca
in Peru.
</P>
<P>
   His recent climbs were sponsored by North Face, the clothing and
equipment outfitter.
</P>
<P>
   In March, Outside Magazine called Lowe the world's best climber.
He shrugged off the accolade, saying that there was no such thing
because climbing was a way of life, not a sport. The best climbers,
he said, distinguished themselves through persistence.
</P>
<P>
   ``And those are the ones that sort of go on and do lots of
climbs, and harder climbs,'' Lowe said in a MountainZone interview
. ``Those are the people that just can't shake it off. That's what
I am.''
</P>
<P>
   In the same interview, Lowe said his biggest challenge was
balancing the passion to climb with his love for his family, whom
he described as life's greatest reward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would let climbing slide away if I had to to maintain my
relationship with my family,'' he said. ``Because it really is the
big adventure.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowe is survived by his wife Jennifer and three sons, Max, 10,
Sam, 6, and Isaac, 3.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
