u s BC-BBN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT     10-06 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: METS' SECOND BASEMAN DOESN'T PLAY SECOND FIDDLE
ANYMORE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Venezuela)   By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Luis Gonzalez stood by his dressing stall in the
Arizona Diamondbacks' plush, subdued clubhouse. This was Tuesday
night rapidly segueing into Wednesday morning, and Gonzalez, a
32-year-old outfielder, was attempting to put a stunning 8-4 loss
to the Mets in perspective.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks had just suffered the equivalent of a
first-round knockdown to a challenger that showed neither fear nor
respect. Arizona, the National League West champion, was favored
and rested. The Diamondbacks clinched the division so long ago that
they had time to sit and watch the Mets' soap opera drama unfold in
the last two weeks. Little did Arizona know that it would soon
become part of the Mets' script.
</P>
<P>
   That script invariably includes a knock at the door. In Game 1
of the division series Tuesday night, the stranger at the door was
Edgardo Alfonzo, the Mets' 25-year-old second baseman. In his first
at-bat against the indomitable Randy Johnson, Alfonzo, down no
balls and two strikes, cracked a home run over the
left-center-field wall. The confidence spread immediately. After
that, every Met battled Johnson, refusing to be cowed by his
reputation. The Mets had great at-bats, not all resulting in hits,
but they set Johnson on the defensive early in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Alfonzo's homer signaled an early turning point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alfonzo has been hitting in the clutch all year this year,''
Gonzalez said. ``Monday, he hit a dramatic home run to start that
game off, today two more. He's definitely the guy we've got to
stop, because if he gets hot, he can pretty much carry that ball
club _ like he's been doing the last couple days.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez got to know Alfonzo when they played winter league ball
in Venezuela, Alfonzo's native country. ``He's not a flashy guy,''
Gonzalez said. ``He's a quiet-personality type guy and he goes out
there and gives you everything he's got. It's kind of weird to see
him playing in city like New York.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``Alfonzo's a very good hitter. He's done what
everybody in baseball knows he's capable of doing. The more years
you get up here, you realize what you're capable and not capable of
doing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets are beyond tired, playing on adrenaline. Three
emotional games at home against Pittsburgh, a flight to the
Midwest, a night game in Cincinnati for the wild-card playoff,
another flight halfway across the country, and across three time
zones, to face the 6-foot-10-inch Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Alfonzo's first-inning home run was medicinal, and set the tone
that lasted until his stunning grand slam in the ninth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Alfonzo had filled a great divide.
</P>
<P>
   Answer the question ``Who is Alfonzo?'' and you also answer the
question ``What is a second baseman?''
</P>
<P>
   Alfonzo has done what second basemen often do: play second
fiddle to fellow infielders. Play in the shadows of acrobatic
shortstops who do their loop-de-loops and hard-hitting third
basemen and first basemen with limited mobility but hearty bats.
</P>
<P>
   The second baseman emerges from the shadows when all seems lost,
or the team needs a missing punch. Last season, Alfonzo played
third base. When the Mets signed Robin Ventura, Alfonzo moved back
to second with feather-light effortlessness. Now the Mets have the
best infield in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   After Tuesday night's game, Mets Manager Bobby Valentine said:
``Over the last few years Edgardo Alfonzo has been a fabulous
baseball player; he has star quality, but he's improving. He's
learning about himself every day that he goes out there, gaining
confidence. And with confidence comes performance like you saw
tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   At the plate, Alfonzo has become far more patient and highly
selective of the pitches he will go after. Now he comes to bat with
a plan, no longer content to simply ``let it happen,'' not content
to allow pitchers to dictate the pace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I come to home plate now, I have an idea what I'm
going to do,'' Alfonzo said. ``I want to have patience at the plate
until I see a good pitch to hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Alfonzo's temperament and talents are a perfect fit for a Mets
infield with the low-key Ventura at third and John Olerud at first,
and the flamboyant Rey Ordonez at short.
</P>
<P>
   ``John and I are about the same,'' Ventura said. ``Rey is flashy
and loud _ the epitome of the Latin shortstop; he has the flair and
the energy that the rest of us don't have.''
</P>
<P>
   And Alfonzo?
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just above John and I,'' Ventura said. ``He's more into a
shell than Rey, but he's above us. He's a pretty good dancer, and
he can sing.''
</P>
<P>
   Last August, Alfonzo seemed ambivalent when someone asked if he
minded obscurity in a news-media-driven town where notoriety can
often mean dollars. He said that anonymity is fine at one level
``because I'm able to go out.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``I can go out with my wife and not worry.''
</P>
<P>
   In the same breath he expressed hope for a change, and that some
celebrity would come his way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometime, it's going to happen and, hopefully, that will be
pretty soon,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Change doesn't just happen. You have to force change, and force
transformation. What better way to do it than to homer three times
in two games in October on a New York baseball team?
</P>
<P>
   Alfonzo's transformation is indeed under way.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
