<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-KING-960&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JORDAN'S NEW KING ASSUMING KEY ROLE IN MIDEAST TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By WILLIAM A. ORME Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMMAN, Jordan _ Not long ago, King Abdullah planned a quick trip
abroad, to Vermont, to serve as best man at the wedding of a
Deerfield Academy classmate.
</P>
<P>
   But in another reminder of his new role as a pivotal player in
the high-wire world of Middle Eastern peacemaking, his autumn
weekend in New England soon blossomed into an official visit to the
United States, his second in just five months.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday afternoon, accompanied by the U.S. ambassador to
Jordan, King Abdullah flew off for a long week of Washington
meetings capped by a session at the White House. He carried with
him, somewhat ambivalently, a private message for President
Clinton, one that had been delivered to him here this week by an
emissary of President Saddam Hussein of Iraq _ another of Jordan's
problematic neighbors _ even though the king says has no illusions
about any imminent improvement in Iraqi-U.S. relations.
</P>
<P>
   The king is to discuss Jordan's military needs with Defense
Secretary William Cohen and duty-free access to the U.S. market
with Commerce Secretary William Daley. He will brief World Bank
president James Wolfensohn on his ambitious economic reform plans _
a prerequisite for further multilateral financing _ and promote
Jordan's potential as a high-tech, low-wage industrial haven to
computer entrepreneurs in Virginia and Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   And he hopes to prod Congress to release a promised $200 million
financial package that would make Jordan the second biggest
recipient of economic aid per capita, after Israel.
</P>
<P>
   But his main goal is to maintain the momentum toward the broad
regional peace settlement that he considers the key to Jordan's
security and economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Syria doesn't resolve the problem with Israel, then we pay
the price,'' he said before departing Wednesday. ``If Israel
doesn't resolve the problem with the Palestinians, again Jordan
will pay the price.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite those concerns, Abdullah leaves behind a country
increasingly comfortable with the ambitious and self-assured
leadership style of a 37-year-old ruler who was barely known when
he suddenly and unexpectedly ascended to the throne last February.
</P>
<P>
   And his surprising willingness to break with some of the
policies of his revered father, King Hussein, is already reshaping
Jordan's regional alliances and domestic agenda in ways that his
Arab neighbors and U.S. policy-makers both find welcome.
</P>
<P>
   In a wide-ranging conversation Wednesday with a small group of
European, American and Israeli journalists, King Abdullah sketched
out his views on the state of the peace talks and Jordan's changing
role as a regional intermediary.
</P>
<P>
   He is guardedly optimistic about negotiations between Syria and
Israel, despite outward signs that an initially positive dialogue
has degenerated into a sterile exchange of old and incompatible
bargaining gambits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, I think things are moving along better than the
atmosphere suggests,'' he said, citing his continuing contacts as
``a middle man or mediator'' with Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak
and, through the king's son, with Syrian President Hafez Assad.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the Syrians were saying and what the Israelis were saying
were really pretty much the same things,'' he said. ``They were
both in the same ball park, and what we did was to try to get the
messages to either party. As they start to sit down _ the Syrians
with the Israelis, the Syrians with the Americans _ then we have
done what we needed to do, and Jordan will pull out.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said he shared the concerns of many Arab leaders that
Israeli peace talks with Syria could overshadow the much more
complex and, in his view, far more important talks between Israel
and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peace with Syria is not peace with the Arab world,'' the king
said. ``The Arab world cannot warm towards Israel if you do not
solve the Palestinian issue, and there are many countries that want
a warm relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   An admirer of Barak, King Abdullah nonetheless warned that his
decision to press for a comprehensive final settlement, even at the
expense of negotiating delays, is being misinterpreted as
deliberate procrastination.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Barak won the election, maybe some people don't want to
admit it, but there was a euphoria all over the Middle East,'' he
said. ``You had the Syrians coming out of their shell, believing in
Barak and believing in Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak wanted ``to make something that would last, that would
actually make the Palestinians happier than what we had achieved in
Washington,'' the king said. ``He had good intentions in his heart.
But the perception in the Middle East was, this was further delay,
and that maybe this was not the man that we all thought he was.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his desire to expedite talks between Israel and the
Palestinians, King Abdullah rejects any direct role.
</P>
<P>
   He has said the Palestinians should take administrative control
of the Muslim holy sites of Jerusalem, which still remain formally
in his family's traditional charge. Unlike his father, he defers to
Palestinian Authority president Yasser Arafat as the sole leader of
the Palestinian people, except, of course, for the 2 million
Palestinians who remain citizens of Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had good relationships with Arafat from Day 1,'' he
said. ``We want to make sure that the Israelis and the Palestinians
have the best atmosphere to move forward with the peace process.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet he curtly rejects the notion of an eventual confederation
between Jordan and an independent Palestinian state, an idea
resuscitated recently by Arafat, but which many Jordanians fear
would spell the end of an independent Hashemite-led state here.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no such word as confederation in my vocabulary,''
King Abdullah said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   When he assumed the throne last February, Abdullah portrayed
himself as the keeper of the flame, as the custodian of his
father's complex political and diplomatic legacy. But within months
he began changing some of the terms of that inheritance.
</P>
<P>
   He sought rapprochement with his father's old adversaries in
Syria and Kuwait and an end to testy rivalries with Egypt and the
Palestinian Authority. Domestically, he began revamping an
entrenched political order that enriched an Amman elite but
effectively disenfranchised the Palestinian majority. He has
insisted on free-market reforms that will prepare Jordan for entry
into the World Trade Organization, perhaps as soon as next year,
but which will also threaten local business monopolies that
prospered during his father's reign.
</P>
<P>
   His most dramatic break came in September, when he ordered the
arrests of the local leaders of Hamas, the radical Islamist
Palestinian group that King Hussein had long tolerated as a
counterweight to Arafat and as a concession to Jordanian Islamists,
who also oppose peace with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   But senior officials here now portray the Jordanian branch of
Hamas as a renegade terrorist operation supported by Iranian
intelligence and conspiring against Hamas leaders within the
Palestinian territories. Arafat repeatedly asked the new Jordanian
government to take action against the group, foreign diplomats and
senior Jordanian officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jordan has made itself quite clear that Hamas offices will be
shut down in Jordan, and that is what will happen,'' King Abdullah
said Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
