<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-TEST-BAN-470&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEAL ON TEST BAN STALLS AS SENATE VOTE APPROACHES
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A deal to postpone a Senate vote on a treaty
banning underground nuclear tests stalled Wednesday on the
Republicans' aim to avoid having the pact become a campaign issue
in 2000 and the Democrats' desire to keep the accord alive next
year.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, a growing number of lawmakers on both sides urged
shelving the treaty, which faces near-certain defeat in a vote
scheduled for early next week, to avert a political and diplomatic
embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   With critics and supporters girding for a floor debate starting
on Friday, President Clinton signaled that he would welcome
postponing the vote on the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty, which he
signed in 1996. ``After two long years of inaction,'' Clinton said,
``one week is very little time for considered action.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Democrats and White House officials conceded that the
treaty did not have the two-thirds Senate majority required to
pass. But after having badgered Republicans for more than two years
to bring up the accord, they are now having trouble negotiating a
way out.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate majority leader, Trent Lott, and the Democratic
leader, Tom Daschle, began talks on Tuesday. But aides said no
discussions were held Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like playing a game of chicken,'' said Sen. Joseph Biden,
D-Del., who supports the treaty. ``Egos and raw politics start to
get in the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday afternoon Clinton assembled a group of current and
retired military officers, Nobel laureates and other treaty
supporters at a White House ceremony. They argued that the pact
would make it more difficult for countries like Russia, China,
India and Pakistan to develop and field more advanced nuclear arms.
</P>
<P>
   But under pressure from his conservative wing, Lott telephoned
Clinton's national security adviser, Sandy Berger, to warn him that
the Senate would vote next week, unless Clinton agreed not to bring
up the accord for the rest of his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   White House aides and Senate Democrats rejected that condition
and suggested that the high-stakes brinkmanship could run right up
to the actual vote. More than 150 countries have signed the treaty.
But only 23 of the 44 nuclear-capable nations whose approval is
required have ratified it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president does not want a vote now, but he doesn't want to
put it off to 2001, either,'' said Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., who
dined at the White House with Clinton and about 10 other senators
on Tuesday. ``He doesn't want to look like he's backing down, and
he'd have a hard time explaining it to our European allies.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott, on the other hand, does not want Democrats wielding the
treaty as a campaign issue next year. ``Lott is willing to put it
off,'' Specter said. ``But he doesn't want to face the same
crescendo next spring.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A small group of senators on each side sees advantage in the
treaty's failure. Republicans could kill one of Clinton's top
foreign-policy goals, and Democrats could accuse the Republicans of
contributing to the spread of advanced nuclear arms.
</P>
<P>
   As partisan passions heat up, several senators have appealed to
their leaders and Clinton to shelve the treaty. ``Setting it aside
is not so bad an idea,'' said Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash., who is
close to Lott and who opposes the accord.
</P>
<P>
   Two leading Democrats who back the test ban, Robert Byrd of West
Virginia and Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut also called for a
postponement.
</P>
<P>
   At a second day of hearings before the Armed Services Committee,
senators wrestled with two major issues, whether the treaty could
be adequately verified and whether a complete ban would jeopardize
the American nuclear arsenal's safety and reliability.
</P>
<P>
   Critics like Sen. Robert Smith, independent of New Hampshire,
said the treaty would tie the hands of the United States and could
not assure the detection of low-level nuclear explosions that
nations like Iran or Iraq might conduct to test crude nuclear
devices.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary William Cohen and Gen. Henry Shelton, chairman
of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, acknowledged that the proposed
testing rules were not perfect, but that 320 seismic monitors that
would be installed under the accord would detect detonations large
enough to threaten America's nuclear deterrence.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has not conducted any underground nuclear
tests since 1992. Government scientists now use a $4.5 billion
annual program that uses non-nuclear explosive tests and
sophisticated computer modeling to maintain the safety and
reliability of the arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   But critics, including six former defense secretaries, say as
the weapons age, confidence in their reliability will decline,
unless they are periodically tested. ``Over time, the components of
our weapons corrode and deteriorate, and we lack experience
predicting the effects of such aging,'' wrote the former
secretaries, Frank Carlucci, Dick Cheney, Melvin Laird, Donald
Rumsfeld, James Schlesinger and Caspar Weinberger, all Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. John Shalikashvili, a former chairman of the Joint Chiefs
of Staff, told senators that the directors of the national
laboratories had assured military leaders that the aging would not
pose a problem until at least 2005, when the scientific testing
program would be more advanced.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-99 2141EDT &QL; 
