<HEADER>
A8948 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LA     10-06 1094
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO'S TO BLAME?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The National Football League is not coming back to Los Angeles.
Should we laugh, or should we cry?
</P>
<P>
   On one hand, it's reassuring to know we're not going to be
saddled with a west coast version of the Cleveland Browns, an
expansion team that might require 3-to-5 years to become average
and put a heavy drape over our NFL TV viewing choices.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles is not Cleveland, you see, and it's time everyone
stops apologizing for it. We're a sophisticated city that doesn't
need to cling to a sports team for its self-esteem. And having
danced in the pale moonlight with Georgia Frontiere and Al Davis,
we've lost any sense of romance about the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to sports teams, we demand a pre-nup, especially
when the NFL is involved. The bottom line for fans is that the NFL
situation in L.A. has never been better. No team equals no losers
and more TV. Pass the chips and salsa.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, it's frustrating to play the black box tape
from the wreckage of Wednesday's decision and realize the same kind
of people incompetent and/or stubborn civic leaders and prospective
owners with short arms and/or big egos made the same kind of
mistakes that have been dogging L.A. football interests now for
more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   The blame for this particular failure spreads quicker, thicker
and farther than the oil from the Exxon Valdez.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Haagan
</P>
<P>
   . He was the Coliseum Commission president who in 1987 refused
to follow through on promised renovations to the Coliseum on behalf
of Davis and the Raiders. That decision led the Raiders to look
elsewhere and their eventual return to Oakland after the 1994
season.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim city officials
</P>
<P>
   . In acquiring the land to build the Pond, they had to negotiate
with the Rams. President John Shaw gave up some land rights in
exchange for a buyout clause in the Rams' lease at the Big A.
Anaheim officials, despite knowing the Rams were unhappy, never
thought the Rams would pay it. Well, they didn't. St. Louis did.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles Mayor Richard Riordan
</P>
<P>
   . In 1995, Dodgers owner Peter O'Malley stepped up with an offer
to build, with his own money, a $300 million football stadium next
to Dodgers Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   O'Malley was re-energized by the NFL idea after several years of
in-fighting with the Bud Seligs of baseball. But Riordan, urged by
City Hall colleagues on behalf of the Coliseum, talked O'Malley
into letting the Coliseum bid run it's course.
</P>
<P>
   The rest is sad history. O'Malley agrees, the idea loses steam,
he puts the Dodgers up for sale, Fox buys them, and the
organization begins its descent to hell.
</P>
<P>
   City Councilman Mark Ridley-Thomas
</P>
<P>
   . Ridley-Thomas hammered the idea of returning to Coliseum, and
his conviction was sincere. But he and everyone in the Coliseum
effort made a huge mistake thinking the NFL would return without
more of its favorite kind of money, public.
</P>
<P>
   Even when the NFL gave the Coliseum its tentative backing in
March, the league all but said it would seek a sweetener to the
modest $40 million in fresh money already committed. How it came
dressed, as parking garages, is irrelevant. The NFL wanted more,
and Ridley-Thomas et al should have known it would come to that.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Roski and Eli Broad
</P>
<P>
   . Roski and the good people in Carson may be the only innocents
in the drama. Roski doggedly pursued a team for the Coliseum and
was willing to pay for stadium construction by himself.
</P>
<P>
   But once the league started holding hands with Michael Ovitz,
Roski and Broad should have called an audible. The league clearly
wanted Ovitz in charge of a L.A. franchise because of his marketing
vision and ties to Hollyweird.
</P>
<P>
   Broad, who is rich enough to buy Michael Ovitz and his favorite
couple, Tom Cruise and Nicole Kidman, bristled at the idea of being
a silent money man behind a classic OPM (other people's money)
charlatan like Ovitz. Ovitz (and the NFL) kept waiting for Broad
and Roski to call and join his group, but it never happened.
</P>
<P>
   Governor Gray Davis
</P>
<P>
   . Davis thought he was helping things by sending his man, Bill
Chadwick, into the fray to settle the league's public money issues.
But all Chadwick did was anger NFL owners with financial demands
and waste six weeks of time Roski could have used working to keep
the Coliseum alive.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Ovitz
</P>
<P>
   . From the very beginning, there was conjecture that Ovitz
didn't have the scratch to build a stadium and own a NFL team, and
it turns out it was true. Ovitz had a rich ally in grocery
millionaire Ron Burkle, but the Ovitz franchise fee offer was a
short-armed $450 million and included the league carrying a note on
stadium construction.
</P>
<P>
   Remember this the next time someone steps to a podium and says
he has a vision. It's often all he has.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL
</P>
<P>
   . I've saved the most guilty party for last, because every act
of this entire passion (passionless?) play was directed and
produced by the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   In December of 1994, Paul Tagliabue came to a Raiders game in
San Diego and said the Coliseum was no longer a viable NFL stadium.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, the league approved a deal for the Raiders to play at a
new stadium at Hollywood Park, but then submarined it, saying the
idea was underfunded. What the league actually did was insist on a
second tenant and refuse to agree to Davis' terms on the use of PSL
(private seat license) and Super Bowl revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout 1998, the league urged Ovitz to aggressively campaign
for a franchise and new location, leading him to Carson and the
kind of competition for an expansion team the league wanted. But at
no time during the process did the league ever offer a hard
franchise fee figure or even commit to conduct an auction.
</P>
<P>
   Even after choosing the Coliseum, the league did what it could
to keep other sites alive, and even encouraged an eleventh-hour bid
by Marvin Davis and Hollywood Park as another hedge to create the
kind of competition that yields $700 million franchise fees.
</P>
<P>
   Touchdown, NFL.
</P>
<P>
   There will undoubtedly be talk now of an existing NFL team
moving to Los Angeles, or the return of the Raiders. But that's all
it will be until someone builds a stadium. I wouldn't expect to see
Mssrs. Roski, Broad and Ovitz hanging around for another parry with
the NFL unless they plan to buy a team that moves here, which isn't
likely.
</P>
<P>
   So for the moment, all we can really do is congratulate Houston.
We'll see you on TV.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
