<HEADLINE>
OFF-SPEED PITCHES LEAVING RANGERS OFF-BALANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
NEW YORK _ Rangers hitters are carnivores. They're aggressive,
take-no-prisoners batters that love to feast on fastballs. Any
pitcher that relies too much on the hard stuff is going to get
pounded.
<TEXT>
<P>
   That's why the Rangers led the American League with a .295
average and set club records with 230 home runs and 945 runs.
</P>
<P>
   This bit of inside information is hardly top-secret. American
League pitchers have known this for years and the ``book'' on the
Rangers has always been inducing them to be overaggressive at the
plate.
</P>
<P>
   Yankees pitcher Orlando Hernandez did so in beating the Rangers,
8-0, in the first game of the American League Division Series on
Tuesday and Andy Pettitte knows that will be important for him in
Game 2 tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, at the beginning of the game you have to set a tone
and show them that you're going to throw strikes and be
aggressive,'' Pettitte said. ``If we get a lead again, that will
get them to start pressing a little bit. That's when teams start
swinging at bad pitches. The game will dictate that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the key for me is just to go out and try to get
command of everything and get strike one and throw strikes. Then
you can start expanding the strike zone.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees don't know anything more about the Rangers than any
other American League team. They just use what they know better.
Their pitching staff was second in the American League with a 4.13
earned-run average, trailing only the Boston Red Sox and Pedro
Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   But it does appear the Yankees pitching staff ``owns'' the
Rangers. They've held them to one run in four playoff games going
back to last season's Division Series.
</P>
<P>
   Even during the regular season, the Yankees beat the Rangers in
eight of 12 meetings by holding them to a .246 batting average,
their lowest against any team. The Rangers drew 33 walks in those
12 games while striking out 81 times. The Rangers hit .307 in 10
games against the Cleveland Indians with 35 walks and 63
strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   But then, the Indians don't have the Yankees' pitching staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before the game, I was saying that's one series \Ragainst the
Rangers\S I didn't want to play again,'' Yankees manager Joe Torre
said. ``We gave them one run in three games last year but you know
they're so good offensively. But again, and I allude to Pedro
Martinez pitching in the All-Star Game. You have McGwire, you have
Sosa, you have all those good players.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if you're on your game, you can control the game somewhat.
And we've been fortunate against this club that we have been able
to pitch well.''
</P>
<P>
   Two Rangers had success Tuesday. Rusty Greer, the Rangers' most
patient hitter, had two walks his first two times up. Ivan
Rodriguez, the Rangers' best breaking-ball hitter, had a double and
a single, the only hits off Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to have controlled aggression,'' Greer said. ``By
that, I mean you go up there thinking: hit, hit, hit, take. You've
got to be prepared to swing the bat early, but sometimes part of
you has to recognize and take a pitch. Any time you think: take,
then swing, that's when I get in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers aren't stupid. Juan Gonzalez didn't hit .326 with 39
home runs and 128 runs batted in by going up there swinging at
anything. He did make the proper adjustment Tuesday night but a
great catch by Bernie Williams robbed the Rangers of a big inning.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, batting with two on and one out in the first inning,
saw a steady stream of off-speed breaking pitches from Hernandez
and ended up striking out on a low slider. Batting in the same
situation in the third inning, Gonzalez made Hernandez get the ball
up and he lined one into the right-center gap. But Williams made a
sliding, lunging catch to take away an extra-base hit, and the
Rangers' rally died.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers also had a chance at Hernandez in the sixth inning,
trailing 3-0. Greer, leading off the inning, worked the count 3-1
but popped up a pitch he should have creamed. Gonzalez then worked
a walk from Hernandez but got doubled off when first baseman Tino
Martinez made a leaping catch of Rafael Palmeiro's blistering line
drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Juan's ball dropped _ Bernie made a great catch _ and
Rafael's ball goes into the corner, it's a different ballgame,''
Rangers general manager Doug Melvin said. ``They made two great
defensive plays. But this is just too good of a lineup, we have too
many good offensive players, not to go out there and have a good
run.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers have done it against 12 other American League teams;
they just need to do the same thing against the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care, back when I played in the dark ages, good
pitching stops good hitting,'' Torre said. ``That's what this game
is based on.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
