<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UKU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SELF-PROMOTION HELPED UKU
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE IRVINE  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Putting a highlight film together is not an uncommon tactic for
a high school or junior college football player looking for a place
to play at the next level.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the highlight film actually persuade a coach particularly
one that has no previous knowledge of the player to sign the player
doesn't often happen.
</P>
<P>
   But, without his self-prepared video, Austin Uku, who played at
Narbonne High and Long Beach City College, probably would have
never been discovered by the coaches at the University of Arizona.
And the 6-foot-1, 230-pound Uku certainly wouldn't be in the
starting lineup at defensive end when the Wildcats play host to USC
on Saturday if former Narbonne teammate Brandon Manumaleuna hadn't
delivered the highlight reel to the Arizona coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``You search high and low for a player,'' Arizona defensive line
coach Marty Long told the Arizona Republic, ``and all of the sudden
a kid brings in the tape and says, `Look at my buddy.' I recruited
the school (LBCC), I (visited) the school and I didn't know
anything about him.''
</P>
<P>
   Not many colleges knew much about him especially not as a
defensive player. Uku, who grew up in Pittsburgh, moved to Southern
California during his sophomore year to live with his mother, Carol
Fuller. He filled several roles in high school. He played tailback,
fullback, safety, defensive end, defensive tackle, defensive end,
linebacker and cornerback at Narbonne.
</P>
<P>
   When he went to Long Beach City College, though, Uku fancied
himself as a running back. He played that position for most of his
two seasons despite LBCC coach Larry Reisbig's suggestion that Uku
would be more valuable on defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always loved running back,'' said Uku, who did see limited
duty on defense. ``But last year, we had four running backs and the
coaches were trying to spread the ball out evenly. When (defensive
end Scott Parkhurst) broke his ankle I felt I could help the team
out more on defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Parkhurst, who was leading the team with nine sacks, was injured
in the seventh game of the season. Uku, who had 330 yards and four
touchdowns rushing, only played on defense during the final four
games, but he was selected Al-South Coast Conference after
contributing 27 tackles, including 18 for loss, eight sacks, 10
pass breakups, 10 quarterback hurries, a fumble recovery, three
forced fumbles and a safety.
</P>
<P>
   College scouts were flocking to LBCC, but not many of them had
offers for Uku. Only Oregon State and Cincinnati were showing
serious interest until Uku sent out the videos. When Arizona
offered, Uku jumped.
</P>
<P>
   ``The scheme at Arizona fit me,'' said Uku, who was born in
Nigeria and moved to Pennsylvania when he was a year old. ``And
Brandon and I are basically best friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Uku didn't join Arizona until the Wildcats training camp began
and thought he would see limited action behind Mike Robertson, who
started four games last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I might be a third-down type of guy,'' Uku said.
</P>
<P>
   He's been much more than that. Uku was one of the few Arizona
defenders to play well in the opening loss to Penn State and was in
the starting lineup by the third week. In five games, Uku has 18
tackles, with four for loss, a sack, a pass breakup, a forced
fumble and fumble recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Strangely enough, one of the year's highlights for Uku came
during the 41-7 loss to Penn State.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the first time that my father (Eustace Uku) had seen me
play,'' Uku said. ``That was pretty special.''
</P>
<P>
   It's hardly been a special year for the Arizona defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's probably been most surprising to me is that we haven't
played good defense,'' Arizona coach Dick Tomey said. ``We've
played pretty good defense around here for a long time. We haven't
been able to do that this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Missed tackles have become commonplace for a Wildcat defense
that has allowed 33 points and 397 yards per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very confusing to me,'' USC coach Paul Hackett said after
watching the Wildcats defense on tape. ``What I do see is,
strategically, a defense that creat a lot of problems for an
offensive football team. They put a ton of people up front and the
plan is to get you confused.''
</P>
<P>
   Uku is expected to play a big part in that confusion on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``My confidence is getting greater and greater every week,'' Uku
said. ``It should be through the roof when I completely learn the
defense. All I can do now is stay consistent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
