<HEADER>
A8957 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBN-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-     10-06 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL DECISION NO SHOCKER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wow, I can't believe it.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL gave Houston an expansion team over L.A.
</P>
<P>
   What a shock!
</P>
<P>
   The next thing someone is going to tell me is that the earth is
round. Or that the sun sets in the west. Or that Ted Turner and
Rupert Murdoch despise each other. Or that there is smog and
traffic congestion in Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   L.A. had about as much chance of securing the NFL's 32nd
franchise as Michael Ovitz does of being given a glowing
testimonial dinner by Michael Eisner.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone with the barest knowledge of economics could have
predicted months ago that Houston would prevail against L.A. for
the most compelling reason imaginable money.
</P>
<P>
   When it came to hyperbolic rhetoric, inflated promises and
Hollywood glamour, L.A. had it all going with the publicity-crazed
Ovitz leading its charge.
</P>
<P>
   But when it came to actually putting up capital with no strings
attached no deferred payments, no name-dropping of billionaire
friends, no silly mumbo-jumbo utterances calculated to con gullible
journalists Houston had it all going with a person, Bob McNair,
quite willing to put his cash where his mouth is.
</P>
<P>
   Score a dazzling knockout for Houston with McNair's $700 million
franchise fee offer making a mockery out of the puny $400 million
pittance tendered by Ovitz and his wealthy pal Ron Burkle.
</P>
<P>
   McNair stepped to the plate and jolted a Mark McGwire home run.
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz stepped to the plate amid great gloating and fanned
ignobly.
</P>
<P>
   L.A. reminds me of an aging beauty queen, or to be gender
equitable an aging Mr. Universe who lives in a perpetual state of
self-deception and refuses to accept reality.
</P>
<P>
   If you listen to L.A.'s representatives in recent times, you'd
come to the conclusion that the entire NFL soon would be blown
asunder unless it stuck a team in the second largest television
market in America.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that the NFL has survived quite admirably without L.A.
the past four years franchises have appreciated in value during
this period more than 30 per cent and the fact that two teams, the
Raiders and Rams, already have spurned the city is an indication of
the delusional state of L.A.'s leaders.
</P>
<P>
   If you listen to Ovitz and it would be difficult not to since
the guy the past couple of years has been gamboling around
extolling the virtues of first Carson and then the Coliseum and
finally Hollywood Park you'd have thought L.A. was a certainty to
get an NFL team.
</P>
<P>
   And that has been the problem for L.A.
</P>
<P>
   There have been too many guys with fancy Dunn &AMP; Bradstreet
ratings and entrees to the movers and shakers of the entertainment
community slinging nothing more than a bunch of horse manure.
</P>
<P>
   First, the Ed Roski-Eli Broad Coliseum group and now the
Ovitz-Burkle tandem has besieged the NFL and the media with a lot
of windblown prattle that hasn't been backed up by firm financial
commitment.
</P>
<P>
   So what's next for L.A.?
</P>
<P>
   Well, immediately, someone should stick a horse muzzle on the
mouth of Ovitz, who has received more ink for doing nothing than
any person I can recall since the heyday of George Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   I mean, Ovitz is supposed to have all these fantastically
wealthy friends, yet not one not even the ``billionaire'' Ron
Burkle was willing to come even close to matching McNair's offer.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, Ovitz thought L.A. was going to get an NFL franchise
on the cheap because it is, after all, L.A.
</P>
<P>
   But the NFL owners, a hard-boiled lot who became rich because of
a passionate fascination for money, weren't interested in such a
sentimental concept.
</P>
<P>
   L.A. might have matchless weather and wonderful amusement parks
and gorgeous beaches and plenty of celebrities, but that extra $10
million each owner would derive from McNair's kindly overture was
far more appealing to tastes that are greed-driven.
</P>
<P>
   I'm sure the happiest person about L.A.'s latest rejection is Al
Davis, stuck these days with the Raiders in Oakland, much to his
distress.
</P>
<P>
   Davis desperately wants to return here, and still might if he
can (a) get out of his long-term lease in Oakland and (b) if he can
find a suitable way to have a stadium built for him in L.A.
</P>
<P>
   As he found out during his 13 years here and as everybody else
has found out who's tried to do it, that is a most daunting task.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the prospect of Al Davis and the Raiders returning to
L.A. - as implausible as it might seem is far more likely than
Michael Ovitz ever bringing a team to these parts.
</P>
<P>
   But one can't count out Mr. Ovitz at least in the language
department.
</P>
<P>
   If success were measured purely in words and not in actions then
I suspect one can perceive Michael Ovitz as being a godsend for
L.A. football.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
