<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 21:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8965 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKEES-NYT &LR;      10-06 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPATIENCE PROVES COSTLY FOR RANGERS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's not as if the Yankees possess some secret formula on how to
shut down the fearsome offense of the Texas Rangers. It's not as if
the Rangers are numb to the strategy that is destroying them; the
Texas coaching staff has reminded the Rangers players to swing only
at strikes and to ignore the slop the Yankees' pitchers are
throwing out of the strike zone.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rangers keep swinging recklessly and the Yankees keep
shutting them out, inning after inning after inning. Texas, which
has averaged nearly six runs a game during the regular season over
the last two years, has scored one run in its last four playoff
games against the Yankees. The Rangers lost by 8-0 in Game 1 of the
three-of-five-game division series Tuesday night, after scoring a
single run in three games during their 1998 division series against
the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Including the last game of the 1996 division series, the Rangers
have scored one run in their last 42 playoff innings against the
Yankees. ``With our offense, our ball club, to me it's
mind-boggling,'' said Johnny Oates, the Rangers' manager.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' Andy Pettitte will face Rick Helling of the Rangers
in Game 2 Thursday night at Yankee Stadium, before the series
shifts to Texas Saturday, when Roger Clemens faces the Rangers'
Esteban Loaiza.
</P>
<P>
   Texas led the American League in batting in each of the last two
seasons, its lineup capable of the incredible. Juan Gonzalez, the
Rangers' right fielder, has driven in 100 or more runs eight times
in his career, catcher Ivan Rodriguez is coming off a season in
which he accumulated 199 hits and Rafael Palmeiro is going to get
consideration for the most valuable player award after hammering 47
home runs and driving in 148 runs.
</P>
<P>
   But it may be that the Rangers, as good as they are, may not be
suited for the post-season. Most of the teams that have won
championships in this decade are stocked with patient hitters who
work the count and give themselves a chance to anticipate a
particular pitch in a certain situation _ and often drive the
opposing pitcher off the mound in the middle innings because of an
escalating pitch count. The Yankees of 1998 may have been the best
example of this trait, and in forcing Aaron Sele to throw 117
pitches in five innings Tuesday, they show they still possess that
quality.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, however, do not. The Texas lineup is very
aggressive. During the regular season, the Rangers averaged 3.73
pitches a plate appearance, an average number for a team stocked
with so many veteran hitters, and during the regular season, the
Rangers ranked fifth in the league in walks _ and fifth in
strikeouts. The Yankees were third.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez drew only 97 walks combined in 1998 and 1999; Bernie
Williams had 100 walks this season. Rodriguez had only 32 walks
last season and 24 this season. Ranger shortstop Royce Clayton had
39 walks and 100 strikeouts, Lee Stevens 52 walks and 132
strikeouts, Todd Zeile 56 walks and 94 strikeouts. It is the way
they have hit all year: attack.
</P>
<P>
   In meetings before Tuesday's game, the Rangers' batting coach,
Rudy Jaramillo, repeated to his hitters how important patience was,
but once Game 1 began, they reverted to their usual mode. Gonzalez
chased an off-speed pitch out of the strike zone with two runners
on in the first inning and struck out with an off-balance swing,
and this continued most of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Orlando Hernandez kept throwing changeups and breaking balls _
and he often changed the speeds of his breaking balls _ and the
Rangers' hitters kept swinging, often off balance, hitting pop-ups
and fly balls. Hernandez walked six in eight innings, but as Yankee
Manager Joe Torre and others noted, it was clear that Hernandez was
pitching around certain hitters _ Rusty Greer and Palmeiro,
particularly. ``He has a lot of confidence in his ability to throw
strikes when he wants to,'' Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   Of his approach, Hernandez said, ``That's a tactic that we
discuss within the team that I don't think should be discussed here
with you.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers did not work out at Yankee Stadium Wednesday. But
Doug Melvin, the general manager, and the coach Bucky Dent met with
reporters and spoke hopefully of a game in which Texas hits as it
usually does. Once somebody gets a hit and everybody starts
relaxing, Dent said, then the runs will come.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin said: ``I know that the guys are going out there and
giving it their best. We're a very good offensive ball club, and
we'll break out of it somewhere along the line here. Just hope it's
sooner than later.''
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte allowed one run in seven innings against the Rangers in
Game 2 of last year's division series, pitching in the same pattern
established by David Wells in Game 1: changeups and off-speed
pitches low in the strike zone. He pitched much more effectively
after the trade deadline by relearning to trust his fastball on the
outside corner, when facing right-handed batters.
</P>
<P>
   It will be crucial for Pettitte to get strike calls on the
outside fringe of the strike zone _ and if he does, the Rangers
will have to continue to swing aggressively. But this might be good
news for Texas: Chuck Meriwether, who will umpire behind home plate
Thursday night, has a reputation for not liking to call out hitters
on third strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``When this team breaks out, it's going to be big,'' Dent said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rangers better break out soon, or they will be left to
dwell on another post-season failure. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-99 2150EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
