<DOCNO> NYT19991006.0430 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 21:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8967 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-HOMEWORK-INTERNET-SFC     10-06 1206
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMEWORK-INTERNET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 WEB SOFTWARE GIVES PARENTS ACCESS TO SCHOOL RECORDS  &HT;     By DAVID LAZARUS 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
SAN FRANCISCO -- Lori Anzini, director of technology for the
Pittsburg Unified School District in Contra Costa (Calif.) County,
knows how tough it is to stay ahead of kids.
<P>
   When Pittsburg High School installed a system eight years ago to
automatically phone parents if a student missed a class, kids
quickly figured out how to get around the incriminating evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would beat their parents home and erase the tape on the
answering machine,'' Anzini said. ``When my own daughter was in
high school, she was able to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   It has taken a while, but schools are upping the ante. Many now
use the Internet to post attendance, grades and homework
assignments online, allowing parents to keep tabs on their kids as
never before and, ideally, to be more involved in the education
process.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see it as `Big Brother is watching you,' '' Anzini
said. ``But the reality is that parents are responsible for their
kids up to a certain age. Parents need to have a way to see where
their kids are at all times.''
</P>
<P>
   Like a more grown-up version of the Web cams that allow anxious
moms and dads to peek in on day-care centers, a variety of
resources is available on the Internet to give parents almost full
access to the academic records of their school-age youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   Some are offered by private companies that hope to fill a niche
among cash-strapped school districts (and turn a buck via
subscription and advertising fees) and others are overseen by
schools using commercially available software or Web-hosting
services. Pittsburg High School is launching an increasingly
popular service called Internet Student Information System, ISIS.
Using ISIS, a pressed-for-time parent need only click onto the
school's Web site, enter a user I.D. and password, and up comes a
full menu of options relating to his or her child, including class
attendance, grades, test scores, disciplinary problems and even
immunization shots received.
</P>
<P>
   The software, which can cost as much as $3,000 per school, was
developed by a Southern California firm called EduLink Systems.
</P>
<P>
   David Funderburk, EduLink's president, said demand is slowly
growing for online tools that help parents monitor their kids'
academic performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of kids, when they get home from school, they don't want
to say much,'' he observed. ``ISIS is easier for most parents than
having to go into the school and speaking with a teacher or
counselor.''
</P>
<P>
   EduLink is now shipping newly developed software allowing
schools to add homework assignments to the mix. Pittsburg High
plans to add the homework option this month. The catch to this
latter application, though, is that it requires teachers to input
the information each day, and many educators are voicing reluctance
to adding a task to their busy workloads.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is training the teachers how to do it,''
Pittsburg's Anzini said. ``This is especially true for the older
ones. But we've got a lot of young teachers that are really excited
about this. They know that getting the parents to participate is
the way to make children succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone, though, is convinced that this brave new world of
education is for the best. Michael Kamil, a professor of education
at Stanford University, said one upshot of these electronic
advances is a shifting of responsibility for the student's
performance from the school to the parent _ potentially leading to
less supervision in the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a long-term erosion of respect for schools,'' Kamil
said. ``There's been a long-term shifting of responsibility between
what we want schools to do and what we want parents to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Simply posting academic records online, he insisted, will not
necessarily lead to parents being more in touch with how their kids
are doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I tell you that Johnny scored 72 on his test, what does it
mean?'' Kamil asked. ``Information needs to be interpreted in
context. Seventy-two could be the best score in the school and it
could be the worst in the school.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, he pointed out that a growing number of tech-savvy
youngsters are more than capable of hacking into school computers
and fiddling with their records, and that passwords do not provide
the highest level of security.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, although advocates of online school resources trumpet
the Net as a preferred medium for communication between parents and
teachers, Kamil said most educators would say otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's just no substitute for face-to-face meetings with
teachers,'' he said. ``It really is the only way to learn how your
kid is doing.''
</P>
<P>
   For some parents, however, the Net may be the only opportunity
they have to connect with their child's school.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to keep communication lines open with parents,
especially at the high school level,'' said Jeff Reich, principal
of Antioch High School in Contra Costa County, which launched its
own ISIS service two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   He said as many as 400 parents have registered to access ISIS
since its introduction, and some visit the school's site every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're appreciative,'' Reich said. ``They don't have to worry
about when report cards are coming out or about attendance.''
</P>
<P>
   Such appreciation hasn't been lost on those with an
entrepreneurial bent. A number of Internet companies aim to be
intermediaries between parents and schools.
</P>
<P>
   To date, most of these companies have targeted school districts
in the South and Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Maddox is head of a firm called Teacher's Pet, based in
Roanoke, Va. His service allows teachers to post homework
assignments online so that parents can make sure their kids are
keeping up with their classes. About 100 schools subscribe to the
service for up to $795 a year, depending on the number of teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Private schools eat this up,'' Maddox said. ``Their parents
are more customer-oriented than those at public schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's quite a bit of resistance from the teachers,'' he
added, ``but that's not a battle we want to fight. It's up to the
administrators.''
</P>
<P>
   For its part, GradeNet, based in Tulsa, charges parents $24.95 a
year for the first student and $19.95 for additional students for
online access to grades, assignments and other academic
information.
</P>
<P>
   The company's president, Roger Fox, said he hasn't signed up any
customers yet, but is confident that schools will be attracted to
the service because they would bear no financial burden for posting
and hosting information.
</P>
<P>
   ``My core belief is that this is so valuable, we will not have a
problem getting subscribers,'' he said. (Texas, Fox feels, ``seems
like real fertile territory.'')
</P>
<P>
   So what do kids think about having their parents use the
Internet to check up on them? Nearly all providers of online
academic resources acknowledged that there's a Big Brother aspect
to these services, but they uniformly stressed that the value to
parents far outweighs whatever discomfort may be caused to their
offspring.
</P>
<P>
   Or, as Antioch High's Reich put it, ``Go to class and you don't
have to worry about it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
