<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Wednesday, 10/06/99. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT45) CLEVELAND -- Oct. 6, 1999 -- BBA-REDSOX-INDIANS-3, 10-06
-- Boston Red Sox catcher Jason Varitek tumbles behind home plate
while chasing down a foul ball in Game 1 of the National League
Division Playoffs on Wednesday night against the Clevelan Indians.
Varitek did not come up with the ball. (Jim Davis/Boston Globe
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT44) CLEVELAND -- Oct. 6, 1999 -- BBA-REDSOX-INDIANS-2, 10-06
-- Nomar Garciaparra of the Boston Red Sox being greeted at the
plate, right, after hitting a first inning home run in Game 1 of
the National League Division Playoffs on Wednesday night against
the Clevelan Indians. (Jim Davis/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT43) CLEVELAND -- Oct. 6, 1999 -- BBA-REDSOX-INDIANS-1, 10-06
-- Pedro Martinez of the Boston Red Sox pitching in the first
inning of Game 1 of the National League Division Playoffs on
Wednesday night against the Clevelan Indians. (Jim Davis/Boston
Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT42) BETHLEHEM, Pa. -- Oct. 6, 1999 -- LEHIGH-ON-THE-RISE-2,
10-06 --Chris Reed, seated, and Brian Reichert, in a facility at
QED which makes gallium arsenide wafers for the semiconductor
industry. Slowly but steadily, a high-technology phoenix is rising
on the steel shards of Bethlehem and several other towns in the
region that comprise the Lehigh Valley. (Laura Pedrick/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT41) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 6, 1999 -- CONGRESS-CRUISE-SHIPS,
10-06 -- Testifying on cruise ship safety before a Senate committee
Wednesday are, from left, Edmund Welch of the Passenger Vessel
Association, Veronica Sanchez of the Cruising America Coalition,
Allen Walker of the Shipbuilders Council of America, Larry O'Toole
of the National Marine Engineers' Beneficial Association, Al
Wallack of Voyager Holdings Inc. and Cynthia A. Colenda of the
International Council of Cruise Lines. (Justin Lane/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT40) NEW YORK -- Oct. 6, 1999 -- BUSH-CAMPAIGN, 10-06 -- Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas mixes with the crowd outside Giovanni's
Restaurant in the Bronx on Wednesday. Facing a backlash from some
conservative Republicans, Bush softened his stern appraisal of the
Republican Party, which only a day before he had characterized as
too fixated on affluence and not sensitive enough to people's
needs. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT39) MANCHESTER, N.H. -- Oct. 6, 1999 -- DOLE-CAMPAIGN, 10-06
-- Republican presidential hopeful Elizabeth Dole greets supporters
at an annual dinner held by the New Hampshire Federation of
Republican Women on Monday in Manchester. Six weeks ago, Mrs. Dole
surprised campaign watchers, many of whom had declared her
presidential bid a model of lost opportunities, by placing a strong
third in the Iowa straw poll. (Joel Page/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT38) OVER SOUTHERN TURKEY -- Oct. 6, 1999 -- IRAQ-U.S.-2,
10-06 -- A U.S. F-16 is refueld before returning to its patrol
sector over northern Iraq earlier this week. Ever wary of killing
civilians when F-15's and F16's strike inside Iraq, the Air Force
has begun filling 2,000-pound, laser-guided bombs with concrete
instead of explosives and dropping them on what commanders here
call sensitive military targets near populated areas, according to
American military officials. (James Hill/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT37) INCIRLIK, Turkey -- Oct. 6, 1999 -- IRAQ-U.S.-1, 10-06
-- Maintenance personnel secure and F-15 in a hangar at the
Incirlik Air Force base in southern Turkey on Monday. Each bomb
painted on the side of the aircraft represents a successful bombing
mission. Ever wary of killing civilians when F-15's and F16's
strike inside Iraq, the Air Force has begun filling 2,000-pound,
laser-guided bombs with concrete instead of explosives and dropping
them on what commanders here call sensitive military targets near
populated areas, according to American military officials. (James
Hill/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT36) BETHLEHEM, Pa. -- Oct. 6, 1999 -- LEHIGH-ON-THE-RISE,
10-06 -- A site under construction for QED, a Bethlehem company
that makes gallium arsenide wafers for the semiconductor industry,
is just one sign of the area's high-tech resurgence; an old steel
plant can be seen in the distance. So much for the persistent
perception of the Lehigh Valley as a place whose time has come and
gone. (Laura Pedrick/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT35) ATLANTA -- Oct. 6, 1999 -- FBN-NFL-REACTION-HNS, 10-06
-- Bob McNair, left, poses with NFL Commissioner Paul Tagliabue
during a news conference on Wednesday after Houston was awarded an
expansion team. The NFL picked Houston over Los Angeles preferring
a smaller market's record $1.1 billion proposal to a shaky one from
its bigger, more glamorous rival. (Andrew Innerarity/Houston
Chronicle Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT34) BRIELLE, N.J. -- Oct. 6, 1999 -- DATEK-RESIGN, 10-06 --
Jeffrey Citron of Datek Online Holdings, on a dock at his home in
Brielle. Under pressure from his own management team and a group of
outside investors, Citron agreed to step down Wednesday as chairman
and chief executive of Datek and to relinquish any role in the
company he helped fashion into a Wall Street powerhouse. (Steven O.
Boljonis/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 6, 1999 -- CONGRESS-HEALTH-2, 10-06
-- House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., right, turns to
take part in a radio show as, from left, Reps. Robert Menendez,
D-N.J., Patrick Kennedy, D-R.I., and David Bonior, D-Mich. pocket
their notes after a news conference on healthcare legislation,
Wednesday. House Republicans on Wednesday set up a procedure that
reduces the prospects for enactment of landmark legislation to
define patients' rights and regulate HMOs. (Justin Lane/New York
Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 6, 1999 -- CONGRESS-HEALTH, 10-06 --
Reps. David Dreier, R-Calif., left, and Porter Goss R-Fla. talk to
reporters about healthcare legislation on Tuesday. House
Republicans on Wednesday set up a procedure that reduces the
prospects for enactment of landmark legislation to define patients'
rights and regulate HMOs. (Justin Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) NEW YORK -- Oct. 6, 1999 -- BUSH-CAMPAIGN-ASSESS, 10-06
-- Gov. George W. Bush, of Texas gets a pat on the back from New
York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani as Gov. George Pataki of New York,
left, addresses a news conference on public assistance on Wednesday
at the Long Island City Job Center. Bush, the Republican party's
front-running presidential candidate, seems to be defining his own
credentials as a ``compassionate conservative'' by distancing
himself from Republicans on Capitol Hill. (Stephen Crowley/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) UNDATED -- Oct. 6, 1999 -- BOOK-COLUMN, 10-06 -- Judith
Keller, left, and Melissa Bank. Ms. Bank plucked a piece of the
life of her friend, Ms. Keller, a playwright and filmmaker, and
included it in her best-selling collection, ``The Girls' Guide to
Hunting and Fishing.'' Ms. Keller says she and Ms. Bank had agreed
in writing that when the story would be introduced this way: ``As
told to me by Judith Keller.'' It wasn't. (Chester Higgins Jr.,
left; Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) NEW YORK -- Oct. 6, 1999 -- MOBYDICK-OPERA-REVIEW, 10-06
-- Laurie Anderson sings, talks and performs on assorted musical
instruments in ``Songs and Stories From Moby-Dick.'' In an hour and
a half of music and dance - elegantly lighted and illustrated,
fastidiously organized and presided over in a spirit of somber
whimsy - Ms. Anderson and a small troupe of players and musicians
give us what amounts to a book of essays. (Sara Krulwich/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) ATLANTA -- Oct. 6, 1999 -- BBO-BRAVES-ASTROS-COX, 10-06
-- Atlanta Braves' outfielder Gerald Williams steals second base
early in Game 2 of the National League Division Playoffs between
the Braves and the Houston Astros at Turner Field on Wednesday.
Williams later scored on a Brian Jordan single. (Frank Neimeir/Cox
News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) CHICAGO -- Oct. 6, 1999 -- VIEW-OPERA-2, 10-06 -- Mark
McCrory, Catherine Malfitano and Kim Josephson in rehearsal in
Chicago for ``A View From the Bridge.'' The opera opens Saturday
night at the Civic Opera House here to a sellout crowd of more than
3,600. (Todd Buchanan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) CHICAGO -- Oct. 6, 1999 -- VIEW-OPERA-1, 10-06 --
Rehearsing for the opera ``A View From the Bridge,'' which opens
Saturday: from left, Mark McCrory, Juliana Rambaldi, Kim Josephson,
Catherine Malfitano and Gregory Turay. The singers, who have had
their parts since spring, began rehearsals in August. (Todd
Buchanan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) UNDATED -- Oct. 6, 1999 -- GINSBURG-AUCTION-B&AMP;W, 10-06
-- On the block: ``Allen Ginsberg Dancing to the Grateful Dead.''
(1967) Two years after his death, Ginsberg's estate is carrying out
his wishes and auctioning off his belongings, Thursday at Sotheby's
in Manhattan. (Sotheby's/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) CLEVELAND -- Oct. 6, 1999 -- BBA-REDSOX-INDIANS-BOS,
10-06 -- On Tuesday Dan Duquette, the Red Sox's general manager,
watches intently as his team gets ready for Wednesday's meeting
against the Cleveland Indians. It is the third time the two teams
have met in the post-season in last five years. (Jim Davis/Boston
Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) NEW YORK -- Oct. 6, 1999 -- SCHOLAR-FLOATER, 10-06 --
Herb Weber, a retired professor of exercise physiology at East
Strudsburg University, in East Stroudsburg, Pa., reads ``Hannibal''
by Thomas Harris while waiting for his wife who was visiting the
Museum of Natural History on Wednesday. (Librado Romero/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) AUGUSTA, Ky. -- Oct. 6, 1999 -- ROSEMARY-CLOONEY, 10-06
-- Rosemary Clooney at home in Augusta; she also owns a house in
Beverly Hills. At 71, Ms. Clooney is a survivor of a swinging era
whose greats are almost all gone. She still sings the old songs the
way they were meant to be sung, and she tells priceless stories of
watching the fights on television with Crosby and his date for the
night, the young Grace Kelly, in sweater set and pearls. (Mark
Lyons/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- Oct. 6, 1999 --
AUTHOR-SURVIVORS-BOS, 10-6 -- Rita Arditti, author of ``Searching
for Life: The Grandmothers of the Plaza De Mayo and the Disappeared
Children of Argentina,'' stands next to a poster that was produced
by Grandmothers of Plaza de Mayo. Arditti, an Argentine scientist
who has lived in Cambridge, Mass. for 35 years, interviewed dozens
of the grandmothers, who have been searching for their kidnapped
grandchildren, whose mothers were slain by the military, for more
than 20 years for the book. (Mark Wilson/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) BOSTON -- Oct. 6, 1999 -- FOOD-WATERS-BOS, 10-6 --
Cookbook author Alice Waters, one of the two most famous women in
food. The other is, of course, Julia Child. Her own food epiphany
came early, when she went to France as a college student. ``I sort
of came to it so simply,'' says Waters, who grew up in New Jersey
and admits she had had no particular interest in food or cooking
before that year. ``It's just a way of life I fell in love with.''
(Bill Greene/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) WORCESTER, Mass. -- Oct. 6, 1999 -- SMILEY-FACE-BOS,
10-6 -- Harvey Ball, 79, inventor of the Smiley Face at his home in
Worcester. Some 42 years ago, Ball then a commercial artist,
enclosed two dots and a curved line in a yellow circle and created
an image that became an icon so quickly he never secured the
trademark to his design. Ball has since fended off a long series of
challenges to his authorship. (John Bohn/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) HAVANA -- Oct. 6, 1999 -- CUBA-ARCHITECTURE-3, 10-06 --
Cuban architects Teresa Martin, 32, and Oscar Garcia, 36, with a
projection of one of their latest projects, the Hotel Packard. The
striking new hotel, fusing a masonry base with a sleek steel roof
and a huge exterior ceramic mural, is to be built near a modish new
restaurant which opened this year. The last three decades have seen
Cuba's amazing architectural heritage yield to the utilitarian and
its architects recede into the shadows. But in recent months, a
generation of Cuban architects pressing for change say they are
scenting the whiff of a renaissance. (Sven Creutzmann/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) HAVANA -- Oct. 6, 1999 -- CUBA-ARCHITECTURE-2, 10-06 --
The Hotel Habana Libre, formerly the Havana Hilton, built in 1958,
towers over buildings from another era in Cuban architecture. The
last three decades have seen Cuba's amazing architectural heritage
yield to the utilitarian and its architects recede into the
shadows. But in recent months, a generation of Cuban architects
pressing for change say they are scenting the whiff of a
renaissance. (Sven Creutzmann/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) HAVANA -- Oct. 6, 1999 -- CUBA-ARCHITECTURE-1, 10-06 --
Cuban architect Emilio Castro in front of his latest project, the
Hotel Palacio Cueto, in Old Havana. Built in 1906, it is now being
restored as a hotel after many years as an apartment building. The
last three decades has seen Cuba's amazing architectural heritage
yield to the utilitarian and architects recede into the shadows.
But in recent months, a generation of Cuban architects pressing for
change say they are scenting the whiff of a renaissance. (Sven
Creutzmann/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) PITTSBURGH -- Oct. 6, 1999 -- CIR-ROTARY-PHONE, 10-06 --
Jonathan Finder, a Pittsburgh doctor who collects and sells rotary
telephones, shows off some of the beauties from his collection. ``I
sell a ton of pink Princess phones,'' he says. ``There are a lot of
professional women who grew up in the '70s who never got them as
little girls, and by God, they're going to get one now.'' (Gary
Tramontina/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- Oct. 6, 1999 -- CIR-INTERNET2-2, 10-06 --
Jaron Lanier runs a virtual reality project that takes advantage of
Internet2's speed. ``The goal is to stress the network,'' says
Lanier, who hopes that the project will be ready for a full working
demonstration by April. ``We're really trying to push Internet2 to
its limit.'' (Jeffery A. Salter/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) ANN ARBOR, Mich. -- Oct. 6, 1999 -- CIR-INTERNET2, 10-06
-- Douglas Van Houweling is president of the group that oversees
Internet2. Proponents of the Internet2 project, whose users are
almost exclusively at universities, say it is a unique sandbox in
which researchers can conduct experiments in areas like advanced
videoconference techniques, virtual reality and telemedicine.
(Peter Yates/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- Oct. 6, 1999 -- ROCKEFELLER-GARDEN, 10-06 --
David Kamp watches the passing of fall in his urban marsh in
Rockefeller Center. ``When you are calm, you experience more,''
says Kamp, who designed the garden as a place of rest and
meditation in the middle of a clamorous city. (Fred R. Conrad/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) UNDATED -- Oct. 6, 1999 -- WALL-BOOK-REVIEW-B&AMP;W, 10-06
-- The recent crisis in the Taiwan Strait makes ``A Great Wall: Six
Presidents and China, An Investigative History'' - Patrick E.
Tyler's account of three decades of United States policy-making
toward China - especially welcome, for Taiwan has always been at
the center of the United States-China relationship. Tyler tells a
complex story with impressive clarity. (Naum Kazhdan/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) UNDATED -- Oct. 6, 1999 -- HOME-IMPROVEMENT-B&AMP;W, 10-06
-- The basics of the water system in a home are easy to understand.
After water enters the house, the supply line splits into a cold
and a hot line. The hot line starts with cold water, but it is
routed to a heater where the water is heated to a temperature of
about 140 degrees Fahrenheit. Both lines are routed to fixtures in
the bathroom, kitchen, laundry room, and so on, where they may
tapped for water. (Edward R. Lipinski/New York Times Illustration)
LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) AUSTIN, Texas -- Oct. 6, 1999 -- YOGURT-SHOP-MURDERS-2,
10-06 -- On Dec. 7, 1991, officers from the Austin Police Dept.
investigate the scene at the I Can't Believe It's Yogurt! shop
where four young women were found murdered and the business set on
fire the night before. On Wednesday police arrested a man in West
Virginia and another near Dallas suspected to committing the crime.
(Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) UNDATED -- Oct. 6, 1999 -- YOGURT-SHOP-MURDERS-1, 10-06
-- On Wednesday police arrested a man in West Virginia and another
near Dallas suspected in the murder of four young women on Dec. 6,
1991 at the I Can't Believe It's Yogurt! shop where two of the
victims worked. They were, from left, Eliza Hope Thomas, 17,
Jennifer Harbison, 17, Sarah Harbison, 15 and Amy Ayers, 13,
(Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 6, 1999 -- SCOTUS-FLOATER, 10-06 -- A
lone anti-abortion rights advocate protests outside the Supreme
Court building on Wednesday. The court is in its first week of the
1999-2000 term. (Shana Raab/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEWARK, N.J. -- Oct. 6, 1999 -- CIR-CHILD-WEBSITES, 10-06
-- The Internet is a vast information repository where - as these
children at a community technology center in Newark are finding out
- websites geared for them are a growing presence. Many employ
human or software filters to block pornographic, profane and
violent sites. (Thomas Dallal/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- Oct. 6, 1999 -- CIR-EBAY-EXHIBITION, 10-06 --
Maurice Berger, a guest curator at the Whitney Museum, is an
experienced online forager. Under his auspices, the museum got
involved in a fierce online bidding war for a 25-year-old copy of
Playgirl magazine - the first time, Berger says, that a major art
institution has curated part of an exhibition by buying artifacts
via the Internet. ``I've addicted half the museum to Ebay,'' he
says. (Angel Franco/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) AUGUSTA, Ga. -- Oct. 6, 1999 -- NORWOOD-PROFILE, 10-06 --
Rep. Charlie Norwood, R-Ga., during a hearing on health care at a
hospital in his home district. Norwood, a dentist, is pushing his
own party leaders for new managed care regulations. (Alan S.
Weiner/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) UNDATED -- Oct. 6, 1999 -- KOCH-COX-B&AMP;W, 10-06 --
Testimony is under way in the latest legal battle between William
Koch, left, of Palm Beach, and the company led by two of his
brothers - one of them his twin, David, also of Palm Beach, seen
here with his wife Julia. Although the government is the named
plaintiff in a case involving how the company, Koch Industries,
measured oil it obtained under leases from the federal government
and American Indian tribes, the Justice Department is not
participating in the case. It's being bankrolled by William Koch,
who stands to gain as much as one-third of a judgment for the
government under a whistle-blower statute. (Palm Beach Daily
News/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) LONGVIEW, Texas -- Oct. 6, 1999 -- SERVICE-DOG-COX-2,
10-06 -- Matthew Coates pets his service dog Carol at home. Of the
89 commands Matthew can give Carol, to assist him in his everyday
life, one of his favorite is ``Carol, lap.'' ``I like that command.
She gets in my lap, and I can hug her or whatever,'' Matthew said.
Carol, a white golden retriever, was a special delivery to Matthew
from the Make A Wish Foundation. She is a service dog from the
Assistance Dog Institute in Rohnert Park, Calif. (Bahram Mark
Sobhani/Longview News Journal)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) LONGVIEW, Texas -- Oct. 6, 1999 -- SERVICE-DOG-COX-1,
10-06 -- Matthew Coates is taken to his next class by Elisha
Pierce, his instructional assistant, as his service dog, Carol,
walks along side. Carol, a white golden retriever, was a special
delivery to Matthew from the Make A Wish Foundation. She is a
service dog from the Assistance Dog Institute in Rohnert Park,
Calif. The pouch on her back carries some of Matthew's school
supplies. (Bahram Mark Sobhani/Longview News Journal)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
