<SLUG> BC-GEOCAST-INTERNET-TECHNOLOGY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 GEOCAST REVEALS ITS SECRET TECHNOLOGY  &HT;     By BENNY EVANGELISTA 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Silicon Valley startup Geocast Network Systems secretly has been
developing a technology that uses digital TV broadcasting to
deliver video programs and interactive Web content to personal
computers.
<P>
   Now, Geocast is taking the cloak off its product.
</P>
<P>
   Geocast will announce Thursday that Hearst-Argyle Television
Inc., which operates 28 broadcast television stations reaching
nearly 18 percent of U.S. households, will invest up to $10 million
in the startup.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst-Argyle also will allocate portions of its stations'
digital broadcast frequencies for use by Geocast Network.
</P>
<P>
   Geocast CEO Joe Horowitz said the deal, which gives
Hearst-Argyle an undisclosed stake in the company, is a key step
toward his vision of creating a new network that would give
consumers a new high-speed way to download and watch digital TV
programs on their PCs or download new software or CD albums in
seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It allows us to use the mass-medium distribution system yet
personalize it for the individual consumer,'' Hearst-Argyle
Chairman and co-CEO Bob Marbut said in a telephone interview. ``To
me, that's a powerful idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Geocast Network created a buzz in Silicon Valley after it
received funding in December 1998 from three major venture capital
firms _ Kleiner Perkins Caulfield &AMP; Byers, The Mayfield Fund and
Institutional Venture Partners. It's the first time in more than a
decade that all three have invested in the same startup, though
Horowitz has declined to say how much the partners have invested.
</P>
<P>
   Geocast, founded a year earlier, has assembled a team of top
venture capital, technology and media executives, including 10
engineers who helped develop Netscape Communication Corp.'s Web
browser.
</P>
<P>
   However, the buzz was about a secret product that few on the
outside had seen. But because of the deal with publicly traded
Hearst-Argyle, Horowitz said he believed it also was time to reveal
Geocast technology, which the company hopes to market by the end of
next year.
</P>
<P>
   In a preview earlier this week, Horowitz said the network will
center around a receiver slightly smaller than a VCR that would
connect to a desktop computer. The receiver would cost less than
$300 but would not require subscription fees.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Geocast would use an unused portion of digital TV frequencies
to beam a ``multicast'' of Web-style programming and data to
Geocast receivers. Consumers could program a receiver to download
only what they wanted.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; A handful of TV stations began all-digital, high-definition
broadcasts last November 1. Congress and the FCC have set a goal to
convert all the nation's 1,600 TV stations to digital by 2006.
</P>
<P>
   Horowitz said the technology is capable of playing back video at
30 frames per second, about the same quality as standard TV video
and far above the 12-frames-per-second rate now available with the
fastest Internet connection.
</P>
<P>
   Horowitz, a former venture capitalist, said the network would
make TV newscasts or other programming available for playback at
anytime. The technology also would allow consumers to download
digital music videos, CDs or an electronic shopping catalog.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can give you a whole software package in a matter of
seconds,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Geocast would not replace Internet connections, which still
would be needed for e-mail and direct contact between the computer
user and Web sites. Online purchases, for example, still would need
an Internet connection.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the complaints about the Internet is that it's just too
much work to find what you're looking for,'' Horowitz said. ``Now
with the broadcast industry becoming a digital world, there are
opportunities to talk to the PC world.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the idea could succeed though Geocast has many
hurdles to overcome before proving that consumers will feel a
compelling need to buy another electronic box for their computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Merging broadcasting with the Net has, in theory, sounded like
the best of both worlds, but in practice, it has proven
difficult,'' said analyst Ross Rubin of Internet research firm
Jupiter Communications.
</P>
<P>
   Although previous attempts to use analog broadcast frequencies
to beam personalized information like traffic and weather reports
have not succeeded, the digital spectrum is wider and more
flexible, said Rubin, Jupiter's vice president of research.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance with Hearst-Argyle is a key step for Geocast, but
``ultimately, they need more deals like that,'' Rubin said. ``It's
important for them to form cable-network-type deals and also strong
partnerships with leading online properties.''
</P>
<P>
   Hearst-Argyle has two stations in Sacramento, Calif., and one in
Monterey, Calif., but none in the San Francisco Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   Geocast's financial backing is ``impressive,'' Rubin said. But,
he added, ``even the best venture capitalists make some bad bets.''
</P>
<P>
   A recent study showed that computer users were spending more
time online and less time watching television.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's our target audience,'' Horowitz said. Geocast could
help broadcasters ``recapture some of that market.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
