<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 21:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8987 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-AT&AMP;T-EXEC-QUITS-(TRIM     10-06 1127
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT&AMP;T-EXEC-QUITS-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHIEF OF AT&AMP;T'S CABLE TV OPERATION QUITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the most significant executive departure from AT&AMP;T
since C. Michael Armstrong took over as the company's chairman in
1997, AT&AMP;T announced Wednesday that Leo J. Hindery Jr., chief
executive of AT&AMP;T's cable television operation, had decided to
leave the company.
</P>
<P>
   Hindery, 51, is a longtime media and cable television executive
and his departure throws the first major wrinkle into AT&AMP;T's plan
to use cable television systems across the nation to offer
consumers communications baskets of interactive television,
high-speed Internet access and local and long-distance telephone
service. The unit that was led by Hindery is spending billions of
dollars to upgrade cable lines, retrain employees and develop the
complex computer systems needed to offer such a variety of
services.
</P>
<P>
   As the former president of Tele-Communications Inc., the big
cable provider that AT&AMP;T agreed to acquire last year, Hindery
enhanced AT&AMP;T's credibility in the sometimes-clannish cable
industry, which is dominated by a mere handful of companies, many
family-controlled.
</P>
<P>
   While Hindery and AT&AMP;T publicly described the move as amicable,
many analysts, investors and executives close to the company said
that Hindery, with his hard-driving, anti-bureaucratic manner, had
developed an irrevocable personality conflict with Armstrong, who
is more measured in his management style. While it is not totally
clear whether Hindery was encouraged to step down, or, in the words
of one investor, ``simply couldn't take it anymore,'' analysts and
executives said his departure was clearly related to the mutual
frustration between Hindery and Armstrong, though the two agreed on
most substantive matters of strategy.
</P>
<P>
   The role of maintaining AT&AMP;T's stature within the cable
fraternity will now fall largely on Amos B. Hostetter, who helped
put together AT&AMP;T's deal to acquire Mediaone Group Inc., another
leading cable carrier, earlier this year. Hostetter is chairman of
AT&AMP;T's cable operation and a member of AT&AMP;T's board.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T said Wednesday that he would spend more time at the cable
unit's headquarters in Denver to help develop strategy and maintain
relations with other cable operators.
</P>
<P>
   John Malone, the former chairman of TCI and another titan in the
cable business, is also on AT&AMP;T's board.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T chief financial officer Daniel E. Somers was tapped to
assume Hindery's day-to-day role on an interim basis. AT&AMP;T has
commissioned an outside search for Hindery's permanent replacement,
though it is remotely possible that Somers, who before joining AT&AMP;T
in 1997 was chairman of Bell Cablemedia PLC, a cable operator in
Britain, could keep the job.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T controller Nicholas Cyprus will assume Somers' financial
responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Hindery is known as an innovative, fast-moving deal maker. While
at TCI, he helped reshape the cable industry by swapping cable
systems to create big ``clusters'' that could be operated with
lower costs and by striking joint ventures with other companies.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts and executives said that perhaps Hindery was not
the best fit as AT&AMP;T, a famously regimented organization, moved
beyond acquiring cable operations and began the dull but vital work
of integrating the cable unit into the larger AT&AMP;T structure.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the world of Leo; he accomplished what almost nobody
else has ever done, which is reconfigure the cable industry,'' said
Jessica Reif Cohen, the lead cable analyst for Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co.
``Personality-wise, I don't think that anyone would be surprised
that he left AT&AMP;T. I think the only surprise is the timing.''
</P>
<P>
   Comcast Corp. president Brian Roberts said, ``Leo emerged as one
of the leaders, if not the leader, the last several years and has
accomplished so much to position this industry for the next
millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Wednesday, Hindery did not seem to think that
news of his departure would come as a huge surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike and I came to the conclusion that I wasn't going to stay
forever and against that backdrop this seemed to be the most
thoughtful way to move forward,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   According to executives close to AT&AMP;T, it became clear that
Hindery was not going to spend the rest of his career with the
company, not because he and Armstrong disagreed on the fundamental
direction of AT&AMP;T's cable business, but because they disagreed on
the manner and pace they should employ.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, both Hindery and Armstrong appear to agree that
high-speed Internet access to AT&AMP;T's cable systems should be opened
beyond the current monopoly enjoyed by the Excite(AT)Home Corp. But
while Hindery tried to negotiate a side deal with Yahoo, the Web
portal, and openly criticized the merger of the Excite Web portal
and the At Home cable modem venture, Armstrong preferred a less
confrontational approach.
</P>
<P>
   While there did not appear to be one precipitating incident that
led to Hindery's departure, media executives and people close to
AT&AMP;T pointed to two recent episodes that highlighted, and perhaps
increased, the conflict between Hindery and Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   Just last Tuesday, news reports emerged that AT&AMP;T's cable unit
had agreed to buy up to 3 million set-top boxes from General
Instrument Corp. and Motorola Inc. in a deal worth as much as $1
billion. The problem, the executives said, was that Armstrong
learned about the deal from the news accounts. No one at AT&AMP;T is
allowed to spend more than $100 million without explicit approval
from the board, the executives said, and Hindery had appeared to
ignore AT&AMP;T's internal authorization process before making a deal
with the two equipment makers. The deal has not been publicly
acknowledged by AT&AMP;T and the executives said they were unsure if
AT&AMP;T was legally obligated to go through with it.
</P>
<P>
   Then, on Wednesday, Hindery appeared to issue a flat denial to a
reporter that AT&AMP;T was in discussions about breaking up
Excite(AT)Home or changing AT&AMP;T's relationship with the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely not,'' Hindery told Reuters. ``There have been no
discussions under way whatsoever.''
</P>
<P>
   But less than 24 hours later, AT&AMP;T issued an official statement
essentially repudiating Hindery, saying that discussions were
proceeding. According to people close to AT&AMP;T, the company's legal
and communications departments were livid that Hindery might have
misled investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leo was used to saying, `I speak for a company and I make the
decisions,' '' one senior media executive said Wednesday. ``He
could never bring himself to say, `I have to check with Mike, I
have to go see.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
