<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8991 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-CAMPAIGN-630&AMP;ADD     10-06 1128
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-CAMPAIGN-630&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN A NEW TOWN, GORE HERALDS A NEW DAY
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ Arriving in Tennessee to cut the ribbon on
his headquarters, Vice President Al Gore Wednesday continued his
efforts to put a new face on his presidential campaign, naming a
black woman to his inner circle and promising supporters a
``rip-tootin''' candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   The transplanting of his headquarters from Washington's K Street
power corridor to a squat one-story Nashville office building hard
by the railroad tracks _ and a world away from Washington and the
Clinton White House _ was as good a sign as any that change was in
the air.
</P>
<P>
   The chief change is that Gore is now visibly in charge,
directing a campaign that he believes has been crowded for too long
by people with only a halfhearted commitment to his longtime
ambition to be president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lights!'' the candidate called, squinting into a brilliant
sun, as local television cameras trained on him Wednesday morning
in the parking lot outside his still-empty headquarters, a former
rehabilitation center adjacent to a mound of rubble from nearby
highway construction.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, ``there was perhaps too much caution around him,''
said an aide back in Washington, where members of the campaign
staff were packing boxes to clear out of the old headquarters by
the middle of the month. ``Things were too much by the book. Now
it's 100 percent Al Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   The shift to Nashville is intended partly to separate those who
can make a full-time commitment by moving here from those whose
family and professional obligations, including work for other
candidates, make them less available to Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you have absolutely committed yourself, then providence
moves too,'' the vice president told a largely black crowd of about
150 people at the Jubilee Restaurant here after the ribbon-cutting
at the new headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   In introducing the ``new'' campaign, Gore announced that Donna
Brazile, the deputy campaign manager and national political
director, would be the campaign manager, replacing the departing
Craig Smith, whose duties were largely superseded when Tony Coelho
became campaign chairman in May.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brazile, who becomes the first black woman to manage a
presidential campaign, is one of three top advisers moving from
Washington to Nashville. The others are Coelho and Carter Eskew,
the media strategist. Bob Squier, another media strategist, has
left the campaign because of illness, and Gore has replaced two of
his pollsters, Mark Penn and Celinda Lake, with Harrison Hickman,
who will remain in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   While Gore has been effusive about shuffling his campaign _ a
redirection that he admits was forced on him by his sag in the
polls _ the staff is in an extreme state of flux. A number of his
aides are still deciding whether to move to Nashville, and more
personnel changes are in the works.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Gore is fiddling with his stump speech. He is
trying to tell voters more about himself, and to make a personal
connection to inspire local Democrats across the country to work on
his behalf. This also includes casting his opponent for the
nomination, Bill Bradley, as a turncoat for leaving the Senate
after the Republicans had assumed control of it and briefly
considering a run for the presidency as an independent.
</P>
<P>
   Another matter of preoccupation for Gore's top advisers now is
his effort to win the all-important endorsement of the AFL-CIO,
which is meeting in Los Angeles next week. Before Ms. Brazile and
Coelho move in here, they are headed to Los Angeles, where Coelho
is to meet with James P. Hoffa, president of the teamsters' union,
to try to nail down the federation's backing. Shortly after that,
on Oct. 27, Gore makes a joint appearance with Bradley in New
Hampshire, the first of the primary-election states.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The new shift ``is not just about real estate,'' said a Gore
aide, Laura Quinn, who will stay in Washington in the vice
president's office, which is distinct from the campaign office and
is remaining largely intact. ``It's a tactical shift, a strategy
shift, a message shift.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Quinn said that while many on the staff had been surprised
by the decision to move to Nashville, she felt more encouraged
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came in today,'' she said, ``and there was a great report
from Peter Ragone in New York, from the political shop on the AFL,
from Michael Whooley in New Hampshire.''
</P>
<P>
   Ragone is the campaign's spokesman in New York. Whooley is a
political strategist who moved his family from Boston to Washington
only a month ago to work full time for Gore. Since he will oversee
the campaign in New Hampshire and Iowa, he will be traveling
through early February and so can keep his family in Washington
rather than having to move to Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   As of a week ago, when Gore announced his campaign shake-up, he
had about 185 people on the payroll in Washington. Coelho said
about 40 percent of the staff there would move to Nashville. The
move should save some money, aides said, given that prices here are
lower than in the capital, but its primary purpose is to get out of
the Washington mind-set.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is more than symbolism,'' Coelho said. ``There's a
bonding that comes with it. There won't be the barriers that are
put up in Washington all the time. It's very difficult to run from
the Beltway, because people there have too many other separate
interests and you don't have the connection to the candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   The campaign also has several dozen paid workers in just four
states: 32 in Iowa, whose caucuses in four months kick off the race
in earnest; 30 in New Hampshire; 10 in New York, and four in
California.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brazile will manage these field workers from Nashville. She
has a reputation as a strong organizer, particularly of blacks and
union workers. She also comes with a history of having been removed
from Michael Dukakis' 1988 presidential campaign for spreading
unsubstantiated rumors about Dukakis' opponent, Vice President
George Bush. Gore's appointment of her indicates he has little
concern about this. As one aide back in Washington put it:
``Spreading rumors? Holy smokes! In this town?''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brazile is former chief of staff to Eleanor Holmes Norton,
the District of Columbia's delegate to Congress, and has overseen
efforts to increase black turnout in congressional campaigns across
the country. ``She earned it,'' Gore said of her appointment.
</P>
<P>
   In another spiritual flight about commitment, Gore pointed to
scripture in explaining why he had chosen Ms. Brazile: ``Whatsoever
thy hand findeth to do, do it with all thy might.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
