<SLUG> BC-SOC-INTLNOTES07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Euro 2000 berths up for grabs
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ This weekend's final Euro 2000 qualifying games have
plenty of significant consequences riding on them. As a result,
UEFA is ordering simultaneous starting times. Five automatic berths
and six playoff spots are still to be determined in what has become
a surprising turn of events.
</P>
<P>
   In Group 5, England needs Sweden to beat Poland in Stockholm on
Saturday to get into next month's eight-team playoff round. France,
the World Cup champion, must beat Iceland in Paris, then hope
Ukraine can topple Russia in Moscow. Ukraine leads Russia and
France by a point in Group 4, but the latter trails by four in goal
differential. In Zagreb, Croatia plays hated rival Yugoslavia,
which leads it in Group 8 by two points. Sandwiched in between is
Ireland, which has a tricky finale at Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   Italy needs only to tie at Belarus to win Group 1 over Denmark.
Turkey trails Germany by two points in Group 3 and needs to win in
Munich to avoid a playoff. Israel leads Cyprus by a point for the
playoff berth from Group 6, but both teams hit the road, playing at
group winner Spain and Austria, respectively. Romania is all but
certain to win Group 7 by finishing up at hapless Liechtenstein,
while Portugal could wrap up an automatic bid as the best
second-place team with a win over Hungary in Lisbon.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Scotland got a first-half penalty-kick goal by John
Collins and held on for a 1-0 win over Bosnia-Herzogovina in Group
9 to join Slovenia in the playoffs. Norway, Spain and the Czech
Republic have qualified for the 16-team finals next summer, along
with co-hosts Belgium and the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   ENGLAND: CHELSEA ROUTS UNITED
</P>
<P>
   Two consecutive draws at home to lowly clubs should have been an
ominous sign for Manchester United. On Sunday, Chelsea quenched a
scoring drought by handing the Premier League champions their worst
loss in three years, a 5-0 drubbing that snapped United's unbeaten
streak in all competitions at 46 matches. Gustavo Poyet had two
goals and high-priced signee Chris Sutton got his first since
transferring from Blackburn. The match was marred by a red card
issued to United's Nicky Butt, who kicked a prostrate Dennis Wise
after a midair collision. Butt claims he was pinched on the leg by
Wise.... Arsenal's Patrick Vieira is facing a long suspension and
hefty fine after spitting on Neil Ruddock of West Ham and abusing a
referee in a 2-1 loss for the Gunners.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: DORTMUND STILL LEADS
</P>
<P>
   Borussia Dortmund maintained a two-point lead in the Bundesliga
with a 3-0 win over Hansa Rostock. Striker Victor Ikpeba, recently
fined $10,000 for complaining about a lack of playing time, was
inserted into the lineup and scored twice.... Youri Djorkaeff had
goals in the 66th and 82nd minutes in Kaiserslautern's 4-2 win over
Unterhaching as the 1997-98 champions began inching out of the
bottom half of the table.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY: LAZIO, MILAN IN THRILLER
</P>
<P>
   If Sunday's 4-4 draw between Lazio and AC Milan is any
indication of what might be in store in Serie A, then it should be
even more spectacular than last season. AC Milan, which edged Lazio
by a point for the title in May, overcame a 3-1 deficit to lead
4-3, thanks to a hat trick from Andriy Shevchenko. But the Roman
club earned a point when Marcelo Salas scored in the 74th
minute.... AS Roma moved into second place behind Inter Milan by
virtue of a 3-1 win at Fiorentina as Cafu had two goals. But the
price was steep. Striker Marco Delvecchio will be out at least four
weeks with a pulled leg muscle, while midfielder Francesco Totti
could miss as much as three weeks with a groin strain.
</P>
<P>
   SPAIN: VALENCIA FINALLY WINS
</P>
<P>
   Preseason favorite Valencia built a 3-0 lead in the first half
Sunday, then hung on, despite holding a man advantage, before
beating Real Madrid 3-2 for its first Primera Division win of the
season. Madrid's Roberto Carlos was sent off for a hand ball in the
penalty box in the first half, and manager John Toshack was tossed
for arguing.... At Barcelona, it doesn't seem to matter who scores
the goals as long as Rivaldo and Patrick Kluivert are involved.
They had a goal apiece, assisting each other in either half, as the
champions easily dominated Valladolid 2-0 to keep their edge on
Rayo Vallecano at the top of the table.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: NECAXA TAKES CUP
</P>
<P>
   Sergio Vazquez scored the winning goal off a rebound in the 66th
minute as shorthanded Necaxa defeated Alajuela of Costa Rica 2-1
Sunday in the finals of the CONCACAF Champions Cup in Las Vegas.
Necaxa, fourth in the current Torneo Invierno, qualifies for the
World Club Championship in Brazil in January.... Guadalajara took a
slim lead in Group 4 of the Torneo Invierno with a 2-1 victory over
Leon on Sunday as Jesus Arellano slammed in a rebound off the post
in the final minute of play.
</P>
<P>
   S. AMERICA: PALERMO TEES OFF
</P>
<P>
   With his transfer to Lazio delayed for three months, Boca
Juniors striker Martin Palermo took out his frustrations on
Gimnasia-Jujuy. He scored his ninth and 10th goals in a 3-1 win.
Palermo, who was to move to Italy this week for a reported $25
million, will have to wait until December, after the Apertura
season is over.... Former Brazilian World Cup coach Mario Zagallo
was fired as coach of lowly Portuguesa after a 1-0 loss Sunday to
league-leading Corinthians.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
