<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-GREER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A REGULAR-SEASON WONDER, RANGERS' GREER FIZZLES IN PLAYOFFS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
NEW YORK _ The Rangers had a day off in New York yesterday to
ponder their fate in the American League Division Series.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most puzzling for them is how their offense can be so powerful
in the regular season, yet so impotent against the New York
Yankees. An 8-0 loss in Game 1 left them with one run in four
playoff games against the Yankees going back to last year's
Division Series.
</P>
<P>
   Left fielder Rusty Greer may be foremost among the Rangers'
offensive contradictions. He has consistently been one of their
best clutch hitters, with 14 game-winning hits in the Rangers' last
at-bat since the start of 1995.
</P>
<P>
   But he has never been a factor in postseason play. He was
0-for-2 with two walks in the opener, dropping him to 3-for-29
overall in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The experience has been good, but the results have been
lacking, both individual- and team-wise,'' Greer admitted. ``But
you go about your business just like you have all season, relax,
swing the bat and try to hit the ball hard. ... A lot of it is just
being hot at the right time, having a good series and having some
luck.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers were hoping to change their luck against the
Yankees. They wanted to be more patient, work counts and get good
pitches to hit. That's part of what makes Greer a good hitter. He
hit .300 this year with 96 walks and 67 strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly with what Rusty's done before you expect him to do
well,'' Rangers manager Johnny Oates said. ``But we need a bunch of
guys to break out, not just Rusty.''
</P>
<P>
   Greer's two walks helped the Rangers get two rallies going early
in Game 1. But Yankees starter Orlando Hernandez worked out of
both, striking out Todd Zeile with the bases loaded in the first
inning, and, with runners at first and second in the third, getting
Juan Gonzalez and Rafael Palmeiro on fly balls.
</P>
<P>
   From that standpoint, Greer did his job by giving the Rangers'
best power hitters a chance to do serious damage. But the Rangers
are a team in desperate need of a clutch hit, an area in which
Greer has so often come through in the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm better in 162 games because I try to be
consistent,'' Greer said. ``You have slumps. You're going to have
five games where you're not going to get hits, but you're also
going to have five games where you can redeem yourself. In the
playoffs, it comes down to five games, and, if you're not swinging
the bat well, if they're not falling, you don't have another 100
games to redeem yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Rangers don't have an extended period of time. They must
win tonight or go back to Arlington on the brink of elimination.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Rusty will have a good series,'' Rangers general
manager Doug Melvin said. ``I think one of the reasons he's such a
great hitter is that everybody concentrates on other guys and he
kind of sneaks in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Now would be a good time.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
