<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Detroit not just winging it this year
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Detroit had gone 41 seasons without a Stanley Cup, so
the Red Wings shouldn't have suffered much in parting with it after
winning titles two years in a row.
</P>
<P>
   But ``defending champions'' sounds a lot better than ``defending
quarterfinalists.'' In the words of Steve Yzerman, ``Now we're one
of the other guys. It's kind of humbling.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether humility can be equated with danger is yet to be
determined. The Red Wings, who retain far more talent than
vulnerabilities, play the Thrashers tonight at Philips Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit is 1-1 but has outplayed the two Stanley Cup finalists.
The Red Wings defeated Buffalo 2-0, then lost to Dallas 3-2. Scotty
Bowman's team outshot both foes, 44-22 and 34-14, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Motivation isn't a problem. The same couldn't be said last
season, when a possible two-Cup hangover caused the Red Wings to
start 6-6 and rise and fall often during the season _ no more so
than in the playoffs, when they won four in a row against San Jose
and two against Colorado before losing four to the Avalanche to get
bounced in the second round.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our players understand the importance of the regular season
now,'' Detroit general manager Ken Holland said. ``Subconsciously,
they thought they were judged on how they did in the playoffs and
not the regular season. That's true to a certain extent. But you
need the 82 games during the year to prepare for the playoffs. The
same inconsistencies we showed in the regular season were evident
later.''
</P>
<P>
   Most hockey teams discount the preseason. Not the Wings. They
went 2-7 in exhibitions last year; this year, they were 7-1-1-0,
with only 14 goals allowed, five in one game. Defense was the
biggest problem last season. It is the primary focus of Bowman,
Holland and the players this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clear the players are more committed to doing things as a
team,'' Holland said. ``As you go along, you see if they remain
totally focused. It doesn't guarantee you'll win the Cup but it
certainly gives you a better chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Holland is feeling the heat as much as anyone else. Just before
the trading deadline last year, he acquired four veterans _
defensemen Chris Chelios and Ulf Samuelsson, winger Wendel Clark
and goalie Bill Ranford _ that he thought would help them win a
third title. But the tenures were short-lived for Samuelsson, an
unrestricted free agent; Clark, who signed with Chicago; and
Ranford, now in Edmonton. Only Chelios remains, and he's 37 and
central to the age concerns on Detroit's roster. If defenseman
Nicklas Lidstrom had not re-signed, the results could have been
disastrous.
</P>
<P>
   In making the deals, Holland mortgaged the future, trading away
a young defenseman and former No. 1 pick Anders Eriksson, two
first-round picks, two seconds and a third.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if he is now gun-shy about making a deal, Holland
said, ``Gun-shy's not the right word. I don't anticipate we would
be as aggressive at the trade deadline this year, because we have
to keep an eye on the future. But for the last three or four years,
the thinking has been that the future is now. I would do it all
over again. We had won two straight Stanley Cups, and we had a
chance to make our mark on history. Over time, you've only got so
many bullets. To not sacrifice a little to try to win the Cup
would've been wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Detroit made no significant changes this year _ except perhaps
in attitude.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
