<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 22:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9003 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-GLF-FEATURE07-COX     10-06 0535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-FEATURE07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Keep insults at 19th hole
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It has been 11 days since the Ryder Cup ended, and the
whining is still audible from the other side of the pond.
</P>
<P>
   Puh-leeze.
</P>
<P>
   Do we need to even mention that Europeans get killed watching
soccer games?
</P>
<P>
   Or that the Europeans originated tacky behavior at the Ryder
Cup, cheering missed putts by Americans and making a mockery of
sportsmanship.
</P>
<P>
   Or that European fans were poking umbrellas through fences at
the Belfry in England in 1993, trying to trip American players as
they walked past.
</P>
<P>
   Or that every time Sergio Garcia made a putt at Brookline, he
danced as though a hornet had come to rest in his BVD's.
</P>
<P>
   And consider the fact that the Europeans played so slowly, it
was beginning to look as if Y2K could become a factor.
</P>
<P>
   That said, the celebration at the 17th hole at Brookline after
Justin Leonard's monster putt probably was not the right thing to
do. But the Europeans, given the same set of circumstances on their
home field, probably would have done the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   Did the celebration affect the outcome? Probably not.
</P>
<P>
   For all the talk of people being in Jose Maria Olazabal's
putting line, Tom Lehman was so far away from it, he almost fell
into a bunker trying to get to Leonard.
</P>
<P>
   What was bad about the celebration?
</P>
<P>
   The wives, girlfriends and hangers-on who followed the ecstatic
players toward Leonard. Next time, the PGA of America has hinted,
they won't be allowed inside the ropes.
</P>
<P>
   What was good about the celebration for the Europeans? It
conveniently deflected the real issue of the day, which was that
Europe, after the biggest two-day lead in the history of the Ryder
Cup, managed the worst collapse in sports since 1964, when the
Philadelphia Phillies blew a 6 1/2-game lead in two weeks and lost
the National League pennant.
</P>
<P>
   Let's blame the European tabloid media for some of the cover-up.
Nearly every post-match question concerned the Americans'
celebration. Tabloid reporters, noted for heartless ``choking dog''
accusations, instead attacked American behavior they felt
intolerable.
</P>
<P>
   While golf fans should celebrate that the Ryder Cup controversy
created incredible interest in their sport smack in the middle of
baseball pennant races and college football season, unfortunately,
two separate issues have been lumped together. The celebration was
one thing. Fan rowdiness is another.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that fans now yell things at golf tournaments that in
the past might have been limited to, say, Giants Stadium, was a
problem for both teams. Colin Montgomerie was a favorite target,
but David Duval and Davis Love III also were razzed by fans.
</P>
<P>
   American golf fans have become an embarrassment, and that's a
legitimate beef for the Euros. The PGA of America, PGA Tour and
U.S. Golf Association need to start expelling fans at the first
insult, not after a warning.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine an insult yelled at Justin Leonard just as he prepared
to strike that historic putt. Or at Olazabal a moment later.
</P>
<P>
   That truly would be a shame.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
