<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 22:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9010 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKN-HAWKS-RIDER07-COX     10-06 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HAWKS-RIDER07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rider arrives in camp after case of cold feet
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHATTANOOGA, Tenn. _ In a rambling, often puzzling series of
statements, Isaiah Rider tried to explain Wednesday why he was late
to the Hawks' training camp.
</P>
<P>
   Rider said his two-day tardiness was because he did not want to
play for a rebuilding team, was concerned about his future
free-agent status, had decided that he had wanted to be traded but
changed his mind and did not have a real excuse for arriving late.
</P>
<P>
   Rider, fined about $15,000, met with general manager Pete
Babcock and later with coach Lenny Wilkens, both of whom had
expressed their disappointment in the player's unexcused absence.
</P>
<P>
   Rider said he was ready to go to work because both men had
allayed his fears.
</P>
<P>
   The former Minnesota and Portland player, obtained in August
with Jim Jackson for fellow guards Steve Smith and Ed Gray,
expressed great optimism a few days after the trade but said the
euphoria of a fresh start faded as his personal anxiety grew. Rider
did not say anything about his failure to contact management about
his agitated condition or why he did not return Babcock's frequent
telephone calls. ``I became discouraged by what was written at home
and (in Atlanta),'' he said but would not be specific.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he thought that the Hawks could not win, he said, ``I'm
optimistic; I'm not a negative person. But we're not as good as
Portland. I feel like we have a dominant big man, good, quick point
guard coming in, good forwards and some new guards now. I think we
have a better chance of winning now that I've talked to Lenny than
I did three or four weeks ago.''
</P>
<P>
   With free agency a year away, he said he knew he had no clout.
``I thought I don't have much leverage, but I'd rather go to a team
that's, you know, competing in the last year of my contract rather
than a rebuilding team. But I feel a lot better about it now. I
have to go in with a positive attitude. I'm not a loser. Even in
Minnesota they said Rider played hard, (that) he led that team.''
</P>
<P>
   Rider also said, ``I'm an emotional guy. There were some tears
shed (in the meetings). I want to win. I'm not concerned with
shooting a lot, and it felt good to hear where they were coming
from, and I think it made them feel good to hear some of my
concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   Rider said his arrival was delayed last week by unspecified
legal issues that were resolved Friday. He said he could have flown
from San Francisco to Atlanta on Sunday in time for Monday's
mandatory meetings but did not do so. He said he did fly overnight
Monday and arrived in Atlanta at 7 a.m. Tuesday in time for a
connecting flight here. However, he said, ``I don't fly
crop-dusters. Anyone who knows me can tell you that. I saw this
30-, 40-seat plane and I wasn't getting on it. Those planes crash
and kill people.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the plane Rider refused to board was either a 50-seat
jet or 66-seat prop plane, both operated by Delta. He did not
arrive here until midmorning Wednesday, by car. He arrived at the
UT-Chattanooga arena about 11 a.m. after former NBA referee Ken
Hudson picked him up at the team hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Rider met briefly with Babcock and took a physical that cleared
him for the team's evening practice. Before taking Rider to the
arena, Hudson said, ``I gave him a good talking to, sort of brother
to brother. That's why he didn't get here sooner.''
</P>
<P>
   But the often-troubled Rider said he did not feel better about
the situation until he met with Wilkens on Wednesday afternoon and
fully understood his role as a primary weapon on a team that feels
good about its chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't realize how strong they felt about that. I thought I
would be thrown to the wolves, or I would play hard and then I
would be left out there at the end of this year and I would rather
play for a winning squad than average 25 and not do well and my
stock still goes down. I do know now that they want me to be a big
part of this team, so I will work hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Rider, for all of his past problems, showed dedication to
winning last season with Portland. After averaging 18.5 points per
game his first five years in the league, he accepted a reduced rule
and averaged 13.9, and the Trail Blazers advanced to the Western
Conference finals before San Antonio swept them.
</P>
<P>
   Hawks president Stan Kasten was pragmatic about Rider's absence.
On Monday, Kasten said, ``J.R. will come in, he'll play his 2,600,
2,800 minutes, and then he'll sign a contract with us next
summer.''
</P>
<P>
   Babcock said that Rider was told Wednesday that he will have
that opportunity and that his performance and his behavior will
determine whether the organization would like to have him back.
</P>
<P>
   If the Hawks choose not to keep Rider at the end of this season,
they will shed $5.4 million in salary cap money. With four players
in the final years of their contracts _ Rider, Bimbo Coles,
LaPhonso Ellis and Anthony Johnson _ the Hawks will have the option
of dropping more than $10 million from their payroll next summer
and going under the league salary cap, which will exceed $36
million.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
