<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 22:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9013 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-REAGAN-BIO-MORRIS-NYT     10-06 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REAGAN-BIO-MORRIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAGAN MEMOIRIST DEFENDS UNCONVENTIONAL METHOD OF CHRONICLING
PRESIDENT  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By C.J. CHIVERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Edmund Morris, whose memoir of President Reagan's
life threads fiction through fact, began a 14-city tour on
Wednesday night promoting a book that has provoked fascination and
scorn.
</P>
<P>
   Morris opened his tour at the Barnes &AMP; Noble bookstore across
from Lincoln Center, penetrating deep into overwhelmingly
Democratic territory to talk about his unconventional manner of
chronicling the life of a most Republican president.
</P>
<P>
   He was received warmly by a standing-room-only crowd of about
200 people, who listened intently as he shared anecdotes about ``a
consummate actor'' who was a master at using ``charm to garner
power.''
</P>
<P>
   Morris, a member of Random House's stable of accomplished
writers, received a Pulitzer Prize in 1980 for his biography of
Theodore Roosevelt. Handpicked by Reagan's staff, he was granted
enviable access in the hope that he would produce the definitive
text on an often opaque man.
</P>
<P>
   Definitive or no, the text he produced has seeded a news media
storm.
</P>
<P>
   The book, ``Dutch: A Memoir of Ronald Reagan,'' went on sale
last week. It includes a fictional character, modeled loosely after
Morris himself, who encounters Reagan repeatedly through life. In
one section, this character edits Reagan's prose for the sports
pages of a college newspaper; in another, he reports to a young Lt.
Reagan while serving in the Army Air Force; in the end, he leads
the ailing former president back to his place of birth.
</P>
<P>
   By imposing an imaginary character on a work of nonfiction, the
biography of a president no less, Morris has raised questions about
what readers can trust in his work, about Random House's commitment
to longstanding standards, and about the hazy lines at which
celebrity legend meets historical fact.
</P>
<P>
   Morris offered a polished defense of his methods on Wednesday
night. He said: ``All I ask of the readers of this book is that you
accept, in the early chapters, the presence of a spectator. Maybe a
better word would be a projector.
</P>
<P>
   ``My projector projects a documentary which is absolutely true
to historical fact.''
</P>
<P>
   Random House, which advanced Morris $3 million, is anticipating
brisk sales. It augmented the initial press run of 300,000 with
another 75,000 copies before the first copy of ``Dutch'' was sold.
</P>
<P>
   The publishing giant is also standing behind Morris' work. Its
corporate Web site describes the author's fictions as ``a unique
literary method'' in which Morris' ``biographical mind becomes in
effect another character in the narrative.''
</P>
<P>
   Independent reviews have ranged from praise to contempt,
although the negative reactions stand out for the sharpness of
their disgust.
</P>
<P>
   Michiko Kakutani wrote in The New York Times that Morris had
squandered priceless access to a sitting president, and written not
a biography but a ``cloying, egocentric novel.'' Writing in The
Wall Street Journal, Peggy Noonan, a former Reagan speechwriter,
described ``Dutch'' as a ``belly-flop into the pools of
Narcissus.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Perry, a spokesman for Random House, said criticism had
split between ``book people,'' who had reviewed ``Dutch'' warmly,
and historians and journalists troubled by the book's fictions.
</P>
<P>
   Perry brushed aside suggestions of an erosion in Random House's
standards. ``I think that's just absurd,'' he said. ``The book is
just too good.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, Morris took his case directly to potential
readers.
</P>
<P>
   The customers seemed compelled to attend on Wednesday night, if
only because of an enduring curiosity over Reagan's idiosyncratic
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Morris satisfied their inquisitiveness, describing a president
who occasionally displayed ``astonishing ignorance.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He was convinced that trees caused acid rain, threatening the
entire industrial Northeast,'' he said, to chuckles.
</P>
<P>
   Morris' tour continues during the next five weeks with signings
in San Diego, Los Angeles, San Francisco, Washington, Chicago and
elsewhere. He returns to New York for an Oct. 23 signing at the the
Henry Luce Foundation in Manhattan, and finishes the tour on Nov.
14 at Bookends in Ridgewood, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Walter Gilligan, Bookends' store manager, said Wednesday that
ever since Morris was criticized, sales have been hot.
</P>
<P>
   ``People love an underdog,'' Gilligan said. ``Friday, Saturday
and Sunday, we sold the heck out of the book. The book was blah
until then.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
