<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 22:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9018 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-DOLE-CAMPAIGN-1STLD-W     10-06 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOLE-CAMPAIGN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOLE BELIEVES SLOW AND STEADY WILL AT LEAST KEEP HER IN THE RACE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS ``basic'' for ``basis'' in 9th graf; TIGHTENS reference to
Dole declining interview in 2nd optional trim) 
(ATTN: Calif., S.C., Ky., Ariz., Calif.) (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By DIANA JEAN SCHEMO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Ask June Shockency, a sergeant-at-arms in
California's Republican Party, what she thinks of Elizabeth Dole,
and her face brightens: ``intelligent, outgoing, warm,'' she says.
But ask Mrs. Shockency about Mrs. Dole's message the last time she
heard her speak, and there is a pause. ``I really can't remember,''
she finally says.
</P>
<P>
   Six weeks ago, Mrs. Dole surprised campaign watchers, many of
whom had declared her presidential bid a model of lost
opportunities, by placing a strong third in the Iowa straw poll.
And since then, she has crisscrossed the country, drawing
enthusiastic crowds familiar with the Dole name and intrigued by
the first woman to make a viable bid for the White House.
</P>
<P>
   But at the same time, her campaign remains something of a puzzle
to outsiders. Although national polls show her running second to
George W. Bush, she has been able to raise only about a tenth of
the money he has collected.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, her campaign has lost three top advisers, including
two spokesmen who left in the last month. The personnel changes
have lent her campaign an air of turmoil, turning routine matters
like obtaining her schedule into exercises in tenacity.
</P>
<P>
   Recent days have seen a wave of speculation that her
fund-raising problems would soon force her to drop out of the race.
And even avid supporters have taken to touting Mrs. Dole as a fine
choice _ for vice president.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a hard go for us,'' Tom Daffron, Mrs. Dole's
campaign manager, said recently with some understatement. ``There's
no doubt about it.''
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the biggest challenge these days is turning the
curiosity of voters like Mrs. Shockency into support. And in a
series of campaign appearances over the past couple of weeks, many
voters seemed intrigued by her candidacy, but few declared outright
that they would vote for her.
</P>
<P>
   Known for carefully rehearsing speeches down to her trademark
catch in the throat, Mrs. Dole cuts an equally meticulous figure
before voters and donors, with outfits matched down to the polish
on her fingernails. She couches her pitch in a heavy dose of
Southern charm, still carrying the lilt of her native Salisbury,
N.C., and speaks of restoring the values of an earlier era.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we worked to eliminate the federal deficit,'' she said
in a recent address, ``we have done little to eliminate the deficit
that exists in our basic American values: honesty, integrity,
personal responsibility, civility, and respect for our fellow
man.''
</P>
<P>
   Her staff adamantly rejects speculation the she might be the
next Republican to drop out of the race. And until recently her
aides have maintained that Mrs. Dole was deliberately holding off
on taking policy stands so early in the primary race and focusing
instead on building a broad base of support.
</P>
<P>
   But wounded by the speculation, she appears ready to strike a
newly aggressive stance. On Thursday she will outline a tough
anti-drug policy at the Mexican border, and on Friday she will
strike at the home state of Sen. John McCain, with a fund-raising
luncheon in Phoenix. ``I'm out there running hard, working hard,''
she said Wednesday in Lexington, Ky.
</P>
<P>
   With Republican Party faithful lining up behind Bush of Texas,
Mrs. Dole's strategy aims to stay in the race as the strongest
alternative should Bush fall, gathering in Republicans,
particularly women, who have traditionally remained outside the
political process. ``Her strength is her grass roots appeal,'' said
Kathleen Harrington, deputy campaign manager for Mrs. Dole.
</P>
<P>
   When asked their impressions, people say they look favorably
upon Mrs. Dole, a former president of the American Red Cross, whose
husband was the party's presidential candidate in 1996. But surveys
of voter intentions show her steadily slipping behind the Bush
juggernaut. One recent nationwide survey, by CNN-Gallup-USA Today,
shows Bush with 62 percent support among Republican voters, and
Mrs. Dole with 10 percent, down from 16 percent in April.
</P>
<P>
   Other Republican hopefuls remain in the single digits, but some,
like McCain have been gaining visibility, buoyed by an aggressive
campaign and a newly published memoir. McCain, who sat out the Iowa
straw poll, raised $3 million in the last three months, while Mrs.
Dole's fund-raisers, raised half that much during the same period.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Dole has so far avoided the thrust and parry of battle with
other candidates. Famous for her meticulous planning, she shies
away from press conferences or interviews with reporters she does
not know, and she has remained largely absent from the
rough-and-tumble political talk show circuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's back in the pack and she's going to have to do something
to get noticed,'' said Martin P. Wattenberg, a political science
professor specializing in presidential politics at the University
of California at Irvine. Mrs. Dole, he said, ``has to have a catch,
and it has to be something more than `I'm a woman.'''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In her speeches, Mrs. Dole always acknowledges the historic
nature of her candidacy, but says she does not want people voting
for her because of her gender. She advocates building up the
country's nuclear defense, tighter border surveillance to stop
drugs from Mexico, and increasing local control over schools. She
supports the use of school vouchers, which would allow parents of
children in failing public schools using public funds to switch
their children to private schools.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Dole reminds voters that polls show her a consistent second
behind Bush, capable of beating either Al Gore or Bill Bradley in a
two-way race, and she sells herself as an experienced hand at
government who advocates traditional values. Her heaviest applause
comes when Mrs. Dole discusses an issue that actually has little to
do with the presidency: discipline in the schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm impressed,'' said Frank Long, a training technologist at
Carolina Eastman, a chemical company in Columbia, S.C., where Mrs.
Dole spoke to about 200 workers last week. But Long said he wanted
to hear other candidates before deciding his vote.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, speaking to the Christian Coalition in Washington,
Mrs. Dole delivered her call for old-fashioned values with more
steel than ever before. She said that while America enjoyed a
budget surplus, it was suffering a deficit in moral values, and she
called for posting the Ten Commandments in classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is wrong that our children are not allowed a silent moment
of prayer in school, that a constitutional amendment is necessary
to ensure a child's right to pray,'' she told the Coalition. ``And
it is right that we protect the sanctity of life, that we replace
abortion with adoption, require parental notification, and that we
continue the ban on federal funding.''
</P>
<P>
   Campaign aides say that Mrs. Dole has strong ideas about the
type and pace of campaign that she wants to run. She insists any
important communication from her staff come to her in writing.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   A strategy paper from her campaign, disclosed to The New York
Times by a person close to her campaign, says a ``shooting war''
against the front-runner is far better left to Steve Forbes, while
Mrs. Dole should focus on doing well in Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Winning Iowa's primary would give Mrs. Dole a 15 to 20 point
``bounce'' to bolster her showing in New Hampshire a week later and
build momentum going into South Carolina, staffers say. After
August's straw poll in Iowa, Mrs. Dole surged from fourth to second
place among New Hampshire voters, said Ms. Harrington.
</P>
<P>
   ``We captured that bounce,'' Ms. Harrington said, ``and we've
been able to translate it into organizational strength in South
Carolina.'' While Republican governors across the nation have
already rallied behind Bush, the early primary states have
Democratic governors, another advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Sinclair, a political scientist at the University of
California at Los Angeles, said a cautious campaign so early made
some sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have rivals and the media hitting the candidates if they
don't say anything, and if they say the wrong thing, they can
easily get killed before the public ever starts paying attention,''
Ms. Sinclair said. ``You've got to at least be able to arrive at
the point where people pay attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Campaign watchers, though, said that with the race coalescing so
quickly, Mrs. Dole should aim for greater visibility now, not
later.
</P>
<P>
   ``This strategy of ambiguity is more common when candidates have
reason to believe people already like them,'' said Larry Bartels,
author of ``Presidential Primaries and the Dynamics of Public
Choice.'' ``It's hard to get people's attention without saying
something more substantial.''
</P>
<P>
   Others suggest Mrs. Dole has not appeared hungry enough for the
job. ``She doesn't want to go for the brass ring,'' said Frank J.
Luntz, a Republican strategist.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   After some early gaffes discussing issues like abortion and drug
control, Mrs. Dole has shunned press conferences, opting instead
for brief appearances before reporters, usually after her speeches.
These typically end when an unwelcome question pops up. Mrs. Dole
glances at her nearest aide, who instantly announces, ``Okay. Last
question.''
</P>
<P>
   For several weeks, her aides said she was too busy to be
interviewed for this article.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   At fund-raising dinners, Mrs. Dole tells donors that she could
obviously not hope to match Bush in fund raising, but requires just
enough to stay in the race. Daffron noted that Mrs. Dole and Bush
shared similar bases of support. When one rises in popularity, the
other falls. ``To the extent that he stumbles, we are the
alternative,'' Daffron said.
</P>
<P>
   One campaign official appeared perplexed that Bush emerged
unscathed after questions arose about whether he used cocaine as a
young man, and his service in the Texas Air National Guard during
the Vietnam War. ``He so far just seems to be a Teflon candidate,''
the official said.
</P>
<P>
   Many people, including those throwing the $500-a-plate dinners
for Mrs. Dole, increasingly speak of her as a potential candidate
for vice president. As the last guests sauntered out of Richard and
Pamela Scurry's penthouse on Fifth Avenue in Manhattan recently,
Scurry said he knew it was a ``long shot'' to bet on Mrs. Dole
becoming the next president.
</P>
<P>
   ``But vice president?'' he asked. ``I don't think that's a long
shot at all.'' This month's Mirabella, a woman's magazine,
headlined it's story on Mrs. Dole's bid, ``Vice Can Be Nice.''
</P>
<P>
   But, as strategists are quick to point out this year, even vice
takes work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
