<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Spurrier turns down LSU's jersey request
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Leave it to Steve Spurrier, Florida's irrepressible
coach, to change the subject.
</P>
<P>
   While folks in Gatorland were lamenting Florida's defense,
shredded in a 40-39 overtime loss to Alabama on Saturday, the media
turned its attention to a letter Spurrier wrote to LSU coach Gerry
DiNardo, copies of which were ``accidentally'' faxed to Louisiana
media members this week.
</P>
<P>
   In the letter, dated Jan. 14, Spurrier informed DiNardo that
Florida would not honor LSU's request to wear its traditional white
jerseys for Saturday's game in Baton Rouge.
</P>
<P>
   LSU likes to wear white at home, but by NCAA rules, the home
team must wear dark jerseys unless the visiting team agrees to
switch.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Spurrier agreed to wear blue jerseys at Baton
Rouge, and the Gators, ranked No. 1, lost 28-21. Spurrier thought
his team was treated poorly during that trip. In the letter, he
wrote:
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the nasty, vulgar treatment our team received from
LSU fans during our last visit to Baton Rouge, we have decided that
from now on, we will wear the traditional white jersey on the road
and dark jersey at home.''
</P>
<P>
   Sincerely,
</P>
<P>
   Steve Spurrier
</P>
<P>
   Football coach
</P>
<P>
   When asked about it after practice Monday, Spurrier did not back
down.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to get them real mad,'' he said. ``We play better
when the other guys are mad at us. I found that out. Alabama came
in here and said all the nice things, and we all sat back and read
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, we can get LSU talking nasty about us. That makes
us play a little better, it seems.''
</P>
<P>
   The only team previously to deny DiNardo's request to wear white
was Vanderbilt, his former employer, in 1996. DiNardo responded by
breaking out gold jerseys, and LSU ripped the Commodores 35-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like the gold jerseys,'' Spurrier said, suggesting that LSU
should wear them again.
</P>
<P>
   WORTH NOTING
</P>
<P>
   _ Saturday marks the first time since 1961 that No. 3 Michigan
and No. 11 Michigan State have been unbeaten when they met. Tickets
are going for $450 on the Internet. Michigan has won 23 of the past
29 meetings.
</P>
<P>
   _ Texas A&AMP;M has not scored an offensive touchdown since Sept.
18. That's 29 possessions in a row without getting into the end
zone.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wisconsin coach Barry Alvarez, whose knee-replacement surgery
has been delayed, will coach Saturday's Minnesota game by phone
from his Mayo Clinic bed in Rochester, Minn.
</P>
<P>
   _ Utah running back Mike Anderson did not play high school
football, choosing to play drums in his high school marching band
in Winnsboro, S.C. He leads the Mountain West Conference in rushing
with an average of 102.5 yards per game. Anderson is 26 years old.
He enrolled at Utah after spending four years in the Marines.
</P>
<P>
   _ Hofstra running back Vaughn Sanders ended his career 7 yards
short of the school career record because he broke his leg in a
27-14 victory against Massachusetts on Saturday. Bill Sanford's
school record is 2,503 yards.
</P>
<P>
   WORTH QUOTING
</P>
<P>
   ``We're undisciplined and sometimes just plain dumb.''
</P>
<P>
   _ JOE PATERNO, Penn State coach, whose team has fumbled 17 times
in five games.
</P>
<P>
   BY THE NUMBERS
</P>
<P>
   54: Consecutive sellouts for the annual Texas-Oklahoma game,
Saturday at the Cotton Bowl in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   46: Consecutive games won by Division III Mount Union, dating to
the 1996 season. The Purple Raiders, who have won the past three
Division III championships, can tie Oklahoma's NCAA record with a
victory against Heidelberg.
</P>
<P>
   84: Ohio State's ranking in total defense. The Buckeyes, who
play Purdue on Saturday, are giving up averages of 396 yards and 29
points per game.
</P>
<P>
   2-5: UCLA's record since Miami ended the Bruins' 20-game win
streak in December.
</P>
