<HEADLINE>
CRUISE INDUSTRY GETS TOUGH LECTURE AT SENATE HEARING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz., Texas)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By DOUGLAS FRANTZ   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. John McCain warned the cruise industry
Wednesday that Congress might restrict its access to American ports
unless the companies did a better job of abiding by United States
laws and insuring the safety of passengers.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, R-Ariz., chairman of the Senate Committee on Commerce,
Science and Transportation as well as a Republican presidential
candidate, said at a committee hearing that he was appalled by
cruise ships' continuing violations of environmental laws and by
sexual assaults aboard the ships.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got a credibility problem right now,'' the senator told
Cynthia Colenda, president of the International Council of Cruise
Lines, the Washington trade group for the 17 foreign-registered
cruise companies that dominate the industry in North America.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Colenda responded by saying the industry had taken several
steps in recent months to improve compliance with environmental
regulations and insure that sexual assaults and other crimes aboard
ships are reported to the proper law-enforcement authorities.
</P>
<P>
   While the cruise industry is booming, its performance on safety,
security and environmental matters is coming under scrutiny in
Congress. On Thursday, the House Transportation and Infrastructure
Subcommittee on the Coast Guard and Maritime Transportation will
hold a hearing to examine two recent fires aboard Carnival Cruise
Lines ships and the industry's overall record in security and
environmental compliance.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of articles over the last year, The New York Times
has documented cruise lines' efforts to cover up reports of sexual
assaults aboard ship and their record of repeated violations of
federal environmental law.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's chiding of the industry Wednesday was particularly
stinging because it came at a hearing on legislation he has
introduced to increase access to U.S. ports by foreign-flagged
cruise ships.
</P>
<P>
   The Passenger Vessel Services Act of 1886, intended to protect
the American shipping industry, requires that ships going from one
U.S. port to another be U.S.-flagged and U.S.-built and have an
American crew. To comply with the law, foreign-flagged cruise ships
sailing out of U.S. ports must stop at a foreign port before
returning to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The impact of the requirement has been felt particularly on the
West Coast. For instance, instead of embarking from San Diego for
their cruises along the coast of Mexico, ships leave from Ensenada,
Mexico, some 75 miles to the south. As a result, a coalition of
ports and tourism groups has pushed to abolish or alter the 1886
law, to increase use of U.S. ports.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's bill would create a two-pronged exemption.
Foreign-flagged cruise ships would be allowed limited access to
U.S. routes until Dec. 31, 2006, and American companies could buy
foreign-built cruise ships and re-flag them as United States
vessels to help stimulate an American cruise industry.
</P>
<P>
   McCain and Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, who is
co-sponsoring the bill, acknowledged at the hearing that prospects
for passage were already slim, because of opposition from
Democrats, some labor unions and operators of smaller American
cruise ships.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain cautioned the bill's proponents that any chance of
passage depended on erasing the impression that foreign vessels
ignore United States laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurts our efforts,'' he said, ``if these kinds of
violations of law continue.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the senator said, such violations increase the chances
that Congress will act in the opposite way, adding to the
restrictions that are already law.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
