<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Oxendine gets a start, but Chandler
 &HT;    still `doubtful'
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Falcons still aren't sure, but Tony Graziani could
start at quarterback Sunday at New Orleans. The start would be
Graziani's second in a row and third in the last four games.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Chandler's role in practice was limited Wednesday because
of his strained right hamstring. ``I would say he is doubtful,''
coach Dan Reeves said.
</P>
<P>
   The definite news is at running back. Second-year pro Ken
Oxendine, like Graziani a former seventh-round draft choice, will
become the third player to start there this season.
</P>
<P>
   Byron Hanspard, who passed Oxendine on the depth chart after an
encouraging preseason, is battling left knee problems again.
Hanspard also sprained his right shoulder Sunday against Baltimore,
when he had 20 yards on 14 carries in a 19-13 overtime loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``The shoulder is bothering him, as well as the knee,'' Reeves
said. ``Until he gets healthy, it is very difficult for any running
back. Kenny has got to be ready to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Oxendine has carried 13 times for 33 yards, a 2.5-yard average.
The 6-foot, 230-pounder rushed 18 times for 50 yards as a rookie
but lost a fumble on his first pro carry at San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to it,'' said Oxendine, whose greatest
claim to fame as a player at Virginia Tech was rushing for 150
yards and catching passes for another 60 yards in an Orange Bowl
loss to Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   ``All through high school and college, you're always trying to
become the starter,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the final preseason game of 1998, Hanspard tore the anterior
cruciate ligament and the patella tendon in his left knee against
the Bengals. Some described the injury as career-threatening.
</P>
<P>
   He appeared to be strong in the preseason, and in the last
exhibition, a 28-16 win at Cincinnati, he had 69 yards and two
touchdowns on 11 carries, including a 43-yard scoring run.
</P>
<P>
   But Reeves said Monday that Hanspard lacked the quickness and
elusiveness that marked his rookie season of '97, when he rushed 53
times for 355 yards, a 6.3-yard average.
</P>
<P>
   This season, he has 53 carries again, but for 155 yards, a
2.9-yard average. Atlanta's rushing offense is averaging 71.5 yards
per game, which is 29th in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Hanspard has been bothered recently by swelling, discomfort and
stiffness in his left knee. When he visited an orthopedist, the
doctor flexed his knee to break up scar tissue that was tightening
the joint.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was sore. Everything is fine,'' Hanspard said. ``I've done
my best. If they're not pleased with that, then I can't do anything
about that. I'm going to support whoever is at running back.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
