r s BC-OUT-HIKING-LADN     10-06 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-HIKING-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HENNINGER FLATS AS GOOD AS GOLD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT PURDUE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Pining for an evergreen escape from the heat and
the clattering din of the city?
</P>
<P>
   Relief is tantalizingly close if you possess the thigh muscles
and lung power to ascend to Henninger Flats from Eaton Canyon
County Park. Perched on the south-facing slopes of the San Gabriel
Mountains high above smog-shrouded Altadena, Henninger Flats is a
verdant oasis of cool pines and cedars encircled by the pungent
brittleness of Southern California chaparral.
</P>
<P>
   It's 3.7 miles from Eaton to Eden (7.4 miles round-trip), though
you'll have to earn your ticket to paradise by making a
calf-cramping elevation gain of 1,640 feet. Along the way, you'll
also be switchbacking into a unique chapter of L.A. history.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1880s, William K. Henninger, his pockets bulging with
gold from nearby San Gabriel Canyon, moved to the flats to grow
fruit and nuts. He packed his produce down to Pasadena and Los
Angeles for sale. Some two decades later the land was leased by the
U.S. Division of Forestry for use as an experimental tree farm;
more than 60,000 conifers were raised between 1903 and 1907. The
L.A. County Fire Department bought the flats in 1928 and took over
the tree plantation. Today the department grows more than 20,000
evergreens each year; they are planted to rejuvenate burned areas,
control erosion and stabilize hillsides.
</P>
<P>
   At Henninger Flats _ an area the size of a few city blocks _ the
wind murmurs through towering pines and the scent of cedar needles
wafts on the breeze. Tired hikers and mountain bikers, tongues
lolling, linger over picnic lunches and nab a few ``zzzs'' in the
shade. To the delight of backpackers, there are 18 campsites and
water spigots.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so nice because it's got that up-in-the-mountains feel,''
said Dan Schauer of Sierra Madre one recent afternoon. Schauer and
his wife, Marsha, were enjoying Henninger Flats for the first time
after turning back on their previous attempt to reach the locale.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were kind of frustrated last time, but this time we said,
`We're going to make it,' '' Dan said.
</P>
<P>
   They did ... barely. ``We just collapsed when we got here,''
said Marsha, gazing at the 40-foot-high trees, which on this day
outnumbered visitors a good 10 to 1. ``But it's so nice with the
pines. It's so pretty that I'm surprised it's not more crowded.''
</P>
<P>
   You have the option of two starting points for the hike. Begin
at Eaton Canyon Nature Center in the park of the same name off
Altadena Drive. Or light out from a fire road gate on Pinecrest
Drive, about a mile north of the nature center, for a 3-mile hike
with a gain of 1,350 feet. If it's your first time in the area, a
stop at the well-stocked nature center (open 9 a.m. to 5 p.m.
daily; free admission) is highly recommended.
</P>
<P>
   From the nature center, the trail heads north through parched
Eaton Canyon for 1.1 miles, then turns right and climbs the Mount
Wilson Toll Road. More than 70 years ago, tourists by the carloads
were making this ascent; today it's closed to all motor vehicles
but is popular with mountain bikers. The fire road zigzags up the
mountainside, offering ever-grander views of Pasadena and the San
Gabriel Valley, but woefully little shade. Pack plenty of water.
This is dusty chaparral country, dominated by the evergreen-shrub
chamise, laurel sumac, chaparral yucca, black and white sage and
California buckwheat, and no water can be found at Henninger.
</P>
<P>
   At times the fire road seems to soar straight into the sky, but
take deep breaths and after an hour or two of huffing _ depending
on how many breaks you take _ you'll finally arrive at the island
above the haze. Just in time, no doubt, for a walk through the (air
conditioned!) Henninger Flats Visitors Center at hike's pinnacle
... and a nap.
</P>
<P>
   After 40 winks, retrace your steps back to your rig. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
IF YOU'RE GOING ... &QL; 
From the Foothill Freeway (210) eastbound, exit at Sierra Madre
Boulevard/Altadena Drive in Pasadena and turn left. Follow the
signs to the Eaton Canyon Nature Center, 1750 N. Altadena Drive,
and the first trailhead to Henninger Flats.
</P>
<P>
   To shorten the hike by 1.4 miles round-trip, continue north on
Altadena Drive to Pinecrest Drive, turn right and park near the
gate at 2260 Pinecrest Drive. Walk around the gate on a fire road
that soon intersects the Mount Wilson Toll Road.
</P>
<P>
   Allow at least 4 hours to complete the 7.4-mile round-trip from
the nature center, less for the 6-mile round-trip from Pinecrest
Drive. (Bicyclists are permitted only on the Pinecrest Drive
option.)
</P>
<P>
   Map: Mount Wilson 7.5-minute series topographic.
</P>
<P>
   Hiking information: Eaton Canyon County Park, (626) 398-5420.
</P>
<P>
   Camping: (626) 794-0675. Overnight stays are allowed at
Henninger Flats for up to 14 days; free camping and fire permits
are required and may be picked up at the Henninger Flats Visitors
Center at the apex of the trek. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
