<SLUG> BC-OLY-SYDNEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SYDNEY GAMES ARE ALMOST ON SCHEDULE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By FRANK LITSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Last year, Michael Knight, the president of the
organizing committee for next year's Sydney Olympics, ran into
Peter Ueberroth, who held a similar job for the successful 1984 Los
Angeles Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   As Knight related the story Wednesday, he said Ueberroth told
him, ``You will have serious problems that you don't know are
coming.''
</P>
<P>
   Knight asked, ``What problems?'' He said Ueberroth replied:
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what they are, but they're coming, something you
don't expect. When it happens, I want you to remember that every
set of Games has its own set of problems. We had the Soviet-bloc
boycott. Montreal had the boycott of African nations. Just embrace
them and move on. Sight unseen, I'd take your problems over the
ones I had in 1984.''
</P>
<P>
   Six months after Knight talked with Ueberroth, Knight was
saddled with a big problem: a scandal involving excessive gifts to
International Olympic Committee members from the Salt Lake City
committee before and after it was awarded the 2002 Winter Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   There were allegations that Sydney, Atlanta (1996 Summer
Olympics) and Nagano, Japan, (1998 Winter Olympics) employed
similar generosity in winning IOC approval for their Olympic bids.
However, Knight said an inquiry by Sydney organizers and the New
South Wales government ``found we were generally clean, but not
absolutely unblemished. We couldn't find anything worthy of further
investigation by the police.''
</P>
<P>
   Did Sydney obtain the 2000 Olympics corruptly? ``No,'' Knight
said emphatically.
</P>
<P>
   Knight, a 47-year-old minister in the New South Wales state
government, met here with editors and reporters from the sports
department of The New York Times Wednesday. He said almost
everything was on schedule for the Sydney Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Physically,'' he said, ``we're in good shape. Financially,
we're in pretty good shape.''
</P>
<P>
   Revenue from ticket sales has been encouraging. Knight said such
events as the opening ceremonies and finals of track and field,
swimming, basketball, gymnastics, cycling, field hockey and rowing
were sold out, with many tickets at premium prices. He said when
$220 million worth of tickets were offered to the Australian
public, $340 million in orders were received.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now,'' he said, ``we're telling some people that we can't give
you all the tickets you wanted, but wouldn't you like to see some
other sports, too?'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
