<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF: ENGLAND, GERMANY, GUATEMALA, PERU, MEXICO 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: PINOCHET EXCUSED
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Augusto Pinochet was excused for health reasons from having
to appear in person at Friday's reading of a court decision on a
Spanish request to extradite him to Madrid on torture charges. A
doctor said the 83-year-old former Chilean dictator suffered two
small strokes in September. Requiring him to attend would put him
``under great strain,'' said Dr. Michael Loxton.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: A CHOCOLATE WALL
</P>
<P>
   Berliners marked the 50th anniversary of the founding of East
Germany by erecting a 13-ton wall of chocolate some 39 feet long.
More than 40 Italian confectioners from Perugia stacked up 400
45-pound chocolate bricks near where the Berlin wall once divided
East and West. Some eastern Germans have reacted to the anniversary
with warm recollections of life before unification; others find
nostalgia for a police state distasteful.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   GUATEMALA: CLANDESTINE GRAVES
</P>
<P>
   Forensic anthropologists have been searching for clandestine
graves on the grounds of the former headquarters of the Mobile
Military Police in Guatemala City. Their investigation was
authorized after human bones were found at the site this year by
construction workers. Carla Villagran, the dean of the political
science department at the University of Rafael Landivar, said, ``I
imagine it is not the only one, but it is the one we have access
to.''
</P>
<P>
   PERU: FUJIMORI HUNTS REBELS
</P>
<P>
   President Alberto K. Fujimori began a combined army and police
operation in the central jungle region to hunt down a column of 60
Shining Path rebels who shot down an army helicopter over the
weekend, killing five officers. Fujimori promised to ``annihilate''
all the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: STRIKE LEADER TELLS OF BEATING
</P>
<P>
   A leader of the students who have maintained a strike since
April at the National Autonomous University of Mexico said he was
abducted for five hours and beaten by 15 unidentified assailants.
Alejandro Echevarria Zarco heads a student faction called the
megaultras for their staunch opposition to lifting the shutdown of
Latin America's largest university.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
