u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-BRAVES-NYT     10-06 0908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-BRAVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILLWOOD IS BRAVES' ONE-HIT WONDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ With the Atlanta Braves facing a crucial situation,
Kevin Millwood pitched a dominant game.
</P>
<P>
   Throwing a complete game one-hitter, and overpowering the
Houston Astros with a nearly flawless performance, Millwood led the
Braves to a 5-1 victory Wednesday afternoon in Game 2 of their
National League division series at Turner Field. The
three-of-five-game series is tied, 1-1, as the scene shifts to
Houston for games Friday and Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   After playing poorly in a 6-1 loss in Game 1, the Braves needed
a lift, and Millwood delivered the finest pitching performance of
his career. The one-hitter was the fewest hits allowed in a
post-season complete game since 1967, when Jim Lonborg of the
Boston Red Sox threw a complete-game one-hitter against the St.
Louis Cardinals in the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   How good was Millwood? At one point, he retired 15 consecutive
batters. He didn't walk anyone. And Houston never got a runner to
second base after the second.
</P>
<P>
   It was a big-time performance, and it reinforced how important
Millwood has become to Atlanta's pitching staff. The Braves have
three Cy Young award winners in their rotation _ Greg Maddux, Tom
Glavine and John Smoltz. But this year, Millwood was Atlanta's most
consistent starter (18-7 with a 2.68 earned run average), and
Wednesday, he was almost untouchable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've pitched a one-hitter before, but it was the biggest game
I've pitched in, so I would have to say it was my best performance
ever,'' said Millwood, a 24-year-old right-hander who had eight
strikeouts. ``About the second or third inning, I threw a few
sliders and a couple of curves and I had good control. I knew if I
threw the right pitch and kept them guessing, it was going to be a
pretty good game.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston's only run came on a second-inning home run by Ken
Caminiti. Millwood retired the next 15 batters, and the only other
Astro to reach base was Jeff Bagwell, who was safe on a
seventh-inning error by third baseman Chipper Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Braves pecked away at the starting and losing
pitcher Jose Lima, who was 21-10 in the regular season. They scored
single runs in the first and sixth innings, then broke the game
open with three runs in the seventh when they chased Lima, then
beat up on reliever Scott Elarton.
</P>
<P>
   This looked more like the Atlanta team that went 103-59 during
the regular season, and while the Astros were happy to leave
Atlanta with a split, they had seen more than enough of Millwood.
</P>
<P>
   ``A stronger game has not been pitched against us all year
long,'' said Houston manager Larry Dierker. ``He spotted his fast
ball, he threw hard, and he has a curveball to finish you off. We
really only hit two balls hard the whole game.''
</P>
<P>
   Leading by 2-1, Atlanta scored three runs in the eighth inning.
Bret Boone started the rally with one out when he nearly hit a home
run to left field. When left fielder Daryle Ward misplayed the
carom off the wall, Boone went to third base on the error. Jones
was intentionally walked, then Brian Jordan sent Carl Everett to
the warning track in center field for a sacrifice fly that scored
Boone, while Jones went to second. At that point, Dierker had seen
enough of Lima, who was relieved by Elarton. But instead of
subduing the Braves, Elarton was hammered. Ryan Klesko stroked a
single to left field that scored Jones, then Andruw Jones hit a
single that scored Klesko.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves went ahead, 2-1, in the sixth inning, as Jones
snapped an &QC; 0-for-20 slump in division series play. With one out,
Klesko singled, then Jones hit a sharp grounder toward third base
that scooted under Caminiti's glove into left field. Ward charged
the ball in left field, hoping to prevent Klesko from going to
third base. But Ward slipped, and not only did Klesko reach third,
but Jones went to second. It was ruled a double for Jones, then
Eddie Perez delivered a sacrifice fly to center field that scored
Klesko.
</P>
<P>
   It was important for the Braves to start well, and they did,
jumping out to a 1-0 first-inning lead on an RBI single by Jordan,
who was 1 for 3 with 2 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   A lineup change by Braves manager Bobby Cox paid immediate
dividends, as Cox moved Jordan from fifth to the cleanup spot
behind Chipper Jones. In Game 1, Klesko was 0 for 4 as the cleanup
hitter, as the Astros pitched around Chipper Jones and attacked
Klesko. As Cox hoped, Jordan gave Chipper Jones better protection,
and Jordan was inspired by hitting cleanup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I accept challenges,'' Jordan said. ``When the other team said
they were going to pitch around Chipper, I took that as an insult.
It's a slap in the face. They walked Chipper to get to me, and I
hurt them.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's 1-0 lead was short-lived, as Caminiti tied the game
with a rocket that reached the stands in a hurry. But after that,
Houston's bats were silent while Millwood and the Braves took
command.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH
</P>
<P>
   The Braves asked umpire BRUCE FROEMMING to check JOSE LIMA's
pants for pine tar before Atlanta batted in the first inning.
Lima's pants were checked, and he was allowed to pitch. ``If I put
pine tar in my pants, nobody is going to beat me,'' Lima said. ``I
don't have to cheat to win ball games. I'm not going to be stupid
enough to have pine tar on my pants. This is not the time to be
suspended.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
