<SLUG> BC-FBN-HOUSTON07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Houston beats L.A. for expansion team
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Its offer buoyed by a record $700 million franchise
fee, Houston rejoined the NFL on Wednesday. The surprising decision
means Los Angeles, the nation's second-largest television market,
will remain without professional football for now.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL's expansion committee, meeting in Atlanta, voted 14-0 on
Wednesday morning to recommend Houston.
</P>
<P>
   It took the full membership of 31 owners less than an hour to
approve Houston unanimously, 29-0, with Arizona and St. Louis
abstaining. Twenty-four votes were needed for approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly it goes beyond reason and it's much more than I
anticipated paying when I first entered into this process,'' said
Bob McNair, the majority owner of the Houston group. ``But we knew
we had to differentiate ourselves (from Los Angeles) and that's
what we attempted to do. We wanted to make certain everyone knew
that we had an outstanding proposal.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston, which lost the Oilers to Nashville after the 1996
season, will begin play in the American Football Conference in
2002, when the league will be realigned into eight divisions of
four teams each. One existing team in the AFC will move to the NFC
under the new plan.
</P>
<P>
   McNair earlier reached an agreement with the Houston Livestock
Show and Rodeo and the Harris County-Houston Sports Authority to
build a $310 million, 70,000-seat stadium, which will be the first
football-only venue with a retractable roof. Government funding of
$195 million will help pay for the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our facility will be second to none,'' McNair said.
</P>
<P>
   Two groups from Los Angeles, which lost the Raiders to Oakland
and the Rams to St. Louis after the 1994 season, made proposals for
the franchise. But neither offer was anywhere close to the one
McNair put on the table.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood super agent Michael Ovitz, whose group included actor
Tom Cruise, offered a franchise fee of $400 million with another
$150 million in deferred payments. Ovitz most recently proposed
building a stadium at Hollywood Park in Inglewood, Calif., but
there were concerns about access to freeways.
</P>
<P>
   Real estate mogul Ed Roski sought a team for the Los Angeles
Coliseum, but the venue's age and lack of parking were worries.
Also, neither L.A. group could guarantee public funding for
construction or renovation of a venue.
</P>
<P>
   ``The consensus with both (potential sites) in Los Angeles was
that there was still quite a distance to travel to have things
completed,'' NFL commissioner Paul Tagliabue said. ``There were
concerns about the stadiums there being state of the art and about
guaranteeing the success of the franchise in terms of fan support
and sellouts.''
</P>
<P>
   The Houston deal also means $5 million more for each of the 31
NFL owners, who split franchise fees annually.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a financial windfall,'' Dallas Cowboys owner Jerry
Jones said. ``You're splitting everything between 32 teams now.
Houston had to move the owners' eyes off of what was perceived as
the No. 1 goal _ to address the No. 2 television market. They did
that and that's pretty impressive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the difference between Houston and Los Angeles is that
(Houston) was there. It was done, as opposed to `a chance' or
`maybe' (in L.A.).''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
