<SLUG> BC-FBN-NAME-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW FRANCHISE NEEDS A NAME 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DAVID BARRON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ With the suspense of which city gets the 32nd NFL
franchise out of the way, now comes another intriguing question:
What will be the name of the new Houston pro football team?
</P>
<P>
   One thing is for certain: Oilers is not a possibility. That name
was retired by NFL Commissioner Paul Tagliabue as part of his
agreement with Bud Adams to change the team's name to Tennessee
Titans after the Houston Oilers moved to Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   Given the NFL's stance in such matters, don't expect a reprise
of Houston's other pro football team of recent vintage, the Houston
Gamblers of the USFL.
</P>
<P>
   Other than those names, everything appears to be in play. Steve
Patterson, owner Bob McNair's point man on the expansion project,
said Wednesday that about 20 to 25 names have been registered and
are under consideration.
</P>
<P>
   Among those, according to a search through Network Solutions, a
Virginia company that assists companies in registering Internet
domain names, are:
</P>
<P>
   _ Roughnecks (a throwback to the city's Oilers roots, but an
obvious target for headline writers who couldn't turn down the
chance to refer to the Houston 'Necks).
</P>
<P>
   _ Roughriders (Teddy Roosevelt, after all, did count Texas among
his recruiting spots during the Spanish-American War).
</P>
<P>
   _ Wranglers (a nod to the Old West, but is it too close to
Cowboys for comfort?)
</P>
<P>
   _ Toros (short, punchy, perfect for headline writers, with more
than a passing nod to the city's Hispanic heritage).
</P>
<P>
   _ Texans (an obvious choice, but it already was used by the
Dallas Texans, now the Kansas City Chiefs, and Houston fans might
prefer something more city-specific).
</P>
<P>
   _ Texians (now you're going way back to the name used for Anglo
inhabitants of the state in the early 19th century, when Texas was
a part of Mexico. Could it possibly fly with NFL Properties? How do
you market a Texian?)
</P>
<P>
   _ Hurricanes (another obvious choice, but why tempt fate?)
</P>
<P>
   _ Roustabouts (and you thought Elvis had left the building).
</P>
<P>
   There will, of course, be more to come. Team officials plan to
launch a new Web site, www.houston2002.com, and that site may
contain information about how the team will get its name.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
