<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-NO-DOUBLE-PARKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOUBLE-PARKING ENDS AS A NEW YORK RIGHT  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By WINNIE HU   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It has long been part of New York's social contract:
car owners who must struggle with the city's byzantine parking
rules are permitted _ wink, wink, nudge, nudge _ to double-park
while one side of a residential street is being cleaned, and police
officers are not pressed into issuing them tickets.
</P>
<P>
   But now, in the Giuliani administration's zeal to unclog the
streets, the Police Department no longer seems willing to look the
other way. From narrow drives to broad avenues, many alternate-side
parkers were surprised, and in some cases, infuriated this week to
find tickets stuck to their windshields.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so blown away,'' said Laura Juszczak, a medical
researcher who retrieved a $55 ticket from her dark blue Toyota
Camry at 8:30 a.m. Tuesday, 30 minutes after her husband had left
their car double-parked on West 101st Street to clear the way for
street cleaning on the other side.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was this general understanding that you would be allowed
to move over because of the pressing parking situation in the
city,'' she said. ``This is our home and I think it shows a general
disdain for us and a mean-spiritedness.''
</P>
<P>
   The frustration of owning a car in New York City is a given,
particularly in Manhattan, where there are only about 30,000 legal
curbside parking spaces for the hundreds of thousands of vehicles
that use its streets daily. Desperate drivers have long relied on
the city's tacit acknowledgment that there are few alternatives for
those vehicles displaced every other day for up to three hours to
allow street cleaning.
</P>
<P>
   But just as it was when the Giuliani administration declared
that another seemingly inalienable New York right _ jaywalking _
had no place on the city's streets, so now is the city enforcing
the longstanding, but long ignored, ban on double-parking.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the Police Department started an aggressive
campaign, known as Operation Move Along, that focuses on commercial
areas.
</P>
<P>
   The first day of the campaign resulted in 8,288 tickets for
traffic offenses, including 2,230 tickets for doubled-parked cars
and 1,003 for double-parked trucks, said Officer Carmen Melendez, a
police spokeswoman. Fines start at $55 for illegal parking and run
up to $280 if the police place a clamp on a tire and tow the
vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, some police officials acknowledged that ticketing or
towing was not always the bottom line. James Savage, a former
president of the police officers' union, the Patrolmen's Benevolent
Association, said it was long accepted that officers should ignore
double-parking violations during street cleaning.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was always an unwritten violation,'' he said. ``You just
knew _ for practical reasons _ you let people double-park on those
days.''
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Mode, the chief spokeswoman for the Police Department,
said that double-parking on a residential street has always been
illegal, and that any driver who does it runs the risk of getting a
ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cars still have to get up and down those streets, and
ambulances and fire trucks,'' she said. ``This is a safety issue.
This is a logistical issue.''
</P>
<P>
   For some, the crackdown on double-parking was long overdue.
Allison Baker, a personal trainer, said that she has often been
blocked in by double-parked cars. One time, she even tried to call
the police herself after waiting half an hour for another driver to
move out of the way.
</P>
<P>
   John Kaehny, executive director of Transportation Alternatives,
a group that wants to reduce car use in the city, said drivers
should realize that they cannot always park free in a place like
New York City. ``There is no such thing as a free lunch and that's
what motorists parking in the street are trying to get,'' said
Kaehny, who pedals his bike to work. ``It should have been enforced
a long time ago.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
