<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 22:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9046 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-NORWOOD-PROFILE-ART-N     10-06 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NORWOOD-PROFILE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A REBELLIOUS TEAM PLAYER: CHARLES WHITLOW NORWOOD JR. 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga.) (See also CONGRESS-HEALTH) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
may make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ ``I've got a lot of professional memory,'' Rep.
Charlie Norwood said Wednesday afternoon, reflecting on his
experience with managed care companies in the years he practiced
dentistry in Augusta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know how they deny care,'' he went on, leaning against a
wall near the House floor, sweating through his shirt after hours
of debating and arm-twisting on behalf of his bill that would
establish more stringent standards for insurers and health
maintenance organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they wanted was always the cheapest care, not the best
care,'' he said. ``It drove me crazy, but I wouldn't just let them
say `no' when my patients needed something. I'd fight them.''
</P>
<P>
   It was this experience that led Norwood, a 58-year-old
Republican who is otherwise devoted to his party's principles and
its leaders, to form an alliance with Democrats on the issue of
regulating the managed care industry. His legislation is scheduled
to be voted on in the House of Representatives on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of managed-care restraints had nothing to do with his
decision in 1994 to sell his dental practice and run for Congress,
he said. Quite the contrary, Norwood said, it was his concern over
the way the government was becoming ever bigger. ``I believe in a
smaller federal government,'' he said, ``more freedom, lower
taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   In his dental practice, he said, he had found Medicaid
regulations ``awesome and absolutely nuts'' and the rules imposed
on his office by the Occupational Safety and Health Administration
nightmarish.
</P>
<P>
   In the health area, Norwood's main concern was President
Clinton's plan for universal health insurance, a plan that he
thought would be disastrous because it envisioned limiting
patients' choice of doctors and doctors' choice of treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Norwood defeated an incumbent Democrat in a district of small
towns and rural areas in eastern Georgia and came to Washington as
an acolyte of Newt Gingrich and a loyal foot soldier in the
Republican revolution.
</P>
<P>
   It was an entirely new career after 25 years of practicing
dentistry.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Whitlow Norwood Jr. was born July 27, 1941, in Valdosta,
Ga., near the Florida border. After graduating from Georgia
Southern University and the Georgetown University dental school, he
spent two years as a dentist in the Army, including a year in
Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Out of the Army, he set up dental practice in Augusta and became
active in the Georgia Dental Association, including a term as
president.
</P>
<P>
   He and his wife, Gloria, have two grown sons.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the aggressive class of Republicans who won control of
the House in the 1994 election, he was close to Gingrich and a
staunch supporter of the Contract With America, then the party's
manifesto. Through Gingrich's influence, he was given a seat on the
Commerce Committee, one of the most influential panels in Congress
and one that has jurisdiction over the regulation of health
insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   In his second term, Norwood made it clear that he had a mission
to put some restraints on health maintenance organizations. Working
with Democrats and some dissident Republicans, he assembled 230
sponsors, more than half the members of the House, for legislation
to allow patients injured by the denial of their claims to sue
health plans in state court with no limits on damages that could be
collected for lost wages or medical expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders were vigorously opposed to the measure, and
they put Norwood on a working group headed by Rep. Dennis Hastert
of Illinois, then the chief deputy Republican whip and now the
speaker, to see whether a compromise could be worked out.
</P>
<P>
   The group came up with a bill that did not allow the right to
sue but did put other restrictions on health plans. In the spirit
of party unity, Norwood went along. The bill was passed by the
House on a party-line vote but died in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Norwood decided not to compromise. The ability to sue
insurers was important to keep them in line, he decided. ``Why do
they need immunity anyway unless they are denying benefits?''
Norwood asked Wednesday. ``Why should this industry be the only
industry in America that has a shield of immunity.''
</P>
<P>
   It has not been easy to take on his leaders, he said. Recently,
he has spent his evenings at home watching war movies to build up
his gumption.
</P>
<P>
   Did he expect repercussions from his disloyalty?
</P>
<P>
   ``I imagine they'll put some logs in the road for me,'' he said
of the party's leaders. ``They can't let me off scot-free.''
</P>
<P>
   But overall, the matter has been a boon to him politically, he
said. ``I may never have anybody ever run against me again,'' he
said with a laugh. ``The people in the 10th District of Georgia are
very pleased with what I'm doing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-99 2250EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
