<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991006.0473 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 22:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9047 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-MUSEUM-DISPUTE-NYT     10-06 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MUSEUM-DISPUTE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROOKLYN MUSEUM RECEIVES SUPPORT IN LEGAL BATTLE WITH MAYOR  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By KIT R. ROANE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani and the Brooklyn Museum
of Art prepare for a hearing in U.S. District Court Friday, a surge
of support for the museum's legal position has begun to emerge,
some of it from institutions queasy about the art at the center of
the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Most prominent among the institutions that have come out in
support of the museum, though not necessarily of the controversial
exhibition that has sparked the dispute, was the Metropolitan
Museum of Art. Its director, Philippe de Montebello, said in an
Op-Ed article in The New York Times on Tuesday that he regretted
``that the mayor has given undue notoriety to artists who deserve
to remain obscure or be forgotten.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, the museum joined a half-dozen other cultural
institutions in a friend of the court brief filed in support of the
Brooklyn Museum, which has been embroiled in a bitter battle with
Giuliani over the exhibition ``Sensation,'' because it includes a
painting of the Virgin Mary spattered with elephant dung. Giuliani
has denounced the art as ``sick stuff.'' The museum has sued to
prevent the mayor from withholding city funds from it because of
the exhibit.
</P>
<P>
   Also joining in the legal battle in support of the museum
Wednesday was the City Council speaker, Peter F. Vallone, a
Catholic who has said that the art was ``offensive.'' Valone's
office said that he would join in another friend of the court brief
expected to be filed Thursday by Public Advocate Mark Green.
</P>
<P>
   Vallone and officials of the Metropolitan Museum were among
dozens of individuals and groups that have given legal support the
museum. But unlike many of them, they have also found Giuliani's
dislike of the art at least tenable.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Clendenin, a spokesman for Vallone, said that while the
speaker ``finds the art very offensive, we fund cultural
institutions with the knowledge that they can make decisions that
people find offensive.'' He said the mayor was in violation of the
city charter by trying to pull the city's funding of the museum.
``I'm sure that libraries have many books that are offensive,'' he
added, ``but we are not about to burn books or close libraries.''
</P>
<P>
   Harold Holzer, a spokesman for the Metropolitan Museum of Art,
said that his museum's support was ``very limited.'' He said that
it was based on First Amendment grounds and only addressed the
belief that the mayor could not cut funds to the Brooklyn Museum
because he did not like the artwork that it showed. He also noted
that Montebello, paraphrasing Voltaire, said in The Times article
that ``so much as I may disagree with some of the exhibitions they
may mount, I will defend to the death their right to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's office did not respond to several calls seeking
comment on the court briefs.
</P>
<P>
   The museum has filed a federal lawsuit against the city and the
mayor asserting that by withholding its city funding. Giuliani is
violating its First Amendment right to artistic expression.
</P>
<P>
   The city has announced its intention to cut off $7.2 million in
funding that it provides the museum each year. It has also gone to
state court seeking to terminate the museum's lease and to take
control of its board, saying that taxpayers should not have to pay
for offensive exhibits.
</P>
<P>
   Floyd Abrams, the lawyer who is representing the museum in its
federal suit against the city, said that the support from other
cultural institutions demonstrated that ``the arts community, the
literary community, the museum community and much of the city as a
whole are coalescing around a single theme: no mayor may be
permitted to serve as the censor of what the public may see.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the mayor said he would also cut off city funding to
any other publicly financed cultural institution in the city that
mounts an exhibit that he considers an attack on religion.
</P>
<P>
   The idea that the mayor might broaden his sights or that some
other politician may attempt similar measures has also frightened
many of them, said Victor A. Kovner, the former city corporation
counsel under Mayor David N. Dinkins, who filed the brief joined by
the Metropolitan Museum of Art.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the mayor can do this to the Brooklyn Museum, there is a
question of what he will do to others,'' he explained. ``So this is
an ominous threat to everybody.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-99 2251EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
