<HEADER>
A9059 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBA-RANGERS-YANKEES-H     10-06 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-YANKEES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DANNY ROBBINS  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
NEW YORK _ The New York Yankees held a light workout Wednesday. The
Texas Rangers, ensconced in their hotel, took the day off.
Hopefully, no one in the team's traveling party purchased the
Triborough Bridge.
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the Yankees-Rangers American League Division Series resumes
with Game 2 tonight at Yankee Stadium, the Rangers will be forced
to define their future.
</P>
<P>
   Having absorbed an 8-0 drubbing in Game 1 on Tuesday, the
Rangers must win tonight or face the prospect of beating Roger
Clemens and David Cone in Texas over the weekend to force a
decisive fifth game.
</P>
<P>
   Having lost seven consecutive playoff games to the Yankees and
having scored only one run in the last four, the Rangers must win
simply to cast out some growing demons, to overcome what general
manager Doug Melvin calls ``this hump'' of losing to the Yankees in
the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal, without looking at other teams, is to win the World
Series,'' Melvin said Wednesday, trying to make sense of what has
happened in the last four years to the team he has put together.
``We feel this is the best chance we've had. This is the best team
we've had. We still think we have the team that can do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you have to win a (playoff) series before you can think of
the World Series. We all know what we have to do. It's just been
that the Yankees have made it difficult for us.''
</P>
<P>
   All the talk of how this could be the Rangers' year, of how they
had improved and how the Yankees had come back to the pack after
lapping the field in 1998, melted away Tuesday as Texas'
high-powered offense returned to its postseason funk of a year ago.
Ivan Rodriguez's two hits, a double in the first inning and a
single in the third, were all the Rangers could muster against
Yankees starter Orlando Hernandez, who went eight innings, and Jeff
Nelson, who pitched the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's series started in similar fashion, with David Wells
throwing eight shutout innings and giving up only five hits, and
ended in a Yankees sweep.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have confidence in your ballclub,'' Rangers left fielder
Rusty Greer said. ``We wouldn't have won 95 games if we didn't have
confidence. We have to regroup, obviously. Thursday becomes a
must-win game for us. The hill got a little steep. If we don't
produce Thursday, it becomes even steeper.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers will try to get untracked against Yankees lefthander
Andy Pettitte, who ended the regular season considerably stronger
than he started it. After going 5-7 with a 5.59 ERA in his first 16
starts, Pettitte finished 9-4 with a 3.84 in his last 15,
improvement some attribute to the fact he was the subject of
well-publicized trade rumors.
</P>
<P>
   The Game 2 starter for Texas will be Rick Helling, who won 13
games but gave up a major-league-leading 41 home runs, including 13
in September.
</P>
<P>
   Helling said he would feel no extra pressure as a result of his
team's lack of offensive production in Game 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have complete faith in our offense,'' he said. ``You look at
what we've done over the last two years offensively, we're one of
the best offensive teams in baseball. Our offense is capable of
scoring 10 runs a game if we start swinging the bats the way we
can.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody will tell you if you put yourself in position to
have success, eventually it's going to happen. `El Duque'
(Hernandez) threw a great game. We had chances early to score runs
and just couldn't get that big hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our team has traditionally gotten that big hit when we needed
it, and eventually it's going to happen. I have a ton of faith in
our offense. It doesn't put pressure on me. I'm trying to throw
zeros on the board anyway. I don't worry about the offense. More
times than not, they're going to score runs for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers did have their share of tough outs Tuesday, the most
dramatic being Yankees center fielder Bernie Williams' play on Juan
Gonzalez's drive to the gap in right-center with runners on first
and second and one out in the third inning. At that point, the
Yankees had only a 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a very good ballclub, and we'll break out of it
somewhere along the line here,'' Melvin said. ``I just hope it's
sooner rather than later.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt they (players) think about it. But this is
just too good a lineup, too many good offensive players, to go out
there and not give it a good run.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to give credit to the Yankees, too. Their pitchers
are very good. And, you know, if Juan's ball is dropped _ Bernie
doesn't make a great catch _ that ball Rafael (Palmeiro) hit goes
into the corner (instead of being caught by Yankees first baseman
Tino Martinez), it's a different ballgame. They made two great
defensive plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``We focused on each game during the regular season. We didn't
get too up or too down after losses. We have to continue to have
the same approach.''
</P>
<P>
   Now in his sixth year as general manager, Melvin has seen a
franchise that never had appeared in the playoffs suddenly become
one that, unless events change swiftly, could be known for getting
there and falling apart at the sight of pinstripes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know we went through a couple of years where we couldn't
beat the Mariners, and I think we put that behind us,'' Melvin
said. ``We went through not playing well in the Texas heat. We were
going to blow the chance to be in the postseason (because of the
heat). So this is just another hurdle. It's a big hurdle, the
Yankees are, but I think we can overcome it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-99 2258EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
