<HEADER>
A9180 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-PROFILE-HNS &LR;      10-06 1387
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PROFILE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
`NICE GUY' FINISHES FIRST AS McNAIR AWARDED NFL TEAM 
 
By JOHN WILLIAMS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A 23-year-old Robert Cary McNair came to Houston from
South Carolina in 1960 with a psychology degree, a wife and two
children, $700 in the bank and the promise of $3,000 loan to get
started in an auto-leasing business.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, McNair agreed to pay the National Football League
one million times what his net worth was 39 years ago to became
owner of the league's 32nd franchise.
</P>
<P>
   In between was a business career that has led McNair from one
industry to another, through a bankruptcy court that left him with
about $500,000 in 1983, and onto this year's list in Forbes
Magazine of the 400 richest Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The American dream has come true for McNair, the son of
working-class parents who was the first in his immediate family to
graduate from college.
</P>
<P>
   Now 62, McNair wants to leave a legacy in his adopted home town.
That includes a winning team playing in a state-of-the-art stadium,
the site of many future Super Bowls.
</P>
<P>
   After paying $700 million for the franchise, McNair doesn't
expect it will earn any returns for himself and others in his
ownership group for ``many, many years.'' But it will provide what
he calls ``an emotional equity.``
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like Houston is a special city,'' he said. ``I came
here when I was 23 and had $700 in the bank. I was just impressed
with the fact that the people who had capital in Houston didn't
just sit on it and keep it to themselves. They kept reinvesting in
people like me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a beneficiary of that environment, and I'm glad now to be
able to reinvest in my community and, hopefully, improve it for
everybody,'' he said. ``If it weren't for a strong sense of civic
pride, I would not be doing this.``
</P>
<P>
   Those associated with McNair _ a man known for honoring
handshake deals and a stout Presbyterian who donates millions of
dollars annually to charity _ say the words ring true.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really is a nice guy who finishes first,'' said Chuck
Watson, owner of the Houston Aeros minor league hockey team. Watson
is expected to buy about 15 percent of the new football team.
</P>
<P>
   Even his opponents in the NFL bidding war speak highly of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here I am, trying to get the same team McNair wants, trying to
do my best to better him, and damned if I'm not saying to myself,
`Gee, this is really a good guy,''' said Los Angeles developer Ed
Roski.
</P>
<P>
   McNair was born in Tampa, Fla., into a family that moved all
around the South as his father slowly worked up the ladder of the
Sunshine Biscuit Co.
</P>
<P>
   He recalls fond childhood memories, including playing in the
restaurant his maternal grandfather owned across the street from
the Have-A-Tampa cigar company, a venue for dice and card games.
</P>
<P>
   His interest in sports was displayed early, when he played
football, basketball and baseball in high school. He also played on
the University of South Carolina's junior varsity basketball squad,
but quit ``because I had nothing else to prove.''
</P>
<P>
   He also had to work his way through college in various sales
jobs. After graduation, McNair went to work for a fellow South
Carolina graduate and Sigma Chi fraternity brother in an auto
leasing company. The business fell flat after about five months,
leaving McNair out of a job.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, he was offered a $3,000 loan to move to Houston and
start what eventually because Executive Auto Leasing.
</P>
<P>
   A quick learner, he put the business on a sound financial
footing, then spent the next 20 years building it, selling it,
using the equity to form a bigger one and starting the process all
over again. Ownership of an auto-leasing company became ownership
of an equipment leasing company, which became ownership of a
trucking company.
</P>
<P>
   But trucking deregulation slowed McNair's steady rise, forced
him into Chapter 11 reorganization bankruptcy. One of his companies
that leased trucking equipment owed $10 million it could not
immediately pay.
</P>
<P>
   He eventually repaid all creditors 100 cents on the dollar, and
accumulated enough personal assets ``to last my family about three
years.'' By then, he and his wife, Janice, had four children.
</P>
<P>
   McNair began looking at other industries, especially ones that
would let him take advantage of the lessons he had learned through
the deregulation of trucking. Borrowing more money, he formed a
Cypress Telecommunications, a long-distance telephone carrier.
</P>
<P>
   His big coup was taking advantage of the impending deregulation
of electricity. In the early 1980s, amid rising oil prices, power
companies and large power users were looking for ways to save
money.
</P>
<P>
   In response, McNair founded Cogen Technologies, which helps
companies save by employing ``cogeneration'' plants. For example, a
power plant that burns oil to create electricity can recapture the
heat generated from that process to create steam, another form of
energy, which also can be used to generate electricity.
</P>
<P>
   Quickly, McNair's business took off. Earlier this year, Cogen
sold most of its assets to Enron Corp. for $1.4 billion, partly so
McNair could pursue his dream of owning a pro football team.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is someone who really does go after his dreams,'' said
Enron Chairman Ken Lay, who has known McNair for almost two
decades. ``He is very smart and very capable, and when he sets his
sights on things, he gets it done.``
</P>
<P>
   Always consumed with sports of all kinds, McNair had spent years
trying to get an NFL team and a National Hockey League team. He
bought a stable five years ago, and his horses have won major
races. He owned part of Touch Gold, which the 1997 Belmont Stakes,
and Strodes Creek, which placed second in the Kentucky Derby. He
also shares a 75-foot sailing yacht with former U.S. Commerce
Secretary Bob Mosbacher.
</P>
<P>
   Lay noted another McNair trait, one he and others believe helped
him negotiate with the NFL for two years despite the league's
obvious desire to put the expansion team in Los Angeles:
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't get mad.
</P>
<P>
   Several people who were close to McNair over the last two years
said he rarely even raised his voice about the frustrating
negotiations. He views obstacles as challenges, not reasons for
quitting.
</P>
<P>
   And he did not make a wrong step during the arduous NFL
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has to have a big ego because people don't do what he has
done without one,'' Lay said. ``But he doesn't let his ego get in
the way of what he wants to do.``
</P>
<P>
   Watson said he first began talking with McNair about getting a
football team at the urging of San Diego Padres baseball team owner
John Moores. At the time, Moores was just giving up hope of getting
another NFL team for Houston, a venture that included Watson.
Moores thought McNair might be the best person to move forward with
the effort, Watson said.
</P>
<P>
   Watson and McNair had their first conversation about the NFL at
the River Oaks Country Club in Houston, where McNair is a member.
</P>
<P>
   ``During our golf game, we talked about our philosophies toward
sports,'' Watson said. ``We both agreed that we wanted to enhance
Houston's image around the country. We'd never hire anyone who
might damage the city's image.``
</P>
<P>
   They have worked together to get an NFL team, though Watson's
role has diminished as his duties as CEO of Dynegy have increased
over the last two years due to the company's growth spurt. Over
time, Watson's stake in an NFL team has dropped from a 50-50 split,
when the expansion fee under consideration was $400 million, to 10
percent to 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob and I have had nothing in writing, it's all been in a
handshake'' Watson said. ``It drives our attorneys a little nuts,
but he is a person you can trust.``
</P>
<P>
   McNair has said he will not run the team, leaving that to
top-notch coaches and administrators.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job is to make sure they perform,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A member of Memorial Drive Presbyterian Church, McNair views his
good fortune with humility.
</P>
<P>
   ``My whole view about my money is that we're all stewards in
this world,'' McNair said. ``I don't own anything, I'm just a
steward. Everything belongs to the good Lord. I'm only going to be
here a short period, so I'm just stewarding those assets.``
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
