<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    All Millwood, all even
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If one game could capture what Kevin Millwood has been
all about this season, Wednesday afternoon's Game 2 of the Division
Series wraps it up. And it's why the Braves are still alive and
well, having gained a split with the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   With their backs to the wall and desperate for a win in this
best-of-five series, the Braves turned to their 24-year-old alleged
fourth starter with the nasty repertoire and crowned him a
postseason hero.
</P>
<P>
   Millwood pitched only the fifth one-hitter in postseason history
for a 5-1 victory in the first playoff start of his life. Well,
actually the second.
</P>
<P>
   There was that playoff appearance he made for the Class A Durham
Bulls in 1996. He pitched eight shutout innings then, which should
come as no surprise now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew today would tell me whether I've got it,'' said
Millwood, who made last year's playoff roster but didn't pitch.
``It's good to go out and pitch well.''
</P>
<P>
   Facing the possibility of yet another Braves postseason coming
to a premature close, the calm and collected Millwood needed to be
perfect. And he almost was.
</P>
<P>
   If not for a two-strike fastball in the second inning to Ken
Caminiti, who homered for the second time in the series, and an
error by Chipper Jones on a Jeff Bagwell grounder in the seventh,
no Astro would have touched base. Two of Millwood's 105 pitches
were hit hard _ Caminiti's and a Stan Javier line drive, which Bret
Boone safely snared for the game's final out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that start was probably the most dominant postseason
start I've ever seen,'' Chipper Jones said. ``Tommy Glavine in Game
6 in the World Series in 1995 was awfully dominant. If it's
possible, I think Millwood was more dominant.''
</P>
<P>
   With Millwood in control, the Braves finally loosened up
offensively. Brian Jordan was back in the cleanup spot and drove in
two of the Braves' four runs off Jose Lima. Ryan Klesko, seeking
redemption for his bases-loaded strikeout in Game 1, came through
with three hits.
</P>
<P>
   And Andruw Jones recovered from a pair of weak at-bats to give
the Braves their first extra-base hit of the series and a giant
offensive lift with his double in the sixth inning. Jones ripped an
0-1 Lima pitch off Caminiti's glove to set up an Eddie Perez
sacrifice fly for a 2-1 lead. The Braves added three runs in the
seventh on consecutive RBIs by Jordan, Klesko and Andruw Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to show them the Braves are not going to roll
over,'' Jordan said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
