<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-POLE07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bobby Labonte on Charlotte pole
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE, N.C. _ Bobby Labonte really can't explain it, neither
can crew chief Jimmy Makar.
</P>
<P>
   For some unknown reason, the Pontiac No. 18 driver has
flourished during qualifying at Lowe's Motor Speedway in Charlotte
this year. Labonte captured the pole position Wednesday night for
the UAW-GM Quality 500 on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   It is the second Charlotte race in a row that Labonte will be
the pole-sitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I have a secret... The No. 18 car (of Joe
Gibbs Racing) seems to always do good at Charlotte throughout its
history,'' said Makar. ``We've just been able to come up with a
(car setup) that likes this place and hits on a regular basis.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Labonte, ``I think Jimmy Makar is a big key. He always
seems to have same setup for this track, and we've always done
good.''
</P>
<P>
   Labonte, who is second behind Dale Jarrett in the Winston Cup
points standings, won the pole with a speed of 185.682 mph. He will
share the front row with Rusty Wallace, who is still one shy of his
50th career victory.
</P>
<P>
   John Andretti, Mark Martin and Tony Stewart round out the top
five.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is the fourth time I've been third-fastest here,
so obviously I'm no better than third-best when it comes to
qualifying here,'' Andretti said with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Burton was the biggest surprise in first-round qualifying,
but not in a positive way. Burton was last at 50th in qualifying
after the No. 99 Ford slid sideways on the first turn of the lap.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no way of saying (exactly what happened),'' Burton
said. ``I'm real disappointed with the run, but I am proud I didn't
wreck it. I did a good job of not wrecking it, but it's a shame
(because) we'll have to start (the race) in the back of the pack
and we had a fast car today.''
</P>
<P>
   Labonte won the pole at the Coca-Cola 600 in May and finished
runner-up to Burton in the race. Labonte also started No. 1 in The
Winston, an exhibition at Charlotte between many of the top
drivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the track and I won my first race here,'' Labonte said.
``Nobody can ever take that away from me. I guess I have a special
place in my heart for it. I always have liked coming here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it's a combination of things. Everything works out
good and I've got a good confidence level going into qualifying,
race day or practice, whatever the case may be.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
