<SLUG> BC-COLLEGES-FUNDRAISING-700&AMP;ADD(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DONATIONS TO COLLEGES SWELL AS HARVARD LEADS THE PACK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)  (js) 
 By JACQUES STEINBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Universities don't usually set fund-raising goals that they
can't meet, but when Harvard decided in 1992 that it would try to
raise $2.1 billion by Dec. 31, 1999, the task seemed herculean: The
university would have to collect an average of nearly $1 million a
day for seven years.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, the Harvard president, Neil L. Rudenstine, informed a
gathering of alumni at the Harvard Club in Manhattan that the
university had not only reached its target but had exceeded it,
raising $2.3 billion _ with three months still remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Though no U.S. college or university has ever raised as much in
a similar period _ Yale and Columbia, believed to be the closest
competitors, each raised $1.7 billion over seven years in the 1990s
_ Harvard's experience is only the most dramatic example of a
larger trend: Donations to institutions of higher education are
swelling beyond even the grandest expectations, thanks in part to a
booming economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Donors are much more willing to talk,'' said Will Melton, the
vice president for external affairs at Middlebury College in
Vermont, which has raised all but $57 million of the $200 million
it hopes to collect from October 1997 to June 2001. ``They are not
reluctant to talk about their wealth and success, and they want to
share it with the institutions that mean something to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the golden age of philanthropy, and Harvard rode the
market climb perfectly.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvard collected $462.7 million in gifts last year, an increase
of 124 percent over the $206.2 million in donations that it
recorded in 1992, the end of the most recent recession.
</P>
<P>
   Over the same period, annual contributions rose 152 percent at
Princeton; 141 percent at Columbia, and 68 percent at Stanford,
according to figures from the Council for Aid to Education, a
nonprofit organization that tracks contributions to colleges and
universities.
</P>
<P>
   While, in general, the number of donors to each institution did
not increase appreciably, the size of donations has grown.
</P>
<P>
   At Harvard, a mere 85 gifts _ out of the 172,000 received since
1992 _ provided nearly half of the campaign goal, university
officials said. Each was at least $5 million.
</P>
<P>
   The largest gift, $70.5 million, was pledged in 1995 by John L.
Loeb, class of 1924, a former member of Harvard's governing body,
and his wife, Frances Lehman Loeb.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Among the most lucrative aspects of the campaign was the focus
on female donors, who have generally given substantially less than
male classmates at Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   Rita Hauser _ a member of the law school class of 1959, who,
along with her husband, gave $14.5 million to the law school and
$10 million to establish the Hauser Center for Nonprofit
Organizations _ led an effort that raised $40 million from female
alumni.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Harvard intends to use its trove for a variety of purposes.
</P>
<P>
   The school's Widener Library, for example, is to receive a $70
million renovation, and repairs to the freshman dormitories, at
about $65 million, have already been completed. And 25 new faculty
positions have been added to improve the ratio of undergraduate
students to professors.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of the campaign, the university's endowment has
grown to $14.2 billion, from $6 billion in 1994. The university's
annual budget is $1.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when institutions have been under external pressure to
spend more of their endowments on their operating expenses,
particularly to reduce tuition, Harvard has continued to spend
about 5 percent of the value of its endowment annually. But because
the size of the endowment has expanded so dramatically, the portion
of the operating budget financed by the endowment has grown to 28
percent, from 18 percent about a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   At Harvard, tuition and other fees, including room and board,
are $34,350 this year. Nearly half the students who attend Harvard
receive scholarships, with the average grant about $17,200,
university officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Harvard should be willing to part with a bit more of
its endowment each year, to lessen the burden on students,
Rudenstine, the president, said, with an eye on the cycles of the
world economy over the last century: ``You have to make sure that
the thing can last forever.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   While other institutions contacted Wednesday were fairly envious
of Harvard's good fortune, Rudenstine said that, in reality, $2.3
billion does not go as far as it used to.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably going to take $500 million alone just for new
space, new equipment, new people, new technicians, new inventions
and new teaching, just in the next three to five years,''
Rudenstine said. ``There is a lot more to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-99 2317EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991006.0483 </DOCNO>
