<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 23:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9200 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-BOTCHED-PLASTIC-SURGE     10-06 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOTCHED-PLASTIC-SURGERY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUEST FOR BEAUTY WENT AWRY AT HANDS OF A FAKE SURGEON, MIAMI POLICE
SAY
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By RICK BRAGG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI BEACH, Fla. _ The bodybuilder, a former Mr. Mexico and a
runner-up Mr. Universe, just wanted his pectorals enhanced. But he
woke from his anesthetic-induced sleep to find that the plastic
surgeon, who turned out not to be a doctor at all, had given him
women's implants. He had breasts.
</P>
<P>
   It sounds, said the police on Miami Beach, like some supermarket
tabloid fiction, something that would run alongside tales of aliens
and Elvis and babies born with horns. But the nightmare story of
the former Mr. Mexico, Alexander Baez, is not only real, the police
said, but part of a larger bad dream involving the man patients
knew on fashionable South Beach as Doctor Reinaldo.
</P>
<P>
   The police in Florida were searching Wednesday for Reinaldo
Silvestre, a 58-year-old man who, they say, pretended to be a
doctor and performed an unknown number of cosmetic surgeries in his
Miami Beach office, procedures that resulted in the disfigurement
of Baez and at least two other patients, both women.
</P>
<P>
   Using animal anesthetic, he clumsily cut open and prodded inside
the bodies of his patients, leaving gruesome scars, said Miami
Beach Capt. Charles Press, who watched a videotape of one of
Silvestre's operations. ``It was a butcher job you wouldn't want to
have happen to your dog,'' Press said.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators, who said Silvestre had operated in his clinic
since at least June 1998, predicted that the number of cases would
probably grow as patients too embarrassed to come forward now are
located and interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very, very badly,'' said Jeannette Bernal, 32, who had
a breast augmentation in the summer of 1998. Silvestre botched the
first one, and only made it worse with four more operations that
left her breasts disfigured, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Not only is Silvestre not a plastic surgeon, he is not a doctor
of any kind and holds no license to practice medicine anywhere, the
police said. He has been charged with practicing medicine and
administering narcotics without a license and aggravated battery.
</P>
<P>
   Press would not comment on the search for the fake doctor, who
has vanished and may have fled the country. Two of Silvestre's
employees _ his assistant and anesthesiologist _ have been
arrested.
</P>
<P>
   It is a story that shocked even veteran investigators in South
Florida, for whom beheadings, serial killings and ritual murders
are old hat. ``I've been here 25 years, and I thought I had seen it
all,'' Press said, ``until this.''
</P>
<P>
   Silvestre, a confident, smiling, Cuban-born man who easily won
people over, his patients told the police, operated from the Ocean
Health Center on Lincoln Road, in trendy South Beach. He lived
well, on Hibiscus Island on Miami Beach, from the $3,000 to $4,000
he charged for each surgery, according to police records.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, Baez, hoping to enhance his bodybuilding career,
went in for his surgery. ``Amateur,'' Press said, is too kind to
describe what happened: Baez, who had been given Katamine, an
anesthetic used on animals, kept waking up, in tears, as Silvestre
tried to force the too-large implant into his chest. ``He wakes
up,'' Press said, ``and he's got breasts.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, months and several medical procedures later, Baez has a
large scar on the right side of his chest, and still has the
bulging breast implant on the left side.
</P>
<P>
   Baez was not the only one Silvestre put under the knife, the
police said. There was Ms. Bernal, whose boyfriend left her after
the botched surgeries, and Mileidi Pimienta, whose complaint led to
the investigation of Silvestre. When her breast augmentation
surgery only led to several failed attempts to repair the original
damage, resulting in breasts of drastically differing size, she
went to the police.
</P>
<P>
   It was Miss Bernal who made the videotape that would help
investigators make their case against the phony doctor. As a favor
to the doctor after her first surgery _ but before she knew about
his deceit and her own medical problems began to show _ she
video-taped the operation on Baez.
</P>
<P>
   In some parts of the country, where plastic surgery is still
less common than podiatry, the news of the botched surgeries might
not resonate so loudly. But here in Miami, it was a lead story on
television news, complete with pictures. Looks matter here more
than other places, said experts on cosmetic surgery.
</P>
<P>
   In part, it is the warm weather, which puts more flesh on
display. But the culture of beauty here comprises more than that.
</P>
<P>
   ``People look at themselves in the mirror, and they go looking
to see how they can improve themselves,'' said Seth Thaller, a
professor of medicine at the University of Miami and chief of
plastic surgery at Jackson Memorial Hospital in Miami. ``They do it
to make themselves feel better. They want to put their best face
forward. People down here are out all the time, they wear shorts.
They want to feel like teenagers.''
</P>
<P>
   Thaller said that anyone considering such procedures should
check credentials and backgrounds. But the case of Silvestre is
proof, said both medical experts and investigators, that many
people do not investigate thoroughly and accept, almost on face
value, the promises of plastic surgery. Silvestre, the police said,
would meet people in public and sell them on his practice.
</P>
<P>
   Press compared Silvestre's methods to a horror movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was sickening,'' he said, ``how he did it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
