<HEADLINE>
DATEK ONLINE'S CHIEF AGREES TO STEP DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo (NYT34) was sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Under pressure from his own management team and a group of
outside investors, Jeffrey A. Citron agreed to step down Wednesday
as chairman and chief executive of Datek Online Holdings and to
relinquish any role in the company he helped fashion into a Wall
Street powerhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Citron, who is 29, will still be the company's largest
shareholder, but Datek executives said they hoped his departure
would help remove some of the questions about the company, which
has become the subject of a growing number of criminal and
regulatory inquiries.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, law enforcement officials said Wednesday that they are
looking into Datek and Citron as part of an investigation of Robert
E. Brennan, the flamboyant penny-stock promoter who has been banned
from the securities industry for life after bilking small investors
of hundreds of millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Datek executives said they were unaware of any investigation
into possible ties between Brennan and Datek and Citron but added
that they were cooperating with several criminal and regulatory
investigations.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question we want to disassociate ourselves from the
past,'' said Edward J. Nicoll, Datek's former president and chief
operating officer who was named to replace Citron as chairman and
chief executive. ``The company's value has been diminished as a
result of the investigations. But we want to do the right thing,
ethically, morally and in every way.''
</P>
<P>
   Datek, which blossomed from a small Brooklyn operation into the
nation's fourth-largest online brokerage firm, is best known on
Wall Street for creating an electronic trading market called Island
ECN, which matches buyers and sellers of stocks without market
makers.
</P>
<P>
   To help finance its plan to register Island as a stock exchange,
the company, which is now based in Edison, N.J., has invited
outsiders to invest in recent months, opening itself to more
scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years the company has been the subject of
investigations by the Manhattan district attorney, the U.S.
attorney for Manhattan and the Securities and Exchange Commission
for a range of possible offenses, including participating in a
money-laundering scheme, illegal trading activity and fraudulent
accounting practices, according to people close to the
investigations.
</P>
<P>
   Partly because of concerns about those investigations, Vulcan
Ventures, the venture capital firm financed by Paul Allen, the
co-founder of Microsoft, decided in July to withdraw a planned $300
million investment in Datek. Two other companies, TA Associates of
Boston and Groupe Arnault of Paris, went ahead with investments
totaling $195 million.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Datek dropped a planned initial public offering of
stock because of similar concerns, despite widespread enthusiasm
about the company's prospects on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   Citron, who joined Datek when he was 17 years old and worked his
way up from clerk to day trader to chief executive in 1997, was
considered a technology and trading wizard.
</P>
<P>
   Nicoll said Citron ``literally changed the shape of Wall
Street,'' by transforming a small Brooklyn brokerage firm into the
nation's fourth-largest online brokerage house in less than a
decade.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   And Bill Burnham, a general partner at Softbank Capital Partners
and a former stock analyst who specialized in online trading, said
Datek under Citron's leadership broke new ground on Wall Street by
introducing low-cost electronic trading, thus empowering individual
investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an incredibly talented guy,'' Burnham said Wednesday. ``I
think he just realized that the company would benefit if he stepped
aside.''
</P>
<P>
   Citron did not return calls for comment. In a statement released
by the company, Citron said he was ``stepping aside to let this
seasoned team of professional managers lead Datek Online as it
begins on an important new phase in its development.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The company said that Citron would ``pursue other interests.''
</P>
<P>
   But Nicoll said that Citron's decision to step down came after
more than a month of meetings with his management team and with the
consultation of several of the company's largest investors.
</P>
<P>
   Top executives at Datek also conducted an internal inquiry, a
step prompted by an investigation by the U.S. attorney's office
into trading activities at Datek, according to people close to the
company. Datek's review shed more light on Citron's relationship
with Raft Investments Inc., a firm that loaned money to day traders
and is under inquiry by the U.S. attorney's office, people close to
the company said, though they declined to elaborate on what the
review found.
</P>
<P>
   Following the company's review, Citron agreed to stepdown.
Although Citron owns about 30 percent of Datek, the company said in
its statement that he ``entered into an agreement'' to turn over
all his voting and management rights to the company's board of
directors.
</P>
<P>
   According to the pact, Citron will have no role in the company
for two years. After that time, it is unclear what role he may
resume.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
