<SLUG> BC-CT-ELECTION-LAWS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONNECTICUT GOVERNOR SEEKS OVERHAUL OF STATE ELECTION LAWS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD Conn. _ Struggling to keep his head above a bribery
scandal that threatens to swamp his administration, Gov. John G.
Rowland of Connecticut urged legislators Wednesday to undertake a
sweeping examination of state election and ethics laws.
</P>
<P>
   Although the call included no specifics, it was the first time
the governor voiced his support for any overhaul of the laws
governing the financing of campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   The change of heart comes at a time when the governor faces
daily questions about the actions of one of his running mates last
fall, Paul J. Silvester, the former state treasurer, who pleaded
guilty last month to money laundering while in office. And it
follows an accumulating series of ethics issues that have become an
insistent backdrop for Rowland's administration since he took
office in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Silvester, who lost the race for treasurer last November,
pleaded guilty to accepting cash kickbacks in return for placing
$500 million in state pension investments with certain equity
funds. He is now cooperating with federal prosecutors, and lawyers
for some other politicians under investigation say Silvester has
provided details about his dealings with high-level Connecticut
officials of both parties, including the governor.
</P>
<P>
   The governor, who appointed Silvester to the vacant treasury
post in 1997, denies any wrongdoing. Nevertheless the investigation
seems to be consuming a great deal of Rowland's attention.
</P>
<P>
   Usually affable and approachable, Rowland Wednesday was hustled
away after his speech by an unusually large contingent of state
troopers, and an aide slammed the door of his limousine when
reporters tried to ask him what kind of overhaul he might have in
mind.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, as Silvester provides information for investigations by
the Internal Revenue Service and the Federal Bureau of
Investigation, the scandal has become a baleful presence hovering
over politicians of both parties in a state that has traditionally
been known for relatively clean politics.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's call came during a speech at the 25th anniversary
luncheon of the state Elections Enforcement Commission, which, just
hours before, had voted to begin an investigation of the financing
of Silvester's campaign, including his links to the governor and
the state Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland, who battled many ethical questions in his first term,
remained popular and was overwhelmingly re-elected last year. Now,
both his friends and opponents are wondering about the impact of
the current scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even short of proving criminal behavior by the governor or his
aides themselves, there's a cumulative weight of all these
stories,'' said Sen. George C. Jepsen, a Democrat from Stamford who
is the majority leader.
</P>
<P>
   Longtime supporters of tighter campaign-finance laws reacted
with skepticism to the overture from Rowland, whose emissaries have
fought such legislation during past legislative sessions. Miles S.
Rapoport, a former Connecticut secretary of the state who now is
executive director of Democracy Works, a nonprofit group in the
state that supports drastic change in campaign-finance laws, said
he was concerned that the governor did not specify even one change
he would support.
</P>
<P>
   ``In his remarks today, there was absolutely no content,''
Rapoport said. ``If the governor is truly open to taking away the
desperate need for dollars that in part drove the Silvester
scandal, I would be delighted. Given his past, I'm skeptical.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rowland said he expected debate and many changes in the laws
when the Legislature convenes this winter. ``What a great way to
begin our session this year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland directed the staffs of the state Ethics Commission and
the state Elections Enforcement Commission to develop ``a reform
package that all of us in a very bipartisan way can live with.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The tragedy, if I can call it that _ the scandal, if I can
call it that _ over the last two weeks, has helped us all focus on
the problems and the improvements that still have to take place,''
Rowland said.
</P>
<P>
   After the governor was driven away, his spokesman, Dean Pagani,
said the review could include the possible taxpayer financing of
campaigns. Pagani said the governor also would consider a ban on
contributions from anyone who does business with the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``His position is that everything should be looked at,'' Pagani
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
