<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
 
Don Zimmer says he was more scared than anything 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Coach Don Zimmer was at his club's optional workout
yesterday, looking as handsome as ever despite getting hit by Chuck
Knoblauch's foul ball in the fifth inning of Game 1 on Tuesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer was taken to the clubhouse for a couple of innings, but
later returned to the dugout holding an ice pack on his left cheek.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw the ball come at me,'' Zimmer said. ``What I did was
turn my head. When the ball hit me, I didn't know whether it hit me
up in the head, whether it hit me in the cheek bone; I didn't know.
When I woke up this morning, I knew where it hit me the hardest,
right here on the neck. It scared me more than anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer has been through worse, and not because he's a former
Rangers manager. He was hit twice in the head by pitches as a
player, in 1953 in the minor leagues and in 1956 by Cincinnati's
Hal Jeffcoat while playing for the Los Angeles Dodgers. That injury
required a metal plate to be inserted inside his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of guys sitting in the dugout are not paying
attention,'' Zimmer said. ``As many times as I've been hit in the
head, I pay attention. If I hadn't been paying attention, it might
have hit me solid and I could have been hurt.'' Yankees changes
Manager Joe Torre is planning two changes in his lineup for Game 2
tonight. Chili Davis is expected to be the designated hitter
instead of Darryl Strawberry, and Joe Girardi will catch instead of
Jorge Posada.
</P>
<P>
   Davis is 3-for-12 with two home runs against Rangers starter
Rick Helling, and Strawberry has never faced him. Girardi is the
regular catcher for Yankees starter Andy Pettitte as well as Roger
Clemens, and Posada is usually behind the plate for Orlando
Hernandez and David Cone. Greatness rides the subway The Yankees
have won one game against the Rangers, but already two themes have
emerged in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Will there be a Subway Series?
</P>
<P>
   Are the Yankees the Team of the Decade?
</P>
<P>
   Talk of a Subway Series heated up even more after the New York
Mets defeated the Arizona Diamondbacks, 8-4, in the first game of
their National League Division Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a great team,'' Yankees general manager Brian
Cashman said. ``It's a scary team. I'm sure the National League
opponents that have to go through them aren't comfortable playing
them. I just hope we can get to the World Series, but I'll
certainly be rooting for them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Braves are usually considered the team of the '90s
because they have won eight division titles. But they've also won
only one World Series while the Yankees have won two.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly think we're qualified to be in that debate,''
Cashman said.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
