<SLUG> BC-CHIP-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOUSANDS OF CHILDREN IN KANSAS, MISSOURI COVERED BY NEW HEALTH
PLANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DONNA MCGUIRE  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Michelle Guymon feels fortunate that her three children avoided
broken bones and other health problems the last seven or eight
years. Without insurance, the medical bills would have been
disastrous.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just had to take our chances,'' the Blue Springs woman
said. Insurance, she said, was something the family just could not
afford.
</P>
<P>
   Her children are covered now _ through the state.
</P>
<P>
   Since Missouri and Kansas started new children's
health-insurance programs in the last year, more than 65,000
previously uninsured children have gained coverage.
</P>
<P>
   The publicity has helped other children, too. About 33,000
children from families too poor to qualify for the new programs
have been provided traditional Medicaid instead.
</P>
<P>
   Insured children can receive everything from immunizations and
physicals to X-rays, counseling and dental care.
</P>
<P>
   Supported by $24 billion in federal funding, this nationwide
crusade marks America's largest expansion of health insurance for
children in more than 30 years. Kansas and Missouri officials are
campaigning to enroll thousands more children in coming months.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've touched a lot of children through this effort that we've
never been able to touch before,'' said John Garlinger, a spokesman
for the Kansas Department of Social and Rehabilitation Services,
which receives about $31 million annually in federal funding for
the program.
</P>
<P>
   Eligible children live in families in which parents earn too
much to qualify for Medicaid but too little to afford private
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, officials hope to enroll 2.8 million children in the
new insurance programs and 600,000 more in Medicaid by next
September.
</P>
<P>
   So far Kansas and Missouri are meeting or exceeding their
enrollment targets. Missouri officials think their program may be
one reason the state's number of uninsured people declined in 1998
while the number of uninsured rose nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Yet challenges remain, starting with continued recruitment. Many
families are still not aware of the new programs. The problem
appears more serious in St. Louis, where enrollment lags behind
Kansas City levels. Yet even in Kansas City, recruiters constantly
are considering new ways to spread the word.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem: Gaining insurance does not guarantee access to
services, especially dental care. A committee recently formed in
Kansas City will study why Jackson County does not have enough
dentists. It is a problem also experienced in parts of Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   In Kansas, some parents have turned down health insurance for
their children after learning that they were too poor for the new
program and eligible instead for Medicaid. They think Medicaid has
a stigma. They don't want it.
</P>
<P>
   That is a perception state officials worried about when they
started the new insurance program, too. Both programs are funded by
federal and state funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people, especially in the Midwest, don't want to feel
like they are dependent on the government,'' said Susan Kannarr,
who directs implementation of the new Kansas program for the
Department of Social and Rehabilitation Services. ``How do we
convince those people that health insurance is important for their
kids?''
</P>
<P>
   Some people need no convincing.
</P>
<P>
   In July, Warren Jackson took his grandson to the dentist and
learned that the 9-year-old needed a root canal. Jackson, who lives
in Kansas City, Kan., knew his daughter could not afford the $650
bill. Neither could he. Perhaps the dentist could work out some
type of payment plan, he thought.
</P>
<P>
   Then Jackson told the dentist's receptionist that his grandson
had enrolled in HealthWave, the new Kansas health insurance
program. She replied that the root canal was covered. Completely.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a godsend,'' he recalled. ``Just unreal.''
Criteria vary
</P>
<P>
   Across the country, children up to age 19 can enroll in the new
health-insurance plans if they meet eligibility guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Those guidelines vary among states, with Missouri having one of
the most generous plans in the country.
</P>
<P>
   A Missouri family of four can qualify with earnings of nearly
$50,000, though some premiums apply to the higher-income families.
The Guymons, for example, pay less than $70 a month to cover three
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``It saves me $100 a month,'' said Michelle Guymon, who
considered adding the children to her employer's plan when she
started working for a public school this fall. Her husband is
self-employed in the construction business and has no company-paid
insurance. If she had put her children and her husband on her work
plan, her paycheck would have been gobbled up by insurance
premiums, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri's new insurance program, called MC+ For Kids, is an
expansion of the state's Medicaid program. It offers the same
benefits and the same choices of medical plans as traditional
Medicaid. Statewide, more than 52,000 children have enrolled since
coverage began in September 1998. About 20,000 other children have
been added to traditional Medicaid rolls.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas created HealthWave separate from Medicaid, though
benefits are the same. A family of four can earn up to nearly
$33,000 annually and still qualify for HealthWave.
</P>
<P>
   More than 13,700 children have enrolled in HealthWave since it
started in January. An additional 13,000 Kansas children have
joined traditional Medicaid rolls.
</P>
<P>
   Under Kansas guidelines, one child may be eligible for Medicaid
while another in the same family is eligible for HealthWave. As a
result, some parents may need different pediatricians for different
children. That is one of the few complaints child advocates have
about the Kansas program.
</P>
<P>
   In Missouri, child advocates worry that income verification
rules discourage some families from applying. State officials say
such safeguards (parents must show pay stubs as proof of income)
are needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There should be some checks or balances or everybody will come
in,'' said Marilyn Knipp, associate director of the Missouri
Department of Social Services, which receives about $52 million a
year in federal funds for its new program.
</P>
<P>
   Other critics think the state is being too generous with its
income guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hear from one side (the child advocates) that we are not
enrolling enough kids and from the other side that we are enrolling
too many,'' Knipp said. ``That was unexpected. These are uninsured
kids who are eligible for health care,'' she said, and agency
officials think they should be covered.
Spreading the word
</P>
<P>
   For decades, states have enrolled poor families in Medicaid when
the families applied for other state services, such as cash
welfare.
</P>
<P>
   They had no program set up to inform working families about the
new health-insurance program. How would they get the word out?
</P>
<P>
   A committee at the Local Investment Commission in Kansas City
began brainstorming last year. The Heart of America United Way set
up meetings.
</P>
<P>
   There were some bumps, especially in Missouri. Some early
promotional materials failed to explain what MC+ For Kids was all
about. Other materials incorrectly listed the eligibility criteria
as being the same for all income levels. Applications in Spanish
were late being printed.
</P>
<P>
   Other efforts, however, helped. For example, traditional
enrollment forms for Medicaid in Kansas and Missouri were more than
a dozen pages long. At two pages the new forms are much easier to
complete.
</P>
<P>
   State hot lines also have been set up. Recruiters staffed booths
at both state fairs and sent brochures to schools.
</P>
<P>
   And in Kansas, people like Helen Monroe were hired.
</P>
<P>
   Monroe is the HealthWave recruiter for Wyandotte County. She
visits businesses, churches, civic organizations, malls _ anywhere
she thinks she might find eligible children. She asks employers to
inform employees about the program. She asks groceries to let her
put up posters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never go anywhere without an application,'' Monroe said
recently while visiting a meeting of foster grandparents.
</P>
<P>
   After explaining the program, she asked the grandparents to help
her spread the word. Some asked for forms. One promised to talk to
people at her church.
</P>
<P>
   In Missouri, recruiters think churches and small businesses will
be the next places to go in search of families. They have already
placed advertisements on city buses and sent thousands of fliers to
schools.
</P>
<P>
   It may take several times of seeing the MC+ message before
parents apply, said Linda Johnson, who leads a health-insurance
task force for the Local Investment Commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some parents won't let their kids ride bikes or play outside,
because they are afraid the kids will get hurt,'' she said. ``Plus,
these kids don't get preventive (dental) care, so we are seeing
kids with major dental problems.''
</P>
<P>
   In both states officials look at the numbers of children
enrolling and know they have made a dent in the uninsured
population. But they are relying on old census data that said
60,000 Kansas children and 90,000 Missouri children lacked
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   They are uncertain how many more children need to reached.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to find out how many kids are still showing up at
doctors' offices and pharmacies and dentists' offices still
uninsured,'' Johnson said. ``My goal is to make sure (the numbers)
are going down.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
