<HEADLINE>
POPULARITY OF CHARTER SCHOOLS HURTS KC SCHOOL DISTRICT'S
ENROLLMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PHILLIP O'CONNOR  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The unexpected popularity of charter schools
is playing havoc with the Kansas City School District's efforts to
adequately staff classrooms, district officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Five weeks after classes resumed, Van Horn and Southeast high
schools still have 40 to 50 students in some classes, far above the
recommended number.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly not something we want for our children,'' Mary
Long, Van Horn principal, said this week. ``But it's the situation
we're in.''
</P>
<P>
   Teachers at other schools that experienced large drops in
enrollment this year will be reassigned to other schools.
</P>
<P>
   The district notified 14 elementary teachers this week that they
were being transferred. The district said it expected to hire 26
more high school teachers and a still-undetermined number of middle
school teachers to ease the overcrowding problem.
</P>
<P>
   The district also is asking students in schools that are
overcrowded to voluntarily transfer to less-crowded buildings. No
layoffs are planned, because the district still has teaching
vacancies.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the move of students to charters may force the
district to close schools, some board members said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have the enrollment to justify them anymore,'' board
member Lance Loewenstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Like many urban districts, the Kansas City district typically
reorganizes its teaching staff in the first quarter of every school
year to account for unexpected shifts in enrollment. District
officials say the annual reorganization is disruptive but necessary
to comply with Missouri class-size standards and stay within the
budget.
</P>
<P>
   District officials, however, said it was impossible to plan for
the full effect of charter schools. The publicly funded
experimental schools began operating in Kansas City this year and
already have enrolled an estimated 4,500 students, including many
former district students.
</P>
<P>
   Difficulty in projecting which schools district students would
attend resulted in some schools being understaffed while creating
student overcrowding at others.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can we make predictions on the unknown?'' said chief of
staff Cheri Shannon, who oversees the reorganization.
</P>
<P>
   The staffing issue still angers many parents.
</P>
<P>
   At a school board meeting Tuesday night, parents from Hartman
Elementary School, which serves children in kindergarten and first
grade, complained that moving teachers this late in the school year
would be traumatic for their children. The district initially
allocated 10 kindergarten teachers to Hartman this year, but
enrollment plunged to 289 from 428.
</P>
<P>
   Parents pleaded that the district not move the teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said they could not afford to maintain a 12-to-1
student-to-teacher ratio at Hartman while other elementary schools
had more than 30 students in some classes. In kindergarten through
second grade, the state recommends 20 students per teacher.
</P>
<P>
   The district Tuesday notified the Hartman principal that the
school would be losing four kindergarten teachers and one
first-grade teacher. But that plan was put on hold after board
members asked for a meeting next Tuesday to receive a more detailed
report.
</P>
<P>
   At the same school board meeting, a Van Horn parent complained
about the lack of teachers and the long-term use of substitutes in
a social studies class. She said students were being told to do
their homework from other classes, visit or sleep.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no instruction occurring,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She questioned whether students in the class would be given a
grade of incomplete, given the amount of class time lost.
</P>
<P>
   The district on Wednesday approved hiring 11 more teachers for
Van Horn, and officials said students would not receive an
incomplete in the course.
</P>
<P>
   Board member Patricia Kurtz questioned whether the students
would ever be given a chance to catch up on missed course work or
just miss out on learning.
</P>
<P>
   District officials say they intend to begin the planning process
earlier next year to reduce staff movement during the school year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realize that it is disruptive to the educational process,''
Shannon said.
</P>
<P>
   Superintendent Benjamin Demps Jr. warned the board to expect the
enrollment figures and teacher allocations to continue to shift
throughout the current school year. The district already has found
many cases of students simultaneously enrolled in district and
charter schools. In other instances, students who began the year in
charter schools have returned to district schools, while students
who began the year in district schools have moved to charters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I, at this point, can't say what our enrollment is going to be
over the next six months,'' Demps told the board. ``The numbers
could change again next week. We're in a very uncertain time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
