<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-PENSIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPPORT GROWS IN CONGRESS FOR PENSION SYSTEM TO AID HIGH EARNERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio, Md.)   (bl)  
 By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Support is growing quickly in Congress for a vast expansion of
retirement tax breaks for business owners, executives and highly
paid workers, moves that Republicans and Democrats alike say would
be popular with voters.
</P>
<P>
   The leading proposal, known as the Portman-Cardin Pension Reform
Plan, has 148 sponsors and would raise the $10,000 limit on annual
tax-deductible savings in 401(k) plans to $15,000 and, for those
age 50 and older, to $20,000.
</P>
<P>
   The stated goal is to include many more employees in retirement
programs by making the plans more attractive to business owners and
to simplify complex rules that are designed to make sure most
workers share in the benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Rob Portman, R-Ohio, the plan's leading sponsor, said that
more firms are opting for executive-only plans without tax breaks.
``We need to try something new because the system we have isn't
working,'' he said, ``and we need to get more people covered.''
</P>
<P>
   But even the bill's co-sponsor acknowledges that it may not do
that. Critics say the bill is actually little more than cover for a
plan to shower new tax benefits on the rich.
</P>
<P>
   One provision would allow businesses to cut pension benefits by
as much as one-third for workers making less than $160,000 annually
without reducing benefits for those earning more. Supporters say
they expect few businesses to do that.
</P>
<P>
   Norman Stein, a University of Alabama Law School pension
specialist who analyzed the Portman-Cardin plan, said it ``should
be called the Retirement Reduction Act.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill's co-sponsor, Rep. Ben Cardin, D-Md., said in a speech
last week that the bill might not increase the number of people who
would collect retirement benefits, but it had such strong support
from business that it was worth giving its provisions a try.
</P>
<P>
   Easing regulations and raising savings limits would make
retirement plans more attractive to business owners, he said, and
should be viewed as ``part of an overall strategy that will
eventually cover more people.''
</P>
<P>
   Cardin and Rep. Rob Andrews, D-N.J., are circulating a letter
among House Democrats urging them to support the bill. Andrews said
``anything we do that increases contributions to retirement plans
is a good thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics acknowledge tens of thousands of new retirement plans
would be created if Portman-Cardin is enacted, but they fear that
few lower-paid workers would benefit.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Halperin, a pension specialist at Harvard Law School, has
estimated that the expanded tax breaks would let a person easily
accumulate tax-deferred retirement benefits of $5 million, even if
not one additional lower-paid worker got a dollar in benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill turns the concept of using tax benefits to expand
retirement income security on its head,'' he said, adding that the
proposal ``while well intentioned and containing many good ideas,
would on the whole do more harm than good.''
</P>
<P>
   Dianne Bennett of Buffalo, N.Y., president of Hodgson, Russ,
Andrews, Woods &AMP; Goodyear, the largest law firm in upstate New
York, said that if the Portman-Cardin plan becomes law its likely
effect ``would be to expand retirement plans that benefit only
owners of business and to dramatically reduce the benefits
granted'' to the rank and file.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bennett, a pension specialist, cited examples from
retirement plans that she has drafted for clients to show that most
of the benefits already flow to a few highly paid employees, a
situation that she said would worsen drastically if the proposals
were enacted.
</P>
<P>
   She added that ``many of my clients will not like what I am
saying or that I am saying it.''
</P>
<P>
   A senior Clinton administration official said support for the
proposal was spreading quickly among Democrats eager to tell voters
that they have made an easily understandable improvement to the
401(k) plans.
</P>
<P>
   The official said none of the lawmakers he had talked to seemed
to understand the provisions that could harm workers.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters and critics agree that the greatest need is to have
more people collect benefits when they retire. Supporters have
focused on how more people would be ``covered'' by such plans, a
measure of how many people could potentially participate in a plan,
rather than how many will actually collect benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides also agree that increasing the amounts that can be
put away untaxed will encourage more savings in retirement plans.
But critics say that the increase will be narrowly focused among
those already saving the maximum.
</P>
<P>
   Few workers are held back by the current $10,000 limit on
tax-deferred 401(k) savings.
</P>
<P>
   Only 4 to 11 percent of 401(k) plan participants save the
maximum now, according to the Employee Benefit Research Institute,
a nonprofit group in Washington whose studies are regarded as the
standard for the benefits industry. Workers save an average of
$3,000 each in 401(k) plans, the institute estimated.
</P>
<P>
   Portman-Cardin may be included in a bill to raise the minimum
wage by a dollar, to $6.15, in two steps.
</P>
<P>
   The additional $10,000 that older workers could save each year
would add $360,000 to a retirement nest egg of someone who is 50
years old, retires at 65 and earns historic stock market returns.
</P>
<P>
   Current law generally limits the total amount that a worker and
an employer together can set aside in a retirement plan to 25
percent of pay up to a maximum of $30,000 of savings.
Portman-Cardin would increase that to $45,000.
</P>
<P>
   Another provision would let some people sock away their entire
paycheck, where it would grow untaxed until the money is withdrawn
in retirement. That option would be attractive to those who can
live off investment income, such as dividends and capital gains,
and to those two-income families who can live on one paycheck.
</P>
<P>
   Raising benefits at the top means that 62 percent of the new tax
breaks would flow to people in the top 10 percent income group,
analysis using the Treasury Department's economic modeling software
found.
</P>
<P>
   The middle fifth of households would get just 3.2 percent of the
tax breaks, according to the Center on Budget and Policy
Priorities, a Washington advocacy group for the poor, which
performed the analysis.
</P>
<P>
   The Portman-Cardin plan has wide support from business
organizations and is similar to proposals by Sen. William Roth, ,
R-Del., for whom the popular tax-free Roth IRAs are named.
</P>
<P>
   The provision that most concerns critics would increase the
maximum annual pay that can be considered in calculating pension
benefits by 47 percent, to $235,000 from $160,000.
</P>
<P>
   That would let highly paid business owners increase their own
pension benefits by 47 percent without raising benefits for
employees earning less than $160,000.
</P>
<P>
   Alternatively, the provision would allow a business owner to
collect the same number of dollars from the retirement plan for
himself, while cutting retirement benefits by up to one-third for
everyone making less than $160,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   But James Delaplane, vice president for retirement policy at the
Association of Private Pension and Welfare Plans in Washington,
said market forces should discourage that type of response.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
