<HEADLINE>
JOHNNY OATES ADJUSTS RANGERS ROSTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Because the Yankees are pitching left-hander Andy
Pettitte tonight, Rangers manager Johnny Oates is making one lineup
change and considering another.
</P>
<P>
   Oates said Roberto Kelly will start in center field instead of
Tom Goodwin, and he's considering using Luis Alicea at second base
for Mark McLemore. Alicea was used at second base against
left-handers late in the season until he suffered a pulled
hamstring muscle on Sept. 13.
</P>
<P>
   Alicea hit .290 against left-handers this season while McLemore,
a switch hitter, hit .163. Oates said he'll wait to see how Alicea
is running today before making a decision.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly also has hit left-handers much better than Goodwin. Kelly
hit .358 against them while Goodwin hit .262.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, Oates said, ``We just need to swing the bats better.
If we don't swing the bats, we're not going to win. We ought to
score more runs by accident, but there's not much else we can do.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's called going up there and hitting the baseball. We had
one chance to run \RTuesday\S and Pudge \RRodriguez\S stole a base.
You've got the nine best hitters in the lineup. There's nothing
else you can do but relax and try to get some hits.'' Advice from
Dent One member of the Rangers understands what it's like to hit
well and win in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Bench coach Bucky Dent not only hit his famous home run in the
1978 playoff game against the Boston Red Sox, but he was the Most
Valuable Player in the World Series. Dent hit .417 with 10 hits in
24 at-bats to lead the Yankees to a world championship in six games
against the Los Angeles Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   In watching the Rangers struggle against the Yankees, Dent said,
``The big thing is for us to relax. Over the course of the year,
we've gone into a little bit of a funk at times and broken out of
it. So, we just need to relax, do the things we've always done and
remain positive because we have a good-hitting club.''
</P>
<P>
   Dent said the Rangers just need that one hit to get the offense
rolling. They didn't get it in Tuesday's 8-0 loss to the Yankees.
Instead, Yankees pitcher Orlando Hernandez struck out Todd Zeile
with the bases loaded in the first inning and got both Juan
Gonzalez and Rafael Palmeiro to fly out with two runners on base in
the third inning. Those were the Rangers' two best chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``When this team breaks out, it's going to be big,'' Dent said.
He said it ``We're a very good offensive ballclub, and we'll break
out of it somewhere along the line. You just hope it's sooner than
later.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Rangers general manager Doug Melvin. Record losing streak The
Rangers have lost seven consecutive Division Series games, tying
the record held by the Houston Astros. The Rangers lost the final
three games of the 1996 series to the Yankees, got swept by them in
three games last year and lost on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros lost the final three games of the 1981 Division
Series against the Los Angeles Dodgers, got swept by the Atlanta
Braves in 1997 and lost the first game to San Diego last year.
Pursuing Bernie Doug Melvin was the Yankees scouting director in
1985 when he signed Bernie Williams as a 17-year-old free agent out
of Puerto Rico. He considered signing him again last off-season
when Williams was a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It went through my mind last year to get heavily involved with
him,'' Melvin said. ``But at the time, we were a pretty good
offensive ballclub and our needs have been pitching. We were
pursuing that No. 1 starting pitcher that everybody wants us to
get.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I was in Banff, Alberta, last \RNovember\S on a week's
vacation when I got a call from Bernie Williams. I returned the
call and Bernie was on the phone. He said he just signed with the
Yankees. I didn't know what he was calling about, whether to
express interest or not. I was fortunate to get a guy like Rafael
Palmeiro.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
