<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: GUERRILLA MARKETING IS GOING MAINSTREAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The moon hung in the sky over Union Square, and fans
of the fusion-jazz group Incognito were lined up in front of the
Irving Plaza theater, waiting for the doors to open. Ivan Ramirez,
``guerrilla marketer,'' spied an opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   With two assistants _ Ian Zucker, an 18-year-old just out of
high school, and Danny DeJesus, a much-tattooed disk jockey known
as Ruido/Mentol Nomad _ he descended on the group, handing out
cassette tapes of an unrelated band called Supreme Beings of
Leisure and taping posters of another group, Break Beat Era, onto
the cart of a willing hot-dog vendor. ``We'll be selective,''
Ramirez said with a certain degree of satisfaction. ``We won't give
out the tapes to everybody. We try to niche it.''
</P>
<P>
   The people in line reacted with mild interest, amusement or
indifference. ``I get this all the time,'' said one, Timothy
McDaniel. ``This word-of-mouth and foot promotion is the best. You
have it in your hand. You can ask them questions.'' As Ramirez
worked his way down the line, a theater security guard stuck out a
beefy hand for a cassette. He got one.
</P>
<P>
   Such tactics, long in place at small companies trying to get a
toehold, are starting to be embraced by the mainstream as they
evolve into more subtle forms. Coca-Cola Co. has used Ramirez's
company, Cornerstone Promotions in New York, as guerrilla marketers
for Sprite. Nike has used it to help drum up interest in its Quick
Six shoes. Even the National Football League has joined the game,
trying to develop fans among 12- to-24-year-olds. Other companies
have invested in their own guerrilla marketing teams, whose
full-time job is to promote company products at the grass-roots
level.
</P>
<P>
   The purpose, these companies say, is mainly to reach younger
consumers by cutting past all the static that the companies
themselves created and that young people have tuned out _
television, radio, print and Internet ads.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that to reach teens, we have to talk to them where
they live, in a language that they understand, with a message that
is meaningful and delivered by a credible source,'' said Polly
Howes, a Coke spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   With guerrilla marketing _ unexpected, subtle and usually
delivered by young people _ companies say they can get higher sales
and sometimes rejuvenate their images, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a term for out of the box, plus some,'' said Lisa
Skriloff, president of Multicultural Marketing Resources, which
specializes in advertising by demographic group. ``It goes beyond
tried-and-true methods. It's something that would almost catch
someone by surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   Others see it as one more way to blur the traditional
definitions of advertising and marketing. ``Advertising used to be
something you could point to and say was advertising,'' said John
Stauber, editor of P.R. Watch, a newsletter that monitors the
public-relations and marketing industries. ``There's now more and
more advertising that is more propagandistic. It slips the
marketing below the level of any audience awareness and often puts
it in the mouth of somebody who is more likely to be trusted by
that target audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of guerrilla marketing is still about hitting the pavement,
with ``street teams,'' to hand out free samples and fliers. But
lately it has begun to take other forms as well, through product
placement and unexpected appearances on television and the
airwaves.
</P>
<P>
   Fresh Samantha, a seven-year-old juice company based in Maine,
has three employees in their early 20s who drive up and down the
East Coast in a Winnebago towing a huge bottle of juice. Their
finest moment, in their opinion, came earlier this year when they
got themselves, and their bottle, onto the ``Today'' show. The team
members dressed up in fruit and animal costumes, made sure they
were assembled before the program's studio windows at Rockefeller
Center at 4:30 a.m., ahead of the crowds, and took along a huge
banner with the company's name on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They held up the banner and the camera showed them maybe 10 or
15 times,'' said Betta Stothart, the juice company's marketing
director. They also persuaded the show's hosts to take a bottle of
juice, and it sat on the set for the rest of the show. A similar
coup took place recently with a film crew making the television
series ``Sex and the City,'' Ms. Stothart said. The crew agreed to
show the juice on camera if the company would supply the product
free.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know when it's going to work,'' she said.
``Sometimes it fails miserably. They've gotten a lot of parking
tickets.'' Still, she called it ``the most powerful way to
communicate the identity of our company.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   For other companies, guerrilla marketing is one tool among many.
``We do it to complement our air war, in traditional TV and
print,'' said Glenn Chin, director of life style marketing for EA
Sports, a division of Electronic Arts that makes sports video
games.
</P>
<P>
   A recently developed boxing game called Knockout Kings includes
subtle messages about Ecko, a clothing line, as well as a singer
called O who has yet to be marketed by his recording label,
Hollywood Records. ``It seemed a perfect synergy,'' Chin said.
``Kids can dress their boxer in Ecko clothes. It's
cross-pollination.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, EA Sports has guerrilla-marketing teams in 12 areas
of the country who visit concerts and other places where young
people congregate, as well as student representatives on 30 college
campuses, Chin said.
</P>
<P>
   Other companies trying to break into crowded markets have turned
to the same program. ``You need to be incredibly proactive,'' said
Michele Peranteau, a spokeswoman for Jeremy's Microbatch ice cream,
based in Philadelphia. ``You can't be reactive.'' Jeremy's, founded
three years ago, has street teams in half a dozen cities who
distribute coupons and samples.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very cost-effective,'' she said, adding that sales have
risen 75 percent since the teams were first sent out in the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez's company, Cornerstone, was founded three years ago by
Jon Cohen and Rob Stone, two friends who were sales executives in
the music business. Using their connections, they put together a
group of disk jockeys from around the country and now use the group
to promote consumer products like Nike sneakers and Sprite and a
Web company, Boo.com, that is being developed to sell sports
apparel and footwear. Some of the promotion is through CDs that
include ads as well as music and are distributed monthly to DJs.
</P>
<P>
   In another program, which began in May, Cornerstone signed a
contract to promote the Nike Quick Six, a shoe that was new last
spring. As disk jockeys who had been given pairs of the shoes
extolled them on the air, most listeners were unaware that the
shoes were being marketed to them.
</P>
<P>
   At Nike, the tactic was only one part of what a company
spokesman described as ``intersecting our brand with popular
culture.'' Did sales go up? A spokesman, Erin Patton, would say
only that the shoe was ``a very successful shoe.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The most successful marketers these days are really striving
for a more personal, two-way communication with the consumer,'' he
added, ``and the vehicle of that is the nuance of culture the
consumer is interested in.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen, for his part, says promoting products by connecting them
to popular music does work. ``I'm not saying we can be as effective
as a huge national ad,'' he said, emphasizing that his company is
extremely selective about what it promotes because of worries about
losing its credibility. ``But word of mouth can be so effective,''
he added. ``We get to the taste makers.''
</P>
<P>
   The company is also betting heavily on the Internet for its
music clients as well as consumer-products companies, transferring
the tactics of street teams like those led by Ramirez to the
virtual battlefield.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a team of people who do the equivalent of what Ivan is
doing on the Internet,'' Cohen said. ``We'll bring in X amount of
kids; they'll go to every search engine and set up giveaways and
get people to sign up for things.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having a street team is part of guerrilla marketing,'' he
added, ``but we're moving beyond that. There's no end to it. The
end is if it's not done in a tasteful manner, it'll be everybody
just throwing things at everybody.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
