<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ACCUSES SENATE OF BIAS IN REJECTING JUDGE CANDIDATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE KRASKE AND KEVIN MURPHY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The White House continued Wednesday to accuse
Senate Republicans of unfair treatment of minorities in the
selection of federal judges.
</P>
<P>
   One day after a party-line vote defeating the nomination of
Ronnie White, the first African-American to serve on the Missouri
Supreme Court, President Clinton's spokesman produced a study that
said whites were confirmed more easily than minority nominees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact remains, there appears to be a higher bar for them,''
White House spokesman Jim Kennedy said. ``Unfortunately, Judge
White had the bar moved up even higher.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Kit Bond characterized the White House accusations as
``unmitigated political hogwash.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The administration is once again playing the race card,'' said
the Missouri Republican. ``It's absolutely unsupported, and it's
unworthy of someone in the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   Black groups who also criticized the rejection of White as a
U.S. district judge in St. Louis asked whether the Senate had
created a new judicial litmus test _ unequivocal support of the
death penalty. White declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Others continued to see the defeat of White, the only judicial
appointment killed on the Senate floor since Robert Bork in 1987,
as an election ploy by Republican Sen. John Ashcroft of Missouri.
He faces a re-election race next year against Gov. Mel Carnahan, a
Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft disputed that allegation, noting that he had opposed
the nomination since shortly after Clinton nominated White in 1997.
Republican Senate leaders also denied that any higher bar was
imposed on White or minorities in general. They continued to say
that White's soft record on the death penalty was the key factor.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said support for White crumbled when Bond, who had
served as White's sponsor, pulled his support at the last minute
Tuesday. That left White without an official Senate backer from his
home state, an untenable position for a nominee already opposed by
Ashcroft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must defer to my colleagues from Missouri with respect to a
nominee whose jurisdiction, if confirmed, would be wholly limited
to that state,'' said Sen. Orrin Hatch, a Utah Republican and
chairman of the Senate Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri Attorney General Jay Nixon, a Democrat who tried to
unseat Bond last year, accused the senator of betraying the black
voters who had given unusual support to a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon, who had accused the Republican of blocking the nomination
in 1998, on Tuesday told the Associated Press that Bond's vote was
a ``classic bait-and-switch.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that the political heat's off, he's safe to assist in
tanking the nomination of a fine man for blatant political
reasons,'' Nixon said.
</P>
<P>
   Bond said he expected a partisan reaction from Nixon. Bond
explained that he changed his mind when he heard from law
enforcement officers who were not comfortable with White's record
on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton on Tuesday issued a sharp condemnation of a ``process
that has lost any pretense of fairness.'' On Wednesday the White
House referred to a study conducted by the nonpartisan Citizens for
Independent Court in Washington. The analysis covered the 1997-98
term of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   In that time, 75 percent of 55 women and minorities were
confirmed, compared with 85 percent of the 68 white men nominated,
the study said.
</P>
<P>
   The average number of days between nomination and final action
was 167 for white men and 243 for women and minorities. For
successful nominees, the number of days was 154 for white men and
194 for women and minorities.
</P>
<P>
   The study also compared white nominees to minorities. It found
that 79 of 92 white men and women nominees eventually were
confirmed, compared with 20 of 31 minority nominees.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft let a spokesman respond to questions Wednesday about
Clinton's comments.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's outrageous for the president to accuse...senators from
all over the nation of racial bias,'' Steve Hilton said. ``Where is
one scrap of evidence for such scurrilous suggestions?''
</P>
<P>
   White's record as both a judge and a three-term state lawmaker,
he said, ``is a complete refutation to those kinds of assertions.''
</P>
<P>
   According to data compiled by Ashcroft's office, the senator had
voted for 23 of 26 black judicial nominees and 50 of 58 women
nominees in the last five years.
</P>
<P>
   Late Wednesday, Ashcroft and Bond released a letter they sent to
Clinton urging him to make another nomination soon. The nominee
should ``enjoy widespread support in our state,'' especially from
law enforcement officials, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Black groups, meantime, continued to assert that White's skin
color ultimately cost him a federal judgeship.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're outraged,'' said Yvonne Scruggs-Leftwich, executive
director of the Black Leadership Forum, a group that represents 26
civil rights groups, including the NAACP and the Urban League. ``We
think that this is a blatant and outrageous example of racism.''
</P>
<P>
   In rejecting White, the Senate sent a message that only nominees
who expressed unwavering support of the death penalty pass muster,
Scruggs-Leftwich said. That, by itself, could undercut the number
of blacks who won federal judgeships, because many
African-Americans traditionally oppose capital punishment. They
contend that the death sentence is disproportionately meted out to
black defendants.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate should avoid judicial litmus tests, particularly when
it comes to the death penalty, said Robert Popper, a law professor
at the University of Missouri-Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``In death-penalty cases, you want judges to be very, very
careful in reviewing decisions with capital-punishment
implications, because life is at stake,'' Popper said. ``It seems
to me there should be a right for a justice to dissent.''
</P>
<P>
   Allegations continued Wednesday that Ashcroft opposed White for
political gain. Democrats charged that Ashcroft wanted to keep
focus on the death- penalty issue, which ensnared Carnahan earlier
this year when he commuted a death row inmate's sentence at the
request of Pope John Paul II.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters asked Carnahan on Wednesday whether he thought race
played a part in the Senate's rejection of White.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people have to make their own judgment,'' Carnahan
said. ``It is statistically true that minorities and women have a
harder time being confirmed by the Republican U.S. Senate. It is
very graphic how many of the minorities have been held back.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Bailey, assistant dean of the University of
Missouri-Columbia law school, said he also sensed that politics was
at play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Judge White became a pawn in the political match that's
occurring between Ashcroft and Carnahan,'' Bailey said. ``I think
Ashcroft is demonstrating that he's tough on crime, and he's going
to try to demonstrate that Carnahan is not as tough and concerned
about crime as he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats noted that in a majority of the instances when White
voted to reverse a death sentence, the Ashcroft appointees on the
court joined him in an unanimous agreements. The Democratic
Senatorial Campaign Committee in Washington said Ashcroft did
``irreversible damage to the integrity of his office.''
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft drew support from the conservative Landmark Legal
Foundation, based in Kansas City. The Senate's job is to provide
advice and consent regarding any presidential nominee and not to
``rubber stamp'' the choice, noted foundation president Mark Levin.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that White was strongly opposed by law enforcement
groups, Levin said it followed that the Senate would reject him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, this has nothing to do with Mr. White's race,'' Levin
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are a lot of groups out there who want to turn
this into something it's not. They're getting their lead from the
president of the United States, who is demagoguing this issue to
the hilt.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
