<SLUG> BC-PEPSICO-PROFIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEPSICO PROFIT RISES 6.7 PERCENT, SLIGHTLY BEATING EXPECTATIONS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a performance that was in line with expectations, Pepsico
Inc. reported a 6.7 percent increase in third-quarter profit
Wednesday on the strength of higher earnings at its Frito-Lay and
Tropicana units.
</P>
<P>
   Net income rose to $507 million, or 34 cents a diluted share,
compared with $475 million, or 32 cents a share, in the period a
year earlier. The results were adjusted to include the August 1998
purchase of the Tropicana juice company and the spinoff of the
Pepsi Bottling Group. Analysts had expected the company to earn 33
cents a share, according to First Call/Thomson Financial.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue rose 6.5 percent, to $4.58 billion from $4.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all of the profit growth came from the Frito-Lay snack
unit, where earnings increased 11 percent, and Tropicana, where
profit grew 54 percent. That was in contrast to the performance at
Pepsi-Cola North America, the largest division of the company's
soft-drink business, where case sales were flat compared with those
in the period a year earlier. Concentrate shipments declined 2.5
percent, although revenue increased 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The situation at Pepsi-Cola, which is a result of higher
supermarket prices after several years of steep discounts, is
mirrored at the Coca-Cola Co., Pepsi's rival. Nevertheless, the
earnings announcement from Pepsi sent the share prices of both
companies skyrocketing. Shares of Pepsico rose $1.75, or 5.6
percent, to $33.1875. Coke rose $4, to $51.9375.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Conway, a beverage analyst for Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter, said there was little reason for the jump other than what
he observed had been ``a minibeverage rally'' during the day, when
the market rose for many consumer stocks. ``Coke's stock had been
in a downward spiral since June, and at some point the spiral slows
or stops,'' he said. ``Since early June, Coke's market cap has
declined by $40 billion, which is almost as large as Pepsi's market
cap today.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the earnings were mostly unsurprising.
``Soft-drink profits were worse than I expected, and snack food was
completely in line,'' said Jennifer Solomon of Salomon Smith
Barney.
</P>
<P>
   In a conference call with analysts Wednesday afternoon, Roger A.
Enrico, the chairman of Pepsico, expressed confidence that the
soft-drink business would rebound. One of the tactics Pepsico plans
to use is a new commercial starring singer Ricky Martin. Enrico
also suggested that higher prices, which went into effect earlier
this year, would not be repeated in terms of percentage increases
in the future. The increase was 5.2 percent this year, compared
with typical increases of 2 percent to 3 percent in previous years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not going to just sit around and say, `We know the
industry will come back,' although we know it will,'' he said.
``People in this industry are pretty good marketers. If some of the
price points are wrong, we will make adjustments to those price
points.'' But he added that he did not expect to call for a sharp
increase in marketing for any of Pepsico's businesses. ``I think
we've got enough money there to have the right impact in the
marketplace,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One factor in Pepsico's recent stock slide was the unexpected
resignation last month of Philip A. Marineau, the president of
Pepsi-Cola North America. Marineau left to become chief executive
at Levi Strauss. Enrico made no mention of the change, except to
note that Marineau's successor, Gary M. Rodkin, who formerly led
Tropicana, was coming up to speed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
