<HEADLINE>
FINDING RIGHT MIX ON LINES WITHOUT MODANO NOT EASY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Stars coach Ken Hitchcock is finding life
without No. 1 center Mike Modano to be a tad more confusing than he
expected.
</P>
<P>
   He's trying to mix and match the pieces from Modano's line with
other lines.
</P>
<P>
   He had winger Jere Lehtinen playing on a line with Joe
Nieuwendyk and Jamie Langenbrunner yesterday at practice while
Brett Hull practiced on a line with Pavel Patera and Mike Keane.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see where it goes to,'' Hitchcock said. ``I think we've
got to be flexible. We're learning when you take out a player like
Mo or Syd, adjustments have to be made.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Modano (concussion) nor defenseman Darryl Sydor
(fractured eye socket) will be available when the Stars play
Anaheim tomorrow night and San Jose on Saturday. Hitchcock said the
focus when playing those teams is usually checking, a role Modano's
line played well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without Mo, we've had to structure some different thoughts,''
Hitchcock said. ``I don't know if we have anything cut in stone.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock also said backup goalie Manny Fernandez will get his
first start of the season this weekend. Hitchcock said he is
leaning toward playing Ed Belfour against Anaheim and Fernandez
against San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   Injured winger Grant Mashall (groin) and recently acquired
winger Chris Murray are also expected to get into the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to make a decision \Rtoday\S on Marshall,''
Hitchcock said. ``We'll play both this weekend, but we'll play one
guy at a time. I don't know if we want to try to break them both in
at the same time.'' Best memories Some of winger Blake Sloan's best
memories have come in Joe Louis Arena in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   He guessed he played upward of 40 games there while playing
college hockey at Michigan. His best memory might have come on
Tuesday, with his father and grandfather on hand, as he scored his
first NHL goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good to get the monkey off my back,'' said Sloan, who
took 36 NHL games before scoring his first goal. ``I've been
getting some good chances. I've been working on bearing down on
chances. I was just trying to stay positive and just keep going at
it. It's just kind of a sigh of relief.''
</P>
<P>
   While he sighed, his teammates screamed.
</P>
<P>
   His linemate Juha Lind jumped so high when Sloan scored, a
spectator would've thought he scored the goal. The Stars' bench
also celebrated like it was a game-winning goal at the buzzer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our players were as excited for Sloany as anybody because he's
had so many opportunities,'' coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``We've
played three games, and I bet if you look back, he almost leads the
team in shots. He's played so well out of the gate. We knew he
could score at practice and we knew if he got one, he was going to
be able to score in this league.
</P>
<P>
   ``That one goal is going to go a long ways into making him a
bona fide right winger.'' Kariya returns Oft-injured Anaheim
captain Paul Kariya returned to the Mighty Ducks lineup in time for
Tuesday's 4-0 loss to Phoenix. He had been sidelined by a sore left
hip for most of training camp.
</P>
<P>
   So, will the Ducks risk playing him in what could be a physical
game tomorrow night against the Stars?
</P>
<P>
   ``Paul is going to play against Phoenix,'' Ducks coach Craig
Hartsburg said. ``So, I don't see any reason he wouldn't play
against Dallas.'' Learns a lesson Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said he
likes playing Detroit, especially so early because the game always
allows him to learn something about his team.
</P>
<P>
   So, what was the lesson in Tuesday's 2-0 victory?
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, the gauge out there was when they are on the top of
their game and we're not, it can be very embarrassing,'' Hitchcock
said. ``And when we're on top of our game, we can dictate the tempo
too.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
