<SLUG> BC-ADVANCED-MICRO-DEVICES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVANCED MICRO SAYS LOSS IS SMALLER THAN EXPECTED 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Advanced Micro Devices Inc. reported a loss for
the third quarter Wednesday that was smaller than expected as sales
of its new Athlon line of microprocessors accelerated.
</P>
<P>
   Advanced Micro executives said they were on track to achieve
their goal of break-even results in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But they said that uncertainties remained regarding the supply
of chip sets and motherboards, the main boards of personal
computers, because of the earthquake in Taiwan. Advanced Micro is
vulnerable to supply constraints in Taiwan because it depends on
manufacturers there for the circuits that accompany its PC
microprocessors.
</P>
<P>
   Advanced Micro reported its results after the close of the
market. Its shares closed at $19.4375, up 81.25 cents, on the New
York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Advanced Micro's fortunes have improved since August, when it
introduced the Athlon, which gives it the ability to compete with
the high end of Intel Corp.'s Pentium line. Before August, the lack
of a high-end chip had put Advanced Micro at the mercy of Intel's
aggressive price cuts. Intel could afford deep cuts on its low-end
Celeron processors because it still had good profit margins in its
higher-powered chips, which are commonly used in work stations and
servers.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week Advanced Micro introduced a 700-megahertz
version of the Athlon that was immediately available in computers
produced by IBM and Compaq. Intel's Pentium III currently tops out
at 600 megahertz, although faster versions are expected soon.
</P>
<P>
   Advanced Micro chairman W.J. Sanders said, ``Sharply higher
sales of flash memories and sales of AMD Athlon processors at
higher margins than those experienced on AMD-K6 family processors
combined to boost revenues smartly and cut our operating loss by
more than $70 million compared to the immediate-prior quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   For the quarter, which ended Sept. 26, Advanced Micro reported a
loss of $105.5 million, in contrast to earnings of $1 million, or 1
cent a diluted share, in the period a year earlier. Sales fell 3
percent, to $662.2 million, from $685.9 million in the third
quarter of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The loss per diluted share was equivalent to 72 cents; analysts
had expected Advanced Micro to lose 97 cents a share, according to
First Call/Thomson Financial.
</P>
<P>
   Sales for continuing product groups were up 16 percent from the
second quarter and up 1 percent from the third quarter of 1998, the
company said.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders said that he had set a break-even goal of $850 million
in revenue and that the company could have revenue exceeding $800
million in the fourth quarter based on current order rates. But he
said the situation in Taiwan remained uncertain and information was
being updated daily.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, the company said it had asked investment bankers at
Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette and at Salomon Smith Barney to find a
buyer for its communications product group, which makes integrated
circuits for telecommunications and computer networking. Advanced
Micro said it hoped to complete a sale of the unit in the first
half of next year; the unit had revenue of $70 million in the third
quarter and employs about 400 people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
