A9222 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBA-YANKEES-PETTITTE-     10-06 0615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-PETTITTE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PETTITTE NO ACE IN SEASON, BUT IN PLAYOFFS, HE'S BEEN KING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Five-time Cy Young award winner Roger Clemens is 1-2
in nine postseason starts. He hasn't won one since 1986. Strikeout
artist Randy Johnson would've made Babe Ruth shake in his shoes
during the regular season. But in the playoffs? Try seven
consecutive losses.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's quiet Andy Pettitte. Two World Series victories
and four playoff victories in three postseasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put more on what someone's accomplished in big games,'' said
Yankees manager Joe Torre, who stood by his pitcher during rough
times and rampant trade speculation this season. ``I try not to
lose sight of the big picture.''
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte is scheduled to start Game 2 of their American League
Division Series today against the Rangers at Yankee Stadium. Three
months ago, Pettitte, deemed washed up by some at the tender age of
27, seemed a sure bet to be traded.
</P>
<P>
   He struggled mightily in the first half of the season, going 5-7
with a 5.59 earned-run average. Playing for an owner who fashioned
the what-have-you-done-for-me-lately mantra long before it was in
vogue, Pettitte was central to many trade rumors despite winning 81
games in five years for the Yankees, more than any Yankees pitcher
this decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``It almost seemed like I was struggling for my life
individually,'' Pettitte said.
</P>
<P>
   He insists the rumors never affected his performances or
motivated him, especially during the turnaround second-half after
owner George Steinbrenner publicly said Pettitte had something to
prove.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte said hard work with pitching coach Mel Stottlemyre
helped him rediscover his two-seam fastball. He also said Torre's
unyielding support helped him relax. With renewed confidence,
Pettitte rolled to a 9-4 record with a 3.84 ERA after the All-Star
break. He finished the regular season with a 14-11 mark, his fifth
consecutive season with double-figure wins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been saying it all along, it makes you feel good when you
know \RTorre's\S behind you,'' Pettitte, who resides near Houston
in Deer Park, said. ``In the past, I've been able to do some good
stuff in the postseason. He remembers stuff like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitching in the playoffs for a fourth time, the question hanging
on Pettitte is this: Is he the finesse pitcher with pinpoint
control able to last into the late innings? Or is he the erratic
pitcher who, as recently as his previous start, walked six and
allowed six hits and six earned runs in 41/3 innings?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think mentally, I am a lot tougher than that,'' Pettitte
said. ``Me and Mel worked hard trying to figure out my mechanics.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's pitching matchup, Pettitte vs. Rick Helling, is a
rematch of last year's Game 2, a 3-1 Yankees victory that gave them
a commanding 2-0 lead heading back to Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte, 2-0 against the Rangers in the playoffs and a far
better pitcher at Yankee Stadium than in Arlington, pitched a dandy
in that one, going seven innings and allowing one run on three
hits, while striking out eight and walking none.
</P>
<P>
   In his only outing against the Rangers this season, Pettitte
earned the win in that 21-3 debacle at The Ballpark in Arlington on
Aug. 23. Before this season, Pettitte had a 6.42 ERA vs. the
Rangers, who can load the lineup with right-handed batters.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've given me trouble in the past, that's no secret,''
Pettitte said. ``If you keep stuff in the heart of the plate,
you're going to get hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees will be satisfied as long as Pettitte continues to
produce in a big way in the playoffs.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
