r s BC-BBA-RANGERS-HELLING-T     10-06 0607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-HELLING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELAXED RANGERS PITCHER HELLING AWAITS YANKEES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Right-hander Rick Helling, the Rangers' scheduled
starter for Game 2 of the American League Division Series, held
court yesterday morning at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers must beat the New York Yankees tonight or leave the
Bronx trailing the best-of-five series, two games to none. And if
yesterday's session were a court of law, a spectator might have
wondered if Helling perjured himself in his 15-minute deposition
with the media.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody expected us to win, so there's not really pressure on
you when you're not expected to win,'' Helling said nonchalantly.
``It's when you're expected to win that there's pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   No sweat dripped from Helling's brow despite the glare of camera
lights that soaked him and his wool coat on a chilly, October
morning. Helling (13-11) appeared to be one cool customer, and the
28-year-old pitcher better be the Rangers' version of the Iceman
tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, the Rangers could be staring at the possibility of
being swept for a second consecutive season in the Division Series
by the Yankees on Saturday night at The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think really anybody expected us to win this series
anyway,'' Helling said. ``To me, all the pressure is on the
Yankees. They won the first game. Obviously, it would be nice if we
won the second game and went back home with a split.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been the underdog all year. Everybody has talked about
us being matched up with the Yankees ... and if we could finally
beat them, and we haven't yet.''
</P>
<P>
   That burden falls squarely on Helling's shoulders tonight, and
his right arm should be cause for concern. Helling went 2-4 with a
7.68 earned-run average during his final seven starts of the
regular season and surrendered 15 of his major league-high 41 home
runs during that period.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have the utmost confidence in myself that I'll make the
pitch when I have to,'' Helling said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers need Helling to duplicate his June 16 start against
New York. Helling surrendered only four hits and two walks through
seven scoreless innings, and the Rangers escaped Yankee Stadium
with a 3-0 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Helling proved merciless with runners in scoring position that
evening. The Yankees went 0-for-6 in those at-bats, and that bears
greater significance considering the Rangers' inability to produce
runs against New York's rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eventually, it's going to happen,'' Helling said. ``I have a
ton of faith in our offense, and it doesn't put any pressure on me.
I'm trying to put zeros on the board anyway. I don't worry about
what they do. More times than not, they're going to score plenty of
runs for us.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our offense is capable of scoring 10 runs a game if we start
swinging the bats the way we can.''
</P>
<P>
   Helling will be best served by regaining the feel for his
curveball, a pitch ``that's game-to-game with me,'' he said.
Helling needs command of his curveball to complement his fastball,
which he throws about 70 percent of the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have confidence in it,'' Helling said. ``If it's not
working, I'll use my other pitches. You make the best with what you
have that night. Obviously, you don't just throw a couple of them
in the first inning and say, `Oh, it's not working,' and then throw
it away.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to keep throwing it and make the hitter know you're
going to throw it. Obviously, if it's working, it'll make your job
easier. The more pitches you have in your repertoire, the easier it
is to pitch.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
