A9226 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-UNIONPACIFIC-GM-DEAL-     10-06 0467
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNIONPACIFIC-GM-DEAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNION PACIFIC ORDERS LOCOMOTIVES FROM GM UNIT IN $2 BILLION DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By TIMOTHY PRITCHARD   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Union Pacific Corp. said Wednesday that it had ordered
1,000 locomotives worth more than $2 billion from a Canadian
division of General Motors Corp. It was Union Pacific's biggest
step yet to improve a railroad network that was so slow and snarled
two years ago that some customers rebelled and began sending
freight by truck.
</P>
<P>
   The General Motors Electro-Motive Division in London, Ontario,
about 150 miles southwest of Toronto, will deliver the new
locomotives over the next four years. It is the largest single
order for locomotives ever placed by the Omaha-based railroad, and
the largest piece of business ever won by the Canadian
manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   Union Pacific will replace about 1,500 older locomotives in its
current fleet of 7,000 with the new ones, said John Bromley, a
spokesman for Union Pacific. ``We were faced with significant
maintenance and overhaul costs if we hadn't done something to
reduce the average age of the fleet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Union Pacific has been replacing about 200 locomotives each
year, with some leased and some purchased. It will lease the 1,000
new locomotives through General Motors.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadian plant, which employs 2,700 people and can make 600
locomotives a year, had been preparing for layoffs because of a
decline in orders. ``We now see a stable order book for the next
three to four years,'' said Kevin McKittrick, a spokesman. The
plant also makes light armored vehicles and is Canada's largest
military contractor.
</P>
<P>
   The 4,000-horsepower SD70 models ordered by Union Pacific have
been in use on North American railroads for the last five years.
</P>
<P>
   Union Pacific is currently investing about $2 billion a year in
new equipment to try to become a more efficient competitor.
</P>
<P>
   Its $5.4 billion purchase of Southern Pacific Transportation
Corp. in 1996 created the largest railroad in the United States _
and a textbook case of how to mismanage a merger.
</P>
<P>
   The two rail networks, with 53,000 employees, 7,000 locomotives,
155,000 freight cars and 36,000 miles of track, failed to meld and
adapt, causing delays and lost shipments. Customers ranging from
grain farmers to petrochemical producers revolted, sending their
products via trucks instead. Some called for tighter regulation of
big railroad mergers.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months congestion has been reduced and average train
speeds have risen, but some customers continue to complain, and
Union Pacific's management acknowledges that it still needs more
modern equipment and operating procedures.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Union Pacific shares finished unchanged at
$48.0625. GM shares rose 37.5 cents, to $65.75.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
