<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 23:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9232 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-INDIANS-AR     10-06 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-INDIANS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTINEZ HURT AS RED SOX FALL TO INDIANS, 3-2
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photos NYT 43,44 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ For baseball fans of New England, October is the
cruelest month, the time of year when championship dreams are
crushed. The blow sometimes comes early, as it did in 1978, with a
Bucky Dent home run to give the Yankees a victory in a pennant
playoff. It might come late, with a Mookie Wilson ground ball in
1986, to give the Mets new life in a World Series.
</P>
<P>
   For this season, although it is too soon to be sure, Boston's
gloom might have begun Wednesday night, midway through the opening
game of the first round of a three-round tournament. Boston's Pedro
Martinez, baseball's best pitcher, was cruising along with a 2-0
lead over the Indians. He seemed to be gaining pace and momentum.
Then he suddenly left the game with a back injury, not taking the
mound for the fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians erased the lead with a two-run home run by Jim Thome
in the sixth and went on to win by 3-2 on a bases-loaded single by
Travis Fryman off Rich Garces in the bottom of the ninth. Cleveland
takes a one-game-to-none lead into the Game 2 of this best-of-5
division series on Thursday afternoon. The winning run was scored
by Manny Ramirez, who led off the ninth by getting hit by a pitch
from Derek Lowe, who performed well but took the loss.
</P>
<P>
   Also pitching well but not getting the decision was Cleveland's
Bartolo Colon, who left after eight innings after allowing two runs
and striking out 11 batters, his season high.
</P>
<P>
   Starting the top of the ninth with the score tied at 2-2 was
Cleveland's Paul Shuey, who got credit for the victory. Colon's
exit ended what had started as a duel between two friends from the
Dominican Republic who are among the best pitchers in the American
League.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday here, Charles Nagy will pitch for Cleveland against
Bret Saberhagen. Game 3 and Game 4, if necessary, are scheduled for
Saturday and Sunday at Fenway Park in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez's injury was described as a muscle strain in the middle
of his back. The team announced the prognosis for his recovery as
``day to day,'' but his departure was a jolt to both the Sox and
the hopes of New England fans, whose team has not won a World
Series since 1918.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez entered the game with a record of 23-4, best in the
league, and with the league's best earned run average, 2.07. He
also led in strikeouts with 313 and is considered a sure bet for
the Cy Young Award as the league's best pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   When Lowe came on in the fifth, Boston not only had a 2-0 lead,
but Martinez had given up just three hits and seemed to be
improving. He retired the Indians in order for the first time in
the fourth, getting the final out while covering first base and
taking the throw from Mike Stanley on a grounder by David Justice.
</P>
<P>
   Though they lost the league's best pitcher, the Red Sox regained
the league's best hitter Wednesday night. Nomar Garciaparra, who
missed the last week of the season after being hit on the right
wrist by a pitch, returned and helped create the first two runs. He
led off the second inning with a line-drive home run that barely
cleared the wall in right-center field. In the fourth, he led off
with a double and scored on a single to left by Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra walked in the sixth inning, drawing a cheer from the
Cleveland fans, and was doubled off first after Justice caught Troy
O'Leary's fly ball against the wall in left and threw back to the
infield. Garciaparra had already rounded second and was doubled off
easily.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians tied it at 2-2 in the bottom of the sixth when a
throwing error by third baseman John Valentin on a routine grounder
allowed Manny Ramirez to reach first with two out. The next batter,
Thome, hit Lowe's first pitch into the right-field seats.
</P>
<P>
   Colon is almost four years younger than Martinez and their
friendship is like that between a freshman and a senior from the
same neighborhood who attend rival schools. Colon is 24 years old
and Martinez will turn 28 on Oct. 25. Both are from the Dominican
Republic, a cradle of talent for baseball. Martinez, an established
star, comes across as confident and relaxed, speaking confidently
in both English and Spanish. Colon, an emerging star, seems more
tentative, using a teammate as an interpreter..
</P>
<P>
   Colon said Wednesday afternoon that Martinez is something of a
mentor to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great person, he can help me a lot with my pitching and
with life,'' Colon said, with translation provided by catcher Sandy
Alomar. ``Whenever we get together or before the game, whenever we
see each other, we have conversations about pitching. He is a great
person to follow.''
</P>
<P>
   Colon finished the season tied for second in the league in
victories with 18, with five defeats. His ERA of 3.95 ranked
seventh. In previous games matching the two pitchers, Martinez was
3-0 and Colon was 0-2.
</P>
</TEXT>
